<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS, EX-HOSPITAL EXEC TELL APPEALS COURT THAT TRIAL JUDGE
ERRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES and ROBERT BOCZKIEWICZ  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Two Johnson County physicians and a former Kansas City
hospital executive say they were wrongfully convicted in a kickback
scheme because the judge committed serious errors at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The physicians, brothers Robert and Ronald LaHue, and the former
chief executive officer of Baptist Medical Center, Dan Anderson,
made the claims in separate written arguments filed recently with
the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are due to respond to the defendants' filings in the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants want the appeals court to overturn their Medicare
fraud convictions. In April 1999, a federal jury in Kansas City,
Kan., found the LaHues and Anderson guilty of conspiracy to defraud
the federal government and of paying and receiving payments in
return for the referral of nursing home patients to Baptist and
other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants say that the payments were for legitimate medical
services and that the business relationships between the doctors
and the hospitals benefited the patients and Medicare alike.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the defendants single out as an error an
instruction given by U.S. District Judge John W. Lungstrum to the
jury. Lungstrum told jurors that to return a guilty verdict, they
had to find that the payments were made with the intent, ``at least
in part,'' to induce the doctors to refer patients to the
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The jury instruction ``effectively criminalized innocent
conduct,'' Anderson contends. Anderson says the jurors should have
been instructed that he could not be convicted unless ``the primary
purpose'' of the payments was to induce referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under (Lungstrum's) interpretation, every hospital would
violate the statute on a daily basis through normal business
activities,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief, Ronald LaHue says federal prosecutors in effect
gagged potential defense witnesses, including hospital personnel
and the lawyers who drafted the contracts between the LaHues and
Baptist, by naming them as unindicted co-conspirators. That
prompted the witnesses to invoke their Fifth Amendment right not to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Naming them as co-conspirators amounted to manipulation and
coercion by the prosecutors because, LaHue says, no criminal
charges were ever brought against them. LaHue says Lungstrum should
have granted his request to grant the alleged co-conspirators
immunity from prosecution so they could testify.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants also contend that Lungstrum erred by admitting as
evidence the handwritten notes of the lawyers involved in setting
up the business arrangements between the LaHues and Baptist. The
lawyers were indicted but later acquitted by Lungstrum, who found
the evidence against them insufficient. The lawyers' notes were
highly prejudicial and should have been excluded, the defendants
say.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Anderson says he should have been treated no
differently than Dennis McClatchey, another Baptist executive, whom
Lungstrum acquitted after the jury convicted him. Lungstrum
concluded the evidence for conviction was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants also point out that Lungstrum denied them an
acquittal or new trial despite his finding that there was no
evidence that patients referred by the LaHues received substandard
care or were denied their choice of a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Congress intended to criminalize those practices _ not the
practices of which the defendants were convicted, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and the LaHues were sentenced to prison but remain free
pending their appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
