<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT HORIZONS, SAME VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nine weeks, Tony Amend and Brad Rincker had time to think
about what their jobs meant to them. Both Teamsters were locked out
of their warehouse jobs at Associated Wholesale Grocers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what both decided: Their jobs were hard, physical labor _
the kind that most people simply wouldn't care to do or wouldn't
last in for the decade-plus they each had under their belts.
</P>
<P>
   Both agreed that before the lockout and for months on end, they
had made many personal and family sacrifices to work mandatory
overtime, often putting in up to 14 hours a day, 70 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   And both were shocked at the lockout, not quite able to believe
that after years of work, they were drawing state unemployment
money.
</P>
<P>
   This week, after AWG and the union settled their dispute before
the National Labor Relations Board, and the union signed a contract
with an AWG subcontractor to operate the warehouse, both men
reported back to work.
</P>
<P>
   On Amend's first day back, he put in 14 hours. He said his
supervisors were happy to see him and he was happy to be there,
despite some hassles with equipment that had been damaged during
the Teamsters' absence.
</P>
<P>
   As the sole support of his family, Amend was delighted to be
done with mowing lawns, painting houses, doing landscaping _ any
odd job he could find to supplement his $306-a-week unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   On Rincker's first day back, he decided to turn in his
resignation. Faced with immediate 12-hour workdays, he realized his
life's priorities had changed during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Rincker, who didn't have the same family financial obligations
as Amend, had used the lockout time to jump into a 30-week
Microsoft certified software engineer training program. He'd
already returned to Penn Valley Community College and, after three
semesters of night school, had a 4.0 grade point average in
computer network administration classes.
</P>
<P>
   So one man is back in the saddle, and the other chose to ride a
different horse. But both carry similar impressions from their time
in the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Principal among them is good will toward the supervisors who
acknowledged them as thinking, well-intentioned workers who had
goals, personal needs and strong work ethics. They appreciate those
supervisors who worked with them to adjust work hours to
accommodate personal needs or took care to explain company
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also exude optimism about the ability of the Teamsters,
the warehouse operator, Elite Logistics and AWG to make a go of it
together. It won't be easy; the lockout and months leading up to it
exacerbated a nasty atmosphere of us vs. them, labor vs.
management.
</P>
<P>
   Both hope that Elite will hire enough people to do the jobs and
that the excessive overtime will end, making life easier for all
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Both think there's a chance now to improve work conditions and
work relationships. Amend expects to do his part on the job.
Rincker will cheer from afar.
</P>
<P>
   Both urge the public to pay attention. There's a ripple effect
throughout the economy when work stoppages occur for any reason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
