<SLUG> BC-NY-MAIL-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CHARGED IN $1.5 MILLION MAIL THEFT SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Pa., N.J.)   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A young couple used mail pilfered from thousands of
homes in Queens and Long Island neighborhoods to steal more than
$1.5 million from banks and credit card companies, prosecutors said
Wednesday. They called the crime one of the most brazen and
methodical cases of identity theft they had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Queens District Attorney Richard Brown said the couple, Ismael
Irizarry, 28, and Luisa Irizarry, 27, hired 16 people to plunder
mailboxes in affluent and middle-class neighborhoods like Forest
Hills and Bayside in Queens, as well as communities in both Nassau
and Suffolk counties.
</P>
<P>
   Their victims included ``many prominent names in the New York
metropolitan area,'' including political and civic leaders, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Irizarrys moved to Pembroke Pines, Fla. Mr.
Irizarry, who was indicted in November, was arrested in January on
a visit to New York. He is being held without bail.
</P>
<P>
   His wife remained at large until she was arrested in Florida on
Friday, June 2.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 18 months, starting in 1998, Brown said, the
couple and their assistants combed through hundreds of thousands of
pieces of mail to steal credit card applications, checks and
personal information like Social Security numbers and drivers'
license numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that the Irizarrys, who formerly lived in
Queens, set up a computer database of all the information and
applied for credit cards and cashed stolen checks. Some of those
checks were deposited in the bank accounts of two fictitious
corporations, Millennium Import/Export Co. and Genesis
Communications, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Irizarrys were indicted on charges of grand larceny,
possessing forged checks, falsifying business records, scheming to
defraud and possessing stolen property. A conviction on grand
larceny, the most serious charge, could lead to up to 15 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Irizarry's lawyer, Salvatore Chetta of Queens, could not be
reached for comment. Lawyers at the public defender's office in
Dade County, Fla., who are representing Ms. Irizarry, did not
return calls seeking comment about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Queens district attorney's office and the
U.S. Postal Inspection Service found a list of 2,000 names of
victims in the computer database, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Irizarry was arrested by Florida police officers after she
tried to lease cars using stolen checks under the alias of Gloria
Casanove, Brown said. She was charged by the Miami police with auto
theft and assaulting a police officer, and is awaiting extradition
to New York, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added that she also faced outstanding warrants in New
Jersey and Pennsylvania for unspecified crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
