u a BC-NON-EDUCATOR-SUPERINT     06-08 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NON-EDUCATOR-SUPERINTENDENTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG-CITY SCHOOL SYSTEMS FIND INNOVATIVE LEADERS WHO ARE NOT
EDUCATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Revises 2nd and 3rd grafs to clarify who objects to Bersin's
approach and reword phrase on his not being an educator; subs 12th
graf for attribution on explaining trend toward non-educator
superintendents; subs 13th graf to remove Bersin's age, which could
be be confirmed; subs 14th graf to include Bersin's salary and
remove reference to San Diego being 8th largest district)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Alan D. Bersin, superintendent of the San Diego
schools, is talking tough with 35 student teachers: ``Our reading
levels, by and large, are abysmal,'' he tells them. The dropout
rate is huge, he says, and he has laid off 600 paraprofessionals
because ``they have added virtually nothing to student
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Bersin is arguing the case for his sweeping campaign to reshape
the schools, with prescribed blocks of time for teaching literacy,
and constant teacher training in the methods to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' union objects to Bersin's approach, and his reform
plan squeaked through the school board on a 3-2 vote in March, but
his not being an educator is no longer much of an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bersin is the former U.S. attorney for southern California, one
of the first of a new breed of high-profile outsiders taking over
big-city school districts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Los Angeles board of education named Roy Romer,
the former Colorado governor, as its new superintendent. In May,
Harold O. Levy, a corporate lawyer, was chosen to lead the New York
City school system, the nation's largest. They are the first
non-educators ever chosen for those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Other urban districts, too, have turned to law, business,
government and the military for new leadership and an outside
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   For many of these newcomers _ often the children of immigrants
who view their families' success as a direct result of public
schooling _ education is the era's biggest challenge and leading a
school system is today's Everest of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public education is what distinguishes this country, both
vertically, in history, and horizontally, from other societies
around the world,'' said Bersin. ``For the first time, there is a
real belief in this country that every child has the right to a
quality education. This is the most important challenge San Diego
faces. It gives reality to what is otherwise the empty myth that in
this country, you can do anything you want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy, in an effort to recruit teachers to the cause, has said
recently, ``Urban education is the equivalent of the Peace Corps of
the '60s or the civil rights movement of the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has had two nontraditional superintendents in a row, one
from the military, one from the private sector. Houston's
superintendent is a former school board member; Chicago's a former
city budget director; Kansas City's a former top federal aviation
official.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``These are all very smart, very talented individuals who
have a clear idea of where they're going, and how to get there,''
said Michael Casserly, executive director of the Council of Great
City Schools. ``What's not clear yet is whether they can produce
the same academic gains as a skilled educator.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts in educational administration say it is precisely
the sense that educators have failed the schools _ and that
outsiders may have an edge in effecting change.
</P>
<P>
   ``School districts need to change how they conduct themselves if
we are to improve student achievement, and that kind of change does
not usually come from those inside the system,'' said Bersin, a
product of the New York City public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bersin was San Diego's chief federal law enforcement officer
when he was given the $165,000-a-year job of heading the nation's
eighth-largest urban school district, which has 145,000 students.
Now he is steeped in the language of education, talking
passionately about creating a community of learners, or about
children who score in the bottom quartile on the SAT 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take long to understand the issues, to see the
extraordinary talent of many of the people inside the system, and
the ways the system has functioned as an obstacle to their
growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1990s, it was almost unthinkable to choose a big-city
superintendent from outside education. Traditionally, they were
former teachers who became principals and then superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nontraditional superintendents split the
responsibilities of leading their districts, handling school board
meetings, bond issues, union matters and politics themselves, but
leaving issues of pedagogy to a deputy with educational
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Bersin turned to Anthony Alvarado, a former New
York City educator best known for his success in raising student
achievement and creating innovative schools in two Manhattan
districts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Alvarado's long history in New York included a difficult
chapter: in 1984, his year as chancellor ended with his resignation
amid charges of personal financial irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, he is the chancellor of instruction, and head of
the district's new Institute for Learning _ and, he said, delighted
to be able to focus on raising the quality of instruction. Alvarado
is not revered in San Diego as he was in New York. He knows that
many there see him as a brash outsider imposing heavy-handed
changes on a system he does not know. But, he argues, his changes
grow out of solid research, not personal whim.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of evidence about what helps kids learn,'' he
said. ``We know literacy and math are the gatekeeper skills that
give kids access to academic success for the rest of their lives.
We know summer school helps reduce the learning loss that occurs
when poor kids are out of school for a long time. It's not Tony
Alvarado doing summer school, it's what works.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a surgeon, visiting hospitals in different cities,
there's a stunning similarity in the tools, the length of the
incision, the mortality rate. When we started, the elementary
programs here had 200 reading programs, sometimes four or five
different programs in the same school. And what all these programs
generated was only 41 percent of the kids reading at or above grade
level.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The commitment to systemic change is profound, according to
Kimiko Fukuda, a 33-year veteran of the San Diego system who is the
only one of the old assistant superintendents to remain as an
``instructional leader'' in the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd read Alvarado's work, and I understood the problem of
every teacher being in private practice, almost an independent
contractor,'' she said. ``But when I tried to change things as an
assistant superintendent, it didn't have much impact, because it
was voluntary, and the union didn't like it. You really can't make
this kind of change unless it's from the top, and it covers
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, each principal is required to spend two hours a day in
classrooms helping teachers improve their work. Peer coaches in the
schools help with teaching methods, too, and principals attend
weekly training sessions on literacy techniques such as ``guided
reading'' and ``shared reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Some principals love it.
</P>
<P>
   At Central Elementary School, a year-round school with 1,200
mostly Hispanic children crammed into a facility built for 800,
Elaine Arm, the principal, sings the praises of Bersin's
educational overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``'I've been reborn,'' she says. ``I feel powerful. I'm not just
an administrator now; I'm an instructional leader; I'm in
classrooms every day and I love it. There is real focus. We know
what we are supposed to do, and why. It's an enormous change, all
because of this superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   If something as abstract as school reform can be made visible,
Bersin's version is on view on the hallway bulletin boards, where
sweetly childish writings _ ``I like when the frog got the peach
down.'' _ are posted beneath the state learning standard that
prompted the assignment. ``3.1 We are learning to distinguish real
stories from make-believe,'' or ``2.6 We are learning to write a
response to literature.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is visible as the fourth graders write book essays
following a ``rubric'' that tell them the first paragraph should
contain the title, author and theme, the second should compare the
main characters and the third should compare the problems they
faced and the solutions they reached.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this approach is not universally accepted. Many San
Diego educators say the reforms impinge on their spontaneity and
overemphasize literacy, neglecting social studies and science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher I work with is mostly hoping this will pass,''
said one of the student teachers Bersin was addressing. ``Her
attitude is `I've been teaching for 10 years, and what the heck is
guided reading?' She doesn't think the principal who's supposed to
be leading it understands all this new stuff any better than she
does.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The student teachers seem energized by Bersin's approach, but
wary, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's change, and it makes people nervous,'' said Les
Henderson, who expects teacher certification next month. `We're
talking about institutionalizing education, standardizing things,
and I'm on the fence about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two years into Bersin's reign, some local educators question how
long he can talk about the district's poor performance without
being held responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes three to five years to bring real change,'' said
Bruce S. Cooper, a professor of educational administration at
Fordham University. ``The problem is that large districts are so
unmanageable and unstable that the average superintendent only
lasts two and a half years.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can stay the course, it may be Bersin, a Brooklyn
native with an easy charm, a sharp mind, and a golden resume: Phi
Beta Kappa at Harvard, All Ivy and All-East Football Teams, and
Rhodes Scholar at Oxford, where he overlapped a year with Bill
Clinton, and then, like the president, moved on to Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation he headed west, first as special counsel to the
Los Angeles Police Commission, then handling commercial litigation
at Munger, Tolles &AMP; Olson. He moved to San Diego for a sabbatical
teaching law school in 1992, shortly after the birth of his second
daughter, now a second grader in the district. Bersin's oldest
daughter is at Harvard, and his youngest is in kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows you what a Republican town San Diego is that three
weeks after I got here, I was the head of Clinton for President.''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, President Clinton appointed him U.S. attorney, and
starting in 1995, he also served as Attorney General Janet Reno's
border czar. Faced with the intractable problems of the border _
drug trafficking and illegal immigration _ he gained attention by
reframing the issues in terms of public safety, making it possible
to work with Mexico toward some common goals.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bersin keeps a politician's schedule: he goes from the student
teachers' visit to throwing the first ball at the Padres game, from
a visit to Central Elementary to teaching an eighth grade history
class at Correia Middle School, and on to a staff meeting on
portfolio assessment at Curie Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   He talks with every teacher, every administrator, asking lots of
questions, listening hard and saying how much he values their
ideas. He stops to ask a custodian how things are going. ``We've
made everyone in the system, the bus drivers, everyone, understand
that their job is to support learning in the classroom,'' Bersin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bersin has prodigious energy, and seems to take real pleasure in
all the public contact. But he is not, he says, headed for
political office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd wanted elective office, I'd have stayed in the U.S.
attorney's office, putting bad guys in jail, which plays to the
public,'' he said. ``I'm in a position to choose what I do and
where I can make a difference. And this is the most important
challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
