<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CRUSH ORIOLES, 11-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Edgardo Alfonzo, it was another typical game on
Wednesday night. He homered in the first inning to drive in the New
York Mets' first run, tripled in the sixth to score the go-ahead
run _ and somehow did nothing to draw attention to himself in an
11-3 victory over the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo is the Mets' stealth superstar, quietly posting great
numbers while others get more fanfare. He is probably the National
League's best second baseman, but he has never been an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a really special player when it's all said
and done,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``Right now, he's one of
the finest players in the game, but he keeps trying to improve. I'm
really proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo bats in front of Mike Piazza, the star catcher, and
after Alfonzo delivered a functional, 382-foot homer to left on
Wednesday night, Piazza followed with a mammoth blast that traveled
64 feet farther, over the fence beyond the visitors' bullpen in
left.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, when Alfonzo rifled a triple to right off Scott
Erickson, it took his average to .350 and was the pivotal hit in a
four-run inning that put the Mets ahead to stay. But the more
memorable at-bat that inning was the one that tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie Jason Tyner, a slap-hitting leadoff man who has not
homered since high school, turned on a pitch and sent Albert Belle
retreating for the catch, just in front of the warning track. Kurt
Abbott, who opened the inning with a triple, scored on the
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott later doubled to start a five-run seventh inning that
burst open the game.
</P>
<P>
   But in the sixth, the game was still close; the Orioles were
leading, 3-2, when the Mets' starter, Rick Reed, left the game
after throwing 99 pitches in five unsteady innings. Reed, pitching
for the first time in 11 days after straining a muscle in his left
side, allowed three runs on eight hits, including a homer by Cal
Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said he was too strong after the layoff, throwing fastballs
up in the zone _ dangerous territory for him. He said he finally
stopped doing that against the last batter he faced _ Belle, who
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to overpower anybody, that's for sure,'' said
Reed. ``That at-bat was probably the best I was throwing all night.
I guess if you're going to end your night, you might as well end it
on a positive note.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyner saved a run for Reed in the fourth inning, but it was
almost his duty: he had allowed B.J. Surhoff to reach third when he
dropped a fly ball by Ripken that went for a two-base error.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Tyner got a running start on a fly by Charles
Johnson, and lofted his throw home as Surhoff tagged up. The ball
took one hop, Piazza reached up to get it and used his left foot to
block Surhoff's path to the plate, applying the tag and completing
the double play.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, meanwhile, was happy to spread the credit among the
whole team. ``This was a pretty good game, from the first at-bat to
the end,'' Alfonzo said. ``It was a good sign that we put
everything together tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
