<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT     06-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DEFEAT PACERS IN GAME 1, 104-87 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Being a former prime-time player himself, Larry
Bird decided before Game 1 that stopping Shaquille O'Neal was
useless. Bird, the coach of the Indiana Pacers, would concede
points to O'Neal, the game's most awesome physical presence, and
make the other Los Angeles Lakers beat his team _a strategy
employed often against Michael Jordan in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal's every unmolested spin toward the baseline, with
each soft hook and forceful dunk, Bird had to know: it did not work
then in the National Basketball Association finals and it does not
work now.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, the league's reigning most valuable player, nearly
swallowed the Pacers whole on Wednesday night, powering the Lakers
to a 104-87 victory before nearly 20,000 people at the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 1-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game finals, the
Lakers are host to Game 2 on Friday night, at which time Bird and
the Pacers may have to re-evaluate their game plan. Feasting on
single coverage for much of the evening on Wednesday night, O'Neal
did not take a rest until 1 minute 32 seconds remained in the first
half, leaving the floor with 21 points and a 15-point Laker lead.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana threatened several times _ once cutting to 71-69 with
less than two minutes remaining in the third quarter _ before the
Lakers buried them in the fourth, outscoring them by 27-16. Neither
Reggie Miller nor his teammates ever gave the impression that they
wanted the Lakers to be anything but huge favorites on their home
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Miller did not score until 8:19 remained in the third quarter,
and finished with 7 points on 1-of-16 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the Lakers with 43 points on 21-of-31 shooting, 19
rebounds and 4 assists in 44 minutes. Kobe Bryant was next, with 14
points.
</P>
<P>
   For the Pacers, Mark Jackson (18 points), Austin Croshere (16)
and Rik Smits and Jalen Rose (12 apiece) were the leading scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Except at the end of the third quarter, when the Pacers found
some life, O'Neal dominated. Backing in against Smits or simply
jumping over the Indiana front line, he could not be defended.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Ron Harper played nice supporting roles, giving the
Lakers 16 points and 8 assists combined by halftime. The Lakers
went to the locker room with a 55-43 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The first act of the coronation was going swell for Coach Phil
Jackson, most of his team's parts functioning well enough to keep
Indiana a double-digit lead away.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Lakers have done throughout the playoffs, they lost
their focus on offense and hung their heads on defense as the third
quarter wore on. A lead of 67-52 began dissipating and nearly was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   With Miller struggling badly, Jackson started penetrating as if
he was directing traffic at St. John's in the 1980s. Breaking
Bryant down on defense by backing in with a high power dribble or
merely waiting for his teammates to come open on a staggered fast
break, Jackson brought the Pacers back.
</P>
<P>
   A 17-4 binge featured 8 points by Jackson. In all, he had 10
points in the quarter and 3 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's knifing reverse layup with less than two minutes left
in the quarter cut Los Angeles's margin to 71-69 _ a development
that quieted the crowd and raised all the old lack-of-desire issues
on the Laker bench.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that O'Neal and Bryant made sure they finished the
task. Bryant sandwiched two hanging, pull-up jump shots between the
defining block of the game by O'Neal to give the Lakers a 75-69
lead heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, trying hard to get on track offensively, seemed to have
a lane on the left wing. He began dribbling in when he was
startlingly met by a leaping O'Neal. Lofting his shot high enough
to clear the painted square above the rim, Miller felt confident
that the shot would escape O'Neal's fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   It did not. As the ball approached its apex, O'Neal sent it back
to the floor, the sequence sending his towel-waving teammates and
the fans into an uproarious state.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was not done. Finding open teammates cutting to the
basket or kicking out to whoever was standing alone on the
perimeter. With less than five minutes left, he had as many points
in the quarter (8) as the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had said before the series that the Pacers were decided
underdogs. ``They've got a lot of Goliaths and we have a lot of
Davids,'' he said. ``We also brought a lot of slingshots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller forgot his weapons, returning to the player who made
3 of 18 shots in Game6 of the Eastern Conference finals last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to his native Los Angeles for the first time in the
playoffs, he had one of his most forgettable performances in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Each time he went to the basket, he was swarmed by
purple-and-gold jerseys. With less than four minutes left, he
appeared to have another open lane on the right side of the basket.
</P>
<P>
   But in a blink, the Lakers converged and he threw up an
awful-looking, off-balance left-handed layup that made him 1 for 16
for the night. He had 7 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the other end, Brian Shaw caught O'Neal spinning
toward the rim out of the corner of his eye. He lobbed the ball,
and O'Neal caught it and dunked.
</P>
<P>
   As the final minutes wound down, Bird and the Pacers had yet
another difficult question to answer. How to stop O'Neal, of
course, is important. But here is another one: How to start
Miller? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
