<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLYLIFE08-FOSSILS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTHLY LIFE POSSIBLY BORN IN UNDERSEA INFERNO  &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
An Australian researcher probing the rocks of ancient deep-sea
volcanoes reported Wednesday that he has discovered the fossilized
remains of threadlike microbes that lived more than 3 billion years
ago.
<P>
   The discovery led other scientists to speculate that underwater
volcanoes might have been the birthplace of earthly life itself _ a
highly controversial theory first espoused by an American
oceanographer more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the deep-sea ``hydrothermal vents'' cradled life
emerging for the first time, the discovery does show that some of
the most primitive early life forms could have thrived amid the
viciously hot, sunless darkness of erupting matter _ and not only
on Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   The new discovery is being reported Thursday in the journal
Nature by Birger Rasmussen, a research fellow in geology and
geophysics at the University of Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In an informal account that Rasmussen e-mailed to The Chronicle
Wednesday, he wrote: ``Rather than a warm little pond, the cradle
of life may have been a sulfurous, subterranean inferno, not unlike
a medieval version of hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discovery opens up new possibilities in the search for
ancient life on Earth, and can be applied to strategies for finding
primitive life elsewhere in the solar system.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen's conclusions drew criticism, however, from several
space scientists, including Kevin Zahnle, an astronomer at NASA's
Astrobiology Institute at the Ames Research Center in Mountain
View, where scientists study the ingredients for life both on Earth
and on distant planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing at all that suggests this find has anything to
do with the origin of life, although it is likely to be the oldest
truly believable evidence for early life on the earth,'' Zahnle
said.
</P>
<P>
   To most scientists, the essential ingredients for life as we
know it would include sunlight as an energy source for
photosynthesis and a plentiful supply of complex organic compounds
that could evolve into living organisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could look around the solar system,'' Zahnle said, ``and
you'd find plenty of good candidates for the evolution of life _
like Titan, the moon of Saturn, for example, or Callisto or Europa,
two of Jupiter's moons.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest known life forms discovered so far include rock-like
clumps of fossilized blue-green algae, known as cyanobacteria,
found in ancient ocean sediments, which have been dated to 3.7
billion years ago. But they required sunlight to power
photosynthesis, and most scientists believe that on Earth, at
least, sunlight was essential for life to originate.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side is John B. Corliss, a former oceanographer at
Oregon State University who in 1977 was a lead scientist aboard an
expedition diving to a deep-sea volcanic vent off the Galapagos
Islands. That voyage brought back an astonishing and unexpected
trove of strange and unknown creatures and bacteria thriving in the
vent's boiling hot water. Two years later, he first proposed that
many such volcanic vents in the seas of the early Earth could have
been sites where life _ perhaps nourished by sulfides _ first
evolved from organic compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Corliss' hypothesis was widely derided when he proposed it at a
meeting in San Francisco in 1980, but he continues to argue for his
thesis and elaborate on it. Now a director of the Systems
Laboratory at the Central European University in Budapest, Hungary,
Corliss called the Rasmussen account ``an exciting and beautiful
paper _ my vision turned into reality'' when he was informed of it
by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen's report described how he found the ``fossil remains
of thread-like organisms'' in a massive sulfide deposit that
apparently once formed part of a deep-sea hydrothermal vent where
searing hot water erupted from the vent's chimney at a temperature
of 650 degrees Fahrenheit. The twisted tangle of microbes,
Rasmussen said, must have been alive some 3.235 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The region Rasmussen explored is known as the Pilbara Craton of
southwestern Australia, and it is known for the antiquity of many
of its rocks that once lay thousands of feet below sea level.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, twisting skeins of thread-like formations that
Rasmussen believes are the fossils of primitive microbes are only a
thousandth of a millimeter in diameter and three-tenths of a
millimeter long, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is probable, Rasmussen said, that submarine volcanic vents,
heated by semi-molten magma deep in the Earth's crust, were
abundant billions of years ago. ``It is possible that bacterial
communities flourished in similar settings long before these
findings would suggest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep beneath the ocean, hot springs would have been attractive
habitats for primitive microbes, protected from the effects of
early planetary bombardments, and bathed in a rich brew of metals
and (chemical) nutrients. Such environments could have provided a
safe setting for life hundreds of millions of years before the
Earth's surface was habitable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The undersea volcanoes, however, would have been a far cry from
the ``warm ponds'' and ``primordial soups'' that many evolutionary
biologists have considered as the most hospitable locales for life
to emerge. There, increasingly complex organic molecules might have
combined, learned to reproduce with the aid of primitive genetic
material, and finally built membranes around themselves to become
the first true harbingers of earthly life.
</P>
<P>
   Earth's earliest days are known as the Archaean, and in a
commentary on Rasmussen's paper in Thursday's Nature, Euan Nisbet,
a geologist at the University of London, writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps, then, the earliest Archaean life was confined to the
vicinity of hydrothermal systems.'' But he adds: ``Here we are deep
into guesswork, however ... we still know little about the far edge
of the world of life _ where did it come from?'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of EARLYLIF (44384 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
