<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT EXPOS, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ With his peripheral vision, Carl Pavano could see
Yankees scurrying from corner to corner, but he could not catch
them. The bases were infested with base-stealers, and the Montreal
pitcher tried, stepping off the pitching rubber and threatening
them. Sometimes he just held the ball and hoped they'd stop.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York Yankees kept running on Wednesday night,
swiping five bases and changing the basic dynamic of this game
early, then going on to win, 7-2. After his team's six-run rally in
the fifth inning, Orlando Hernandez breezed to his sixth victory,
allowing four hits and three walks in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won four of six games on this road trip, playing the
Atlanta Braves and the Expos. Over their last eight games, they are
batting .317 with 32 extra-base hits, and averaging 6.1 runs a
game. They will begin a three-game series against the New York Mets
at Yankee Stadium Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   As spring training began, Manager Joe Torre met with his new
first-base coach, Lee Mazzilli, and pushed him to push the Yankees'
base runners, who were somewhat lax in 1999, sometimes failing to
recognize opportunities to run. Mazzilli had played for Torre with
the Mets and was adept at stealing bases. ``Give them your mind and
their bodies,'' Torre told Mazzilli.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have run more this year, though with mixed results
in late April and into early May; after 34 games, the Yankees had
21 steals, but had been thrown out 16 times. But in the last 21
games, it's as if they've become mind readers, swiping 24 bases in
26 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees knew about Pavano was that he could be slow in
his delivery to home plate _ 1.3 seconds at his quickest. Ricky
Ledee led off the game with a single, took a lead. Mazzilli carries
a stopwatch and times pitchers, and Pavano was registering 1.5 or
1.6 seconds. Pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it took a while for me to get to the plate tonight,''
Pavano said later. ``I got the impression the last couple of starts
that guys are really starting to run on my delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way Pavano could have been rescued from the fate he
invited was if he had been paired with a strong-armed catcher. But
Charlie O'Brien turned 40 last month and is closing in on the end
of his career. As respected as he is for his ability to handle
pitchers, age has drained his arm strength and weakened his throws.
It was a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger reached first leading off the third inning when
Pavano grazed his left hand with a fastball. El Duque batted in an
obvious bunt situation. Lee Stevens, the Montreal first baseman,
charged on the third pitch _ the Yankees were playing hit-and-run _
and Bellinger broke for second.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien caught a fastball high and outside, a perfect pitch for
a throw to second, but the Montreal catcher bounced the ball 20
feet short of second base. Bellinger had gotten a huge jump, but
O'Brien's poor throw was an open invitation for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run,'' Derek Jeter said. ``We may not have the
fastest guys, but we're capable of stealing bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee singled with two out to score Bellinger, before Ledee
swiped second. Bernie Williams singled and stole second in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Montreal led by 2-1 after four innings, and with one out in
the fifth, Ledee chopped a routine grounder to shortstop, where
Geoff Blum fielded cleanly, set himself and threw high and wide, an
error. On the first pitch to Jeter, Ledee was running, and Jeter
grounded a single between the middle infielders as Ledee motored
into third.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch to Paul O'Neill, Jeter was running, and
O'Neill smashed a single to left-center; Ledee scored, Jeter
trotted into third.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano kept throwing to first base, trying to hold the runners,
but so long as he delivered the ball so deliberately, there was
nothing he could do; the Yankees were on the move. O'Neill swiped
second, and he and Jeter scored when Williams singled to center.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano could have been out of the inning, but Tino Martinez
drove the ball against the fence in left-center, a triple,
Martinez's fourth of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Manager Felipe Alou ambled out of the dugout, calling
for Mike Johnson, and when Jorge Posada smashed Johnson's second
pitch for a two-run homer, the Yankees led, 7-2, having scored six
runs with six batters, aided by Mazzilli's mind and their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with the way we played tonight,'' Torre
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alou said: ``They probably could've stolen 10 bases tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
