<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA STICKS UP FOR AL WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The American League West hasn't been mistaken lately
for, say, a black-and-blue division. Some go so far as to say it's
the weakest of the major leagues' divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy it,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said before
Wednesday night's interleague game against San Francisco at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, the AL West is one of the best divisions around.
Look at Texas, at Seattle, at us .. those are some pretty good
offensive clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This division can swing the bats with anyone in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia wasn't merely plugging for votes as commissioner of the
AL West, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the records,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. It's the only division in which every club in it is over
.500.
</P>
<P>
   RECHARGING: Tim Salmon on Tuesday was the Angels' designated
hitter for a second successive night and for the third time in four
games, instead of taking his customary place in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving him of a couple of days off to recharge,''
Scioscia explained. ``We want to make sure he's ready when we play
at Arizona (this weekend) and we won't have the DH. Plus, he fouled
a ball off his right shin the other day.''
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF THE DH ...: Like anyone who spent his entire playing
career in the National League, as Scioscia did (he was with Texas
one year but never played because of injuries), the mere thought of
the DH is, well, (ital) ugh! (endital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around the DH for the first time, I can see there are a
lot more offensive strategies than I thought there were,'' Scioscia
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he went on, ``I definitely prefer the National League
style of play which lets the pitchers hit.''
</P>
<P>
   PITCHERS HITTING: With interleague play moving into an NL park
this weekend in Arizona, indeed, the Angels' pitchers will have to
take their turn at the plate, some for the first time in the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   For the past couple of weeks, the pitchers have been appearing
regularly in the batting cage at Edison Field in preparation,
mostly working on bunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect a lot,'' Scioscia said, ``but I don't expect
injuries, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Angels pitchers were 4 for 21 (.190), including three
doubles and seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   DUSTY ON HOOPS: Dusty Baker, the Giants' manager, said he's
pulling for the Lakers in the NBA finals, which is understandable,
of course, since he grew up in Riverside and played nine years with
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know Larry Bird,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Really? How's that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him in Cincinnati, when I was with the Dodgers,'' Baker
said. ``Tommy John, who was from Indiana, brought him into the
clubhouse one day ... like he was trying to recruit him to Indiana
State.''
</P>
<P>
   A young Bird, indeed. &QL; 
STILL A DIRTBAG: Angels second baseman Adam Kennedy said his
brother, Long Beach State catcher Brian Kennedy, will be playing
with the Dirtbags again in 2001, his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about whether he should stay in school or sign
(professionally),'' Adam said. ``He figured if he wasn't drafted in
the first 10 rounds he was going to go back (to Long Beach
State).''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, the younger Kennedy wasn't drafted at all.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: The Giants' Barry Bonds is off the best homer
pace of his career. His home run in Tuesday night's game was his
25th, the most in the majors and also the most homers he's hit
prior to the All-Star break. His previous pre-All-Star break high
was 24 in 1993, one of his three MVP seasons. ... In the fifth
inning, Angels center fielder Garret Anderson grounded into a
double play for the 13th time this season. That tied him for the
major league lead in the dubious category. ... The Giants are in
the midst of a 24-game run exclusively within California (three in
Anaheim, three in Oakland and 18 at home). ... The Angels are idle
tonight, then begin a nine-game trip Friday night in Arizona.
They'll draw the Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson Friday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
