<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-AUCTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD HISTORY UP FOR AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. _ Quick, you're being chased by a
charging buffalo. Do you: a) call for help on Maxwell Smart's
umbrella phone; b) jump on a plastic horse and try to outrun him;
or c) take aim with the Red Ryder BB-gun Peter Billingsley longed
for in ``A Christmas Story''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'd like to sit back to ponder the question in Grandpa
Munster's electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the oddest close-out sales in history, Ellis Props is
unloading all of its stock - nearly a million fake grenades, rubber
steaks and other items used in TV and film production will be
auctioned off over five days at the Universal City Hilton and on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a sense of Hollywood history and a letter of credit
can join in the bidding on Ellis' 92-year collection, including the
fake bison on casters used in early Western pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've struggled for 30 years to create a Hollywood Museum,
and one is going up for auction today,'' said Keith Burns, a pop
culture expert brought in by the current owners, Dan Pearlman and
Robert Wolf, to place value on items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's poetic that it's the auctioneer's gavel that will sound
off the end of an era.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even the Ellis name will be going up for bid, Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its opening by Ellis Zamansky in 1908, the facility and
its adjacent graphics house have gone through the hands of a few
different owners, one of which apparently allowed the destruction
of many of the records that would identify which items were used in
which films.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgic buyers could end up purchasing items for considerably
less than they would sell for if they were properly titled, Burns
said. Still, just the chance at owning something that could have
been worn by Marilyn Monroe or shot by John Wayne is expected to
draw plenty of bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Those expected to participate in the bidding include major
studios seeking to decorate their theme parks, productions
companies, collectors, professional dealers and representatives
from other prop houses, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   The auction will mark one of many sad moments in Hollywood's
history, Burns said, adding that during the past 30 years, he has
been appalled at the indifference to Hollywood's history.
</P>
<P>
   James Comisar, who boasts he has one of the world's largest
collection of television's artifacts, browsed the facility shaking
his head as he thought about all of the artifacts that have made
their way to landfills throughout the years. ``It's horrific how
these things end up in the garbage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In modern high-tech and special-effects driven films, there is
little use for Gatling guns or ``Star Trek'' space log books.
</P>
<P>
   But to fans, these auction items are still in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people shuffled through the Ellis La Brea Avenue
facility Wednesday afternoon, getting a first-hand look at what
will be auctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Another prop house owner, who asked not to be identified, said
he has seemed to run into the same problem as the owners of the
Ellis facility: most items either run at once or just sit there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs us too much to just let it sit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Santa Clarita resident Susan Zatarain, 45, searched for movie
posters amid the vintage televisions and parking meters, she
surmised that this auction would be especially worthwhile for
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this auction will be huge,'' she said. ``You'll
literally be paying pennies on the dollar for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction will take place between 10 a.m. and 6 p.m. beginning
today and ending Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders can either go to the hotel or visit livebid.amazon.com
on the Internet. Photos of the items will be presented at the hotel
and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
