<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, LAKERS MANHANDLE PACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Indiana Pacers' worst fears became a stark
reality last night at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers came out timid, fell into a 17-point hole in the
first period and had no answer for a major Shaq Attack as the Los
Angeles Lakers captured Game 1 of the NBA Finals, 104-87.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 of the best-of-seven series will be here at 8 p.m.
tomorrow before the series shifts to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off a heated seven-game series against Portland, the
Lakers pounced on the Pacers early. Shaquille O'Neal muscled in 43
points, collected 19 rebounds and blocked three shots as the Lakers
sifted through the porous Pacers defense almost at will.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's imposing presence, combined with an unusual
disappearing act by Pacers guard Reggie Miller, left Indiana in the
Lakers' dust. Miller, a Southern California native and UCLA
product, had one of his worst NBA games ever as he scored just
seven points on 1-of-16 shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was 21-of-31 from the field and overpowered a Pacers
squad that too often used single-coverage against the league's Most
Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got the ball in deep positions and was making the quick
move and making high percentage shots,'' O'Neal said. ``Those shots
were falling. If a lot of those shots keep falling, we're going to
be a hard team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot 51.1 percent from the field and outrebounded
Indiana, 48-36, in what Lakers coach Phil Jackson called ``a
feeling-out game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought neither team played exceptional good basketball,''
Jackson said. ``We rode Shaq's coattails tonight for that victory,
and we'll be prepared for a better game \Rtomorrow\S night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period of time where we were winded and they took
advantage of it and made it difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   If winning by 17 is difficult, then the Pacers are truly in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, in his first NBA Finals, remains confident despite his
rough outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put the ball in the basket,'' Miller said. ``But if
they continue to give me those looks they're going to be in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to continue to attack the basket. It was just one of
those off-nights, and Friday will be an on night.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird defended Miller's poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not uncommon for a guy in his first Finals, after he
carried us in the playoffs, to go out and struggle,'' Bird said.
``He had one bad shooting night. There's no one giving up on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't give up on Reggie Miller because he's too valuable to
this team. The next game I hope he takes another 17-20 shots,
because that's what he is; he's a shooter and a scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant added 14 points for the Lakers, Ron Harper tallied
12 and Rick Fox 11. Mark Jackson paced the Pacers with 18 points,
Austin Croshere scored 16 and Jalen Rose and Rik Smith each scored
12.
</P>
<P>
   A nifty reverse layup by Jackson moved the Pacers within 71-69
late in the third period. But even then it was as if the Lakers
were toying with the Pacers as they went on a 25-10 run and a 96-79
lead with 4:02 left.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the surge with 12 fourth-quarter points and left the
game shortly thereafter to a thunderous ovation.
</P>
<P>
   hurt us,''] Mark Jackson said O'Neal hurt us, and ``we're going
to have to make some adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But as crazy as it sounds, we feel really good about where we
are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Lakers. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
