<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS6-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A NATIVE CROSHERE OUTPLAYS L.A. NATIVE MILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Well, at least one native Southern Californian _
playing in his first NBA Finals, eager to contribute but without
the pressure to lead his team _ had a memorable game.
</P>
<P>
   Many thought Reggie Miller would be the one, but it was Santa
Monica native Austin Croshere, the 6-foot-10 standout from
Crossroads High, who stood out in Game 1 for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   On a night Miller couldn't buy a basket (1-for-16 shooting),
Croshere scored 16 points off the bench (nine more than Miller) in
26 minutes and was the second highest scorer of any Pacer.
</P>
<P>
   He was the team-high scorer for most of the game until Mark
Jackson scored his 18th point late in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   His six rebounds were second only to Dale Davis' eight in the
final Pacer stats.
</P>
<P>
   Also, on a night the team shot 42 percent from the field,
Croshere made 6 of 7 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the primary scoring option,'' he said, ``so I'm not
double-teamed.''
</P>
<P>
   He often had his way around the court, especially when Robert
Horry guarded him. He had a team-high 11 first-half points in just
14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Croshere said he simply was taking advantage of the
opportunities the game presented, but he always has the potential
to score, especially in Game 1s.
</P>
<P>
   Against Philadelphia in the conference semifinals, he scored 11
points, grabbed 11 rebounds and added a season-high five assists.
</P>
<P>
   Against New York in the conference finals, he scored a playoff
career-high 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a double-double in the third game of the
Milwaukee series (11 points, 10 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things get overlooked in a game like this,'' teammate
Jalen Rose said. ``He led us in scoring in Game 1 of the last
series, so it's no surprise he can go out and score 16 points.''
</P>
<P>
   While the attention fell on Miller, the UCLA and Riverside star,
Croshere arrived in Los Angeles with his teammates amid no fanfare,
which he said helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last two days, I've been around family,'' he said,
``and haven't had time to think about the magnitude of the game,
the NBA Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams leave him alone in first games, then make adjustments.
Against New York, Croshere had five points. But against
Philadelphia, he scored 20 and put in 16 against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Which Croshere will show up in Friday's Game 2? He isn't sure,
but he hopes his performance Wednesday drew notices from the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they make adjustments to stop me, that's going to make
other people a whole lot more open,'' he said. ``Obviously, I'd
like to remain a scoring threat, but we need more offense from
others.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
