<HEADLINE>
RANDALL CUNNINGHAM, COWBOYS AGREE IN PRINCIPLE ON CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Free-agent quarterback Randall Cunningham has
agreed in principle with the Cowboys on a contract believed to be
worth close to $1 million in base salary and signing bonus for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, reportedly three years in length but possibly as
short as one year because of salary-cap reasons, includes a heavy
incentive package, said Cunningham, who will be Troy Aikman's
37-year-old backup with 130 NFL career starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I want to be in Dallas. It's very, very close to
getting done ... I just haven't signed anything yet,'' Cunningham
said by phone from Las Vegas last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon I get home \RHenderson, Nev.\S, I'm going to read the
contract over carefully and all the salary-cap stuff. If it's what
I think it is, I'll sign it. And I want it to be what I think it
is.'' Cunningham does not have an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Jones, Cowboys vice president//player personnel, has
been dealing with Cunningham. Jones didn't want to comment
yesterday, indicating that the team was waiting to hear from
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who was released by the Minnesota Vikings on Friday,
just 18 months after being the NFL's top-rated passer (1998), also
has had discussions with Detroit and Tampa Bay. The Bucs made him
an offer.
</P>
<P>
   His admiration for the Cowboys begins with owner Jerry Jones,
who impressed Cunningham with his desire to win another Super Bowl,
and his longtime respect for Aikman, a rival since 1989 when Aikman
broke into the NFL while Cunningham was at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of these guys who goes in and tries to take Troy's
job. I'm not one of these guys who's going to stir up things,''
Cunningham said. ``In Dallas, I know I can go into a camp, receive
the plays and have time to study them. My prayers are that Troy
stays healthy all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay appeared to be the favorite before the Cowboys entered
the bidding Saturday, when Jones and several Cowboys coaches met
Cunningham in Las Vegas during a three-day retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Jones has been very consistent with his words,''
Cunningham said. ``It's basically, `Hey, Randall, we want you.'
That's the bottom line. I want to be where I'm wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's backup is Paul Justin, 31, who previously played in
Indianapolis, Cincinnati and St. Louis. If Cunningham signs, Justin
may be in a fight for his job, or he could be kept as the No. 3
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   When Cunningham declined to take a $3 million cut in pay for
2000 on a five-year, $28-million contract that he signed with the
Vikings in December 1998, he was released. He collected a $1
million roster bonus on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the money because God is going to give
me what he believes I should have,'' Cunningham said. ``I just want
to be on the right team, with the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has been something of a Cowboys killer over the
years, 8-4 lifetime in games against Dallas. Overall, he's 79-50-1
in 14 NFL seasons, plus 3-6 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, favored to win the NFC East for a second year in a
row because of owner Daniel Snyder's aggressive off-season
spending, improved their quarterback depth by acquiring Jeff George
(who beat out Cunningham after 61/2 games last season at Minnesota)
to be Brad Johnson's backup. Jones could argue that
Aikman-Cunningham is a counter punch with clout. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
