<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS4-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ FINALLY HAS WIDE-OPEN SPACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was like exiting a crowded freeway in Los
Angeles onto a wide-open dirt road in rural Indiana. Finally,
Shaquille O'Neal and the Lakers could breathe again.
</P>
<P>
   Caged and locked down against the tall, fast, athletic Portland
Trail Blazers during the Western Conference finals, O'Neal was free
to roam in the Lakers' 104-87 victory over the Indiana Pacers
Wednesday in Game 1 of the NBA Finals at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gone were the heavy leans of 7-foot-2 Blazers center Arvydas
Sabonis and the help defense of long-armed defenders Rasheed
Wallace, Scottie Pippen and Brian Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Portland swarmed and harassed O'Neal, controlling him for long
stretches and forcing other Lakers to step up.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, not nearly as deep, quick or big, defended O'Neal
straight up with slow-footed, 7-foot-4 Rik Smits, then sent token
help from their guards and forwards. O'Neal's response? 43 points,
19 rebounds, three blocked shots and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got the ball in deep position and made a quick moves,''
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal attempted 31 shots Wednesday, making 21. He shot
!ital!nine!off! times Sunday against Portland in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a one-man show out there tonight,'' Pacers coach
Larry Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Portland, Indiana's double teams were passive,
allowing Shaq enough space to catch the ball easily, then punish
Indiana inside. The Pacers don't have enough bodies or athletic
ability to defend O'Neal the way Portland did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do a better job on Shaquille,'' Reggie Miller
said. ``We know he's going to get his looks, but when he's getting
his looks like that, a lot of them are too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were more aggressive in the third quarter after Smits
left the game with his fifth foul. Out of necessity, they started
crowding Shaq with two and three defenders when he caught the ball,
inviting him to find open teammates on the perimeter rather then
shoot over three bodies.
</P>
<P>
   It was a gamble, though. Indiana doesn't have the quickness to
double team then race back to close out shooters on kickbacks. As a
result, the Lakers were consistently getting open looks.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for a while. The Lakers went cold late in the third
and the Pacers responded with a 13-2 run to cut the lead to 75-71.
But in the fourth, L.A. made an adjustment, running players to the
basket rather than having them stand on the perimeter. O'Neal was
able to find them for easy layups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing he started doing was hitting cutters coming in
and we weren't picking up guys,'' Bird said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
