   WWII-JEWISH-CHILDREN (Paris) _ In the village of Chabannes in
the Creuse region of central France, from 1939 to 1943 some 400
Jewish children found a safe haven. The moving story of this
unlikely community has now been rescued in a documentary, ``The
Children of Chabannes.'' By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   KOONS-PUPPY (New York) _ When it comes to public sculpture, Jeff
Koons's giant topiaryesque ``Puppy'' is a rarity, a guaranteed
crowd-pleaser with serious art credentials. A 1992 work, its has
been seen in Germany, Spain and Australia, and is now stationed at
Rockefeller Center until Sept. 5. Irresistibly cute, 43 feet high
and quilted with flowers, it occupies the spot traditionally
reserved for New York's most famous Christmas tree and easily holds
down this patch of unusually fetishized turf. ``Puppy'' is
identifiably a West Highland terrier sitting attentively on its
haunches. By Roberta Smith.
