<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS3-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S QUIET NIGHT OK BY HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reggie Miller might have been nearly invisible
because of his atrocious shooting Wednesday night, but Kobe
Bryant's low profile in Game 1 of the NBA Finals was intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored a quiet 14 points in the Lakers' 104-87 victory
over the Indiana Pacers before 18,997 at Staples Center, but he
didn't mind being away from the spotlight, at least for one game.
</P>
<P>
   With Shaquille O'Neal (43 points) nearly scoring at will against
the Pacers, Bryant saw little reason to try to disrupt the game
plan of constantly feeding the ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's feeling it, you have to get him the ball,'' Bryant
said of O'Neal, who took 31 shots. ``Tonight I told him in the
locker room, `Thanks for the night off, Chief. Go get some rest.'
There are some nights when I was feeling it. It's great to roll
with the punches.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Bryant and O'Neal didn't always so easily co-exist.
This season, Bryant's willingness to relinquish scoring in favor of
team success might explain why the Lakers have reached the NBA
Finals for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Kobe's) done that all season for us,'' Lakers guard
Derek Fisher said. ``Those guys respect each other's abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that could have limited Bryant was foul trouble.
He had two fouls in the first half, then picked up two more in the
third quarter while trying to guard Indiana point guard Mark
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the fouls more on himself than anything the Pacers
were trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first foul was just my fault overplaying Mark Jackson,''
Bryant said. ``A couple other fouls were my fault as well. I don't
think they're doing anything in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored only seven more points than the struggling Miller,
but he came up huge when the Lakers needed a boost in the third
quarter. The Pacers had made up a 15-point deficit in the period,
cutting the lead to 71-69 with 1:42 left.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Bryant went to work. He hit a six-foot runner to
give the Lakers a 73-69 lead, then came back with a 13-foot running
jumper to increase the advantage to six points. It helped deflate
Indiana's momentum and restored the Lakers' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Bryant said. ``They got within two points and
the crowd started picking up and the intensity started picking up,
the pressure started building up.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was back into the shadows. He attempted just one
shot in the fourth quarter, and missed. HIs restraint was
remarkable. He even was caught in the game's final 2 minutes with
the ball in his hands as the shot clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   That's something that's almost never happened before for a
gunner like Bryant, but he's concentrating on team success at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're three games away from a championship and that's our
ultimate goal,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Pacers are probably going to pack their defense
inside against O'Neal and open up the perimeter in Game 2. It's a
trend that has occurred in the Lakers' previous playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make adjustments and I'm sure they'll concentrate
on Shaq,'' Fisher said. ``We have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bryant isn't forcing anything, while making
sure he soaks up the atmosphere of playing in his first career
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun looking up and seeing the banners. Seeing
(the words) NBA Finals on them, and on our jerseys,'' Bryant said.
``Normally, we're watching on TV and now we're playing in them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
