<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TAKE CARE OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lest anybody doubted it, Game 1 of the NBA Finals
offered incontrovertible proof that the Lakers are a reflection of
their home. We're not talking about Hollywood and its
pretentiousness, Venice and its capriciousness, Beverly Hills and
its garishness, Malibu and its stubborn individualism, or South
Central and its unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   The current object of greater L.A.'s magnificent obsession
looked like a team that belongs in an arena named for an
office-supply superstore. The Lakers' 104-87 victory over the
Indiana Pacers was so businesslike, the players might as well have
dispensed with their sweats and donned dress suits on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal produced points with all the efficiency of a
Xerox machine spitting out collated copies, collecting 43 points in
44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper, with a little help from his teammates, reduced
Reggie Miller's scoring line until it was too small to matter.
Miller missed 15 of his 16 shots from the field on the way to seven
points, 17 less than his postseason average.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers stapled the Pacers to the floor, outrebounding them
under their own basket 24-3 over the final three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   From Derek Fisher's defense on Travis Best to Rick Fox's 11
points off the bench, everybody did his part to methodically
dismantle the Pacers. It was as precise a performance as the Lakers
have mustered in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went about business the way we haven't in a long time,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers came out incredibly clear-headed for a team that
could have been forgiven for being a step slow and a little
unsteady after three days of drinking in their success in Game 7 of
the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Eschewing the flashy plays for the fundamentally sound ones, the
Lakers left it to the likes of actress Salma Hayek, who came to the
Staples Center with her black hair dyed purple, to provide most of
the color.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Lakers maintained a collective demeanor that
was very monochromatic, in sharp contrast to the kaleidoscope of
emotions they showed in their victory over Portland Sunday that
secured their spot in this best-of-seven championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Their stolid expressions sent a message to the Pacers; namely
that the Lakers are not content merely to be here in these Finals.
They played as though they have unfinished business to attend to;
namely, bringing to Los Angeles the NBA title the city has been
lustily eyeing since Phil Jackson was hired as the head coach last
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling the guys for two days, we haven't done
anything yet,'' Harper said. ``All we did was get the spot we
should be at. Don't believe the hype, I told them, and go out there
and play basketball. It was good to see everybody come in and have
their heads on straight.''
</P>
<P>
   So determined were the Lakers to treat their first NBA
championship game in nine years as though it were just another day
at the office, Robert Horry shooed a television cameraman out of
the way after pregame introductions so he could spring to the rim
and hang on for good luck, per his custom.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers would prove just as accommodating as that cameraman,
clearing out from under the basket so the Lakers could score 32
points in the paint in the first half _ 64 for the night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal methodically set up his office in the low post and went
to work on Rik Smits and, when Smits repaired to the bench to
rearrange his ribs, Sam Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-year center had 15 points after 12 minutes to set an
Indy 500-like pace. It was dizzying, really, to see O'Neal run laps
around Indiana, which stubbornly stuck to single-teaming him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq set the tone in the first quarter,'' Fox said. ``They
seem not to be very concerned about stopping Shaq. I hope that
remains the case. When he's able to get off to that kind of start,
his energy level goes up and he gets even more confident and he
starts to make plays for the others around him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Lakers looked as consolidated as the greater L.A.
metropolis is scattered. It's a breathtaking sign and we're not
talking about the block letters in the hills above Hollywood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
