<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-08 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS' MILLER VANISHES IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Swashbuckling into the NBA Finals in his old
hometown, Reggie Miller was his usual bashful self:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming in here to shock the world,'' the Indiana star
said before the series, apparently not anticipating that he would
accomplish the feat all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing so abruptly his last name could have been Dotcomstock,
Miller missed 15 of 16 field goal attempts in Game 1, shocking
those who thought Miller's preseries rhetoric was serious.
</P>
<P>
   The best way the Pacers could shock the world would have been to
do the right thing _ abdicate their position to the Portland Trail
Blazers. Making the Finals a best-of-14 between the Lakers and
Blazers ... now that would be not only a shock, but a delight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with apologies to the catchy-name skills of Shaquille
O'Neal, the Lakers-Pacers matchup Wednesday night at Staples Center
felt like The Big Anti-climax.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, unfortunately, are still so occupied peeling their
hands from their own throats that they are unavailable to accept
any invitations this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pity. The Pacers looked so overmatched Wednesday in the 104-87
defeat, particularly in view of the fact that the Lakers played,
for them, somewhat tepidly, that the remainder of this series would
be justified in avoiding release to movie houses and going straight
to video.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for those committed to seeing this thing through,
the Lakers have left enough evidence this postseason _ two losses
to Sacramento, three to Portland _ that nothing can be assumed of
them. Particularly in view of the fact that Miller can't possibly
be as bad as he was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His driving one-hander halfway through the third period saved
him from replacing Seattle's Dennis Johnson in the Finals Hall of
Shame. In Game 7 of the 1978 Finals against Washington, Johnson
went 0-14.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Johnson had the summer. Miller at least has
Game 2 Friday, and he was already playing that game in the press
briefing, as if Game 1 didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   If the point was legitimate, that would give him eight for
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they continue to give me looks like that, they'll be in
trouble,'' he said defiantly. ``All my shots felt good. If they
play me like that, it's only a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his reputation as a shooter without conscience, Miller
was unfazed by the fact that he was the biggest flop in this town
since ``Howard the Duck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad I got up only 16 shots,'' he said. ``I feel I
should have gotten 25 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Given LA's historic problems with random, reckless shooting, the
threat deserves at least a police inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Owing to Miller's newness in the environment _ after years of
chronic bridesmaid-ism, Wednesday night was the Pacers' first
appearance at the altar of the Finals _ his coach was willing to
offer slack to his star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not uncommon for a guy in his first Finals to go out and
struggle a little bit,'' said Larry Bird. ``He's carried us a long
way. He'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was resolved enough to deliver a minor shot to the
Lakers: ``The (Lakers defense) wasn't physical at all. Compared to
our last two series, this was nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers really didn't have to pound on the Pacers, who were
executing a self-thrashing that had a certain Blazers quality about
it. Absent the caliber of athletes found on the Blazers, the Pacers
decided to skip double-teaming O'Neal, which Wednesday night was a
bad idea that ranked with thatch roofs in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The large gentleman did a fair impression of the Romans as they
marched through Germania in ``Gladiator'' _ 43 points, 19 rebounds,
three blocks and a big hand in fouling out the Pacers center, Rik
Smits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so big, so powerful, he jumps so high ... he just
overpowered us,'' Bird said. ``If he keeps catching the ball in the
paint like he did tonight, we have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the carnage, the Pacers drew some resolve from the fact
that they knocked down a 17-point Lakers lead in the second quarter
to two in the third quarter and were still hanging in the game in
the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy as it sounds, we feel good about where we are right
now,'' Pacers point guard Mark Jackson said. `We feel we can make
adjustments on Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   But after O'Neal scored eight more points Wednesday than he
scored the last two games combined against Portland, the
possibility exists that the Pacers are, in fact, crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Even O'Neal was hard-pressed to devise a solution to his nimble
largeness. Asked how he would defend himself, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't. I'd just go home. Fake an injury, or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's an adjustment the Pacers might consider. It would
also shock the world, just as Miller promised.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
