<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SLOW DOWN SHAQ?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They widened the foul lane to try to stop Wilt
Chamberlain and they banned the college dunk to try to stop Lew
Alcindor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what can be done to slow down Shaquille O'Neal? And how
soon will that revised rulebook be rolling off the presses?
</P>
<P>
   Ban the offensive rebound? Ban the jump-hook? Widen Rik Smits?
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers, the rest of the Eastern Conference and NBC
television are setting up a suggestions box at Staples Center.
Deadline for submissions, Friday at 6 o'clock, in time for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   What everybody suspected but the Pacers didn't want to admit was
confirmed Wednesday when O'Neal dropped 43 points on them in
leading the Lakers to a 104-87 victory in Game 1 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers not only can't stop the Lakers' 7-foot-1, 335-pound
center, they can't even hope to contain him. Not without an act of
the rules committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (double-teamed) him, we played him straight up, and he
handled all of it,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird said, holding his
exasperation inside. ``If he catches it in the paint, we'll be in
trouble. Somehow we've got to keep him out of that paint area.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if they didn't try.
</P>
<P>
   Smits, the 7-foot-4 Indiana center, and Dale Davis, its
6-foot-11 forward, took turns. Smits and Davis joined forces in the
second quarter. Forward-center Sam Perkins (6-foot-9) came off the
bench spend 20 minutes with his shoulder in the small of O'Neal's
back, trying to push a stone uphill.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Mark Jackson (6-foot-3) made it a triple team for short
stretches, guarding Shaq from the front and trying to keep the ball
out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, raise your hand if you didn't take a turn at guarding
Shaq on Wednesday. At one point, I thought I saw Bird signal for
the guy in the Pacers-logoed tuxedo _ and his inflated flamingo _
to go in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The guy wouldn't have had a prayer. On the other hand, nobody's
ever tried a flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal played all but four minutes and hit 21 (matching his 2000
playoffs high) of 31 shots, while grabbing 19 rebounds, recording
four assists and three blocks, one of them particularly well-timed.
</P>
<P>
   After the Lakers opened a 53-36 lead in the second quarter, the
Pacers had pulled within 73-69 when Reggie Miller drove along the
left baseline late in the third, looking for his second basket of a
horrible NBA Finals debut. O'Neal bounded across the lane to swat
Miller's floater to the sideline, starting a Lakers fastbreak that
ended with a Kobe Bryant running jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everytime we got within six or four _ we got
within two at one point _ Shaq just took over the game,'' Bird
said. ``I thought we did a good job of keeping a body in front of
him, but he's so strong and he jumps so high, he just went right
over us and got the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird hesitates to double-team O'Neal because, he admits, the
Pacers aren't quick enough to get back to the shooter if Shaq
passes the ball back out, as he does.
</P>
<P>
   And Bird doesn't sound like a Hack-a-Shaq man. He said fouling
O'Neal intentionally ``isn't in the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves ... ?
</P>
<P>
   If somebody doesn't come up with something, and quick, it's not
only the Pacers who are going to pay, and not only this week. It
might be the whole Eastern Conference and it might go on for a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Western contenders have loaded up on big men with an eye on
Shaq, knowing they'll have to go through him _ or around him _ to
the Finals. Portland, with Arvydas Sabonis, Rasheed Wallace and
Brian Grant, thought it had the answer in the Western Conference
finals until about the 10-minute mark of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   But there are only so many good big men to go around. This could
become an annual event _ O'Neal faces his tests in the West, then
gets a walkover in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Hall of Famer lined up against him this time, as
there was in 1995 when Shaq's Orlando Magic was swept in the Finals
by Hakeem Olajuwon's Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of that embarrassment helps to inspire O'Neal on this
season's ``mission,'' as he calls it, to win his first title.
</P>
<P>
   He played like he meant it Wednesday, taking a big first step
toward joining Olajuwon, Bird, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Michael Jordan
and Magic Johnson on the list of regular-season MVPs who earned the
same award in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sliver of hope for the Pacers. O'Neal has enjoyed many
of his finest moments this spring in series openers _ 46 points
against Sacramento, 37 against Phoenix, 41 against Portland.
Sometimes opponents figure something out before Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to come at him a lot harder with our double- and
triple-teams,'' Smits said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a possibility. It's also a possibility the Pacers don't
have an answer. Then there's Shaquille O'Neal's answer when
somebody asked how he'd try to stop Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't,'' he said. ``I would go home. I'd fake an injury
or something.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
