<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD, BATS DO IT FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mickey Hatcher, the irrepressible hitting
coach of the Angels, has an interesting twist on how to go about
winning games, which manager Mike Scioscia disclosed,
tongue-in-cheek, prior to Wednesday night's match with San
Francisco at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hatch doesn't even know our pitchers' names,'' Scioscia was
saying. ``He just knows them by their numbers. All he asks is that
they get 27 outs, somehow, and no matter how many runs they give up
he figures his hitters will get more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher's somewhat unconventional theory then got a severe test
by the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   It was left for Darin Erstad, who had already slugged two home
runs, to single home Bengie Molina from second base with the
decisive run in the bottom of the eighth inning and the Angels came
away with a hard-earned 10-9 win in front of a crowd of 22,940.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who have displayed a remarkable knack of late by
coming from behind, this time came from ahead. They blew leads of
4-0 and 9-4, built primarily on the strength of Erstad's two home
runs, his 11th and 12th, and a three-run homer by Troy Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   But in the bottom of the eighth with the score tied 9-9 Molina
singled off of reliever Alan Embree. With two outs, Edgard Clemente
ended an 0-for-17 skid with a single to left. Erstad followed with
his run-scoring single to left, giving him five runs batted in for
the night to match his career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing out, the ball is juiced, I use a corked
bat,'' he said, kidding, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Turning serious, he added, ``I prepare, I work hard ...
sometimes it happens, sometimes it doesn't,'' said Erstad, who's
certainly making it happen far more than not.
</P>
<P>
   He's hitting a stunning .388 for the season and, on the
just-completed homestand, he was 15 for 29 (.517) with six
successive multiple-hit games, giving him an American
League-leading 33 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the one stat I care about is runs scored,'' Erstad said.
``When I cross the plate it means things are going well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad crossed it twice Wednesday night. And, as he said, things
went well.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Kent Bottenfield let a 4-0 lead get away after only
three innings. And the bullpen, which, overall, has been superb,
was tagged for five runs in just three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has been great,'' Erstad said. ``This was a night
when we (the hitters) picked !ital!them!off! up.''
</P>
<P>
   The win enabled the Angels to complete a 4-2 homestand against
the Dodgers and Giants and climb to within a game of first place in
the tight-knit American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels jumped out quickly, jolting Giants starter Russ Ortiz
(Montclair Prep) for four runs in the first inning, three on Glaus'
17th home run.
</P>
<P>
   The lead lasted all the way to the third.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield had retired the first six Giants. But in the third
inning they batted around, scoring four runs to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went to work again. Erstad slugged the first of his
two homers in the fifth inning, a two-run blow. And he hit another
two-run homer in the sixth when the Angels scored three more to
open a 9-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield left after six innings, but Al Levine certainly
didn't provide much relief. He was jarred for a pair of two-run
homers by Jeff Kent, his 17th, and by Armando Rios, his fourth. In
the space of six batters Levine's ERA shot from 3.00 to 3.74.
</P>
<P>
   And, suddenly, it was a one-run game, 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants then tied the score in the top of the eighth against
Shigetoshi Hasegawa, on J.T. Snow's one-out run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   But Hasegawa (5-1), the victim of a homer by Barry Bonds in
Monday night's 11-inning loss to the Giants, then hurled a 1-2-3
ninth to earn the win.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much as Hatcher had mapped it out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
