<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LAD     06-08 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SHAQ, ALL THE TIME IN LAKERS' GAME 1 WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the Lakers' moment in the sun at long last
arrived, the crowd dispersed, a fog lifted, and there, standing in
the daylight _ standing all alone _ was the Lakers' offensive
machine, ready to churn out points by the dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal hardly remembers daylight, blanketed as he was
by an overcast sky of Wallaces and Pippens and various other shades
of Trail Blazer for the last two weeks. But no longer. O'Neal
roamed freely again through the paint Wednesday, with nary a
double-team in sight, and he did what 7-foot-1 MVPs do.
</P>
<P>
   Catch. Shoot. Catch. Shoot.
</P>
<P>
   With a steady, repetitive rhythm a metronome would envy, O'Neal
filled the Staples Center nets for 43 points, and the Lakers rolled
to a 104-87 victory over the Indiana Pacers to take a 1-0 lead in
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was a familiar-enough sight as O'Neal hit 21 of 31 shots,
adding 19 rebounds, three blocks and four assists. But it's been
awhile since he could catch and move and jump _ or even breathe _
with such ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt pretty good to be able to get deep touches and go with
single coverage,'' said O'Neal, who faced nightly triple-teams by
Portland in the last round. ``I was just taking the high-percentage
shots, and those shots were falling.''
</P>
<P>
   So were the Pacers, to an early double-digit lead in a game they
never led after a 2-0 start. Coach Larry Bird started with single
coverage, switched to double coverage sometime after O'Neal had his
first two-dozen points, then found that wasn't much of an
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did a good job keeping a body in front of him,''
Bird said, ``but he's so powerful, and he jumps so high, he's so
strong, he just went up over us and got the ball and put it in. So
it's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as rough for the Pacers was that their version of Superman
_ Reggie Miller, who like O'Neal has come to identify with the Man
of Steel _ was a super dud. Miller went 0 for 7 in the first half
and went to the bench late in the fourth quarter having scored just
seven points on 1-for-16 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A few more nights like that, and the Lakers will have their
first championship since 1988. But they were the first to warn
against using Game 1 as an indicator of things to come. O'Neal
might not get as much space to operate. Miller certainly won't
shoot that poorly again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that once he came out early and made some
shots, his game was just there,'' teammate Ron Harper said of
O'Neal. ``And we kept throwing the ball into Shaq. And when you
throw the ball into a guy his size, the things he does, it's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper also had a successful night guarding Miller. But he
noted: ``First game. That's all it was, Game 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson said it was clear O'Neal felt more
comfortable with room to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could measure it tonight and see it,'' he said. ``You have
to remember, if you go back and look at all our beginning games
against all the teams in all the series we've played in the
playoffs, Shaq must be averaging close to 40 points a game in the
first games. Then things will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our first, frontal piece of our offensive machinery, and
our primary weapon, and teams are going to have to adjust if
they're going to beat us in a series,'' Jackson said. ``We do
anticipate they'll make adjustments at some level, and we'll have
to counter that and find a way to offensively play.''
</P>
<P>
   A third-quarter charge got the Pacers into the game for the
first and only time. Down 67-52, the Pacers went on a 17-4 run to
close the gap to two points, the closest they had been since the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson scored eight points in the run, and Dale Davis
scored twice on offensive rebounds as the Pacers briefly took
control of the boards. The Lakers absorbed the blow, and with two
quick jumpers from Kobe Bryant, then a bucket from Brian Shaw with
2.1 seconds left, pushed the lead to 77-71 to head into the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers cut a double-digit lead back to six again early in
the fourth, but O'Neal scored off an offensive rebound and Rick Fox
hit a jumper to make it 87-77. Minutes later, a Fox 3-pointer
pushed the lead to 15, and the Pacers were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed the game plan 10 times better than we have in any
game this playoff series,'' Fox said. ``That was due. It was due
that we look a lot sharper than we had.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 21 points by halftime as the Lakers raced to a 55-43
lead. Indiana had a difficult time keeping pace, with Miller
scoring zero points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (O'Neal) starts out like he did and he had the game he
had going, that's what opened it up for guys like myself and Rick
and whoever else out on the perimeter to have open shots,'' Shaw
said. ``But if we don't establish him early on in the game like
that and they play everybody else straight up, it's more of a
struggle.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
