r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS5-LA     06-08 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS5-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENCH GIVES LAKERS PLENTY OF HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Don't forget about the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the glare of Shaquille O'Neal's supernova performance
Wednesday night was the play of two Laker reserves, Derek Fisher
and Rick Fox, who didn't light up the scoreboard near as
brilliantly as O'Neal but didn't seem to mind the lack of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The little-used Fisher and the often-maligned Fox both played
arguably their best games of the playoffs, but for different
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's role in the NBA Finals can best be described as
``designated defender.'' Whenever Indiana's Travis Best enters the
game, Fisher is never far behind, charged with defending the
Pacers' quick guard. In 19 minutes, Best missed five of seven shots
and scored four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make life hard for Travis, and not even worry
about offense,'' said Fisher, who hit two of four shots and scored
five points. ``The biggest thing is just to stay in front of him.
He's going to make shots, but the biggest thing is to stay in front
of him and make him take tougher shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher averaged 14 minutes per game in the playoffs entering the
Finals, but much of that playing time came with the game already
decided. Fisher is now considered an important part of the Lakers'
success, and the mention of that fact draws a smile to his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always easier when you know what your role is,'' Fisher
said. ``I know what I have to do out there, what I have to
concentrate on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, meanwhile, had his biggest offensive output of the playoffs
with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the Portland series, Fox had to forego offense and emphasize
physical play against the Trail Blazers' larger forwards, but
against the Pacers, Fox was able to roam the perimeter and made
three of four shots from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to do much in the playoffs, and it feels
good to make an impact now,'' said Fox, who played 24 minutes, most
among Laker reserves. ``It feels nice to break out of these limited
minutes and my limited effectiveness.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
