<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES RUN WILD IN 6-1 VICTORY OVER SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sometimes the race does go to the swiftest.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly was the case Wednesday night as the Colorado
Rockies ran the Mariners off their feet, with the pace-setter being
_ no surprise here _ Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   The fleet center fielder stole four bases, including a steal of
home in the first inning, leading the Rockies to a 6-1 victory at
Safeco Field in the final game of a homestand that saw the Mariners
finish a lackluster 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had hoped for more than just settling for a winning
record. Seattle came into the homestand with a 15-6 home record,
and six wins was the target this time around. Now, after a day off,
the Mariners hit the road for a tough 10-game road trip through San
Francisco, Kansas City and Minnesota starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how we came out of it tonight, we need to do better
on the road,'' manager Lou Piniella said, cognizant that his team's
10-16 road record is hardly the stuff of which champions are built.
``Outside of the third game against Chicago (a ninth-inning loss on
an error), we played all right here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we need to do better on the road, so we might as well
start on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, in addition to setting a new personal best with the
four steals, moved into a tie for the major-league lead with
Florida's Luis Castillo with 26. He put the Mariners in a
first-inning, 1-0 hole with a subtle execution of the double steal
with teammate Mike Lansing, then two innings later stole second and
third to set up and score Colorado's second run.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part in the series, the Mariners did what they
wanted to do _ they played exceptional defense, including plays by
shortstop Alex Rodriguez and second baseman Mark McLemore that made
a few highlight reels Wednesday night. And they kept baseball's
hottest hitter down _ the Rockies' Todd Helton, hitting .418 when
the series started, went just 2-for-11.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Moyer gave the Mariners six decent innings in his second
start off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle couldn't do what it most wanted to do Wednesday _
finish the job and get that sixth win.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners couldn't do it because they couldn't shut down the
speed game. The Rockies finished with seven steals, most of them
instrumental in Colorado's minimalist offense.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Tom Lampkin said he was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had five throws (on steals) tonight, and I made four
horrible throws,'' Lampkin said. ``I had a chance to throw out all
of those guys. It was a lack of execution on my part. Usually the
runner steals off the pitcher. Tonight, they stole against me.''
</P>
<P>
   The more Lampkin thought about it, the more agitated he became
at his part in a game that gnawed at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get so mad that I want them to try to steal,''
Lampkin said. ``My arm feels so good, I call pitches hoping that
I'll get a chance to throw. What happened tonight was that instead
of burying the throw right on the bag, I was guiding the ball, and
the ball sails on me when I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners couldn't even get the minor satisfaction of scoring
the final run. John Olerud thought he'd led off the bottom of the
ninth with a home run into the right-field corner, but after
circling the bases, Olerud arrived home to find the call had been
overturned and his homer had been nothing but a long foul ball.
Olerud eventually struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-base umpire (Laz Diaz) said he didn't get a real
good look at the ball,'' said Piniella, who argued the changed
call, then watched a replay later. ``And the other three umps
assured me the ball was foul. Turns out they were right.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, who has been struggling (8-for-34, .235) on the
homestand, needed the hit to stay above .300. He finished the night
at .299, and he's just one of the Mariners' struggling left-handed
hitters. Lampkin, who drove in Seattle's lone run with a sacrifice
fly but also hit into an inning-ending double play in the sixth, is
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many runs I cost the team tonight,'' Lampkin
said. ``Offensively, they gave me pitches to hit every at-bat, but
I didn't handle them good.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella isn't that jazzed about the rest of his left-handed
lineup, which Wednesday night included Raul Ibanez (0-for-2), John
Mabry (0-for-3) and Stan Javier (0-for-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact that some of our left-handed hitters need to start
hitting the ball better,'' Piniella said. ``It's one thing to give
players rest, but the players you use (instead) need to hit the
ball a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners managed only five hits, three by the right-handed
Rodriguez, one by Olerud and one by the right-handed Edgar
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Left or right, that's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0029 </DOCNO>
