</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA FINALS: IT'S SIMPLY A MISMATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the course of human events, there have been
some scandalous mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf War in which an American-backed U.N. military
contingent crushed Iraq certainly was one.
</P>
<P>
   The fights of Joe Louis routinely deteriorated into such
one-sided recitals that his opponents became immortalized as
members of Louis' Bum of the Month Club.
</P>
<P>
   Guys who married Liz Taylor when she was young _ Eddie Fisher
comes to mind _ certainly found themselves in a harrowing struggle.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure anyone ever got the better of Howard Cosell in a
war of words.
</P>
<P>
   But for pure domination, for sheer violation, for downright
overwhelming, overpowering devastation, Shaquille's O'Neal one-man
wreckage of the Indiana Pacers Wednesday night ranks right up there
among the storied mismatches in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening moment of the NBA championship opener at
Staples Center, O'Neal turned the proceedings into his private
show, soaring above, around, over and through the awed Pacers for
43 points, 19 rebounds, three blocked shots, four assists and
thunderous ``MVP'' chants from the appreciative 18,997 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode Shaq's coattails to victory,'' said the Lakers' coach,
Phil Jackson, in an understatement of epic proportion that,
nevertheless, aptly summed up his team's 104-87 win over the
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   What O'Neal did to Rik Smits, Dale Davis and Sam Perkins and
Austin Croshere _ the principal Pacer foils who vainly attempted to
defend the Laker center _ was embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   If there was such a thing as a mercy rule in the NBA, the
referees Wednesday night would have stepped in and stopped the
plundering by O'Neal that left the Pacers battered, bruised,
bewildered, belittled and behind in this best-of-seven series that
won't go past four games unless the Pacers figure out how to slow
down O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew before the game that Shaq was going to go off
tonight,'' revealed Kobe Bryant, who gladly assumed a secondary
role _ he scored a mere 14 points _ on an evening when O'Neal sank
21 of 31 shots and failed to distinguish himself only at the free
throw line (1 of 6).
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq told me he was going to get in deep tonight. And that's
what happened. He got in deep early when they weren't
double-teaming him, and by the time they did start double-teaming
him it was too late. He was in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh was Shaquille O'Neal in a groove!
</P>
<P>
   He was Wilt Chamberlain, Bill Russell and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
wrapped into one terrifying force that refused to be silenced.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was thrilled that those Portland tormentors, Arvydas
Sabonis, Scottie Pippen and Rasheed Wallace, no longer were in the
vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was still seething over Sunday's Game 7 performance
against the Trail Blazers in which he scored a mere 18 points and
was limited to a mere 9 shot attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he desperately wanted to show Indiana the reason he was
the league's almost unanimous MVP _ some numskull sportscaster
thirsting for national publicity voted for that mighty force, Allen
Everson _ and establish early control of a series in which his team
is the huge favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, Shaquille O'Neal played with a fierce passion for 44
minutes, and the beleaguered Pacers seemed intimidated by his
hulking, 7-1, 340-pound body that was as active as it as been at
anytime this season.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked O'Neal afterward if he thought the Pacer
players were shying away for him when he was leaping for rebounds,
or wheeling toward the basket for a shot, he replied, ``I'm just
doing what I've been doing my whole career, getting the ball deep
and taking shots. I think I'm one of the last true centers left.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if the Pacers were scared of O'Neal, but none of
them came faintly close to handling him.
</P>
<P>
   And you got the impression from the opening tipoff which the
Lakers won that Phil Jackson's troops could do pretty well what
they wanted to do against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at times, they seemed to be toying with the Eastern
Conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   They built a 17-point first quarter lead (33-16), watched it cut
to 6 in the second (37-31), built it back to 17 again (53-36)
before intermission, watched it cut to 2 (71-69) in the third, and
then built it back to 17 (96-79) in a final period when O'Neal
erupted for 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to get our focus up,'' said O'Neal, whose
post-game utterances will never be entered into the National
Archives in Washington D.C. ``Game 1 is always a difficult one. We
got this one, and we just have to real ready and real focused for
Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   What can the poor Pacers did against Shaquille O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird said the double-teams were soft, and, of course,
Reggie Miller doesn't figure to miss 15 of 16 shots in an unique
achievement that was as inglorious as O'Neal's was glorious.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal caused two of Miller's misses with mighty blocks that
ignited the crowd and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal figures to dispense many more heroics before
this one is over, which could be soon if he continues his carnage
against the Pacers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 0250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
