<HEADLINE>
NASA LAUNCHES SALE OF ADVERTISING ON SPACE STATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 375-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By CHARLES ARTHUR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Space _ the final frontier. For advertising, that
is.
</P>
<P>
   The American space agency NASA intends to try to offset the cost
of the International Space Station (ISS) by selling advertising
access, and perhaps even advertising space.
</P>
<P>
   You will also be able to e-mail astronauts there, and perhaps
even talk directly to them, though they may be too busy assembling
the $60 billion ISS to take much time to reply.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was announced this week by Daniel Tam, assistant to the
administrator for commercialization of NASA. ``Some would argue
that there is nothing terribly new about viewing NASA images from
space,'' Tam told the International Advertising Association, in
London. ``After all, millions around the world watched the grainy
image of Neil Armstrong take the first walk on the moon in 1969.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Internet technologies able to ``stream'' data from
space, ``the images will be so clear that it would be like you are
there next to the astronauts and cosmonauts as they work and live
in space. It is very likely that you can actually talk to them live
as they go about their daily routine.''
</P>
<P>
   How the astronauts may feel about having one person, or one
million people, asking them through their headsets to wave as they
go past their house is not yet clear. But Tam insists: ``You
certainly will be able to send and receive e-mails from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The move has been forced on the agency by falling budgets from
the U.S. government for the past eight years. The ISS and the space
shuttle absorb half of the agency's $13 billion annual budget _ and
so they are going to have to pay their way.
</P>
<P>
   Tam will say that ``in the process of truly opening the space
frontier to all, the advertisers of the world will make it a better
world for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NASA announced a joint venture with a Silicon Valley
start-up company, Dreamtime Holdings, to create a new Internet
``portal'' at www.dreamtime.com, to provide a commercial outlet for
the huge amount of NASA space data collected over the past 40
years. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 375-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
