<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-REVENGE-CLINTON-STARR     06-08 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVENGE-CLINTON-STARR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABLES MAY HAVE BEEN TURNED ON CLINTON'S ENEMIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tables may have been turned, finally, on the
bizarre cast of characters who tried to bring down President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A new book commissioned by Talk Miramax, the Disney-owned
publishing venture headed by Tina Brown, seeks to examine the
private lives of the investigators _ including Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel who led the charge against Clinton and gave his
name to the famously lurid report into the presidential
pecadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the book was revealed Tuesday by Internet
journalist Matt Drudge, himself no friend of the Clintons, in an
apparent effort to derail it before it is even published.
</P>
<P>
   The author, John Connolly, a New York magazine journalist, has
entitled his book ``Insane Clown Posse,'' a reference to a
foul-mouthed rap group beloved of immature white American
teenagers, but also no bad way to describe the odd cast who tried
to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   The book ``digs deep into the private sex lives and business
dealings of major and minor Clinton critics,'' wrote Drudge.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed that it looked at the number of Starr's staff who
were gay, amongst other issues. ``There are no less than six gays
involved in the case. Two of the `elves,' and three of Starr's
young male protege's were gay,'' he quoted the book as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very little has been written on the personal lives of the
people who were behind the Lewinsky case,'' writes Connolly,
according to Drudge. It seems unlikely he will find out much about
Starr, who lives a life of apparently irreproachable virtue in the
Washington suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   One target is Ann Coulter, the blonde-maned, virulently
anti-Clinton columnist, who has complained of dirty tricks against
her by Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy began a program of harassment by calling me at home 6
times a day until I changed my number, sending me flowers, and
hiring a private investigator to look into my personal life,'' she
told Drudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a copy of the letter his P.I. sent to an ex-boyfriend
of mine, stating that he was hired by John Connolly to look into
me.'' The author spoke to at least one of Coulter's former
boyfriends, Bob Guccione, Jr., founder of the music magazine Spin,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter was introduced to Connolly by Lucianne Goldberg, another
key figure in the Clinton saga.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a New York literary agent who spied for the Nixon
White House in the 1972 election, is another likely target of any
probe. It was her idea for former White House employee Linda Tripp
to secretly record Monica Lewinsky's reports of sexual involvement
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg now runs a Web site where visitors can discuss whether
aliens are really Satan's angels and exchange vitriolically
anti-gay messages.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks seem to be working: Talk/Miramax seems suddenly to
have got cold feet about the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it emerges that John Connolly has been using the kind of
unprofessional means that are detailed in the Drudge Report, we
will consider cancelling the book,'' Jonathan Burnham, editor in
chief of the publisher, told the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who is gay, said the revelations about gay members of
Starr's staff concerned him. ``That disturbs me deeply, both for
personal and professional reasons,'' he told the Post. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 575-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
