<HEADER>
A7896 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-TWO-LEBANONS-OPED-IHT     06-08 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-LEBANONS-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH LEBANON HAS A HARD ROW TO HOE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 800-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOHN K. COOLEY   
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Israel's precipitate withdrawal from southern Lebanon
offers huge challenges and opportunities to investors and the
millions of Lebanese emigres abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Beirut, the once vibrant economy and outward-looking
society were devastated by the civil wars from 1975 to 1990, but
repairs had been going reasonably well since.
</P>
<P>
   Then came recent violent exchanges between Israel's armed
forces, which left southern Lebanon at the end of May, and the
Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas, now taking credit for driving them
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just how,'' asks a woman university professor with training in
both the Mideast and America, ``would you expect people to invest
or bring themselves and their money back here when from one moment
to the next you or your property might become a war victim?''
</P>
<P>
   She speaks from experience. In May, Israeli jets hit the
electric power station near her family apartment in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they set it afire,'' she recalls, ``and we lost our
electricity, their helicopter gunships came back and deliberately
strafed the fire engines and rescue crews, killing a fireman we
knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Israeli raids in May followed an especially murderous
exchange in the former occupation zone between Hezbollah fighters
and Israeli occupation troops and their Lebanese mercenaries of the
former South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   For most people now, the SLA is becoming only an unpleasant
memory. Its fighters, hangers-on and camp followers, instead of
protecting the rear of the retreating Israelis as they were hired
to do, defected, surrendered to the authorities or fled to Israel
by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss along with his senior ally, Syria,
which still keeps 35,000 increasingly unpopular troops in Lebanon,
and relief agencies now must decide if and how to repatriate SLA
members who want to come home. Some would face prosecution for
offenses including high treason, for which they could be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Upwards of 5,000 former fighters and their families languish in
Israeli resort camps. ``We'll try to help anyone,'' says a Swiss
Red Cross official here, ``who wants to risk coming home to face
the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, my Lebanese-American driver who threaded his big Chevy
through chaotic traffic and Lebanese families gawking at Israel
through the border fence, mentioned another conundrum for the
Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   As we sipped coffee in bracing, hilltop air on the edge of the
former Israeli occupation zone, there was general euphoria
generated by contented villagers and Hezbollah fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's extended Muslim family has lived for more than a
generation in Michigan, but he returned to his roots here a couple
of years ago to try to make a go of it. ``How,'' he asks, ``are you
going to get people like my family to come back here, as the
government wants?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Michigan, my family and relatives live in nice houses, like
those we saw a few minutes ago across the fence in Israel. Do they
want to come back to a ruined economy, few or no jobs, no schools
and anti-personnel mines the Israelis left behind, just because the
mountain air and the eggplants and tomatoes here taste so good?''
</P>
<P>
   In northern Lebanon, reconstruction after the civil wars revived
good hotels, restaurants, beach resorts, night life and other urban
amenities. These encouraged a few Western and Arab tourists to
return despite ruinously high real estate prices here.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Lebanon has always been a different, poorer world of
dirt farmers growing tobacco, vegetables and fruit on mostly small
plots, and undereducated villagers who dream only of emigrating to
Detroit, Los Angeles or Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Reuniting the two Lebanons would be a bit like trying to rejoin
long-separated Siamese twins. One has been growing and developing
sporadically, despite conflict and upheavals. The other is
dessicated, scarred, undernourished and weary.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from Lebanese ministries daily arrive in the south to try
get public clinics working, phones connected, tap water and
electricity connected, and roads and schools repaired. They are
finding that Hezbollah is already doing these jobs, as de facto
guardian of the south.
</P>
<P>
   As my friend Hussein reflected out loud on the road back north
to the other world in Beirut, preserving and rebuilding southern
Lebanon requires ``real peace both on the ground and on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, there is a kind of armistice, not too unlike the
one that Lebanon signed with the new state of Israel in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the needed peace accords between Israel and Syria and
Lebanon are still only hopeful memoranda. Providing the real thing
and guaranteeing it must now be the task of those in Damascus,
Jerusalem, London, Paris and Washington who are dedicated to
building a better Middle East. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: John K. Cooley, an author and ABC News
correspondent based in Athens, lived and worked in Lebanon for many
years. He contributed this commentary to the International Herald
Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 800-word commentary from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 0259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TWO-LEBANONS-OPED-IHT     06-08 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
