<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ (Ernest Murray is managing editor of The
Lufkin Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ There is an 8x10,
black-and-white photo of Mickey Mantle hanging in my office. ``To
Gary, Mickey Mantle'' is scrawled in black ink. Mantle is in Yankee
Stadium, down on one knee, a Louisville Slugger leaning against his
then-strong body, a slight smile on his face. The photo is sharp
enough that you can read the inscription on the bat: ``Genuine
Mickey Mantle Louisville Slugger.'' What else?(Gary Borders is
editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED
for Sunday. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush is getting the
oddest form of political praise since, since _ uh, since Ronald
Reagan was getting it. Al Gore is getting the most curious slam
since, since _ uh, since Michael Dukakis was getting it. Here they
are in tandem: Bush gets credited for saying ``I don't know.'' Gore
gets graded down for knowing too much. (John Young is opinion page
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   DINING-SANFRANCISCO _ SAN FRANCISCO _ You don't ask for seconds
at the French Laundry, the Napa Valley restaurant where any meal
may consist of 15 mini-courses. Each is a two-bite inspiration, an
arresting sensation of the here and now slipping down your throat.
That is the reason that people book their plane tickets around a
reservation at Thomas Keller's 62-seat sensation that has become
the non plus ultra of America's dining destinations. To reserve,
you must call two months to the exact calendar date ahead of time,
and be prepared for stinging rejection if others beat you to the
punch. But even if you can't book at the French Laundry, the Bay
Area has now more than ever enough outstanding dining options to
guarantee a thrill at every turn. To make the most of your vacation
you have to plan meal by meal ... which we are only too happy to do
for you. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BISTRO _ How is that two exquisite, authentic French bistros are
a few doors from each other in, of all places, the Napa Valley? We
tell...(Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   CHEF-SCOTT _ Atlanta native Sarah Scott, an executive chef at
the Robert Mondavi Winery in Napa Valley, shares her Top 10
favorite Bay area restaurants. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
freelancer; not for use by NYTNS clients.) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   BIO-PARK _ SANTO DOMINGO DE HEREDIA, Costa Rica _ The guide's
voice was curiously lacking in urgency as she turned suddenly,
pointed to my feet and said: ``Watch out for the coral snake.'' Her
warning had all the concern of someone telling me I was about to
step on a wayward house cat or an errant ball instead of a highly
venomous tropical serpent. Welcome to the National Institute for
Biodiversity Park, a unique environmental theme park that opened in
February. (Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ ANNISTON, Ala. _ Driving I-20 between Atlanta and
Birmingham, skimming by fireworks bazaars and barbecue palaces, you
wouldn't imagine that Hitler's silver tea service and Napoleon's
good-luck charm are just beyond the Anniston exit ramp. Or that
those rarities keep company with dinosaurs, a savannah full of
mounted African wildlife, a century-old collection of extinct and
endangered birds, a pair of Egyptian mummies, and Jeff Davis'
pistols. They're all here, with much, much more, in the Berman
Museum and Anniston Museum of Natural History, side-by-side in
Lagarde Park. (Schemmel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer;
not for use by NYTNS clients). 38. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
