<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-C     06-08 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: OUR NEW DANCE OF DEATH
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From time to time during the Persian Gulf war,
Patriot missiles shot down incoming Iraqi Scuds on their way to
Saudi Arabia. But most Patriots couldn't hit their targets, and
those that did caused damage when their debris fell from above.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, President Clinton is on his way to deploying 100
interceptors in Alaska to shoot down incoming rockets from rogue
states or terrorists. Vice President Al Gore endorses the program,
while Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his likely rival to succeed
Clinton in the White House, wants to do even more.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks like the idea of having an umbrella around in case of
rain. It rains quite often in Seattle, where Boeing, as prime
contractor, has been billing taxpayers at a rate of $2 billion a
year for the current six-year phase of the anti-missile project.
</P>
<P>
   The big idea is to give Clinton technical cover by having the
system pass some tests before he gives Gore political cover by
approving ``limited'' deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign governments abhor the idea. They tend to view such
shields as destabilizing, following the same train of thought that
President Nixon followed when he signed the ABM Treaty in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   (Some Republicans in Congress hold the quaint view that the ABM
Treaty is dead because the Soviet Union is gone. Inconveniently,
the United States signs treaties that view Russia as the legitimate
successor to the Soviet Union.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, Boeing and Uncle Sam are batting .500 in the Missile
Defense League.
</P>
<P>
   The first test, last Oct. 2, proved that a homing mechanism
could intercept a target traveling at intercontinental-range speeds
when fired on a near-collision course under ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The second test, on Jan. 18, using more advanced components,
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another test, known as IFT-5, is scheduled soon. It will
take until IFT-19, to be held in 2005, before the project has its
first operational flight test.
</P>
<P>
   By then, many domestic politicians who like the missile project,
and many foreign leaders who don't, are likely to have moved on.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unlikely that opinions will shift in the scientific
community, which by and large views the project as a waste of
money. On this issue, the scientists link arms with the arms
controllers, who recall engaging in the same sobering dance of
death during the Cold War and arguing, successfully, for a ban on
nuclear missile shields.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, a policy analyst at the Federation of American
Scientists, said, ``It's fairly easy to imagine the Chinese
thinking, 'because China is now a great power, and because the
Americans and Russians won't build down to China's level of
strategic forces, maybe (we) should build up to theirs.' Looking
ahead 10 or 15 years, that's the main reason I would be sorry for
making these decisions today.''
</P>
<P>
   But most politicians find it hard to make decisions beyond the
next election. And Clinton, who for the first time has no elections
lying in wait, feels he must defend the National Missile Defense
Act, which he signed into law last July 23 and which mandates
deployment of a system ``as soon as is technologically possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
