<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX     06-08 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: HAVING THE PRESIDENT FOR DINNER
 &HT;    By JOE MURRAY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We were arguing politics. That's what friends do.
</P>
<P>
   Was he a successful president or was he not?
</P>
<P>
   I said he was. My friend said he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   I said, despite some ups and downs, he has to his credit a
general period of prosperity during his two terms in his office and
_ lest we forget _ he was the president who got us out of Korea.
</P>
<P>
   My friend said his creation of the Interstate highway system _
funded as a business favor to the auto industry _ pushed ugly,
urban sprawl across rural America, and, in addition, his botched
Cuban diplomacy was a legacy of disaster waiting to happen, and
which shortly did happen with the Bay of Pigs invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Old politics _ as far back as the Eisenhower administration _
was what we were arguing. That's what really old friends do.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I'm in Washington, he and I get together, convening at
a restaurant of his choosingto discuss politics, then and now.
</P>
<P>
   He talks pretty good politics. He picks very good restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   This was a small French place way out on Connecticut Avenue NW,
a long cab ride for me but only a short distance for him. As a
matter of logistics, it was the logical choice.
</P>
<P>
   Though still a world traveler, my friend is nearing 80 and has
been staying closer to home the past year after replacement surgery
on his knees. Everything seems to be going well, and the hope is
that he'll be going as strong as ever before too long.
</P>
<P>
   The other evening was the first time we had been together since
last fall. The first thing he did was apologize for the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be such a nice, dingy little place,'' he said,
looking with remorse around the clean, well-lighted, brightly
decorated interior. ``Then they remodeled it, the crowds started
coming and the food hasn't been the same since.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can't have everything.
</P>
<P>
   I had the soft-shell crabs, he had the veal medallions and, in
honor of each other's company, we each had one more glass of
influential beverages than normally we allow ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, there were fresh raspberries and ice cream, frothy
coffee and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   That's as far as we had gotten, the Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls JFK with a deep fondness for the fallen hero and all
the glory that once was Camelot, whose great promise likely would
have been fulfilled in a second term.
</P>
<P>
   I see Kennedy as a rogue aristocrat, but astute politician, who
had back-pedaled on the civil rights issues he supposedly
championed, and, moreover, was likely to be exposed during the
upcoming election for the womanizer that he was. Assassination, at
it turned out, was a good career move.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter. I had my say, my friend had his say, and we both
had a good dinner, parting friends the same as always.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine our ever falling out over politics, not with so
much still ahead of us.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Johnson administration, the Nixon administration,
the Ford administration ... the list goes on and on, and then
starts over again.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas 75915; Web site, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
