<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0609-CO     06-08 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    Remembering the Mick and his restaurant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ There is an 8x10, black-and-white photo of
Mickey Mantle hanging in my office. ``To Gary, Mickey Mantle'' is
scrawled in black ink. Mantle is in Yankee Stadium, down on one
knee, a Louisville Slugger leaning against his then-strong body, a
slight smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The photo is sharp enough that you can read the inscription on
the bat: ``Genuine Mickey Mantle Louisville Slugger.'' What else?
</P>
<P>
   There is just a hint of crow's feet under his eyes. He was
probably just past his prime when the photo was taken. Maybe it was
1961, when Roger Maris hit 61 home runs to break the Babe's record,
and Mantle chased right behind him with 54. Or 1964, when the
Yankees won their fifth straight pennant but couldn't beat St.
Louis in the World Series, falling victim to Bob Gibson's fastball.
By then, Mantle's knees were beginning to give out. He would limp
along with only occasional flashes of his old brilliance for a few
more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   I got my photo when Mantle opened a restaurant in Longview, out
on Highway 80 west of town, down by the used-car lots.
</P>
<P>
   A new building was built a mile or so past Treasure City, an
early precursor to Wal-Mart, long gone now. The restaurant was
called something like ``Mickey Mantle's Country Cooking,'' and it
opened in 1970. Mantle planned to open a string of these
country-cooking places throughout Texas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   My parents took us to eat there when Mantle came to town for the
grand opening, and I stood in line for an hour or so to get his
autograph. Mantle stood patiently, signing a stack of 8x10s. I
shook his hand and got him to inscribe a photo to me. I remember
even in retirement he still seemed strong enough and fit enough to
play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant flopped. I don't know why. Maybe the food was
lousy. Maybe Mantle was ahead of his time. After all, country
cooking was what everybody ate at home in East Texas in 1970, or
maybe while on the road in places with names like ``Gladys' Cafe,''
or ``Mom's'' -- places with no air-conditioning and fly strips
hanging from the ceiling. If you planned to go to a nice, sit-down
restaurant, you probably wanted something more exotic than chicken
and dumplings. That's what I had on my only visit to Mickey's
place.
</P>
<P>
   These days, country cooking is all the rage, because hardly
anybody has time to cook those types of meals at home, and we're
all worried about cholesterol and fat. These days, chicken and
dumplings are an exotic treat.
</P>
<P>
   Last time I looked, a church was operating out of Mantle's old
restaurant site in Longview.
</P>
<P>
   I was not a Yankee fan as a child. Far from it. I was, and still
am, a Boston Red Sox fan, which means I view the Yankees with the
same low estimation as Teasips view Aggies. I am a Teasip too,
which means I get to suffer both through baseball and football
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 10 years of my life, the Yankees won the pennant
nine times. Lucky for me, I was blissfully ignorant of baseball
until I was about six or so and could read, so I only suffered for
five years or so. I learned to read as much by going over the
Boston Record-American box scores and game stories as I did
struggling through ``See Spot run.''
</P>
<P>
   I hated the Yankees, but I loved Mickey Mantle. It was hard not
to. He was that good. I would dream that the Yankees would go
insane and trade him to Boston. With my true baseball hero, Carl
Yastrzemski, batting third, and Mantle batting cleanup, maybe my
team could rise out of the cellar to the top. Thus are the dreams
of children.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, Mantle went over the edge from simply
a hard-drinking, carousing ballplayer whose most famous line was
``If I'd known I was going to live this long, I would've taken
better care of myself,'' to a full-blown alcoholic who went public
with his addiction after checking into the Betty Ford Clinic. By
last week, he was dying in a Dallas hospital, his liver ruined.
</P>
<P>
   Mantle got lucky. A liver donor was found and transplanted. He's
not out of the woods, but his odds are improving.
</P>
<P>
   Root for him to make it. He has not exactly led an exemplary
life since leaving baseball, but man, he gave us baseball fanatics
some great memories. Even if it was against the home team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
