<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mr. Spock or Sgt. Schultz
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush is getting the oddest form of
political praise since, since _ uh, since Ronald Reagan was getting
it.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is getting the most curious slam since, since _ uh,
since Michael Dukakis was getting it.
</P>
<P>
   Here they are in tandem: Bush gets credited for saying ``I don't
know.'' Gore gets graded down for knowing too much.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stretch to say that Bush on the campaign trail is Sgt.
Schultz, whose ``I know nothing _ nothing!'' guarantees job
security. But Bush is not posing as a Star Trek commander, either.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, a reverse condition. Advisers urge that he drop the
Mr. Spock routine, lest one of his own aides one day writes the
fall-of-Gore memoir, ``All Too Humanoid.''
</P>
<P>
   These rivals offer a most interesting contrast when they debate
face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times' Frank Bruni is among those who have observed
the apparent mileage Bush has gotten as the candidate who doesn't
read heavily, who doesn't know intricate details, and who indeed
appears to wear that condition as a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this exchange relayed by New Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson
when he and Bush were at a governor's conference with speakers
weighing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``George turns to me and says, `What are they talking about?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   To this, Bush told his GOP compatriot, ``You don't know a thing,
do you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one thing,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush replied, ``Neither do I.'' And then they high-fived.
</P>
<P>
   A curious trait, Capt. Kirk. These beings apparently have a
secret code that includes hand-gesture greetings.
</P>
<P>
   NOT A DETAILS GUY
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who spends time with Bush should not be surprised at the
exchange. He does not present himself as the Answer Man. He is as
engaging as he is disengaged from nuts and bolts. He is one who
sets goals and who delegates the details.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, that is easier to pull off as governor of Texas.
The legislature meets every other year. The Reconstruction-era
constitution almost makes a governor subservient to the lieutenant
governor, who runs the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. presidency by contrast is only the most powerful
elected office in the solar system. So, what commander will it be,
voters?
</P>
<P>
   CURSE OF SPECIFICITY
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush has learned the age-old lesson that
vagueness pays and details sometimes only incite.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is one issue on which Bush has not sprinkled
generalities like Bac-Os. The experience shows that a little
specificity demands a lot.
</P>
<P>
   How much would the Bush plan syphon off for private retirement
accounts? And how to replace the money now being paid to cover
current retirees?
</P>
<P>
   Or take the issue of an anti-missile system, which under Bush
would be far more extensive than the limited system proposed by
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush last week said he envisions an umbrella not only for this
continent but for U.S. allies as well. Hmmm. Best be vague about
those costs.
</P>
<P>
   The time will come when the details guy, Gore, will square off
against Bush under studio lights. It will be fascinating to see if
Gore's background of having been in Congress for 16 years and vice
president for two terms will result in a technical knockout, or if
Bush will dance his way past the details and into America's hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere right now someone is trying ``I don't know'' out as a
billboard slogan beside the candidate's smile, or maybe a bumper
sticker for the masses: ``Bush: He don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
