   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GECKO-STICKY-FEET (San Francisco) _ They're Tokay geckos _ big,
sometimes nasty-tempered lizards that resemble miniature dinosaurs.
Their feet are almost unbelievably sticky, which allows them to
scamper across walls and ceilings with ease. With so much ease, in
fact, that scientists at the University of California at Berkeley,
Stanford and elsewhere are investigating an astonishing possible
explanation for their stickiness based on invisible micro-forces of
the atomic world. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   VOCATIONAL-EDUCATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Facing fears that some
high school students won't pass the New York state exams to be
required for graduation, some Board of Regents members want tests
tailored to vocational students. The idea is to improve the
educational program _ and job prospects _ for the roughly 295,000
high school students in such courses as auto mechanics, building
trades and computer networking. But educators fear the new exams
may prove onerous to those who study trades and who previously were
not required to take the tests. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The best employees think like
owners, the best owners think like employees, and the best
companies think like customers. If you consider yourself a good
employee and you see that your company is about to lose a customer,
do whatever you can to fix it. If your corporate culture frowns
upon that, think seriously about whether you're working for the
right company. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT NEWS (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOLA-GLAUDINI (San Francisco) _ While writer and director Greg
Harrison makes an ambitious stab at exploring San Francisco's rave
subculture in his new film, ``Groove,'' it is actress Lola Glaudini
that most moviegoers will walk away remembering. Either Harrison
saved all of his best lines for Glaudini's character, Leyla, a
transplanted New Yorker whose dreams of continuing her education
seem to have once again dissolved into the nightlife, or Glaudini
is the one actor in the film capable of lending her character any
real depth. Let's go with the second option. By CRAIG MARINEB.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-WINE (Sebastopol, Calif.) _ As a single mother, Barbara
Hom often sits down to a meal of grilled cheese sandwiches and a
glass of wine. As a businesswoman, her job is paring foods with
wine. But don't ever accuse her of being a wine snob. In fact, her
philosophy might be summed up this way: Never apologize for your
taste in food or wine, because everybody's palate is different. By
BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-STEELY-DAN (Concord, Calif.) _ The musicians of Steely Dan
are not lousy, they are just playing lousy music, a kind of hybrid
form that takes a bit of rock and a bit of jazz and a bit of soul
and screws up the best parts of each. Toss in pretentiously
innocuous lyrics and what you have is the ``Star Wars'' of music _
geek worship. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVOR (Undated) _ Wouldn't it be great to have 16
celebrities compete in the ``Survivor'' television contest? Tony
Danza, Kathie Lee Gifford and Martha Stewart are among our choices
for castaways. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BELMONT-STAKES (Elmont, N.Y.) _ For the first time in 30
years there will be no Kentucky Derby or Preakness winner, but
Wednesday's draw brought a competitive field of 11 3-year-olds to
the fore for the 132nd Belmont Stakes, five of them newcomers to
this Triple Crown series. Peter Pan winner Postponed figures to be
the strongest of the five for Saturday's $1_million Belmont. He is
trained by Scotty Schulhofer, the defending Belmont champion. By
MATT GRAVES.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-STEVE-YOUNG (Santa Clara, Calif.) _Steve Young's fateful
Friday deadline to bring to a close his protracted career decision
may slop over to Monday with the expected announcement that he
plans to retire from football. Sorry about that, Denver. San
Francisco 49ers executives say the 38-year-old quarterback and
expectant father wants time to gather ``his people'' together for
his retirement announcement. Sorry about that, Littleton. By JOHN
CRUMPACKER.
</P>
