<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refilling ink cartridges saves money but can be risky
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I read that a kit has been developed and is being sold that
allows you to refill black or color printer ink cartridges. I want
to try it but can't remember the company offering the kits. Can you
help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Dobrin, Beachwood, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Sue: There are two schools of thought on refilling ink
cartridges in printers. One is that you shouldn't do it because the
risk outweighs the cost savings. The other is to get a good kit and
do it right to save a buck or two.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Yeah, if you get a bad kit or refill the ink cartridges
improperly, you run you the risk of spilling ink inside your
printer. You could have quite a mess on your hands, literally. All
the money you would have saved is put toward getting your printer
cleaned out.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: On the other hand, you can save quite a bit of money.
You'll pay $25 to $30 for four to six color refills. As for the
black cartridge, you'll pay about the same for the kit but get 10
to 15 refills. Think about it. Instead of paying 20 bucks a pop,
you're getting several refills for the price of one. Be aware,
different printers require different ink formulas. No one ink works
for every printer. Make sure you buy specifically for your printer.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You cannot refill indefinitely. You may be able to refill
up to 20 times if you take care of your cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: There are many companies out there that provide this
service. Check out Richland Marketing at www.refills.com. They have
kits for Apple, Canon, Epson, HP and a few others. Other sites to
research are www.netwares.com or
www.affordableprinter.com/right.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Before replacing our PC, we want to ensure all personal account
numbers and information are removed. Is there software available?
One suggestion was to reformat the hard disk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Nicolson, Cumming, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Your concern is legitimate. Deleting files doesn't
necessarily erase those rascals. It just removes pointers or
references to where those files are located. Anybody who knows
squat about a computer can recover that data. Even reformatting the
hard drive can still leave data behind that somebody can ferret
out.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: The good news is that there are utilities that can zap your
data for good. They act as electronic paper shredders. One option
is BCWipe for Win 95/NT. It's a free disk tool that gets rid of
files permanently. Go to cnet.com, and search for BCWipe.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Another file-wipe freebie is Eraser for Win 95/98/NT. It
overwrites files over and over using carefully selected patterns.
It removes all the magnetic bits and pieces from the hard disk.
It's also at cnet.com. Also, a good source for these two utilities
and freeware in general is freewarefilez.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
