<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-YARD-VACATION-LADN &LR;      06-08 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARD-VACATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASING INTO BACKYARD BLISS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
So you want to get away without taking an elaborate vacation? OK.
Pick a nice warm day _ which shouldn't be difficult these days.
Step outside, take a good look around and repeat the following
(mood music and chanting rhythm optional):
</P>
<P>
   My yard is my sanctuary ... My yard is my sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it can be. With a little bit of work, that little
bit of at-home seclusion will be yours for the enjoying _ during
the warm summer and all year long.
</P>
<P>
   How much work, and what kind, is strictly up to you. Homeowners
have been known to hire a landscaper to redo their entire garden or
build an enclosed atrium or gazebo. Creating your sanctuary could
involve bringing in some comfortable patio furniture, or installing
a hammock that practically screams ``Relax!'' _ or perhaps simply a
chaise and some strategically hung wind chimes will do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Those willing to part with a little more cash might install a
pond, a fountain or both. The sound of water, say garden and design
experts, is a tranquillity enhancer. Ditto, the presence of
chirping birds, which a well-stocked feeder or bird bath is likely
to bring. Plants like columbine and buddleia will attract birds and
butterflies. Use ferns for the shadier areas. Trees can be soothing
and effective as a buffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice when people do some privacy planting of trees around
the perimeter zone,'' says Randy Mineo, owner of the Chatsworth
Nursery Center and Custom Landscaping. ``You won't have anyone
staring in. Plus, it's greenery.''
</P>
<P>
   Landscaping is by no means your only option. You can carve out a
bit of seclusion using anything from a simple bench to some
decorative lighting to careful use of shade. Maybe the aromatic
plants will help you set the mood. Or maybe, it's all in the
decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Fritz, home decorating consultant for Target stores, says
glass gazing balls that reflect surrounding areas are gaining
popularity as well. Officials from Home Designs say little outdoor
wood fireplaces called chimeneas are starting to ... er ... heat up
with customers anxious for some evening outdoor lounging.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing balls, stepping stones, outdoor fireplaces ... where to
even begin?
</P>
<P>
   First, consider your space, experts say. Determine what sorts of
atmosphere enhancers you find relaxing, then figure out what works.
Develop a philosophy about what you're trying to achieve, whether
the goal is to re-create a Mediterranean garden or simply to carve
out a little hideaway where you can sneak off to be alone and quiet
with your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I describe it, the idea is to bring the indoors
outside and the outdoors inside, blurring the lines between the
two,'' says Linda Hallam, the Iowa-based editor and writer of two
outdoor decorating books (``Garden Style'' and its follow-up
``Garden Style Projects'') published by Better Homes and Gardens.
``Just going outside isn't all that comfortable if you don't have
the shade and somewhere comfortable to sit.''
</P>
<P>
   Shade from the summer heat is critical, which is one reason
large market umbrellas will never be out of style. Only the shapes
and colors will change says Gil Kemp, president of the Home
Decorators Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the person with the 1/2-acre yard has more options
than the one with the townhouse balcony. If you've got enough yard
space to make strolling a viable option, landscape designer Rita
Goodman recommends incorporating elements of the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little meandering pathways, with a little surprise at the end
like a fountain or a bench,'' says Goodman, the owner of Rita
Marshall Goodman Designs in Tarzana. ``Something where you don't
see everything at once. Maybe you'll have a gateway or a trellis
leading into another area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do really lovely things in a very small space with
furniture, the right lighting and plants if you lay everything out
properly,'' she added. ``Figure out what's going to be dominant and
what's not so important.''
</P>
<P>
   A small and somewhat challenging space is precisely what Mary
Stephenson had to work with, since her Saugus home is built into a
hillside. She ended up putting in a pond and a waterfall, but
didn't make that area a place to sit and relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no walkway, but you can look out over it and just get
an overall feeling of calmness,'' says Stephenson. ``I can hear the
waterfall through all of my windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson works at Garden Concepts in Santa Clarita, a store
that specializes in fountains, statues and ponds. Garden Concepts
recently helped restore and enhance a 1-million-gallon outdoor fish
pond and fountain at the Norton Simon Museum of Art in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of us don't need something on quite that large a
scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like whimsical,'' says Garden Concepts co-owner Melissa
Moat. ``We've built a pond out of a whiskey barrel with a little
sprayer frog. Some people only want to spend $300. Others will
spend $5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   A secluded bit of backyard bliss doesn't necessarily mean your
entire yard has to be off limits. When she moved into her Agoura
Hills home, Carlyn Medaglia says she and her husband expected to
leave her large yard rustic and parklike. A portion of the hillside
was lost during flooding, so the Medaglias had to resurface with
railroad ties and overhanging bushes. They also have a somewhat
tucked-away gazebo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've left it pretty natural,'' Medaglia says.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of it. The family also had growing children who
would later use the large grassy area to practice soccer and
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking to do some evening outdoor lounging can do a lot
with mood lighting. Votive candles and luminarias are popular, as
are many different types of lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always use one color, usually a warm light with a low
voltage,'' says Goodman. ``It adds an extra sparkle to the trees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
