<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for  &UR; FRIDAY,
June 9,  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-TERROR (Athens) _ Britain's defense attache was killed
early Thursday in a roadway ambush that police believe could be the
work of Europe's most elusive urban guerrilla group, November 17,
which has claimed 21 killings since 1975. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Abandoning plans to create any type
of representative government in Chechnya, President Vladimir Putin
on Thursday signed a decree imposing direct presidential rule in
the breakaway republic. The direct rule will likely last two to
three years. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Japan's former prime minister, Keizo
Obuchi, was remembered Thursday in a solemn state service marked by
effusive eulogies, cannonades, an honor guard dressed in crisp
white uniforms and thousands of dark-suited mourners, including
President Clinton. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N (United Nations) _ With the secretary-general issuing a
report that says Iraq now has plenty of its own money to meet its
needs, the Security Council is prepared to extend by six months the
oil-for-food program. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown) _ As British marines prepared to leave
Sierra Leone, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook on Thursday visited
Freetown and pledged long-term support. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-EXECUTE (Miami) _ Florida's third effort to put a man to
death by lethal injection, after a series of botched electrocution,
went gruesomely wrong on Wednesday when prison officials struggled
for 33 minutes to insert an intravenous tube into a convicted
killer. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CONEY-ISLAND (New York) _ Old-timers and tourists and
politicians cling to the distant fantasy that Coney Island will be
what it once was, and now there are grand plans from City Hall: a
$31 million sea-front stadium; $30 million more for amateur sports
facilities; and another $30 million for a boardwalk facelift. By
David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOTEL-CBS (New York) _ Bryant Gumbel's Early Show on CBS
decided to have bands play in the morning in front of the studio at
Fifth Avenue and 59th Street. But the bands wake the guests at the
nearby Sherry Netherland Hotel, and on Thursday the hotel is taking
CBS to court. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INSECTICIDE (Undated) _ Dow Chemical has agreed to stop
making the main ingredient in almost every household insecticide
after an Environmental Protection Agency review showed that the
chemical, chlorpyrifos, is more of a health risk to humans,
particularly children, than previously thought. By Andrew C.
Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES _ Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FINANCE (Washington) _ The Senate is scheduled to vote
on campaign finance reform in a measure introduced into an
unrelated bill by Sen. John McCain. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   A package of articles on the Microsoft antitrust case is
planned, including: MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Undated) _ A reconstruction of
the Microsoft antitrust trial. By Steve Lohr and Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (With)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SCHOLARS (Undated) _ Legal scholars react to the
Microsoft trial. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD (Los Angeles) _ Over the last year or so, the
worlds of old-line Hollywood and the dot-coms of the new economy
have been intermingling with increasing urgency, taking their first
faltering steps toward the coming age of digital entertainment,
whatever that might turn out to be. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-RATES (Frankfurt) _ The European Central Bank surprised
investors Thursday by raising interest rates by a half point, to
4.25 percent. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan will release first-quarter GDP data.
By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   PA-COAL-MINES (Scranton, Pa.) _ The hundreds of visitors who
take the guided tours at the Lackawanna Coal Mine every day are
meant to come back into the sunshine with a greater appreciation of
a way of life that left deep veins of loss, misery and cultural
trauma through successive generations of families in the anthracite
fields of Northeast Pennsylvania. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   SNAPSHOTS-MET (New York) _ Family snapshots have become art in a
highly unusual and sublimely endearing exhibition called ``Other
Pictures: Vernacular Photographs From the Thomas Walther
Collection'' at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   PLOTLESS-BALLET (New York) _ Plotless ballets, sometimes
dramatic in an abstract way, continue to reign supreme among
American choreographers. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   PIMP-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``American Pimp,'' a terse,
skillfully edited documentary by the Hughes Brothers (Allen and
Albert), is a breezy montage of interviews with pimps of varying
ages in several U.S. cities that purports to uncover the realities
behind the myths surrounding those flamboyantly attired street
hustlers. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   CHABANNES-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Children of Chabannes,''
a documentary, was made by Dean Wetherell and Lisa Gosselsa and is
a moving record of the heroism of ordinary people in the village of
Chabannes who gave refuge to nearly 400 Jewish children, protecting
them from the Nazis. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   VERITE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ The documentary ``Cinema Verite''
by Peter Wintonick asks whether cinema verite is a style or a
movement; a technique or a philosophy; or, as Frederick Wiseman,
one of its great avatars, suggested, a piece of ``pretentious and
pompous'' French jargon? Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   LABOURS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Kenneth Branagh has directed
``Love's Labour's Lost,'' a whimsical, affected adaptation of
Shakespeare's most forgettable early comedy. Reviewed by A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SUNSHINE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ The century, or at least one
Hungarian Jewish family's experience of it, from the twilight of
empire to the fall of communism, is the subject of Istvan Szabo's
churning, sometimes clumsy, often thought-provoking _ and decidedly
long _ film, ``Sunshine.'' Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
