<HEADLINE>
GREEN ARCADIAS PAST AND FUTURE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By MAC GRISWOLD  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    There is now another pressing reason to visit Wales this summer,
besides Welsh Black beef, cut from the only cattle in Britain that
have never been fed anything but good green Welsh grass, or so the
Welsh say.
 &HT;    After dining royally on one of those filets cooked by Rod
Peterson, the acclaimed chef at the Cawdor Arms Hotel in Llandeilo,
I headed for the new National Botanic Garden of Wales in nearby
Llanarthne. There I was delighted to find the same natural-systems
approach to the world, but transformed into the most advanced _ and
good-looking _ sustainable machinery for keeping plants, people and
interior climates in sync.
 &HT;    The heart of the 568-acre garden, the first new national botanic
garden in Britain in two centuries, is Sir Norman Foster's
312-foot-long transparent oval bubble, the Great Glass House,
rising lopsidedly above what was once private parkland and pasture.
 &HT;    It is sunk into the hillside to conserve heat and tilted to
offer views of the countryside as well as to receive maximum sun.
The garden hadn't opened when I visited in December, but the solar
machinery was already cranking comfortably.
 &HT;    Additional heat comes from an environmentally friendly ``biomass
burner,'' also handsomely housed by Foster &AMP; Partners and fueled by
wood cut from a nearby coppice of trees, the kind that can be cut
back to stubs that will continually sprout new shoots (poplars,
willows).
 &HT;    These are especially vigorous thanks to a boost from the
nutrient-rich water produced by a natural waste treatment system
that handles all effluents. And if that hard-working coppice
doesn't provide enough fuel, local contractors will be given tax
rebates to haul in clean lumber waste.
 &HT;    The botanical garden is the first in the world where the energy
demands required to care for rare and endangered plants have been
designed to have as little impact on the environment as possible.
It is also the first to group together in one macroclimate the
flora of a single ecosystem from all continents, instead of having
a little glass-enclosed rain forest, say, followed by a separate
desert enclave.
 &HT;    The computer-generated high-precision geometry that has made
global architecture more curvaceous and freeform (Frank Gehry's
Bilbao Guggenheim, or Foster &AMP; Partners' Canary Wharf station
entrances to the London Underground) has been used here to make one
large arched chamber, the largest single-span glass greenhouse ever
built.
 &HT;    The ecosystem it displays is what is known as ``Mediterranean,''
which confusingly includes other regions that are nowhere near the
Mediterranean itself.
 &HT;    Chile, California, Southwest Australia, South Africa and the
Canary Islands all possess geographic areas and climatic conditions
that are similar to those of Cannes, Morocco or Israel. Together
these regions account for only 1.7 percent of the Earth's surface,
but they provide habitat for over 20 percent of all known plant
species. Many of them, such as tender ceanothus or plumbago vine,
are among the most beautiful garden plants, those that American
temperate-zone gardeners like me long to grow.
 &HT;    Inside, under the spare arches of Sir Norman's building, lies an
18-foot gorge slashed into the earth by the American landscape
architect Kathryn Gustafson, whose radically pared-down designs can
be seen in France, England and the Netherlands. (She has also been
commissioned to design the terrace for the new Rose Center for
Earth and Space at the American Museum of Natural History in New
York.)
 &HT;    A walk down between its pale buff sandstone ``cliffs,'' now clad
in plants grouped by their regions, is a conservatory experience
different from any other because of the dramatic change in levels.
At the bottom lies my favorite of these Mediterranean zones, the
low evergreen ``forest'' of the Canary Islands, one of the most
endangered and unknown habitats on earth.
 &HT;    A mere 115 square feet, this ``forest'' has a waterfall and a
sunken pool and is planted with lovely, rare laurels, willows and
viburnums that are barely hanging on in their native home. Up at
the top, on the concourse level, there is a restaurant serving
light fare tucked under the north rim of the building with a view
over Gustafson's ``canyon'' and the Welsh hills beyond. (A more
substantial restaurant occupies a former stable.)
 &HT;    The garden's decision to know its plants from birth was very
important, considering how threatened many of the plants in this
glass house are. Though the staff now depends on some nursery-grown
stock for immediate effect, it eventually aims to have plants only
from seeds of known natural provenance, in order to preserve stocks
of genetic diversity and vigor.
 &HT;    There is a lot more going on at the garden, much of it rather
elaborate and symbolic (groups of rocks represent Wales' geologic
ages, for example). The plantings seem too sketchy to support the
heavy theoretical freight. They will grow and soften and be better
in a decade. Now, much of the garden has that bare, just-planted
look.
 &HT;    In the meantime I found that the best thing to do, besides
wander through the Great Glass House and marvel at the brainy
sustainable systems, was to climb Paxton's Tower. This 18th-century
folly perched on a nearby hill offered a marvelous chance to look
down on the design for the future I had just wandered through.
 &HT;    The other Welsh garden I visited, nearby Aberglasney, definitely
looks to the past. In 1471 when a Welsh bard, Lewis Glyn Cothi,
wrote about ``A fortress made bright by whitewash,
/And encompassing it all around, nine green gardens ...'' he was
probably thinking of Aberglasney and its owner at the time,
Rhydderch ap Rhys, whose skills the poet compared to those of Adam,
the first gardener.
 &HT;    Current archaeology has turned up nothing that links the
present-day garden layout with that 15th-century paradise, but it
has revealed something almost as rare: a Renaissance garden with
high walls, a cloister, a parapet walk _ the works _ the only such
design in the country known to have survived.
 &HT;    A gatehouse once thought to be a garden folly is in fact the
original 17th-century entrance to a courtyard. From there an
archway opens into the enclosed garden that lies just below the
much later (Queen Anne) house.
 &HT;    The remains of a delicate double flight of stairs leads to the
spot on top of the wall where a summer pavilion once stood. It
faced what are now the crumbled outlines of an airy banquet room.
From there, Sir Rice Rudd, owner of the garden in the mid-17th
century, would have looked down onto his parterres.
 &HT;    Parterres of what? Grass? Gravel? Boxwood? Nobody yet knows.
Part of the excitement here is the uncertainty of date and purpose
of many of the garden features.
 &HT;    Stories of recovering and saving this mystery buried under as
much as five feet of soil, trash and stinging nettles keep
horticulturists and preservationists agog, however.
 &HT;    Aberglasney changed hands many times and has suffered many
vicissitudes, including having the Ionic columns of its fine
porticoed house mysteriously ``disappear,'' only to turn up in a
Christie's catalog. They were set back in place late in 1999, part
of the overall plan of the Aberglasney Restoration Trust, financed
by an anonymous American benefactor, beginning in 1995.
 &HT;    This is the first spring that Aberglasney will be open to the
public. Though excavations continue inside the cloister, a fine
trio of gardens in adjoining walled enclosures has been recently
planted and still looks new. One surrounds a 17th-century oblong
pool; another is a typical kitchen garden; the third was designed
in concentric ovals by Penelope Hobhouse, the noted English garden
designer.
 &HT;    For the framework, she used only evergreens known to gardeners
during the Rudd period of the garden, but boldly filled her design
in with top-class ornamental plants, ancient and modern, from every
corner of the globe.
 &HT;    Hardly a Welsh garden but a good stop en route to the other two
is Hergest Croft, in Kington, Herefordshire, close to the border.
Gardened intensively for over a hundred years by three generations
of plant collectors and aficionados who luckily also had a sense of
design, Hergest should be better known to Americans _ if only
because it is so quintessentially English.
 &HT;    Paradoxically, when the English garden, they often want to leave
home, in the sense of letting their imaginations wander wildly to
exotic places. Does this happen because they live on such a small
island or because they once had such a large empire?
 &HT;    The reasons are not clear, but at Hergest, the 50-acre garden
begins at home in England in the exuberant conservatory of a robust
Victorian red brick house. It adjoins a picture-perfect kitchen
garden furnished with crooked old apple trees and a pair of
herbaceous borders.
 &HT;    Next comes a series of linked spaces, mostly planted with the
trees and shrubs for which Hergest is famous, including 59
Champions of the British Isles (the largest trees of their kinds).
There are more than 4,000 species and hybrids planted with tutelary
intelligence and high art, and about as many ways to enclose or
open views both large and small as exist in the world.
 &HT;    A visitor finishes in the Himalayas, in what is known as Park
Wood, a secret valley high-shaded by oaks and beeches where
rhododendrons bloom from January to August. Many specimens were
planted as early as 1910; they tower 20 feet tall or higher as they
do in their native habitat. Cascades of flowers rush down their
sides.
 &HT;    I walked into this wood on a June morning when the mist was
curling up from the pond at the rhododendrons' feet, and knew I was
traveling with Kubla Khan in Xanadu.
 &HT;    After a trip to the future at the Great Glass House, into the
past at Aberglasney, and far into a Coleridgean fantasy at Hergest,
I was ready for another piece of Welsh Black beef.
 &HT;    -----
 SIDEBAR: THREE GARDENS IN FOUR DAYS  
 &HT;    Following is a proposed four-day itinerary for seeing the three
gardens:
 &HT;     DAY 1  _ Take the train from Paddington Station (three hours)
to Swansea to pick up a car rental (Alamo has locations in both
Swansea and Worcester). Train fare $102 first class, $69 standard
class, at $1.60 to the pound. From Swansea take the M4 to exit 49
for Llandeilo _ about 35 minutes.
 &HT;    Spend the night in Llandeilo at the Cawdor Arms Hotel. You can
walk to the ruins of nearby Dinefyr Castle and back in the
afternoon. Dine at the Cawdor Arms. Walk around the pretty town of
Llandeilo.
 &HT;     DAY 2  _ After seeing the National Botanical Garden (morning)
and Aberglasney (afternoon) _ a picnic lunch can be packed by the
hotel or you can have lunch at the botanical garden _ spend a
second night at the Cawdor Arms. (Aberglasney can provide a list of
other nearby hotels and B&AMP;Bs.)
 &HT;     DAY 3  _ Head to Hergest Croft in Kington, Herefordshire, near
the Welsh border, taking a picnic (available from the Cawdor Arms).
A two-hour drive via the A40 north to Llandovery, the A483 to Buith
Wells, then the A481 and then the A44 to Kington.
 &HT;    The place for dinner and the night after seeing Hergest is
Broxwood Court, with an 1858 garden by the Victorian landscape
designer William Nesfield, 10 minutes away.
 &HT;     DAY 4  _ Turn in the car in Worcester, about 35 miles from
Broxwood on the A44, or drive back to London.
 THE GARDENS  
 &HT;    National Botanic Garden of Wales, Llanarthne, Carmarthenshire;
(44-1558) 668-768; fax (44-1558) 668-933; www.gardenofwales.org.uk.
Open daily at 10 a.m. except Christmas; May 24 through August
closes at 6 p.m.; September at 5:30 p.m.; November and December at
4:30 p.m. Last entry one hour before closing. Admission $10;
children $4.60; family $24.60.
 &HT;    Aberglasney, Llangathen, Carmarthenshire; telephone and fax
(44-1558) 668-998; www.aberglasney.org.uk. Open April 1 to Oct. 31
9:30 a.m. to 6 p.m., last entry 5 p.m. $6; children $3.
 &HT;    Hergest Croft Gardens, Kington, Herefordshire; telephone and fax
(44-1544) 230-160; www.hergest.co.uk. Open April 1 to Oct. 31, 1:30
to 6 p.m., last entry 5 p.m. $5.40; children under 16 free.
 LODGINGS  
 &HT;    Cawdor Arms Hotel, Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire; (44-1558)
823-500; fax (44-1558) 822-399. The 16 rooms are $92 to $115 for a
double with bath and breakfast. Prix-fixe dinner $32.
 &HT;    Broxwood Court, Broxwood, Herefordshire; (44-1544) 340-245, fax
(44-1544) 340-573. $117 for one of the seven doubles with bath and
breakfast. Prix-fixe dinner $31. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Mac Griswold is the author of ``Washington's Gardens at Mount
Vernon'' (Houghton Mifflin).)
 &HT;    -----
