<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN SALT LAKE CITY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By MATTHEW BROWN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Mormon pioneers came to this once desolate, high-desert valley
to get away from the rest of the world. But 153 years later, the
roughly 1 million people living at the base of the Wasatch
Mountains are preparing to welcome the world for the 2002 Winter
Olympics.
 &HT;    In Salt Lake City, work crews are erecting two hotels and
expanding the Salt Palace Convention Center. Interstate 15, widened
to 12 lanes, will stretch the length of the valley, joining a new
light-rail train to help handle the expected crowds of athletes,
spectators and workers.
 &HT;    Athletes are already training at the Utah Olympic Park, about 30
miles east of the city. Visitors can tour the park ($5 a car) and
even try out some of the courses.
 &HT;    But sports aren't the only attractions this summer: The city is
host to an international music competition and the Utah Arts
Festival.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    At Olympic Park in Park City, every Saturday beginning July 1
spectators will be able to watch members of the American and other
free-style ski teams slide down an artificial surface to a ramp
that sends aerialists twisting and flipping in the air before
splashing into a 750,000-gallon pool.
 &HT;    And you can try it yourself: for $125, intermediate skiers 15
years and older can be coached for a day in free-style aerial
skiing on July 8, 15 and 22 and Aug. 5 and 19.
 &HT;    Even nonskiers can get a taste of the sport daily from July 1 to
Sept. 1 by strapping into a harness attached to thick bungee chords
while an instructor helps with back flips and other maneuvers. The
cost is $5 for up to five minutes.
 &HT;    For the less adventurous, tours of the bobsled run and ski jumps
are given daily 11 a.m., and 12:30 and 2 p.m. The 60- to 90-minute
tours cost $6; $4 for seniors and children 5 to 11. For park
information, call (435) 658-4200.
 &HT;    A different kind of challenge is the Gina Bachauer International
Junior Piano Competition and International Piano Festival. The
competition _ among 27 contestants ages 11 to 13 from nine
countries _ takes place June 13 to 17 in Assembly Hall on Temple
Square downtown and is free. The top six contestants play a concert
June 24 at 7:30 p.m.
 &HT;    The festival, honoring the 250th anniversary of the death of
Johann Sebastian Bach, includes guest artists performing recitals,
lecturing and teaching master classes, in which a pianist is given
a lesson before an audience. Tickets to the master classes, June 19
to 23, cost $20 a day or $75 for five days from (888) 521-9200. The
free recitals, June 1 to 28, feature the complete keyboard works of
Bach.
 &HT;    The Utah Arts Festival takes place noon to 10 p.m. June 22 to 25
at the Utah State Fairpark, 155 North 1000 West. Jazz, folk, pop
and classical music, modern dance and poetry readings will take
place on five stages. Food from around the world will be available,
125 artists will sell their works and there will be hands-on art
projects. Admission is $5, $2 for age 60 and older and for everyone
on Thursday and Friday from noon to 3 p.m.; children under 12 are
admitted free.
 &HT;    Fourth of July celebrations will take place at Sugarhouse Park,
1500 East 2100 South, and Rice-Eccles Stadium, at the University of
Utah. Beginning at 1 p.m. in the park, there will be food, an arts
festival, activities for children, and in the evening, a
performance by the Utah Symphony and fireworks. The celebration is
free but parking is limited; (801) 535-6323.
 &HT;    At the stadium, the Red Hot 4th Stadium Extravaganza will
feature music by the bands Chicago and They Might Be Giants.
Tickets are $12, $18 and $24 from the Huntsman Center, (801)
581-6641, or Smith's Tix, (800) 888-8499.
 &HT;    From July 17 to 24, world champion cowboys converge on Salt Lake
City for the Days of '47 Rodeo in the Delta Center, 301 West South
Temple. Competition is nightly at 7:30. Tickets cost $10.50 to
$29.50 from Ticketmaster, (801) 325-7328. Information: (801)
325-2000.
 &HT;    The city will nearly shut down on July 24 for the 153rd
anniversary of the Mormon pioneers' arrival to the valley. Salt
Lake residents hold services, parades, road races, festivals and
fireworks. The Days of '47 Parade begins at 9 a.m. along 200 East
and ends up at Liberty Park, 600 East 1300 South, where a
Neighborhood Fair and Native-American celebration and fireworks
will take place.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    Visitors and lifelong residents alike marvel at the majestic
mountains that ring the Salt Lake Valley, which offer hiking for
all levels.
 &HT;    For an easy walk, head to City Creek Canyon just north of
downtown. From Second Avenue and Canyon Road, walk north through a
residential area and Memory Grove Park, then follow the road to a
gatehouse, where a five-mile paved road begins. Walkers and
cyclists have it to themselves on odd-numbered dates, and walkers
share the road with cars ($2.50 a vehicle) on other days. The
canyon is open 8:30 a.m. to 10 p.m. Call (801) 483-6880 to reserve
picnic sites, which cost $2.50 to $30.
 &HT;    More demanding trails and climbing can be found in Millcreek
Canyon, east of the city _ (801) 483-5473 for information _ and Big
Cottonwood and Little Cottonwood Canyons, to the southeast, (801)
466-6411.
 &HT;    They say the sunsets are beautiful from Buffalo Point on
Antelope Island. But the best time to visit the largest island in
the Great Salt Lake may be in the morning, when the pesky gnats and
mosquitoes are not swarming.
 &HT;    Antelope Island State Park, 30 miles northwest of Salt Lake City
off I-15, is home to a 500 buffaloes that roam freely, along with
mule deer, big horn sheep, antelope and coyotes. More than 30 miles
of hiking trails reach vantage points that offer spectacular views
of the lake. Take your own water. The island's beach at Bridger Bay
is the best place to experience the sensation of floating on the
salt water.
 &HT;    Park fees are $7 a vehicle or $4 per cyclist or pedestrian. The
30 camp sites cost $10 a night. Information: (801) 773-2941; camp
site reservations: (800) 322-3770.
 &HT;    At Temple Square, visitors can learn about Mormonism, get a
close-up view of the six-spired Salt Lake Temple and walk inside
the domed Tabernacle.
 &HT;    But another popular place is across the street in the church's
Family History Library, 35 North West Temple, (801) 240-2331. The
library has the largest archive of its kind in the world and is a
gold mine for genealogists of any faith or belief.
 &HT;    For newcomers to the searching out of one's roots, the library
has computer terminals with easy-to-use software. Terminals are
also at the Family Search Center in the Joseph Smith Memorial
Building, 15 East South Temple. Use of the library and center is
free. The library is open Tuesday through Saturday, 7:30 a.m. to 10
p.m. and Monday 7:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Center hours are 9 a.m. to 9
p.m., Monday through Saturday.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Hotel Monaco, 15 West 200 South, with 1930s French decor, is a
lively addition to the downtown hotel scene. The daily manager's
social at 5 p.m. offers guests a free neck and shoulder massage
with a glass of wine. The hotel is a refurbished 15-story bank
building with 225 rooms, a restaurant and a bar.
 &HT;    The 10-foot ceilings and extra-long beds make it a favorite for
visiting professional basketball teams. A double room is $149;
(801) 595-0000, fax (801) 532-8500.
 &HT;    For a more conservative setting there is The Inn at Temple
Square, 71 West South Temple. The 90 rooms, most of which have
views of either the Mormon Temple or Abravanel Hall, the city's
premier concert hall, have the look and feel of a country inn. The
inn and its restaurant do not serve alcohol. A double with a
king-size four-poster bed is $130 on weekdays and $99 on weekends.
 &HT;    Rates include a hot breakfast; (800) 843-4668, fax (801)
536-7272.
 &HT;    Little America Hotel and Towers, 500 South Main St., offers a
broad selection of accommodations _ from the Governor's suite for
$800 a night to motel-style rooms for $59 on weekends. There are
850 rooms in the tower and other buildings, two restaurants, two
swimming pools, a fitness room, a hair salon and four gift shops. A
double in the spacious tower suites is $164, while smaller garden
rooms go for $129. Rates drop about $35 or more on weekends; (800)
453-9450, fax (801) 596-5911.
 &HT;    Budget: Downtown Hampton Inn, 425 South 300 West, is close to
some of the city's best restaurants and microbreweries. The
158-room hotel has an indoor pool, hot tub and exercise room. A
double is $79, with Continental breakfast; (801) 741-1110, fax
(801) 741-1171.
 &HT;    Luxury: Wolfe Krest Bed and Breakfast, 273 North East Capitol
Blvd., is the newest and one of most luxurious B&AMP;Bs in the area.
The three-level Georgian revival mansion was built in 1905 and has
13 rooms, one with wheelchair access, all with fireplaces. Rates
are $150 to $300, with a hot breakfast either in your room or in
the dining area; (800) 669-4525, fax (801) 531-0522.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Under state liquor laws, the New Yorker Club, 60 West Market
St., (801) 363-0166, is considered a private club, but nonmembers
can buy a two-week membership for $10, which is valid for six
people. It offers elegant rooms with Italian marble floors and soft
lighting.
 &HT;    Appetizers include ahi tuna roll with a rich wasabi butter
sauce; a popular entree is roast rack of lamb with rosemary cream
and fresh vegetables. Try the raspberry almond tart for dessert. A
meal for two with wine is about $150. Like all but one of these
restaurants, it is closed Sunday.
 &HT;    The owners of the Metropolitan, 173 West Broadway (at 300
South), (801) 364-3472, have transformed a former warehouse into a
chic, pricey spot. The intriguing menu includes a pudding-like
Maine lobster tapioca brulee, Asian pear salad, and seared
yellowfin tuna in a citrus sauce. A dessert of fruit soup comes
with a corkscrew of caramelized sugar. Dinner for two with wine,
$160.
 &HT;    The basement location in a dingy strip mall belies the excellent
Tuscan food at Michelangelo Ristorante, 2156 South Highland Drive,
(801) 466-0961. Ravioli stuffed with porcini mushrooms and Parmesan
cheese is served in a rich sauce of truffle oil and butter. The
tiramisu is excellent. Dinner for two with wine, $75.
 &HT;    To get out of the punishing summer heat, head up Emigration
Canyon to Ruth's Diner, 2100 Emigration Canyon Road, (801)
582-5807, for breakfast, lunch or dinner. You can sit in the
original dining car or on the patio next to the creek and try
anything from burgers and salads to spicy coconut curried shrimp. A
favored dessert is Ruth's bananas _ a parfait of sliced bananas,
vanilla ice cream and warm rum sauce. Dinner for two with wine,
$50. No reservations, and the wait can be long for Sunday brunch.
 &HT;    For a step back to the time of car hops, burgers and malts, head
to Hires Big H, 425 South 700 East. The place is swarming with
teen-agers and families craving the Big H burger on a soft
flour-dusted bun ($2.65), greasy fries ($1.65), and thick malts
($2.29). You can order from your car or eat inside. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Matthew Brown is a journalist in Salt Lake City.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Matthew Brown 
