<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: PERFUNCTORY DISCOUNTS VS. THE BEST BARGAINS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: We have included some optional trims in this article
to make cutting the piece for length an easier task. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    ``When are Americans going to stop obsessing about airline
prices and look at their hotel bills?'' asked Ed Perkins during the
recent meeting of the Editors' Council of the Society of American
Travel Writers.
 &HT;    Like many mature travelers, Perkins, retired editor of the
Consumer Reports Travel Newsletter, knows that when you analyze the
expenses for almost any trip, the biggest cost is often lodging.
 &HT;    I heard that loud and clear nearly a decade ago when Bill Todd,
then marketing director of Choice Hotels, told The Mature Traveler
that hotel discounts for seniors should be large enough to make it
worthwhile for them to want to alter their travel itineraries _ be
it driving 50 or 100 miles farther than planned or changing travel
dates from weekend to midweek or from high to low season _ to
capture the biggest savings.
 &HT;    This year, the dividing line between perfunctory discounts _
those offered because other establishments are doing so _ and
discounts of real value to seniors is much clearer, as I learned
while doing The Mature Traveler's annual survey of senior discounts
at hotels nationwide. Some promotional strategies that hotels are
using are not only elusive, but are a downright disservice to
customers of all ages. Here are some observations.
 &HT;    Many reservation operators are unfamiliar with their company's
senior programs. In fact, several had to look up the most basic
information, such as the eligibility age.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The concept of a flat percentage discount for seniors is
beginning to disappear. This became clear when many lodging
reservation centers explained that they couldn't disclose their
discount until I told them my destination and dates. This has to do
in part with room availability, which all discounts rely on, but it
certainly shouldn't affect a company's basic senior discount
policy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Many hotel reservationists at their 800 numbers even refused to
quote a senior discount price of any kind. In one instance, an
operator told TMT that she would provide ``the best price'' for a
specified hotel and date and make a reservation. She then said that
when I appear at the front desk to check in, ``You may get a senior
discount. I have no way to know for sure.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    More of the smaller, regional chains are giving discounts of
around 10 percent, but the offer is not necessarily chainwide since
each establishment decides whether or not it wants to participate.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A great many chains have a two-tier discount system. One
discount is for members of AARP, CARP and Mature Outlook. The
second is offered by the hotel chain itself, can be a different and
lower percentage for non-members and, in many cases, has different
age requirements.
 &HT;    When a property or chain works to understand the mature-traveler
market and then develops a program based on what it has learned,
the programs are more usefulnot only to the hotel, but also to
seniors' pocketbooks and travel plans. For example, Hilton's Senior
HHonors program, one of the better deals in the industry, now
includes new brands that extends the program to nearly 2,000
locations compared to last year's 450.
 &HT;    The program, once limited to Hilton and Conrad International
hotels, is now available at Doubletree, Hampton Inns, Homewood
Suites and Embassy Suites. Open to those ages 60 and older, the
program costs $55 the first year in the United States, or $75
outside, and can result in discounts of up to 50 percent or better.
Benefits also include restaurant discounts and frequent-stayer
rewards.
 &HT;    The global impact of such a change: More overseas lodging groups
probably will be examining _ and changing _ their own offerings for
senior travelers to meet the competition.
 &HT;    Some special promotion packages include travel with
grandchildren, while others take into account the special interests
of the senior set by including anniversary offers _ activities such
as nostalgic music events and trips that commemorate moments of our
youth, like the end of World War II, the start of the Korean War or
the day Elvis Presley died.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, there's a downside to all these wonderful, new
options: For some, hotel-shopping has become a time-consuming
chore. Here are some strategies to simplify the process:
 &HT;     _ GO OUTSIDE THE BOX.  If your hotel of choice is known as a
``business hotel,'' catering mostly to corporate world, it is
likely to have special deals on weekends when business people are
home. A resort may have openings midweek when business people are
at work. If the location makes the bulk of its money during the ski
season, look for summer deals, etc. As mature travelers, we have
more flexibility than others on the road.
 &HT;     _ TRY ALTERNATIVES.  Investigate programs that offer other
travel benefits, such as homestays, home exchanges or bed and
breakfasts. These offer travelers the opportunity to learn about an
area from local residents _ and to get a good night's sleep.
 &HT;    A condo or apartment can supply much more space and freedom for
a group of two or four while helping to cut costs on meals. (Why
eat out when you've got your own kitchen?)
 &HT;    Campus accommodations or hostels can also lower your travel
budget. Lodging brokers or Web auction sites can be helpful, too,
however many mature travelers complain that the time it takes do to
a Web search detracts from the savings they might find.
 &HT;     _ DON'T LEAVE HOME WITHOUT THEM.  Make sure to carry that
all-important identification that can help cut costs _ namely, your
AARP/CARP card; frequent-stay hotel group cards; or proof of
membership to any lodging discount programs, such as the
Entertainment 2000 directories, which entitle members to discounts
of up to 50 percent off published room rates at certain hotel
chains.
 &HT;    One reader recently wrote to me about her experience trying to
locate lodging near the airport when her flight was canceled. She
found herself within walking distance of a hotel with a great
senior discount program while her peers paid two and three times
more. Guess her pals didn't know how important it is to ask for the
senior discount. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
