<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;     Q:  I frequently travel to Italy on business and am tired of
the hotels my company books for me. Could you recommend affordable
lodging in hotels there that are authentic in design and cater to
American road warriors?
 &HT;     A:  Golden Tulip Hotels and Summit Hotels &AMP; Resorts accommodate
guests in some of Italy's best locations and uniquely embody
classic Italian architecture, design and art. These hotels are
situated where visitors have complete access to the sites and
routines of Italy's greatest cities.
 &HT;    In Rome's city center, the four-star Bernini Bristol, Hotel
Giulio Cesare and GT Mecenate Palace have cozy, pastel-colored
rooms and characteristic Roman atmosphere ripe with detailed
columns and arches.
 &HT;    Naples boasts the gorgeous seaside Grand Hotel Santa Lucia with
ocean views and breezy enchantment in its marble lobby and bar. The
GT Grand Hotel Baglioni and Hotel Minerva keep guests in the middle
of the action as Florentines stroll by and congregate in the many
squares and bars that surround these stylish Tuscan hotels.
 &HT;    Also in Florence, Summit's exciting Hotel Brunelleschi
integrates a sixth-century Byzantine tower and 12th-century church
into the facade of their 96 rooms and private museum.
 &HT;    However, in Florence nothing quite captivates travelers like the
palatial Grand Hotel Villa Cora. In the center of exclusive Viale
Machiavelli Park, this mansion provides its visitors with a chance
to live like royalty in an extravagant house of riches.
 &HT;    All these hotels have dazzling restaurants with creative local
specialties and imaginative preparation. Most hotels provide
well-equipped conference rooms, fitness rooms and garden terraces,
as well as special services and suites for the American business
traveler.
 &HT;    Continental Airlines' partner, AerItalia, offers incredible
BusinessFirst seating to most destinations in Italy at a reasonable
price. Golden Tulip and Summit Hotels deliver the best of Italy at
very reasonable rates. For more information, call Summit at (800)
457-4000 and Golden Tulip at (800) 344-1212.
 &HT;     Q:  I am one of the few females that I know who enjoys playing
golf. But sometimes I find it intimidating to play with men, and I
rarely have the time to drive long distances to get to courses. Do
you know of any golf facilities near New York City?
 &HT;     A:  Why not make the most of a weekend by spending it golfing
and relaxing at Manhattan's Doral Park Avenue Hotel? This hotel
offers female guests an ``Afternoon Tee Golf Package'' that caters
to female golfers of all levels.
 &HT;    The package includes deluxe room accommodations, a complimentary
golfing book for women by Cheryl A. Leonhardt and a number of
members-only privileges at The Golf Club at Chelsea Piers, just
minutes from the hotel.
 &HT;    Also included is a one-hour private lesson (designed especially
for women) with a PGA instructor, club rentals and video analysis
of technique.
 &HT;    The Doral Park Avenue Hotel, located at Park Avenue and 38th
Street, has the feel of a European boutique hotel with Italian
marble baths and neoclassical furnishings and provides guests with
data ports, delivery of The New York Times daily and views of Park
Avenue and the Murray Hill district.
 &HT;    Prices for the ``Afternoon Tee Golf Package'' start at $305 per
weekend night and $345 for midweek nights.
 &HT;    For more information and reservations, call (877) 99-DORAL or
(212) 687-7050, or visit www.doralparkavenue.com on the Web.
 &HT;     Q:  My husband and I are traveling more frequently to
developing countries for both business and pleasure. We always make
sure to get the necessary immunizations prior to departure.
However, where can we turn if, despite our efforts, one or both of
us becomes ill while traveling abroad?
 &HT;     A:  You are smart to be concerned, because 40 percent of
Americans traveling to developing countries contract illnesses from
bacteria, viruses or parasites that are unknown at home.
 &HT;    Although there are many travel-assistance or medical-evacuation
options available to international travelers, a new standard of
distance medical care is emerging thanks to technology.
 &HT;    WorldClinic at Lahey of Burlington, Mass., is setting such a
standard by providing patients abroad with immediate access to U.S.
board-certified emergency physicians 24 hours a day.
 &HT;    No matter how minor the illness, WorldClinic's physicians can
evaluate any medical situation, diagnose and treat the problem and
oversee all medical care until your return home. The firm prepares
its patients for departure by assembling medical records and
preparing custom prescription medical kits.
 &HT;    For more information, contact WorldClinic at Lahey at (800)
636-9186, or visit www.worldclinic.com on the Web.
 &HT;     Q:  Help me find the perfect Mexican restaurant in Manhattan.
 &HT;     A:  Coming from Southern California, I consider myself a good
judge of Mexican restaurants, and for years have found that New
York City has few places for great South-of-the-border food.
 &HT;    Therefore, I was happy to encounter Casa Mexicana while passing
through the city. Here, Chef Luis Herrera and owner Ramon Angeles
create authentic dishes from different regions of Mexico and bring
dignity to the Tex-Mex scene.
 &HT;    Placing a romantic, hacienda-style space in the trendy Lower
East Side shows an ingenious stroke of imagination and common
sense. The cooking combines Mexican ingredients with creative
French culinary technique to create clever and tasty dishes, such
as chicken tamales wrapped in a banana leaf with sunflower seeds
and a mole poblano. Fresh sangria, Spanish wines and Mexican beers
are on hand. Don't miss pastry chef Josefina Hernandez's desserts,
such as rose tequila sabayon with rose-petal sorbet.
 &HT;    Casa Mexicana has a downstairs lounge with music for guests who
have given up the night's decision-making to the tequila and
sangria. Located at 133 Ludlow St., Casa Mexicana is a great way to
start a night out or to end one. For more information, call (212)
473-4100.
 &HT;     Q:  I would love to send my daughter on an exotic trip as a
graduation present, but I can't afford to go overboard. Do you have
any recommendations for spectacular but reasonably priced
vacations?
 &HT;     A:  Because it is considered the low season, right now is the
perfect time to visit the hip Caribbean island of St. Barts. Hotel
Guanahani, the island's only full-service small luxury resort, is
currently offering off-season packages through October.
 &HT;    Guanahani's ``St. Barts Spree'' gives guests a luxury ocean-view
room for five nights and includes round-trip airport
transportation, two meals daily, tax and service charges and either
a complimentary one-hour jet ski rental or two one-hour tennis
lessons. The best part of this package is the price _ only $1,650
for two people.
 &HT;    Most guests find the low season at St. Barts the ideal time to
visit since crowds have thinned and the weather is still sunny and
warm.
 &HT;    Boasting private gardens, colorful bungalows and two stunning
beaches, Hotel Guanahani provides everything a vacationer could
want _ from aquatic sports such as snorkeling and windsurfing to
tennis facilities (with a pro on hand to give advice and
instruction) to a tranquil lagoon where you can just unwind.
 &HT;    Hotel Guanahani also offers other low-season packages at
incredible rates from three to seven nights. Packages must be
reserved and fully paid before arrival.
 &HT;    For more information, visit http://www.leguanahani.com/, or call
Leading Hotels of the World at (800) 223-6800. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions to William Tomicki, P.O.
Box 5148, Santa Barbara, Calif. 93150. Although he cannot answer
each query individually, selected questions will be included in his
column. Mr. Tomicki, who logs over 150,000 miles each year, is the
publisher of ENTREE, a travel newsletter. 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 William T. Tomicki 
<TEXT>
