<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON SHOULD BE KNOWN FOR HIS PROJECT, NOT HIS PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the name Kermit Washington resonates in the mind of the
average sports fan it is more than likely because it is inevitably
linked to the name Rudy Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   The name should stand for achievement, both athletic and
academic. Kermit Washington was the last career 20-point,
20-rebound man in college basketball. Kermit Washington played in
an NBA All-Star game. Kermit Washington stood for unrelenting
hustle and professionalism. Kermit Washington also embodied the
concept of student-athlete, joining the likes of Bill Bradley, Tom
McMillen, Bill Walton, Bob Elliott, and Doug Collins as a GTE
Lifetime Hall of Famer for combining athletic and academic
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   More than any of this, Kermit Washington is a compassionate
human being who has made 10 trips to Africa in the past five years,
and not to take fancy pictures on a photographic safari, either. He
runs Project Contact, a movement that brings much-needed medical
attention to suffering people in such war-, famine-, and
disease-wracked countries as Kenya, Burundi, Rwanda, and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great, great, great thing he does,'' says Dale
Steininger, a friend who has been to Africa with Washington. ``I
think the NBA has a lot of misconceptions about Kermit, and it's
all because of the Rudy Tomjanovich thing. If you mention Kermit's
name, they don't know what he does there.''
</P>
<P>
   They should. The medical community in Portland, Ore., certainly
does. The 40,000 people who have been served by Project Contact
surely do. And Kermit has tried to tell them, not because he's
looking for a plaque, but because he thought the world's most
prestigious and richest basketball organization might be interested
in making a contribution to a worthy cause run by an unjustifiably
demonized alumnus to whom the league owes a long overdue apology.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kermit Washington tried to go through channels to
inquire about a league donation, he was rebuffed, and chillingly
so, by a functionary whose name he does not recall. ``They made me
feel like a piece of trash,'' he says. ``I was told, `Well, we've
already allocated our fine money.' I said, `How can you do that?
The season hasn't even started yet. You don't know what you'll be
taking in. Dennis Rodman might contribute a million dollars
himself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kermit Washington became part of the American sports dialogue on
the night of December 9, 1977, when he punched Rudy Tomjanovich in
the face so severely that the Houston forward required extensive
plastic surgery and was prevented from playing for the remainder of
the season. Kermit Washington was big and black and Rudy T was
not-quite-as-big and white, and so guess which one became an
instant national villain?
</P>
<P>
   He was finishing a fight he did not start. It began with an
elbow from Kevin Kunnert and ended when Washington, sensing that
someone was rushing toward him from the rear, turned and landed
what can only be described as the Perfect Punch, a ferocious blow
delivered by a great physical specimen to a man approaching at full
speed. Moving past the gory details, Kermit Washington basically
punched Rudy T's face in.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Larry O'Brien suspended Washington without pay for
two months, representing an approximate $80,000 hit. Kunnert was
neither fined nor suspended. Kermit Washington never played another
game for the Lakers. He was traded to the Celtics, for whom he
played 35 games before being part of the deal with the Clippers
that brought Tiny Archibald, Billy Knight, and Marvin Barnes to
Boston. He spent three years in Portland (making the All-Star team
in 1980) and finished his career with Golden State in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But he was always The Wild Man Who Punched Rudy T. Never mind
that the real Kermit Washington was a bookworm of a family man with
a strong social conscience. Never mind that the easily available
videotape evidence from that fateful game substantiated his story
that he was merely defending himself from God-knows-what when he
realized someone was speeding toward him from the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if I were walking down the street and was attacked by
a mugger,'' Washington said in a 1978 Globe interview. ``I fight
him off when his buddy comes in from nowhere to help. I nail him.
Now here comes the police and there is the mugger and his friend,
lying there. I am hauled off to prove my innocence. If I hadn't
protected myself from (the 7-foot) Kunnert, I might be the one
lying in the hospital. And how did I know what was on Rudy's
mind?''
</P>
<P>
   The question posed then was, ``Will this thing ever die?'' The
answer, Washington says, is ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just yesterday,'' he was saying recently, ``three people asked
me about the Rudy thing. It amazes me. It never dies. So many times
when people meet me, it's `Aren't you the one . . . ' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Punch and its aftermath have haunted Washington for 23
years. The name association, he believes, has prevented potential
NBA employers from taking his job applications seriously. One
former NBA coach, an ex-teammate no less, said, frankly, ``If I
hire you as an assistant, they'll think there's something wrong
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington became so frustrated by all this he decided to take a
lie detector test a while back. He wanted tangible proof he was
telling the truth when he said he was only trying to protect
himself when he threw the fateful punch. ``I passed with a score
they told me was two or three times higher than necessary to verify
truthfullness,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kermit Washington is in both the restaurant and radio business.
He owns ``Le Slam Sports Cafe'' in Vancouver, Wash., and he does
morning radio on KKGT in Portland. But more than anything, he is in
the humanity business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching television,'' he says, ``and I'd see people
suffering. I don't like bullies, and I think poverty is a bully,
disease is a bully, and ignorance is a bully. Being in the
restaurant business is not much fun. Radio is not that rewarding.
If I become a bum tomorrow, I can now say with a smile on my face
that I did something good with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't take doctors and nurses to Africa without dealing with
the M-word. You don't buy medicine without paying for it. Kermit
Washington is no millionaire. He raised money for one trip by
raffling off a car (OK, it was a Porsche). He raised money for
another trip by holding off on paying his taxes. He got money for
another trip by trading an original LeRoy Neiman print to Clyde
Drexler for his 1992 Dream Team jersey and then auctioned the
jersey for some 15 grand. ``Make sure you point out that Clyde just
gave me the jersey without asking for anything,'' Washington says.
``I wanted him to have something, so I gave him the print.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's first trip in 1995 was in the company of someone
else's group. He decided he wanted more personal freedom to do what
he wanted to, so he formed his own organization. When he needs
volunteers for a trip, he simply gets on the radio and asks for
them. ``You get as many as you want,'' he says. He makes sure they
know what to expect. Africa is unlike anything they have ever
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been robbed. I've lost 15 pounds in three weeks. It can
be pretty rough,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Once he saw for himself what conditions are like for
people in these countries, he knew he had to keep trying to bring
help. ``I think it's unacceptable behavior not to at least try to
help people in need,'' he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've helped over 40,000 people, and it costs less than a
dollar a person,'' he says. ``I know that sounds like a commercial.
But it's true. With $100,000 we could help 100,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA may still think Kermit Washington is a pariah, but the
people who work for, and who have been treated by, Project Contact
think he is a permanent MVP (Most Valuable Person). If you agree,
you might want to contact them at the GTE Web site,
lifesplaybook.com. But it's not about him. It's about people in
desperate need of help.
</P>
<P>
   Kermit Washington knows who he is. More people should.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
