<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BILLY-BUDD-REVIEW-LAD     06-08 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-BUDD-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARING PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 4 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless your travels regularly take you to Gold's Gym in West
Hollywood, you won't see more high-grade beefcake on display
anywhere in Los Angeles these days than in ``Billy Budd,'' Benjamin
Britten's brawny musical treatise on divine authority versus human
expediency.
</P>
<P>
   And unless you're planning a trip to the sweet hereafter, you'll
be hard-pressed to witness a more perfect presentation than the one
currently docked at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Not that director Francesca Zambello's production is simply a
triumph of muscle over mind. Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching these shores via London and Geneva, this production
reminds us what exuberant power opera has when exactly the right
singers, musicians, sets, lights and costumes converge at the right
time, in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   Fortifying her rep as a rising visionary, Zambello and company
achieve a remarkable synthesis of naturalism and abstraction,
clarity and ambiguity, the bulky imperatives of narrative form with
the ethereal majesty and streamlined gravity of Britten's score and
E.M. Forster and Eric Crozier's sinewy libretto.
</P>
<P>
   That's not even mentioning the magnificent central triad of
singers aboard the British warship Indomitable: bass Jeffrey Wells,
a touch stiff but otherwise excellent; baritone Rodney Gilfry, the
closest most of us probably will see to a definitive Billy Budd,
and, in his Los Angeles Opera debut, the superb tenor Robert Tear,
a model of anguished vocal integrity as the spiritually tortured
Captain Vere.
</P>
<P>
   Together, and supported by an all-male ensemble that's solid
from stem to stern, they maintain an exquisite equilibrium among
Britten's warring chords. Conductor Roderick Brydon martials the
gently billowing strings, shimmering woodwinds and awesome
batteries of blazing horns with great authority and nuance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the darkly mystical Herman Melville novella that inspired
it, Britten's opera tracks a wavering course between good and evil.
``Billy Budd'' is a moral as well as musical odyssey that carries
us through the blue mists enshrouding the envious, scheming
Master-at-Arms John Claggart (Wells), then launches us into the
pure, major-key light that crowns Claggart's prey, the innocent
sailor Billy Budd (Gilfry).
</P>
<P>
   Now 41, Gilfry has publicly pondered hanging up his signature
role for good. When that day comes, please break the news to me
gently. Watch how Gilfry's stoic Billy plumbs the paradoxical joy
in his death-row aria, neither Christlike abstraction nor naive
man-boy. Listen how gracefully he bends the notes while bidding
farewell to the ship, the Rights o' Man. No wonder Wells' Claggart
is clearly ga-ga over him.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder, too, at Alison Chitty's split-level, hydraulically
powered set, which mirrors the upstairs/downstairs divide between
officers and men and reinforces the brutal claustrophobia of ocean
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Budd,'' which one critic described as Melville's ``final
testament of acceptance,'' is a swan song for Peter Hemmings, L.A.
Opera's retiring founding general director, who has been working to
bring this production here for years. Hemmings is England-bound
next month. The rest of us may rejoice that his ship has come in. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
- What: ``Billy Budd.'' &QL; 
- Where: Los Angeles Opera at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion,
Performing Arts Center of Los Angeles County, 135 N. Grand Ave.,
downtown. &QL; 
- When: 7:30 p.m. today and June 11 and 14; 2 p.m. June 17. &QL; 
- Tickets: $27 to $146. Call (213) 365-3500. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
