<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-MILLS-ART-BOS &LR;      06-08 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MILLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A FATHER'S WORDS, A DAUGHTER'S BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   C. Wright Mills was to social science in his day what the Beats
were to literature: a stranger in a '50s land who stormed through
the decade hellbent for the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best-known sociologist of his day, thanks to such
books as ``White Collar'' and ``The Power Elite,'' Mills died
before the '60s became The Sixties. Yet in everything from
enthusiasms (Fidel Castro, jeans, motorcycles) to vocabulary (it
was Mills who coined the term ``New Left''), he presaged the
counterculture that was to come.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wright Mills was just 45 when he died, in 1962. His
daughter Kathryn was 6. Thus the five years she spent gathering her
father's correspondence for the just-published ``C. Wright Mills:
Letters and Autobiographical Writings'' was an opportunity to
deepen a relationship death denied her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was valuable for me to learn more about my father through
adult eyes instead of kid's eyes,'' she said over lunch last week.
``When you read 600 letters someone wrote over the course of their
adulthood you learn a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills did not lack for detractors. As his onetime Columbia
colleague Daniel Bell wrote in 1960, in much of his work ``no point
is ever argued or developed, it is only asserted'' and ``Vulgar
Marxism has become vulgar sociology.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills preferred to see himself as an anarchist rather than
Marxist. The vulgar part he probably didn't mind so much. A
self-described ``North American aboriginal,'' he was the sort of
man who could go into a steakhouse, order a full meal, eat it, then
order another. He wrote for 15-hour stretches and boasted of having
once racked up an 800-mile day on his motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it big, boy!'' he'd urge his students. For him, those
were words to live by. Always juggling too many projects, he didn't
restrict himself to sociology. Several times he wrote to
correspondents of his intention to write a novel, a play, or even a
movie script. One screenplay he wanted to call ``Enthusiasm.''
Perhaps it was autobiographical.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was a six-footer who weighed 200 pounds, but size wasn't
what made him seem larger than life. It was his energy, his
ambition, his forcefulness. He failed his draft physical because,
as he writes in a letter, ``They told me I ticked too fast
inside.'' In the end, his heart failed him. But it took at least
three coronaries to do it _ and before he died, he managed to marry
three times, build two houses with his own hands, and father three
children (Kathryn Mills has a half-sister Pamela, who collaborated
on the new book, and a half-brother, Nik).
</P>
<P>
   ``He was exhausting, a man whose pressure never let up,'' the
literary critic Irving Howe once wrote. Howe, who was friendly with
Mills until they parted politically, recalled him as ``a figure of
power, a fiercely grinding power that came down like a fist.''
</P>
<P>
   The man his daughter remembers was exhilarating rather than
exhausting. ``He may have been fatiguing for adults sometimes,
because he would challenge them and be demanding _ he demanded a
lot of himself _ but from a kid's point of view, he wasn't tiring
at all. He was just fun. He would joke around and be dramatic. He'd
take me to nursery school on his motorcycle _ and I really liked
that! And I remember him resting on the study couch. That's where
we watched Westerns together on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   After her father's death, Mills was raised by her mother in
suburban Washington, D.C. She graduated in 1976 from Hampshire
College, where the focus of her studies was political economics
(``I wonder where that interest came from,'' she laughs). After a
year at Boston University Law School, she became a VISTA volunteer
in Framingham, Mass., then spent four years working as a community
organizer in Mission Hill in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A tall, slender woman with a fondness for detail, Mills lives in
Brookline, Mass. with her husband and their 13-year-old son. She
oversees the contracts department at a local publisher, where she
has worked since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   It gives Kathryn Mills considerable satisfaction to see the
volume she's edited contributing to a larger revival of her
father's work. This year has seen reissues of ``The Power Elite''
and ``The Sociological Imagination'' (both from Oxford University
Press), and the University of Illinois Press is planning to reissue
his first book, ``The New Men of Power: America's Labor Leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   On a much more personal level, assembling the letters solved a
longstanding problem for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I didn't have a good way of referring to my
father in conversation. When he was alive, I called him `Daddy,' of
course. But as I got older, that sounded funny. If I said to
someone, `Daddy's book is being misrepresented,' calling him
`Daddy' didn't sound right since I was all grown up (or at least as
grown up as I was likely to become any time soon). So I tried
calling him `Mills,' but that seemed even more odd. Now I call him
`Wright,' and that feels comfortable. After spending years going
through his old mail, it's only natural that I'm on a first-name
basis with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
