<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-STEELY-DAN-HNS &LR;      06-08 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STEELY-DAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO MEDAL FOR STEELY DAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAIG MARINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Calif. _ It has taken nearly 30 years to fully
appreciate, but Steely Dan really did pick the perfect name for
their band.
</P>
<P>
   When polished studio pros Donald Fagen and Walter Becker
assembled more of their kind for the ``Can't Buy a Thrill'' album
in 1972, the name just seemed like an oh-so-clever literary nod to
their oh-so-clever-to-be listeners. These were the kinds of people
who hung around in coffeehouses before there were coffeehouses on
every corner _ and back when it was still considered perfectly fine
to sit around in bars instead.
</P>
<P>
   But after listening to Fagen and Becker and their latest
collection of expert musicians one recent night at the Chronicle
Pavilion in Concord, there really could be no other name. The
original Steely Dan, after all, was a famed sexual stand-in. And
what Fagen and Becker and their bunch put out onstage is exactly
the same thing musically: a stand-in for the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   The second biggest problem with Steely Dan the group _ the first
being, naturally, their mere existence _ is that the group always
includes some of the best musicians around. The cream of the crop,
the best guitarists and horn players and back-up singers and you
name it. So that makes it nearly impossible to dismiss Steely Dan
out of hand as being lousy.
</P>
<P>
   They are not lousy musicians, they are just playing lousy music,
a kind of hybrid form that takes a bit of rock and a bit of jazz
and a bit of soul and screws up the best parts of each. Toss in
pretentiously innocuous lyrics and what you have is the ``Star
Wars'' of music _ geek worship. It's not a pretty sight, watching
the aging masses shaking their expanding bottoms to tunes that you
used to dive to the radio dial to shut off. Toss in the
Concord-ness of it all, and it was altogether a frightening
evening.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like this was a nostalgia tour, since these guys never
toured when they were huge. With good reason. Fagen looks like a
singing accountant, and Becker looks like that embarrassing uncle
everyone's got who just won't own up to the times and cut off that
gray pony tail that hangs behind his bald dome.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just as easy to see why these guys sold millions of
records. Just when you thought it was safe to turn on the radio
again, they come out with a new album, ``Two Against Nature,'' that
includes some creepy song about incest with an infectious hook that
sounds like every other song they ever did.
</P>
<P>
   And they did every other song they ever did in Concord, or all
one long version of the same song. It was nearly impossible to tell
the difference. Each song let one or more of the musicians take an
extended solo that bordered on the self-indulgent. Yet every song
stuck into the inside of your brain like some alien life form,
whether it was ``Do It Again,'' or ``Black Friday,'' or ``Deacon
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially ``Deacon Blue,'' with that bit about drinking whisky
all night long and dying behind the wheel _ man did that get a
cheer, and this from a bunch that could probably remember each time
they got drunk in college.
</P>
<P>
   The only way a song could be mercifully purged from the brain
was with the group's vicious tactic of playing the next tune, which
would then occupy the vacated area until it was, in turn,
exorcised. Luckily, the band took a half-hour break after being
onstage for 60 minutes or so. As luck would have it, however,
someone allowed them back onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, it was disappointing to see such obvious musical
talent wasted on songs like . . . well, any of them, ``Royal
Scam,'' for instance. The horn players alone could have given the
crowd two hours or more of pure entertainment if they were cut
loose on some real material, their skills were that apparent. On
``Royal Scam,'' they got to play six notes at the beginning, then
build to an annoying crescendo that did manage to drown out even
more irritating lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for Fagen and Becker to set their people free _ if
they're lucky, the band is probably only making union scale per
night anyway. You know the trombone player isn't seeing a big chunk
of those $75 seats down in front, or pride alone would have allowed
him to bail out somewhere on this tour by now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
