<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 1722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTING IN THE LAND OF NO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Antarctic, there are more than 80 words to describe snow.
Toddlers have almost as many meanings for the word ``no.''
Sometimes it actually means no, as in absolutely not. Mostly it
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The typical 2-year-old arrives in the land of no at about the
same time she's making physical and cognitive leaps from being a
tentative walker to a confident, proficient one who can run, climb,
and even go backward; from taking the world at face value to being
able to make some cause-and-effect links.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is no coincidence, says psychologist Alicia
Lieberman, a leading specialist in toddler development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capacity to go where they want transforms their feelings
about themselves, enabling them to see themselves in a new way,''
she says: `` `I run so fast, Daddy can't catch me! I climb so high,
Mama can't see me! I can make things happen, I can shape my own
experience!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of noes is a natural byproduct of this
newfound sense of power. ``It's the password of autonomy,'' says
psychiatrist Kyle Pruett of Yale University. Rather than see it as
an act of defiance or disobedience, he and Lieberman say, parents
should interpret ``No!'' as a plea for participation: ``Remember,
I'm a partner now. I can have input into what happens to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``no'' is intended to be the beginning of a
conversation, not the end of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell parents to pretend your child has uttered a whole
phrase after the `no,' '' says child developmentalist Maureen
O'Brien, TouchPoints consultant at Children's Hospital in Boston.
For instance: ``No, I have something to say''; ``No, I need more
time''; ``Tell me more, I'm scared/unsure''; ``I want to be in
charge, how about some choices?'' O'Brien is the author of a
forthcoming HarperCollins series of books on 1-, 2-, and
3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that toddlers don't yet have many
words available to them, says pediatrician Leonard Rappaport,
director of developmental medicine at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want control and they want our involvement. `No' is one
of the few ways they have to engage us,'' he says. That the
engagement is often negative doesn't matter. ``It's still
interesting to them,'' Rappaport says, almost as if they are
fact-finding.
</P>
<P>
   Because this dialogue between parent and child plays out in a
society that places a high value on the individual, we walk a
tightrope: Give a toddler too much control and he feels unsafe and
insecure and likely turns into a brat; don't give him enough and he
lacks a sense of competence, feels bad about himself, and becomes
even more negative.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the middle ground?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Pruett say it lies within parents' ability to read
a toddler's signals, to know when it's OK to provide structure to
move them away from ``no'' and when it's important for ``no'' to
count. ``That helps them learn to label feelings and regulate
emotions,'' says Lieberman. ``If we don't do that, we leave them at
the mercy of feelings they can't control.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
What to look for &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the signals to pay attention to:
</P>
<P>
   --Context. What is he doing when he says no, what's going on
around him? If you say it's time to go to the playground and he
says no, perhaps it's because he's intent on what he's doing right
now and needs time to accept that he has to stop and then to
actually prepare to leave. Maybe something frightened him at the
playground last time, a dog, perhaps, and he's worried it might
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   --Mood. Is this often a time of day when he gets angry and
negative? Maybe he's hungry. Was he up twice last night? Maybe he's
overtired. Has it been a busy day? Maybe he's overstimulated and
feels out of control. ``When a `no' is global rather than in
response to something specific, being held is almost always what
they need,'' says Pruett, who is president of Zero to Three, the
National Center for Infants, Toddlers and Families. He is also the
author of ``Me, Myself and I: How Children Build Their Sense of
Self, 18 to 36 months'' (Goddard).
</P>
<P>
   --Tone. Is this a ``no'' with a lot of passion behind it or is
it matter-of-fact? Maybe it's a question, as in ``Are you serious
or not, Mom?'' If there's passion _ and 2-year-olds can have a lot
of it _ there may also be fear: ``I don't want to pet this dog
because I'm terrified of it!'' ``That's a `no' that absolutely
should be respected,'' says Lieberman. She is a professor at the
University of California/San Francisco and author of ``The
Emotional Life of the Toddler'' (Free Press).
</P>
<P>
   --Body language. What are his eyes telling you? Is there an
angry glint or a playful twinkle? If he's digging himself in, you
have to decide how important this issue is and whether it will be
worth the struggle. If it's playful, play along: ``What happened to
Mr. Yes? Where did he go?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A possible scenario &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how all of this can play out together:
</P>
<P>
   It's time to get dressed, and your 2-year-old says ``No!'' and
grabs her shoe. If you assume she's saying ``No way, I refuse to
get dressed, you can't make me,'' there's bound to be a power
struggle. But maybe she's showing spunk in the name of autonomy.
Maybe grabbing the shoe isn't an aggressive act but a way to tell
you, ``These shoes hurt.'' Maybe she's saying ``I want to be in
charge!''
</P>
<P>
   Test out the possibilities, suggests O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, put her other shoe in front of her and say
brightly, ``Let me see you do it!'' Or put sandals out: ``Would you
rather wear these today?'' If your interpretation is accurate,
she'll move along happily. If you get another ``no,'' pay more
attention to tone and body langauge. Is this ``no'' less forceful,
with a slightly quizzical look? Perhaps she's checking to see how
serious you are: ``Do I really have to do this now or can I stretch
it out?'' In that case, says O'Brien, ``Validate: `That's right,
Mattie. It's really time. Mom is in a hurry.' '' Your tone will
tell her you mean business.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all this interpreting takes a lot of time,
something we often don't have. O'Brien says her worst moments in
the land of no were almost always in the morning, trying to get
twins dressed and out of the door. ``I would say, `I know you want
to do it yourself, but Mommy has to rush. On another day, you can
do it.' My words were understanding but my tone let them know I was
serious,'' she says. ``On Saturday when I had all the time in the
world, I would say, `Now it's your turn.' If it took them 25
minutes to put on one shoe, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Empathizing with a toddler and validating her emotions _ ``I
know it's hard not to get what you want''; ``I know you don't want
to do this right now'' _ is often a winning strategy. ``When their
emotions get acknowledged instead of just their behaviors, they
feel understood on a deeper level and it's easier for them to move
on,'' Pruett says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alternative approaches &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other strategies to get beyond ``no'':
</P>
<P>
   --Ignore it. ``Proceed matter-of-factly, without registering the
`no,' as if nothing has happened. You'd be surprised at how often
she'll go along with you,'' says Lieberman. Don't overdo this,
however; it can be disrespectful. (If this works, by the way, it
can mean two things: ``no'' can also sometimes mean ``yes''; ``no''
was simply a chance to vocalize and didn't necessarily have any
real meaning.)
</P>
<P>
   --Distract him. The trick is to engage his imagination. A
playful tone _ ``What do you mean, no? Are you a Silly Billy?'' _
has a powerful effect to help a child out of a negative pattern,
says Pruett. Lieberman likes to tell a story: ``When we ride in the
car, I wonder if we'll see the yellow cat . . .''
</P>
<P>
   --Offer choices. This works magic, says Pruett, father of a
toddler himself. But he cautions, ``Only give a toddler choices
you're prepared to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   --Provide more information. When you interrupt him at play to
say it's time to change a diaper, he may not realize he can go back
to the sandbox immediately. Tell him so, says O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   --Rephrase. When you say, ``Alex, let's get dressed and go to
the playground,'' he may only hear the first part. ``If he heard
the whole thing, he might agree,'' says O'Brien. ``Rephrase it: `We
can go to the playground, but first let's put on shoes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the typical toddler's one-note symphony doesn't last
forever. That's the good news. The bad news? It often gets replaced
by two notes: ``Me do!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The typical toddler hears ``no'' once every three minutes,
according to researcher. The more frequently we use it, the more
we'll hear it back; the more inconsistent we are in its use,
sometimes meaning no, sometimes not, the more difficult it will be
to interpret what she means by it.
</P>
<P>
   --Children whose parents beg _ ``Please, please, please do this
now'' _ or bargain their way out of everything _ ``If you come now,
we can get ice cream'' _ get the message that if they say no loud
and long enough, they'll get their way. On the other hand, a reward
now and then is OK: ``You were so helpful when I needed to hurry!
That deserves a special treat!''
</P>
<P>
   --Practitioners generally agree that refusal to toilet train is
a child's ultimate no, a general protest to feeling overly
controlled. (This is most likely in a child 3 or older.)
</P>
<P>
   --By 2 1/2, most toddlers understand more words than they can
speak. If you find substitutes for your ``no'' _ ``Watch out!''
``Be careful!'' ``Look out!'' ``Danger!'' _ he will, too.
</P>
<P>
   --Avoid asking your toddler ``Why?'' or ``Why not?'' Young
children often misunderstand it and think you're scolding. Try
instead ``Tell me what you mean.''
</P>
<P>
   --For us, ``OK?'' is a rhetorical question; to a toddler, it's
veto power: ``Let's go to the store now, OK?'' Drop the ``OK'' and
simply state what you want: ``We're going to the store now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT: A delightful book (reminiscent of the Eloise
series) for 4- to 8-year-olds on having good manners: ``Kitty in
the City: Mind Your Manners, S'il Vous Plait'' by Kinsley Foster
(What's Inside Press, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
