<HEADER>
A8106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-PORN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-08 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-PORN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... user agreements.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The industry has taken steps to clean up its business practices,
says Craig Tant of CCBill Inc., a third-party billing company in
Phoenix that handles merchant accounts for more than 10,000 porn
sites. He notes that about 95 percent of his customers run an
honest business. But, he admits, ``we have seen scams that are
outrageous.'' Service companies like CCBill and SexTracker are
reaping huge profits, although their founders won't say exactly how
much. The real money in Internet pornography, some say, is being
made by the business-to-business companies that provide hardware
and services to Webmasters. ``The people who made the money in the
gold rush were the people selling the stuff to the miners, not the
miners themselves,'' says Duvall.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Edmond of SexTracker is riding high in Seattle these
days. At 26, he oversees a company with 100 employees and more than
29,000 clients. He fashions himself as a kind of sheriff bringing
order to the wild, wild West of the adult Internet. ``We take
professionalism very seriously,'' he says. ``This is not a
fly-by-night operation where there are a bunch of guys with
strippers sitting on their laps.'' In fact, many virtual porn shops
are run in makeshift home offices where computer programmers type
at keyboards and customer-service operators take technical
questions and complaints. ``You can be an adult-content provider
and live in an upscale neighborhood, and no one is the wiser,''
says Hardie.
</P>
<P>
   At the offices of the New Hampshire Phoenix Group, for instance,
three women smoke cigarettes and field phone calls in a relaxed
suburban setting.
</P>
<P>
   Customer-service representative Mercedes Taylor (a pseudonym)
says she was attracted to the job because smoking is permitted and
casual dress is encouraged. A single mother, she makes more money
now than she did as a teacher. ``I'm not the morality police,'' she
says. ``This is not my lifestyle, but I love my job. It's creative.
It's cutting-edge.'' Why would Daniels, a classically trained
musician who still conducts a local chorus, turn his basement into
a porn shop as opposed to, say, a Web business that sells sheet
music? ``This business makes money,'' he says simply.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL; 
SIDEBAR: SOME PIONEERS OF THE PORN SITES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, when the Web was in its infancy, Colin Daniels (a
pseudonym) and his wife ran a small giftware business specializing
in new-age jewelry, or ``goddess sort of stuff.'' On a whim, they
put their brochure on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing much happened - until they added a catalog of ``funky
Goth lingerie.'' Suddenly, the site was swamped with traffic, and
their computer server costs soared. As an experiment, they asked
users to subscribe for $10 a year. ``Lo and behold, people were
sending checks and e-mailing credit card numbers,'' says Daniels,
who now runs an online adult entertainment business from the
basement of his home in southern New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels is not alone. In the past few years, the Internet has
given rise to a new breed of porn merchant, a group of
computer-savvy entrepreneurs with plenty of ambition and few
inhibitions. Most of them got into the business by accident during
the early days of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Tant, for instance, is vice president of CCBill Inc., a
Phoenix-based company that hosts Web sites and handles credit card
processing for the adult entertainment industry. Four years ago, he
and his brother-in-law were selling juice bars on the Internet;
they were looking for someone to share a server with when they were
introduced to their first client in the porn field. ``We didn't
start out or plan to be in this business,'' says Tant. ``It was an
opportunity that just sort of appeared.'' One of the largest sites
was launched in 1995 by Beth Mansfield, an accountant in Tacoma,
Wash., who was worried about how to pay for her children's
education. Jane Duvall was selling advertising for a newspaper near
Seattle when adult sites emerged online; she and her husband, a
former scientist, set out to monitor the scams in the industry with
Jane's Guide, an online consumer magazine for the skin scene.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first adult entertainment sites was born in 1995,
when an MIT graduate (who requested anonymity) registered, on a
whim, a domain name with a common sexual reference. For kicks, he
downloaded a few dirty pictures from the Usenet news groups and put
them online. When the site was bombarded with traffic, he asked
users to pay $5 a month; the checks rolled in. This computer
programmer suffers from a chronic illness; when he started the
site, he couldn't work outside the house. ``I was sitting around in
my living room wondering what to do with myself,'' he recalls. ``I
wasn't dead yet, but I only offered people three-month
subscriptions because I didn't want people to be ripped off by
sending me money and then I dropped dead.'' Today, he still makes
enough to support himself and to run free online support groups for
people with HIV and other chronic illnesses. But he doesn't
consider himself a pornographer. ``I'm actually more of a computer
consultant, and I do a lot of public advocacy work,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PATTI HARTIGAN &QL;
</P>
