u a BC-SHACKLETON-BOAT-ART-B     06-08 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHACKLETON-BOAT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BOAT BUILDER REACHES FOR A BIT OF ANTARCTIC HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHELSEA, Mass. _ Shortly after 1 p.m. Wednesday, a crane was
preparing to plop a 23-foot-long boat freshly hewn from mahogany
and white oak timbers into the Mystic River, its shipwright and
captain a 54-year-old salt who has ridden many an Antarctic gale.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, Bob Wallace was airborne, riding his newest
boat, slung from the crane's cables, en route to its inaugural
splash into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, a bespectacled resident of Carver, has taken on a
somewhat unlikely hobby. He builds replicas of the James Caird, the
little open boat that in 1916 carried Sir Ernest Shackleton and
five crewmates into history as survivors of one of the greatest
adventures of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also has a somewhat unlikely goal. But he doesn't talk
about it much because Bob Wallace doesn't talk about anything much,
according to friends.
</P>
<P>
   If finances, crew, and logistics fall into place, he would like
in the next year or two to be the first person to duplicate
Shackleton's 800-mile crossing from Elephant Island to South
Georgia Island in the South Atlantic Ocean, a feat three
expeditions in the past nine years have tried, but failed, to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   The boat launched Wednesday will spend the summer at the Peabody
Essex Museum in Salem, where remarkable photographs taken during
Shackleton's Antarctic survival epic will be displayed from June 23
until Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace built his first copy of the James Caird last year in
Uruguay. It was used for shooting an Imax film and a WGBH-TV
``Nova'' special, both of which are still in production. The boat
was destroyed in a storm off Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   So one might have thought that Wallace would have been thinking
about ballast, bracing, joinery, and rigging at 1:44 p.m. when this
newest James Caird first touched the saltwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn,'' said Wallace, a man who seldom swears. ``I forgot the
champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been chasing the shadow of Sir Ernest Shackleton since the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy veteran, sea captain, and wooden boat builder, Wallace
was camping year-round on Bassett Island in the Bourne village of
Pocasset, rowing ashore each day to work in a nearby boatyard, and
generally believing he was roughing it in the manliest of ways.
Then he heard about Shackleton, and started reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I had thought all along I was a tough guy,'' he said with
a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, Wallace has been captain of the
oceanographic research ship Abel-Jay. The job has taken him to
Antarctic waters a half-dozen times. The father of a 12-year-old
son, Wallace is married to a psychologist. What probing questions
might she ask about his goal?
</P>
<P>
   `` `How's your life insurance? Don't let it lapse,' '' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   To understand Shacketon's journey, Wallace suggested imagining a
cat trying to cross an interstate highway cluttered with speeding
18-wheelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trucks are storms,'' he said. ``They come that fast.
You've got to thread between them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1914, Shackleton and a crew of 27 other men set out from
England intent on becoming the first expedition to walk across the
Antarctic continent. But they never even reached dry land. For the
next two years, the men, foiled by an ice sheet that smashed their
ship, survived on rations of penguin meat and self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort for help, six men sailed and rowed one of
the mother ship's lifeboats to South Georgia Island. Everyone
lived, eventually returning in 1916 to a world at war and a country
that did not particularly care about the heroics of a band of men
who got themselves in deep trouble looking for glory.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the publication of all-but-forgotten photographs
taken on the expedition kindled interest in the Shackleton story.
The photographs' only appearance in New England will be at the
Peabody.
</P>
<P>
   As Shackleton's journey became better known, adventurers from
Germany, Ireland, and other countries sought to retrace his
passage. None, so far, have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Wallace) doesn't talk about his abilities, but if there is
one guy truly competent enough to do the job, that would be Bob,''
said John Fish, a Cape Cod-based underwater surveyor who has put to
sea a number of times with Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace isn't offering a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do it, I'm going to have to get things rolling this year.
This interest in Shackleton is at its peak,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What did he learn Wednesday after just a few hours on the water?
</P>
<P>
   ``She's kind of tender, this one,'' Wallace said, laconic as
always. ``Ballast is going to be critical. Pretty tight space, too.
If I go, a total crew of four should do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
