<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-INTOUCH-ART-BOS &LR;      06-08 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-INTOUCH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE CULT OF THE HYPERCONNECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Scott makes his money on cranberry lemonade and orange mango
juice. But he's a BlackBerry addict.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket Nectars cofounder, a self-described ``juice guy,''
is part of a growing cult of hyperconnected entrepreneurs. Scott
swears by his BlackBerry, a calculator-size wireless e-mail device
that's the hottest new gadget on the street _ and on the beach and
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried everything,'' Scott says. ``Most of it, I think, is
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's a BlackBerry evangelist. He uses it all day, every day,
he says, to answer more than 100 messages sent to his regular
e-mail address, to maintain his calendar and address book, and to
check his to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   As summer kicks in, the BlackBerry is just one of many high-tech
tools business people are plunking in their pockets to stay in
touch, whether they're working or slipping out for an afternoon in
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy digital phones that work for talking and trading stocks,
Palms, two-way pagers, and tiny computers top the list of gadgets
the 24/7 crowd can't live without.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the surprise: Toting technology isn't just about
fueling workaholic tendencies. It's about getting work done fast,
so there's more time for fun.
</P>
<P>
   Scott calls his BlackBerry ``my greatest freedom provider
ever.'' It has cut down on his cell phone use, because he can
respond quickly via e-mail to simple business inquiries. He can get
a question answered while he's in a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a bonus: ``Your friends start to realize they can
reach you on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He and venture capitalist Jonathan Guerster, of Charles River
Ventures in Waltham, Mass., are lobbying to improve the telephone
signals that power the BlackBerry on Nantucket. Guerster, whose
summer refuge is also on the island, says, ``This device has
totally influenced the way I get business done.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerster says the berry fits the typical venture capitalist's
attention deficit disorder. The landscape of meetings is changing
dramatically, as people sit and surreptitiously respond to e-mails
with deft thumbs on tiny keypads.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Fillat, managing director at Advent International in
Boston, keeps his BlackBerry clipped to his belt. Polaris Venture
Partners in Waltham just ordered the product for its staff. They
cost about $400 a pop, plus $40 a month for e-mail service.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Curvey, online brokerage chief at Fidelity Investments, is
addicted to her two-way wireless pager, an Interactive 950 by
BlackBerry's maker, Research in Motion Ltd. of Ontario. It's
wireless messaging, as opposed to e-mail. She takes it everywhere
and says she'd give up her phone if she were forced to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't live without it,'' Curvey confesses. Hundreds of
Fidelity executives use the same pager _ a device Fidelity also
sells to its brokerage clients. Key features include automatic
indications that people have received and read messages _ and the
ability to get timely market information. Want to check Nasdaq or a
certain stock price every two hours? You can program the pager to
send it to you.
</P>
<P>
   Most business people say they rely on two gadgets. The most
frequent picks: a cell phone and a Palm, the popular line of
hand-held computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Michl, gadget guru and managing director at Ascent Venture
Partners in Boston, says he was disappointed by the Palm when he
rushed out to grab the first one on the market a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it,'' he says. He didn't like the pen technology _
using an attached penlike tool instead of a keypad. He returned his
first two Palms within 30 days of buying them. But now he has a
Palm 5X, and he's a convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finally ready for prime time,'' Michl says. It's fast,
and the screen's easy to read. It can store up to 10,000 addresses,
400 e-mails, and 3,000 to-do items. Michl uses it for Lotus Notes,
and he can download books and calculators, even games. It weighs 4
ounces and costs about $400. Another model, the Palm VII, is
Internet-enabled.
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone's still important, too, Michl says. He uses
Motorola's StarTac, a common favorite. Jon Flint, founding partner
at Polaris, says that on his weekly treks on planes, trains, and
automobiles, he stays in touch with a cell phone and a Palm.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Nadig is Boston chief for MetaMarkets, manager of the
OpenFund, an online mutual fund that posts all its trades
real-time. He stays glued to his cell phone but loves his Casio
Pocket PC. It's only a little bigger than a Palm III, he says,
``and infinitely more powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   For $600 (plus add-ons that quickly get you to $1,000) Nadig
does all his e-mail on the Casio, including receiving attachments.
On top of the usual conveniences of address book, calendar and task
list, he can download books, his daily newspaper, and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most important, it loads the spreadsheets we use to run the
fund,'' says Nadig, an information animal who's balancing the
demands of a young, venture-backed company with a new family.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has abandoned the laptop for hand-held toys. Tony
Zona, chief executive of Quantum Bridge Communications Inc., a
North Andover, Mass. fiber-optics start-up, says his laptop goes
with him everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC allows me to do virtually everything (besides make
calls) _ email, research, calendar management, presentations, and
budgets.'' And Zona still believes in the cell phone: ``It's
important to stay connected _ anywhere, any time.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a downside to all of the gadgetry, business people
say, it's that they're essentially always on call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is, you're always accessible,'' says Charles
River's Guerster. ``The bad news is, you're always accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Alper, an analyst at Gomez Advisors in Lincoln, Mass., says
the need to stay in touch is concentrated among a high-powered
minority. For other people, he suggests, the technology is
expensive, inconvenient overkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a subset of hyperactives out there who always have to
be connected,'' Alper says. ``When I go away, I don't even check my
e-mail. It can wait.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he says, ``It's a balance you have to strike between
your professional and personal lives. Otherwise, you never get off
the fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   A cell phone and Palm are enough for Gautam Prakash, a partner
with Bessemer Venture Partners in Wellesley Hills, Mass. Beyond
that, he says, ``My brain gets fried.'' Forget the Blackberry, he
adds. ``I don't want to be that connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the juice guy, has the answer to that. ``If it ties you
up more than it helps you,'' he says, ``shut it off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
