<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BAD NEWS MAY BE GOOD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was chaos and shock at APBnews.com's (www.apbnews.com) New
York headquarters this week as the respected crime-news Web site
fought for its survival. The 18-month-old operation had attracted
contributors _ ranging from Pulitzer Prize winner Sydney Schanberg
to former O.J. prosecutor Marcia Clark _ won lots of critical
praise, and taken numerous journalism honors. On Tuesday, reporter
Kevin Heldman won a prestigious Livingston Award _ for excellence
by journalists under 35 _ for his coverage of the Japanese penal
system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, APBnews.com ran out of money, pink-slipped 140
employees and, by midweek, was running on volunteers while
desperately seeking new investors. ``I'm hopeful we'll get
something done this week,'' declared a harried Mark Sauter, a
cofounder and the site's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news generated genuine condolences. ``This particular
company, it's just a shame,'' says Kevin Clark, CEO of
ScreamingMedia (www.screamingmedia.net), which distributes online
content. But a number of analysts also view the APBnews.com
predicament, like the NASDAQ correction and e-commerce shakeout, as
a healthy signal to venture capitalists and cyber entrepreneurs
that reality has finally overtaken exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of shakeup is a good thing,'' says Dan O'Brien,
senior analyst at Forrester Research. ``It's going to shake out
some of the nonsense and the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   The current ``retraction'' is ``going to be healthy over an
extended period,'' says Larry Pryor, executive news editor of the
Online Journalism Review (www.usc.edu), who thinks APBnews.com may
have been a victim of its overarching and expensive ambitions to be
the worldwide leader in crime news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Specialize, concentrate, focus,'' Pryor advises online
journalists. ``Come up with a quality product that fills a
speciality niche.''
</P>
<P>
   APBnews.com wasn't the only recent online media casualty. On one
end of the spectrum, CBS laid off 24 of its Internet division
staffers this week. On the other, NewsWatch.org _ a modest online
media criticism magazine published by the nonprofit Center for
Media and Public Affairs _ closed up shop last week when its
benefactor cut the fiscal lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   APBnews.com's troubles were the most noteworthy, however,
because the company looked so promising. According to spokesman Joe
Krakoviak, the site had more than 1 million unique viewers in
April. And it was working on new revenue sources, having just
reached agreement with the Prentice Hall publishing company to
develop a Web site for students studying criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a round of financing last summer netted APBnews.com a
healthy $20 million. ``People were literally trying to force money
on us,'' recalls Sauter, son of former CBS News president Van
Gordon Sauter. Then came the technology sector market shock and the
dough dried up. Sauter says investors went from being
``irrationally supportive'' of online journalism ventures to
``irrationally set against them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years, if you had dot.com on your name, you got all
the money you could possibly misspend,'' says Krakoviak. Now,
venture capitalists want revenue streams before the content
schemes. Given that environment, a number of analysts say the moral
of the APBnews.com story is to think smaller and smarter.
</P>
<P>
   APBnews.com ``tried to do too much too soon,'' says Online
Journalism Review editor Joshua Fouts. ``There's this gold rush
mentality that we have to have the buffet meal instead of a salad
first.'' Fouts says the shrewder business models belong to more
modest, niched sites like the comedy-oriented Suck.com
(www.suck.com) and The Smoking Gun (www.thesmokinggun.com), which
unearths ``confidential and quirky'' documents like Billy Bob
Thornton's and Angelina Jolie's marriage license.
</P>
<P>
   According to ScreamingMedia's Clark, there's another dark cloud
on the horizon for online journalism innovators _ the approach of
old media companies who have finally concluded that ``the Internet
is to be embraced instead of feared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the online content companies are going to experience
competition from some of the more traditional content companies who
are aggressively moving online,'' he says. If so, the Internet obit
pages may fill up with more victims like APBnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Romenesko is becoming a victim of his own success. The
proprietor of a wildly popular journalism-news Web site
(www.poynter.org), the low-keyed Romenesko recently won a Webby
Award for best news site, was profiled by New York magazine, and
receives 200-300 e-mails a day from journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Given that volume, Romenesko has begun changing the character of
his site. Where it once relied heavily on stories and items written
by media reporters, it now contains a growing number of e-mails
that create a forum for intramedia skirmishing. Visitors recently
witnessed one APBnews.com staffer e-mailing another ``to go shove
it,'' and a heated debate about whether the Saturday Philadelphia
Daily News is published before the bulldog edition of the Sunday
Philadelphia Inquirer. (Whew!)
</P>
<P>
   Romenesko says he's created a ``pub atmosphere,'' by opening up
the e-mail debate. But here's a vote against it. Anyone interested
in hearing fellow journalists whine, accuse, and speculate can
simply wander into his or her newsroom. Romenesko's site was better
when it eschewed such chatter for more emphasis on ``just the
facts, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Jurkowitz is the Boston Globe media reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
