 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and a coding)  
 WEB CAMERAS AT DAY-CARE CENTERS CAPTURE PARENTS' ATTENTION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if parents are confident about the safety of a day care
center, worries often haunt them throughout the work day. Does the
timid toddler morph into the diapered despot when mother and father
are out of sight? Or the greedy grabber? Or, worse yet, the lonely
left-out?
</P>
<P>
   Curious parents no longer have to peek from behind the cubbies
to see what's going on: they use a Web camera.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a controversial frill in the day-care
industry, a growing number of parents are getting the chance to
become a cyberfly on the day-care wall. At work or at home, they
simply log onto a Web site, type in a password, then enter the
world of Playground Time, Nap Time, and Circle Time.
</P>
<P>
   Via video cameras installed in each room, parents see their
child's activities in images delivered as slowly as snapshots
updated every few seconds or as quickly as a real-time movie. The
footage comes without audio, so there are no squeals of delight or
shouts of a tantrum.
</P>
<P>
   The security benefits are obvious, but some child psychologists
worry that these centers aren't giving enough thought to how the
spontaneous and often wild world of childhood can be misinterpreted
on film.
</P>
<P>
   And will the staff and children become more inhibited if they
know parents will watch them at random moments of the day?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a staff member, you will never pick your nose
again,'' said Jacqueline Olds, a Cambridge, Mass. child
psychiatrist. ``And if you're a child, you feel that loss of
privacy in spades.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these concerns, these Web cameras have been hooked into
the ceilings of a growing number of child-care centers nationwide
over the past year, especially those catering to computer-savvy
two-career couples. National groups overseeing day-care groups
don't have any figures, but several major companies that run these
video services report wiring hundreds of centers in dozens of
states.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts will see an influx of wired centers this summer
when Knowledge Beginnings, a company based in San Rafael, Calif.,
activates five sites around Boston.
</P>
<P>
   These Web cameras, however, are not just part of the high-tech
beltway. Bright Beginnings in Winthrop, Mass., which became perhaps
the state's first wired center last summer, is located between two
auto body shops on a semicommercial strip. And in the coming year,
Knowledge Beginnings will unveil sites in Littleton, Concord,
Newburyport, Peabody, and Hyannis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   For parents who are only too familiar with the heart-wrenching
details of the death of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen while in the
care of Louise Woodward as well as the sexual molestation
convictions at the Fells Acres Day School, these video cameras can
seem like a godsend, judging by the early reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear so many horror stories,'' said Bob Scalli, 38, a real
estate investor whose 4-year-old son is enrolled at Bright
Beginnings. ``To me, a picture is worth a thousand words. With the
cameras, we are connected even when we're away.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Hatch, regional director for operations for Knowledge
Beginnings, said the Web cameras ease the minds of parents who are
away 8 to 10 hours a day. He said grandparents who live abroad, as
long as they have Internet access and know the password, also can
watch their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're providing another window for them to peek into,'' he
said. ``It's an extension of our open-door policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said his center's Web site offers more than photo images;
it provides chat rooms for parents to ask questions about topics
ranging from toilet training to reading. The site lists the menus
for lunch and snack, progress reports, and curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   These amenities come at a price. Knowledge Beginnings is at the
high end, charging $800 to $1,170 a month for a five-day program,
with infant care costing the most. Parents pay an extra $15 or so a
month if they want the video-viewing option.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bright Beginnings site, which has fewer amenities, the
monthly charges are $560 to $780 a month, and the video services
are included.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the video option, however, may be worth it to
parents who want the reassurance that their child who was sobbing
at drop-off time was laughing in the dress-up area minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful to know that 20 minutes after you got to
work, the child was really OK,'' said Ellen Modica, family services
coordinator for the Child Care Resource Center in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some early-childhood specialists warn parents not to have
a knee-jerk positive reaction to anything related to the word
``computer.'' They expect that the cameras will influence
children's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   They say children as young as 2 or 3 years old may interpret the
cameras as a symbol of their parents' overwhelming power, and delay
their struggles toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   Several children interviewed at centers that have cameras
described them as tools to monitor their behavior, much like the
Santa Claus notion of knowing whether ``you've been naughty or
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They watch people when they do bad things,'' said Huy Pham, 5,
who is enrolled at Knowledge Beginnings in Chelmsford, where the
cameras are scheduled to be activated in two months.
</P>
<P>
   While some children said the cameras were simply for fun or a
way to say hello to parents, a 4-year-old boy said the devices were
the video eyes of the staff. ``If the teachers are somewhere else,
they can say, `This is a good boy or this is a bad boy,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Olds, the child psychiatrist, said hard-working parents should
guard against becoming the ``over-scrutinizing'' parent, the one
who confronts the day-care staff because the video showed their
child getting pushed one day. She emphasized that the camera should
work to enhance, not erode, a trusting relationship between staff
and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Hooper, director of the Arlington Children's Center, which
does not have video cameras, said she can imagine a scenario in
which a teacher has to intervene in a crowd of children. Depending
on the context, that teacher's actions could seem tyrannical or
timid _ or totally appropriate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some psychologists also wondered whether parents may feel free
to work longer hours, as long as they see the reassuring image of
their happy child on the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the psychological impact of these cameras appears to
have taken a back seat to the security issues. Day-care operators
go to great lengths to reassure parents that each family has a
special password, so Web-surfing strangers cannot view the
children. Cameras are not aimed at bathrooms or diaper-changing
areas, and images cannot be printed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
