<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE READERS SPEAK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers write, suspicious about nefarious uses of Night Vision,
angry that I even review SUVs and pickup trucks, wondering why
their tires are lasting so long. They want answers. I've got 'em.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I have over 85,000 miles on . . . my 1995 Buick Regal. The
tires are Goodyear Invicta GS. I have checked the tread regularly
using the Lincoln's head-on-the-penny technique and looked at them
carefully when the car is on the lift for an oil change. I have
never had tires last this long . . . . This is making me nervous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Not to worry, says Dave Wilkins, a Goodyear spokesman. The
reason you can insert the penny upside down in a groove and still
have enough tread to touch part of the dead president's head is
that you obviously know about tires and take care of them, keeping
them inflated properly, rotated regularly, and aligned. Wilkins
says he often gets calls from folks with 100,000 miles on their
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to check for wear on tires, he says, is to watch for
a ``wear indicator.'' It is a small band of rubber that will appear
running across the tread groove when the tires wear to a certain
point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I have heard that Ford has delayed the introduction of the
new Thunderbird. A dealer said they were afraid there would be too
much demand and they want to be sure they can build enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  An auto manufacturer holding off on production because of
fears that demand might be too high? Right. Here's the plan for the
new Thunderbird, according to Ford's Kathleen Hamilton. Production
starts in 2001. The T-Birds will be ready for sale in the 2002
model year. My advice: Get in line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  After a column on Cadillac's new Night Vision system, which
lets the driver see objects well beyond the range of headlights,
one reader asked if Night Vision would allow ``young kids'' to
drive without lights for kicks or criminals to flee the law.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Stuart Klapper, director of automotive programs for
Raytheon, which developed Night Vision along with General Motors,
says it can't happen.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Night Vision system is linked to the headlights. If
the headlights aren't on, neither is Night Vision.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he explains, the system for civilian autos is weak
compared to what Raytheon builds for the military. You couldn't
drive at night with just the former. You can with the latter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  Most of the vehicles you review fall into the category of
gas-guzzling, overpowered, destructive trucks . . . . The
glamorization of SUVs makes you responsible for the environmental
and safety hazards they create. Do you want this on your shoulders?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Here is how I choose what I write about: which vehicles are
people most interested in buying; which vehicles represent a step
forward in what and how we drive; which vehicles are ``fantasies''
that most of us will never be able to buy but we can share
vicarious thrills about because I drive them.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, truck sales (including SUVs) exceed auto sales. When
I am write about them, I am writing about what people obviously
want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, I wrote 38 reviews of cars and 13 reviews of
SUVs, trucks, and vans. Anger at the thought of me even reviewing
an SUV apparently blinded this reader, who probably did not see
reviews of the Honda Insight, Toyota Echo, Ford Focus, and lots of
little two-seat sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, I've got big shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My husband and I are looking to replace our pickup tuck.
The truck we want is too expensive. We are interested in the Subaru
Outback, but magazines have warned it has poor pickup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Subaru has an answer.
</P>
<P>
   At the Detroit International Auto Show this year, the company
unveiled a new engine for the Outback, an H-6 (that's
horizontally-opposed cylinders) 3.0 liter. It will generate 212
horsepower _ plenty to give the small SUV the pop you want.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I have heard Toyota has a new SUV ready to hit the market.
What is it called?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Actually, Toyota, even while saying it would like to be a
greener company but these are what customers are demanding, is
introducing two SUVs. If you want big and luxurious, go for the
Sequoia, a V8 Suburban-sized beast based on the Tundra pickup
truck. If a more car-like SUV is your desire, they will have the
Highlander, all-wheel-drive, not as high from the ground, not
really meant for off-road travel but good for winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  When I asked in a column how it can be that the outside,
commuter lane on Interstate 93 north comes to a complete halt as
you approach the 128 intersection while cars three lanes over on
the right are making their exit _ and how if one jerk trying to get
by just one more car by using the passing lane before swerving to
exit causes the backup _ a reader had a question: Didn't I mean the
inside lane, when I spoke of the commuter lane, and isn't the exit
lane the outside lane?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Well, sign me ``Confused.'' I always considered the lane I
passed people in and commuted in to be the outside lane, and that I
exited from the inside lane, much as a race car going into the pits
from the inside lane on a track. Maybe the reader is right. What do
the rest of you think?
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
