</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 THE ROUSH VERSION: SUV'S DELUSION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is for all those folks who drive their big SUVs like
idiots, weaving in traffic at high speed, tailgating at any speed,
snapping through lane changes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the SUV you think you are driving.
</P>
<P>
   But, it is not the top-heavy, ready-to-roll, hard-to-stop rig
you really do drive and with which you endanger others when you
shift into nitwit.
</P>
<P>
   This one started out as a Ford Expedition XLT. The Expedition
was introduced in 1997 and has done quite well up against the
Suburban and other competitors. Like most big SUVs, it is based on
a pickup truck, in this case the F150. In its original form, this
test Expedition was a solid, dependable SUV with all the inherent
benefits and dangers of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then the folks at Roush Performance in Detroit got their hands
on it. If you're a NASCAR fan, you'll recognize the name Roush and
know where we're headed here. If not, a briefing: Jack Roush owns
Roush Industries. It has three divisions: Racing (he sponsors five
Winston Cup teams), Technology, and Performance.
</P>
<P>
   The latter group, drawing on the engineering that comes out of
Technology and the brand recognition that Racing provides, takes
certain Fords _ the F150, the Mustang, and the Expedition _ and
tweaks them big-time, with their own suspensions, interior options,
supercharged engines.
</P>
<P>
   Which gave us this beast we just spent a week driving.
</P>
<P>
   Now before all you folks who get upset when I test a big
gas-guzzler of an SUV begin firing off your hate mail, I've got
something in the weeks ahead for you. I'll be in Arizona in the
middle of June at a competition called FutureTruck. There, 10
engineering schools from around the country will each take a
Suburban that they have rebuilt to make them more environmentally
friendly, and run through tests to see who has done the best job.
It's important because it represents where SUVs, if they continue
to be mass produced, will have to go.
</P>
<P>
   Roush only sells about 250 of these special Expeditions a year,
so we're not talking huge environmental impact here. This is a car
for special people with special wants _ mostly guys over 35 with
healthy incomes and a need for speed, even in a big rig.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it sells best in Southern California and
Texas, according to Joe Thompson, the national sales manager for
Roush Performance.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with the 5.4-liter V-8 that is an Expedition. They do
only one thing to the engine, but it is a big thing: Roush bolts on
a Paxton supercharger, but limits it to 6-8 pounds of boost.
Enough, says Thompson, for ``exhilaration without destroying the
power train.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it gives a 40 percent increase in horsepower to 365.
Torque is up 30 percent, to a whopping 483 lb.-ft. Of course, that
helps cut gasoline mileage to 10.25, but folks who buy this car _
with more than $17,000 in Roush goodies added to the Expedition's
sticker _ probably aren't looking to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a 3 1/2-ton rocket that seems launched at start
and pounds through a seemingly endless torque curve.
</P>
<P>
   It's lowered by two inches for stability and the suspension has
a big upgrade that includes high performance Billstein shock
absorbers, lowered springs, and thicker sway bars.
</P>
<P>
   It works, as the big rig is remarkably nimble and virtually free
of the dangerous pitch and roll you get in standard SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   The inside is luxurious and headroom and legroom abound. The
Roush package includes wood-grain dash inserts, leather seats with
extra side bolsters, and machined billet floor pedals. The Roush
logo is everywhere _ floor mats, pedals, front and rear windows.
The seats are solid and supportive, and even the middle bench has
the feel of three buckets. The rear bench is more spartan, but is
comfortable as well.
</P>
<P>
   Television sets in the back of each front bucket keep middle
seat passengers happy. Ergonomically, it's very well designed with
pockets and bins everywhere and a huge center console that holds a
CD changer and still has big space.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 dealers nationwide are authorized to sell Roush
Fords (see www.roushperf.com for details). You can buy what a
dealer may have in stock, or order an Expedition, which Ford will
ship to Roush for the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   This is not for everyone, obviously.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the car that many jerks think they are driving _
although they are not.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   Cupholders with slots cut away from the circle for _ amazing _
coffee cup handles.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   A speedometer that only goes to 100. Not that we need to go
there, but who are they kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
