<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING THE ATTACK OF A BESTSELLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Worst-Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' comes with a
warning: ``Do not attempt to undertake any of the activities
described in this book yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a survival handbook, no? In the event I find myself,
say, entwined in a python, the authors' advice (``Try to unwrap the
coils, starting from whichever end is available'') seems like it
might be useful. So, given the warning, am I supposed to just let
the thing squeeze me to death?
</P>
<P>
   David Borgenicht assured me that I should feel free to wrestle
the python, but if anything goes wrong I should consider myself
warned. In other words, I shouldn't call James ``Helping Injured
People'' Sokolove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Worst-Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' is a publishing
phenomenon. The little yellow book came out late last year with no
fanfare, but it quickly became a word-of-mouth success. There are
now 500,000 copies in print, and it's about to go to its ninth
printing. Last Sunday it was on The New York Times bestseller's
list at No. 4 in the advice, how-to, and miscellaneous category. On
Sunday it will jump to No. 2, just behind ``Chicken Soup for the
Teenage Soul III.'' All of this has surprised the authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in publishing long enough to know that the odds of
having a bestseller are about as long as finding yourself in some
of the scenarios in our book,'' said Borgenicht, from his office in
Philadelphia. ``Actually, you're probably more likely to be
attacked by a shark than have a bestseller.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has obvious appeal for those of a paranoid disposition.
Others read it for laughs; some bookstores stock it on the
``humor'' shelf. But the book taps into something bigger: the
current rage for stories about nature-as-ordeal. It appeals to many
of the same readers who loved ``The Perfect Storm'' and ``Into Thin
Air.'' Borgenicht describes these types as ``people who want to
think of themselves as adventurous even if they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Borgenicht said he came up with the idea for the book while
reading an article on how to land a plane in an emergency. ``I
started thinking about all the cool stuff I've seen in action
movies, the situations the heroes get into,'' he said. ``But
they've got stunt men and trick photography. What about the rest of
us?''
</P>
<P>
   The authors interviewed experts in various fields, among them
Coleman Cooney, director of the Bullfight School (``How to Deal
With a Charging Bull'') and Chris Caso, stuntman (``How to Jump
From a Building Into a Dumpster'') and Joe Jennings, skydiving
coordination specialist (``How to Survive If Your Parachute Fails
to Open'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these situations are not likely to happen, but they do
happen to people now and then, so you never know,'' Borgenicht
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the off chance you may have to wrestle an alligator, here's
some advice: ``Cover the alligator's eyes. This will usually make
it more sedate.'' The handbook doesn't say just what you're
supposed to cover the alligator's eyes with. Your hands?
Peek-a-boo, Mr. Alligator. The advice about how to escape from a
swarm of killer bees seems easier to implement. It boils down to
this: Run for your life.
</P>
<P>
   Borgenicht and Piven are working on a related book, ``The
Worst-Case Scenario Travel Handbook,'' a collection of advice from
experts on subjects such as how to survive a plane crash, how to
deal with terrorists, how to avoid being rude to people in other
countries. ``Everything,'' says Borgenicht, ``from insult to
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
