<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHO'S BEHIND THE FINAL CURTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, dear reader, you have a rare opportunity to participate
in a historic event. This column, you see, isn't destined for the
bottom of the bird cage or the recycling bin. No, today's column is
a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just about art: It is art. Some day soon, these humble
words will end up in the archives of conceptual artist Joey Skaggs
as part of the documentation of his latest opus. Skaggs is a
culture jammer who has spent the last 30 years fooling the media
with elaborate hoaxes. The media, he says, is his medium, so
everything written about him immediately becomes part of his work.
Voila: Art.
</P>
<P>
   This creative exercise begins at the end _ as in death, the
ultimate exit, the inevitable last call. In October, Skaggs's alter
ego Stuart MacLelland sent out a press release announcing
finalcurtain.com, the Web site for a chain of funeral theme parks.
``Death got you down?'' it asked. ``At last an alternative!'' The
concept, complete with time shares, vacation packages, galleries,
and restaurants called Dante's Grill and Heaven's Gate Cafe, proved
that you don't have to go gentle into that good night: Instead, you
can dance merrily on the tombstones, or ``site-specific works of
passage.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was a prank orchestrated to satirize the death
industry and to expose the media's willingness to jump all over a
to-die-for story. And jump they did. Stories about Final Curtain
appeared in dozens of newspapers and magazines, including ``The Los
Angeles Times'' and ``Mother Jones,'' as well as on radio stations
and Web sites. Skaggs exposed the prank himself by issuing another
press release last month, explaining how he had spent two years
hatching his hoax.
</P>
<P>
   So who is this crazy character and why does he do this? ``I'm an
artist, and the media is my canvas,'' says Skaggs during a
telephone interview from Hawaii, where he says he is vacationing in
a sort of ``birdcage, tree house by the beach.'' Something,
allegedly a cardinal, chirps in the background. ``In my own
self-righteous way,'' he continues, ``I think there are
sociopolitical issues that need to be examined. That's what my art
is. It's not wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The person in the bird cage claiming to be Skaggs is an outgoing
fellow, certainly not lacking in self-esteem. But he's spent his
whole career hoodwinking journalists and proving that they
shouldn't believe a word anyone says without doing a thorough
background check. So how do we know this guy is really Skaggs? He
sent somebody else to represent himself on a segment of ``To Tell
the Truth'' and pulled the same stunt on ``Entertainment Tonight.''
And he won't give his age _ ``You don't need to know that'' _ but a
1994 ``New York Times'' article put his age at 48 in 1994, which
would make him 54, give or take a year. When he isn't hanging out
in Hawaii, he says he lives in SoHo and makes a living teaching at
schools including his alma mater, New York's School for the Visual
Arts. A Joey Skaggs is, in fact, listed in the Manhattan phonebook,
and the registrar at the School for the Visual Arts confirmed that
Skaggs is on the list of occasional instructors there and that he
graduated with a degree in advertising in 1982. Hmm. He must have
been a late bloomer: Do the math.
</P>
<P>
   A quick check of Dow Jones Interactive unveils scads of articles
written about Skaggs and his scams over the past 20 years. (They're
also documented at www.joeyskaggs.com.) These include: The Fat
Squad, a team of calorie cops run by Joe Bones; Portofess, a
confessional on wheels featured at the 1992 Democratic Convention;
and Cathouse for Dogs, a bow-wow bordello. And then there was the
Celebrity Sperm Bank, a scheme launched in 1976 that caused outrage
among the media and the moralists. The Internet, of course, makes
it easy to make money off such stunts. Remember all the attention
given last year to RonAngels.com, the Web site ostensibly
auctioning off model's donor eggs that was run by a notorious
pornographer?
</P>
<P>
   Skaggs, the performance artist, differentiates himself from the
con artists: ``It's all in the intent,'' he says. ``There's no
money in it.'' He also says he would be happy if some hard-working
journalist sniffed out the truth. ``I have never been busted,'' he
says, sighing. ``That is the sad truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But not exactly the whole truth. Journalist Brock Meeks exposed
his Sexonix project in 1993 when Skaggs claimed to have invented a
cybersex apparatus that was confiscated by Canadian customs agents.
And in 1992, nobody showed up when he announced a press conference
at New York City Hall to unveil a Brooklyn Bridge lotto.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, however, that many media outlets don't own up to
their mistakes when they fall for his tricks. ``Everyone wants
acknowledgment and verification,'' he says. The media hacktivist,
it turns out, craves media attention. ``Satirists don't have a lot
of friends,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have quite a scrapbook. Scaggs maintains an
extensive archive of articles written about his culture jams.
``Like it or not, you are part of my art,'' he says. ``You're very
brave _ and foolish, too.'' So you, dear reader, have a choice. You
can keep this column for your own art collection, you can put it in
your birdcage, or you can send it to Skaggs to add to the Final
Curtain memorial. He, or one of his aliases, can be reached at
info(at)joeyskaggs.com or P.O. Box 212, Anahola, Hawaii 96703.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The folks who run a bizarre Web site called Temple ov Thee Lemur
(www.totl.net) don't try to pass themselves off as culture jammers
or artists. They're just a bunch of British blokes with a strange
sense of humor. (Don't ask about the name: It's based on an obscure
pun and would take way too long to explain.) Last week, they
announced that they had created a potato-powered computer. The site
even had an FAQ. Sample queries: How long do the potatoes last? Can
you eat them?
</P>
<P>
   The BBC ran a serious piece about this nonexistent invention,
illustrated with a photograph of ``the potatoes in action.'' USA
Today and other august media outlets picked up the story. But Web
master Steve Harris says he never expected anyone to believe you
could run a microchip off a potato chip. ``We never intended to
fool anyone,'' says Harris, 25, of Southampton, England, one of
seven tech heads who run the site. ``Most of our readers are geeks,
and we thought it was obvious that it was a windup.'' Translation:
Windup is British for hoax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enough windups. The following items are entirely true.
</P>
<P>
   --Texas death row inmate Michael Toney tried to auction off five
seats to his execution on eBay. The auction site shut down the sale
a few hours after it began, and Toney's lawyer said his client's
action was ``totally inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   --Teen pop icon Britney Spears and bad boy rapper Eminem are
working together in cyberspace. No joke. The latest song making the
rounds online is an unauthorized remix called ``My Name is Crazy.''
It pairs the raunchy lyrics to Eminem's ```My Name Is'' with
Spear's slick pop hit ``Crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   --Newt Gingrich and his lovely fiance Callista Bisek (No. 3!)
are in dire need of a tart tin and a citrus zester _ along with
every kind of wine glass, champagne flute, and brandy snifter
imaginable. The lovebirds are registered online at Williams-Sonoma
and Macy's, and they still need plenty of stuff on the lists. (The
Waterford decanter goes for a mere $298.)
</P>
<P>
   The Williams-Sonoma gift list is the featured document this week
on TheSmokingGun.com, the Web site run by two crackerjack
investigative reporters who have dug up incriminating evidence on
everyone from Howard Stern to alleged multimillionaire Rick
Rockwell. These guys would never fall for something like The Final
Curtain. And you never know: They might dig up some dirt on Joey
Skaggs some day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Patti Hartigan's e-mail address is hartig(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
