 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes web site pioneers sidebar)  
 SEX-DOOR NEIGHBORS: WEB PORN DOES SUBURBIA  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The four-bedroom brick colonial seems to be the very model of
mainstream suburbia: two cars in the driveway, friendly dogs at the
door, a pool in the backyard, a grand piano in the
climate-controlled library. The owners are Internet entrepreneurs.
In their spare time, they like to garden, rock climb, and sail.
</P>
<P>
   And down in the basement, they run a profitable online
pornography business that specializes in bondage and domination.
</P>
<P>
   When the neighbors ask what they do, the owners say, ``We're in
e-commerce.'' Located in southern New Hampshire, the Phoenix Group
is a multimillion-dollar operation that employs a staff of seven,
including a former middle school teacher. ``We're not doing as well
as Bill Gates, but we have a nice nest egg,'' says Phoenix Group
founder Colin Daniels (a pseudonym), 45, a former professional
musician. Daniels says his business, which includes a flagship
site, boasts a cumulative total of 150,000 customers a year; he
points out that many of these customers sign on for the service for
short periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when venture capitalists and business leaders are
falling all over themselves trying to figure out how to make money
on the Web, entrepreneurs in the online adult entertainment
industry are floating in profits. With its global reach, instant
accessibility, and anonymity, the Internet has brought pornography
into the mainstream, taking it out of the penthouses and mansions
of porn kings and placing it smack in the basements and garages of
middle America.
</P>
<P>
   Since virtually all of the companies are private and many of the
merchants tend to be cagey and circumspect, it's hard to determine
the exact size of the industry. Most analysts steer clear of the
trade, and ratings services like Media Metrix don't track adult
sites as a separate category. But according to a 1999 study by the
New York-based research firm Datamonitor, adult content accounts
for 69 percent of the $1.4 billion market for online services;
other estimates put the online porn business at between $1 billion
and $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In April, some 17.6 million users, or 22 percent of all Internet
users, visited an adult site, according to Nielsen/Net Ratings. And
the top-rated porn site in April received more traffic than such
popular mainstream sites as AskJeeves .com, Priceline.com, and
Barnes andNoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wide-ranging content Industry sources estimate that there are
tens of thousands of porn sites on the Internet, offering
everything from still photographs to live Webcams and streaming
video. The content is all over the map; virtual sex shops sport
names like Lust Highway, Sex on the Strip, Busty Amateurs, and
Granny Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Run by amateurs and semi-pros all over the country, many of
these sites are turning a handsome profit. While the top few sites
are run by a handful of old-fashioned porn purveyors, there is a
brand-new group of proprietors that includes slick young computer
wizards, former porn stars, and suburban swingers. Young and old,
male and female, they pioneer new technologies and marketing
methods years before they are adopted by the mainstream corporate
world. Almost all of them use pseudonyms, and many of them defy
stereotypes, like the Cambridge programmer who runs a paid porn
site so he can afford to run free support groups for people with
HIV and other chronic disorders. ``A lot of these people are geeks
who obsess about code, not content,'' says Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the adult entertainment industry exists in its own
alternative universe on the Internet, independent of the vagaries
of venture capitalists and the Nasdaq market. It has its own
villains and heroines, its own search engines and service
organizations, its own award ceremonies and trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   It has a fair share of hucksters and rip-off artists, but it
also has its own self-appointed consumer watchdog, a former
advertising saleswoman named Jane Duvall who runs Jane's Guide, a
popular Web site that monitors industry fraud.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's part of a college curriculum: Last month, San
Francisco State University launched a course that studies the
online skin scene.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is: Sex sells.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Danni Ashe, a former centerfold who has become a sort
of poster girl for the flourishing industry. She started her
soft-core site, Danni's Hard Drive, for $8,000 in 1995; her
business now employs 38 people and grossed $5.2 million last year,
with projected earnings of $7 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are all genetically programmed to want to have
sex and talk about sex and look at sex,'' says Ashe, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated technology But the success of the industry doesn't
ride on hormonal instinct alone.
</P>
<P>
   Porn has always driven the development of media technology, from
nickelodeon peep shows to videocassettes to Webcams to live,
streaming video. The next generation of Internet add-ons is already
in development; one company is marketing a line of tactile devices
called ``cyberdildonics,'' and Vivid Entertainment Inc. invented a
neoprene cybersex bodysuit with 36 built-in sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware manufacturers often test new high-end systems on porn
sites, which generate heavy traffic and require high bandwidth.
``It's all very confidential, but the major vendors do it all the
time,'' says Chris Buerger, manager of networking for Datamonitor.
</P>
<P>
   The online pornographers also pioneered marketing techniques
that have been adopted by mainstream merchants and publishers all
over the Internet. They were early adapters of pop-up windows and
exit consoles that invite users to visit affiliated Web sites; the
referring site gets a cut of any business conducted at the next
site. Amazon.com and other e-merchants now have similar referring
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The free porn sites, or ``farm'' sites, make decent money this
way; many of them are run by the same folks who operate the
subscription sites, which charge up to $25 a month. Cooperation is
the name of the game in the industry: Large or small, providers are
all involved in a complex web of partnerships and profit-sharing
deals.
</P>
<P>
   The adult sites also expertly monitor and filter traffic,
building demographic profiles of customers to target ads
specifically to users. ``You don't try to sell a lawnmower during
`Oprah,' `` explains Andrew Edmond, chief executive officer of
SexTracker, a Seattle-based service company that hosts porn sites
and markets statistical analysis tools.
</P>
<P>
   The porn industry has always been a few steps ahead of the
mainstream entertainment industry, which is embroiled in lawsuits
involving Internet piracy and hasn't figured out how to make money
of its own online. Likewise, none of the megahyped start-ups
offering mainstream online entertainment have been able to develop
a following, sustain a profit, or pay back their investors. Two
high-profile Net entertainment start-ups, DEN and Pixelon, are both
mired in scandal and headed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream attention To be sure, Hollywood executives are
watching the adult world, but they're doing it quietly. ``It's not
like they have big board meetings and trot out the porn and say,
`Get me some of that,' `` says Mark Hardie, a former analyst with
Forrester Research. ``But they are looking at areas where money is
being made and asking, `If they're making money, why can't we?' ``
That is, of course, the question of the moment on Wall Street and
Main Street alike. But even the porn sites are seeing a drop in
profits these days, in part because the credit card companies are
putting the squeeze on shady operators, instituting higher fees and
penalties for merchant accounts.
</P>
<P>
   American Express recently announced it was dropping all merchant
accounts for online porn sites. And the scams in the industry are
notorious. Some sites are rigged so that users trying to exit are
bombarded by page after page of smut; other sites offer ``free
trial'' periods and then bill customers before they can cancel.
Late last year, Seth Warshavsky, the Seattle wheeler-dealer
infamous for selling the Tommy Lee and Pamela Anderson Lee sex
video online, was accused by his employees of double-billing
thousands of customers. And in April, a scam artist duped Web users
out of thousands of dollars by using software that reset their
modems to dial the African nation of Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Some adult entertainment moguls turn a blind eye to such fraud,
but others in the business are trying to force the industry to
police itself. ``There is an attitude in the adult industry of
`Rah, rah, we're all in this together,' `` says Duvall of Jane's
Guide. ``But my big thing is that people should know what they're
getting and they shouldn't get ripped off.'' Her site crusades
against scams and evaluates porn sites on such consumer issues as
customer service and user agreements.
</P>
<P>
