<HEADER>
A8132 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-PERFECT-WINE-HNS &LR;      06-08 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-WINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADVICE ON CHOOSING A WINE FOR ANY TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEBASTOPOL, Calif. _ How does a woman's love for a grilled
cheese sandwich with a glass of wine lead to the creation of an
unusual wine-food pairing system?
</P>
<P>
   For Barbara Hom, it was simple. As a single mother, she often
sat down to a meal of grilled cheese sandwiches, or maybe even a
bowl of ramen noodles. And she'd reach for a glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she began to refine a system she calls the ``flavor
spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things are never quite this easy. Hom, in fact, had a
solid resume and history of hard work to back up her theories about
food and wine pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the owner of an award-winning restaurant in Santa Rosa,
Calif., Hom began her culinary career working with her father, a
Chinese master chef who came to the United States in the 1940s.
From him, she learned the basics of Asian cuisine, which figure
strongly in her cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Though she got a college degree in mathematics, her first love
was cooking. She won a trip to Europe after she graduated from
college, fell in love with it and stayed two years by picking up
cooking jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to California, she opened a restaurant, Fans,
but decided to close the eatery a few years after she became a mom.
Before long, she was back at work, however, as chef/owner of Night
Owl Catering in Sebastopol and contracting her services out as chef
to Sonoma County wineries and wine groups.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ever accuse her of being a wine snob. In fact, her
philosophy might be summed up this way: Never apologize for your
taste in food or wine, because everybody's palate is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snobbery doesn't encourage people to drink wine,'' said Hom.
</P>
<P>
   At a March media seminar for Huntington Wines, a member of the
Wimbledon Wine Group, Hom paired the wines with some of her dishes,
such as Salmon in a Coriander and Lemongrass Crust or a tart Lemon
Custard ice cream, to show how food works in unexpected ways with
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Her flavor spectrum is basically a four-part approach.
</P>
<P>
   First, you can take the traditional approach, which she calls
``mirroring.'' Find a flavor in the food, such as duck with a black
cherry sauce, then match it to a wine with similar flavors, such as
a zinfandel.
</P>
<P>
   Second is the contrast approach. ``This takes the characteristic
of the wine and balances or complements it with the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a food is big and bold, everyone automatically thinks you
have to have a big, bold wine. But sometimes, something delicate
will work if there is a flavor contrast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth aspects to her flavor spectrum are where
she diverges from the traditional. These are the ``controversial
matches'' and ``outside-the-box'' pairings.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of controversy arose, for instance, when she was sitting
around with chef friends to plan a high-profile event. The dessert
was supposed to be chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found we had mixed opinions about what should be served
with chocolate and everyone felt very strongly about it. Then I
realized it just had to do with your individual palate. When I read
up on the subject, I found that people's body chemistry really does
make a difference in how they perceive tastes,'' said Hom.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking ``outside the box,'' the fourth aspect to her pairing
system, led to pairing the lemon ice cream with a Huntington
chardonnay, as an example. ``Everyone says wine can't go with ice
cream, but the Huntington had all this citrus in it _ and it just
worked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what I've done (with the flavor spectrum) is put into
words things we all have felt. If you go into a restaurant and
order wine, you don't want to be intimidated. So you might say
(about your wine choice), `I know (there) is a controversy on
this,' and go ahead and just order what you feel like ordering.''
</P>
<P>
   By presenting these and other seminars to the public and groups
of restaurant employees, Hom says she is hoping to bridge the gap
that sometimes develops between the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to say is that everyone has an opinion _ and
everyone's opinion has validity.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does she drink with that grilled cheese sandwich?
Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can take a thin wine, like some of the Napa
chards that are reaching for a rich, buttery taste but not quite
getting there, and find that the fat in the food actually helps the
wine taste better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recipes from Hom, developed for Mark West winery, are available
on the Web site www.markwestwinery.com, and click on ``cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Bonnie Walker by e-mail at bwalker1 &LR; express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
