<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHENTIC VOICES THAT SPEAK OF THE HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four or five times a year I get a packet in the mail. I know
immediately what's inside _ essays a reader wants to share with me.
</P>
<P>
   A mother has discovered a child is gay, or a wife is struggling
to comprehend her husband's sudden abandonment. A child has watched
an estranged parent die, or a woman is trying to come to terms with
her infertility. I read these stories, deeply moved by the effort
these women have made to understand the hand life has dealt them.
Having wrestled with questions of meaning and identity, they have
moved beyond depression, rage, and fear to gain valuable insights
into how to survive and thrive.
</P>
<P>
   I find that the literary quality is usually outstanding, the
content compelling and affecting. The accompanying letter usually
asks if I can suggest a way to get their work published, but
although such sharing was once an essential part of the
transmission of culture, I have to report that there is almost no
market for this kind of writing now.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of columnists in newspapers and magazines,
but with few exceptions, they write about contemporary events. They
analyze them and have lively and often controversial opinions about
them. On any given day, many write about the same subject _ Bush
vs. Gore, Columbine, or Elian _ helping us make sense of the
information flooding us, giving it context and spin. We give them
the power to tell the rest of us what's important in the external
world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what of the inner world? There's little mention of it in the
media until it reveals itself in acts of dishonesty, violence, or
madness, but in reality every current event reflects a myriad of
inner worlds. The actions of Bush and Gore are a result of
character and private intentions. Our fascination with Columbine
fixes on the motivation of children who kill. Our passionate
convictions about Elian stem from our feelings _ pro or con _ about
the nature of the father-son bond.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these seem vast unknowables. As a culture, we now disdain
``confessional'' writing and distrust the self-serving admissions
of politicians and celebrities. We swim in a glut of secondhand
theories and opinions while starving for trustworthy accounts of
real experience. Women no longer routinely confide in one another
while jointly tending children. Married couples rarely live near
parents to whom they can turn for seasoned advice. Most of us have
few close intergenerational contacts. Consciousness raising has
given way to less intimate book groups. And we're far too busy to
linger on the phone with a friend, go out for a heart-to-heart talk
with a colleague after a meeting, or study the inner workings of
any family but our own.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we still long for contact, connection, and communion.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Self-Disclosure: An Experimental Analysis of the
Transparent Self,'' Sidney Jourard states that writers who are
authentically self-revealing enrich other people's ability to live
in the world more fully. ``To learn of another's experiencing is to
broaden and deepen the dimensions of one's own experience,'' he
writes. ``The disclosed experience of the other person enables us
to see things, feel things, imagine things, hope for things that we
could never even have imagined before we were exposed to the
revelations of the discloser. . . . The vicarious experience (of
reading) can shape our essence, change us, just as firsthand
experience can. Experience seems to be as transfusable as blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of our grandparents had the certainties offered by
religion, but we are expected to create our own values. Where can
we find inspiration without voices that speak of the heart? How can
we understand extreme behavior unless we observe how ordinary
people falter under stress and then find the strength to go on? How
can we benefit from what others have learned? Why aren't we
surrounded in our daily life by writers willing to face the
complexity of their lives and thus help us to reflect more deeply
upon our own?
</P>
<P>
   This culture dizzies us with commercials and dazzles us with
entertainment. Somewhere, unacknowledged and unpublished, someone
is recording her own authentic experience, addressing herself to
people who wish to expand their lives by reflecting on the truth of
another's. It takes courage to reveal oneself in the face of
disdain and disparagement; it takes courage to be open to the views
of a person very different from oneself. But there are such writers
and such readers.
</P>
<P>
   I have been privileged to know both.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
