<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PYRAMID-SCHEME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAINE, CONSTERNATION OVER A PYRAMID SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Maine _ For the hundreds of Mainers who have made
thousands of dollars through what state officials consider a
high-priced pyramid scheme, the clock is ticking good and loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing Lives'' hit the Lewiston-Auburn area three weeks ago,
promising participants an ``unconditional gift'' of $14,000.
Participants say packets of cash have circulated among many of this
area's prominent residents _ including city officials and police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts say this chronically cashed-strapped region came to
life with the new windfall, with strangers bonding over ``the
game'' and restaurants filling up with newly-rich diners.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Attorney General Andrew Ketterer called an end to
the euphoria, giving players until June 14 to return the money or
risk prosecution. But to his surprise, this time the participants
aren't all listening.
</P>
<P>
   Several participants in Lewiston-Auburn have challenged
Ketterer's grasp of legal matters, arguing that Changing Lives is a
perpetual-motion ``game,'' not a pyramid scheme. They say they
should not have to return winnings, which Ketterer says amount to
$100,000 in some cases. ``If we're just spreading wealth around our
community, I don't see what the problem is,'' said Laurie Appleton,
25, of Auburn, who said she was introduced to Changing Lives by a
friend who is a police officer in a nearby town. ``I'd like to see
anyone tell me that I'm going to be prosecuted for giving gifts to
people. I'm pretty sure that I didn't wake up in Russia this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the streets and storefronts of Auburn and Lewiston,
participants like Appleton were weighing their options, waiting to
see how serious Ketterer's threats would be. Many were scurrying to
collect and return money in exchange for receipts they could show
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the scheme is now too large for authorities to
prosecute everyone. It has moved beyond Maine and has planted deep
roots in other states, including New Hampshire and Massachusetts,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, `Look, they're just telling you that
because the government's not getting their share of the action.
They're mad,''' Ketterer said. ``It's bizarre, in that sense. It's
like a fire that you're not able to stomp out.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they could confirm that at least several
hundred Mainers participated in the scheme. Participants
interviewed put the figure much higher, at 2,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   There are internal investigations going on in both the Lewiston
and Auburn police department concerning the possible involvement of
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's experience has been duplicated in other states in recent
weeks, where unusually high-priced and resilient money-making
schemes have reminded authorities of the rise in such activities
during the late 1970s and early '80s. In Florida's Panhandle, it
was a very similar scheme called ``Gifts from the Heart,'' which
reportedly drew dozens of law enforcement officials and resulted in
charges against 19 people, including a former investigator from the
state Attorney General's office. In Texas, an arrangment called
``Women Helping Women'' promised participants as much as $40,000
for an initial pay-in of $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   A similar arrangement called ``Women Helping Women'' cropped up
in Maine's Washington County a few months ago, said Brian
MacMaster, chief investigator in Ketterer's office.
</P>
<P>
   In a packet of informational materials that has been distributed
among scores of area businessmen, Changing Lives is billed as a
``simple, natural activity that has changed many lives.'' New
recruits _ known as ``freshmen'' _ ship by overnight mail a $2,000
cash gift to a ``senior'' at the top of a four-level board. After a
senior has received eight gifts, he or she ``graduates'' from the
game with $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Participants are supplied with telephone introduction scripts.
One begins, ``Hi, Joe, (small talk if needed, but very short) I
have something I want to show you.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lewiston-Auburn, money began changing hands so quickly that
Mike Gilbert, a restaurant owner from South Paris, made $40,000 in
seven days. When he began to get dozens of friends and relatives
involved, ``it took off like wildfire'' and his home began to look
``like Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get a copy machine, a fax machine,'' he said. ``I
spent more money at Office Max.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettering says he has shut down many smaller pyramid schemes in
the past without much of a fight. Since he learned of Changing
Lives three weeks ago, Attorney General Ketterer's tactics have
become increasingly aggressive. Within his office, five
investigators are working on tracing the scheme _ more than he has
ever assigned to one investigation except for a police shooting,
Ketterer said. Once the grace period has expired, Ketterer has
promised to punish everyone involved with civil penalties of stiff
fines and restitution orders.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, 28, is among those who are hurrying to comply with the
attorney general's orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare waiting to happen,'' he said. ``It's like
playing musical chairs. You hope the music doesn't stop on you, but
sometimes it does.''
</P>
<P>
   The get-rich-quick schemes seem to be growing again now after a
dip during the early- to mid-1990s, said James Kohm, a lawyer with
the Federal Trade Commission, which oversees those pyramid schemes
that involve products.
</P>
<P>
   People persist in investing in pyramid schemes because they
can't grasp the vast human involvement that would be necessary to
sustain a scheme over the long-term, according to Kohm. In a scheme
with a ``matrix of three'' _ meaning each person involved is
required to recruit three more people _ taking the project to its
18th or 19th level would mean involving every inhabitant of the
United States and Canada, he said. ``Most of us don't realize how
incredibly powerful geometric multiplication is,'' Kohm said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous participants argued that Changing Lives was immune from
those warnings because past participants were likely to re-enroll
as freshmen after they had received their first $16,000. That feeds
more and more money into the system so that it could have gone on
on forever, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Appleton said the attorney general put a stop to the best thing
to hit the town in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were feeling positive,'' she said. ``It's hard to
explain. People were being good to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the coffee shops and storefronts of Auburn Wednesday,
there were also those whose suspicions had kept them from getting
involved, and they watched the chaos from a philosophical distance.
Harlan Emory, a contractor from Lisbon, said three people had
approached him with offers to get involved in Changing Lives. Three
times, he refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the type of deal where if it's too good a deal it can't
be true,'' he said. ``They run a quick bit by me, I said no, and
away I ran.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
