<SLUG> BC-TECH-TRAVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE MOUSE, WILL TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes sidebar: Tech-Travel-Sites)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snap on your Speedos. Get ready to surf!
</P>
<P>
   The online travel industry welcomes you with an ocean of summer
perks that include bargains on last-minute travel, discounts on
family vacations, and free flight information sent to your
hand-held Palm computers.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? Although most Web travel sites have made advances,
they have a long way to go. Many still aren't delivering on
promises to provide the fastest service, lowest prices, and best
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The worst performers were the big hotel chains and car rental
firms. If you're in a rush, consider bypassing them. Try booking
rooms and cars through online travel agencies like Travelocity.com
and Expedia.com _ two comprehensive sites that allow customers to
compare prices on large numbers of hotels and car-rental companies.
</P>
<P>
   Travel shoppers will find abundant bargains as travel sites
fight for dominance. Last month, customers of Expedia.com could buy
a US Airways ticket and get 50 percent off their next ticket with
the same airline. Budget.com has been promoting a $19.99-a-day rate
on a Ford Ranger pick-up truck.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain hunters also should check out Hoteldiscounts.com, which
promises the lowest prices. Extra enticements at this site include
last-minute bargains on hotel rooms, such as the Doubletree in
Orlando, Fla., for $70 a night.
</P>
<P>
   For new online travel shoppers, Expedia.com is a good starting
place. Its site has dedicated areas for family, cruise, and
adventure vacations. It also offers multiple tools for finding the
lowest air fares. It matches airlines' lowest rates and e-mails
alerts on air fare deals. Like Priceline.com, Expedia.com allows
customers to name their own fare and see if an airline will match
it.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently Expedia.com had offered weaker tools for hotel
shopping, but the company recently revamped its lodging section.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Expedia.com's chief competitor _ Travelocity.com _ may be
a better bet for some shoppers looking for lodging. Travelocity.com
offers reviews from travelers as well as message boards where
tourists can rant and rave.
</P>
<P>
   For seaside cottages and other off-the-beaten track lodgings,
try clicking on Placestostay.com or bedandbreakfast.com. Here's a
friendly warning: Do your homework. Placestostay.com offers
customers reviews, but we were suspicious after finding only raves.
</P>
<P>
   After perusing the Web sites of chain hotels, we decided not to
rate them. It was too hard to find summer vacancies, and virtual
travel sites did a better job of steering customers to available
hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In your online travels, do not anticipate the same customer
service you received during the Internet holiday shopping season.
Expect much worse. In cyberspace, the travel industry is about two
years behind online retailers such as Amazon.com Inc., eToys Inc.,
and Jcrew.com.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile rental sites, for instance, are making the buying
process long and painful. At Budget's site, several attempts to
place an order resulted in errors. When we called the company's
toll-free number for help, a customer service representative blamed
the problems on us.
</P>
<P>
   Travel sites want your money, but they don't necessarily want to
hear from you. Only a handful of travel sites bothered to respond
to e-mail messages. Toll-free telephone numbers were often hidden
inside Web pages and, in some cases, were not listed.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few bright spots. Hertz was the only automobile
rental center to respond intelligently to an e-mailed request for
information, and United Airlines the only airline to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Customer representatives at Hoteldiscounts.com and
Vacationspot.com took extra time to type out personalized
responses. Expedia.com responded in a day but told us to call an
airline for information about a flight.
</P>
<P>
   Finding help at Travelocity.com, however, took some time because
the site's e-mail customer service box was buried at the bottom of
a Web page. Somehow, we managed to click on a promotion to Radisson
and ended up with the hotel's customer service staff.
</P>
<P>
   Several airlines, as well as online travel agency Uniglobe.com,
responded with preformulated e-mail responses _ a tactic used to
save labor costs. These canned answers don't count, especially when
they have nothing to do with the questions.
</P>
<P>
   One site, Budget, yanked an e-mail box from its Web pages
because too many people sent messages. The company made the
decision after its customer service people got swamped with
requests for information, a Budget spokeswoman explained.
</P>
<P>
   On the other extreme is Travelocity.com, which demands that
customers send e-mail rather than pick up the phone. The site
intentionally did not list a toll-free number because it doesn't
want calls from the masses (yes, that includes you). It considers
its phone number to be a customer perquisite, not a prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, we make it more available to people who
make bookings,'' said Terry Jones, chief executive of
Travelocity.com.
</P>
<P>
   What you find off-line is often what you'll get online. We
called US Airways to ask whether a meal was served on a flight, and
a representative didn't know the answer. When we asked again, she
huffed, ``I'll have to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Travelocity.com takes the prize for the longest hold
times. Hoteldiscounts.com had the most complex voice-mail system.
``Press 1 if you blah blah, Press 2 if you want to do this . . .
Hey, we're sending you back to the beginning again! Press 1 if you
blah blah.''
</P>
<P>
   Hint: Press as many buttons as you can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
