<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-RUGGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO ABUSE THE PC? THINK `RUGGEDIZED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer's approaching, and the time is right to head for the
hills. And for some people that means the most distant hills they
can think of. These adventurous types go mountaineering in the
Canadian Rockies or ride a train across Siberia, in their quest to
get away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are still phone messages to be checked and e-mail
to be read. And why shouldn't a fellow be able to do that sort of
thing when he's halfway across the Atlantic in a sailboat, or
halfway up Mount Kilimanjaro?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he can. Some hard-core adventurers carry computers that
are even tougher than they are, and communications gear that puts
them within reach of any phone on earth, no matter where on earth
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping in touch is the most important thing, and the most
difficult. Cell phones are handy and relatively cheap. Too bad they
tend not to work in the planet's more remote locations.
</P>
<P>
   This problem was to have been solved by Iridium, a global
telephone system bound together by a network of 66 low-orbiting
space satellites. Anyone armed with a heavy, clunky Iridium phone
could make phone calls from virtually anywhere on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Just the thing for ``the Rambo of the seas.'' That's what they
call French explorer Philippe Monnet. He has sailed around the
world alone, and he holds the speed records for sailing alone from
New York to San Francisco and from Hong Kong to London. Monnet's
not bad on land, either; he won the notorious Paris-to-Dakar
automobile race and the Paris-to-Cape Town rally, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Monnet took along an Iridium phone when he set sail from France
in January for another round-the-world voyage. The phone worked
well enough to deliver some awful news. ``When I was in the South
Pacific,'' Monnet says, ``Iridium called me to tell me Iridium had
failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iridium consortium had gone broke _ there just weren't
enough world explorers out there to make a go of the business. The
company phoned Monnet to tell him that his phone would soon be good
for nothing but ballast.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Rambo brought along backup. Along with the Iridium
handset, he carried a laptop-size device that lets him use an
entirely different satellite telephone system called Inmarsat.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1979, Inmarsat is accessible from about 98 percent of
the planet's surface, petering out only when you're near the poles.
Monnet was out of touch for a while as he sailed past Antarctica,
but once he headed north, the intrepid explorer was back on the
air, happily accepting phone calls from nosy Boston journalists.
</P>
<P>
   An Inmarsat phone isn't cheap. The least powerful laptop-size
version costs $2,500; a suitcase-size heavy-duty model, capable of
transmitting digital data at 64,000 bits per second, costs $10,000.
But then, data transmission is Inmarsat's chief business. Its
leading customers are corporations that need to relay data from
remote locations. That includes audio and video files. Many foreign
television correspondents digitally compress their videotapes and
beam them to the news desk over an Inmarsat phone at $7 a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, TV networks can afford it. And they can also afford
to provide another vital tool _ a portable computer for digitizing
and compressing video data. Indeed, in our Internet-happy world, a
computer is vital for any world traveler who wants to stay in
touch. But you don't want just any laptop.
</P>
<P>
   When the nearest repair shop is hundreds of miles away, you had
better pack something that will keep working, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   One popular choice is the Panasonic Toughbook, a line of
``ruggedized'' portable computers designed to take severe abuse.
Instead of plastic, a Toughbook's case is made out of magnesium
alloy, and most of them have keyboards and data ports that are
shielded against dust and moisture. An ultralight version costs
about $3,500; a hefty briefcase-size version goes for about $5,700.
</P>
<P>
   John Harris, vice president of marketing for Panasonic Personal
Computer Co., says his company doesn't go out of its way to market
Toughbooks to adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary business is a business-to-business model,'' Harris
says. ``We do almost no consumer or one-to-one sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most Toughbooks are used by road warriors, traveling
techs who need a machine that takes a pounding. They're also
popular with police forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one that actually took a bullet,'' Harris says. ``Half
the LCD (display screen) still worked perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, adventurous folk have heard of the Toughbook and seek
them out. When Seattle-based Alpine Ascents International mounted
an expedition to Mount Everest this year, it took along a
Toughbook, as well as an Inmarsat telephone.
</P>
<P>
   But Toughbook gets some tough competition in the hard-core
computing market, from a Fremont, Calif., company that most people
have never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   If you're familiar with Dolch Computer Systems Inc., you've
probably spent too much time flying the Space Shuttle, or driving
an armored personnel carrier, or exploring for oil in Siberia.
Those are the the sorts of environments in which Dolch products are
common. Or maybe you've been to a computer trade show and seen a
Dolch computer on display inside a sealed plastic box. The computer
sits there hour after hour, under a constant spray of water. With
its sealed data ports and monitor, and its rubber keyboard, a Dolch
computer just doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our notebooks have been on a dog sled mission to the North
Pole, where they used a solar cell to recharge the battery. We've
had several mountain-climbing expeditions,'' says Bob Pruitt,
Dolch's Northeast territory manager. But as with the Toughbooks,
most customers just want a super-reliable machine for use in
hostile conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people in the stone quarries in Vermont that use them
to control the crushing and grinding equipment,'' says Pruitt. ``We
put them on aircraft carriers. We put them in submarines.''
</P>
<P>
   For $5,000, you can get a Dolch NotePAC. That's pretty expensive
for a machine with an outdated Intel Pentium II processor and a
mere 64 megabytes of memory. On the other hand, you'll get a
machine sheathed in sexy-looking magnesium, a computer that will
run in a rainstorm and won't notice if you drop it three feet onto
a stone floor.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, it will survive your summer vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
