u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S WOES GO BEYOND LEGAL TRAVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a Microsoft Corp. shareholder to do now?
</P>
<P>
   That is no casual question in this town, where practically every
diversified money manager owns at least a small piece of the
Microsoft action. Boston's most interested party of all: Fidelity
Magellan manager Bob Stansky and his 42 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone from Stansky to the man on the street with just a few
shares in his portfolio will tell you this has been a nasty year.
Microsoft stock is down 39 percent so far in 2000 and the future
is, well, cloudy. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling Wednesday
was entirely expected bad news, but negative nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to blame all of Microsoft's stock weakness this year
and uncertain outlook on the company's travails in court. It would
also be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the government's case against Microsoft has depressed the
stock and has serious implications for the management of the
company's buisness. But even bigger corporate challenges are taking
a toll away from the headlines, and these issues, perhaps as much
as the antitrust case, will likely determine how the stock moves in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue is sheer corporate physics. On Microsoft's
gigantic scale, it is already difficult and eventually will become
impossible to maintain hyper percentage growth rates that commanded
lofty stock price-earnings ratios. While attention was focused on
court in the spring, Microsoft said it was falling short of sales
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``While people weren't watching, the growth was slowing on the
top (revenue) and bottom (profit) lines,'' said Brian Grove, a
technology portfolio manager at Vaughan, Nelson, Scarborough &AMP;
McCullough, an Nvest LP investment firm. ``Ultimatley that's going
to have more impact on the stock than the court will.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growth rate in the high teens or 20 percent is still doable
but, at least before the stock imploded, the market was (expecting)
30 and 40 percent growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the unstoppable evolution of technology which,
history proves, is extremely difficult to manage.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Microsoft was valued as a virtual monopoly by
Wall Street. But as electronic communications moves further away
from the computer desktop, where Microsoft does enjoy the spoils of
monopoly, the competitive action gets fierce and less profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The move toward wireless communications to access the Internet
has created a hotbed of new competition that cedes nothing to
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for Microsoft today is how they get anywhere
near the footprint they have on the PC in the wireless world,''
said Grove.
</P>
<P>
   As Internet traffic grows, computer servers become an important
growth area where Microsoft is a leader but only in a tight and
crowded race. Throw in new Internet applications services and
software, where Microsoft is turning in mixed results, and you've
got a much more competitive world to manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's success and its ability to remain a dominant
company over the next three years is more dependant on its ability
to execute in all these new areas,'' said Tony Ursillo, a software
analyst at Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``It's less dependant on
what structure the company takes and what sort of constraints may
be put on its conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't start a collection for Bill Gates just yet.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Microsoft's operating system business may not
generate whopping percentage growth but its still one of the
world's biggest cash machines running 95 percent of all personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the company's best weapons: Microsoft worked hard to
hire the smartest people available long after it had buried the
competition and could be justified in coasting a bit. In short,
Microsoft has brains to burn and its not just sitting around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a big head start because they have a lot of smart
people, a lot of money and a great understanding of technology,''
said Ursillo.
</P>
<P>
   We know Microsoft will fight for every market from the set-top
TV box, to the wireless Internet connection, to Web browers. It may
find a new way to thrive, or slide to mere mortal stature.
</P>
<P>
   For now, all attention is focused on the Appeals Court, as
Microsoft begins the legal battle to overturn Jackson's order to
break up the company. But the future for Microsoft and its
shareholders won't be decided in a court alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
