<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANALYSIS-BO     06-08 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOFTWARE GIANT IN A TECHNOLOGICAL LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For an attorney whose client had just received the corporate
equivalent of the death penalty, Bill Neukom sounded remarkably
upbeat Wednesday. Microsoft Corp.'s executive vice president for
law and corporate affairs left the impression that he can hardly
wait to get in front of an appeals court and start shredding the
antitrust judgment against his company.
</P>
<P>
   Newsanalysis
</P>
<P>
   ``Today begins a new chapter in this case,'' said Neukom. ``It
is a chapter Microsoft looks forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals process certainly can't get any worse for Microsoft.
In a terse ruling laced with hostility, federal Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson ordered that the company be carved into two
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom responded in kind, describing the proceedings in
Jackson's courtroom as ``flawed from the beginning,'' and declaring
that the court's findings of fact were riddled with errors and
contradictions. Neukom added that Jackson ``misapplied the
pertinent law'' when he decided that Microsoft violated the Sherman
Antitrust Act. In all, Neukom sounded like a man certain of
ultimate victory.
</P>
<P>
   But as the case wends its way through the appeals courts,
Microsoft finds itself in legal and technological limbo. Many
customers will remain loyal, if only because switching to other
products is so costly and difficult. But the lingering threat of
corporate demolition could undermine Microsoft's plans for a new
generation of Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft does have some cards to play in the appeals process.
If the normal procedures are followed, the case goes next to the US
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. That court has
already held that Microsoft was legally entitled to add its
Internet Explorer browser to the Windows operating system. That
ruling directly contradicts one of Jackson's key findings, and if
the appeals court reaffirms it, much of the government's
anti-Microsoft case collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, while the threat of a breakup has hammered Microsoft's
stock price in recent months, it's done no harm to the company's
sales, which hit $5.65 billion last quarter, up a billion from the
same period last year. Industry-watchers don't see any short-term
moves to abandon the company, as there are few inexpensive
alternatives to Microsoft products, and most consumers don't seem
interested in seeking them out anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this is what the US Justice Department had in mind
when it requested that Microsoft be divided into a company that
makes the Windows operating system and another firm that handles
all other Microsoft activities. Buyers of Windows will still be
able to obtain the same operating system software available now;
the same applies to buyers of Microsoft's office software suite.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust regulators hope that this kind of breakup will
minimize any disruption that a split might cause consumers. But it
also makes it easier for Microsoft to hold onto those customers
through the appeals process. And even if the breakup does take
place, many suspect that consumers would just keep buying their
favorite Microsoft products from the separate companies and give
little support to any new competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ePresence Inc. of Westborough, Mass. has a worldwide partnership
with Microsoft to deploy the company's software in corporate
networks. Scott Silk, senior vice president of marketing and
business development at ePresence, says his firm's clients aren't
holding off on Windows deployments for fear of a Microsoft breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the customers I've spoken to it's almost been more of a
human interest story than a business story,'' said Silk. ``The
customers haven't been saying, `We'd better re-evaluate our whole
strategy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And what if Microsoft is split into two parts? ``They're both
very strong businesses,'' said Silk, ``and Microsoft has a dominant
position in both of those businesses.'' So corporate buyers would
just stick with software from the two Microsofts.
</P>
<P>
   To Jonathan Zuck, the world looks very different. Zuck leads the
Association for Competitive Technology, which represents small- to
medium-sized companies that write software for businesses that use
Microsoft operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Zuck says, members of his organization report that
customers are hesitating to place new orders, because of
uncertainty over Microsoft's future. ``There's a panic in the
industry surrounding this,'' said Zuck, who says 700 software
developers have joined his group in the past week to express their
opposition to a Microsoft breakup.
</P>
<P>
   But a loss of influence for Microsoft doesn't fill Ken Wasch
with panic. ``Consumers win,'' said Wasch, president of the
Software and Information Industry Association, a group that
supports the government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   Wasch believes his members and other companies will respond to a
Microsoft breakup with a torrent of innovative new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dead zone of major software applications is about to show
some life,'' said Wasch. ``Suddenly, in word processors,
spreadsheets, databases, presentation graphics, there will be
competition in them, and that can only be good for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely, said Dan Kusnetzky, a software-industry analyst with
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are driven by the applications they know how to
use, the applications their company is using, the applications
their friends are using,'' said Kusnetzky. ``The people who want to
continue to use software that's compatible with what other people
are using will keep buying Microsoft Office products.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusnetzky doubts that corporate software buying patterns will
shift radically, even if the Microsoft breakup finally goes
through. ``Will people go out tomorrow and buy Corel Office?'' he
wondered. ``I'm not sure if people even know what Corel Office
is.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Microsoft's existing customer base does remain
loyal, the case poses a serious threat to its future prospects.
Microsoft has already had to postpone the announcement of its
vaunted Next-Generation Windows Services. This project is designed
to create new versions of Windows software that work seamlessly
with the Internet and hand-held computers. It's a classic example
of Microsoft's favorite tactic _ the blending of more and more
functions into its operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the breakup order, the court set limits on the
company's ability to integrate new features into its products.
Microsoft's future may depend on Neukom's success in overturning
the entire judgment against Microsoft _ not just the breakup order.
</P>
</TEXT>
