<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LOLA-GLAUDINI-HNS &LR;      06-08 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOLA-GLAUDINI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ACTRESS LENDS DEPTH, INTELLIGENCE TO `GROOVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAIG MARINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Writer and director Greg Harrison makes an
ambitious stab at exploring San Francisco's rave subculture in his
new film, ``Groove.'' Yet most moviegoers will walk away from the
film remembering actress Lola Glaudini.
</P>
<P>
   Either Harrison saved all of his best lines for Glaudini's
character, ``Leyla'' (a transplanted New Yorker whose dreams of
continuing her education seem to have once again dissolved into the
nightlife) or Glaudini is the one actor in the film capable of
lending her character any real depth.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that most of Harrison's script barely takes his
characters below surface level, let's go with the second option:
Glaudini is easily the most skilled performer in the movie,
although naturally, she wouldn't dare say so herself.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a vacant bar in the lobby of the Nikko Hotel, it's
fairly easy to tell that while Glaudini has been earning a living
for years as an actress, this is clearly her first starring role.
For one thing, she listens to questions. For another, she answers
with refreshing honesty. What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable thing about Glaudini in ``Groove'' is that
she is not only strikingly beautiful, but there is an intelligence
in her eyes that makes her character seem brighter and wiser than
the other denizens of the night. In fact, this trait has actually
cost the 28-year-old actress some work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't call yourself intelligent without sounding totally
pompous,'' Glaudini says with an easy chuckle, her New York
background evident in her voice. ``But I have tried out for roles
and had people say `That girl is just too smart.' Most of the time,
it turns out they just wanted nothing more than a breathing prop,
some girl to stand there and hold the arm of a guy. I like to try
to bring a little bit more to my roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaudini made such an impression during two smaller parts on
``NYPD Blue'' that producer Steven Bochco created the role of
administrative assistant Dolores Mayo just for her. She just
finished making another movie, ``Blow,'' with Johnny Depp. So far,
she has been able to hang onto a certain amount of creative control
over the types of women she portrays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough people out there who can play the vapid and
ditzy parts,'' she says. ``I've been lucky enough with the people
I've worked with that they allow me to have some kind of real input
into how my character might move, or the things she would or
wouldn't say.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Glaudini mentions a scene in ``Groove'' where
Leyla is being complimented by David (Hamish Linklater), her
overeducated alter ego who is at his first rave and on his first
Ecstasy trip to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scene in the bathroom, he calls Leyla beautiful, and
she looks at him and tells him `You're high.' That way, she can be
a bit dismissive of him, but still accept his compliment,''
Glaudini explains. ``It wouldn't be realistic if she tried to deny
it somehow. Her beauty is one of the few things she can be
confident about without being arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may be self-conscious about her lack of formal education,
but she knows she's attractive,'' she concludes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Glaudini grew up around the stage, the daughter of playwright
Robert Glaudini. She began her acting career as a child in the
Padua Hills Playwrights Festival, with Ed Harris and Sam Shepard
among its members. It's a craft she takes seriously, to the point
of creating her own private histories for the people she portrays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the `I was born in the hills of Mississippi'
type of thing,'' she laughs. ``But I try to imagine them as
three-dimensional, with a past that has shaped them, something that
will explain why they may do what they do. I find it helps me bring
the characters alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Her formal training as a ballerina has also helped Glaudini, who
says that one of the things she thinks about most in a character is
``physicality, the way they would move, or hold a glass, even.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps her explain how she is able to convey some of the
complexities of her ``Groove'' character, appearing both powerful
and vulnerable alternately.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would walk through a room as Leyla, I would make myself
larger, kind of `peacock' myself,'' she explains. ``But in the
moments when she is with David, and she is more embarrassed by her
incomplete education, I would turn my shoulders in, make myself
more concave. It's something I think about a lot, actually. It's
amazing how much you can say without saying a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaudini says she will continue to choose her roles carefully
for as long as she can, though working in independent films like
``Groove'' does have certain drawbacks. ``I figured out that when
it was all said and done, I made about four dollars a day,'' she
says, laughing and shaking her head. ``I'm going to have to do a
little better than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
