<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8166 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-08 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BEST WORKERS WILL ACT LIKE OWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All it takes sometimes is a trip to the airport
to remind you that one employee can make a huge difference, and
that a smart company knows how to make that employee look good.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with a little everyday horror, the kind that would
make Stephen King yawn. It's not an absolute terror, but one of
nature's gentle reminders that even vacations are never flawless.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Cathy, and I had called the previous night to arrange
for a taxi to pick us up at 9:30 a.m. for the trip to San Francisco
International Airport. When it was 9:35 and no cab had shown up, we
called the taxi company to make sure the morning crew had gotten
the message. Just a few minutes, the dispatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, still no cab. I called the dispatcher
again. The driver's already made the pickup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   When I gently pointed out that the ones being picked up had not
been, uh, picked up, he checked further. It turns out the driver
had picked up someone else from a different address on my street;
he hadn't bothered to make sure he had the right people.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher promised another cab right away. Five minutes
later, with nothing in sight, we asked a friend to bail us out. As
she was about to do it, the cab finally appeared.
</P>
<P>
   We still had enough time to make the flight, as long as our
airline behaved reasonably, which sometimes can be an unreasonable
expectation. In this case, though, the airline didn't behave
reasonably; it behaved spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   We checked our luggage at the curb, where there was virtually no
line. But, of course, there still might be a line when we checked
ourselves in at the gate, as we've always had to do with other
airlines. The threat of more stress awaited us.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing: This airline, unlike others we've flown,
allows a complete curb-side check-in. The skycap took care of the
luggage, asked us the usual questions and gave us boarding passes.
The whole thing took two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After all that, we were early.
</P>
<P>
   Pop quiz: Which of the two companies will get our repeat
business, and which one has lost us as customers for life? Do you
think we'll tell our friends about both companies?
</P>
<P>
   The best employees think like owners, the best owners think like
employees, and the best companies think like customers. The airline
understood that; the taxi company didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The taxi company is in a competitive business, one that makes it
easy for customers to switch to a competitor if there are problems.
The errant taxi driver made a dumb mistake by going to the wrong
address, but we all make dumb mistakes from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   If the dispatcher had thought like an owner, though, he would
have tried to make things right. Being half an hour late for a
time-sensitive appointment is a lousy way to do business. He could
have told the second driver not to charge us for the ride, or sent
a gift certificate or letter of apology, but he did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Smart restaurant workers know how to make saves, such as giving
customers a free glass of wine when a reserved table isn't ready at
the time promised. That glass of wine is a small gesture, but it
can make the difference between appearing sensitive or appearing
callous, and between keeping or losing customers.
</P>
<P>
   If you consider yourself a good employee and you see that your
company is about to lose a customer, do whatever you can to fix it,
even if it's not technically your job. If your corporate culture
frowns upon that, think seriously about whether you're working for
the right company.
</P>
<P>
   Also look at whether the company does whatever it can to make
things easier for everyone involved. By allowing people to check in
completely at the curb, the airline cut down on the redundancy for
both employees and customers. It's a simple, stress-reducing step,
but a lot of airlines don't take it.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what industry you are in, if your company doesn't seem
to be in the hurdle-removing business, your career may be in for a
bumpy ride.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
