<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-800&AMP;ADD-     06-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-800&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMACY AND POLITICS AT MEMORIAL SERVICE FOR FORMER PRIME
MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's late prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, was
remembered Thursday in a solemn state service marked by effusive
eulogies, cannonades, a parading honor guard in crisp white
uniforms and thousands of mourners in dark suits, including
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The service for Obuchi, who died on May 14, six weeks after
suffering a massive stroke, began under a hot and brilliant sky
with a long, slow procession into a large hall. The service was
held by Obuchi's widow, Chizuko, and his 28-year-old son, Takeshi,
who bore a white box containing his father's ashes.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the solemnity of the occasion, what took place
offstage, before and after the ceremony, was a burst of political
activity and diplomacy of great significance for Japan's immediate
future and for the future of East Asia, which often seemed to
eclipse the memorial event.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Japan's imperial family and dignitaries from 170
countries gathered for the occasion in the hall, where a huge
portrait of the late prime minister hung against an illuminated,
powder blue background. Obuchi's successor, Yoshiro Mori,
remembered his friend and political ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am anguished to think how deeply disappointed Mr. Obuchi
must have been to have had to retire from the arena of action,
felled by an unforeseen illness,'' Mori told the other mourners.
``In this moment of bereavement, I can do no more than express my
heartfelt gratitude to former Prime Minister Obuchi for dedicating
his all to this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mori also had a setting in which he could finally enjoy the
statesman's attributes of his office.
</P>
<P>
   And with critical national elections scheduled for June 25, his
power huddles with Clinton, the South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
and other senior leaders from China and Russia provided a welcome
relief from the cycle of provocative blunders and tortured, partial
retractions that have cut deeply into Mori's popularity ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Eager for a boost from the events surrounding the memorial
service, Mori's aides have made much of the bilateral meetings with
Clinton; Kim; the leaders of Australia, Indonesia and Thailand; and
high-ranking officials from many other countries.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Japanese leader and his foreign minister, Yohei
Kono, held bilateral talks with 33 countries over the last two
days.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Following meetings with Mori and Kim, aides to Clinton praised
the South Korean government for taking the initiative in engaging
its northern neighbor, and hinted strongly at a relaxation of U.S.
economic sanctions against North Korea, many of which have been in
place since the Korean War, which ended in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a process in place to work through issues related to
that, and I would expect we would have an announcement on that very
soon,'' said a White House spokesman, P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean leader is due to travel to the North Korean
capital, Pyongyang, on Monday, for the first-ever summit meeting
between leaders of those two countries.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kim told Mori that he would urge his North Korean counterpart to
improve relations with Japan. North Korea fired a ballistic missile
over Japan without warning in 1998, shocking the Japanese and
causing a break in relations with Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had often expressed frustration with
Obuchi and his government over the slow pace of reform to lift
Japan out of its decade-long economic slump. In death, however, the
soft-spoken, consensus-minded Obuchi was praised by Clinton, who
said that history would regard him as someone who ``rose to the
challenge with courage and confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said that Clinton's decision to attend
Thursday's service, flying 26 hours for an eight-hour-stay, and his
strong praise for Obuchi should be seen in the context of the
``unusually strong alliance'' that links the two countries, and
Japan's steady support for the priorities of U.S. foreign policy
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Coming little more than three weeks after Obuchi's cremation,
the date of Thursday's memorial service was itself mired in
politics. The Japanese media widely reported that the service was
held as close as decently possible to the upcoming elections in
order to guarantee a large ``sympathy vote'' and give maximal lift
at the polls to the long-governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Since the date was announced, a string of unusually blunt
nationalist statements by Mori, whose recent description of Japan
as a ``divine country with an emperor at its center'' was strongly
evocative of this country's imperialist prewar propaganda, has
caused support for the government to evaporate in the polls. The
election now stands to become a referendum on Mori rather than a
commemoration of Obuchi.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Political analysts in Tokyo have described the stakes in the
election as extremely high. If the Liberal Democratic Party loses a
significant number of parliamentary seats, Mori would likely be
forced to resign. An even worse debacle for his party, as a 12
percent popularity rating in one recent newspaper poll suggests,
could force the Liberal Democratic Party from power for only the
second time since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's tenure in office has been unusually troubled from the
start. Opposition political leaders and editorial writers have
poked holes into the sometimes contradictory official explanations
of how power was secretively passed from Obuchi following his
sudden hospitalization on April 2 to a brief caretaker prime
minister and finally to Mori.
</P>
<P>
   An account by Obuchi's widow of her husband's last hours of
consciousness was published Thursday in a popular magazine.
Obuchi's claim that her husband spoke to her long after his stroke
_ contrary to doctors' reports _ bolstered the position of Mikio
Aoki, who had been the caretaker leader and said that he had been
asked to exercise power by the dying leader.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of Tokyo Thursday, the kind words often
spoken about Obuchi rarely reflected on Mori, whom voters seemed to
regard with all the suspicion suggested by his historically low
ratings in the opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about Obuchi's political abilities, but he seemed
to have a nice personality,'' said Hiroshi Ogawa, a 60-year-old man
who was in the Toronomon section of central Tokyo. ``Mori, though,
is just out of the question. I've never heard of a prime minister
who has made such a bad impression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1457EDT &QL; 
