<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-STEVE-YOUNG-HNS &LR;      06-08 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEVE-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     END MAY BE NEAR FOR NINERS QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Steve Young's fateful Friday deadline to
bring to a close his protracted career decision may slop over to
Monday with the expected announcement that he plans to retire from
football.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the San Francisco 49ers say the 38-year-old
quarterback and expectant father wants time to gather ``his
people'' together for his retirement announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Mariucci on Wednesday offered what might have been a
clue as to what Young, the 49ers quarterback and a 14-year veteran
of the team, is thinking as he comes to the most important decision
of his athletic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to start talking about Steve all over, but yesterday after
the press conference what I found interesting was he stayed around
for a long time,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said the quarterback visited him, general manager Bill
Walsh and other coaches. ``He didn't want to leave. You know he
loves it here,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a man trying to say goodbye without actually saying
the words.
</P>
<P>
   What seems certain in the continuing drama that is Young is the
player's desire to be captain of his own ship and make his own
decision instead of having it made for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve will let you know,'' Mariucci said. ``There's
speculation, a gut feeling. I don't really know anything for sure.
We owe it to Steve to let him make the call when he feels good and
ready. He's going to handle it beautifully and with class. He'll do
the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci also put Young's Monday breakfast meeting in Denver
with Broncos coach Mike Shanahan in proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, players don't get involved in negotiating with
coaches,'' the coach said. ``Those are two people who don't get
involved in negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Greg Clark, one of Young's friends on the team, said
the recently married quarterback faces ``a big life change. People
say do this, do that, but it's more difficult than that. It takes a
lot of thought. You want to make sure you're thorough. It's a lot
more difficult decision to do than people think.''
</P>
<P>
   While Young may be departing, Clark is not going anywhere for
the next three years, unless, of course, he becomes a salary cap
victim for his 2001 base salary of $1,475,000 or his 2002 figure of
$1,950,000. Clark's deal is worth $6.7 million over three years,
including a signing bonus of $2.147 million to go with a 2000 base
salary of $385,000.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Clark can earn $500,000 in each of the next three
seasons if he plays in 75 percent of the team's offensive plays or
80 percent of the tight end plays. He can also earn $400,000 a year
in other incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we did the play-time incentives because I have
missed some time,'' said Clark, who was not able to play in four
games last year because of injuries. ``That bridges the gap. . . .
It's really an awesome thing when you get to this point of your
career, after the restrictive years and into the free agent years.
That's where most of the money is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-BELMONT-STAKES-HN     06-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-STAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIVE FRESH FACES IN LINE FOR BLEMONT STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, N.Y. _ For the first time in 30 years there will be no
Kentucky Derby or Preakness winner, but Wednesday's draw brought a
competitive field of 11 3-year-olds to the fore for the 132nd
Belmont Stakes, five of them newcomers to this Triple Crown series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division is wide open,'' said trainer Todd Pletcher, whose
Impeachment is the only horse who will have raced in all three
legs. ``There are some fresh horses running, and we've had two hard
races in a row. But the way he runs from way out of it doesn't take
as much out of him as some of the others who are close to the
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment ran third in both the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness, and could match Mane Minister's 1991 record of finishing
third in all three races unless he can overcome 8-5 favorite
Aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pan winner Postponed figures to be the strongest of the
five newcomers for Saturday's $1-million Belmont. He is trained by
Scotty Schulhofer, the defending Belmont champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postponed has really gotten better,'' Schulhofer said. He
acknowledged that the colt isn't as physically imposing as last
year's long-shot winner Lemon Drop Kid or his 1991 Belmont champ
Colonial Affair, ``but he's more versatile, and he's got the
pedigree for a mile-and-a-half.''
</P>
<P>
   Postponed was a distant sixth behind Fusaichi Pegasus in the
Wood Memorial, but Schulhofer changed riders from Jose Santos to
Edgar Prado, and the colt has put in two strong races back-to-back
coming into the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners thought we needed to make a change,'' Schulhofer
said. ``We tried to find a good rider here who we thought would fit
the horse. So far, Edgar's done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded, who closed well for second in the Peter Pan, was made
the 5-1 co-third choice in the field for his Triple Crown debut.
His owner, James Tafelhad, forked over a $100,000 supplemental
entry fee because Unshaded was not nominated to the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for us was the work the other day (at Churchill
Downs),'' trainer Carl Nafzger said. ``We believe he can get the
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tahkodha Hills, another newcomer, was dismissed at odds of 30-1
by veteran linemaker Don LaPlace after finishing fourth behind
Postponed in the Peter Pan. He previously won the Lone Star Derby
and is eligible for a $1 million bonus if he wins the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Globalize was primed to run in the Kentucky Derby before a minor
injury changed the plans of trainer Jerry Hollendorfer. The
Lexington Stakes runner-up finished third in the Peter Pan.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Now is the surprising newcomer to this Triple Crown,
having won three races against New York-breds before a fifth-place
finish in the Wood Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, trained by a confident Bobby Frankel, drew post 5. He
was 1 1/2 lengths behind Pegasus in the Derby, but has won only
once in six career starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Belmont has always been the main goal with his pedigree,''
said Frankel, still looking for his first Triple Crown victory.
``That's why we skipped the Preakness. It doesn't make sense just
to try to get one more victory. This horse has tactical speed, and
he can run all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheelaway also bypassed the Preakness after an eventful fifth in
the Kentucky Derby, and trainer John Kimmel is hoping the strategy
will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having a fresh horse is a positive in this race,''
Kimmel said.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Hefner, one of the pace-makers in the Preakness before
fading to sixth, is expected to keep the pace honest in the
Belmont, as well. He is listed as a 50-1 long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Curule, who ran a creditable seventh in the Derby, also bypassed
the Preakness. He has been training at Belmont since the Derby and
worked an eye-popping :58 1/5 for five furlongs last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
