<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8266 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-OPERAHOUSE-TEXAS-TEX     06-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERAHOUSE-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE IN DOUBT FOR TOURIST ATTRACTION OPERA HOUSE IN TEXAS TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 26 seasons, busloads of tourists have flocked to the
Granbury Opera House to see its Broadway-style musicals and spend a
few bucks on the historic courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   But the Granbury landmark, which helped transform the town into
a tourist attraction, is now in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The opera house is about $60,000 in debt, and, unless grants or
corporate contributors are found, its future is tenuous, said Marty
Van Kleeck, the managing director of the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing that if we don't do something now, that in six
months we could be in deep trouble,'' Van Kleeck said. ``If one of
these shows doesn't do as well as we expect, then we could be right
on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Since a public appeal was made last week, some Granbury
businesses have offered support. But the Hood County seat, 45 miles
southwest of Fort Worth, doesn't have a base of major corporations
like larger cities. And the cost of operating the 1886 structure
keep mounting.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, stage lighting and wiring had to be replaced.
The theater still owes $28,000 on those bills and is also in the
midst of a campaign to replace its seats.
</P>
<P>
   The opera house changed course in 1995. That's when the board
pushed aside Jo Ann Miller, 71, a former Broadway performer who,
almost single-handedly, had brought the theater company to life.
Her longtime protege, Donna Norton, briefly held the reins before
Van Kleeck took over. There was an attempt to reach a younger
audience and do more than traditional summer-stock fare like
``Annie Get Your Gun'' and ``Mame.''
</P>
<P>
   Current and former board members say financial problems existed
long before Van Kleeck was hired.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller disputes that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Marty Van Kleeck has blown it and I think Donna Norton
has blown it,'' said Miller, who remains bitter five years after
being removed. ``The way it was, was a great raving success and now
it's down the tube.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater has a budget of roughly $750,000 _ $650,000 of that
from anticipated ticket sales. The opera house has only about 100
season ticket holders, making it difficult to plan ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after all these years it's been 15 years of slowly
going downhill,'' Van Kleeck said. ``I think some people locally
have taken the opera house for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The playhouse faces more competition for patrons and for grant
money than it did 20 years ago. Granbury Live stages musical revues
on another side of the square and many locals travel to Fort Worth
for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go from here to the Bass Hall (in Fort Worth) and pay
$50 when they could come here for $12,'' said Granbury Mayor David
Southern, an opera house season-ticket holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thought of by locals as being for tourists,'' Southern
said. ``I think people here go once a year and take their
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Granbury provides a portion of its 1-cent-bed tax to
the theater, which accounts for about $35,000 of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Southern said the city should buy and maintain the four
buildings the Opera House owns, then lease them back to the
nonprofit theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will have to explore the possibility of taking over
ownership of the building and incorporating into out tourist
operation much like Grapevine has done,'' Southern said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisa Johnson, the newly installed board president and
herself a city council member, said that ``would be a last resort''
because of the cost of maintenance. And she questioned if it was in
the theater's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
