<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8268 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-EXPERIENCE11-CO     06-08 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EXPERIENCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amis charts own route in memoir
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The many surprises in Martin Amis' ``Experience'' include his
discovery that he fathered a daughter during a long-ago affair, and
the eventual revelation of what befell a cousin who disappeared in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Amis' biggest jaw-droppers is his casual confession
that he's saved none of the letters from his novelist dad, Kingsley
Amis, nor those of his other intelligentsia friends and family. And
yet, this memoir by the author of ``London Fields'' and ``The
Information'' is crammed with his own college-age missives, even
though Amis himself derides their ``tally-ho facetiousness.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Experience'' is a very subjective
autobiography, one that combines self-mockery with considerable
self-absorption. If you're an Amis fan (father or son), you
probably won't mind. If you're not familiar with either of them,
you'll be lost in the book's vacillations between precise detail
and elusiveness. Even longtime readers will occasionally tire of
Amis' parodic use of footnotes; they litter and even swallow nearly
every page of the book _ academic arguments, amusing asides or
flat-out digressions about the writer's life.
</P>
<P>
   Near the start, Amis warns the reader he may indulge in
``certain bad habits,'' including name-dropping. But since he has
met so many interesting people _ including surrogate father figure
Saul Bellow and family friend and poet Philip Larkin _ that's a
prime selling point of the book. He was also a college-era
boyfriend of Tina Brown, former editor of Vanity Fair and The New
Yorker, and now of Talk, the magazine whose book branch is
publishing this memoir. Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   In his novel ``Time's Arrow,'' Amis wrote his hero's life story
in reverse order, from deathbed to birth. So it's no surprise that
he mucks about with chronology when writing about his own life.
``Experience'' drifts from one topic to the next, an artful method
that looks like stream-of-consciousness, but isn't. Interweaving
memories of his bohemian youth, his jovially prickly relationship
with Kingsley, and his own role as a father, Amis creates what
appears to be a comprehensive tapestry. But actually he avoids some
areas you'd like to hear more about.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he devotes whole chapters to excruciating, $30,000
reconstructive dental surgery (trigger for frenzied mockery by the
London media, which accused him of selling out after he brokered an
immense advance for ``The Information''). But Amis sidesteps
writing much at all about his first, failed marriage, or his
relationship with Isabel Fonseca, the woman he left his wife for,
and the dedicatee of his memoir.
</P>
<P>
   While Amis' trademark wit and elegant writing are always
compelling, it comes as a relief when he focuses, in the book's
final third, on his relationship with Kingsley as the older
writer's health starts to fail. It's here that the witty but often
chilly writer finds emotional grounding, as he observes his
hard-drinking, adulterous dad in decline, losing the very mind that
made him one of England's notable literary voices.
</P>
<P>
   Emotional resonance also comes from the figure who haunts the
book even more than Kingsley does: Martin's cousin Lucy Partington,
who failed to come home one late-December night in 1973, and seemed
to have vanished from the planet. She hadn't. But more than 20
years passed before her family learned she was among the many
victims of serial killer Frederick West.
</P>
<P>
   The long-delayed memorial service for Partington and the senior
Amis' funeral color the book's last pages. They're two examples of
what lends the book its title _ the kind of experience that Amis
calls ``that miserable enemy.'' Though his memoir avoids certain
areas of his life, by its end Amis has at least revealed some of
the real losses that fuel the smart/funny fury of his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MEMOIR
</P>
<P>
   Experience. By Martin Amis. Talk Miramax Books. $23.95. 406
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Self-mockery meets self-absorption.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray is a film critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS11-COX     06-08 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poetic in its power, `Jubilo' eloquently captures emotional
Confederate homecoming
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people would tell you that the unlikely story of Howard
Bahr begins in 1996 with the mail clerk at the Nautical and
Aviation Publishing Co. in Baltimore and a man named Jan
Snouck-Hurgronje, the son of a Dutch naval officer. But Bahr
himself would tell you it goes back further, back to one Frank
Smith, whom Bahr calls ``one of the best railroad men I ever knew
and a genuine intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on a night in 1971 that Smith, a brakeman for the
Illinois Central Railroad, put in Bahr's hands a copy of William
Faulkner's ``The Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahr was also working for the Illinois Central at the time and
living in Gulfport, Miss., a young man in his 20s who had gone to
the Navy straight from high school as an escape from a home life he
calls ``not a happy time.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Hamlet'' Bahr went to Faulkner's ``The Town,'' and
from that to another and another. In time he had read all of
Faulkner there was to read, and had decided he, too, would be a
writer. At age 27 he enrolled at the University of Mississippi,
where he would earn a bachelor's degree in English, then a master's
and then a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be years later _ nearly two decades _ before the
manuscript submitted by Howard Bahr, a professor of English at
Motlow State Community College in Tennessee, caught the eye of a
woman who opens the mail at Nautical and Aviation Press. So taken
was Rebecca Irish by Bahr's prose that she insisted that
Snouck-Hurgronje read it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of book you see once in a lifetime,''
Snouck-Hurgronje would soon be telling interviewers. His was a
company whose entire full-time staff was four people, with no
budget for marketing and no track record in publishing fiction. But
he promised Bahr he would nominate the novel for all the important
awards the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bahr was gratified just to be published.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no agent,'' he says today, ``so I couldn't get anybody
to read my manuscript. It's one of those things _ if you don't have
an agent, you can't get published; and if you've never been
published, you can't get an agent.'' But he had seen in a magazine
an ad pitched at writers like himself, without an agent, without an
entree to the New York publishing world.
</P>
<P>
   The book that the Nautical and Aviation Publishing Co. brought
out in 1997 was ``The Black Flower,'' a Civil War novel that
happened to see the light of day at the very time Charles Frazier's
``Cold Mountain,'' itself a Civil War novel, was becoming the
publishing story of the year as well as a National Book Award
winner.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``The Black Flower'' was little noticed. But it was
noticed just enough _ a starred review in Publishers Weekly, an
award from the American Academy of Arts and Letters citing its
``distinguished and exceptional prose'' _ that the snowflakes
slowly became a ball. By word of mouth, ``The Black Flower'' was
quietly becoming a book many had heard about but few had actually
seen. (First editions already have become collectibles, with prices
as high as $300.)
</P>
<P>
   It was about this time that Dawn Nicholson, a sales
representative for Henry Holt and Co., called her bosses in New
York. Nicholson had been traveling throughout the South, Holt
publicist Ida Veltri says, and everywhere she went, people were
talking about a book written by someone she'd never heard of,
published by a company she'd never heard of. Holt, she said, should
look into ``The Black Flower'' with an eye toward buying paperback
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Holt buy paperback rights _ reprinting it under the
company's Owl imprint _ but it also bought Bahr's second novel,
``The Year of Jubilo,'' released this month. After an initial run
of 50,000 copies, it already has gone into a second printing.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Black Flower,'' ``The Year of Jubilo'' is a Civil War
novel, set in 1865 as bedraggled Confederate soldiers go home to
towns in ruin, to fields wasted, to families they left behind. The
bare elements are those of a garden-variety historical romance, but
Bahr infuses this story with the pathos and tragedy of the war
itself. In the poetry of its prose, ``The Year of Jubilo'' rises to
the majesty of Lincoln's Second Inaugural Address. Its narrative
has the strength and sinew of Shelby Foote's three-volume history
of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a story of generals riding off into the eternal smoky
mists of battle, but a story of the bereavement of ordinary people
and of the confusion and chaos at war's end. Not least, it is a
story of the violence that honors no armistice, and of unspeakable
cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people lived in a dreadfully violent time, much more
violent than our own,'' Bahr said. For a time, he was a Civil War
re-enactor, but the masquerades of a re-enactment do not even hint
at the savagery lost to memory.
</P>
<P>
   The opening scene, in which a blind boy hears the sound of
horses' hooves, the voices of strange men and the sudden, panicked
protests of his mother and father, is as heartbreaking as anything
you will ever read. It is a prelude to a masterfully controlled
drama of remorse and vengeance, love and irreparable loss.
</P>
<P>
   Bahr's main character is a Mississippian named Gawain Harper,
who had enlisted only because the father of the woman he wanted to
marry laid down the conditions for marriage: duty to the
Confederate States of America first. With a man he meets along the
way, a strange man without a past named Harry Stribling, Harper
returns three years later to the town of Cumberland, now occupied
by Federal troops but under siege by renegades led by the monstrous
King Solomon Gault. In its own way, Harper and Stribling's journey
is a hell worse than war, a cavalcade of Southern grotesquerie
whose apparent point is moral anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   At journey's end, both Cumberland and the lives Harper returns
to are in wreckage and bewilderment, and his own defeat in battle
is only a preliminary to the struggle that now confronts him. He
learns, if he did not know before, what honor entails and how
grievous sacrifice can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Year of Jubilo'' _ the title comes from an abolitionists'
song _ celebrated the emancipation of the slaves. It celebrated
freedom. But it also unleashed forces that can only be called evil.
As it did, it set the terms for our expiation _ not just as blacks
or whites, Southerners or Northerners, but as human beings who kill
one another out of rabid passion while sharing a common mortal
destiny. In its gravity and ambition, ``The Year of Jubilo'' is a
novel that William Faulkner might have written, but Faulkner never
wrote as beautifully as Howard Bahr.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Year of Jubilo. By Howard Bahr. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $25.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOOK
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from ``The Year of Jubilo''
</P>
<P>
   Willy stood rigid in the yard, clutching the smooth, cool
doorknob painted with flowers. He heard the horses stop outside the
place where the fence was, a jangling and thudding and muttering so
confused he could not begin to fashion a picture of it. He heard
the door of the house open, heard his father's shoes on the porch;
meanwhile the dogs were barking and howling, the horses blowing,
and somewhere among it all the reedy piping of the bird his mother
called a redwing. Then Mother was there, her hands rough and
smelling of soap. GET IN THE HOUSE she said, her voice urgent,
harsh. But Willy couldn't move. His mother stood behind him, her
hands on his shoulders. Then Father was there, too. Willy had not
heard him come, but knew he had by the smell of tobacco and shaving
soap.
</P>
<P>
   His father stood between them and the commotion in the road. YOU
ALL GET IN THE HOUSE his father said in the same voice, but Willy's
mother only gripped him tighter. NO she said. ``No,'' said Willy.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
