<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BIO-PARK11-COX     06-08 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-PARK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Easy being green at Costa Rican INBioparque
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO DE HEREDIA, Costa Rica _ The guide's voice was
curiously lacking in urgency as she turned suddenly, pointed to my
feet and said: ``Watch out for the coral snake.''
</P>
<P>
   Her warning had all the concern of someone telling me I was
about to step on a wayward house cat or an errant ball instead of a
highly venomous tropical serpent. I stopped in midstride and looked
at my feet, fully expecting to see the gaudy black, yellow and
red-striped bands of the coral snake slithering around them. But
there was nothing except my scuffed brown walking shoes and a
concrete walkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was a coral snake there,'' our guide, Anna Navarro,
insisted with a smile as she continued to point at the ground by my
feet. ``They are not supposed to be out here, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Anna shrugged her shoulders and walked on, as if to say even the
wildlife here is still learning the ropes. That's to be expected in
this patch of tropical jungle plopped down in the middle of a quiet
suburban neighborhood. This unique environmental theme park, the
National Institute of Biodiversity Park, opened in February just a
few miles from downtown San Jose, Costa Rica's bustling capital.
Thankfully, all the wildlife, especially the coral snakes, minded
their manners during my recent visit.
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard about the park from my hosts, businessman
Jorge Rodriguez and his wife, Virginia, I was not enthralled with
the idea of visiting a theme park that told me about the natural
wonders of a naturally wonderful country. I wanted to see the real
thing. But they had visited the park before it opened to the public
and were effusive about its merits and what it taught not only
tourists, but lifelong residents of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   More commonly known as INBioparque, for its acronym in Spanish,
the park is a combination tourist attraction, teaching center and
research facility that stresses enjoying and preserving the
country's bountiful natural resources. Officials with the private,
nonprofit National Institute of Biodiversity, which developed and
operates the 13-acre park, are hoping it will become a gateway for
tourists to Costa Rica, which has become something of an ecological
mecca.
</P>
<P>
   The institute was formed in 1989 to put the brakes on rampant
deforestation that was threatening to denude large areas of the
country. Before the park, INBio spent years collecting and
cataloging plant and animal specimens in Costa Rica, which serves
as a land bridge between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans, and
between North and South America. The collecting and cataloging
still goes on through dozens of researchers in the field known as
parataxonomists, but they are virtually invisible to the casual
park visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through INBio we are learning the language of nature,'' said
Rocio Lopez, the park's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   INBio officials believe they can teach visitors and residents
the difference between squandering natural resources and using them
wisely. They refer to this as ``sustainable use.'' That means using
natural resources without using them up. Built on an abandoned
coffee plantation at a cost of about $7.5 million, the park
provides a comprehensive overview of one of the world's most
popular destinations for ecotourists and adventure travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica has 30 national parks and preserves and more than 100
protected areas, although it is only about the size of New
Hampshire. The amount of flora and fauna packed into this country
is almost beyond comprehension. As INBio guides point out
repeatedly, Costa Rica has only 0.03 percent of the world's surface
but more than 500,000 species of plants and animals, nearly 5
percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
   Reproducing even just a portion of that in 13 acres would seem
to be a bit of a challenge, but the park's designers pulled it off.
They have re-created three of the country's seven distinct
ecosystems within its boundaries: a dry forest, a central valley
forest and a tropical forest. Portions of several maritime
ecosystems are in a saltwater lagoon exhibit that opened in April.
The lagoon is stocked with fish, mollusks and underwater plants
found in Costa Rica, all of which can be seen through an underwater
viewing station.
</P>
<P>
   Re-creating the central valley forest was no problem, since San
Jose is in the central valley. To re-create the dry forest,
developers simply brought in plants indigenous to that ecosystem
and then dried out that portion of the park by pumping water out of
it. For the humid, tropical forest, they took the water from the
dry forest, recycled it, and pumped it into the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   The forests are contiguous, so it is difficult to know when
you're passing from one to another. But Anna, who said she and her
fellow guides went through six months of intense training before
being entrusted to lead the public, was well-attuned to those
changes and reminded us of how the plants differed as we moved
along the trails.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing boxes are scattered throughout the forests where certain
species of insects, butterflies and amphibians can be more easily
spotted. Anna stopped us in the tropical forest at one such exhibit
and pointed out three poison dart frogs, each barely larger than a
thumbnail. Two were bright orange, the other two-tone green. The
dart frogs were so named because Indians of Central and South
America put the poisonous mucus excreted from their skin on hunting
darts.
</P>
<P>
   Even Anna was excited about seeing three on the same day. ``You
were lucky you got to see three,'' she told my companion and me.
``Usually we may see only one because they are so small.''
</P>
<P>
   The lagoon is expected to become one of the more popular areas
in the park. It has an open-air amphitheater and two open-air
classrooms where schoolchildren will be instructed in the
importance of saving natural resources. It also has a man-made hill
with a lookout point that provides spectacular views of nearby
Barva and Poaz volcanoes, as well as downtown San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   An eco-tourism office housed in the park is a good place to pick
up brochures about traveling into the countryside to see the real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The park has almost a Disneylike feel to it, with its bright
yellow and blue buildings and its fresh-scrubbed guides in khaki
pants and white polo shirts. It can also have a Disneylike effect
on your wallet. A private tour and lecture are $21 per person.
Group tours are $18 each for adults, $15 for students and $9 for
children under 12. English-speaking guides are available, and the
introductory video is presented in English hourly.
</P>
<P>
   After the video, visitors are shown through two large exhibit
halls with interactive displays that focus on the uniqueness of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Although the park is now being heavily promoted through tourist
agencies and even local cab drivers, the place is so new that even
cabbies who have lived here all their lives have problems finding
it. And finding the park by yourself with the directions in its
brochure _ 400 meters north and 250 meters west of the Shell gas
station in Santo Domingo _ can be more than just a small adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But it's worth the effort, even if portions of the park appear a
bit underdeveloped. That's because many of the trees were planted
only two years ago, according to Anna.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees are tiny now, but come back in 10 years,'' she
invited as she stood next to a plant known locally as ``the Poor
Man's Umbrella'' because of its large leaves. ``Maybe then we'll be
fully grown.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: San Jose is $498 round trip on Delta (one daily
nonstop) and American (connecting service through Miami) airlines.
The park is in the suburb of Santo Domingo de Heredia, just a few
miles northwest of downtown San Jose. Well-marked buses run from
the center of San Jose to downtown Heredia every few minutes for
120 colones (about 40 cents) each way. From downtown Heredia it's
easy to catch a red cab to the park (about $2). Just tell the
cabbie ``INBioparque'' and he'll deliver you, maybe to the back
gate, but you'll be near enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Park particulars: The park is open 7:30 a.m.-4 p.m. daily.
Admission is $18 for adults ($21 for a guided tour), $15 for
students ($17 for a guided tour), $15 for children under 12 (no
guide fee charged). Guided tours are available in English and
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The National Institute of Biodiversity's Web
site, www.inbio.ac.cr/inbioparque, is in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
