r d BC-BISTRO11-COX     06-08 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISTRO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bistros: A flavor of France in Napa Valley
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNTVILLE, Calif. _ Bistro Jeanty and Bouchon _ two of the
nation's best French bistros _ are oddly enough a few doors from
each other on picturesque Washington Street in this Napa Valley
town.
</P>
<P>
   Odd, because the valley was largely settled by Italians and
because the prevalent culinary idiom is ``California cuisine.'' Is
there room for dueling bistros?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' says Sarah Scott, a native Atlantan who is one
of the executive chefs at Robert Mondavi Winery. ``French bistro
food is legitimate and very pure. (These restaurants) signal a
return and seeking out of true and authentic flavors. They're
neighborhoody, and they fit what Yountville is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bistro Jeanty is chef Philippe Jeanty's return to his French
country roots after the many years he spent practicing fashionable
wine-country cuisine at Domaine Chandon. The restaurant is small,
crowded and noisy, with a moderately priced menu of the kind of
homey, provincial French food Jeanty grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   He makes no concessions to American palates. Instead, he wins
converts. His jelled squares of pigs' feet over French green beans
in a mustardy vinaigrette is among his most popular dishes. You may
grimace at your first bite, but it will be like your first bite of
sushi _ a revelation. Now you're ready for the fine-grained and
butter-soft cubes of lamb's tongue with potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   A hand-chopped steak tartare sports a raw egg yolk perched in
its shell on top and a cornet of exceptional french fries on the
side. And the cassoulet comes in a crock deep enough to suspend the
duck confit leg, sausage and bacon in creamy white beans. But it
also tapers to a small base, so you're not overwhelmed by beans.
Even as he pays homage to the classics, Jeanty shows a finessed
hand as a chef.
</P>
<P>
   While Bistro Jeanty evokes a corner cafe in the French
countryside, Bouchon _ with its tile floors and mohair banquettes _
seems more Parisian. Thomas Keller conceived it as a low-key
alternative to catch the overflow from his French Laundry and to
provide Valley food professionals a place to congregate late. Both
the original chef and the original manager (Keller's brother,
Joseph) have left since a somewhat shaky opening two years ago, and
by all accounts the place has improved _ both in terms of food and
'tude.
</P>
<P>
   Diners still pack this boisterous and extremely noisy place for
platters of shellfish _ chilled lobster, oysters, shrimp, clams and
mussels _ served from a station next to the custom-designed zinc
bar. But it's the newer dishes that shine. There's a juicy boudin
blanc (white veal sausage) served with potato mousseline and dense,
sweet figs. And the skate wing served over meltingly soft savoy
cabbage with a whole-grain mustard sauce is a stellar example of
innovative cooking with a grounding in classic French flavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go through this whole (culinary) revolution to
return to this,'' Scott says, ``something you can eat every day.''
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bistro Jeanty: 6510 Washington St., Yountville. 707-944-0103.
Lunch and dinner served daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bouchon: 6534 Washington St., Yountville. 707-944-8037. Lunch
and dinner served daily.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
