<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-DINING-SANFRANCISCO11     06-08 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINING-SANFRANCISCO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the Bay Area _ where food isn't an afterthought, sometimes
it's the reason for the trip _ there's no shortage of culinary
delights available from both classic restaurants and innovative
newcomers
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNTVILLE, Calif. _ With a Mother of Pearl spoon _ hardly
bigger than a tasting spoon in an ice cream parlor _ I scoop up the
``oysters and pearls'' in tiny bites, not wanting to see it end.
</P>
<P>
   This dish is a trim portion of weird, enthralling mush: custardy
sabayon studded with tapioca, then set with plump Malpeque oysters
and an outsized dollop of osetra caviar. Every spoonful startles
the palate with its contrast of eggy richness and brine, and the
beads-on-beads texture rolls on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that good?'' asks the waiter, clearing my dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the best thing I've ever eaten,'' I say, almost
asking (begging, pleading) for another.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't ask for seconds at the French Laundry, the Napa
Valley restaurant where any meal may consist of 15 or 20
mini-courses. Each is a two-bite inspiration, an arresting
sensation of the here and now slipping down your throat.
</P>
<P>
   That is the reason that people book their plane tickets around a
reservation at Thomas Keller's 62-seat sensation that has become
the non plus ultra of America's dining destinations. To reserve,
you must call two months to the exact calendar date ahead of time,
and be prepared for stinging rejection if others beat you to the
punch.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can't book at the French Laundry, you won't be
hurting for great eats. From the Wine Country to the hot South of
Market district of San Francisco, the Bay Area is awash in
astonishing restaurants. In some you'll enjoy the simple, true
flavors of locally grown products. In others, you'll witness the
chef consciously shifting the paradigm, pushing California cuisine
to the next stage of its evolution. But throughout the region,
you'll see that restaurants here benefit from a unique synergy of
natural resources, commitment to gastronomy and the kind of red-hot
economy (bless those dot-com millionaires) that can make this all
possible.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you make the most of Bay Area dining in a few days?
You plan meal by meal.
</P>
<P>
   That means first considering the classics. For some, San
Francisco wouldn't be San Francisco without a dozen oysters and a
gorgonzola cheeseburger on focaccia at Zuni Cafe, a contemporary
French degustation under the tented ceiling of Fleur de Lys or a
roasted fish at Rose Pistola. California wouldn't be California
without Chez Panisse. And the Wine Country offers everything from a
glorious patio amid the vines at Domaine Chandon to killer pigs'
feet at Bistro Jeanty.
</P>
<P>
   But you should also save time (and room in your stomach) for the
important newcomers. Gary Danko, named America's best new
restaurant by the James Beard Foundation, puts fusty Fisherman's
Wharf back on the culinary map. The Fifth Floor, in the hep Palomar
Hotel, showcases the swing-beat showmanship of chef George Morrone.
Throughout the Bay Area wonderful food seems to roll in with the
fog, seep forth from the San Andreas Fault. It is everywhere, and
yours to choose.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
