A8276 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HAWAIIAN-SHIRTS11-COX     06-08 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAIIAN-SHIRTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool prints add instant jazz to dad's look
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hawaiian clothier Ellery J. Chun died recently, just as the
tropical print shirts he's credited with inventing are reaching a
new zenith in popularity, with sales heating up in anticipation of
Father's Day. Chun, who was 91, designed his first set of shirts in
1931 and registered them under the ``Aloha'' trade name five years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical print shirts weren't always considered the height of
sporty stylishness they are today: they had their heyday in the
1940s and '50 when entertainers like Bing Crosby and Frank Sinatra
wore them; but for much of their history they were deemed rather
tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says Dillard's menswear manager Hugh McDonald, ``The look
is very popular with the young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian shirts come in a variety of patterns, ranging from
subtle prints with ocean or beach scenes, to bold,
tropical-inspired designs that make you want to go surfing. Color
schemes run the gamut, from soft pastels and muted shades to
bright, vivid tones.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts can be worn open, buttoned or layered on top of a
matching T-shirt. Pair them with drawstring or cargo pants, khakis,
linen slacks or shorts for the ultimate in weekend wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every man, at some point, wants a few more interesting pieces
in his wardrobe,'' says Jerry Lemmo, manager at Sebastian's Closet
in Atlanta. ``He's going to do a print for a nice change of pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
