<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-VOCATIONAL-EDUCATION-     06-08 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOCATIONAL-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REGENTS FEAR EFFECT OF MANDATORY EXAM ON VOCATIONAL STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICK KARLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY. N.Y. _ Facing fears that some high school students won't
pass the Regents exams to be required for graduation, some New York
Board of Regents members are entertaining the idea of exams
tailored to vocational students.
</P>
<P>
   The central idea behind refining the new state standards is to
improve the educational program _ and job prospects _ for the
roughly 295,000 high school students in vocational or career
preparation courses, ranging from auto mechanics to building trades
and computer networking. Already, education officials have proposed
a certificate proving that these students have mastered a job
skill.
</P>
<P>
   But educators fear the Regents exams may prove onerous to those
who study trades and who previously were not required to take the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone agrees that the new state standards will be tough
to meet, the Regents insist that by refining their requirements
they are not backing down from their high goals, and so far top
officials oppose tailoring or altering the actual exams to
vocational courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not (support) any effort that creates a second tier,''
Regents Chancellor Carl Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a special advisory panel rejected the idea of alternate
exams, in part because such a move would look like a ``second-class
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes may be considered next week when the board, which
sets New York's education policy, considers a proposal for a
vocational Regents diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Educators have been wondering how to integrate the vocational
programs into the larger goal of raising academic achievement for
all of the state's students.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the focus so far has been on a phase-in of the mandatory
Regents exams, which have historically been viewed as college prep
but which all high school graduates will have to pass by 2003. This
is the first year all high school seniors will have to pass the
English Regents exam in order to get a diploma. Mandatory exams in
math, history and science will be phased in over the next several
years.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this academic bar-raising, the vocational certificate
plan emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Regents diploma with a career and technical
endorsement,'' said Education Commissioner Richard Mills.
</P>
<P>
   To earn these endorsements, students may be able to take courses
that are geared to their career studies, such as the science behind
an automobile engine, or the math that goes into building a home.
</P>
<P>
   That's already happening to some extent. Many courses, including
vocational offerings, emphasize reading and writing to prepare
students for the English Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, passing the exams, along with earning a technical
certificate, will be a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of questions about it,'' said Regent Eleanor
Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of students out there who say the only reason
they are here (in school) is because of the career and technical
piece,'' said Bartlett, a retired Albany city school administrator.
``To say to those students, `take five Regents exams,' would be a
stretch. I'm afraid that for some of our students it will be
discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they say there's no alternative, I'm afraid the kids won't
have the time. Does it make sense to penalize the kid because he
wants a technical diploma?'' said Gary Jones, director of
occupational education at the Albany-area vocational education
center in Colonie.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has suggested adapting the Regents exams to vocational
courses _ writing essays about engines rather than ``Moby Dick,''
for example. Some officials may want to alter other exams.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Saul Cohen believes all high school students should take
the same English and math exams, but those in vocational programs
might take other tests tailored to their studies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, vocational students might prepare for a Regents
exam on the history of technology instead of the traditional world
history, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mills, who is cool to the idea of alternate Regents exams,
said the final result may include some changes and compromises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a policy matter that the Regents are going to decide.
You're going to see a very intense debate involving thousands of
people over the next few months,'' Mills said. ``I've never seen a
policy issue emerge from the Regents exactly the way that it went
in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
