<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GECKO-STICKY-FEET-HNS     06-08 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GECKO-STICKY-FEET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS LINK MOLECULAR FORCES TO GECKO'S STICKING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Tokay gecko can scamper across ceilings and
walls because their feet are covered with millions of microscopic
hairs that have astounding bonding power, researchers reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, if verified, could lead to super-sticky adhesives
for use in outer space and on the ocean bottom, said Robert J.
Full, a biologist at the University of California at Berkeley and
one of the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's issue of Nature, Full and his colleagues report
the first measurements of the strength of gecko hairs, technically
known as setae (pronounced ``see tee''').
</P>
<P>
   ``The hairs themselves are so sticky that if we were able to fit
a million or two of them onto the surface of a dime, it would be
enough to lift a small child,'' Kellar Autumn, a biologist at Lewis
and Clark College in Portland, Ore., said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least the 1960s, some scientists have suggested that
setae tips are so tiny that they can exploit molecular-size forces
that are normally unavailable to living creatures.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is van der Waals forces, which are negligible on
the scale of everyday life, but are fairly strong in the short
distances between molecules. (The forces are named for Johannes
Diderik van der Waals, a Dutch scientist who won the 1910 Nobel
Prize in physics.)
</P>
<P>
   These forces between a single gecko hair tip and molecules in a
wall would be extremely weak _ too weak to support a foot-long
gecko as it scampers around a ceiling. But add up the combined van
der Waals forces of millions of hairs on a gecko foot, and there is
powerful sticking power.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists caution that the van der Waals explanation
remains unproven. But it once might have seemed crazy, and now it
has gained credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothesis is feasible because the measured strength ``falls
right in the middle of the range of van der Waals'' forces that one
would expect for millions of gecko hairs, Full said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that a different type of inter-molecular
force is involved: electrical attraction between oppositely charged
particles in the hair tips.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its cause, the gecko's stickiness is a dramatic example
of Mother Nature's creativity and cunning.
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary biologists have long marveled at how nature
continually finds ecological niches for animals to exploit, then
gives them amazing tools with which to exploit them. Consider
bacteria, which orient themselves in liquids by detecting Earth's
magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   So when humans invented buildings with ceilings, geckos quickly
recognized the ceilings as an unexploited ecological niche
blissfully free of predators and deliciously crowded with edibles,
such as bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The evolutionary biologist Charles Darwin argued that life forms
evolved when nature eliminated those that were less fit. The
stickiest geckos were presumably more likely to survive than those
that kept slipping off trees (perhaps into some predator's jaws).
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true in tropical lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of geckos live in areas prone to hurricanes,'' Autumn
said. ``Perhaps their (stickiness) prevents them from being blown
away.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 850 types of gecko, ranging in size from a few
inches to a few feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-DEMOCRATS-BENBARNES-T     06-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-BENBARNES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DEMOCRATIC STAR STILL WIELDS CLOUT IN TEXAS PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He had the golden touch, the kind of talent,
many said, that might just land him in the White House one day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, it all ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 34, he toppled from the throne to the political
graveyard,'' said a 1972 Dallas Times Herald editorial. ``Richard
Nixon once came back from sound defeat, but no one, at this point,
can figure the future of the fallen young white knight, Ben
Barnes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades later, both Nixon and the Times Herald are
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes, Texas' youngest lieutenant governor at age 30, whose
career in elective politics was grounded by the 1971 Sharpstown
scandal and his life rocked by a 1987 personal bankruptcy, is again
making his presence felt at 62.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest incarnation, as elder statesman among Lone Star
Democrats, Barnes is calling on state leaders to quit doling out
what he says are meaningless tax cuts while Texas falls farther and
farther behind other states in spending on education, health and
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas today is drifting toward mediocrity just when it should
be striving for greatness,'' Barnes said in a recent speech that
has sent a few ripples through the capitol. ``Our politicians are
letting it happen and the rest of us don't seem to understand or
care.''
</P>
<P>
   He then ticked off a litany of state rankings: last in state
spending per capita, 22nd in the percentage of residents over 25
with college degrees, 47th in per capita highway spending, huge
high school dropout rates, nearly last in children with health
insurance ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit idly by and let us fiddle while Rome
burns,'' Barnes said in an interview. ``Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   If he sounds angry, he is.
</P>
<P>
   If he sounds like a candidate for office, Barnes says
emphatically that he is not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he returned a $500 contribution to a donor who heard
the speech and thought he was running again.
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that he has no ambitions for elected office,
Barnes said, ``I do want to help set the agenda for the campaigns
in the fall. I want to help the public set the agenda for the next
session of the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   His agenda includes an eye-popping $20,000 teacher pay raise
over the next four years, and hundreds of millions of dollars more
a year for transportation improvements and higher education
spending.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the increases, Barnes says the state should not only
use every dime of any surplus money but also should raise gasoline
taxes by 10 cents a gallon over the next four years. That would
generate $315 million a year for teacher salaries and smaller
classes, and pump $911 million into road modernization, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Black, a spokesman for the Texas Republican Party, said
the GOP can only benefit if Democrats like Barnes talk about
raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a Democrat would say that raising taxes is the key to
greatness,'' Black said. ``And only a Democrat would think that
Texas is heading toward mediocrity when in fact Texas is
skyrocketing toward greatness thanks to Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a powerful Republican, State Sen. Bill Ratliff of Mount
Pleasant, who is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, has
called for a gasoline tax increase to pay for sorely needed
transportation infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, a lifelong Democrat who still contributes much to
Democratic candidates, is quick to point out that he is not
singling out Republicans in his criticism _ including Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an attack on Republicans, or an attack on George
Bush,'' Barnes said. ``Gov. Richards was governor of Texas and we
didn't move Texas ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a millionaire lobbyist, Barnes has spent most of his life at
or near the center of Texas power _ and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Gorman, about 100 miles southwest of Fort Worth, Barnes
was elected in 1960 to the Texas House of Representatives. At 26,
he became the youngest House speaker in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But he fell almost as quickly as he rose. In 1971, state
government was roiled by the Sharpstown bribery scandal. Though
never charged with criminal wrongdoing, Barnes was swept out of
office by a reform-minded electorate, and he finished third in the
1972 Democratic primary for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-rolling 1980s Barnes and former Gov. John Connally
were involved in a series of ill-fated real estate developments,
forcing both into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Parlaying experience and connections, Barnes quickly rebounded
financially as a lobbyist. In 1997, he made headlines when Gtech,
the company that runs the Texas Lottery, paid his firm $23 million
to ``drop'' a lobbying contract.
</P>
<P>
   It had become the focus of considerable controversy and,
incongruously, ended up as fodder for the 2000 presidential
campaign. Compelled to testify in a lawsuit brought against Gtech,
Barnes was asked if he had helped Gov. Bush get a slot in the Air
National Guard in 1968, at the height of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   Through a lawyer, Barnes said that a Houston oilman named Sidney
Adger, a Bush family friend, called him when he was House speaker
to ask that he recommend the young Bush for a pilot slot. Barnes
said he would. Bush has said that neither he nor his father, then a
U.S. representative from Houston, asked for special favors.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the twice-divorced father of four grown children is again
making headlines, but this time there is a touch of the old Barnes
on display.
</P>
<P>
   While some Democrats are encouraging Barnes' tax increase ideas,
others, like former Comptroller John Sharp, call the move unwise.
Texas' problems need to be addressed, Sharp said. But try winning
an election by ``standing up and saying the first thing I'm going
to do is raise taxes,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some politicians tell me, `All this, it will not sell,''' said
Barnes, who plans to make a series of speeches around the state on
the subject and says, ``That's not the reaction I'm getting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
