</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN PROMISES SUPPORT FOR SIERRA LEONE DESPITE WITHDRAWAL OF
TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ The British foreign secretary, Robin
Cook, tried to reassure anxious Sierra Leoneans Thursday of
Britain's long-term commitment to its former West African colony,
even as British troops prepared to withdraw next week and leave the
country's security in the hands of a U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Making a one-day trip through Sierra Leone's rain-soaked capital
here, Cook met with President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and leaders of a
fragile pro-government coalition, including the heads of two
militias that had fought each other for years. He then met with the
civilian and military heads of the U.N. force that had teetered on
the edge of collapse in early May before the British arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have assured President Kabbah that Britain wants to be
long-term partner in ensuring a stable, successful, enterprising
Sierra Leone,'' Cook said at a news conference after meeting the
president. ``And I can assure President Kabbah that Britain is
ready to go the distance until we have achieved our joint objective
of a lasting security.''
</P>
<P>
   The British government is proceeding with its plans to pull out
its 800 marines, saying it has achieved its stated aim of
stabilizing the situation here in the last month as the United
Nations built up its force by more than 3,000 to the current level
of about 11,900. Already, British soldiers who had been guarding
the international airport and western Freetown have been replaced
by U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The planned withdrawal comes as many Sierra Leoneans, clearly
lacking confidence in a U.N. force that appeared helpless against
Foday Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front, have pleaded with the
British to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't leave, don't leave,'' said Muctar Jalloh, the unofficial
mayor of a camp for people whose hands, arms or legs were chopped
off as part of the atrocities that came to define Sierra Leone's
war.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, like most foreign dignitaries before him, paid a visit to
the camp, run by Doctors Without Borders. He met several amputees,
including Abu, an 18-month-old boy whose right leg was hacked off
above the knee when he was 2 months old.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, Cook argued that Britain was not leaving
Sierra Leone. A team of 180 military officials will arrive soon to
train 1,000 soldiers for a new Sierra Leone army, followed later by
a smaller group that will be charged with recreating the rest of
the army over the next three years. Two warships, a frigate and a
supply boat, will remain anchored off the coast of Freetown, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something I totally agree with,'' Kabbah, sitting next
to Cook, said of Britain's plans. He added: ``The British people
have done a lot for us. We appreciate it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kabbah appeared less comfortable at a later news conference with
Cook and the leaders of the military coalition that is propping up
his government. Seated two seats to the president's left was Hinga
Norman, the deputy defense minister, who derives his power mainly
because he controls a militia of tribal hunters who wear charms and
recite verses from the Bible and Koran to steel themselves for
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Two chairs to Kabbah's right sat Johnny Paul Koroma, a retired
Lt. Col. who toppled Kabbah in 1997 and briefly held power. The
followers of Koroma, still considered the real military powerbroker
in the country, participated with Sankoh's group in committing
atrocities against civilians, especially in the brutal invasion of
Freetown in January 1999. But Koroma, now a born-again Christian,
has allied himself with Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how long the alliance between Koroma and Norman,
fierce adversaries for years, will last. What is clear is that
their militias, which had begun disarming under a peace accord
signed last July, have taken up arms again and are unlikely to
disarm under the present situation.
</P>
<P>
   While the British succeeded in guaranteeing the capital's
security and helped repel rebels toward the east, Sierra Leone is
again divided. The Revolutionary United Front again controls the
north and east, including the country's diamond mines.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said that Britain will sponsor a proposal at the U.N.
Security Council in New York to ban the trade of all but
government-certified diamonds from Sierra Leone. But the measure
would mean little since diamonds are smuggled out of Sierra Leone
from neighboring countries, particularly Liberia, and diamond
buyers outside Africa, especially those in Antwerp, have been
unwilling to abide by similar bans.
</P>
<P>
   A number of critical issues remain unresolved. What happens to
Sankoh, who remains in government custody, has yet to be decided.
The U.N. force is expected to grow by another 3,000 soldiers. But
the United Nations has yet to put forth a plan to deal with the new
reality in Sierra Leone, a country where there is no longer any
peace to keep and where many of the other premises behind the
peacekeeping mission have also become irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-member U.N. assessment team visited Sierra Leone this
week and is soon expected to present a report to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
