<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-NASHVILLERESURGENT-10     06-08 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASHVILLERESURGENT-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MEGA-MALL, ARENA AND SPRUCED-UP ZOO, MUSIC CITY HAS REASON TO
SING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Let's imagine you've only been in Nashville for an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   You're driving around town, familiarizing yourself with the
place, gearing up for an evening at the Grand Ole Opry because, as
everyone knows, country music is all there is to Nashville. Before
crossing the Cumberland River and heading toward Music Row and the
Ernest Tubb Record Shop, you think it might be interesting to swing
by Vanderbilt University. And it is; Vanderbilt is a red-brick
wonder, beautiful and inspiring at the same time, reminiscent of
the Stanford campus in California. But you can only look at bricks
for so long; you leave Vanderbilt and start to head downtown when
you glance across this pretty green park _ and there is the
Parthenon, in all its massive Grecian glory. It's quite a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   And so is Nashville itself, a sparkling, pleasant city that
could use as its official motto the phrase ``We're Not Just Country
Music Anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that musicians from Loretta Lynn to Shania Twain aren't
still a huge attraction. Anyone who comes to Nashville on vacation
obviously will have a more than passing interest in steel guitars
and twangy vocals. But it's also safe to say that Nashville has
more to offer, a lot more _ a completely refurbished zoo, some
intriguing museums, various sports attractions, a new mega-shopping
mall, Andrew Jackson's old homestead, and, of course, the Parthenon
replica _ all made even more attractive by amazingly clean city
streets and unclogged highways that make going from one place to
another easy for even the most traffic-shy Nashville visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Those who haven't experienced Nashville lately will find the
city very different. Around 1995, civic leaders decided to clean up
the streets and expand Nashville's tourist outreach. That, in turn,
led to the wooing and winning of the pro football Oilers from
Houston, who then needed a new stadium near downtown Nashville.
That resulted in a much-needed face-lift for the neighborhoods
surrounding downtown's famous nightspots and stores. Nashville 2000
has an almost ivory gleam to it; you'd be hard-pressed to find a
``cleaner'' American city.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything is new _ far from it. The Parthenon in
Nashville's Centennial Park, while not as ancient as the Greek
structure it copies, is still more than 100 years old; the
full-scale replica was built in 1897 as part of the statewide
celebration of Tennessee's 100th birthday. Now it houses various
art exhibits, though younger visitors will probably most enjoy the
gorgeous duck pond outside. (Don't be put off by some scaffolding
on the outside walls; the Parthenon is open for business as usual.)
</P>
<P>
   Though the Opryland Theme Park has closed, the venerable Grand
Ole Opry is going strong, and undoubtedly will until the last song
about straying spouses and dead dogs has been written and sung.
Evening shows featuring dozens of artists (Little Jimmy Dickens,
Porter Wagoner, and many, many more) are held every Friday and
Saturday night, with Tuesday matinees added during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Music Row is still exactly that, a couple of streets (mostly
Division Street and Music Square, which combines parts of 16th
Avenue South and 17th Avenue South) lined with record stores and
agents' offices and music publishing businesses. The Ernest Tubb
Record Shop is on nearby Lower Broadway, as is Tootsie's Orchid
Lounge and the Lawrence Brothers Record Shop, perhaps the best
place in the world to find some out-of-print LPs by obscure country
stars. These evergreen attractions are probably the best places to
buy T-shirts as souvenirs for friends, and Tootsie's still has the
nonstop live music that earned its original reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Wags have described The Hermitage as ``Monticello without the
inventions and Mount Vernon without the charm,'' but Andrew
Jackson's old digs are, in fact, fascinating, though The Hermitage
did have to be rebuilt after an 1834 fire, meaning much of what you
see is faithful imitation rather than original, but at least it's
Jackson-designed imitation. Most of the furnishings were once
Jackson property. A well-preserved smokehouse and the tombs of
Jackson and wife Rachel offer Kodak moments. The Hermitage is open
daily except for Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Opryland Theme Park is the most obvious of the vanished tourist
attractions, but also gone are the Hank Williams Jr. Museum, Twitty
City and the Country Music Wax Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Other traditional Nashville attractions remain: The Ryman
Auditorium, original home of the Grand Ole Opry; the Country Music
Hall of Fame, where Elvis' gold Cadillac is a featured exhibit; and
the Grand Ole Opry Museum. All are worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   But so are the new places, many of which don't have country
music tie-ins.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildhorse Saloon on Second Avenue North opened in 1994, and
it provides a modern counterpoint to Tootsie's and the Opry _ think
Billy Bob's Texas, but smaller and with a third more neon. This is
the Nashville venue you're likely to see on CMT cable, with women
singers more likely to wear tank tops and cutoffs than crinoline
and ruffles. Trick Pony and Mary Sue England are a couple of the
more recent acts, and so-called dinosaur rock has its place _
America and Blood, Sweat &AMP; Tears have played there recently.
Nearby, there's a Hard Rock Cafe, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville Zoo doesn't rival Fort Worth's, but would
certainly hold its own against most other metropolitan animal
exhibits. Apparently, the old zoo was dingy and depressing for man
and beast, but the updated version, which includes great natural
habitatlike areas for cougars, gray wolves and black bears, will
delight most patrons. There's also a huge playground, so kids can
work off some excess energy before getting back in the car.
</P>
<P>
   OpryMills, which opened just a few weeks ago, is a massive $200
mega-mall built where the old Opryland Theme Park used to stand
outside town. Imagine the biggest mall you've ever seen, but on
steroids. OpryMills is most similar in size to Minneapolis'
now-legendary Mall of America, a chain-store mecca of gigantic
proportions. If you can't find an item to buy at OpryMills, that's
probably because it hasn't been invented yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Cumberland Science Museum may be best-known for its
planetarium, but kids will race for Curiosity Corner, which
features the same kind of user-friendly exhibits as San Francisco's
better-known Exploratorium.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new downtown sports arena that provides a home for an
equally new National Hockey League team, the Nashville Predators,
and the Tennessee Sports Hall of Fame, certainly of interest to
ESPN buffs.
</P>
<P>
   More is coming. In May 2001, the Country Music Hall of Fame
takes up new downtown digs that will offer better display space and
room for future expansion. In that same month, Nashville will open
the Frist Center for the Visual Arts, the city's first major fine
arts center (think what the Amon Carter, Modern and Kimbell museums
mean to Fort Worth).
</P>
<P>
   But Nashville's charms aren't limited to the places you read
about in guide books. The whole atmosphere of the city is friendly
and family-oriented. Its public parks sparkle. Common-sense signage
helps visitors find their way around with ease. Though all the
major attractions involve admission fees, there are free programs,
too, like the teen-friendly, free summer concerts on Thursday
nights at Riverfront Park.
</P>
<P>
   Even driving in and around Nashville is fun. Located about in
the center of Tennessee, the city is surrounded by pretty lakes and
sits amid gently rolling, tree-lined hills. The Cumberland River
loops around downtown, which has enough tall buildings to provide
afternoon shade and includes sufficiently varied restaurants to
provide gustatory pleasure no matter which kind of food you feel
like eating.
</P>
<P>
   Geography probably dictates what you'll want to do and when,
though Nashville's freeway system makes it possible to get from one
end of town to the other in minimal time. But the Grand Ole Opry,
OpryMills and The Hermitage are on the northeast fringes of town.
The Capitol, Vanderbilt and the Parthenon occupy acres to the west,
and Music Row stretches mostly south. Two full days and nights, or
certainly a three-day weekend, will probably enable you to do and
see almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   All of Nashville's elements _ the new attractions, the old
tourist favorites, the much cleaner downtown streets and the lovely
surrounding countryside _ combine to offer a special sort of
hospitality. Like a few other places _ Santa Fe, Durango, Portland,
Oklahoma City despite the tornadoes _ Nashville has a unique
atmosphere that's exciting without too much attendant big-city
effluvia. When you're there, you feel as though you're somewhere
special _ and that's what vacations ought to offer.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
