<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LABOURS-FILM-REVIEW-N     06-08 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOURS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE'S LABOUR'S LOST': WHAT SAY YOU, MY LORDS? YOU'D RATHER
CHARLESTON? 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For every man with his affects is born,
</P>
<P>
   Not by might mast'red, but by special grace.
</P>
<P>
   These lines are spoken by Berowne, a witty courtier played by
Kenneth Branagh, who also directed ``Love's Labour's Lost,'' a
whimsical, affected adaptation of Shakespeare's most forgettable
early comedy. There is a great deal of dancing in the movie, which
invokes the name of Stanley Donen and boasts a score packed with
Broadway standards from Jerome Kern, Irving Berlin and the Gershwin
brothers, but not much special grace.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh has assembled a troupe of game, eager young stars,
including Matthew Lillard, the gangly creep show heartthrob from
the ``Scream'' pictures, and Alicia Silverstone, the Bel Air Jane
Austen heroine of ``Clueless,'' and sent them wobblingly forth to
belt out show tunes, declaim pentameter and assay the leaps and
twirls of Stuart Hopps' mercifully simplified choreography. He's
even seen fit to include an Esther Williams-style water ballet
sequence, complete with gold maillots and cabbage-leaf bathing
caps.
</P>
<P>
   If the cast were a sixth-grade class, and you were one of their
parents, you'd burst out of your seat applauding madly, and rush
backstage after the show, exclaiming: ``But you were wonderful!
Really, really great!'' And then you'd congratulate the drama
teacher (that would be the energetic English fellow with the blond
hair and theatrical demeanor), who's so creative, the school is
lucky to have him.
</P>
<P>
   As a paying customer, your reaction may be more subdued, but the
gee-whiz amateurism of this production is indubitably part of its
charm. Watching Adrian Lester, as Dumaine, trying a half-successful
split on a high wooden library table, you can only admire his
effort, and be glad that Branagh did not demand another take. When
Silverstone's voice skids and squeaks over the syllables of words
like ``perplexity'' and ``lamentation,'' you can't help but root
for her in her struggle with the the tongue-tying perplexities of
Elizabethan verse.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubting Branagh's sincere enthusiasm for the
material, which is not only Shakespeare but also old newsreels,
``Casablanca'' and classic MGM musicals. He throws them together
with the gusto of a man playing a tuba with a bass drum strapped to
his back while his pet monkey leaps around with a squeeze box. It's
not art exactly, or even music, but it's entertaining, albeit in an
intermittently annoying kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   For no particular reason, Branagh sets the play in a dreamy
Technicolor Europe on the eve of World War II. The King of Navarre
(Alessandro Nivola) has persuaded his three best pals to join him
in a vow of chastity, which is quickly tested by the arrival of the
French princess (Silverstone) and her three luscious
ladies-in-waiting. The mooning and swooning of the nobility is
mirrored by the bawdier amours of Don Armado (Timothy Spall) and
Jaquenetta (Stefania Rocca), whose cleavage inspires some of
Branagh's most inventive camera work.
</P>
<P>
   Spall, who looks like Peter Sellers inflated with a bicycle
pump, delivers his lines with hilarious pixilation. Nathan Lane, as
the clown Costard, provides another installment in his ongoing
salute to vaudeville. (I'm sure that the rubber chicken came from
his personal collection.) He also sings a slowed-down, wistful
rendition of ``There's No Business Like Show Business'' in top hat
and tails.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? Even though ``Love's Labour's Lost'' is, in
showbiz terms, a turkey stuffed with chestnuts, you wouldn't trade
it for a pot of gold. The film ends with a long, sweetly
melancholic sequence set to ``They Can't Take That Away From Me.''
Even after the song is ended, the melody lingers on, and you leave
the theater tipsy on Shakespeare's raillery and Ira Gershwin's wit,
as though you'd had a glass or two of cheap champagne. There are
worse ways to feel.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE'S LABOUR'S LOST'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kenneth Branagh; based on the play by Shakespeare,
adapted for the screen by Branagh; director of photography, Alex
Thomson; edited by Neil Farrell and Dan Farrell; music by Patrick
Doyle, with songs by George Gershwin, Cole Porter, Jerome Kern and
Irving Berlin; choreography by Stuart Hopps; production designer,
Tim Harvey; produced by David Barron and Branagh; released by
Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Kenneth Branagh (Berowne), Richard Briers (Nathaniel),
Richard Clifford (Boyet), Carmen Ejogo (Maria), Daniel Hill
(Mercade), Nathan Lane (Cstard), Adrian Lester (Dumaine), Matthew
Lillard (Longaville), Natascha McElhone (Rosaline), Geraldine
McEwan (Holofernia), Emily Mortimer (Katherine), Alessandro Nivola
(King), Anthony O'Donnell (Moth), Stefania Rocca (Jaquenetta),
Alicia Silverstone (Princess), Timothy Spall (Don Armado) and Jimmy
Yuill (Dull).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Labour's Lost'' is rated PG (parental guidance
suggested). It has one slightly naughty dance number and some
stylish old-movie cigarette smoking and cocktail drinking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EUROPE-TOURISM-0611-C     06-08 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TOURISM-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN TOURISTS FLOCK TO EUROPE AS VALUE OF THE EURO SLIPS
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (i) international, (l) lifestyles
and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 11
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON, Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALAIS, France _ Wandering a cavernous French mall, David
Botsford stops to study the polo shirts stacked on a table at the
entrance to a casual clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hundred francs _ how much is that?'' asks Botsford, the
president of an Atlanta marketing firm. He reads the sign saying
that he can buy two Celio sports shirts for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``About $30,'' answers his wife, Anita Sharpe, the co-founder of
an Internet media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' says Botsford, who steps into the shop to add to his
growing burden of bargains.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the same shirts would have cost him as much as $40
because the exchange rate then was less friendly to Americans
bearing dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Botsford is shopping at the massive new ``hypermarket'' built in
Calais to attract shoppers from Britain, who bring their cars on
the train through the Eurotunnel to load up on bargains on the
generally cheaper continent.
</P>
<P>
   The discounts are made even more appealing these days because of
the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the cheaper prices is the fall of the euro, the
currency of 11 European Union nations. It was launched in January
1999 at a value of $1.16, but since has lost about a quarter of its
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, the euro has hit a low of about 89
cents before recovering to about 96 cents this week. When the euro
falls, fewer U.S. dollars are needed to buy goods and services in
the euro zone, which
</P>
<P>
   includes Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Holland,
Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   National currencies such as the franc, mark and lira are still
in circulation, but the exchange rates are tied to the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Euro bank notes and coins are expected to enter circulation in
2002, gradually replacing national currencies.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of a weak euro is evident today. A hotel room in
the lovely Belgian tourist town of Brugge cost Botsford and Sharpe
the equivalent of $83 a night, compared to nearly $100 a year ago.
Dinner _ including two bottles of nice Pomerol wine _ for four
adults and two children cost about $20 less this year than it would
have cost last year.
</P>
<P>
   Botsford and his family travel to Europe only occasionally, so
they discovered their buying advantage only after arriving for
their vacation. However, the favorable rate was the main attraction
to many more frequent
</P>
<P>
   international travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Winston, an Oklahoma attorney, and his wife decided on a
trip to Paris in May after concluding France was a bargain they
couldn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about going to South America or Hawaii but we had
been looking at the rates and decided that, what the heck, when are
we going to get a better deal in Paris?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe never. The travel industry says that this is the best time
in more than a decade to get value for dollars in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Even though no one would ever accuse the French capital of being
a haven for budget travelers, the new rates have at least taken
some of the sting out of asking for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Winston's room at the Hotel Cayre St. Germain was $192 a night
this year, compared to about $220 last year. Dinner at Jacques
Cagna's restaurant in the Latin quarter cost $135 for two this year
compared to
</P>
<P>
   about $160 last year. For their 10-day visit in Paris, Winston
expects to save as much as $1,200. ``That's money we're going to
spend on wine and clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Because few Americans follow currency rates very closely, it is
unlikely they'll suddenly stampede Europe, said Neil Martin of the
European Travel Commission. ``But it may encourage them to stay
longer or to shop more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 12 million Americans will invade Europe this summer
_ a record for the eighth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Britain, which is rarely a bargain, is a better deal. The
pound is about 8 cents cheaper at $1.52 than it was a year ago.
Britain is a member of the European Union, but has elected not to
participate in the unified
</P>
<P>
   currency.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good deals, Botsford wondered briefly if the
exchange rate wasn't maybe a bit too good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchange rate was so good, I made the European shopkeepers
richer than I had planned to,'' Botsford said as he surveyed the
pile of shoes, shirts, wine, antique books, Belgian chocolates and
other goodies he
</P>
<P>
   and his wife bought in their shopping. ``Now I have to figure
out a way to get back to Atlanta with twice as much stuff as I
brought over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton can be e-mailed at: bertr(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
