<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8295 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r v BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX     06-08 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
June 9, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call
Carmelita Bevill, Lou Hudson or Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's
National/Foreign Desk at (817) 390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPERA HOUSE-TEXAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For 26 seasons, busloads of tourists have
flocked to the Granbury Opera House to see its Broadway-style
musicals and spend a few bucks on the historic courthouse square.
But the Granbury landmark, which helped transform the town into a
tourist attraction, is now in trouble. The opera house is about
$60,000 in debt, and, unless grants or corporate contributors are
found, its future is tenuous, says Marty Van Kleeck, managing
director of the opera house. By BILL HANNA. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P O L I T I C S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-BEN BARNES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He had the golden touch, the kind of talent,
many said, that might just land him in the White House one day.
Then, suddenly, it all ended. ``At 34, he toppled from the throne
to the political graveyard,'' said a 1972 Dallas Times Herald
editorial. ``Richard Nixon once came back from sound defeat, but no
one, at this point, can figure the future of the fallen young white
knight, Ben Barnes.'' Nearly three decades later, both Nixon and
the Times Herald are long gone. But Barnes, Texas' youngest
lieutenant governor at age 30, whose career in elective politics
was grounded by the 1971 Sharpstown scandal and his life rocked by
a 1987 personal bankruptcy, is again making his presence felt at
62. By JAY ROOT. Story has moved in ``p'' politics category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Answers to questions about how to obtain recordings by
1950s singer Herb Jeffries, where to obtain a leather belt with a
secret money pocket and how to write to Meg Ryan. By ROGERS
CADENHEAD. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T R A V E L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE RESURGENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Nashville _ it's not just for hillbillies anymore.
Music City has gotten downright sophisticated over the past few
years, embarking on a big cleanup and building program that
includes a new arena, a refurbished zoo, a new shopping mall akin
to the Mall of America, and new halls of fame for country music and
sports. And that doesn't take into consideration the city's lovely
parks, including one with a replica of the Parthenon, fine museums
and increasingly sophisticated restaurants. By JEFF GUINN. Story
has moved in ``t'' travel category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
