<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-IDIOTS-SPI &LR;      06-08 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IDIOTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDIOTS AS CONTRIVED AS ANY COMMERCIAL CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 OUR GRADE: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a bizarre commune/radical therapy workshop, middle class
rebel wannabes attempt to break through the soul deadening effects
of modern society by pretending to be retarded. They call this
regression ``spassing'' and supposedly it's a road toward something
primal, pure and authentic.
</P>
<P>
   They take this show on the road like guerrilla performance art,
using it to provoke their audience, to expose the phoniness of
society or simply to extort money from unsuspecting bystanders.
Into his happy band of idiots wanders Karen (Bodil Jorgensen), a
sad, shrinking woman who becomes their quiet but caring mother hen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots'' is Lars von Trier's (``Breaking the Waves'')
Dogma 95 entry. Dogma 95, if you haven't heard, is the Danish
manifesto supposed to save cinema from the contrivances of
commercial filmmaking via a rigorous set of conditions imposed on
its signatories. Von Trier either misses the point or doesn't
really care, for in ``The Idiots'' he turns the supposedly
liberating aesthetics of handheld camerawork, improvisational
performance and ``live'' filmmaking into something just as
contrived as the films he defies.
</P>
<P>
   The public performances are played as slapstick pageants, mining
easy laughs from the disturbed and uneasy reactions of their
hapless targets as if this reveals some flaw in them, and then the
director points his finger at the perpetrators for their
fraudulence. At the center is Stoffer (Jens Albinus), less a guru
than an angry new age tyrant happily manipulating his audiences and
his own drooling followers.
</P>
<P>
   The creepy and increasingly insensitive ``therapy,'' the copious
amounts of gratuitous nudity, and the in-your-face orgy are less
transgressive statements than sour moments of bald exploitation. In
the censored version released in stateside by USA Films, it's
ultimately ineffective: dancing black bars obscure copulation and
male genitalia (while leaving most female nudity alone _ but that's
our own American double standard). This post-production addition
was made with von Trier's approval to give this film an R rating _
as if this might play beyond the art-house circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the film, the two youngest members of the community
unleash bottled up feelings and express themselves through
``spassing'' in ways they never could through words, and in the
climax Karen spits out a speechless response to the life that has
nearly extinguished her soul. For those few minutes, the film
connects with its characters in a pure and honest (if a tad
overwrought) immediacy, but it's too little too late.
</P>
<P>
   Von Trier is far more hypocritical than his straw figure
characters, and for all his attempts to shock and affront the
audience he's simply too cynical and insincere to be provocative.
</P>
<P>
   The Idiots. Directed and written by Lars von Trier. Cast: Jens
Albinus, Bodil Jorgensen, Louise Hassing, Troels Lyby. USA Films.
115 minutes. Rated R for nudity and sex (with much of both obscured
by black bars). In Danish with English subtitles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUNSHINE-FILM-REVIEW-     06-08 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNSHINE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUNSHINE': SERVING THE EMPIRE, ONE AFTER ANOTHER AFTER ...  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   About half an hour into ``Sunshine,'' the first of three
characters played by Ralph Fiennes raises a glass to toast the
passage of time. ``Long live the 20th century!'' he cries, which
is, when you think about it, a profoundly illogical thing to say.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's entirely wrong: the century, or at least one
Hungarian Jewish family's experience of it, from the twilight of
empire to the fall of communism, is the subject of Istvan Szabo's
churning, sometimes clumsy, often thought-provoking _ and decidedly
long _ film. It follows in the footsteps of movies like Visconti's
``Leopard'' and Bertolucci's ``1900,'' epics that aspired to match
the sprawl and capaciousness of classic novels and to show, at once
panoramically and intimately, the process of historical change.
</P>
<P>
   This is never an easy thing to do, and Szabo, working from a
script he wrote with the American playwright Israel Horovitz,
attempts it with minimal subtlety, priming his enormous canvas with
big, cartoonish sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict this will be a century of love, justice and
tolerance,'' Fiennes' character, a rising star of the
Austro-Hungarian judicial system named Ignatz Sonnenschein,
declares after his toast. You don't need to know much about the
last hundred years _ just that they were characterized by an awful
lot of hatred, injustice and intolerance _ to grasp the irony. But
fortunately, and thanks largely to Fiennes, Jennifer Ehle and
Rosemary Harris, the film pulls away from such obviousness and
views the lethal unreason of the past hundred years with gravity,
humor and, most remarkably, with something like sanity.
</P>
<P>
   The first third of the film, which sprints from Ignatz's
19th-century childhood to his death in 1930, doesn't have much time
for nuance. Most of the action takes place at the Sonnenschein
dinner table, which stoically endures being pounded and stormed
away from during the passionate arguments that seem to erupt at
every meal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tsoris is caused by the smoldering passion between
Ignatz and his adopted sister Valerie (Ehle), who is really his
cousin and who will eventually be his wife (and then, since Fiennes
plays both their son and grandson, his mother and his grandmother).
When they aren't provoking family fights, Ignatz and Valerie steal
away for dreamy, heavy-breathing, soft-focus sex, followed by
earnest pillow talk. ``When I'm lying in your arms, I feel like
I've come home,'' Ignatz whispers. No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonnenschein household, overseen by plump, good-hearted
parents who migrated to Budapest from the countryside and made a
fortune selling an herbal elixir called Sunshine, is dominated by a
quasi-incestuous love triangle involving Valerie, Ignatz and his
younger brother Gustave. Their relationship is further complicated
by political differences that erupt, all of a sudden, in a scene of
speechifying melodrama shortly before the assassination of Archduke
Ferdinand. Gustave is a socialist, his brother a steadfast believer
in the empire's brand of liberal multiculturalism, while their
sister turns out to be a budding Hungarian nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   This scene, and many others in the film, is both underdeveloped
and overdone, as though Szabo, in his rush to interpret the history
of Central Europe, couldn't be bothered to dramatize it. The sets
are there _ the complacent bourgeois opulence of the Sonnenschein
apartments, the haughty grandeur of Budapest's cafes and
governmental palaces _ but he never slows down enough to capture
the texture and rhythm of daily life. For all the shouting and
panting, the Sonnenschein family story feels more like a collage of
ideas, events and metaphors than something lived.
</P>
<P>
   But it must be said that the ideas are interesting, the
metaphors occasionally inspired and some of the events
unforgettably powerful. Just as history, properly understood, is
more than just one darn thing after another, so ``Sunshine''
manages, as a whole, to transcend the crude melodrama of its
individual scenes. The stagy political shouting match on the eve of
World War I turns out to be the key to Szabo's understanding of the
20th century. He imagines socialism, nationalism and imperial
liberalism as siblings, born out of an essentially decent,
meliorist 19th-century impulse, and all vulnerable to horrifying
moral corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Several of this Hungarian director's earlier films _ notably
``Mephisto'' (1981) and ``Colonel Redl'' (1985) _ dealt with the
exemplary modern agonies, especially acute in Central Europe in the
middle decades of the 20th century, of decent men driven to
compromise with evil. ``Sunshine'' is a triptych of such stories,
each one displaying Fiennes, with different facial hair and altered
ideological coloration, caught in the pincers of history.
</P>
<P>
   Small compromises lead to big disasters: Ignatz, anxious to
advance his career, changes the family name from Sonnenschein to
the more Hungarian-sounding Sors. His son Adam converts to
Christianity to gain admittance to Budapest's most exclusive
fencing club. He becomes the national fencing champion and leads
his team to the 1936 Olympics but succumbs to the temptations of
snobbery, anti-Semitism and acquiescence to dictatorship. As it
follows Adam's rise and fall, the film begins to breathe a little
more, and Fiennes comes out of himself, acting with the fierce
insouciance that is his best, and often neglected, attribute.
</P>
<P>
   In the next generation Fiennes' flair turns into rage, as he
portrays Adam's son Ivan, who becomes, after World War II, a member
of the Communist secret police out of blind, vengeful rage at the
fascists who destroyed his family. The contours of Hungarian
history from 1939 to 1956, when Soviet tanks crushed an incipient
revolution, is well known, but I'll refrain from revealing the
particulars of the Sors-Sonnenschein family saga.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ivan confronts his own crisis of conscience, the
movie has accumulated sufficient power and momentum to erase the
memory of its earlier awkwardness. It shows such sympathy for its
characters, and approaches its subject with such intelligence, that
it's easy to forgive the clumsy editing, the haphazard insertion of
black-and-white newsreels, and the hyperventilating sexual ardor
that seems to be a Sors family curse.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of it all, the film leaves you with a sense of quiet,
chastened grace, as embodied by the older Valerie, played by
Harris, who is Ehle's real-life mother (the two actresses might
share an Oscar, just as Fiennes might have to compete against
himself). ``She was the only one of us who had the gift of
breathing freely,'' her troubled grandson remarks, and
``Sunshine,'' at last, honors that gift.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SUNSHINE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Istvan Szabo; written by Szabo and Israel Horovitz;
director of photography, Lajos Koltai; music by Maurice Jarre;
produced by Robert Lantos and Andras Hamori; released by Paramount
Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ralph Fiennes (Ignatz Sonnenschein/Adam Sors/Ivan Sors),
Jennifer Ehle (Valerie Sonnenschein), Rosemary Harris (Valerie
Sors), James Frain (Gustave Sonnenschein), John Neville (Gustave
Sors) and William Hurt (Andor Knorr). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 180 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunshine'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has a number of feverish sex scenes, a
scattering of strong language and a horrific depiction of torture
and murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CAPSULES0609-CO     06-08 2034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CAPSULES0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short reviews of selected films
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen and Jim Luksic
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   A _ Excellent
</P>
<P>
   B _ Good
</P>
<P>
   C _ Fair
</P>
<P>
   D _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   F _ Abysmal
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  _Not reviewed
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House''
</P>
<P>
   A cross between ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and ``Kindergarten Cop,''
this enormously broad comedy casts Martin Lawrence as an FBI agent
who goes undercover as a cantankerous Southern granny. The
unoriginal romantic comedy also borrows from ``Tootsie'' and
``Jerry Maguire,'' though it lacks their humor and heart. Directed
by Raja Gosnell (''Never Been Kissed''), the nonsensical farce is
little more than a string of forced situations and crude gags.
Crude humor, sexual innuendo, profanity and some violence; 13 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Center Stage''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Hytner's Big-Apple ballet for teen-age girls,
highlighted by dancer Ethan Stiefel's presence, contains as much
soap-opera conflict as it does bruised feet. A tender romance
involving a premed student and earnest performances are
overshadowed by more cheese and ham than can be found in a New York
deli. Profanity, sexuality, mature themes; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's prehistoric adventure is the first film to combine
computer-animated characters with live-action backgrounds, putting
personified dinosaurs in photo-realistic settings. The visual
result is astonishing, but the story isn't anything you haven't
seen before. The simplistic tale of an iguanodon raised by lemurs
borrows elements from ``Bambi,'' ``Tarzan'' and ``The Lion King.''
Several intense scenes may be too frightening for small children.
Intense images; 6 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas''
</P>
<P>
   This prequel to the critically panned 1994 live-action version
of the popular '60s cartoon is a lame chip off the ol' block. More
effort went into the colorful costumes and sets than into the
story, which finds young Fred vying for the affection of wealthy
heiress Wilma. Much of the humor is of the juvenile
pie-in-the-face, spit-take variety. Despite game performances,
especially Stephen Baldwin as Barney, ``Flintstones'' is hardly a
gay old time. Innuendo and brief profanity; 8 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency''
</P>
<P>
   This sci-fi thriller's premise about a young man who
communicates with his late father via ham radio is easy to buy
until the final 10 minutes. Then the gripping and emotional story
turns rote and sentimental, succumbing to fatal loopholes in its
time-shifting logic. Director Gregory Hoblit's tight cutting
between climactic events in different decades is hard to follow.
The crowd-pleasing finale is full of holes, once you stop to think
about it. Intense violence and disturbing images; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley Scott's thrilling return to Hollywood historical epics is
a bloody, visceral adventure. As with ``Alien `` and ``Blade
Runner,'' Scott creates a convincing, richly detailed world. There
is much gory combat, depicted in hyper-realistic style. There is
also a star-making turn by Russell Crowe. Yet the deft tale of
heroism and intrigue is remarkably somber. The truly gripping
emotional drama doesn't arrive until the 154-minute film's second
half. Intense, graphic combat; 15 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gossip''
</P>
<P>
   This absurd suspense thriller about the havoc wreaked by a rumor
is the directorial debut of Davis Guggenheim (''ER''), yet the film
has all the hallmarks of executive producer Joel Schumacher, in
that it's overly stylized and heavily contrived. The far-fetched
melodrama piles one ludicrous plot twist upon another, stretching
the slight premise beyond all believability. The screenplay is
sketchy. The characters are spiteful, dumb or both. Sexual content
and language, brief violence; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping The Faith''
</P>
<P>
   Few would have expected intense young actor Edward Norton's
directorial debut to be a screwball romantic comedy. The
lighthearted tale involves a priest (Norton) and a rabbi (Ben
Stiller) who both fall in love with the same woman (Jenna Elfman).
Though it's too long at 129 minutes _ an eternity for a comedy _
``Keeping the Faith'' is a sweet, funny film that is heavy on
slapstick and sight gags. There are lots of chuckles and some solid
laughs. Some sexuality and profanity; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thomas Anderson's ambitious follow-up to ``Boogie Nights''
is a riveting family drama that has the epic scope of a grand
opera, encompassing a dozen major characters and nine
interdependent plot lines. The visually dazzling film addresses the
role of chance in life, and it marks Anderson as the most audacious
director of his generation. However, some viewers may find it
difficult to endure. (1/7) Strong profanity, drug use, sexuality,
some violence; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2''
</P>
<P>
   This sequel to the befuddling 1996 blockbuster plays like a
James Bond film without the wit or charm. After a brisk start, the
story settles into a long period of sluggish exposition in which
bland hero Ethan Hunt's (Tom Cruise) personal feelings complicate
his otherwise simple mission. The balletic action for which
director John Woo is known doesn't arrive until the final 40
minutes, and the far-fetched stunt sequences are impossible to
swallow. Intense sequences of violent action, some sensuality; 13
and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Morris' best-selling memoir about his childhood canine
gets a sugary coating from director Jay Russell, whose well-meaning
adaptation slathers on warm photography and a patriotic score. A
nostalgic, innocuous slice of 1940s Mississippi, made digestible by
young star Frankie Muniz. Mild profanity, fleeting violence; 8 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games''
</P>
<P>
   Originally slated for release on Christmas, when its holiday
setting would have made a lot more sense, this preposterous
thriller stars Ben Affleck as a clueless ex-convict forced to
mastermind a casino robbery. The ridiculous story is as hard to
swallow as 2-month-old eggnog. It's all just buildup for the
explosive and extremely bloody heist sequence, in which the robbers
shoot it out wearing Santa Claus costumes. Strong violence,
profanity, sexuality; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return To Me''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hunt's amusing directorial debut turns on a convenient
twist of fate. A widower (David Duchovny) falls in love with a
waitress (Minnie Driver), unaware that she has received his late
wife's transplanted heart. The contrived premise could only happen
in the movies. Hunt's sweet, simplistic romantic comedy is
predictable but entertaining. Its whimsical blend of humor and
drama is carried by snappy dialogue and an appealing cast.
Profanity, mature themes; 10 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Trip''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian comic Tom Green ignites this ``American Pie''-style
tale involving a college student who, with three classmates,
ventures south to block the delivery of a videotape he
inadvertently sent to his Austin, Texas-based girlfriend. It's a
raunchy, sometimes funny, mostly ludicrous romp that you might
expect from the director of ``Frat House.'' Profanity, sexuality,
nudity, fleeting violence; 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo Must Die''
</P>
<P>
   Wherefore art thou, Romeo? Chained and suspended upside-down by
one leg from a rope in a Hong Kong prison cell, where he
impressively overpowers four armed guards to make a thrilling
escape. It's not Shakespeare, but the hip-hop action movie, which
marks Chinese martial-arts star Jet Li's first starring role in
English, is a major kick. Despite its title, the kinetic
crowd-pleaser is focused on supercharged action, not romance.
Violence, some profanity, brief nudity; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules Of Engagement''
</P>
<P>
   This military drama, about a Marine officer (Samuel L. Jackson)
who is court-martialed for allegedly breaking the rules of
engagement during a siege of a U.S. embassy in Yemen, is as full of
holes as the bullet-riddled embassy. Executive producer James Webb
reportedly removed his screenwriting credit from the film over
changes that were made to his script. The obvious, slow-moving and
illogical film is major hooey. War violence, profanity; 16 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Screwed''
</P>
<P>
   This painfully unfunny farce stars Norm MacDonald as a
much-abused chauffeur who gets even with his cheap, nasty employer
by kidnapping her prized pooch and ransoming it for $1 million. The
slapstick comedy of errors is intended to be in the zany tradition
of the Marx Brothers' movies, but there's little connection. The
humor is crude and mean-spirited. The sight gags are disgusting and
bloody. Crude and sex-related humor, nudity, profanity and some
violence; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Noon''
</P>
<P>
   Asian action star Jackie Chan turns cowboy in this
cross-cultural action comedy, set in the Old West. The highly
entertaining, East-meets-West mix of martial arts and punch lines
is unabashedly silly, but it's also hilarious. The film draws big
laughs from cultural-barrier gags, as well as from skewering
Western movie cliches. Chan has terrific chemistry with comic
sidekick Owen Wilson, who delivers a breakthrough performance.
Action violence, some drug humor, profanity and sensuality; 12 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skulls''
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to be a bonehead not to have ``The Skulls'' figured
out in a matter of minutes. The teen thriller has an enticing
premise about secret societies at Ivy League colleges, where future
leaders are molded, but there's never any secret where its story is
heading. The paranoid conspiracy thriller plays like a bush-league
version of The Firm, becoming increasingly ridiculous. Violence,
brief sexuality; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks''
</P>
<P>
   This modestly amusing farce about bumbling would-be bank robbers
appears to be inspired by ``The Honeymooners,'' with diminutive
writer-director Woody Allen in the Ralph Kramden role. Touted as a
return to the slapstick style of his early films, the surprisingly
lowbrow effort offers a few chuckles but no big laughs. The
eccentric characters are tiresome, and the erratic rags-to-riches
story is as tedious as endless sitcom reruns. Profanity; 10 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571''
</P>
<P>
   This rousing World War II submarine adventure about a Navy
mission to capture a Nazi coding device delivers almost nonstop
action. However, you won't need the ``Enigma'' machine to decipher
the film's story. The characters and conflicts are established in
fast, broad strokes. Heavy foreshadowing lays the foundation for
the predictable but exciting climax. Though the course is simply
plotted, ``U-571'' is a fairly thrilling adventure. War violence;
13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin Suicides''
</P>
<P>
   The impressive feature directorial debut of Sofia Coppola,
daughter of Francis Ford Coppola, is a darkly amusing and deeply
poignant look at five troubled teen sisters in 1970s Michigan. The
engrossing story of the beautiful but doomed Lisbon girls unfolds
in flashback, narrated by a now-adult neighborhood boy who was one
of several obsessed with the sisters. Coppola's approach is assured
and heartfelt, but her scripting is uneven. Strong thematic
elements involving teens; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever It Takes''
</P>
<P>
   The title says it all, as this teen-targeting romantic comedy
attempts to modernize Cyrano de Bergerac with a parade of unlikely
circumstances, sexual innuendo and hackneyed byplay. David Raynr
directs with good-hearted intention, but he negates it with corny
cliches and a finale that's crazier than the dickens. Profanity,
sexuality; 14 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where The Heart Is''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams' Southern-fried soap opera, starring Natalie
Portman as a pregnant 17-year-old abandoned by her beau, alternates
between daffiness and overzealous heart-tugging. Among those
befriending the teen, we get compelling turns from Stockard
Channing and James Frain, but hot air from Ashley Judd's unwed
player, who, despite giving birth to four kids (and counting) looks
unblemished and fit as a fiddle. Profanity, sexuality, mature
themes; 14 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
