u e BC-MOVIES-CARTHEFTS0609-     06-08 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CARTHEFTS0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `60 Seconds' a hot-wired thrill ride
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stealing 50 premium automobiles in 72 hours.
It sounds like the latest television game-show stunt, but instead
it is the action-heavy high concept for a glossy summer caper
picture from producer Jerry Bruckheimer (''The Rock,''
``Armageddon''). Set the stopwatch, jimmy the locks, clip the alarm
cords, jump-start the engine, and away we go.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' a remake of a relatively unheralded
1974 flick, goosed up with an A-list cast and some terrific stunt
driving, as well as a completely superfluous explanation of why
former master car booster Memphis Raines (Nicolas Cage) would be
snapped back into a life of grand theft larceny. We don't really
care about Raines' conflicted emotions, just get on with the
thievery already.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is fully an hour into ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' with
48 hours elapsed in the plot, before Raines and his accomplices
swipe the first car on his hit list. Before that, he broods over
whether to risk his new, law-abiding way of life to save his
screw-up younger brother, Kip, from certain death. Yeah, right,
like Raines is going to weigh his options, decide not to steal the
cars and the movie will end with a message about not breaking the
law. How would that get teenage boys to shell out their lawn-mowing
money?
</P>
<P>
   We all know where the movie is going and that it has to lead to
a precision-slick crime spree, which we'll be rooting for all the
way. But first, director Dominic Sena (''Kalifornia'') and
screenwriter Scott Rosenberg (''Con Air'') want us to care about
Raines and his Jean Valjean/Javert rivalry with tenacious police
detective Roland Castelbeck (Delroy Lindo). And to bite our nails
wondering whethera team of retired car thieves, led by Sara
``Sway'' Wayland (big-lipped Angelina Jolie, with
pseudo-dreadlocked blonde hair), will be reeled back in for Kip's
sake.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that when the car pilfering begins, it is
captured with such style and verve that it negates all the
foot-dragging. Candy-colored Corvettes, sturdy Mercedes-Benzes,
sleek Porsches and one particularly macho Mustang GT 500 are among
the quarry, all stolen in one night in a true ``Mission:
Impossible,'' right down to the fake fingerprints applied to avoid
any incriminating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there is a fair amount of humor, as when a mangy,
iron-deficient dog swallows some high-tech car keys, is fed a
laxative and then has to be walked about until they travel through
his system. And we learn valuable information, like a car's vanity
plate ``SNAKE'' may not describe its owner but its cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, obtaining the required 50 stolen cars comes down to
Cage racing the clock and the cops in the Mustang, maneuvering
through the streets of Los Angeles, across the L.A. River basin and
onto the docks of Long Beach in a dizzyingly entertaining
high-speed chase, climaxed by a good ol' ``Dukes of Hazzard'' jump
to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Cage, who may never escape the action-adventure beat and get
back to acting, plays Raines with a single sullen expression and
attitude. Lindo throws in a bit more nuance as the cop who
begrudgingly shows his admiration for his worthy adversary. Robert
Duvall is his usual welcome wily self as Cage's mentor. In the only
female role of any consequence, Jolie gets her fingernails dirty
and has a near sexual encounter with Cage in a parked car but is
otherwise underutilized. So often after winning an Oscar (as Jolie
did for ``Girl, Interrupted''), an actor's next released movie is a
throwaway performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' however, is a high-performance vehicle.
It merely wants to put us in the driver's seat of some action
thrills, and that it delivers. The first hour could stand to be
edited down, but as summer movies go, this is an entertaining joy
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
