<SLUG> BC-PROCTER-GAMBLE-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE CEO STEPS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Prices in last two grafs do not reflect market close)  
 By TIM ARANGO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Durk Jager, the 56-year-old chairman, president and chief
executive of consumer products giant Procter &AMP; Gamble (PG:NYSE),
will step down, effective immediately, the company announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Lafley, a 23-year P&AMP;G veteran and of late the president of
the company's global beauty care division, was named the new CEO.
Former P&AMP;G CEO John Pepper will return from retirement to become
chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup comes at a time of disappointing earnings for P&AMP;G,
which has failed to meet analysts' expectations for six of the last
eight quarters, according to Andrew Shore, an analyst at Deutsche
Banc Alex Brown. While the company characterized Jager's departure
as voluntary retirement, Shore said the writing was on the wall.
``And like a good Japanese soldier, he probably fell on his
sword,'' Shore said. ``Someone had to take the fall.'' Shore has a
neutral rating on P&AMP;G, and his firm has not performed underwriting
on behalf of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with the media and analysts, the company,
the maker of such ubiquitous consumer products as Crest toothpaste,
Pringles potato chips and Folgers coffee, announced the move at the
same time it warned Wall Street that its earnings will fall short
of forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had too much change, too fast,'' Lafley said. He said
P&AMP;G has ignored its core businesses -- such as fabrics and home
care -- while trying to expand into new areas. Lafley said P&AMP;G
scattered its spending across too many new products this year, and
plans to review the company's businesses over the next six weeks to
focus its resources on its core businesses and best new products.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it adopted more ambitious forecasting models,
Lafley said. ``We are going to have appropriate conservatism in our
plans to ensure we meet or beat our commitments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings-per-share growth will be flat for the current quarter,
he said. Previously, the company had forecast 15 percent to 17
percent earnings-per-share growth. This reflects lower volume
growth in fabric and home care, which will be in the low single
digits, according to Lafley. He said the company did a poor job of
marketing its products, and has developed a new ad program to
``target the consumer more sharply.''
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session with analysts, P&AMP;G Chief
Financial Officer Clayton Daley said a divestiture of some of the
company's businesses is possible, but did not say specifically
which ones.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight quarter in which the Cincinnati,
Ohio-based company has been forced to announce that it would not
meet its volume targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not caught off guard,'' said William Steele, an
analyst who covers P&AMP;G for BofA Montgomery in San Francisco. He
said he never expected P&AMP;G to hit its 15 percent EPS prediction.
Steele has a market performer rating for P&AMP;G -- his firm has done
no underwriting -- and he doesn't expect to alter his
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   To assuage investors' fears that other consumer products
companies could similarly disappoint investors, Kimberly-Clark
(KMB:NYSE), maker of Kleenex, Pull-Ups and Huggies, announced that
it was on track with its earnings projections, according to Mike
Masseth, head of investor relations at the Dallas,based company.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble shares were down 5 3/8, or 9 percent, to 56 1/2
in afternoon trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly-Clark shares were trading down 7/16, or 1 percent, at
58 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
