<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE AIMED AT ROWDY MALE TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 OUR GRADE: C-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest over-produced, under-written summer action
extravaganza from producer Jerry Bruckheimer, ``Gone in 60
Seconds,'' is a movie that tries _ and mostly fails _ to make a
motley ring of Long Beach car thieves look exciting and glamorous
and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Plotwise, it's a fairly accurate remake of a 1974 drive-in
exploitation movie that has retained a minor cult following among
action fans for its nicely executed 40-minute car chase _ still an
industry record _ and the fact that its director-star, H.B.
Halicki, was killed in the process of making it.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the Bruckheimer tradition of ``Con Air,'' ``The Rock''
and ``Armageddon,'' this retread has been bloated far beyond its
B-movie origins, beefed up with more characters and an all-star
cast, stripped of any real suspense and loaded down with music cuts
and one-liners aimed at pleasing a crowd of rowdy male teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Its hero is ``Memphis'' Raines (Nicolas Cage), the now-retired
and gone-straight king of the California car thieves who, to save
the life of his younger brother (Giovanni Ribisi), is pressed into
the service of a loathsome gangster for a near-impossible task:
stealing 50 luxury cars in one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Without too much hesitation or soul-searching, he gathers up his
former team of thieves, now all retired and honest citizens _
including his aging mentor (Robert Duvall), ex-girlfriend (Angelina
Jolie) and sidekick comic relief (Chi McBribe) _ and gets down to
business.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it's all screeching tires, revving engines and
crunching metal as he struggles to meet his deadline (with an
annoying on-screen clock occasionally appearing to count down the
time for us) while a dedicated and endlessly frustrated Long Beach
police detective (Delroy Lindo) remains hot on his trail.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully selected teenage audience at the Seattle preview
earlier this week seemed to eat the movie up, howling at every gag
and cheering wildly at every bent fender. Car buffs will also enjoy
the film's numerous references to car culture and an ongoing
classic-car trivia game played by the thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else is likely to find this movie surprisingly
unexciting. The characterizations are broad and clumsy, the
character motivations are so slight the film has zero narrative
interest, and the car chases staged by novice feature director (but
rock video veteran) Dominic Sena display no particular originality
or imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer has obviously paid some big salaries, but his cast
is lackluster and the film serves as an even worse star vehicle.
Cage's sanctimonious character is absurd and dull, Duvall walks
through his role on automatic pilot and Jolie just stands around
with a matted hairdo that makes her look amazingly like John
Travolta in ``Battlefield Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone in 60 Seconds. Directed by Dominic Sena. Screenplay by
Scott Rosenberg. Cast: Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi, Angelina
Jolie, Robert Duvall, Delroy Lindo, Christopher Eccelston.
Touchstone. 119 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
