u w BC-MIGRAINE09-COX     06-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGRAINE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIGRAINES BETTER UNDERSTOOD BUT STILL GO UNTREATED
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Researchers are rapidly learning to understand the
causes of migraines, but millions of victims fail to receive new
drugs that can reduce the frequency and severity of these painful
headaches, experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 28 million Americans who suffer from migraines,
between 5 and 6 million experience an average of three days of
disability per month, said Dr. Richard B. Lipton, a professor of
neurology at Albert Einstein Medical School in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Those people could benefit from a new class of drugs that can
prevent most migraine attacks, said Dr. Lipton. Yet only about 1
million actually take the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A second class of prescription drugs provides relief from pain
and other effects of the headaches, but most migraine sufferers do
not take these drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lipton is among a small group of neurologists from medical
schools around the country attending a government-sponsored
conference here this week to develop ``educational materials'' to
help primary care physicians better deal with migraines.
</P>
<P>
   He said a recent survey by the World Health Organization
concluded that an active migraine headache is one of the four most
disabling conditions known, along with severe psychosis, dementia
and quadriplegia, being paralyzed from the neck down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite very striking advances in migraine treatment in recent
years, the majority of migraine suffers in the United States
continue to treat their headaches with over-the-counter medications
to the exclusion of prescription drugs,'' Lipton said. ``A large
segment of migraine sufferers who experience high levels of pain
would benefit from these treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, sponsored by the National Institute of
Neurological Disorders and Stroke and several professional
societies, was being attended by around 25 researchers, said an
institute spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose was to create brochures, CD-ROMs and other
``educational materials'' for doctors, she said. The cost of the
conference was underwritten by a drug company.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lipton was among conferees who spoke with reporters about
new understanding and treatment of migraine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Welch of the University of Kansas Medical Center in
Kansas City said the development of noninvasive imaging equipment
has allowed scientists to observe the brains of migraine sufferers
during an attack and led to a revolution in understanding of the
condition in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Bright light might be a migraine trigger, he said, and a
migraine sufferer may have a variable ``threshold'' of
susceptibility to the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threshold gets too low and along comes a trigger,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most migraines begin with a ``wave'' of neuro-electrical
activity that starts at the base of the brain and moves over the
top, he said. During this process, researchers have observed the
upper part of the brain sending ``messages'' to pain centers deep
inside, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, blood flow goes up, then drops rapidly in the
wake of the brain electrical ``wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, neurology researchers have realized that the
brains of persons who suffer from frequent migraines are being
changed, perhaps damaged, by the headaches themselves. Many develop
constant headache, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.ama-assn.org/special/migraine/migraine.htm
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's email address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
