<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-STAY-STREET     06-08 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-STAY-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REQUESTS STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day after a federal judge ordered Microsoft (MSFT:Nasdaq)
split in two and restrictions placed on its business practices, the
software company requested a stay of the ruling Thursday and
prosecutors vowed to hurry the coming appeal along to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a Washington, D.C. news conference, Joel Klein, the
Justice Department's antitrust chief, predicted that the case could
end by early 2001 if the nation's highest court grants a review in
its next term. Otherwise, the court would remand the case to the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. A panel of
judges on that ideologically mixed appellate court overturned a
prior ruling adverse to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they prepared to move their war along to the next
battlefield, prosecutors and corporate officials made a pointed
effort to find common ground and leave the light on above the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, reaction to the historic but long-anticipated
judgment was muted. Microsoft's shares were trading down 1 1/8, or
2 percent, at 69 3/8 in Thursday afternoon trading, actually
marking an unusually stable day for the Redmond, Wash.-based
company's stock price as an unremarkable 36 million shares traded
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides expressed hope that the Supreme Court would expedite
the appeals process and said that they would prefer a settlement.
But neither showed signs of willingness to bend on the contentious
issue of breaking up the company. And the parties clashed over
staying the so-called conduct remedies, which consist mostly of
restrictions on Microsoft's interactions with computer and software
makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final judgment, which Microsoft intends to appeal
promptly, will inflict grievous and irreparable harm on Microsoft,
its 35,000 employees, its millions of shareholders, its thousands
of business partners, and the tens of millions of consumers around
the world who rely on Microsoft's products,'' the company wrote in
documents requesting a stay, which it filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing portions of the ruling by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson,
Klein said a stay on the restrictions to Microsoft's business
practices should be denied. He said the company's practices could
cause additional and irreparable harm, citing the dynamic nature of
the software business and calling the proposed remedies
``straightforward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should put those remedies in place, but it's very important
to get a final ruling before the United States Supreme Court,''
Klein said. Referring to William H. Gates, the company's chairman,
he continued: ``And I was quite pleased last night listening to Mr.
Gates, that he would like an expedited ruling as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jackson's recent attempts to pick up the pace of the
trial, which he has said are partially motivated by a desire to
allow appeals to begin, the time required for appeals is not known.
Provisions specific to antitrust law give the solicitor general,
and not the Justice Department's antitrust division, 15 days to
request that the Supreme Court immediately review the company's
appeal. (U.S. Solicitor General Walter Dellinger, an agent of the
Justice Department, is charged with arguing the government's cases
before the Supreme Court.) That would allow the government to
leapfrog the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said that after Microsoft's appeal is filed, ``we'' will
file a motion in federal district court requesting direct review by
the Supreme Court. Jackson must certify that motion, Klein said.
Though the company said in a court filing that it will appeal
``promptly,'' the judge has set no deadline for either party's next
logical filing.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said he was unsure but thought the act allowing the
solicitor general to ask for direct high court review of antitrust
cases has only been used twice, both times in the government's
antitrust case against AT&AMP;T (T:NYSE), which resulted in a breakup.
Since the creation of the act, only the Microsoft and AT&AMP;T cases
have ended in structural remedies.
</P>
<P>
   In response to reporters' queries, Klein also expressed
confidence that the government will pursue Microsoft after the
change of executive administrations. He noted that the AT&AMP;T case
was filed during the Republican Nixon administration, prosecuted
during the Democratic Carter administration and settled during the
Republican Reagan administration despite vocal opposition to a
breakup being expressed by President Reagan's secretaries of
Commerce and Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Klein also said a settlement is the ``preferred course.''
Settlement negotiations in the case fell through April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the interest of the industry, it's in the interest of
the company and it's in the national interest to have Microsoft
address, in a meaningful way, the competitive issues that animated
the case and that the court found, and for people to go about their
business, rather than to have a protracted legal proceeding,'' he
said. He declined to elaborate on whether the Justice Department
would accept any sort of settlement that does not include a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The company was far more clear about its position on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is willing to consider any proposal that would
protect two core principles -- our freedom to innovate and the
integrity of our products,'' said Jim Cullinan, a company
spokesman. ``We will not consider breaking up the company because
it would not protect these principles and would cause significant
harm to Microsoft, our employees, the high-tech industry and
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Miller, the Iowa attorney general and head of the group of
state attorneys general that joined the Justice Department in
requesting a breakup, said, ``The states are always willing to
enter into serious negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Klein seemed to play down the stature of his litigation
partners, who held up a previous settlement by failing to reach a
consensus on whether to demand a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Gates ``seemed concerned that, because of the states' case, that
that would somehow prevent (the appeal) from going to the Supreme
Court,'' Klein said. ``But I can assure you that that would be no
prohibition whatsoever; the state case is consolidated with ours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And in any event, of course, if the Supreme Court were to rule
on our case, it would be the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled Wednesday that Microsoft should be split into two
separate companies to remedy antitrust violations and foster
competition in the markets for computer operating systems and
software applications.
</P>
<P>
   In harsh, scolding and distrustful language, Jackson conceded
that his judgment would anger the company's supporters, called his
own ruling worthy of appeal and said the company's arrogance left
him no choice but to throw a roadblock at Microsoft in the form of
a rushed judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup, the linchpin of the ruling, would place the
ubiquitous Windows operating system in one company and create a
second business for everything else, including software
applications, the Internet Explorer Web browser and the Microsoft
Network Internet service provider and network of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The behavioral remedies take effect within 90 days of a ruling.
These remedies include publishing the so-called source code used by
programmers to design software applications for Windows and placing
guidelines on Microsoft's relations with both computer makers and
other software companies.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
