<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, June 9. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-TERROR (Athens, Greece) _ Britain's defense attache to
Greece was shot dead in the middle of Athens on Thursday in an
attack police said bore all the hallmarks of the shadowy Marxist
guerrilla organization, November 17. The killing, which British
Prime Minister Tony Blair described as ``a contemptible act of
terrorism,'' brought renewed pressure on Greece to clamp down on
rogue terrorist cells before 2004 when Athens is due to host the
Olympic Games. (Summary from wires) By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-DEATHS (United Nations) _ A leading refugee agency said
Thursday that at least 1.7 million people in eastern Congo have
died since August 1998 _ far above the already high expected
mortality of 600,000 for the region. A third of those who died
because of war and poor medical facilities were children under 5.
About 18 million people live in eastern Congo, where Rwanda and
Uganda are supporting a revolution against the government of
President Laurent Kabila. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin on Thursday
moved to put rebel Chechnya under his direct rule, apparently
aiming to assert the Kremlin's power even as rebels step up bold
attacks on Russian forces. In a decree that still must be approved
by parliament, Putin placed the civil administration in Chechnya
directly under his control. He said the move was aimed at
``protecting the constitutional order'' in Chechnya and creating
conditions to restore its government, economy and society. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FINANCE (Washington) _ The Senate is likely later
Thursday to defeat an effort by Sen. John McCain to require
disclosures by tax-exempt groups that secretly raise and spend
unlimited sums on political activities to influence the outcome of
elections. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENT-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Senate plans to vote Thursday
on a proposal, strongly supported by President Clinton, to define a
wide range of new rights for patients. The proposal is likely to be
defeated, but Democrats hope the exercise will help them make some
important political points in this election year. By Lizette
Alvarez and Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-PRISONERS (Dallas, Texas) _ Efforts are growing in state
legislatures and in Congress to help inmates overcome the serious
obstacles they face in obtaining DNA evidence that can prove their
innocence. But those plans are running into continued reluctance by
prosecutors and others to expand the rights of criminal defendants
and further delay what they describe as a slow-moving appeals
process. The proposals to expand DNA testing have been boosted by a
rash of publicized cases lately where prisoners have been set free,
as well as support for tests from a number of death penalty
proponents, including Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. By Richard A.
Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INSECTICIDE (Undated) _ Citing an unacceptable health risk,
particularly to children, federal environmental officials on
Thursday announced that by the end of the year one of the most
common ingredients in home, lawn, and garden bug killers,
chlorpyrifos, would no longer be manufactured for these uses. The
insecticide, also called Dursban, has been widely used for more
than 30 years both in agriculture and in products sprayed by
exterminators and homeowners, including such common items as more
than a dozen kinds of Raid sprays, some Hartz flea collars, and
Black Flag liquid roach and ant killer. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-POLITICS (Washington) _ In addition to its expensive
public lobbying efforts, Microsoft is waging an ambitious and
largely subterranean campaign to turn public and political opinion
against the government's antitrust action. The company, operating
through two ostensibly independent trade associations and their
Internet sites, a grassroots political organizing firm and a media
and public relations company, is attempting to foment support for
its precarious legal position. It is also trying to neutralize a
sophisticated and well-funded effort by its competitors to support
the government's case and turn public opinion against Microsoft. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Undated) _ A reconstruction of the Microsoft
antitrust trial and the evolving views of its judge, Thomas
Penfield Jackson. By Steve Lohr and Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS-BENEFITS (Detroit) _ General Motors, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler division announced Thursday that they
would begin offering medical, dental and prescription drug benefits
for same-sex partners of their 466,000 hourly and salaried
employees in the United States, the largest move yet by corporate
America to provide such benefits for gay and lesbian couples. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   PROCTER-RESIGN (Undated) _ The chief executive of Procter &AMP;
Gamble, the nation's largest consumer products company, resigned
Thursday as the company announced it would suffer another
disappointing quarter and its stock price fell to less than half of
what it was worth just four months ago. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
