<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR TOPS ESTIMATES BY 6 CENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Price in last graf does not reflect market close)  
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Semiconductor (NSM:NYSE), developer of the next
generation system-on-a-chip microchip, surpassed expectations by 6
cents, aided by strong analog and wireless sales.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter ended May 28, the company reported net
earnings, excluding gains, of $134.2 million, or 68 cents a diluted
share, compared to a loss of $40 million, or 24 cents a share, a
year earlier. The consensus estimate of analysts polled by First
Call/Thomson Financial was 62 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Including gains, National Semiconductor, based in Santa Clara,
Calif., reported net earnings of $153.9 million, or 78 cents a
diluted share, compared to a loss of $783.5 million, or $4.65 a
share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The gains amounted to $19.7 million related to an overestimation
of restructuring costs for the disposal of Fairchild Semiconductor
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales rose to $595.3 million from $486 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A ``focus on execution drove our gross margins to 51 percent, up
from 48 percent in the previous quarter,'' said Brian Halla,
chairman, president and chief executive of National Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor makes analog, digital and mixed-signal (a
combination of analog and digital) integrated circuits that are
used in communications devices, networking equipment and
automobiles. The next generation microchip, system-on-a-chip,
combines a microprocessor and logic and memory components in one
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company were down 1/2, or 1 percent, at 63 5/8 in
Thursday afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
