A8312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GOCOM-STREET &LR;      06-08 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOCOM-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO.COM TO SELL CORPORATE NETWORKING UNIT TO INKTOMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (Prices at end do not reflect market close)  
 By JUSTIN DINI   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go.com (GO:NYSE), Walt Disney's (DIS:NYSE) Web tracking stock,
said Thursday that it has agreed to sell its corporate networking
subsidiary to Inktomi (INKT:Nasdaq) in a cash and stock deal valued
at $344.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The move to unload the Ultraseek enterprise business, which
provides customizable search and navigation software to businesses
for their corporate intranet and extranet sites, is part of
Go.com's efforts to focus its business on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great little business, but it's not core to our
consumer Internet business,'' said Steve Wadsworth, Go.com's
president, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   While Go.com is in the midst of refashioning itself from a
general interest portal into an entertainment and leisure site to
take advantage of the strong vertical properties within the Disney
empire such as ABCNews.com and ESPN.com, Wadsworth said the company
would have divested Ultraseek either way. ``We would have reached
the same conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Hollywood, Calif.-based company acquired Ultraseek as
part of its deal to buy Infoseek last year. Talks with Inktomi have
been ongoing for ``a couple of months,'' Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Foster City, Calif.-based Inktomi will acquire 100 percent of
the outstanding stock and assume all stock options of Ultraseek in
exchange for $3.5 million in cash and shares of Inktomi common
stock valued at $341.2 million. Of the total consideration, $317.5
million will be provided to Go.com, the companies said. Disney has
the option to liquidate its Inktomi shares fairly quickly, people
close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our move into the enterprise market sets the agenda for the
delivery of search and navigation software for intranet and
extranet sites,'' David Peterschmidt, president and CEO of Inktomi,
said in a statement. ``Ultraseek's proven technology and extensive
customer base makes it an excellent fit for our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi shares inched up 2 3/16, or 2 percent, to 131, in late
morning trading. Go.com rose 3/16, or 2 percent, to 12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
