<HEADER>
A8313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PIMP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN PIMP': FROM BLAXPLOITATION STEREOTYPE TO MAN ON THE
STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any movie brash enough to put the word ``American'' in its title
is announcing its intention to make a sweeping statement about some
aspect of the national psyche. Putting together the words
``American'' and ``pimp'' sets off instant buzzers and creates huge
expectations for a provocative cinematic dialogue between
flag-waving righteousness and urban sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   But ``American Pimp,'' a terse, skillfully edited documentary by
the Hughes Brothers (Allen and Albert), doesn't live up to its
title. The movie, which the filmmakers researched for several
years, purports to uncover the realities behind the myths
surrounding those flamboyantly attired street hustlers who were
mainstays of 1970s blaxploitation films. But instead of shattering
or even seriously challenging those stereotypes, this breezy
montage of interviews with pimps of varying ages in several
American cities only reinforces them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pimps interviewed (all male and all black) are
obviously nicer to the women whose flesh they peddle than others
are. The movie bends over backwards to be nonjudgmental. But there
is simply no getting around the reality that urban, street-level
prostitution is a nasty game that exploits and degrades the women
who get caught up in it. The only scene in which the panderers and
prostitutes don't appear desperate beneath a surface bravado is a
brief visit to a whorehouse in Nevada, where prostitution is legal.
Here, the women have some choice about their sexual partners as
well as an economic stake in the business.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said a pimp's life is easy. As one man after another
tells his story, we hear complaints that pimps get no corporate
benefits or no health insurance or retirement plan. If they're
lucky enough to stay out of prison and have long careers on the
street, they might be able to retire in middle-class comfort. We
meet one man who married his last prostitute and retired from the
business to become a churchgoing family man. He seems to feel no
regrets about his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pimp'' proposes one fascinating theory about the
origins of the pimp stereotype. He arose, it is suggested, during
the days of slavery when enterprising black men on plantations
appointed themselves protective intermediaries between their wives,
daughters and sisters and the white slave owners who preyed on
them. But having been mentioned, the idea is never developed. A
more substantial movie would have dug up historical photographs,
drawings and texts and made at least a token effort to trace and
analyze this lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the movie prefers to examine the fashion choices of
pimps, like the fetish for alligator shoes. But here, too, its
attention span flags. The movie might have been much more revealing
had it been content to be a history of changing tastes in pimp
fashions. Exploring such a theme, it might have been possible to
find a sociological connection between style and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie illustrates, the iconography of pimp fashion is
nothing if not provocative in its fusion of designer-label chic,
cowboy machismo and the same sort of parody of European royalty
affected by Liberace (of all people!) and adopted and carried to
extremes of stage caricature by musicians like George Clinton. What
it amounts to, of course, is a grotesque, intentionally funny form
of ostentatious consumption, a parody of a capitalist excess. But
such flamboyance also has its uses. The pimps interviewed remind us
that all that flashy garb augmented with gold and jewelry is also a
professional ploy to attract women, because it is an announcement
of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to a man, the pimps interviewed cite money (some also
mention the freedom) as the motive for becoming a procurer. It's
certainly not the women whose flesh they peddle and to whom they
refer in crude anatomical slang. Although a couple of the women
interviewed say they feel loved and protected by their pimps,
during the one scene in which a pimp is interviewed with a woman
sitting on either side, both seem intimidated and speak haltingly,
with fear in their voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pimp'' would have been a much stronger movie had it
chosen only one or two pimps and seriously delved into their lives
and followed their financial and sexual transactions. But the movie
doesn't include a single scene of a pimp or a prostitute
interacting with a client. What we are left with is a mildly
entertaining ``man-on-the-street'' gloss, seasoned with fragments
from blaxploitation movies and music by Isaac Hayes, Marvin Gaye
and others. The mood built up by the film might almost be called
nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PIMP'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by the Hughes Brothers; director of photography, Albert
Hughes; edited by Doug Pray; music by Sean Carasov-The Captain and
Soundtrack Music Associates; produced by Allen Hughes, Albert
Hughes and Kevin Messick; released by Seventh Art Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Rosebudd, Schauntte, Bradley, C-Note, Ken Ivy, Charm,
R.P., Fillmore Slim, Sir Captain, Payroll, Gorgeous Dre, Bishop Don
Magic Juan, Mel Taylor, Kenny Red, Danny Brown and Dennos Hof
(Pimps); Jade, Samantha &AMP; Monica, Latrice and Spicy (Prostitutes).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pimp'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
