<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-TENSIONS-0611-     06-08 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TENSIONS-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO PEACE IS FRAGILE ONE YEAR AFTER THE WAR
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REBELS
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, June 11
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia Shuttling drinks through his cafe full of
rollicking students, Veton Firzi, a dark-eyed 29-year-old Albanian
Kosovar, shouts his good news above the noontime din.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year ago my cafe was looted (by Serbs), and I raced out of
town with nothing before they could find me and kill me. Then
America came and won the war for us,'' Firzi declares, gesturing
toward the bustling cafes stretching down the cobblestone street in
this medieval town. ``Now look. People are home. We're free.''
</P>
<P>
   But the exuberance ends just around the corner from Fizri's
cafe. There, armored personnel carriers and NATO peacekeepers
nestled in sandbag bunkers guard a handful of Serb families
huddling in fear for their lives in Prizren's 500-year-old Orthodox
monastery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like prison,'' says 27-year-old Tanja Filipovic, sitting
in the monastery's 50-square-foot courtyard, the music from Firzi's
cafe filtering over the stone walls. The distance between her and
the elated Firzi may be only 100 feet, but they are separated by an
giant chasm of fear and anger. ``If we leave, they (Albanians) will
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Kosovo, one year after the 50,000-strong NATO-led
peacekeeping force rolled into the province and ended a campaign by
Serb and Yugoslav authorities to wipe out its Albanian majority and
ethnically cleanse a whole people.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months into the peacekeeping mission, the basic rhythms
of life have returned here. But few people are naive enough to say
NATO's chief aim _ establishing a multi-ethnic society _ has been
achieved. At the same time, few officials are brave enough to say
this failure threatens the peacekeepers' mission or the region's
future stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's foolish to say we've achieved peace already,'' says
Bernard Kouchner, the United Nations' highest-ranking civilian in
Kosovo. ``Reality is more complex in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   When NATO soldiers and armor first rumbled into Kosovo June 12,
1999, they passed a desolate landscape of empty towns, shops with
broken windows and burned and destroyed houses. Now the roads are
clogged with with shoppers, 18-wheelers transporting food and
construction materials and sleek Mercedes sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, 800,000 Albanians chased from their towns by Serb
forces have returned home. Most of the 100,000 homes destroyed by
looting paramilitaries have been rebuilt. Farmers are returning to
fields cleared of land mines. Water and electricity have been
restored thanks to the United Nations and other aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Mission in Kosovo, or UNMIK, is paying teachers,
doctors and other civil administrators with funds donated mostly by
European nations. America's NATO allies agreed to foot most of the
bill for Kosovo's reconstruction after the United States paid the
lion's share of the military costs to end the Serb onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   For 8-year-old Ibrahim, Firzi's blue jean-wearing cousin, the
telltale sign that life has not only returned to normal but
improved is that he has a chance to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My (older) brother never got to go to college. The Serbs
wouldn't let him,'' Ibrahim said, showing off his new
Albanian-language textbook purchased with a grant from the Danish
government. ``Now, my teachers say I can be a doctor if I want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim's newfound hopes are a tribute to both the remarkable
outpouring of international aid and an extraordinary level of
cooperation between governments and international humanitarian
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no small achievement, that hundreds of organizations
are working together and that except for a bit of politics at the
top, we have revived whole portions of the society,'' said Dominic
Larismont, a European Union spokeswoman in Kosovo. ``We're
committed to making this work, no matter how long it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this largely exemplary record has not erased bitter
memories, or the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Shootings and other revenge attacks by Albanians against Serbs _
such as a drive-by shooting in late May that killed a 4-year-old
Serb child _ compound the already strained relations between the
two communities.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians make up more than 90 percent of the region's
population and Serbs an estimated 5 percent, but no official
statistics have been compiled since the war.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations believes some 150,000 Kosovar Serbs have left
their homes in the last year to move to Serbia, with many saying
they are afraid to remain in Kosovo. For those who remain, like
Nebojsa Ivanovic and his family, life is a series of well-guarded
moments.
</P>
<P>
   From the family apartment in Pristina, Ivanovic's children are
bused with a NATO military escort to a village outside the capital,
where Serb children from throughout the region gather for school
each day.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic, a 53-year-old athletic-looking former professor, must
take two soldiers with him to the one market in his neighborhood
that will serve him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live like in a ghetto,'' he said. ``Our entire life is in
this apartment and around this building.''
</P>
<P>
   Many officials say anger toward Serbs simmers because no court
has yet tried a case linked to alleged atrocities committed by
Serbs during the war.
</P>
<P>
   There is no final count of the dead from the war. Scholars at
the University of Bordeaux in France have estimated that some 9,000
people died in the 18 months from February 1998, when fighting
erupted between the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) and Serbian
security forces, and June of 1999, when a 78-day bombing campaign
by NATO led to a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The International War Crimes Tribunal at The Hague has reports
of more than 11,000 bodies buried in 500 mass graves. But in
exhuming some of the graves, investigators have often found fewer
bodies than alleged.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't ease Bajram Redzepi's rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of our men were killed, women (were) raped (and )
children watched their brothers and sisters tortured at the hands
of the Serb police. These people must be found guilty. If they
aren't, then Albanian frustration will grow and extremists will
target all Serbs as evil,'' said Redzepi, a former KLA rebel. He
now leads the Albanian population in Mitrovica, a town in northern
Kosovo divided, like Cold War-era Berlin, between Serb and Albanian
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs like Tanja Milenkovic say a priority for her community is
a working justice system for the whole province, one that reduces
Serb distrust of the international community and corrects their
perception that Western countries favor Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen to the killer of this child?'' she asked
tearfully, referring to the drive-by shooter. ``He is a monster if
he thinks a baby was responsible for the war.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials admit they have delayed potentially explosive war
crimes trials in Mitrovica because they fear mass protests. They
worry they cannot guarantee security for either the international
judges who will be hearing cases or the witnesses called to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to give both Albanians and Serbs a stake in running
Kosovo, the United Nations set up two administrative councils last
year. The start-up has been rough. The Serbs walked out of the
project in September to protest Albanian violence and only agreed
to return in April.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to build on that momentum, U.N. officials have eagerly
pressed for local elections to help patch up relations and
consolidate their progress so far. In the past month, posters have
appeared on walls around the province urging people to register for
the vote in elections tentatively set for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first step toward democracy-building,'' Lord
Robertson, the NATO general secretary, told reporters on a May 31
visit to Kosovo. ``People have to take part.''
</P>
<P>
   But a fresh round of violence has again aroused suspicions. Serb
leaders, angry over an upsurge in attacks against their communities
ahead of the one-year anniversary of the peacekeeping mission,
announced on June 5 another boycott of all local administrative
organizations and intimated they might stay away from the
elections, too.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who doubt that elections will do anything even
if they are held.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elections are a flag for the U.N. to raise to the world and
say the mission is not a complete failure,'' said Oliver Ivanovic,
the Serb leader in Mitrovica. ``Elections will just be window
dressing covering the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the suggestions that Kosovo is returning to some
semblance of normalcy, it is the seething indignation of Serbs like
Ivanovic and Albanians like Redzepi that are reminders of how
quickly NATO's accomplishments of the past year could come
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   William Nash, a retired U.S. Army general who led American
peacekeepers in Bosnia in 1995, acknowledges that the persistence
of animosity could unsettle all the efforts for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of war doesn't mean the existence of peace,'' said
Nash, who now runs the U.N. mission in Kosovo's divided city of
Mitrovica. ``We've got to realize it will take years to erase the
hatred they've built up.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's e-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
