u e BC-CHABANNES-FILM-REVIEW     06-08 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHABANNES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANDLE OF HEROISM IN FRANCE'S DARK NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: France, Germany, Israel)   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tiny village of Chabannes, in the Creuse region of central
France, is a quiet, obscure place, one of those corners of rural
Europe that seem strangely untouched by the modern world. But 60
years ago Chabannes confronted 20th-century European brutality at
its worst, and responded with unusual courage and humanity. The
village served as a haven for nearly 400 Jewish children _ most of
them refugees from Germany and Austria _ whom its citizens
protected from the Nazis and from the betrayal of their own
collaborationist government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Children of Chabannes,'' a documentary opening Friday in
New York (it will also be shown on Sunday evening on the HBO
Signature channel), was made by Lisa Gossels and Dean Wetherell;
Gossels' father and uncle were among the rescued children. Inspired
by her father's stories, and by a 1996 reunion of the children and
their protectors, Gossels has constructed a moving record of the
unassuming, uncompromising heroism of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   The children were brought to Chabannes by a Jewish
social-service organization, Ouvre de Secours aux Enfants, and
housed at the local chateau. Their sanctuary was administered by
Felix Chevrier, whose stubbornness and charisma make him a powerful
presence in the film, even though he died in 1962. Chevrier, a
Freemason, was also a staunch embodiment of the French republican
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   His adherence to the enlightenment tenets of universalism and
human rights was shared by many of the villagers, for whom the
embrace of endangered foreigners was an essentially patriotic act.
His eloquent, sarcastic letters to the local authorities, read
aloud by one of his old friends, are nearly as powerful as the
singing of ``La Marseillaise'' in ``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevrier, who recorded the children's activities in journals and
photographs, managed to ensure the survival of his charges even
when the Vichy government began rounding up Jews for deportation to
the Nazi camps. He was aided by Reine and Renee Paillassou, local
schoolteachers now in their 80s, whose pluck is still evident, and
by the tough, pragmatic members of the Jewish organization.
</P>
<P>
   At enormous personal risk they managed to create something like
a normal life, with daily calisthenics, mushroom-hunting trips into
the forest (where they would later hide from the police) and
lessons taught with proper Gallic rigor. The surviving children,
most of whom live in the United States and France, look back on
their time in Chabannes with fondness and amazement. The Chabannais
preserved not only their lives but, more remarkably, their
childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The survival of a few hundred children hardly mitigates the
horror of the Holocaust, and this comparatively happy tale can only
be understood with reference to the horrors of its context. These
have been documented in epochal, large-scale films like ``Shoah''
and ``The Sorrow and the Pity.'' But the cinematic fulfillment of
the imperative to remember has more recently been taken up in
smaller, more individuated acts of commemoration. ``Children of
Chabannes,'' an honest, careful film, is a fine example of this
tendency.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CHILDREN OF CHABANNES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed, produced and edited by Lisa Gossels and Dean
Wetherell; in English and French, with English subtitles; directors
of photography, Mustapha Barat and Philippe Bonnier; music by Joel
Goodman; released by Castle Hill Productions and HBO Signature
Double Exposure.
</P>
<P>
   With: Georges Loinger, Reine and Renee Paillassou and Rachel
Pludermacher (teachers); Peter Gossels, Werner Gossels, Norbert
Bikales, Wolfgang Blumenreich, Jerry Gerard, Ruth Keller and Ernest
Rosner (children of Chabannes); and Serge Klarsfeld (historian).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Children of Chabannes'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
