<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER RETURNS TO HIS COMEDIAN ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 OUR GRADE: B-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Takeshi Kitano has been the one true phenomenon of Japanese
filmmaking in the '90s _ an ex-stand-up comedian and minor actor
(``Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence'') who transformed himself into a
tough-guy icon in a series of critically acclaimed, art house
Yakuza movies (``Violent Cop,'' ``Sonatine''). In his new offering,
``Kikujiro'' _ which, like the others, he wrote, directed and
(under the name ``Beat'' Takeshi) stars in _ he returns to his
comedy roots. He plays his standard deadpan, ultra-violent and
abusive character primarily for laughs in a sappy and enjoyable, if
often uncomfortably edgy, coming-of-age road comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The title character is a henpecked, mostly retired Yakuza thug
whose wife coerces him into baby-sitting a neighborhood child: a
gloomy, fatherless little boy whose mother long ago abandoned him
to the care of his grandmother, and who has no friends and little
to do in his summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Kikujiro has no use for the kid, but gradually he
warms to him and they become a mismatched team as he takes the boy
on a journey across the island of Honshu to reunite him with his
mother: an eventful trip in which they run into a variety of
colorful characters and have a series of bonding adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the film does not completely work and it has one rather
shockingly unnecessary scene in which the child is molested in the
park by an elderly gay monster. Indeed, this one scene seems to
have cost Takeshi his status as the darling of the critics: The
film's recent New York opening got uniformly scathing reviews and
Entertainment Weekly gave it a rare ``F'' grade.
</P>
<P>
   But this seems a massive over-reaction. Much of this movie is
very funny, it has some genuinely endearing moments, Takeshi comes
up with some imaginative little stylistic flourishes and his star
power carries the narrative along nicely. New York critics or no,
the upscale audience at its Seattle International Film Festival
appearance earlier this week seemed to enjoy it immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Kikujiro. Directed and written by Takeshi Kitano. Cast: ``Beat''
Takeshi, Ysuke Sekiguchi, Kayoko Kishimoto. Sony Pictures Classics.
Guild 45th. 116 minutes. In Japanese with English subtitles. Rated
PG-13 for violence and one child molesting scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
