u e BC-VERITE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-08 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERITE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CINEMA VERITE': DOCUMENTARIANS BECOME TALKING HEADS FOR A CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The typewriter,'' goes a dated piece of verse by D.J. Enright,
``is creating a revolution in poetry.'' The digital video camera,
we have been hearing lately, is having the same effect on
filmmaking. Cheap, portable, easy to use, the new technology puts
cinematic expression in reach of the masses. At a recent
documentary festival, everyone I spoke to seemed to come up with
the same analogy: the camera has become less like a printing press
and more like a pencil, something you can grab hold of when the
mood strikes, and use to transform your impressions into art.
</P>
<P>
   The camera as pencil is a new twist on an old idea, the
``camera-stylo,'' a phrase coined by the French ethnologist and
filmmaker Jean Rouch, who also invented the term cinema verite, now
the title of an informative documentary by Peter Wintonick. Is
cinema verite a style or a movement? A technique or a philosophy?
Or is it, as Frederick Wiseman, one of its great avatars, suggests,
a piece of ``pretentious and pompous'' French jargon?
</P>
<P>
   Cinema verite is the preferred English term for what the French
like to call direct cinema, and is itself a translation of Kino
Pravda, a movement dreamed up in 1919 by the early Soviet director
Dziga Vertov. One of the peculiarities of film history is that what
might seem to be the movie camera's most obvious power _ the
capacity to record reality as it unfolds _ should require theories,
manifestoes and a specialized, multilingual vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   It has also demanded, and inspired, technological innovations.
Decades before the coming of High 8 and digital video,
shoulder-mounted cameras and synchronized sound gave filmmakers the
opportunity to wade into the jostle and unpredictability of daily
life, which they recreated in the tranquillity of the editing room.
</P>
<P>
   Wintonick's film, which opens Friday in New York, gamely
revisits the epistemological quandaries that have always troubled
documentarians. He also talks to younger filmmakers who have
adapted the hand-held, in-the-moment aesthetic to make music
videos, fictional television shows and of course ``The Blair Witch
Project.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way some old, still urgent philosophical questions are
broached: Does the camera see the world or imagine it? Does the
story belong to the people behind the camera or the ones in front
of it? Is there any truth in cinema verite?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: There is very little cinema verite in
``Cinema Verite,'' which is a sprightly collage of talking-head
interviews and borrowed clips. The first of these is from an old
Canadian instructional film called ``The Extension Ladder,'' a
fish-in-the-barrel example of the old, boring documentary style
that was swept away by a loosely affiliated band of rebels
including Richard Leacock, Albert Maysles, D.A. Pennebaker, Karel
Reisz and Robert Drew, all of whom turn up to reminisce and
philosophize for Wintonick's friendly, patient cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the film is an exercise in nostalgia. Yes, Wintonick
feasts on the black-and-white glories of old movies both famous and
obscure: Reisz's ``We Are the Lambeth Boys,'' Pennebaker's ``Don't
Look Back,'' Michel Brault's ``Raquetteurs'' and episodes of the
Canadian series ``Candid Eye.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also makes room for Barbara Kopple (who made ``Harlan
County, USA'' and ``Wild Man Blues'') in her fearless prime, and
for Jennifer Fox, a skeptical inheritor of the verite tradition who
made ``An American Love Story,'' shown on PBS last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the old-timers are still active, still following the
first rule of cinematic truth telling: shoot and shoot and then
shoot some more. Toward the end we find Leacock, the movement's
guru and provocateur at 80, looking into a digital viewfinder and
proclaiming that there has never been a more exciting time to be
making movies. Who could disagree?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CINEMA VERITE: DEFINING THE MOMENT'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Wintonick; written by Kirwan Cox; director of
photography, Francis Miquet; edited by Marlo Miazga and Wintonick;
produced by Eric Michel and Adam Symansky; released by the National
Film Board of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   With: Robert Drew, Albert Maysles, D.A. Pennebaker, Hope Ryden,
Richard Leacock, Wolf Koenig, Karel Reisz, Barbara Kopple and
Jennifer Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinema Verite: Defining the Moment'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
