<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WATER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WATER IN BETWEEN': THE YOUNG MAN AND THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada)   (EDS: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of Kevin Patterson's smart and exciting narrative
of maritime adventure, he admits something that travel writers
rarely do: the issues that drove him to brave the dangers of
faraway places were not resolved by virtue of his travels.
</P>
<P>
   This is an age in which travel writing is seen romantically, as
a kind of religious redemption, with the road and its hardships as
elements in a ritual of purification or, at least, self-discovery.
Patterson, a 29-year-old doctor who goes to sea after experiencing
the chagrin of a failed love affair, did learn things _ among them
that home is where he wanted to be. But the author's admission that
he did not find any ``obvious resolution'' to his problems during
his months in a sailboat on the Pacific illustrates the
clear-headedness that elevates this journey above the level of mere
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 a heartbroken Patterson bought a 37-foot ferro-concrete
sailboat from a broker on Vancouver Island with a plan to sail it
to Tahiti and back. It is important to note here that at the time
he became a boat owner, Patterson had never sailed. Surprisingly,
and also refreshingly, he treats this fact with self-deprecating
humor, never considering it much more than an inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the books I'd bought made it clear to me that I had
immersed myself in a pursuit where there was a great deal to
know,'' Patterson writes of this early stage of his trip. ``I knew
none of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, however, he had found a companion for the
journey to Tahiti, a quiet man named Don Lang who rivaled Patterson
in broken-heartedness and, unlike Patterson, had done a good deal
of sailing. They outfitted Patterson's clunky but seaworthy ketch
with food and spare parts and a wind vane to keep the boat on
course when the two men were sleeping. Before too long, Patterson
was heaving to and dousing sails and running storm jibs with the
best of them.
</P>
<P>
   But while he has not written a book about learning how to sail,
Patterson writes a great deal about loneliness and the voyage,
sadness and civilization. ``You could argue that the road selects
for malcontents and wobbly psyches and you will find nothing to
refute that argument in the bus terminal snack bars of my
experience,'' he writes. He recognizes in that passage that he
belongs to a history that has produced a considerable body of
knowledge and thought.
</P>
<P>
   During his long and event-filled journey to Tahiti and back, he
reflects on the literary tradition that grew out of the arduous
escape from the tedium of home, measuring his own experience
against the words and passages of writers who came before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Water in Between,'' in this sense, is good travel writing
and also good literary criticism. As he sailed the seas, Patterson
developed as good an eye for authorial success and failure as he
did for the distant darkening of the sky that foretells a squall.
</P>
<P>
   His main companions in this regard were the men whom sadness
propelled to the planet's farther reaches, men like Richard
Henderson, author of ``Singlehanded Sailing,'' Joshua Slocum, the
grand progenitor of solo global circumnavigation, and several
others. From these writer-traveler forebears, Patterson gets ideas
about the land and home as places of restriction and false comfort
as well as about solitude, the vastness of the sky, the immensity
of nature.
</P>
<P>
   There is a moment in his own experience when his boat is
becalmed in the middle of the ocean near the equator, and he and
Lang swim away from it, trusting that it will go nowhere. ``For
long seconds I had the illusion of being entirely alone,'' he
writes. ``A thousand miles from anyone. It should have been more
satisfying. I started to lose my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not say so, but it is hard to imagine that as well-read
a sailor as Patterson did not think at that moment of Melville's
Pip, the cabin boy of ``Moby-Dick'' who loses his mind when he has
a similar experience.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has a number of mishaps, like losing his anchor and
letting his battery go dead. As he sails, he recounts a few
adventures and misadventures in his past life, including his
experiences as a young doctor in the Canadian army, his encounters
with the Inuit of northern Canada and his long-distance love affair
with a delicately difficult woman escaping her French husband.
</P>
<P>
   He gets to Tahiti. He encounters other lonely sailors, including
some with a striking literary bent. Generally, he is impressed more
by their psychological disarray than their bravery in the face of
the elements. He sails from Hawaii to Vancouver alone, at one point
running into a two-day storm like nothing he had ever imagined.
``But my God, alone on a small boat, listening to wind like that,
there is nothing so full of what sounds like unstoppered human
rage, loneliness and malignancy,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The figure he comes back to again and again, his chief foil and
inspiration, is Bruce Chatwin, author of ``Songlines'' and ``In
Patagonia'' and other travel books that for Patterson, gave
expression to an especially romantic and ascetic philosophy of
travel as redemption. Chatwin in Patterson's sharp and critical
reading, saw sedentariness as spiritual death and self-sufficient,
untrammeled nomadism as happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's long days alone on the sea lead him to see the
Chatwinian philosophy as a pose, a literary device, a kind of
cynicism. Ever since the modern world created the ideal of
individualism, he writes, people have lived out the fantasy of
isolation as a response to alienation, but that is what it is, a
fantasy. Whatever our troubles may be, ``being awake at night,
alone and cold, severed from others, does not have a patch on
home.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not a bad lesson, and it is all the more persuasive
because of Patterson's absence of self-dramatization.
</P>
<P>
   This is a writer more interested in the truth than in heroics.
He has written an old-fashioned story of personal adventure that
probes its own themes with subversive intelligence and ends in a
lucidity that distilled into hard, honed prose is a pleasure to
read.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATER IN BETWEEN'
</P>
<P>
   A Journey at Sea
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin Patterson
</P>
<P>
   289 pages. Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
