<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Talking about a new tone
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a visit to Al Gore's home state today, George W. Bush
proposed two-year budgeting, a commission to study wasteful
spending, and faster votes on appointees as ways to restore order
and civility to government after seven years of the Clinton
presidency. ``Americans look upon the spectacle in Washington and
they do not like what they see,'' he said. Not letting the
Republicans who control Congress off the hook, Bush said in
Knoxville: ``There's enough blame to go around for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   GET ONE OF THOSE NIFTY TOUR T-SHIRTS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is making a ``prosperity tour'' through battleground
states to spotlight his plans to keep America's booming economy
going as voters appear split on whether he would do any better than
George W. Bush. The planned two-week tour, which Gore begins next
week, is meant to fuel his aggressive drive to define his image _
and his message _ in positive and upbeat terms. Some financial and
political analysts suggest the high-tech economy and Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan should get the credit.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING SECURITY IN SOCIAL SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   At a local law enforcement training academy in former President
Richard Nixon's hometown of Whittier, Calif., today, Al Gore
proposed the ``Social Security Protection Act,'' which would make
it a federal crime to sell Social Security numbers. Gore was joined
by Helen and Tim Remsburg of New Hampshire, the parents of Amy
Boyer. Boyer was killed last year by a man who bought her Social
Security number from an Internet web site and tracked her down.
Gore also called for stronger measures to protect medical records
and personal financial information.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOMBERG POLL POSITION
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush holds a slim lead over Al Gore, according to a
Bloomberg News poll released today: Bush 44 percent, Al Gore 40
percent, Ralph Nader 4 and Pat Buchanan 3 percent. The remaining 11
percent are undecided. Other results of the poll: Gore leads among
women 44-40 percent; 58 percent approve of the job President
Clinton is doing, Democrats have a 41-36 edge in congressional
races; cutting taxes is not a priority with voters. The poll has a
3 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN STILL PUSHING PET ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, who sought the White House on the issue of campaign
finance reform, pressed the Senate again to require a secretive new
generation of political groups to disclose their donors. Under
McCain's unrelated amendment to a military bill, nonprofit groups
that engage in campaign-style activity would be required to
disclose both their donors and expenditures. Currently, there is no
disclosure requirement on these groups, nor are there limits on the
donations they can accept.
</P>
<P>
   JUST CAN'T BEAT THE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   The money advantage that won him the Democratic nomination makes
Jon Corzine the early favorite among professional political
observers to capture the open Senate seat in New Jersey. ``I'll be
moving this race from toss-up to a narrow advantage for
(Corzine),'' said Stuart Rothenberg, editor of the Rothenberg
Report, a nonpartisan political report. He listed four reasons:
``short-term election trends in the state favor Democrats and
money, money, money.'' Jennifer Duffy of the Cook Political Report,
which tracks campaigns, gives Corzine ``a slight edge _ just for
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   A DINER, NOT THE FOUR SEASONS
</P>
<P>
   If a moment can have a message, Rep. Bob Franks was sending one
by beginning his race as the Republican nominee for the Senate at
the Lido Diner in Springfield, N.J. ``The Lido Diner, that's as
middle-class New Jersey as you can get,'' Raymond Bateman, an
experienced GOP leader in the state, said with a laugh. ``That's
Bob Franks.'' The image Franks presented at the Lido is one he
evidently expects Jerseyans to be comfortable with, and one he
hopes to contrast with Corzine's self-financed $34 million
scorched-earth campaign against ex-Gov Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE HE STAYS ON THE CANVAS THIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   As a former boxer who once fought with a broken cheekbone, Jim
Florio, the politician, has endured countless analogies to his
middleweight days. He lost the race for governor three times, once
by 1,797 votes out of the 2.3 million cast, only to win the State
House by an impressive margin in 1989. But after the knockout
suffered at the hands of Jon Corzine, Florio may never again be
described as a ``Comeback Kid.'' His friends and close associates,
according to the New York Times, said they thought there was little
chance Florio, 62, would run again for elective office.
</P>
<P>
   ALL THOSE ZEROS AT THE END
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee has set another
record: its first $1 million check. The money came from
1199/Service Employees International Union, which represents
200,000 health care workers, most of them in the New York metro
area. The check was delivered at a fund-raiser celebrating the 70th
birthday of Rep. Charles Rangel (D-N.Y.) that raised $4 million.
The Republican National Committee has received two seven-figure
checks: Amway Corp. gave $2.5 million in 1994, and the company's
founder, Richard DeVos, and his wife contributed $1 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   AND WITHOUT POLITICAL LIABILITY, HE MIGHT ADD
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says he's narrowing his list of prospective vice
presidential running mates, with an eye on candidates who would be
loyal and capable of serving as president. Bush told Hearst
Newspapers editors and executives that he expects to reach a
decision in coming weeks, but will most likely delay his
announcement until closer to the convention in Philadelphia
beginning July 31.
</P>
<P>
   FREE _ AT AN INFORMATION PRICE
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are offering free Internet service for
cybervoters, but people who accept have to answer some fairly
personal questions. Those who sign up for www.freeDEM.com must
answer some 20 questions, ranging from political views to income to
health insurance coverage. Ethnicity is optional. National
Democratic chairman Joe Andrew says no individual's personal
information will be sold, but rather will be used in aggregate for
marketing and to improve the service. The Republicans already have
launched www.GOPnet.com _ Internet access and e-mail for $19.95 a
month
</P>
<P>
   A KINDER, GENTLER CONVENTION . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is planning to break with tradition and lower the
decibel level on partisan attacks at the Republican convention by
focusing on positive proposals for the future. Spokeswoman Karen
Hughes and other advisers say Bush hopes to strike a more
high-minded tone than in conventions past. Though some criticism of
Al Gore and the Democrats is expected, the aides said there will be
at least one concrete departure from the past: No single night will
be set aside for attacks on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND A SHORTER, SWEETER PLATFORM SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   Republicans plan to compress the platform-drafting schedule in
order to limit battles over abortion and other divisive issues. The
only two public platform hearings being planned will focus on
issues such as education, health care and Social Security and avoid
more contentious subjects such as abortion, campaign finance and
tax cuts. GOP spokeswoman Ginny Wolfe said that instead of
beginning platform deliberations the Monday before the convention,
planners are considering distributing the draft Thursday and acting
on it Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   CUTTING THROUGH SHAME AND STIGMA
</P>
<P>
   A year after a White House conference on mental health that drew
wide attention to her own experience, Tipper Gore helped launch an
advertising campaign aimed at teenagers and young adults. She said
the ``shame and stigma'' she felt before seeking treatment for
depression a decade ago too often stops young people from getting
help. She didn't elaborate on her own treatment and whether it
continues.
</P>
<P>
   TO EACH, HER OWN
</P>
<P>
   The way that Molly Beth Malcolm, leader of the Texas Democratic
Party, sees it, George W. Bush is the kind of person who women want
to date and have at their parties, but do not want to marry. The
leader of the Texas Republican Party, Susan Weddington, found that
a ``real offensive'' observation and countered in Bush's defense:
``We're choosing the leader of the free world, not a prom date.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
