   DELL SPEECH - Dell Computers CEO Michael Dell addresses a
National Press Club luncheon. (Andrew Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SOUCOM-DC _ Southern Co. will become the primary supplier of
electricity to Washington, D.C., under an agreement signed Friday
to acquire a network of power plants from Pepco for $2.6 billion.
It's the largest single acquisition yet for Southern and believed
to be the largest U.S. utility asset purchasen by any company. With
the addition, Southern's Southern Energy Inc. subsidiary _ soon to
be spun off into a separate company _ will have as much electric
generating power outside the Southeast as Southern's Georgia Power
Co. subsidiary has in Georgia. SEI also agreed to supply
electricity to Pepco for four years at below-market rates. (Quinn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCOMM-ENDS _ATLANTA _ Supercomm (which ended Thursday) was a
pretty big show, reaching even into the streets _ but at least one
company doing that stretch had an apt name: Elastic Networks. While
about 800 companies set up shop in booths, metro Atlanta-based
Elastic Networks this week parked a large, black recreational
vehicle outside the Georgia World Congress Center as its
contribution to the Supercomm trade show. ``This is our booth,''
said Phillip Griffith, company vice president. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-OUTAGE _ MindSpring mail server shuts down e-mail for
all of MindSpring.com's estimated 1.2 million subscribers. Company
claims its a file server problem. That should have been repaired by
noon. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
