</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-COAL-MINES-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESURRECTING THE MINER'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 3rd take contains hotel and restaurant and site
information.) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCRANTON, Pa. _ ``The miners had a saying: `If the timbers start
talking, we start walking,''' Joe Burke said, turning his head so
that the thin beam from the lamp on his miner's helmet poked into
the gloom, barely illuminating the stout wood columns that seemed
to hold up the roof.
</P>
<P>
   These timbers don't really support the mine roof, explained
Burke. It is held up by pillars of stone that miners leave standing
as they dig out adjoining chambers of coal. ``You could actually
remove all of these timber props, and the roof would stay the way
it is,'' he said. ``Their real job was to let miners know if there
was what they called a squeeze _ pressure or movement in the rock
above. That would make these timbers creak and even crack, which
was basically an early warning system to get out fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiding visitors along a damp and chilly tunnel in the old
Lackawanna Coal Mine, 300 feet under the ground, Burke does not
give the company line on the history of King Coal. Coal mining was
brutish, backbreaking and sometimes fatal for those who went down
into the mines. In Pennsylvania's anthracite mines, 600 to 700 men
died annually in each of the 15 years of heaviest production until
the end of World War I. In all, more than 30,000 workers died in
accidents in the anthracite mines from 1870 to 1949, after which
production fell off sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of visitors who take the guided tours of the mine
every day are meant to come back into the sunshine with a greater
appreciation of a way of life that left deep veins of loss, misery
and cultural trauma through generations of families in the
anthracite fields of northeast Pennsylvania, where thick fingers of
hard-coal deposits are splayed for 450 miles between the folds of
rolling mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Only fairly recently have memories of mining history become
cultural imprints to celebrate rather than bitterly suppress.
``Mining left a mark on many families around here,'' said Tom Supey
Jr., the foreman of the restored coal mine, which is operated by
Lackawanna County. ``A lot of people were killed or watched their
loved ones die of black lung disease, so coal mining was kind of
something they wanted to forget about.''
</P>
<P>
   The American labor movement was born here, starting with the
first miners' strikes in the 1840s. Coal companies and the
railroads that hauled coal often deployed armed thugs to respond to
labor agitation. Like early SWAT teams, squads of brutal Pinkerton
private detectives, as well as the hated Coal and Iron Police, were
rushed by railroad cars to sites of labor unrest. On the miners'
side, the night-riding Molly Maguires, a secret society whose
members had fled the Irish famine in the late 1840s, rallied miners
and exacted violent retribution against many abusive mine bosses in
a struggle of class warfare that was forged into American labor
legend.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, worried that the turbulent history of the coal
fields might be forgotten as its culture faded, Supey and his
brother, Andy, joined with their father, Tom Sr., to lead
fund-raising efforts for restoration of the mine, whose 1,300-foot
main shaft had deteriorated over the years since it was shut down
in 1966. The goal was to reopen the Lackawanna mine as a way to
commemorate a critical American industrial experience whose
narrative, they feared, would otherwise die on the lips of the last
generation of men who had gone down daily into the mines.
</P>
<P>
   The mine, which remains structurally sound, was reopened in
1985, when the idea of luring tourists to a drab, played-out
upstate Pennsylvania city like Scranton was considered eccentric at
best. The regional tourist business increased substantially after
the opening in 1995 of Steamtown National Historic Site, where one
of the country's largest collections of steam locomotives and
steam-era rolling stock are gathered in a 52-acre former rail yard
only a few miles from the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Like Steamtown, whose train-buff visitors often spill over to
the Lackawanna site and the adjacent state-run Anthracite Heritage
Museum, the mine tour emphasizes the real thing. ``You get the
dampness, you get the cold, you get a first-hand look at what
mining was like,'' Supey said.
</P>
<P>
   You also get guides like Joe Burke _ affable, knowledgeable and
deeply cognizant of his family roots in the coal fields. Though
Burke wasn't a miner, his father hauled those roof timbers down
into the mines. A great-grandfather started out as a ``breaker
boy,'' one of many child laborers, whose job was to pick out slate
rocks and sort chunks of coal that rumbled in an endless stream
along troughs in a breaker shed where giant machines crunched the
newly mined coal. The miserable plight of breaker boys inspired
Gilded Age journalists to loud denunciations of coal-mine
exploitation and led to passage of stronger child labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Lackawanna site was one of about 200 mines that once
operated in the northeastern Pennsylvania coal fields. Their
product, anthracite, is a hard, clean-burning coal that first
fueled the small factories, steam engines and iron furnaces of the
19th-century Industrial Revolution; the ruins of four such
structures from this era can be seen at the Scranton Iron Furnaces.
Later, soft bituminous coal from West Virginia and Kentucky fed the
blast furnaces that turned Pittsburgh, 300 miles to the west, into
the steel-making capital of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the demand for anthracite continued to grow in the 20th
century, when it was the primary home-heating fuel for the
burgeoning cities of the Northeast. The anthracite market declined
and the mines began closing only when oil and gas heat displaced
hard coal as the dominant home-heating fuel starting in the late
1950s.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The tour takes about an hour and starts at a loading platform
that faces the old tipple, the area where coal cars were unloaded
and their cargo dumped into the troughs to be crushed and sorted in
the breaker shed. Tour visitors climb onto bench seats in a
steel-gated mine car that slowly descends deep into the earth on a
25-degree slope.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom they exit beside a wooden shack in the dimly lit,
cool subterranean gangway, a central transportation tunnel that
stretches into the darkness. The tunnel is intersected regularly by
dim chambers that probe at upward angles through layers of rock and
sandstone into thick veins of anthracite, natural seams of coal
that radiate for 30 miles into the hills on either side of the
mine.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the constant 58-degree chill and the gloom, the ghostly
echo of water drops splashing on unseen rocks was a constant
companion on the walking tour into the depths of the mine. At the
start, Burke encouraged taller visitors to put on one of the hard
hats on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that there appears to be any actual danger. In the spring,
when the mine reopens for the season, hundreds of schoolchildren
are escorted on daily tour groups, their voices echoing off distant
rock walls. The lighting is adequate to see the pathway in the
various chambers, where thick veins of anthracite appear as shiny
black wainscoting.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.0
</P>
<P>
   In one dim, echoing chamber, Burke showed how miners extracted
the coal from veins that curl through layers of rock pushed up by
the primordial forces that made mountains where an inland sea once
lay. Unlike the more plentiful soft bituminous coal that is
produced to the west and south into the Appalachians, anthracite
does not yield readily to a pick. Explosives are required.
</P>
<P>
   A miner needed to drill a hole into the coal face to insert a
dynamite packing. Burke demonstrated a hand-cranked drill that
required the brute force of three men to do the job. Then,
grunting, he hoisted up a big, clumsy electric drill that was in
use through the 1930s. Drill bits could be as long as 8 feet, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no Black and Decker; it's about 50 pounds,'' Burke
said as he leaned into the tool. ``It's got an electric cord, which
can be pretty dangerous if you were ankle deep in water. Also, if
you're drilling into the coal and you should hit shale, what the
miners called bone, that drill bit could seize up and the handle
could turn into a propeller and rip into your shoulder or your
jaw.'' The tool, which was replaced in the late '30s by a safer
compressed-air drill, also threw off sparks, with potentially
lethal results in a mine chamber where methane gas might have built
up.
</P>
<P>
   Once the dynamite was tamped in, miners retreated far down the
chamber. Burke had his tour group join him in a thundering
recitation of the miner's bellowed warning of an imminent blast:
``Fire! Fire! Fire in the hole!'' Then he flicked a switch
activating a loudspeaker that sent a deep, ominous rumble echoing
through the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   There are other small theatrical touches on the tour. Children
who gather to look into a narrow, dark tunnel shriek when a rubber
mechanical hand meant to represent a buried miner begins clawing at
the rubble. Here and there in the darkened caverns, lifelike
mannequins of miners, including children, can be seen bent to the
grueling work.
</P>
<P>
   One of them shows a ``mule boy,'' perhaps 12 years old, working
beside one of the tens of thousands of mules that used to live in
the mines, hoisting the heavy coal trucks up to the surface, before
they were replaced by small locomotive cars. A mule boy's job,
performed in near darkness, was to tend the beasts and stop runaway
coal carts on a track by using a wood pole called a sprag.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that coal cart started rolling, the mule boy, well he'd
just have to get down under the cart and force that sprag between
the spokes,'' said Burke, who scrambled under the cart to show how
it was done.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous work for a child? ``Well, a good mule was considered
to be a lot harder to replace than a boy,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Around another rocky bend, visitors come upon a wooden ``peg
shanty,'' a ramshackle underground office run by the so-called fire
boss, whose main jobs were to ensure against gas-explosion hazards
and to account for all miners at the end of a shift. On a board
hanging beside the shack, miners would insert wood pegs with their
names on them. The pegs are still hanging there.
</P>
<P>
   A little farther on, we pass into a windy 30-foot-long air
ventilation chamber shut off at either end by big steel doors that
enabled miners to direct the flow of fresh air from giant steam
fans on the surface down into various chambers. A figure of another
child crouches on a crude stool beside one of these doors. ``That
boy was called the nipper,'' said Burke. In the era before child
labor laws, this boy's job was to open and close the doors to
prevent fresh air from going where it wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   The tour ends at the foot of a long cavern, where a hulking,
dusty coal locomotive stands on the tracks. Nearby, a long steel
trough descends from the last dig that was made into ``belly
veins'' where miners had to crawl through small tunnels to claw
away boulders of coal, usually mixed with other rocks, which then
thundered down the chute to be loaded into the coal car for
transportation to the tipple at the surface. There, in the roaring
din of the breaker house, the coal would be broken into smaller
chunks and sorted by hand. ``There's our vein,'' said Burke. ``What
we're looking at is millions of years of the earth's history right
here. We're also looking at the place where work stopped when the
mine closed in 1966. The last day of work was right here.''
</P>
<P>
   He flicked a switch that suddenly plunged the chamber into
impenetrable darkness. Then he gradually adjusted his light, first
to show the pathetically weak illumination of a coal-oil lamp that
would have been used in the early days of the mines, and then to
show the only marginally more intense beam of a later-day
coal-miner's helmet lamp. Finally, the lights came back up, and we
made our way along the gangway to the work shack at the base of the
shaft to wait for the cable car that would haul us to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The group on Burke's tour had been unusually small _ only three
of us, all adult men. At the end of the tour, the guides usually
hand out souvenir ``miner's certificates,'' replicas of the actual
state certificates that licensed miners to use explosives and were
a coal miner's most coveted possession. But none of us wanted to
take a replica miner's certificate. Thanks to Burke's efforts, we
had gotten some small idea of what a real one used to cost.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOURS AND TRAINS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SCRANTON ATTRACTIONS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LACKAWANNA COAL MINE. McDade Park, Scranton, (800) 238-7245.
Guided mine tours leave regularly, 10 a.m. to 4.30 p.m. daily,
through November. Admission: $6 for adults; $4 for children 12 and
under.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA ANTHRACITE HERITAGE MUSEUM. In McDade Park,
adjacent to the Lackawanna mine tour, (570) 963-4804. This
state-run museum has an extensive collection of mine tools and
artifacts, photographs and historical displays on the cultural
heritage, troubled past and ethnic diversity of anthracite mining.
Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., Sunday, noon to 5 p.m. Admission: $3.50
adults, $2 for children ages 6 to 12; $3 for seniors; free to
children under 6; $12 per family.
</P>
<P>
   STEAMTOWN NATIONAL HISTORIC SITE, Cliff and Lackawanna Avenues,
Scranton, (888) 693-9391. A mecca for train buffs, this 52-acre
site in a former working rail yard has a big collection of working
steam locomotives and rolling stock. With maintenance shops,
exhibits and a restored roundhouse. There also are two-hour,
26-mile round-trip excursions by steam train to Moscow, Pa. (Call
for schedule and reservations.) Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily;
until 6 p.m. in July and August. Admission (valid for two days):
$8; $7 for the elderly; $3 for children 6 to 12. Train excursion,
$12; $10 for the elderly; $6 for children 12 and under.
</P>
<P>
   SCRANTON IRON FURNACES, 159 Cedar Ave., (570) 963-4804. The
restored ruins of four big blast furnaces built from 1846 to 1854
by the Lackawanna Iron and Coal Co., a leading producer of iron for
the rails that laid the nation's railroads. Hours: 8 a.m. to dusk.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   MINING AND MOLLY MAGUIRE HISTORY. Old Jail Museum, 128 West
Broadway, Jim Thorpe, PA, (570) 325-5259. Those interested in
pursuing Pennsylvania coal-mine culture can visit the Old Jail
Museum and other historic sites in Jim Thorpe, 57 miles south of
Scranton. The town, rich in mining and railroading history, changed
its name from Mauch Chunk in the mid-1950s to play down its history
in coal and instead honor Jim Thorpe, an American Indian from
Oklahoma who was a 1912 Olympic champion. (In his lifetime, Thorpe
had no connection to Mauch Chunk but was buried there after his
widow persuaded the town to adopt his name as a promotional ploy.)
In 1877 and 1878, the last seven members of 22 alleged Molly
Maguires who were condemned to death after a spate of labor
violence were hanged at the former Carbon County Jail. The gallows
has been restored, and the museum features historical displays on
the Molly Maguires. The museum and jail are open daily except
Wednesdays from noon to 4:30 p.m. Admission: $4 for adults; $3.50
for the elderly and students with ID; $2.50 for children 6 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RADISSON LACKAWANNA STATION HOTEL, 700 Lackawanna Ave.,
Scranton, (570) 342-8300. A 145-room (including 11 suites) hotel in
the elegant 1908 Scranton railroad station, with two restaurants.
Two people, $99 and up nightly.
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTON INN, I-81, exit 51, Scranton. (570) 342-7002; 129 rooms;
two people, $72 and up nightly.
</P>
<P>
   THE INN AT NICHOLS VILLAGE, I-81, exit 58, Clarks Summit. (570)
587-1135. Two people, $89 to $179 nightly; 135 rooms; two
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   COOPER'S SEAFOOD HOUSE, 701 N. Washington Ave., Scranton, (570)
346-6883. Scranton's most popular downtown restaurant; fish
platters, beef and chicken in a bustling pub-like atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL SWITZERLAND RESTAURANT, Route 209 at Hazard Square, Jim
Thorpe, Pa. (60 miles south of Scranton), (570) 325-4563. Casual
dining in a Victorian-style restaurant in a hotel from Mauch
Chunk's 19th-century days.
</P>
