<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat will spread from the Plains to the Middle Atlantic states
Friday as a warm, high-altitude ridge of high pressure envelops
much of the eastern two-thirds of the nation. Hot winds up to 30
mph will build over the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will be tempered over the western Gulf Coast states by
clouds, showers and thunderstorms that develop as moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico circulates inland on the western flank of the warm
ridge. Moisture from a tropical depression over the gulf may inject
a spurt of moisture Friday night, raising the risk of heavy rain in
East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A morning cluster of thunderstorms over the upper Great Lakes
will drop southeastward over New York state. Farther west, a
cluster of potent thunderstorms will erupt over North Dakota and
northern Minnesota near a front linked to low pressure.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRST DEPRESSION
</P>
<P>
   The first tropical depression of the young hurricane season
formed on Wednesday over the Gulf of Mexico. A depression, which
marks the second stage of tropical development, has maximum
sustained winds of 23 mph to 39 mph. Though activity tends to be
limited in June, tropical systems occasionally spin up on the
southern end of weak fronts stalled over the gulf or the eastern
Atlantic. North of such a front, surface winds blow from the
northeast, while, to the south, winds blow from southwest. This
results in a low-level cyclonic spin that can jump start early
tropical storms.
</P>
</TEXT>
