<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S ADDS TO ART ON WEB; AUCTION HOUSES FORM NEW ALLIANCES; AT
THE FRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's has decided not to hold its annual February
auction of contemporary art in its York Avenue headquarters next
year but instead to put it on Sothebys.com, its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   This move allows the house to capitalize on its recent success
in selling lower-priced contemporary art online. It is also a way
of bolstering Sotheby's online business, as the company has had
trouble obtaining enough art and objects to fill its dot-com sales,
people close to the Internet business have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get our customers to regularly check the
Web,'' said Wendy Cromwell, a specialist in Sotheby's contemporary
art department in New York. ``While they may begin looking at the
site during sale times, they should be hunting for art there all
year around.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromwell said that since 30 percent of Sotheby's Internet buyers
were new to the house, holding its February sale online would help
tap a new and broader market.
</P>
<P>
   That sale has traditionally featured lower-priced works _ valued
at $20,000 and below _ which happens to be the price range online
buyers feel comfortable with, Cromwell said. But rather than
offering art that can be seen only online, Sotheby's will put
highlights from the February sale on view in its Manhattan
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Buying art online without the opportunity to view it troubles
many people in the art world. Jason Murison and Wendy Olsoff,
owners of PPOW, a 17-year-old SoHo gallery, for example, say
bidders should have an opportunity to view art before they buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking at all the e-commerce sites, and they're
more like stores with stuff than organized, curated shows,'' Olsoff
said. ``I approached Sotheby's to see if we could collaborate on a
project, since they have the brand-name recognition on the Web and
we'd like to try to sell art online.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsoff proposed something Sothebys.com had never done: sell work
by a group of emerging artists straight from their studios. ``(at)
the Artist's Studio'' _ works on paper by 20 young artists _ will
be on view at PPOW, 476 Broome Street, through July 7. The
exhibition and sale is also online through June 29 at Sothebys.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all young artists coming out of places like Yale and
Columbia,'' Olsoff said. ``While we don't represent any of them, we
always show young artists in the gallery since everyone loves to
discover new talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling only works on paper was a way to keep prices down,
Olsoff added. Prices range from about $300 to $4,500. The Web site
will include shots of each artist's studio along with comprehensive
images of the work offered and artists' biographies.
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't Sotheby's, with its newly expanded galleries,
showing the art there instead of at PPOW, especially since it has
little to exhibit during the summer? Cromwell said, ``This is a
curated show and it should be in a gallery setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Art that isn't sold in Sothebys.com's sale on June 29 will be
for sale at PPOW until the gallery show closes on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCES WITH FRENCH
</P>
<P>
   The art world anticipates that the French government will
eventually change its laws to allow non-French auction houses to
conduct sales in France. Meanwhile American and English houses are
forming alliances with Paris-based companies.
</P>
<P>
   William Doyle Galleries, based in Manhattan, and its London
partner, Bonhams, announced this week that they have entered into
an arrangement with Boisgirard, the Paris house.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and Bonhams have worked together for several years,
conducting joint sales, helping to market each other's auctions and
pooling resources to attract business. With Boisgirard in the
group, they will offer property from the French company both here
and in London, and will exhibit works of art from Paris at Doyle
and Bonhams.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies plan to link their Web sites. ``It's what
every company has to do these days to broaden its base of both
buyers and sellers,'' said Kathleen M. Doyle, chairwoman of William
Doyle Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and Bonhams aren't the first to make inroads into Paris.
Francois Pinault, the French investor who bought Christie's,
acquired the Paris-based Piasa in February. That month, Bernard
Arnault, the new owner of Phillips, acquired Tajan, France's
largest auction house.
</P>
<P>
   COMBINING STRENGTHS
</P>
<P>
   Two powerful companies started by former Sotheby's experts _
Simon de Pury &AMP; Daniella Luxembourg in Geneva and Lucy
Mitchell-Innes &AMP; David Nash in New York _ are joining forces. While
the two aren't formally merging, they will work together to buy and
sell Impressionist, modern and contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the two firms handle art purchases and sales for
some of the world's biggest collectors, including Ronald Lauder,
the cosmetic's heir; David Geffen, the entertainment industry
billionaire; the publisher S.I. Newhouse Jr. and Paul Allen, the
co-founder of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our combined strengths have great advantages,'' de Pury said.
``When we started de Pury &AMP; Luxembourg, I said I hoped one plus one
would make more than two; now I hope two plus two will be more than
four.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Luxembourg have worked with Mitchell-Innes and Nash for a
long time, he said, adding: ``We have great mutual trust and it
goes back for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   APPOINTMENTS AT FRICK
</P>
<P>
   News of appointments at the Frick Collection are rare: its staff
is small and few people leave. But this week it announced that
Colin B. Bailey, deputy director and chief curator of the National
Gallery of Canada, will become the Frick's chief curator. He
replaces Edgar Munhall, who has retired. Barbara O. Roberts, an
independent conservator will become the Frick's conservator,
replacing Sveteslao Hlopoff, who also retired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1810EDT &QL; 
