<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT GREEK POTS TELL STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Greece, Canada, Israel, Pa., Conn.)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just as medieval Christians learned their Bible by
looking at stained glass windows and church sculptures, ancient
Greeks had their mythology illustrated on painted pots.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the late Bronze Age (circa 2900 to 2000 B.C.),
Greeks decorated all kinds of pots: kraters, amphorae, kylixes and
vases. The pots (or the stories they told) must have been
appreciated, because they have been passed down, even when broken
and repaired, for more than 4,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Christie's New York is auctioning 157 ancient Greek
vases that were formerly in the collection of Dr. Elie Borowski, a
connoisseur of ancient Greek and Near Eastern art. ``This may be
the best vase sale since 1980,'' said G. Max Bernheimer, the head
of antiquities at Christie's. ``It is encyclopedic in scale and
comes from one of the best private collections ever assembled.''
</P>
<P>
   Borowski, who was a curator of antiquities at the Royal Ontario
Museum in Toronto, resigned in the 1950s to become a full-time
collector of ancient Greek and Near Eastern art. About 10 years ago
he sold his collection of Greek vases to finance the construction
of the Bible Lands Museum in Jerusalem, which he built to display
his second collection: ancient art that chronicles the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The vases in the sale date from the Minoan era (circa 16th
century B.C.) to the Hellenistc period (323 to 31 B.C.) and include
examples of the Geometric, Archaic and Classical ceramic styles,
some of whose painters have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Some pots tell old tales. Lot 32, for example, is an Attic
krater from around 560 B.C. that illustrates the battle between the
Lapiths and Centaurs. Two Lapith warriors are seen in the heat of
combat with three centaurs. The fierce Lapiths hurl spears at the
centaurs, who are half man and half beast. The centaurs pick up
rocks and throw them at the Lapiths.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, the kind and generous Lapith king
Peirithous invited the centaurs to his wedding. The centaurs got
very drunk and repaid their host by trying to rape the Lapith
women, so the Lapiths attacked the centaurs and sent them packing.
</P>
<P>
   The story is illustrated on a 17-inch-tall column krater
designed to hold wine. ``Can you imagine how much wine it must
hold?'' Bernheimer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Attributed to the painter Lydos, the krater is an example of the
ancient Greek black-figure technique, in which figures appear in
black silhouette against the natural red clay ground of the vase,
with details incised.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, perfected in the seventh century B.C. in Corinth,
was adopted in Athens in the sixth century B.C. and became the
predominant style of the day. ``This one is quite early, when
painters show a lot of influence of the Corinthian vase painting
tradition,'' Bernheimer said, discussing the high quality of the
draftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 38, an Attic black-figure amphora from about 550 B.C.,
depicts Zeus fighting the giants. Dressed in a short white tunic,
Zeus drives a four-horse chariot and wields his thunderbolt as his
sons Ares and Herakles come to his aid. Ares, wearing a crested
helmet and cuirass, crouches, sword in hand while Herakles, with
his signature Nemean lion skin, launches an arrow from his bow. One
helmeted giant has fallen at the feet of Zeus' horses, while
another hides behind a shield decorated with a palmette.
</P>
<P>
   The black is gone from some of the figures. ``The pot is
finished but misfired,'' Bernheimer said. ``In the kiln the glaze
didn't reduce to black the way it is supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost an enormous amount to fire up a kiln, and several pots
were done together,'' he said. ``This pot shows the imprint where
the foot of another vessel sat on its side.''
</P>
<P>
   The obverse side offers one of the earliest Attic renderings of
a rare myth: the capture of the wise old centaur Silenos. The god
Hermes brings the prisoner Silenos to the Phrygian king Midas, who
is seated on his throne. Hermes has bound Silenos' hands and tied a
rope to one foot, which he holds like a leash. His right hand is
raised in greeting to a winged goddess, perhaps Iris, who stands
behind the king. Here the exuberance of triumph and dejection of
defeat are captured in one graphic moment.
</P>
<P>
   The pot does not give the punch line: according to some
accounts, Silenos, in his wisdom, was able to talk himself out of
trouble. The estimate is $50,000 to $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   After Athenian vase painters had mastered the black-figure
technique, they developed the red-figure technique around 530 B.C.
The vase was painted black except for the figures, which were left
natural red. Fine details were applied by brush. A vase that
combines black and red-figured techniques is called bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 81 is a finely painted red-figure vase from the Classical
period, fifth century B.C. It is a kylix, a shallow cup that has a
frieze on the underside. The painting has been attributed to
Douris, and the pot to Python. The underside shows the women of
Thebes dismembering King Pentheus, who had forbidden them to
worship Dionysus. The women persisted, and when they discovered the
king spying on them, literally tore him to bits. The drama is as
striking as the technique.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's antiquities sale on Wednesday in New York features an
exceptional bronze Roman head from about the first century.
Consigned by the heirs of an Englishman, Hans Calmann, it is
thought to be a copy of a lost Greek original by the sculptor
Lysippos, the court portraitist of Alexander the Great, or by one
of his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Keresy, the head of antiquities at Sotheby's, praised the
piece as ``the most important classical bronze to come on the
market in decades.'' It may have been cleaned in the 16th century
and lacquered later, he said, but the original patina remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so lifelike it may be a portrait of a famous athlete in
the fourth-century B.C,'' he said. The bronze has been known to
collectors since it was acquired in the 18th century by the
Venetian senator Bernardo Nani and is expected to fetch more than
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD SHOW
</P>
<P>
   The summer antique fairs in the region outside New York City
begin this weekend, with the Litchfield County Antiques Show in
Connecticut. It opens Friday night with a $75 benefit cocktail and
buffet from 6:30 to 9:30 p.m. at the Goshen Fair Grounds on Route
63 and continues through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 37 dealers include several top Americana specialists, like
the Philadelphia textiles dealer M. Finkle &AMP; Daughter and the
furniture dealers Wayne Pratt, Thomas Schwenke, Anthony S. Werneke,
Nathan Liverant &AMP; Son, and Jeffrey Tillou. Tickets are $8.
Information: (860) 567-0300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
