<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, June 11, 2000. Some budgeted business/financial articles
will move this evening. The rest will move Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BECKETT-FILM (Dublin) _ An Irish theater director, Michael
Colgan, has set out to have all 19 of Samuel Beckett's stage plays
filmed. One of the first, ``Not I,'' was screened last month in
Cannes with Julienne Moore performing the 13-minute ``speaking
mouth.'' Among the other completed films is ``Catastrophe,'' in
which David Mamet directs Harold Pinter, Rebecca Pidgeon and John
Gielgud in his last performance before his death last month. With
actors accepting nominal fees, the Beckett Film Project will be
completed for about $6 million. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROUST (Paris) _ Directors making a film of Marcel Proust's
3,000-page ``Remembrance of Things Past'' have to contend with the
long sentences, the long time spans and the long periods of
contemplation. Leslie Cahli interviews Raul Ruiz, the Chilean
director, to find out how he made ``Time Regained,'' one of the
volumes, into a marketable two-hour film. It opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   MACLEAN-JESUSSON-FILM (New York) _ ``Jesus' Son'' has proven to
be a god-send to director Alison Maclean. The film about alienation
and heroin use in the American heartland in the '70s has her behind
the camera for the first time in eight years. It has transcended
its $2.5 million budget and won excellent reviews. Lions Gate will
open the film on Friday. By Howard Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MONTY-MUSICAL (San Diego) _ The setting of the new musical ``The
Full Monty'' is no longer Sheffield, England, but Buffalo, N.Y. Yet
with the exception of a few new characters, songs and dances, the
theater version of the 1997 film adheres to the funny path of those
desperate men who find friendship and strength by taking off their
clothes to earn money. ``The Full Monty'' is one of several
musicals percolating in California in theaters from Los Angeles to
San Diego. Bernard Weinraub visits several of the new shows.
</P>
<P>
   ANTAEUS-MILLER-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ Formed in 1991 as a
research and study group for classically trained actors who had
strayed from the stage into film and television, Antaeus falls
somewhere in between the prosperous regional theaters and the
struggling theatrical groups. Though Antaeus has mounted only a few
plays, it has a loyal following, which explains why its production
of Arthur Miller's ``The Man Who Had no Luck at All,'' has been
extended twice. The nearly forgotten play flopped on Broadway in
1944, but here it earned the kind of reviews most Los Angeles
theaters only dream about. By David Mermelstein. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ECKERT-WHALES-THEATER (New York) _ ``And God Created Great
Whales,'' which makes its premiere Sunday night at Dance Theater
Workshop's Bessie Schonberg Theater, is loosely based on ``Moby
Dick.'' How loosely? It stars Rinde Eckert as Nathan, a piano tuner
suffering from a degenerative disease and struggling to complete an
opera based on ``Moby-Dick'' before his memory fails. For Nathan,
the white whale is represented at various times by the piano, by
the blank page and by memory itself. In the 80-minute music-theater
piece, Eckert sings, speaks and plays the piano and ukulele before
his mind goes down and he disappears into his opera never to be
seen again. By Don Shewey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-RUMBA (Havana) _ Jon Pareles attended Cubadisco, the Cuban
equivalent of the Grammy awards, and found it devoted to the rumba.
Not the south-of-the-border pop ``rhumba'' of Fred Astaire, or the
brassy big-band rumba of Tito Puente. It was the Cuban rumba that
has been traced back to Africa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT34 moved on 6/6.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROREM (New York) _ For two decades Ned Rorem, the
composer, grimly asserted that the art song was languishing,
especially the American art song. But last month, Rorem admitted
that he had been wrong. While he was predicting the art song's
demise, he said, a generation of song composers emerged right under
his nose. Anthony Tommasini interviews some of the best practioners
of this form.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ARTISTS (Santiago de Cuba, Cuba) _ In spite of severe
shortages of basic materials like paint, brushes, canvas and paper,
Cuban artists are producing work. Annette Grant profiles five
artists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT31 and NYT32 moved on 6/6.
</P>
<P>
   POLYNESIAN-ART (New York) _ Curators, collectors and dealers of
tribal art converged last month on Sotheby's in New York to view,
gossip about and bid small fortunes for two 19th-century Polynesian
rarities: a feather cape and a curious Austral Islands necklace of
whalebone, ivory and human hair. Their obscure histories, traced
last to the little known Niagara Falls Museum, and freshly restored
condition made them hot topics. The objects brought record prices
for Polynesian art: $335,750 for the cape and $313,750 for the
necklace. By Rita Reif.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT33 moved on 6/6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ARTISTS-FUND (Havana) _ On Tuesday, the Cuban Artists Fund
will hold its second benefit, ``New York for Cuban Artists,'' in
New York. The fund supports Cuban artists in all mediums, but this
article concentrates on a dance triumph. This October, at the
International Havana Festival of Ballet, the hottest ticket will
most likely be ``Ballo Della Regina,'' which George Balanchine made
for the ballerina Merrill Ashley. In March, Ashley traveled to Cuba
to teach ``Ballo'' to the Ballet Nacional de Cuba, in the fund's
first major collaboration with a Cuban arts organization.
</P>
<P>
   HALPERIN-DANCE (San Francisco) _ For an artist so influential,
Anna Halprin &UR; 10 &LR;  is barely known outside her worlds, of dance and
ritual healing. Yet those who do know her are drawn to her, as
proven by the large audience at her ``80th Year Retrospective''
last weekend. By John Rockwell.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
