   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOVIES (Paris) _ European television networks are the major
players in financing feature films for theatrical release.
According to a study by the European Audiovisual Observatory in
France, television investment accounts for between 30 and 74
percent of the financing for the production of feature films in
Europe, depending upon the country. Much of that revenue is
generated by public funds derived from taxes on television
companies and by pre-sale agreements. By Kristin Hohenadel.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the ``t'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ASTURIAS-SPAIN (Undated) _ Suddenly the major highway
ended and that was the signal that the pace changed in Asturias, a
green and damp area where there were no great resorts, no
architectural works by Gaudi, no wineries or great restaurants or
well-known museums, writes Amanda Hesser. A 10-minute drive north
and the land dropped off into the ocean. A 10-minute drive south
and the Picos de Europa, a mountain range, explodes from the earth
like an iceberg on a calm sea. We could swim or go hiking or just
take long drives down the narrow passages carved through the
mountains. We did all three.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CUBA (Undated) _ In Cuba, Kirk Kraeutler observes
firsthand ``artful adaption'' to ``tourist apartheid,'' a term that
describes places for foreign tourists with dollars, and places for
Cubans and pesos. Off the beaten path, where he often found more
potholes than pavement, he observes the myriad ways Cubans survive
in their hybrid economy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (New York) _ Betsy Wade offers a guide to
some bus and boat tours of Manhattan. These include: Harlem
Spirituals, which visits the gospel music scene in Harlem; the
Semicircle Tour, a shorter version of the around-Manhattan tour on
the Circle Line; the Queens Jazz Trail; the Hasidic Discovery Tour
in Brooklyn; and a literary tour of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PETS-AIRLINES (Undated) _ Several major airlines
announced rules last month restricting pets traveling as
passengers' checked luggage in the baggage compartments of planes,
at least during the summer. Industry sources say that airlines will
soon require that pets going by air be handled by commercial
shippers, a move that could increase the cost substantially. Betsy
Wade reports on this trend and the services that ship animals in
climate-controlled comfort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HOTEL-SHOPPING (Undated) _ For years, hotels have sold
small items like bathrobes and towels to guests who wanted to take
home more than memories. Such sales were largely defensive to
discourage theft, but increasingly it's a matter of marketing.
Bedside price list's include robes, towels, alarm clocks,
wastebaskets and even the bed. By Terry Trucco.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Two sleek hotels for New Orleans; a
bus link to Yosemite; a Web site on airport conditions and the
reinvention of the summer house in England.  &QL;
</P>
