<P>
   MICROSOFT (Undated) _ Skedlines to come.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDATIONS-AGENDA (Undated) _ The Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation aims, in its own words, at ``helping to improve people's
lives through health and learning. In addition to its sweeping
effort to vaccinate the world's children, it has backed charities
like Cancer Lifeline and the American Cancer Society. According to
its most recent tax return, the Gates Foundation also owned bonds
in a tobacco company, Philip Morris _ raising the issue of whether
its behavior as an investor sometimes runs counter to its
charitable mission. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-HAJI-IOANNOU (London) _ Telios Haji-Ioannou is the first
to admit that he likes the finer things in life. ``My ideal hangout
would be a gentleman's club,'' he said, laughing, during breakfast
at the One Aldwych Hotel. ``I'm not the typical person like my
customers. I come from a wealthy family.'' Indeed, Haji-Ioannou is
filthy rich. But he also happens to be the founder of the
EasyGroup, a feisty London company that has spawned a bevy of
brands here representing all things on the cheap. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-MUSIC-CONTRACTS (Undated) _ Rock star and actress, Courtney
Love, knows how to grab the spotlight. At a new media conference in
New York's SoHo last month, she said, ``Stealing an artist's music
without paying for it is absolute piracy ... And I'm talking about
major label recording contracts, not Napster.'' By Alec Foege.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE-QUESTIONS-BACHELDER (Undated) _ As shareholders gather for
annual meetings, many are finding in their proxy statements further
evidence that executive pay continues to soar. Even severance
packages for top executives can mount into the millions, or tens of
millions. As a leading executive compensation negotiator, Joseph E.
Bachelder III, head of a Manhattan law firm that bears his name,
may deserve a share of the credit, or the blame. By Stewart Kampel.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS (Undated) _ Off the Shelf: ``Age of Access'' by Jeremy
Rifkin. Review by Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-CAREERS (Undated) _ If you phoned Central Casting
looking for some dot-com-founder types, they wouldn't send these
people over: an industrial quality maven, a college professor who
founded a nonprofit group, the head of a government regulatory
agency, all past 40 and well established on traditional paths. Yet
each of them has taken a sharp midcareer turn into territory that
the popular imagination reserves to 20-something nerds in sneakers
and pizza stains: Internet entrepreneurship. Or maybe it's not so
sharp a turn. By Amy Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   SUDDEN-WEALTH-SYNDROME (Undated) _ What Lorna Hudson has against
the rich is unclear, but when they come into the Ford dealership
she manages, she goes right ahead and willingly will sell them a
new car, not for a second giving pause to the emotional damage
she's inflicting. In fairness, Hudson said she was unaware that
some of the clientele might be wracked by pain and uncertainty. The
trouble is they recently became fabulously wealthy, which makes
them susceptible to contracting SWS, Sudden Wealth Syndrome. By
Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DIGEST (Undated) _ Investing notes and news; with Funds
Watch. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ On Sunday afternoons, John B. Leo plays
shortstop in a softball league in Geneva, Ill. As a hitter, he's no
Mark McGwire. But he often gets to base, a good analogy for his
stockpicking style as lead manager of the $2.51 billion Northern
Technology fund. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-TELECOM (Undated) _ Forget DSL, T-1 lines and coaxial
cable: If you believe much of the hype, cell phones will soon be
the most common way for consumers to connect to the Internet _
whether while driving to work, shopping or catching rays on the
beach. So it is no surprise that some people on Wall Street have
become enamored with a convergence of telephone and computer
technology. By Kate Berry.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-CABLE-STOCKS (Undated) _ Have you checked your cable bill
lately? Average rates have risen 33 percent over the last five
years, and the pace shows few signs of letting up. That may irk the
nearly 70 million cable subscribers in the United States, but it
would seem to be good news for cable stock investors. So why is the
Paul Kagan Associates index of cable company stocks down? Investors
see problems for the industry, especially in the growing popularity
of satellite television providers like Hughes Electronics' DirecTV
and EchoStar Communications' Dish Network. By Michelle Leder.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
