u w BC-INTERNET-CHILDREN09-C     06-08 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CHILDREN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONLINE SEXUAL CONTENT, APPROACHES COMMON FOR KIDS, STUDY SAYS
 &HT;    With INTERNET-DATA.
 &HT;    By MIRIAM GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One-fourth of young people surfing the Internet
last year were exposed to pornography and one-fifth were sexually
approached, a national survey reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Children aged 10 to 17 are primary targets for sexual harassment
in cyberspace,
</P>
<P>
   said the report by the Crime Against Children Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This highlights the need to make the Internet a safer place
for young people,'' said David Finkelhor, director of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study, funded by a federal grant through the National Center
for Missing and Exploited Children, surveyed 1,501 young people
across the nation who use the Internet regularly.
</P>
<P>
   It found that 19 percent had received unwanted sexual
solicitations, 25 percent had at least one unwanted exposure to
images of naked people or people involved in a sex act, and 6
percent were threatened or harassed in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Young Internet users encountered unwanted sexual content through
e-mails, by misspelling Web addresses, or by using far-reaching
search engines. For example, Finkelhor said pornographic content
can appear when children search for a favorite topic such as
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   None of the cases resulted in physical harm, the study said, but
experts say cases should still be reported.
</P>
<P>
   In more than half of the cases, the children had not reported
the incident to an adult, the study found. Many children are afraid
their Internet privileges will be taken away, or they are
embarrassed or feel at fault, said Finkelhor. But parents should
teach children to report such cases instead reprimanding them,
Finkelhor suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``More should be done to get kids to talk about these episodes.
We need parents, school counselors and people their own age to help
them report them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If parents notify their Internet service providers or the FBI of
incidents, legal action can be taken against offenders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that not all offenders are adult males trolling
for sex. Some children said they had been subjected to sexual
advances from other teenagers and women in their 20s, Finkelhor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study said parents should be wary of friendships their
children develop on line, but it said they should not necessarily
prohibit such relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches are molesters, but that doesn't mean parents should
avoid signing their children up for Little League, the study said.
``It will be a similarly complicated challenge to protect kids from
dangerous Internet relationships without squelching the positive
ones,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was sponsored by the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on Justice and related agencies, chaired by Sen. Judd
Gregg, R-N.H. Congress wanted to obtain data showing the number of
children victimized in cyberspace before taking legislative action,
Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to preserve the positive uses of the Internet is
to ensure that it is not a sanctuary for pedophiles, child
pornographers and others who prey upon children,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.unh.edu(backslash)ccrc(backslash)index.html
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
