<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT09-COX     06-08 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT SEEKS IMMEDIATE STAY OF ANTITRUST REMEDIES
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as they sought to avoid a court-ordered
breakup, beleaguered Microsoft officials moved Thursday to shelve a
series of tight curbs on the company's business practices that are
set to go into effect in September.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lawyers called on U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson to stay a long list of conduct-based remedies
drafted by the government and imposed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under Jackson's order, Microsoft could not:
</P>
<P>
   _ Threaten or do anything to harm competing products, such as
withholding licensing terms, sales or technical support.
</P>
<P>
   _ Force computer makers to promote, distribute or use Microsoft
products as a condition of licensing its flagship Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the restrictions were needed because the software
giant continues to flout the nation's antitrust laws, and that they
should stay in place for three years after the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's lawyers argued that a stay was necessary to
avoid ``grievous and irreparable harm on Microsoft, its 35,000
employees, its millions of shareholders, its thousands of business
partners, and the tens of millions of consumers around the world
who rely on Microsoft's products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Such radical changes affecting a major American corporation in
an industry as important to the economy as computer software should
not be implemented before Microsoft has had an opportunity to
secure appellate review,'' the defense motion maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials held out little hope that Jackson would
reverse himself and put his judgment on hold while the appellate
courts review the landmark case. But they noted that Jackson needed
to deny their motion to get the appeals' clock ticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectation is that the appellate courts will stay the
entire final judgment,'' said Bill Neukom, Microsoft's veteran
general counsel, who had sat at the head of the defendant's table
throughout the 78-day trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect,'' Neukom added, ``that a stay would also stay
our obligation to begin developing a breakup plan.'' Jackson
ordered Microsoft to submit a plan to create one company to develop
and sell the Windows operating systems, and another to handle
applications software and Internet products.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Joel Klein, the Justice Department's antitrust
chief, urged the U.S. Supreme Court to hear Microsoft's appeal
directly, bypassing the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Klein cast doubt on the possibility of a settlement at this
stage, although Jackson, in separate interviews with two reporters
published Thursday, had held out the hope that the key issues in
the dispute could still be resolved through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative ``that a settlement meaningfully address the
harm that's occurred to this market,'' Klein said as he joined
Attorney General Janet Reno at her weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most troubling aspects of Jackson's order for
Microsoft is that Steve Ballmer, the company's chief executive,
would be bound to hire a ``compliance officer'' for the antitrust
package who would report directly to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson further provided for spot ``compliance inspections'' by
government antitrust attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   That section of his order obligates Microsoft to hand over
``copies of all books, ledgers, accounts, correspondence,
memoranda, source code, and other records and documents'' that
relate to any aspect of the sweeping antitrust remedy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.usdoj.gov/atr, www.microsoft.com/presspass/trial
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
