<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTOR-CARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF COLLECTOR CARS: ON THE AUCTION BLOCK, OR ONLINE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Editors: see also MONACO-CARS) 
 By KEITH MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTE CARLO, Monaco _ Three recent auctions here demonstrated
that the collector-car market continues to gain strength. Yet the
beneficiaries, the old-line auction companies that exhilarate
crowds by sending multimillion-dollar Bugattis over the block,
where they are subject to feverish bidding by celebrity collectors,
are looking warily over their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Internet is changing the ways that multinational
conglomerates and neighborhood pizzerias do business, it looms as a
potential threat to the auction houses that could lose millions of
dollars in commissions if buyers and sellers move online.
</P>
<P>
   The online auction formula is simple: Put a desirable car before
millions of potential bidders and charge a minimal commission to
reflect the site's low overhead. Ebay has proved that the process
works well for old books, Beanie Babies and tens of thousands of
other low-cost, easy-to-describe items.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, eBay established a category specifically for cars
and auto-related products. Now, with the formal introduction next
Monday of eBayMotors.com, the online auctioneer is moving to set up
a one-stop resource center for car shoppers, from commuters seeking
rusty ``station cars'' to connoisseurs of custom-body Duesenbergs.
</P>
<P>
   Even an old-guard competitor credits eBay with increasing the
public's awareness of the auction process. ``Now, someone who has a
dusty old Pez dispenser knows they have an alternative to selling
it at a garage sale,''said David Gooding, managing director of
Christie's International Motor Cars in Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its sales listings, eBaymotors.com will provide
an array of services to aid in online sales, including presale
inspections by authorized personnel, with results posted on the Web
site; financing options; access to collector-car insurance; instant
estimates of the costs of transporting a vehicle; and an escrow
service that will hold money until a car's condition is verified.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these services are required. While any car entered
at a Christie's or Brooks auction is researched and evaluated by
specialists, eBay leaves the due diligence to the buyer and the
seller.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for eBayMotors say that cars receiving presale
inspections are more likely to sell, and for a higher price.
</P>
<P>
   For prospective buyers, eBayMotors promises to put a dizzying
variety of cars within mouse-click range. Only 153 cars were
offered, in total, at the three Monaco auctions. In contrast, eBay
had 3,649 cars listed for sale this week, said Simon Rothman, vice
president and general manager of eBay's automotive division; most
were in a range of $10,000 to $50,000. Rothman projected that car
listings on eBayMotors could total as much as $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The eBay bidder can also buy without paying a commission,
although sellers pay $25 to list a car and just $25 more if the car
sells. In contrast, most auto-auction houses charge up to 10
percent for consignors and 5 to 17.5 percent for buyers _ for total
premiums of $60,000 or more on a $300,000 car.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it takes a leap of faith to spend a substantial sum to
buy a car without actually seeing it. Does its condition match the
representation made by the seller? Is it authentic? Did it really
once belong to Joan Crawford? Are competing bids being made by
legitimate buyers, or is the price being driven artificially
higher?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions apply to any big-ticket item offered online, as
made obvious recently when a painting nearly sold on eBay for
$135,805 on speculation that it was by a noted artist. It was
discovered that the seller and some acquaintances had driven up the
price by bidding on it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Misrepresentation is possible at live auctions, as well, but
bidders are less likely to be fooled if they examine a car and
question the auction company's representatives. Further, the big
auction houses work to resolve disputes between buyers and
sellers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``EbayMotors won't attempt to authenticate items being listed,
but we provide services for those who wish to do so,'' Rothman
said. He depicted eBayMotors as ``a marketplace where automotive
transactions take place.'' By playing the role of a feisty,
no-frills newcomer challenging a full-service institution, eBay is
to Christie's as eTrade has been to Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   While live auctions are far more expensive for both buyer and
seller, they offer more presale services. ``Christie's, along with
other specialist auction houses, really add value to an item,
especially for the ultra-exotic, whether painting, jewelry or
automobiles,'' Gooding said. ``We research the cars being offered,
inspect and drive them where possible and provide educated opinions
for our clients.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions have also been raised about the technological
reliability of online auctions. Robert Brooks, chairman of Brooks
Specialist Auctioneers and Valuers, asked: ``If a customer is
bidding online on a million-dollar Duesenberg and the computers go
down, what's the bidder to do? Does he lose the car? Do we miss a
chance to get the seller the highest price? At a live auction,
there is always a way to keep the sale going.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, at the Meadow Brook collector-car sale in Michigan,
a windstorm cut the power. The audience urged the auctioneer to
continue, which he did, selling cars in a hall lighted by a backup
generator.
</P>
<P>
   EBay can point to its own success as an indicator of future
growth. ``We have had strong double-digit growth in our automotive
sector every month since we began informally in August of 1999,''
Rothman said. ``We also have 10,000 listings for automotive
memorabilia and over 46,900 parts listings. And we have tens of
thousands of new listings each week, as auctions end and new ones
begin.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To compete with online auctions, the live auction companies will
stress quality over quantity, professional services over low
commissions and the thrill of a live event. ``Especially at the
high end, buyers and sellers want to enjoy the drama and spectacle
of a live auction,'' Gooding said. ``After all, it's surely more
fun to be in Monte Carlo watching someone bid on a million-dollar
Maserati Grand Prix car than it is to sit in front of a computer
terminal clicking away with your mouse.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
