<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, June 9, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Moscow serves notice that it intends
to rule Chechnya with an iron military hand for as long as it takes
to suppress the separatist movement. Putin declares the Kremlin
will maintain direct control over the breakaway province and will
not agree to any negotiated pullout. By Brian Whitmore. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-PATIENTS (Washington) _ In a rancorous prelude to
election-year debates across the country, Senate Republicans
narrowly thwart a Democratic effort to bypass stalled negotiations
and pass the most comprehensive overhaul of the managed care
industry since the advent of HMOs. By Bob Hohler. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (Washington) _ Al Gore's mission to ``reinvent
government'' has been reinvented by his opponent, George W. Bush,
who travels to Gore's home state to announce the details of his
plan. By Susan Milligan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-VISION (Rochester, N.Y.) _ Scientist says he's developing
technology that could someday make ``super vision'' a reality for
almost anyone. Using high-tech optics used in large telescopes and
spy sattellites, David Williams believes he can give people the
vision of an eagle. By David L. Chandler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-NIGERIAN (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Survivor of a Nigerian
civil war who later became a doctor and married a US ambassador
tells her fellow Harvard University graduates, in a commencement
speech, they are accountable for upholding social justice and
promoting public health. By David Abel. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERRA-LYCOS (Boston) _ Terra Networks shareholders approve the
purchase of Lycos; Lycos CEO Bob Davis predicts smooth completion
of the merger between his portal and the Spanish telecom company.
By Ross Kerber. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   XCHANGE-CUSTOMER (Boston) _ Xchange, the company that helps
Staples and Daimler Benz fashion highly targeted marketing
campaigns, signs a definitive agreement to acquire
CustomerAnalytics, a privately held Dallas firm. By Chris Reidy.
500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (Paris) _ By Bud Collins. Mary Pierce wins
the accolades of the crowd at Stade Roland Garros -- and a chance
to compete in the finals of the French Championships. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
