<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-08 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANYONE FOR THE CABINET? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Insiders report that Texas Gov. George W. Bush may
announce during the Republican convention, or at least before
Election Day, some if not all of his choices for the Cabinet if he
becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that surfacing in advance an impressive roster of
experienced dignitaries destined to be at Bush's side would bolster
his own shaky credentials as a leader of substance. The message?
Electing Bush is picking a team and not just a man of suspected
intellectual limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that such an announcement would be helpful is pure
bunkum. Not only would it be premature; it would be politically and
psychologically wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Voters expect presidential candidates to stand on their own two
feet without relying on others as political props. Even Bush's
appearance during the early primary season with his parents, the
former president and first lady, was not a plus. When his father
called him ``my boy,'' the younger Bush looked especially immature.
</P>
<P>
   And voters do not like to be taken for granted. They may take
umbrage at a candidate who arrogantly assumes _ no matter how
favorable his polls may be _ that he has the election in the bag.
Bush is supposed to concentrate on wooing the public right up to
the last minute, not on selecting the elite folks who get to ride
to power on his anticipated coattails.
</P>
<P>
   Has Bush forgotten what happened to President Thomas Dewey when
he similarly jumped the gun with his Cabinet names?
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1948. The press and the pollsters all agreed that
President Harry S Truman was political toast and that Dewey, the
Republican nominee, would win in a landslide. Dewey was so
confident of victory that he leaked to a widely syndicated
columnist, Drew Pearson, a list of his Cabinet choices, led by John
Foster Dulles for secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson wrote a column about the choices on the day of the
election before the returns were in. It was published the morning
after Truman's stunning victory and immediately became a classic in
the annals of political unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, seems unfazed by, or perhaps unaware of, that
embarrassing incident. He has already been trying to bolster his
image with selected appearances by Republican heavyweights. When he
disclosed his proposal to reduce the U.S. strategic nuclear arsenal
while deploying a baby Star Wars anti-missile shield, he surrounded
himself with venerable Republican foreign policy experts.
</P>
<P>
   The men represented the conservative old guard of his father's
generation, stable and experienced but not exactly the wave of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   In the cartoon strip ``Doonesbury,'' Garry Trudeau quipped, ``It
looked like Madame Tussaud's (London wax museum) up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder statesmen did lend a certain gravitas to Bush's
venture into new military policy territory. The group's centerpiece
was former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Colin Powell, who
has been flirting openly with Bush over the stewardship of the
State Department. Bush hasn't exactly announced that Powell would
be the next secretary of state, but the prospect has met with loud
applause and seems to be practically a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Any other Cabinet announcements, however, would come as a
surprise. An early selection would please the lucky few but
irritate hordes of other hopefuls who are angling for one of the
spots. Shut out of the charmed inner circle, their enthusiasm for
the Bush candidacy might even wane just when he needed it most.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidency has always been a lure dangled by
presidential candidates to keep ambitious governors and other
statewide officials on their team. The Cabinet is a less obvious
treasure, but lobbying for a seat can also be intense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that game too can backfire, just as the veep game sometimes
does. In 1964 Sen. Eugene McCarthy got miffed because President
Lyndon Johnson had hinted about giving him the vice presidency and
then picked his Minnesota Senate colleague Hubert Humphrey instead.
McCarthy turned against Johnson and never forgave him.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the selection can be important. Bush may be
thinking of ways to pump up interest for what otherwise promises to
be a dull convention. But premature commitments can arouse
opposition as well as support. If he makes a mistake about, say,
the secretary of the treasury, everybody will have plenty of time
to create an uproar before the poor would-be appointee has to go
before the Senate for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   When a president notifies his friends about his plans, he also
notifies his foes. Ronald Reagan learned this lesson in 1976 when
he was trying to take the GOP presidential nomination away from
President Gerald Ford. Trailing in the delegate count, Reagan
announced nearly a month before the convention that if he got the
nomination, Pennsylvania Sen. Richard Schweiker would be his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to bring the fat Pennsylvania delegation to
Reagan. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan and Schweiker, a moderate, were poles apart on many
issues from production of the B-l bomber to a full-employment bill.
Schweiker turned off more potential Reagan backers, particularly in
the South, than he inspired new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for holding preferences for the Cabinet in reserve
until the election is over are as compelling today as in the past.
Bush would be wise to look elsewhere for an attention-getting
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
