<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL09-COX     06-08 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DELL SEES BRIGHT FUTURE FOR BOTH WEB AND PCs
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Dell, who founded the world's most
successful personal computer maker, Thursday hailed the rise of
Internet commerce as a ``revolution'' that has only just began.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, the 35-year-old chief executive of Dell Computer Corp.,
told a National Press Club luncheon audience that ``the pace of
change is only going to accelerate from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Dell maintained that personal computers are also
here to stay, despite widespread reports that they will be
supplanted in time by hand-held devices, Web-enabled telephones and
``smart'' TV sets or other dedicated Web-based appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC has a very bright future,'' he said. ``And I actually
enjoy, to some extent, seeing all the news reports about the demise
of the PC ... from our competitors or industry pundits, because
we'd be happy to gain additional market share from those companies
that believe that it's going away.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Dell said, the company, based in Round Rock, Tex.,
shipped nearly 12 million computers to some 150 countries, more
than any other domestic or foreign manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's revenues have grown in 16 years from $6 million a year to
$27 billion in the last four quarters. Its sales on the World Wide
Web exceed $40 million a day. It is the only company whose revenues
and earnings have grown more than 40 percent annually for the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   That record earned Dell a coveted invitation to speak to the
press club, but the journalists in the audience did not manage to
elicit any news from him on the hottest high-tech topic of the day:
the fate of Microsoft Corp., which a federal judge on Wednesday
ordered to be split in two.
</P>
<P>
   Dell and Microsoft have close business links. Moreover.
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates and Michael Dell, who is 10 years
younger, have long been personal friends.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the legal battle will effect Dell's dealings with
Microsoft and with other operating system companies, he replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``The core issue for us here is what do our customers think,
because our company is essentially a company that delivers what our
customers want to buy and the solutions and service that they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers ... essentially like those products, and we
believe will continue to buy them whether it is one company or two
companies or five companies. And that is really the kind of
operative issue for us. And that's the core issue as we see it.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed further, Dell added: ``I'm not going to comment on
the merits of the case or whether one group did one thing to
another. I'd leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   What Dell did want to talk about is the Internet and,
particularly, how much help it has been in supporting the needs of
computer users.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, he said, ``has become not only a competitive
weapon, but an essential tool for dealing with the volumes and the
complexity of our business in an efficient manner.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.dell.com; www.npc.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
