<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-08 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TRIAL OF OLD DRUM': A BOY-AND-HIS-DOG STORY IN A MORE INNOCENT
ERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only the most hard-hearted can resist the sight of a boy crying
when his dog faces death. Why else is ``Old Yeller,'' an iconic
American movie, recalled when filmmakers want a hard character to
reveal a heart?
</P>
<P>
   Fair warning: I'm a dog owner myself, and the harder parts of my
heart turned to mush during moments in ``The Trial of Old Drum,''
an original movie having its premiere Friday night on Animal
Planet. When the golden retriever Old Drum whimpers after a gunshot
wound, when he howls as he is separated from his young master, when
he offers a peacemaking paw to the town villain _ OK, everyone, a
collective ``aaw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trial of Old Drum'' is manipulative and awkward, and it
features spotty acting, washed-out landscapes, wince-inducing
dialogue, leaps of reason and a load of bathos. Its fans won't
care. At its best, ``Old Drum'' relates a classic story of a boy
and his dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trial of Old Drum'' is based on a true story from the
western Missouri of 1870, when a rhetorically gifted lawyer, George
Vest, delivered a closing statement that popularized the line, ``A
man's best friend is his dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trial of Old Drum'' streamlines the facts and plants a
happy ending on the tale, in a movie clearly geared toward
children.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, Ralph Gaby Wilson, has moved the story to an
invented Eisenhower-era village that retains the innocence of a far
earlier time. ``This is God's country,'' says the adult Charlie
(the singer Randy Travis), whose narration describes the town as a
place where your word is your good name and you don't need to lock
your doors. (That's not the last of the cliches.)
</P>
<P>
   Young Charlie (Bobby Edner) is an only child whose mother has
died, leaving him lovingly attached to Old Drum, a sweet, devoted
and heroic dog. Old Drum is accused by gruff Uncle Lon (John
Schuck) of killing sheep, a high crime in this livestock-centered
economy. Lon wants the dog destroyed. Despite Charlie's attempts to
defend his pet, Old Drum is jailed until the truth can come out in
a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's father is played by big Ron Perlman, whose muted
performance is quietly charming. It's touching to watch Perlman
wrap his large frame around the small boy in an attempt to comfort
him, but the threat to Drum calls for further help: a well-known
city lawyer, played by Scott Bakula, a fine actor best-known for
his Emmy-nominated performances in ``Quantum Leap.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial pits Bakula's George Vest against the prosecutor
Thomas Crittenden (well-played by Tom Duggan). Not surprisingly,
this is the most involving part of the movie, so it's a shame that
the case zips along so quickly and Vest's climactic tribute to dogs
is so disappointing. Bakula's big moment, Vest's history-making
summation, fails to fulfill its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Most children will feel suspense during the trial and sympathy
for all the movie's characters (aside from Uncle Lon, who remains
an unredeemed villain). But even children will puzzle over some of
the script's odder choices, in particular Charlie's alternating
references to Drum as ``good girl'' and ``good boy.'' Is this a
strange attempt at gender equity? If so, it is misguided; just
after Drum is proven capable of fatherhood, Charlie again refers to
his dog as ``girl.'' Huh?
</P>
<P>
   But there's no point quibbling over the movie's flaws. ``The
Trial of Old Drum'' proclaims the worthy soul of a pet, a sentiment
that Animal Planet is wise to embrace _ and that no pet owner would
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TRIAL OF OLD DRUM'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Friday on Animal Planet
</P>
<P>
   Sean McNamara, director; Joe Broido and David Brookwell,
producers. A production of Porchlight Entertainment for Animal
Planet. Bruce D. Johnson, executive producer for Porchlight; David
E. Gerber, vice president of production, and Ross Hammer, executive
producer, for Animal Planet.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ron Perlman (Charles Burden Sr.), Scott Bakula (George
Vest), Bobby Edner (Charlie Burden), John Schuck (Uncle Lon), E.J.
Callahan (Lyle Snelling), Alexis O'Keefe (Ann) and Randy Travis (
voiceover for Charlie Burden).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
