<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EDITORS NOTE FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 9
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: This editors note will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BENNINGTON-DISPUTE-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 27,
about turmoil at Bennington College over the dismissal of some
faculty members in a reorganization referred to events surrounding
the firing of a philosophy professor, Carlin Romano. It said that
before Romano's dismissal he was quoted in The Chronicle of Higher
Education as calling the college president, Dr. Elizabeth Coleman,
``a serial violator of academic freedom'' and predicting that he
would be fired. The Times article also said Dr. Coleman and others
attributed Romano's departure to his chronic lateness with
evaluations and his having threatened a dean.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness the article should have included a response from
Romano. He denies having made threats. His prediction about
dismissal came from an April 28 article in The Chronicle, which
truncated a quotation from the journal's March 31 issue, in which
Romano said he expected ``to be fired or in some way discriminated
against or punished like everyone who has spoken out before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLARK-WARCRIMES-HNS &LR;      06-08 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLARK-WARCRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLARK DEFENDS NATO FORCES AGAINST WAR CRIME CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the former NATO commander
who led last year's successful military campaign to expel Serbian
forces from Kosovo, defended himself Thursday against an Amnesty
International report charging his forces with a war crime in the
bombing of a state-run television station.
</P>
<P>
   NATO jets attacked the main Serbian television station on April
23, 1999, in a pre-dawn raid that killed 16 civilian technicians
and security guards and wounded at least 16 others, according to
Pentagon figures. The attack knocked the television signal off the
air for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Amnesty International, a human rights group,
released a study concluding that forces under Clark's command had
violated international law by purposely attacking the civilian
target.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one instance, the attack on the headquarters of Serbian
state radio and television, NATO launched a direct attack on a
civilian object and (this action) therefore constitutes a war
crime,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a legitimate military target,'' Clark said in an
interview. ``From the very outset of the war, I had ambassadors and
heads of state coming to me, saying, `You've got to get that off
the air. It's poison. (The propaganda machine of Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic) is poisoning our people, his own people. He's
manipulating that conflict by the use of that media.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clark added, ``You are always making tradeoffs in these
decisions. But in this case, it was a huge step to be able to take
out (Milosevic's) major instrument of provocation and command and
control.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the attack, NATO officials maintained that the TV
station, in addition to broadcasting propaganda, also sent
instructions to troops in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Clark acknowledged Thursday that the attack by itself did not
achieve the stated military goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really get the effects until we took out the
electricity. When we took out the electricity, it just so happened
that it made it much more difficult to receive Serb radio and
television in large parts of Serbia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Carla Del Ponte, chief prosecutor for the
international war crimes tribunal in The Hague, cleared NATO forces
of any possible war crimes during the 78-day air war against
Serbia, which lasted from March 24 to June 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte said that ``although some mistakes were made by NATO
... there was no deliberate targeting of civilians or unlawful
military targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing that statement, Clark said the attack ``was assessed by
all of the lawyers as fully in accordance with international law.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Amnesty International doesn't make international
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark was replaced as NATO's top military leader in May and
plans to retire from active duty this month.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CBS-SURVIVOR-STREET &LR;      06-08 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-SURVIVOR-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS'S 'SURVIVOR' TROUNCES ABC'S 'MILLIONAIRE' IN SECOND WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUSTIN DINI   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second episode of ``Survivor,'' which was broadcast on CBS
on Wednesday, topped the previously invulnerable ``Who Wants to be
a Millionaire'' on ABC by 21 percent in ratings, according to
overnight ratings statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' a reality program that features a group of people
stranded on a tropical island with few resources, posted a 12.8
rating and a 21 share, or about 17.9 million viewers, according to
Nielsen Media Research's overnight measurement in 48 major markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire,'' in contrast, posted a 10.6 rating and a 17
share, or about 15.4 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Each national rating point equals 1 percent of the total
households with television. Share is the percentage of TV sets
tuned to a specific program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' won the first showdown between the two shows
when ``Survivor'' made its debut last week, though ``Survivor'' did
pull ahead of ``Millionaire'' in key viewer demographics on its
first night. This week, however, ``Survivor'' scored a clean sweep.
Its ratings grew by 12 percent over its debut, while
``Millionaire's'' fell by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among viewers 18 to 49 years old, ``Survivor'' bested
``Millionaire'' with a 7.4 rating and a 25 share, compared with its
rival's 4.5 rating and 15 share. ``The 'Survivor' demos are huge,
especially for a traditionally older-skewing network like CBS,''
said Tom Bierbaum, who closely tracks TV ratings for media trade
publication Inside.com.
</P>
<P>
   The strong ratings signal continuing ratings success for the
remaining 11-week run of ``Survivor,'' said Marc Berman of
Mediaweek.com, who noted that a second installment of the program
is nearly certain.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, General Electric's(GE:NYSE) NBC unit won the ratings
race for the night, powered by Game One of the National Basketball
Association finals between the Los Angeles Lakers and the Indiana
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Viacom(VIA:), which owns CBS, rose 1 7/16, or 2
percent, to 65 3/16 in early afternoon trading.(Viacom finished
regular trading up 15/16, or 1.5 percent, at 64 11/16.)Walt
Disney(DIS:NYSE), which owns ABC, inched up 9/16, or 1 percent, to
40 3/4. (Disney finished regular trading up 1/4, or 1 percent, at
40 7/16.)
</P>
