<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: U.S. ARMS TALKS
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States have agreed to resume talks on arms
control issues in July, a foreign ministry spokeswoman said. Talks
on arms and other topics were suspended after the bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade by NATO, but have gradually been
reopened. China strongly opposes the American quest for a missile
defense system, which China says could negate its own small force
of missiles and set off an arms race. The United States wants
stronger controls on Chinese missile technology exports.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: U.N. FOOD AID
</P>
<P>
   United Nations planes air-dropped an emergency supply of food
into the Dari Souf district in the north, responding to reports of
several deaths as a result of drought conditions. The world
organization has appealed for $67.8 million in emergency aid to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: EMERGENCY EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a suicide bombing that killed Industry Minister
C.V. Guneratne and 23 others, Parliament has extended by a month
emergency powers that allow the government wide latitude in
arresting people, seizing property and restricting the press.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: ECEVIT SEEKS AEGEAN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said he was ready for ``friendly
dialogue'' with Greece over questions of sovereignty in the Aegean
Sea. During a visit to the Aegean town of Marmaris, he said Turks
have ``no claims on another nation's land or sea.'' A senior
adviser to Ecevit recently recommended that Turkey disband its
100,000-man Aegean army.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MAD COW TESTS
</P>
<P>
   France will begin a nationwide testing program next week to look
for mad-cow disease among the nation's 21 million head of cattle.
The government will spend about $40 million a year on the program
to test some 50,000 cows over the age of 2 that die of unknown
causes or exhibit odd behavior. Officials are warning that the
program could show that France has far more cases of the disease
than previously known.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN: JAILED IN DISCO FIRE
</P>
<P>
   A court sentenced three men to prison terms ranging from six to
eight years and a fourth man to three years in juvenile detention
for setting fire to a Goteborg disco in October 1998, killing 63
teen-agers. According to the indictment, the four, all Iranian
immigrants, acted out of anger at having been evicted from the
club.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: CHILD LABOR ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven countries have ratified a treaty in Geneva banning
the worst forms of child labor, the highest number of countries
signing on to any International Labor Organization treaty. Signers
include the United States, Brazil, Canada, Indonesia and Mexico.
The pact bars children from working in dangerous jobs like mining
and in occupations like prostitution, pornography and drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: STRIKERS FREED
</P>
<P>
   Six leaders of a student strike at the National Autonomous
University of Mexico, the last of the strikers still in custody,
were freed on bail of up to $5,700. The six still face criminal
charges, including robbery and assault. They had been imprisoned
since the federal police ended the nine-month strike in February,
and their supporters staged constant protests demanding their
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: MUGABE ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   In a sharply critical report, Amnesty International officials
accused the government of President Robert Mugabe of either
instigating or condoning killings and torture in an effort to
intimidate voters before this month's parliamentary elections. More
than 20 people have been killed in political violence since March.
Government officials denied the accusations.
</P>
</TEXT>
