<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMSON-SALE-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMSON TO SELL 38 DAILIES FOR $1.58 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Canadian publisher Thomson said Thursday that it would sell
two big pieces of its U.S. newspaper holdings, or 38 daily papers,
to Gannett (GCI:NYSE), the largest newspaper publisher in the U.S.,
and to privately held Community Newspaper Holdings for a total of
$1.58 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, based in Arlington, Va., and the publisher of USA
Today, will pay $1.125 billion for 21 daily newspapers clustered in
Louisiana, Maryland's Chesapeake region, Ohio, Wisconsin and Utah.
The newspapers have a combined daily circulation of 466,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other 17 newspapers, with a combined daily circulation of
260,000, will go to Community Newspaper Holdings, based in
Birmingham, Ala., for $455 million. Those papers are clustered in
Indiana, southern Georgia, West Virginia and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, newspaper companies are seeking to ``cluster,'' or
own several newspapers in a region, in order to concentrate their
ability to attract advertising. Previously, they sought to have as
much nationwide coverage as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Toronto-based Thomson, a traditional print
publisher, announced it would sell 54 newspapers in the U.S. and
Canada, which comprise the entirety of its newspaper holdings
except for Toronto's The Globe and Mail. Thomson still has 11 U.S.
papers and 5 Canadian properties on the block.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomson, proceeds from the sale of the newspapers
will be used to reduce debt and provide additional borrowing
capacity as the company focuses more on providing information
online and through CD-roms and computer software.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with that strategy, Thomson said on Monday that it
would buy Primark (PMK:NYSE), a provider of financial, economic and
market research information, for about $842 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper industry is currently undergoing a wave of
consolidation. Earlier on Thursday, Central Newspapers (ECP:NYSE),
publisher of The Arizona Republic and The Indianapolis Star, said
it had hired the investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to
look into a possible sale or ``other business combination.''
</P>
<P>
   And in March, Tribune Co. (TRB:NYSE), publisher of the Chicago
Tribune, announced that it would acquire Times Mirror (TMC:NYSE),
publisher of the Los Angeles Times, for about $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Gannett closed Thursday trading at 61 3/8, up 1/4 or
0.41 percent. There was no activity in post-market trading,
according to Instinet.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Thomson closed at C$51 on the Toronto Stock Exchange,
up C$1.25, or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
