<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      06-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ John Powell sat before an electronic keyboard and a
bank of computer screens and sound consoles in his basement office
overlooking one of the palm-lined canals of Marina Del Rey. A soft
breeze ruffled the bougainvillea to the sound of rustling water.
``I know it looks like I'm on vacation,'' he said, ``but I'm
actually working.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell has composed music for action films (``Face/Off,'' 1997)
and he has composed music for comedies (``Forces of Nature,'' 1999)
and he has composed music for animated films (``Antz,'' 1998). But
now he is putting the finishing touches on the score for a film
that combines all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run'' is the debut feature film for Aardman Animation,
the Oscar-winning stop-motion animation company behind the popular
``Wallace and Gromit'' series of shorts. It opens on June 21 in New
York and Los Angeles and June 23 elsewhere. ``Basically,'' Powell
said, ``It's `The Great Escape,' but with chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell and his collaborator, Harry Gregson-Williams (who also
worked on ``Antz''), have been trying to walk a fine line with the
film's music. The movie is at one level a spoof of prisoner-of-war
escape films but at another it takes its fowl characters very, very
seriously _ tapping into the spit-in-their-eye cockiness of the
soldiers in those movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard to find the tone,'' Powell said. ``The fact
that it's chickens going over the fence instead of soldiers doesn't
make any difference. I'm taking it as seriously as I possibly
can.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate, Powell turned to his console and queued up the
film's opening credit sequence. The heroine, a plucky hen named
Ginger, has been caught making yet another escape attempt and
tossed into solitary confinement. The angry farmer turns to a trio
of hens watching fearfully from behind a wire fence. ``Nobody
escapes from Tweedy's Chicken Farm,'' he growls. The camera pulls
back from the hens' terrified faces to gradually take in the entire
compound, a network of chicken huts surrounded by barbed wire that
looks very much like a World War II prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have certain conventions for this sort of music,'' Powell
said. Beginning with the whistling POW's in ``Bridge on the River
Kwai'' and continuing with the Elmer Bernstein score for ``The
Great Escape,'' there is always a juxtaposition between a somber
military theme and a chirpy melody that is its counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, as the camera pulls back over the opening credits,
the music swells: a militarist fanfare that is gradually overtaken
with a cheery melody meant to symbolize the unvanquished spirit of
the imprisoned poultry.
</P>
<P>
   The composers began about three months ago, sitting at a
keyboard and picking out a series of main tunes. Then they broke
the movie into sections and divided the work. And finally, when
they were finished with their rough drafts, they flew to England
and did it with a live orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's basically how we do it,'' Powell said. ``We just sit
here for a really, really long time.''
</P>
<P>
   `SHAFT' REDUX
</P>
<P>
   John Singleton knew there were certain things he had to have to
make a new version of ``Shaft,'' the quintessential black action
movie of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew going in that there were some essential elements that I
needed,'' said Singleton, 32, the director of ``Boyz N the Hood''
(1991) and ``Rosewood'' (1997), among other films. ``I needed a
cool actor who could talk a lot of trash and people would love, and
I got that with Samuel L. Jackson. And I knew I had to have Isaac
Hayes' strong theme music. And I had to have the sly leather coat
and the clothes, and Giorgio Armani took care of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 28 years since Richard Roundtree (who has a small
role in this new film) first appeared as the black private eye who
knows how to outsmart both the crooks and the cops. This time
around, Jackson plays the original character's nephew, a New York
police officer, but he still finds himself between drug-dealing
uptown crooks and justice-corrupting downtown big shots. There are
differences between the urban world that Roundtree found in 1971
and the one Jackson finds today but there are also a lot of
similarities. ``Basically they are pretty much the same,''
Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' opens on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   For his next project, ``Baby Boy,'' an independent film that he
begins shooting this summer, Singleton said he planned to return to
South Central L.A. and the problems he chronicled in ``Boyz N the
Hood.'' It will be a followup to that film, he said, but not a
sequel. The characters, for instance, will all be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will all take place in the same neighborhood, where I
can show how things have changed and how they haven't,'' he said.
``My goal is to make the most ghetto movie ever made. I want it to
have so much soul that it just jumps off the screen and grabs
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ICING THE STAR
</P>
<P>
   David T. Friendly, producer of ``Big Momma's House,'' in which
Martin Lawrence plays an FBI agent who goes undercover as a
corpulent Southern granny, said the filmmakers were concerned about
how hard they would could push their star in the stifling heat.
Just as the film was in preproduction, Lawrence suffered a
debilitating case of heat stroke after jogging in a sweat suit near
his San Fernando Valley home. He had only barely recovered when
shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who suffered extreme heat stroke and had this
incredible recovery _ miraculous is not too strong a word _ and he
chose to take on this movie where he was going to be in a 50-pound
fat suit and go through three hours of makeup each morning,''
Friendly said. ``He could have chosen to make a movie where a
couple of people were talking in a room for most of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was quite warm on some of the movie's sets, he added.
``Big Momma's House'' opened on June 2 in a surprisingly strong
debut, earning more than $25 million in its first weekend and
almost toppling ``M:I-2'' from the top of the box-office charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set up this cooling tent for him where he could go between
shots,'' he said. ``It had fresh air blown into it from four
different places. And on really hot days, he wore this apparatus
that had ice water running through plastic tubes inside the fat
suit. It was really brave of him to do this movie right after what
happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
