<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-VOTEBUY-0611-C     06-08 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VOTEBUY-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS ELECTION NEARS, FEARS THAT MEXICO'S FEDERAL PROGRAMS ARE
BEING EXPLOITED TO GAIN VOTES
 &HT;    EDS: For purposes of a locator map, San Pedro El Alto is about
100 miles northwest of Mexico City in the state of Mexico.
 &HT;    Advance for use Sunday, June 11
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO EL ALTO, Mexico Maria del Carmen Peralta usually has
little more than tortillas, beans and eggs to feed five children.
</P>
<P>
   Her family has no bathroom and sleeps in a tin-roof shed that
leaks torrents of rain and turns into a virtual icebox at night in
the cold mountain air here. More out of habit than hope, Peralta
and her kids walk almost two miles on weekends to tend a meager
cornfield while her husband, if lucky, gets a couple of dollars a
day as a brick mason's assistant in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Living on the brink, Peralta has grown dependent on Progresa, a
two-year-old federal welfare program for the poorest of Mexico's
poor. She gets $45 a month as long as she keeps her children in
school and attends regular meetings for mothers.
</P>
<P>
   But now Peralta is worried she could lose that aid.
</P>
<P>
   After years of consistently voting for Mexico's 71-year-old
ruling party, she had decided to vote for an opposition candidate
in Mexico's July 2 presidential election. Then she began to think
twice after hearing threats that if she did, she might well lose
Progresa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all talking about it. Should we dare vote against
them?'' said Peralta, 37, a Mazahua Indian who only studied up to
the fifth grade before she was put to work eking out a living in
these isolated high plains 100 north of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Federal poverty and subsidy programs like Progresa are a hot
political potato in Mexico now, just three weeks before the most
competitive presidential election in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   Election watchdog groups and opposition candidates are accusing
loyalists of the ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI,
of exploiting these programs. They say party officials and
bureaucrats _ especially in rural areas _ are trying to coerce
votes from recipients before an election that could be decided by
just a few percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Progresa, which President Ernesto Zedillo began in 1997,
benefits about 2.6 million Mexican families and as many as 14
million individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has 58.7 million eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and the PRI, which has controlled the
presidency since 1929, deny political manipulation of Progresa or
other programs. And they accuse the opposition of making
unsubstantiated accusations as a pre-emptive strike to discredit
the election should the PRI win fair and square.
</P>
<P>
   A number of investigations of coercion are underway, however,
into allegations of threats and the use of government offices to
distribute election propaganda or sign-up forms pledging votes for
the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sure they are using federal programs to coerce votes,''
said Rogelio Gomez, director of Civic Alliance, Mexico's main
citizens' election-watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many government workers are saying they are being pressured to
pass out sign-up sheets where people write down their name and
election-card number and pledge to vote for the PRI,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   After documenting complaints, Civic Alliance is sending them to
authorities at Mexico's Federal Elections Institute, as well as a
special congressional commission and a federal prosecutor's office
for election crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the group is in a race against time because the election is
so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unequal battle,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Almada, PRI secretary of elections, said, ``Coercion of
votes is a crime. But like all crimes it must be proved.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Pedro el Alto, where approximately 360 women are enrolled
in the Progresa program, Progresa worker Lucina Bernal told Cox
Newspapers a local PRI leader approached her on the street and told
her she would suffer ``consequences'' if she didn't make sure that
the recipients voted for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I could lose my job,'' Bernal said. ``But in this
program you are not supposed to mix politics with assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   She said other Progresa workers in town, however, have succumbed
to pressure to urge recipients to vote for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a lie,'' said Baltazar Lalaurel, a PRI leader in the
region of the state of Mexico where San Pedro El Alto is. ``This is
part of the campaign against us by the (rival) National Action
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic Alliance, Gomez said, began receiving similar complaints
about pressure tactics and the abuse of federal programs about
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints began coming in following a rally last month
where PRI leaders exhorted Mexico's 3 million government workers _
many organized in PRI unions _ to campaign for the party's
presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Handing out gifts of food, T-shirts, building supplies and even
medicines is standard fare during political campaigns in Mexico and
is not necessarily illegal. Public employees are free to support
the candidates of their choice. But it is illegal to use
government-owned supplies, money, offices _ or one's position _ to
coerce voters' allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is passing out forms to public employees and asking them
to circulate them, hoping to use this network to attract at least
12 million pledges for votes for Labastida, according to published
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Some bureaucrats have been discovered using their jobs or
offices to circulate the forms among recipients of programs they
administer. Others have been caught strategizing at work.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday bureaucrats at Mexico's national family-welfare
institute gathered in an auditorium during work hours to discuss
supporting the Labastida campaign. The national director later
admitted to a newspaper that the meeting was a ``mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chiapas and Veracruz states, Gomez said, there are numerous
complaints about Progresa workers attempting to use their positions
to garner rural votes for the PRI. The countryside, where 30
percent of voters live, is a traditional stronghold for the ruling
party
</P>
<P>
   Civic Alliance has already documented one case, Gomez said,
where a Progresa worker in Chiapas circulated forms and unlawfully
obtained signatures or fingerprints of a number of welfare
recipients, along with the numbers of their voter credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be hard for Americans to understand this, but in our
culture this is like a magic act. If these people ask you for your
voter-credential number, you believe you are promising to vote for
them,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Civic Alliance is about to finish an investigation into similar
alleged coercion by federal workers in Oaxaca state who administer
Procampo, a subsidy program for farmers, Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Mexico, Mazahua Indian Everardo Mendoza Vasquez
said he was given a PRI-related sign-up sheet to distribute to
neighbors who receive Procampo in the town of San Felipe de Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza is the Procampo coordinator in that town and he said the
form came from representatives in a local government office that
handles Procampo.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Human Network 2000,'' the form is part of the PRI
get-out-the-vote campaign in the state of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who doesn't support the PRI, said he refused to
circulate the sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to fool people with this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said he doesn't think traditional PRI handouts of
T-shirts, buckets and building materials are as persuasive in
securing votes as they once were. But federal programs, he said,
``are serious. They help some people survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed that every vote is going to count in this tight
race, in which Labastida appears to be neck-in-neck with Vicente
Fox, candidate of the National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   This week Fox began television commercials telling viewers not
to ``fear'' voting for him. ``No public servant will lose his job.
No one will lose Progresa,'' he says in the commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Mexico will be critical in the election because it
contains the second largest number of votes in the whole country
after Mexico City. Vote-buying allegations have surfaced here
before. In last year's gubernatorial race, which the PRI won, a
survey found that nearly one-third of voters in the state had
received an inducement to vote _ including food and agricultural
subsidies, building materials and temporary government jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The same company that did that survey, MUND Opinion Services in
Mexico City, also did a survey recently that found that 65 percent
of Progresa recipients nationwide would vote for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
