<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-PROSPERITY-HNS &LR;      06-08 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PROSPERITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WARNS OF INTERNET THREAT TO PRIVACY &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITTIER, Calif. _ As he prepares to announce a series of
domestic initiatives building on the booming economy, Al Gore on
Thursday addressed the negative side of the technology revolution _
the increasing availability of personal information on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to law enforcement officers, Gore endorsed a series of
measures that would make it harder for people to obtain
confidential information, such as Social Security numbers,
financial data and medical information, now easily accessible on
the World Wide Web for a price.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president announced that the Justice Department is
asking Congress to pass a law making it a federal crime to sell
Social Security numbers, which often are the key to obtaining other
personal information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your personal information should not be misused or abused,''
Gore said at a Los Angeles County sheriff's training facility.
``Today you can leave a trail of virtual footprints that are too
easy to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was introduced by Tim Remsburg, whose daughter, Amy Boyer,
was killed by man who found out where she worked by purchasing her
Social Security number from a Web site for $45.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that what happened to Amy was wrong and could have
and should have been avoided,'' said Remsburg, who met Gore at a
town hall meeting during the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, backed by Gore and sponsored by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Rep. Ed. Markey, D-Mass., would make it a
civil and criminal offense to either sell or purchase Social
Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also has backed separate measures that would
protect private medical records, prosecute so-called cyberstalking,
and enforce financial privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore shared the stage Thursday with Los Angeles County Sheriff
Lee Baca, who endorsed Republican Sen. John McCain during the
presidential primaries. He has not backed Gore or his GOP rival,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore warned of the Internet's potential threats to
privacy, he also said the new technology had transformed the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the vice president will launch a new phase of his
campaign to stress advancements in the economy under the Clinton
administration and how Gore hopes to capitalize on that prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   On what Gore aides are calling his ``progress and prosperity
tour,'' the vice president will hit key battleground states to
announce domestic initiatives made possible by the healthy federal
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has said he will advocate shoring up Medicare
by ensuring that the payroll tax, now collected for the purpose of
financing the health insurance program for the elderly, is not
diverted for any other purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare hospitalization fund is expected to run out of
money in 2025.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is tentatively scheduled to roll out the Medicare
initiative in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days the vice president will likely visit
Wisconsin, Kentucky, Pennsylvania and Ohio and talk about the
environment, health care, education and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting next week I'm going to be talking about things we
must do to open up a new era of prosperity and progress, to build
upon a foundation of economic success we've had the last few years,
to keep that prosperity going and extend it to all who have not yet
shared in it,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has been frustrated because the good economic
times have not translated into stronger voter support for the
candidate. A Bloomberg Poll released Thursday found that voters
believed Bush would do a better job on the economy than Gore by a
margin of 42 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane denied the campaign was troubled by
the lack of credit the public was giving the Democratic candidate.
He said the point of the ``progress and prosperity'' tour was ``to
remind people just how far we've come in the last 7{ years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
