u l BC-MACNELLY-REMEMBERED06     06-08 0182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACNELLY-REMEMBERED0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This is for use with stories about Jeff MacNelly
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost the Michelangelo of editorial cartooning,'' said
Dayton Daily News editorial cartoonist Mike Peters, a longtime
friend of Jeff MacNelly. ``He was truly one of the great
cartoonists of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters recalled that he met MacNelly in 1970, soon after Peters
had begun working for the Dayton Daily News and as MacNelly was
beginning his career at the Richmond News Leader. ``He depressed
me,'' Peters said. ``I just met this guy whose work was so good,
that I left the convention early to go work on my own cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   From that day, Peters said the strength of MacNelly's work
continued to push Peters and other editorial cartoonists to be
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like light shining through a crystal, reflecting colors, he
had the ability to observe the same things you and I see, and to
know what is usable and what is not,'' Peters said.
</P>
