A8420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOKWARS-FILM-REVIEW-     06-08 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKWARS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOOKWARS': SELLING BOOKS ON THE STREET IN A QUALITY-OF-LIFE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The documentary ``Bookwars,'' a minor film about the
book vendors who populate the streets of Manhattan, does not get
into the wars until the last 20 minutes of the picture. Before that
section, which deals with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's ``quality of
life'' mission _ which, among other things, sought to clear
Manhattan streets of vendors _ ``Bookwars'' is a slice of true
life.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Rosette, who directed, edited and narrated the movie (it
begins with the credit ``A Rosette flick'') uses the phrase
``adventures in the book trade,'' and though it's not as
high-concept as ``Bookwars,'' the statement is more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The film grazes the culture of the people who sell books al
fresco; Rosette spent time peddling literature and other volumes on
New York's streets himself and uses a mix of videotape and film to
capture fleeting moments and eccentric characters. There's Pete,
who's the elder, and Rick, who's in training to be a magician, and
Paul, who's referred to as ``the kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosette also shows the kinds of reading material found in
different areas. The Avenue of the Americas ``had more comic books
and porno magazines,'' he says in his mellow voice-over. ``West
Fourth Street was heavy into literature and philosophy. `Naked
Lunch' is a best seller, and `On the Road.''' To the surprise of
absolutely no one watching the film, Rosette plied his trade on
West Fourth. Cool jazz by artists like the organist Jack McDuff can
be heard on the soundtrack, complementing the unruffled narration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bookwars'' provides a glimpse into the way these guys find
materials, scouting yard sales and libraries that are getting rid
of unwanted books. When the police start harassing the street
vendors, pressing them to produce taxpayer identification numbers
or confiscating their wares, a little tension is introduced.
Rosette notes that the First Amendment offers protection for the
street vendors, a protection that a court ruling emphasizes. Yet
the assaults by the city and New York University on the vendors'
livelihood does take a toll, driving many off the streets, and into
a few happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   By that point, ``Bookwars'' _ which ambled through mini-profiles
of Rosette's fellow vendors, all men though not much is made of
this _ is nearly over. There are very few memorable moments: a
gray-haired man comes to one table looking for a paperback edition
of ``The Subterraneans,'' which featured the man modeling on its
cover. The movie is like spending an idle afternoon browsing, and
not buying.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BOOKWARS'
</P>
<P>
   Produced, directed and edited by Jason Rosette; director of
photography, Rosette; music by Rich Goldstein and Little Muddy;
released by Avatar Films. At the Cinema Village.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 79 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Peter Whitney, Rick Sherman, Marvin, Paul, Everett
Shapiro, Polish Joe, Al Mappo, Margueritte, Ron Harris and Jason
Rosette (Street Booksellers).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
