A8427 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HARVARD-COMMENCEMENT-     06-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-COMMENCEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD ALUMNI HEAR SCHOLARLY DISCUSSION OF GLOBALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Harvard-Nigerian)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The punch line of Amartya Sen's opening joke,
a sort of erudite form of self-deprecation, sparked a chuckle among
many alumni in attendance Thursday as the renowned Indian economist
delivered Harvard's keynote commencement address.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Dryden, the English poet, has offered the sobering
thought that honor is `but an empty bubble,' '' the Nobel Laureate
said in opening a weighty speech on the pros and cons of globalism.
``But we honorary graduates refuse to be put off by old Dryden _
especially today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that Dryden was only trying to rhyme with
the previous line of his poem,'' Sen said. ``Having said, `War, he
sung, was toil and trouble,' it would have been difficult to resist
the temptation to rhyme it with, `Honor but an empty bubble...' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was a commencement speech, perhaps, only deliverable to an
audience of Harvard alumni and graduates. The dense address,
sprinkled with citations from Francis Bacon and John Kenneth
Galbraith, even included a bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the students in Harvard Yard Thursday afternoon,
however, were less concerned with the words than the fact the
keynote speech was delivered to the annual meeting of the Harvard
Alumni Association instead of to the graduating class. The
students' ceremony was held in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it reflects the priorities of the university,'' said
Isaac Hodes, 23, a social studies major. ``The university is a
corporation. And this shows how they're more interested in catering
to donors than students.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rebecca Symington, 31, who graduated Thursday from Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government, pointed out that the students are now
alumni. ``Tomorrow, we've been invited to an alumni brunch,'' she
said. ``I guess they're starting early on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning ceremony featured a fellow graduate, Arese Ukpoma
Carrington. A survivor of Nigeria's civil war who later became a
doctor and married a US ambassador, she urged students to uphold
social justice and promote public health throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   At the afternoon ceremony, men festooned in large black top hats
and others clad in kilts and playing Scottish marches on bagpipes
led hundreds of gray-haired alumni to seats set in rows across
Harvard Yard.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonial moment was flush with pride and nostalgia for
Loretta Cornell, who graduated Radcliffe in 1945. Led by the
university band, she and many others in attendance sang a song
about their alma mater with as much enthusiasm as some generate for
the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very emotional experience,'' said Cornell, who has
returned for commencement almost every year since 1970. ``It just
brings back so many memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, before the official keynote speech, Harvard featured
another Nobel Laureate, Irish poet Seamus Heaney. He delivered
several brief poems. One evoked the joy and anguish of a student's
search for knowledge. Another focused on how Harvard must steer
clear of elitism and remain open to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of Sen's speech was as much as globalization has
helped spread wealth throughout the world, it has also contributed
to increasing inequality. While the pros may outweigh the cons of
globalization, he said, the cons can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot, to use Francis Bacon's word's, let these broader
doubts (about globalization) pass `lightly without intervention,'
'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SNAKEBIT-PREVIEW-LADN     06-08 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKEBIT-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE GUY FINISHES FIRST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On perennial TV powerhouse ``N.Y.P.D. Blue,'' Bill Brochtrup
plays a sweet, sensitive guy who's always taking care of others.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Snakebit,'' the award-winning comic drama now at West
Hollywood's Coast Playhouse, Brochtrup plays another sweet,
sensitive guy who's always taking care of others.
</P>
<P>
   Now guess what kind of guy Bill Brochtrup seems in person?
(Hint: You probably wouldn't cast him as the lead in ``Richard
III.'')
</P>
<P>
   But don't be too sure. Although he has been installed on
``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' for seven seasons as the kind, openly gay and
preternaturally efficient police administrative aide John Irvin,
Brochtrup's acting career has been anything but uniform. He's
hoping to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that typecasting is kind of endemic to acting,'' says
Brochtrup while taking a between-rehearsals break from ``Snakebit''
at a West Hollywood bistro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Franz has played a lot of cops. He played like 37 cops
or something on TV shows. Those guys on `The Sopranos' played a lot
of mobsters and Italian guys. There's a certain sensibility that
people have that makes it easy to cast them in things. So when
there's a gay character on something, someone will usually call my
agent. But I think we're all in acting trying to show that we can
do more than people think we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a few months off from ministering to the emotional needs
of Franz's homophobic Andy Sipowicz, Brochtrup, 37, is proving with
``Snakebit'' that he can swing from big-budget TV and film to off-
Broadway theater without skipping a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Written by actor/playwright David Marshall Grant, a Tony nominee
for his performance as a closeted right-wing Mormon lawyer in
``Angels in America,'' ``Snakebit'' shares certain thematic
similarities with Tony Kushner's Pulitzer Prize-winning drama about
love and morality in the age of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Brochtrup plays Michael, an innately decent and
compassionate gay L.A. social worker suffering through a series of
personal crises, including a recent breakup with his boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   His world gets further shaken by a visit from a volatile
straight couple: self-centered actor Jonathan (Christopher Gartin)
and former actress (and Michael's ex-lover) Jenifer (Andrea
Bendewald).
</P>
<P>
   The play enjoyed a long run last spring and summer at the Grove
Playhouse and Century Center in New York, and received both Drama
Desk and Outer Critics Circle award nominations for best play (it
lost out on both to ``Wit,'' starring Grant's ``Angels'' colleague
Kathleen Chalfant).
</P>
<P>
   New York Times theater critic Peter Marks described ``Snakebit''
as a ``deeply satisfying comedy-drama about days of waning love and
friendship in Los Angeles,'' and praised Brochtrup's ``knockout
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. engagement will be brief (through July 2), partly to
accommodate some of its participants' fall TV shooting schedules.
But Brochtrup says he was thrilled when the play's producers asked
him to reprise his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very Los Angeles kind of a play,'' says Brochtrup, who
was born in Southern California and raised in Tacoma, Wash. ``I've
lived here for quite a few years, and when I read this it struck me
as the truest thing that I had read in a long time. It was about
people I knew, in their 30s, living in Los Angeles, the way that
they speak, the things they were talking about, just struck me as
being very true, very real.''
</P>
<P>
   Brochtrup notes some parallels in the emotional makeup of
Michael and John Irvin _ up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a similarity in that I think this character (Michael)
takes in a great deal of what goes on around him and is extremely
sensitive to the needs of the other people at the expense of his
own needs at times. That's kind of what the play is about to me, is
Michael's learning to stand up for himself and to say, 'This is who
I am, these are my needs, this is what I have to do for me. I can't
be there for you and you and you and you and everyone else's
problems.' We haven't seen that happen to John Irvin.''
</P>
<P>
   Both on TV and in theater, Brochtrup, who is gay, has frequently
portrayed gay characters. Two seasons ago at the Pasadena
Playhouse, in the world premiere of Jonathan Tolin's ``If Memory
Serves,'' he portrayed a famous actress's gay personal assistant
who views life as one vast ``Mildred Pierce'' remake.
</P>
<P>
   In another career-building role, he played a saintly,
AIDS-stricken male model in the off-Broadway drama ``Raft of the
Medusa,'' which drew him to an ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' producer's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running ABC hit not only has made Brochtrup practically
a household name: His portrayal of John Irvin also has twice earned
awards from the Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation for its
positive representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's limiting,'' he says of playing so many gay
characters, `'but I don't worry about that, for a couple reasons.
One, I think that I try only to play characters that I think are
well-written. I pass on a lot of things that I don't think are
well-written, gay characters and straight characters. So if I can
play gay characters my whole life who are as well-written as
'Snakebit' and 'N.Y.P.D. Blue,' it's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brochtrup plans to get out of town for a few weeks this summer
after ``Snakebit'' closes. He'll have to hurry back though:
``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' resumes shooting Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he was switching between ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' and
``Snakebit,'' his mind and body kept hop-scotching between coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go in on these bright, sunny days (in L.A.) and put on
these overcoats, and pretend it's New York. Then I went to New York
(to do 'Snakebit') and we put on shorts and sandals and walked
around like in a Beechwood Canyon house. It was a very strange
experience. And now it's finally getting it right, to be in the
right place doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Who says nice guys finish last in Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
What: ``Snakebit.'' &QL; 
Where: Coast Playhouse, 8325 Santa Monica Blvd., West Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Thursdays through Saturday, 3 p.m. Sundays; through
July 2. &QL; 
Tickets: $25. &QL; 
Information: (310) 289-2999.
</P>
</TEXT>
