r e BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-L     06-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF SILENT FILM STAR NOT KEEPING QUIET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, the great physical comedy of silent film greats
such as Charlie Chaplin would seem wonderfully suited for transfer
to the Internet. The films don't even need sound to have an impact,
and the jerkiness of the old films is an odd echo of what happens
when Net congestion hits a Webcast.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to see any of Chaplin's great features legally
available on the Internet any time soon, said his daughter,
Josephine, who is the liaison between the comedian's descendants
and Association Chaplin, the Paris-based organization devoted to
preserving his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anything on the Net,'' said Josephine Chaplin.
``It's such a small screen. It becomes something banal. To put it
on the Net, it seems degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is a concern about loss of control over the
comedian's work, because his work could easily be chopped up
online, Josephine Chaplin said.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's on the Net, ``We don't know where it's going,'' she
said. ``People are cutting things up, there's a question of
quality. We just want to keep it in its entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans !ital!can look forward to seeing more of Chaplin's work on
DVD, however. At the end of next year, the family will begin
working with a new distributor, enhancing DVDs of 11 Chaplin
features with the massive archive of outtakes, photographs and
other archival material compiled through the Association Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest will be the shots Chaplin cut when he
reissued his films in 1971. The family won't, however, release the
films' original versions, even though they had been in the public
eye for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through and made the cuts, which were his final
cuts,'' Josephine Chaplin said. ``They were very good cuts. We'll
just put out the final versions. It was his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Chaplin's best-known, and loved, works will be on display
tonight in beautiful form at UCLA's Royce Hall, when the Los
Angeles Chamber Orchestra plays with a newly struck print of his
1936 satire of the Industrial Age, ``Modern Times.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which will tour 25 other cities around the world with
live orchestras over the next 18 months, still has some things to
say about technology and humanity three-quarters of a century and
one Information Revolution after it was created. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beat it
</P>
<P>
   One of the more smirk-inducing announcements of last month's
Electronic Entertainment Expo was word that singer Michael Jackson
will be among the wild array of virtual boxers in the sequel to
Midway's fun, funny Ready 2 Rumble videogame.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who apparently is a big fan of the original R2R,
contacted Midway about being in the sequel, and subsequently had
his dance and boxing moves motion-captured, the company said. Ready
2 Rumble: Round 2, due in November on five gaming platforms, also
will include Los Angeles Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal, other
secret celebrities and 11 of the original game's fighters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hobby horse
</P>
<P>
   America's gone to the birds, says Brent Cohen, the chief
operating officer of eHobbies.com (at www.ehobbies.com). Or more
properly, it's spending a lot of money on birding, as much as $34
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Santa Monica-based eHobbies has begun selling birding
supplies, like field guides, feeders, binoculars and the like,
including all the products of the biggest birding house, Kalmbach
Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has jumped into astronomy and comic books and
action figures. The site will offer about 7,000 comics and figures,
along with apparel, posters and related collectibles, and recently
acquired Next Planet Over, one of the better Web sites in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   And for amateur astronomers (who have made huge contributions to
the field, identifying all sorts of heavenly bodies), they'll offer
everything from inexpensive computer software and books to $5,000
telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   EHobbies already sold radio-controlled toys, diecast models,
rocketry and trains, and tools and supplies for all those areas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Still smarting
</P>
<P>
   It billed itself as ``the first smart club,'' but the Hollywood
edition of New York's beloved Knitting Factory isn't feeling so
smart this week. It won't make its scheduled Wednesday debut party
because of construction and permit delays, spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   The entire club is to be wired to the Web, to pump programming
to and from KnitMedia's fine Internet site
(www.knittingfactory.com). A wad of interesting acts already booked
into the club were left scrambling for other venues because of the
delays.
</P>
<P>
   When it !ital!does open, the club will be located next to the
Hollywood Entertainment Museum in the heart of Hollywood Boulevard.
Best guess for a more realistic opening date is three to five
weeks. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. This column and
related material can also be found all week at dailynews.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
