<HEADLINE>
HOSTILE ENVIRONMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients on or after Sun., June
11) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `toight' refers to June 11) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Orleans has always been considered a big sinkhole of lust
and corruption metaphorically in Hollywood entertainment, but in
``On Hostile Ground,'' the city is literally depicted as a seamy,
praetorian sinkhole. This disaster teleflick expends a lot of
energy convincing viewers of the science that posits the Big Easy
as a Big Queasy _ huge underground pockets are giving way, sucking
the populace down with them _ but of course it's really more
interested in the requisite splashy carnage than connecting the
rudimentary narrative dots.
</P>
<P>
   We're in the season of the big, dumb summer movie, and this is
TV's version: spectacle on a budget. It follows the tried-and-true
formula that ``Jaws'' made evergreen way back when: Something's
threatening the townsfolk, but addressing it, even admitting it,
would dry up those tasty tourist dollars, so everyone plays ostrich
and ignores the problems until all hell breaks loose.
</P>
<P>
   John Corbett stars as Matt, an engineer haunted by a past
mistake (although since he's our hero, it's clear that the mistake
wasn't !ital!his mistake). He's one half of the city's power
couple; the other is his girlfriend, Allison Beauchamp (Jessica
Steen), a mayoral assistant whose perky niece (Brittany Daniel) is
in town to party down during Mardi Gras. Matt and Allison are the
quintessential cute couple, but his gun-shy nature is in need of a
good natural disaster to prod him into tying the knot.
</P>
<P>
   Duly noted. So when bodies start disappearing down sinkholes,
Matt urges caution _ pointing to a crack in a French Quarter
sidewalk, he barks, ``This wasn't here two days ago!'' But the
requisite weaselly mayoral media attache (Peter Stebbings) doctors
evidence so the mayor allows the revelry to continue unabated.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you have no story if a guy advises caution and
authorities heed his advice and then nothing of note happens, so of
course the mayor's is a disastrous decision from which only Matt
can save the city. Naturally, said perky niece will be endangered
while wearing a white Lycra catsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of semi-special effects create some modest disaster _
if your eyes don't pop, they won't shut tight, either. Corbett and
Steen lead an admirably committed cast (although no one in the
whole movie manages a Southern, let alone Cajun, accent). Its score
blends zydeco and generic action-thriller music incongruously yet
somewhat successfully _ and therefore, amusingly. It's likely no
dumber _ nor smarter _ than any of the other formulaic stuff you'll
see this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ----- &QL; 
The show: ``On Hostile Ground.'' &QL; 
What: Thriller about a sinkhole swallowing New Orleans during Mardi
Gras. &QL; 
The stars: John Corbett, Jessica Steen, Brittany Daniel. &QL; 
Where: TBS. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight; also Saturday and June 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
