<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-08 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY LOOMS LARGE FOR PIERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The ball looked as big as a melon to Mary Pierce, and
she lashed out at it boldly, hungrily, with both hands, like her
man, Roberto Alomar, about to devour a hanging curve.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis, billed as the best tennis player on this planet,
was on her sneakered heels. She was one point _ one swing _ from
defeat, and all France was poised to celebrate. It was in Mary's
hands: a place in the final of the French Open, which no
French-blooded woman has won for 33 years . . . and she blew it.
</P>
<P>
   She backhanded the ball well beyond the baseline, and the mass
groan of 15,166 patriots stuffed into tumultuous Stade Roland
Garros could be heard all the way to Montreal, Pierce's birthplace.
Match point had vanished, and Hingis clung to her serve to 5-5,
eventually winning the second set and pulling even.
</P>
<P>
   Would there be another sip for Mighty Mary, who is about as
French as Coca-Cola, but today is being toasted across the country
as a commodity as precious as a great Champagne? Could the
American-bred, French passport-clutching Pierce, frequently the
victim of nerves in the chaos of this claypit, firm up enough to
disregard the bungled opportunity and keep French hearts from
bleeding?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, saluted by none other than the president of the
Repblic, Jacques Chirac, was a resounding, ``Oui!'' Over the phone,
following Mary's momentous 6-4, 5-7, 6-2, triumph, he, a tennis
hacker, declared that she is Jacques's favorite jock.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else's, too. As far as Chirac and the citizenry are
concerned, she's as French as Joan of Arc, Edith Piaf, and Madame
Dafarge, even though she hasn't lived in the country longer than a
few months, some time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am American and I am French, and I'm proud of both,'' said
Pierce, offspring of a French mother and American father, after
breaking Hingis's strangehold on her: seven wins in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary is international,'' said Nathalie Tauziat, the leading
French player of the last decade, and at first resentful of Pierce
trying to fit into her country's Federation Cup team. ``And we are
glad to have part of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough. The United States had its chance for her sporting
allegiance, but the US Tennis Association declined giving financial
support she needed, wary of her overbearing father.
</P>
<P>
   That first match point appeared hopefully and disappeared
darkly. Throughout the stadium and the land, witnesses mourned,
fearing that the chance for a successor to 1967's victor, Francoise
Durr, was gone for another year. But the 33-year-old drought will
end Saturday _ if Mary can solve the cunning of Conchita Martinez.
Conchita won Spanish bragging rights in a 6-1, 6-2, self-liberating
defeat of three-time champ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, against whom
she had been 3-13.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce conceded, ``Yeah, I was nervous on that match point.
Trying for a little too much.'' She had just undergone 2 1/2 hours
of IV'ing and other treatment for a ``startling, first ever attack
of leg cramps. I was contemplating suicide at that moment,'' she
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just really . . . tried not to get upset. I kept
thinking that was a chance I let slip, but I tried to stay calm in
the third. I still get nervous. I still get tight. But I've learned
from experience to stay relaxed and not worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like 1994,'' she said, recalling her debut as a
French finalist, a loss to Sanchez Vicario, 6-4, 6-4. ``I was 18.
I'd been playing great (crunching defending champion Steffi Graf,
6-2, 6-2, in the semis), but I started thinking about it too much.
I thought, `Oh, God, I'll have to give my victory speech in French'
_ and my French was poor then. I practiced the whole night and I
was a nervous wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous wreckage has been strewn throughout her emotional life,
but Pierce is clearly overcoming. And recovering from the mental
(sometimes physical) bruising by dear old dad, Jim Pierce, the man
who put her on a court and drove her toward the heights. She had to
get a restraining order against him. However, as she gains greater
self-belief, there has been something of a rapprochement. They talk
on the phone; she accepts tennis advice.
</P>
<P>
   Her romance with Alomar, another competitive type, and
``newfound religious faith'' have been stabilizing. Fingering the
rosary around her neck at difficult moments, this Mary hailed
another one, then gunned groundies that kept Hingis without a
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But 53 long minutes passed before Pierce got her second look at
a decisive point. Though her legs were pinched and buckling in the
jaws of cramps, she seized this one _ in both hands again, a
roaring backhand that Hingis couldn't handle. Court Central erupted
as though Vesuvius while she blew kisses to the throng, and planted
a real one on Hingis, her doubles partner and superior for so long.
Pierce last floored the kid four years ago, when Hingis was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time Mary was in the final,'' said Hingis. ``I was
13, playing the junior final against Sonia Jeyaseelan. I won but
she didn't. But today, Mary ran me too much with those drives from
corner to corner, more than two hours (2:10). I had come back from
that match point, but by the time I saw her stretching herself, in
trouble with cramps, I was too much tired. It was too late for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brilliant performance, Mary solidly controlled points from
the baseline, punctuating the backcourt assault with surprise
rushes for scoring volleys. She busted Hingis for 3-1 in the last
set, but Martina retaliated to 2-3 as the multitude seethed and
squirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Pierce's day in the sunshine and fair, if tricky,
winds. Roland Garros has been a haunted house for Hingis. Loser of
last year's uproarious final to Steffi Graf, upset in the final of
1997 by the fleeting Iva Majoli and the 1998 semi by Monica Seles,
she has felt the weight of crowds pulling against her, the cocky
prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it,'' said Hingis, a pro not alibi-ing. From 2-3
down, she melted as Pierce made her throttling move, permitting
only four more points.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce stroked to 5-2, and the crowd bobbed deliriously, doing
the wave for a couple of minutes, a prelude to their lady's washing
away Hingis's serve in the concluding game.
</P>
<P>
   Once more the match point ball looked big, as big as the moon,
and Pierce made a mighty moon shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
