<HEADLINE>
XCHANGE STRENGTHENS CUSTOMER-ANALYSIS ROLE WITH ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Xchange Inc., which helps the likes of Staples Inc. and
DaimlerChrysler take information from their customer databases and
fashion it into targeted marketing campaigns, has signed a
definitive agreement to buy CustomerAnalytics, a privately held
Dallas firm.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock transaction is completed later this month,
CustomerAnalytics would receive about 5.2 million shares of Xchange
stock. On Nasdaq, Xchange shares rose $2.1875 Thursday to close at
$23.125. Based on that price, the deal could have a value of around
$120 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the fast-growing arena of customer-relationship management,
Xchange aims to be a soup-to-nuts provider. By buying
CustomerAnalytics, its third acquisition in less than a year,
Xchange adds one more entree to its menu of services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This helps close the loop for them,'' said Tom Richards,
research director of Meridian Research, which follows the
customer-relationship industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, CustomerAnalytics had revenues of $17.7 million, much
of it coming from financial services clients such as FleetBoston
Financial and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. In 1999, Xchange earned $1.1
million on revenues of $43.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Xchange, a Boston company that until recently was known as
Exchange Applications Inc., began life as a firm that composed
direct-mail letters and scripts for telemarketers on behalf of
financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, it has sought to broaden its range and pursue
clients outside the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Xchange bought a Seattle company that specializes in
marketing on the Web and with e-mails. In April, Xchange bought a
Boston database mining company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to help our clients optimize relationships with
their customers,'' said Dan Haley, Xchange's chief deal officer.
</P>
<P>
   With Xchange's help, clients analyze their databases to identify
their most profitable customers and to predict future behavior
based on a customer's past habits.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Xchange helps clients use that information to devise
marketing campaigns to very narrow segments of profitable
customers. Those campaigns can use e-mails, direct mail, or a
telemarketer's pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Xchange seeks to measure the effectiveness of those
marketing campaigns to determine which ones might be used again.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a bank client, Xchange's software package might
be used at the bank's central office. CustomerAnalytics specializes
in a simpler package that can be deployed to all of the bank's
branch offices.
</P>
<P>
   When a customer comes into a branch, the system gives a branch
manager the customer's history and can offer suggestions for
pitching the customer additional bank products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PLOTLESS-BALLETS-2TAK     06-08 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLOTLESS-BALLETS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DRAMA OF DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance preceded drama in ancient days and the tension
between the two forms is felt today in choreography. Ballet, more
than modern dance, has seen the comeback of an old opera-house
genre, the full-evening narrative spectacle. But plotless ballets,
sometimes dramatic in an abstract way, continue to reign supreme
among American choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   To tell a story or not is far from a burning issue: dance-drama
is no longer a contradiction in terms. Nonetheless, the great
divide in aesthetics exists, is mirrored in public taste, and is
embodied this weekend at American Ballet Theater and New York City
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling dominates in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' John
Cranko's boisterous treatment of Shakespeare's comedy, which has
its company premiere Friday night at Ballet Theater, with two
performances Saturday at the Metropolitan Opera House. A high point
is Kate's rollicking romance with a drumstick as Petruchio tries to
starve her into submission. Cranko was a man of the theater and
``Shrew'' was a big hit in the Stuttgart Ballet's debut season in
New York in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if no one goes to ``Swan Lake'' just for the story, I am
not sure one attends ``Shrew'' for the dancing. I once timed the
ballet's opening moments to see how long it took before anyone
danced a conventional step: 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cranko had two wonderful virtuoso leads, Marcia Haydee and
Richard Cragun, for whom he created his typical Soviet-style duets.
But in 1969 ``Shrew'' masked the weak technique of a young
ensemble. ``Shrew'' is a brilliant exercise in blocked-out movement
rather than real choreography. It is dance poor in certain respects
but expressive physical theater in its storytelling. Compare
``Shrew'' to ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' the musical based on the same
material, and you won't miss the words. Domenico Scarlatti, whose
music is used in the ballet, is no Cole Porter, but then Porter is
no Scarlatti.
</P>
<P>
   Across Lincoln Center plaza, New York City Ballet makes the case
in its Diamond Project (a series of new works) that pure form in
dance can be expressive in itself.
</P>
<P>
   This was an idea shared by the French poet Stephane Mallarme,
who saw ballet as an art that invoked an ideal through abstraction.
The female dancer, in his view, could be part of a narrative but
she operated on a level akin to poetry: like a poem, her dancing
required no ``scribe,'' as he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Plotless choreography, as promoted by City Ballet's co-founder,
George Balanchine, constantly reveals rich levels of formal
structures and combinations of steps in relation to music. But it
can also be too plain, with nothing behind a classroom display.
</P>
<P>
   Pure dance has nevertheless been the norm in the Diamond
Project, established in 1992 by Peter Martins, City Ballet's
artistic director, to encourage new choreographers. The latest
premiere, Christopher d'Amboise's ``Triptych,'' will be performed
Saturday afternoon at the New York State Theater, and Kevin O'Day's
``Swerve Poems'' is to be repeated Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth and ninth premieres are by Martins on June 17 and
Miriam Mahdaviani on June 20. The Martins work will be seen along
with his ``Todos Buenos Aires'' and ``Slonimsky's Earbox.'' Both of
these were performed at the May 3 gala that included Christopher
Wheeldon's ``Mercurial Manoeuvres'' and Helgi Tomasson's ``Prism.''
</P>
<P>
   So successful were these four plotless ballets that one was
obliged to rethink some occasional dark thoughts, namely that City
Ballet should widen its range. It could even revert to the dramatic
works and eclectic repertory it had from 1948 through the early
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Martins smiles at news conferences when asked if any
choreographers would be drummed out of the New York State Theater
should they attempt a story ballet under his watch. There is no
rule, he replies, except that the classical vocabulary must be used
by every choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   City Ballet today is the company as it was redefined by
Balanchine from the 1970s until his death in 1983. Like many
artists in the twilight of their careers, he pared his work down to
essentials. Essentials in the Balanchine canon meant identifying
music with dancing. Virtually all new ballets were suddenly named
after their musical titles and older ones like Balanchine's
``Ballet Imperial'' were stripped down to plain costumes and
retitled after a score (``Tchaikovsky Piano Concerto No. 2'').
</P>
<P>
   The process was carried on with a vengeance in the festivals
that Balanchine organized in tribute to composers: Stravinsky (1972
and 1982), Ravel (1975) and Tchaikovsky (1981). Even a Balanchine
work that seems to hover around the edges of dance-drama like the
1980 ``Robert Schumann's `Davidsbundlertanze,''' given this season,
is really about its music. Here, Balanchine seemed to tell a story
about a Schumann-like figure descending into madness against Rouben
Ter-Arutunian's neo-Romantic decor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the work's ruling image of the alienated artist was directly
related to the music's coded references to the composer's imaginary
brotherhood arrayed against the Philistines. Even at his most
theatrical, Balanchine offered a translation of the music as he
understood it.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine himself could turn out full-evening original
narrative works. Two of his most innovative ballets were ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' (1962), more musical than literary in its
inspiration, and ``Don Quixote'' (1965). With a
stream-of-consciousness structure, that work was very different
from 19th-century Russian ballet versions of Cervantes' novel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Balanchine dropped ``Don Quixote'' from the repertory, and
plot seemed to interest him less in his later years. One of the
things he admired about Martins as a novice choreographer, he once
said during a conversation, was that Martins did not tell stories.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of the Diamond Project's first four premieres in
May grandly justified City Ballet's emphasis on the plotless. The
question is whether City Ballet can remain true to itself only if
its new works tell no story.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the City Ballet was also defined by Jerome
Robbins' early choreography, which was strong on distilled dance
drama. (``The Cage,'' ``Afternoon of a Faun'' and ``Fancy Free''
from that early era are in the repertory.) It was also a company
that presented works by a range of choreographers, including Antony
Tudor and Frederick Ashton. Even Cranko created a Gothic ballet,
``The Witch,'' danced by the company on tour in London in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The City Ballet of that era is no more. But this does not mean
that Ashton's ``Illuminations,'' an evocative 1950 ode to the poet
Arthur Rimbaud, cannot be revived by the company that created it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that City Ballet is identified with plotless works and
that Ballet Theater specializes in story ballets is a formula that
is only partly true. It is not surprising that the works of Tudor,
Ashton and Cranko have been danced by both Ballet Theater and City
Ballet. There was a time when lines were not as clearly drawn in
competing aesthetics.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Tudor, Ashton and Cranko came out of
British ballet. The British are not immune to abstraction, but in
dance, at least, they like to tell stories.
</P>
<P>
   Distinct from the 19th-century classics, the 20th-century
narratives at Ballet Theater spring out of this tradition.
British-born choreographers have dominated that wing of the
repertory and include Kenneth MacMillan (``Romeo and Juliet,''
``Manon,'' ``Anastasia''), Ronald Hynd (``The Merry Widow'') and
Ben Stevenson, artistic director of the Houston Ballet
(``Cinderella,'' ``The Snow Maiden'').
</P>
<P>
   Tudor's exquisite one-act ``Jardin aux Lilas'' (repeated June 16
to 17), represents psychologically driven dance from another era
(1936). Its entangled tale of an arranged marriage is nothing but
dramatic. But this is drama, compressed and atmospheric, not spun
out in the measured linear fashion of the three-act ballets.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all those works, including the ``Othello'' that Lar
Lubovitch created for Ballet Theater a few seasons ago, have a
literary inspiration. Kevin McKenzie, the company's artistic
director, makes no apologies for his preference for full-length
narrative works: they afford dancers an opportunity to shine as
individuals and have box-office appeal to a general public.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine took 40 years to educate his public to appreciate
dance for dance's sake. But in recent years, even companies
directed by his disciples throughout the country have staged
full-evening ballets with plot to satisfy public demand.
</P>
<P>
   Why that demand exists is open to debate. Possibly, the return
to figurative painting has its counterpart in dance, whose audience
now rejects the abstraction embraced after the 1960s. But perhaps
it is also that people like to see characters with whose emotions
they can identify. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Mallarme warned that his ideal ballet performance was impossible
as long as the spectator, because he paid for his seat, felt
entitled to see a mirror of himself onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, familiar signposts in a ballet translated from literature
can elevate the spirit, as Leonid Lavrovsky's ``Romeo and Juliet''
proves on the Bolshoi Ballet's current tour of the United States.
Certainly, the best introduction to ballet for children is a dance
work whose story they can follow.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century classics, however, are in a different category.
One goes to see how ``Swan Lake'' is danced, not how it ends.
</P>
<P>
   City Ballet now includes a sampling from the 19th century.
Balanchine and Alexandra Danilova staged ``Coppelia'' for City
Ballet. Martins has added his stagings of ``The Sleeping Beauty''
and ``Swan Lake.'' McKenzie's straightforward ``Swan Lake'' is new
at Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Quixote,'' ``La Bayadere'' and ``Le Corsaire,'' all in
Ballet Theater's season, have negligible or impossible plots: they
are machines for dancing and it is the quality of that dancing that
determines if they will endure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
