<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-08 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIES (AND BUNGEE CORDS) THAT BIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More male eyes tear up in ``Pop and Me,'' a likable
documentary about fathers and sons, than turn misty in
``Frequency,'' the macho tear-jerker about filial devotion that
word of mouth has turned into a surprise hit. Could it be that the
tough-but-tender ethos of Robert Bly's ``Iron John'' has trickled
down into the cultural mainstream despite the buckets of glib
derision heaped on the men's movement? The coincidence of these two
male weepies suggests perhaps yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop and Me,'' directed by Chris Roe, a generically clean-cut
young Californian who seems largely untouched by life, follows the
boyish filmmaker on a nine-month trip around the world with his
recently divorced and unemployed 55-year-old father, Richard. While
on the road, between bickering and making up, the Roes interview
pairs of fathers and sons in various cultures about their
relationships. Although the majority of these interviews turn out
to be question-and-answer sessions that reveal almost nothing, two
or three are quite touching.
</P>
<P>
   We visit the home of a bossy Egyptian general who, in the custom
of many Muslim families, unconditionally rules the roost in a
household where he is surrounded by several generations of his
family. According to Islamic teaching, he tells us, children must
unquestioningly obey their parents. Judging from the film's joint
interview with the general and a grown-up son who lives at home and
clearly idolizes his father, such strictures can help ensure a
familial social stability. But even in this tight-lipped
environment, as the general is questioned about whether he loves
his son and awkward hugs are exchanged, the mists begin to roll
into their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It is in Australia, of all places, while visiting an old friend
of Richard's, that the Roes' kissy-huggy ethos is stonewalled by
the son of a rancher who smugly dismisses this freshly thawed style
of filial camaraderie as wimpy ``American stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The interviews and some pretty travel scenery are really only
the glue holding together the story of Chris and Richard's thorny
relationship while traveling. Their agreement before setting out is
that Chris will be in charge of the film and Richard, who is
footing the bill, in charge of travel, meals and accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris, the second of three sons, resents being bossed around
by his father, and their relationship becomes increasingly strained
until the end of the trip, when Chris coaxes his acrophobic dad
into a dual bungee jump while holding a camera and sound equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For a film devoted to celebrating intimacy and the breaking down
of emotional barriers, ``Pop and Me'' is oddly withholding of
information about the travelers. By the end of the movie Chris, who
has done a smooth job of directing, seems almost as blank as he did
at the beginning. When addressing the camera he is affable enough,
but we get no sense of any inner life beyond his continual
peevishness about not being in command.
</P>
<P>
   We learn a great more about Richard, who comes fairly close to
being an ideal father with his mixture of confidence, humor,
optimism and general openness. Born in the Bronx, he recalls being
the son of a hopeless alcoholic who spent the last decades of his
life in a mental institution. In the film's most touching story, he
recalls paying a rare visit to the hospital shortly before his
father's death and apologizing for being such a neglectful son. For
a moment his father emerged from his fog, Richard recalls, just
long enough to forgive his son.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't find out is anything about the career or the
marriage Richard is leaving behind or why he is stranded without
even (we learn at the end of the film) a home base to go back to.
Talk about midlife crises! Although Richard appears affluent enough
not to have to worry about making a living once he returns to the
United States, his future at the end of the movie is a complete
mystery. ``Pop and Me'' leaves you wishing more cards had been put
on the table.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `POP AND ME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Chris Roe; directors of photography, Erik Arnesen
and Roe; edited by Jesse Negron and Roe; music by Steve Edwards and
Mazatl Galindo; produced by Richard Roe and Roe; released by
Seventh Art Releasing. At the Village East.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Chris Roe and Richard Roe.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GROOVE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROOVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GROOVE': INTO THE NIGHT, ENDLESSLY SEARCHING FOR THE PERFECT
RAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: `Dmitri' in 4th graf with no last name is cq.) 
(Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who would want to go to a party that actually lets you know
where it is?'' vents a very frustrated Neil (Jeff Witzke) in
``Groove,'' the shambling but mostly knowing and funny comedy from
the director Greg Harrison. If you're nostalgic for the days of
chasing around the city to find a gig and arriving just in time to
see a pair of 16-year-olds earnestly discussing the merits of
drum-and-bass versus jungle music, then ``Groove'' is the movie for
you. If you're not so inclined, the film's seductive lack of
pretension will make a fan of you.
</P>
<P>
   The only showy sequence in the entire picture is at the
beginning, and its portent is used as a joke: a garage door
ominously cranks open and four figures stand dramatically
backlighted, with rain pouring behind them. This Impossible Mission
Force is Ernie (Steve Van Wormer) and his crew checking out an
abandoned warehouse as a rave site.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes place in San Francisco over the course of a
single night, with the word of the supposedly hush-hush party
getting out via the Internet and pagers. Although Harrison uses two
elements so venerable that they have calcified into institutions _
the rave scene and the life-changing-night scenario, which was a
dried chestnut even when ``American Graffiti'' employed it _ the
director manages to make ``Groove'' about moments.
</P>
<P>
   There's a girl staring contentedly at a spinning dryer while her
Walkman pumps it up, and Guy (Dmitri), Ernie's second in command,
riding the BART with a huge mirrored disco ball on his lap. Like
``Graffiti,'' ``Groove'' does away with plot and instead uses its
wild-party setting to follow several people who are attending the
rave, or trying their best to find it.
</P>
<P>
   This film doesn't assume the pose that raves are anything new or
dangerous; rather, the view is that they're an entrenched circuit
with tribal complications.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the comedy is. The surly Todd (Angelo Spizziri),
who gets many of the best lines while waiting for his Ecstasy high
to kick in, observes that if the girls weren't all sporting Tickle
Me Elmo backpacks, they'd be hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When'd you go all Haight-Ashbury on me?'' he barks at his
psychotropic connoisseur friend Cliff (Ari Gold, who directs sharp
short films when he's not acting). ``You used to listen to Nitzer
Ebb.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before, Cliff _ a teaching assistant during the day _
was spotted by a couple of his students. When it's clicking,
``Groove'' connects like an Ecstasy-fueled screwball comedy:
everyone's synapses get scrambled by their desires and by the
juiced beats per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other films built around electronica song scores, which
employ every sleight of hand at the filmmakers' disposal,
``Groove'' settles assuredly into a spartan look at the world of
the rave. How sad; now that even Ronald McDonald was featured in a
commercial at an underground spot a few years back, movies about
raves are finally getting made.
</P>
<P>
   There have probably been more rave movies in the last 12 months
than there were in the previous decade. It's too bad that none were
produced in the early 1990s, when the scene had some currency and
Orbital's ``Halcyon'' _ which is part of the well-selected
soundtrack _ could raise the roof.
</P>
<P>
   At times here, there's a high corn quotient. Lola Glaudini is
the jaded Leyla, who is a little too old to still be hitting raves
and is looking for something worthy of commitment. David (Hamish
Linklater) is at his first rave and tries showing some game by
telling Leyla he's from back East _ East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's inside jokes is that he grew up a little more
than an hour from the home of techno music, Detroit, and was too
nervous to make that trip.
</P>
<P>
   The film doesn't dwell on the many firsts that occur, like
David's inaugural rave experience and Ecstasy consumption.
``Groove'' often belongs to Ernie, who is a techno altruist; he'd
have to be, since he's charging only two bucks a head for a
till-dawn jam that includes food and bottled water. He's down with
the politics of dancing, so chilled that even a police bust cannot
stop him, evoking the Alan Freed of ``American Hot Wax.'' When he
finally gets a chance to hit the floor _ ``You have control of the
bridge,'' he tells his pal Guy _ the spark in his eyes is as potent
as any of the mood-altering substances being passed around.
</P>
<P>
   The film's real barometer is Maggie, played by the willowy
Elizabeth Sun. Whenever things are bumping, there she is, her
twists shaking like it's all good. ``Groove'' is just that.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been better only if the last shot were from an
earlier scene: Todd's high, as it finally kicks in and he toys with
a globe like a stoned kitten.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GROOVE'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Greg Harrison; director of
photography, Matthew Irving; music supervisor, Wade Randolph
Hampton, with music by John Digweed, Mixmaster Morris of
Irresistible Force, Jonah Sharp of Spacetime Continuum, the
Hardkiss Brothers and Octave One, among many others; produced by
Danielle Renfrew; released by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 86 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes party language and many, many drug
references.
</P>
<P>
   With: Lola Glaudini (Leyla), Hamish Linklater (David), Denny
Kirkwood (Colin), Mackenzie Firgens (Harmony), Vince Riverside
(Anthony), Rachel True (Beth), Steve Van Wormer (Ernie), Nick
Offerman (Sergeant) Elizabeth Sun (Maggie), Angelo Spizziri (Todd),
Jeff Witzke (Neil), Dmitri (Guy) and Ari Gold (Cliff).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
