<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALGARY-IMAGE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALGARY JOURNAL: OIL CITY IS MOVING ON, TO HIGH-TECH SPARK PLUG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Playing on Americans' fear of the unknown, a
Best Western Hotel television ad last winter showed business
executives bucking an unpopular travel request down the corporate
ladder. Finally, the request stopped at a hapless underling,
standing wide-eyed by a photocopier as a colleague asked, ``Have
you ever been to _ Calgary?''
</P>
<P>
   Calgarians complained, and the hotel chain pulled the
commercial. But many others here in the most prosperous city in
Canada's most prosperous province just shrugged it off, attributing
it to the provincialism of an American ad copy writer.
</P>
<P>
   With the highest household Internet connection rate in Canada,
the country's largest concentration of corporate headquarters
outside of Toronto and a brand new venture capital stock exchange
incubating hundreds of new companies, people in this steel and
glass city on the edge of the Canadian Rockies are too busy making
money to lose sleep over outdated stereotypes. In fact, a little
negative publicity might cool off a city that has seen its
population grow by two-thirds since 1975, to 860,000 today, pushing
up housing prices by one-third since 1995, the fastest rate of any
city in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic,'' groaned Alnisha Haji, a hairdresser who moved
here from Winnipeg a few years ago. ``Places that used to take half
an hour to get to, now take an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the lowest unemployment rate of a major Canadian city,
4.7 percent, migrants still flock here at the rate of 50 a day.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things I noticed here were the help wanted
ads,'' said Michelle Simick, 27, a newspaper reporter who moved
here this spring from her native Vancouver. ``They have signs
everywhere _ in front of the 7-Elevens, in front of the
restaurants, even a board up in the mall. I have never seen that in
Vancouver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People my age here seem to be a lot further along than people
in Vancouver,'' she said. ``People in Vancouver seem to be slogging
away at service jobs, waiting for jobs that never open up.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With Canada's tallest building west of Toronto, this modern city
of high-rises enjoys its image of a sunny, squeaky clean city, even
serving as ``Metropolis'' for the filming of all three modern
Superman movies. But on June 11, this showcase metropolis will be
thrust into the world spotlight when 3,000 delegates from 80
countries converge here for the World Petroleum Congress, a
five-day event that takes place every three years.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest event to hit Calgary since the 1988 Winter Olympics,
the congress may not capture wide attention despite high gasoline
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But protesters, noting the expected attendance of 200
journalists, are gearing up for a series of photogenic protests,
promising a miniature version of the antitrade protests that shook
Seattle six months ago. In a genteel city where parking meter
attendants wear cowboy hats to charm the tourists, it is unclear
how Calgary will cope if violence breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Targets will be easy to find. Penthouse floors of downtown
skyscrapers proudly bear the names of oil companies: Gulf, Husky,
Mobil, Shell and Petrocanada. But while energy sector companies
occupy half of downtown's office space, appearances are deceiving
in a city long labeled Canada's ``energy capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipsawed by a series of oil price shocks, Alberta has
diversified, seeing the energy industry's part of the provincial
economy drop to 20 percent today from 35 percent 15 years ago. In
the near suburbs, before housing developments sprawl across
shortgrass prairie to the Rockies, about 1,200 new high technology
companies have sprung up in recent years, now employing 50,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Professors at a University of Calgary high technology center
have licensed 300 technologies in the last decade. To lessen
economic dependence on oil, Alberta's government has set up two
$700 million funds, one for engineering research, the other for
medical research. Last year, of Alberta's 10 fastest-growing
companies, 6 were high-tech companies based in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People have learned,'' said Ralph Klein, Alberta's premier,
who was Calgary's mayor during the energy downturn of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This year, Alberta expects to record the highest growth rate, 5
percent, of Canada's 10 provinces. The premier placed much of the
credit on low taxes. Alberta has no sales tax, Canada's lowest
gasoline tax and, starting Jan. 1, will have Canada's first flat
provincial tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come out here, they are amazed,'' said William L.
Hess, a Montreal native who runs Calgary's new Canadian Venture
Exchange. ``The entrepreneurial drive, the quality of work
available to professionals are unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since opening six months ago as a fusion of two old exchanges in
Calgary and Vancouver, the national exchange here has seen its
daily trades quadruple, to an average of about 28,000. With 2,800
small capital companies listed, it is now moving east, opening
branches this summer in Winnipeg and Toronto. The new exchange
replaces the Vancouver Stock Exchange, which lost credibility over
stock manipulations of mining companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The downside of Calgary's boom has been an affordable housing
squeeze. In the last year, the minimum income needed to buy the
average house here jumped by one-quarter, knocking 45,000 families
out of the market, according to mortgage analysts. ``Homelessness
has grown incredibly here,'' said David W. Lewry, who runs the Inn
From the Cold Society, a network of homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   But in general Calgary's success has provoked mostly envy,
starting in neighboring British Columbia. Alberta, with only
three-quarters of British Columbia's population of 4 million,
expects to see its gross provincial product surpass its western
neighbor's this year, hitting $75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder the new Canadian Venture Exchange will headquarter
in Calgary and not Vancouver,'' Mark Milke, British Columbia
director of the Canadian Taxpayers Federation, complained in an
essay in The Calgary Herald. ``The stockbrokers are simply
following the moving vans of other enterprising British
Columbians.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Edmonton, Alberta's capital, Don Ghermezian, manager of the
West Edmonton Mall, the world's largest shopping mall, sniffed in
an interview: ``Calgary has nothing. OK, it has a tower with a
revolving restaurant. Big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, newspapers like to paint Calgary and Alberta as
weird bastions of reactionary politics and lifestyles. In reality,
Calgary is middle of the road by U.S. standards. Last fall, a
Calgary judge established the right for local lesbian couples to
adopt children legally.
</P>
<P>
   A yuppie haven in reality, Calgary has a household Internet
connection rate of 60 percent and a population that, surveys
indicate, prefers skiing over hockey and bicycling over fishing.
With the local National Hockey League team, the Calgary Flames,
losing money, The Calgary Herald is campaigning to expand the sales
of season passes with scare headlines like ``No Bucks, No Pucks.''
</P>
<P>
   In this city of migrants, social mobility is often greater than
in blue-blooded eastern Canada. In May, Mayor Al Duerr bestowed
Calgary's Citizen of the Year Award on Mitzie Wasyliw for
preserving an old ranching homestead. A newspaper report noted that
Wasyliw got her start here in the 1970s when she blew into town and
became one of the city's first ``exotic dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure there is a bit of Toronto looking down their noses
at the West,'' Hess, the stock exchange president, said of
intercity rivalries. ``But, frankly, there is a bit of the West
looking down its nose at Toronto.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
