<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-08 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S PLAYING IN THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film
or series. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   ``BATTLEFIELD EARTH,'' starring John Travolta and Barry Pepper.
Directed by Roger Christian (PG-13, 117 minutes). In the year 3000,
beings from the planet Psychlo conquer Earth in only nine minutes
and reduce all humans to grunting illiterates. The chief nasty,
Terl (Travolta), devises a scheme to put the man-animals to work in
the gold mines for him. He sees potential in one cave dweller
(Pepper) and straps him to a machine that beams the wisdom of the
ages into his head. Little does Terl realize that by educating a
human, he is sowing the seeds of his own destruction. Sitting
through this film with its stock villains is like watching the most
expensively mounted high school play of all time. It may be a bit
early to make such judgments, but ``Battlefield Earth'' may well
turn out to be the worst movie of this century (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE,'' starring Martin Lawrence. Directed by
Raja Gosnell (PG-13, 97 minutes). This fitfully amusing film,
starring the comic whirligig Lawrence, could best be described as
``Stakeout'' goes ghetto, with a touch of ``Tootsie'' for flava _
er, flavor. Lawrence plays Malcolm, an FBI agent with a penchant
for doing undercover work in full body makeup. Here he impersonates
Big Momma, a stubborn old Southern woman. Why? Big Momma's
granddaughter is on the run because her ex-boyfriend, Lester, a
murderous bank robber, has escaped from prison and is after her.
Malcolm believes he can use her to get to Lester. This isn't much
of a movie; it looks like a series of baseball card shots and may
have the worst rhythms ever in a film directed by a former editor
(Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``CENTER STAGE,'' starring Ethan Stiefel, Sascha Radetsky,
Amanda Schull, Peter Gallagher and Donna Murphy. Directed by
Nicholas Hytner (PG-13, 113 minutes). Hytner's film tracks the
professional and romantic travails of a group of young dancers at
the fictitious American Ballet Academy in New York. The script is a
patchwork of show biz movie and romantic comedy cliches and the
acting rarely rises above daytime soap-opera obviousness, but who
ever went to a dance movie to see good writing or realistic acting?
The movie is loaded with lively dance sequences, and Hytner films
them beautifully, especially the show-stopping finale,
choreographed by Susan Stroman and spiritedly danced by Stiefel,
Radetsky and the lovely Schull, who carries the movie with her
energy and grace (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``DINOSAUR,'' with the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard and
Ossie Davis. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton (PG, 90
minutes). Reputedly the most expensive animated feature ever made,
Disney's showcase of computer animation technology begins with a
breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that the
rest of the movie never quite lives up to. The story, of a young
dinosaur raised by lemurs who must lead a herd of his fellow
reptiles to safety after an asteroid strikes the earth, is cobbled
together from other Disney plots. But the effects _ the dinosaur's
movements and their nearly seamless insertion into real locations _
will impress skeptical grown-ups (the movie reportedly cost about
$200 million). More important, the film, in spite of some
potentially upsetting scenes of carnivorous mayhem, will delight
children and whet their desire for the inevitable tie-in
merchandise (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``EAST-WEST,'' starring Sandrine Bonnaire, Oleg Menchikov
and Catherine Deneuve. Directed by Regis Wargnier (PG-13, 115
minutes). After World War II the Soviet government undertook a
propaganda campaign to entice Russians living in the West to return
home. Aleksei Golovine (Menchikov) and his French wife, Marie
(Bonnaire), the couple at the heart of Wargnier's sumptuous, moving
historical melodrama, are luckier than most of their fellow
returnees, who are killed or imprisoned on arrival. ``East-West''
chronicles Aleksei's ambivalence about their new life in a drab,
depressing communal apartment and Marie's desperate attempts to
escape it. The film may be faulted for dissolving the horrors of
history in Hollywood-style catharsis, but it also uses the
resources of old-fashioned emotionally emphatic filmmaking to shed
light on forgotten history. ``East-West'' is a grand costume
pageant, full of grandeur and period detail, but it is also the
portrait of a marriage under extreme external and internal pressure
as well as a showcase for two great film actresses: Bonnaire and
Deneuve, playing an actress who becomes aware of Marie's plight
during a Soviet tour (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``FREQUENCY,'' starring Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel.
Directed by Gregory Hoblit (PG-13, 100 minutes). ``Back to the
Future'' meets ``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a Wonderful Life''
meets ``The Sixth Sense'' in this entertaining but shamelessly
sentimental supernatural soap opera with a macho heart. Caviezel is
a morose young policeman who contacts his dead father, a heroic
firefighter, on a ham radio and contrives to save him from the
accident that cost him his life during the 1969 World Series. From
here, the two collaborate on changing other aspects of the past and
on catching a serial killer. There are enough testosterone tears to
soak Shea Stadium (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``GLADIATOR,'' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: what would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. Crowe is the noble Roman general who ends
up fighting for his life. Crowe gives a performance with
ball-of-fire intensity, suffused with a movie star's impatience. He
holds the movie together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``HAMLET,'' starring Ethan Hawke and Liev Schreiber.
Directed by Michael Almereyda (R, 112 minutes). Almereyda has
rooted his voluptuous and rewarding new adaptation of Shakespeare's
play in today's Manhattan. The city's contradictions of beauty and
squalor give the movie a sense of place, and New York becomes a
complex character in this vital and sharply intelligent film. Often
shaded in lush, soothing hues of blue, ``Hamlet'' exudes an
intoxicating masochism in which half the cast is battling
despondency and the other half has the glint of imminent insanity.
Here the melancholy of Hamlet (Hawke) over the death of his father
is almost a state of grace: it gives him a sense of purpose that
the other characters lack. The director's rigorous trimming has a
boldness and vivacity that make this version exhilarating while
leaving Shakespeare's language and intent intact (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``M:I-2,'' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Sir Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes). Cruise returns
as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's loud, flashy,
incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked with movie
references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission: Impossible''
movie and to Woo's earlier, and superior, Hong Kong action films _
but it's at once overheated and flat. The plot, involving killer
viruses, is baffling rather than twisty. The introduction of a love
interest (Newton) who also happens to be the bad guy's
ex-girlfriend adds an element of melodrama that's more annoying
than affecting. Some good car chases and explosions, though
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``ROAD TRIP,'' starring Breckin Meyer, Seann William Scott, Amy
Smart, DJ Qualls and Tom Green. Directed by Todd Phillips (R, 91
minutes). ``National Lampoon's Animal House'' meets ``There's
Something About Mary'' in the gross-out farce of the late spring.
Four college boys led by Josh (Meyer) embark on a desperate
1,800-mile journey from upstate New York to Texas to intercept an
X-rated dorm room video mistakenly sent to Josh's loyal girlfriend
in Austin. The fun is all in the gags, among them the notorious
French toast sequence, the envelope-pushing sperm bank scene and
the hilarious car-jumped-over-the-bridge demolition derby. You'll
laugh despite yourself (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SHANGHAI NOON,'' starring Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson.
Directed by Tom Dey (PG-13, 110 minutes). Chan is one of the great
physical comedians, and this martial arts western spoof is a
high-spirited, marvelously silly showcase for his talents. Chan
plays Chon Wang, an Imperial Guard dispatched from Beijing to the
Old West to rescue a princess played by Lucy Liu. But the heart of
the movie is the interplay between Chan and Wilson, who depicts his
inept outlaw sidekick with goofy, spacey charm. After the glum
bullying of ``Gladiator'' and the noisy bombast of ``M:I-2,'' it's
refreshing to see a movie so good-natured, so confident in its
ability to provoke not queasy awe or numb exhaustion, but pure
delight (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SMALL TIME CROOKS,'' starring Woody Allen and Tracey
Ullman. Directed and written by Allen (PG, 95 minutes). The sweet,
funny wisp of a movie starts out as a parody of ``Big Deal on
Madonna Street,'' then turns into a child's-eye ``Bonfire of the
Vanities,'' before returning to its original mode as a caper
comedy. Allen and Ullman are Ray and Frenchy Winkler, an inept
thief and ex-con and his upwardly mobile wife whose cookie business
takes off and allows her to indulge her dream of being a Park
Avenue hostess. If the movie suffers severely from attention
deficit disorder, the jokes are funny (but mild), the screwball
comic tone impeccably sustained and Ullman (putting on her Fern
Rosenthal voice) and Elaine May (as Frenchy's dimwitted cousin)
delightfully goofy (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``TIME CODE,'' starring Jeanne Tripplehorn and Stellan
Skarsgard. Directed by Mike Figgis (R, 93 minutes). Figgis'
astonishing new film, shot in a single day with hand-held digital
video cameras, tells four stories simultaneously, in real time.
``Time Code'' is at once a mordant satire of the hypocrisy and
self-delusion of the film industry and an earnest declaration of
faith in the medium itself. In addition to its technical
innovations, which test the limits of the human eye, ear and mind,
the film boasts some brilliant improvisational acting from its
enormous cast. Especially fine are Tripplehorn and Skarsgard, whose
strongly emotional performances add a measure of pathos. Whether
``Time Code'' will ultimately be seen as a bold prophecy of the
dawning visual age or as a passionate, gimmicky curio is for the
future to decide. At present, though, it is hard to think of a more
exciting demonstration of the inexhaustible possibilities of film
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571,'' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
were cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8467 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE YOUNG AND THE CLUELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By   THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday's Microsoft ruling was about a lot of technical
matters _ Internet browsers, market share, the Sherman Antitrust
Act. But if you read carefully Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
ruling to split up Microsoft, you will see that this case is also
about attitude. In my view, it's an indictment of the attitude of
the high-tech community in general toward government, but it's
certainly an indictment of the particular attitude and arrogance of
Microsoft. Bless Jackson's heart for that.
</P>
<P>
   For many in Silicon Valley, government is irrelevant at best and
obstructionist at worst. For many in the high-tech community, the
world runs on electrons and stock options, and government is
basically an institution of tax-seeking bloodsuckers. The idea that
none of Silicon Valley's innovations would ever have flowered
without the rule of law maintained by Washington or without the
global stability maintained by the U.S. military _ funded by U.S.
taxpayer dollars _ is really a foreign notion to many in the
dot-com world. Tell techies that without America on duty there
would be no America Online and they will look at you as if you were
speaking Latin (or Fortran).
</P>
<P>
   No one epitomizes this attitude more than Bill Gates. As far as
I'm concerned, the government had grounds to break up Microsoft
simply for what Gates did last year _ which was to hire an army of
Washington lobbyists to try to get Congress to cut the budget of
the Antitrust Division of the Justice Department while Microsoft
had its case before that department. Think about the arrogance
behind that strategy. How would you feel if the biggest company in
your town tried to use its influence to slash the funding of your
police department, at a time when the police were bringing charges
against that company? That's what Microsoft did.
</P>
<P>
   And that to me is the real point of Jackson's ruling: Microsoft
isn't a threat just because it's big. GE is big. Intel is big.
Cisco is big. Microsoft is a threat because it is big and deaf to
some of the bedrock values of the American system.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Jackson is a conservative Republican appointed to the
bench by Ronald Reagan. He is not someone naturally hostile to big
corporations. Yet on virtually every count the judge ruled in favor
of the government and against Microsoft, pulling no punches when he
wrote: ``Microsoft as it is presently organized and led is
unwilling to accept the notion that it broke the law or accede to
an order amending its conduct ... There is credible evidence to
suggest that Microsoft, convinced of its innocence, continues to do
business as it has in the past, and may yet do to other markets
what it has already done in the PC operating system and browser
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to predict what effect Microsoft's breakup
could have on the computer market, the software market or the stock
market. But it could not have come at a better time for the
rule-of-law market.
</P>
<P>
   We are entering a whole new era of cyberspace, which is going to
make governance of things we cherish, and the enforcement of even
some basic laws, much more difficult. Look around: Internet
companies are already violating people's privacy to troubling
degrees; new technologies are making it easy for anyone to copy a
book, movie or CD and send it to a friend without regard to
copyright or royalties; e-commerce is increasingly going to deprive
local and state governments of taxes; and the unregulated universe
of cyberspace is making it easy for two students in the Philippines
to send out a computer virus that melts down 10 million computers
worldwide overnight.
</P>
<P>
   That's why in the age of cyberspace, government is going to
matter more, not less. And you are going to want the rule of law
more, not less. The danger, though, is that young people _ raised
in the Internet age and bedazzled by technology companies and
billionaire geeks like Bill Gates _ will lose sight of this fact.
So too might all their parents with Microsoft stock in their
401(k)'s.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about Microsoft. There will always be another
Microsoft as long as there is another Jackson or another Joel Klein
ready to take on such behemoths when they become abusive. But there
won't always be another U.S. government, as we know it, if global
technology companies grow so big and powerful that they think they
can have their way with Washington, or if these emerging Internet
giants snooker us into keeping cyberspace unregulated, so they can
have their way with us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BAY-NURSING-HOMES-HNS     06-08 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-NURSING-HOMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAY AREA NURSING HOMES FAIL TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than 40 percent of nursing homes in the San
Francisco Bay Area were found with violations that either caused
harm to residents or put them at risk of death or injury, according
to a federal report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The audit of the region's 288 nursing homes, commissioned by
nine members of Congress, also found that only 18 _ 6 percent _
were in full or substantial compliance with all federal standards
in recent inspections by government auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators, all Democrats, immediately responded to the
report with proposed legislation calling for more monitoring and
accountability in the nursing home industry nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the deficiencies discovered by surveyors between 1997
and January in the nine-county Bay Area involved failure to prevent
falls and accidents or to provide proper medical care or sufficient
staff, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and Oakland had an even higher rate of violations
than the Bay Area overall, with 44 percent being cited for such
infractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area facilities covered about 22,000 residents, most of
whom have their care paid for by Medicare or Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Considering California is one of the two best states for
hospital and nursing home regulation, the report caused
consternation, said Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., who initiated the
audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow we've dropped some of these hospitals through the
cracks,'' Stark said. ``If this is as good as it gets, we could
have real trouble in the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But a representative of the state's nursing home industry said
that the information was anecdotal and that the report of the
nursing homes was subjective.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, California ranks 46th among all states for
per-resident spending in such facilities, said Betsy Hite,
spokeswoman for the California Association of Health Facilities,
which represents 1,500 long-term and assisted living care
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of California and the feds want us to provide the
services of the Ritz Carlton, but they want to pay a Best Western
price,'' she said, adding that the industry was 30,000 workers
short and could not keep up with the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Although her organization's figures show that only about 3
percent of nursing homes statewide are deficient, the report by the
House Government Reform Committee's Democratic staff painted a far
bleaker picture in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   It found that only 18 homes in the region were in full or
substantial compliance with all federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it clear that this report is not intended to
assign blame,'' the lawmakers said in a statement issued Thursday.
``It is intended to be a wake-up call that nursing home patients,
some of the most vulnerable members of our society, are in need of
better care than they are receiving today and that policy changes
are needed to help them receive better care.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was requested in anticipation of the proposed
``Nursing Home Staffing Accountability and Training Improvement
Act,'' introduced Thursday by Stark and the other representatives.
The others were Reps. Anna Eshoo, Nancy Pelosi, George Miller, Tom
Lantos, Ellen Tauscher, Barbara Lee, Zoe Lofgren and Lynn Woolsey.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would hold skilled nursing care facilities more
accountable for providing adequate nurse and caregiver staffing,
which has so far been difficult to verify. It also would call for
periodic audits to assess the adequacy of staffing services
provided to nursing home residents under Medicaid, and would direct
the federal government to undertake a comprehensive assessment that
produces recommendations for improvement in training and skills of
certified nurses aides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
