<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: COW COUNTRY NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I want to take this opportunity to apologize to the state of
Rhode Island for making fun of its Mr. Potato Head campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the Rhode Island Tourism Division scattered
large, gaily decorated statues of Mr. Potato Head hither and yon in
an effort to publicize its new marketing program for ``Rhode Island
_ Birthplace of Fun.'' I was not as supportive of this venture as I
might have been.
</P>
<P>
   But little did I know that my very own city was preparing a
similar effort involving large, gaily decorated statues of cows. By
next week at this time, New York is going to have more than 500 of
them in the parks, on the traffic islands, wherever. We'll be
seeing even more of the cows than of Rick Lazio. (As Republican
Senate candidate, Lazio, in a spasm of overenthusiasm, promised to
one-up Hillary Rodham Clinton's sweep through all 62 counties by
visiting every single block in the state.)
</P>
<P>
   Animal statues are the new urban rage. Even as we speak,
Cincinnati is being decorated with pigs. ``There are lizards in
Orlando, moose in Toronto, horses in Lexington and fish in New
Orleans,'' said Owen Findsen, the visual arts critic for The
Cincinnati Enquirer. Cincinnati has recently begun to re-embrace
its 19th-century nickname of ``Porkopolis,'' and Findsen, in a
telephone interview, said he had just heard about a near-riot of
enthusiastic citizens pressing to see the new all-pig fountain
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful if you talk to Lexington,'' he warned. ``They're
very serious about the horses. They don't want anybody to poke
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Rapids, Mich., is reported to be encouraging civic pride
and tourism with huge painted rabbits. Miami has flamingoes.
Lynnwood, Wash., is laying claim to the decorative chicken
franchise. While New York is having its cow experience, West
Orange, N.J., and Stamford, Conn., will be staging similar events.
``West Orange has one cow done by the guy who plays Furio in `The
Sopranos'; wait till you see his work,'' gushed Jerome Elbaum, the
organizer.
</P>
<P>
   (We pause here to note that currently in the metropolitan New
York region, no public event is regarded as truly successful unless
at least one member of the ``Sopranos'' cast participates.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year Chicago set up 300 fiberglass cows painted by local
artists, and the results were remarkable. ``The officially named
Cows on Parade has been covered by everyone from The Jakarta Post
to The Wisconsin State Farmer, brought more publicity to Chicago
than the 1996 Democratic National Convention and generated up to
$200 million in tourist dollars,'' said the rather envious Kansas
City Star, in a report about plans to get Kansas City on the cow
bandwagon. (``It shows spunk and confidence. We could use both,''
exhorted a local museum director.)
</P>
<P>
   Elbaum is president of one of several enterprises now competing
for the business of filling up American cities with gaily decorated
bovines. Truly this is a remarkable era _ we now enjoy an economy
so expansive it can accommodate two Microsofts and four different
cow parade companies. ``It's a wonderful opportunity for people who
do not frequent art museums to see all these wonderful expressions
of pure art,'' he said. ``I mean, you will see cows that look like
the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel.''
</P>
<P>
   Several questions come to mind here, one of them being how many
additional tourists are going to come to New York City when they
hear it has cow statues. Another is why a city that could never
figure out how to privatize garbage collection has decided to put
its public art in the hands of a profit-making venture based in
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The New York cows, which were decorated by local artists and
schoolchildren, include several really imaginative numbers _
there's one cow with a desk coming out of its side that I would be
proud to call my own. But as a group, they're actually a little
off-putting. It may be the statues' expressions, which are
somewhere between blank and surly _ cow-like, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   And of course the whole thing has nothing whatsoever to do with
New York City. Say what you will about Mr. Potato Head _ and I will
personally never say another word again _ he was definitely born in
Rhode Island. If New York City had wanted animal art, we should
have painted pigeons.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
