<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     06-08 0202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINT ETIENNE: `SOUND OF WATER' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT ETIENNE: ``Sound of Water'' (Sub Pop). ``Sail away, sail
away,'' Sarah Cracknell of Saint Etienne coos in ``How We Used to
Live,'' the nine-minute mini-suite that sums up ``Sound of Water''
as it drifts between distant, unhappy memories and persistent hope.
For a decade, Saint Etienne has been leavening pop songs with
dance-club rhythms, coolly observing how far astray passion and
ambition can lead. The band's fifth unified album, ``Sound of
Water,'' floats above the fray; its songs yearn for escape and
sanctuary. Saint Etienne collaborated with the minimalist German
electronic group To Rococo Rot and with Sean O'Hagan, the Beach
Boys idolator from the High Llamas. The few uptempo songs are
skeletal and abstracted, transparently displaying their underlying
patterns of clicks and blips and nonsense pop syllables, while the
ballads sway between two chords like Brian Wilson in a hammock.
Saint Etienne remains fascinated with pop construction, but has
moved past cleverness and easy ironies. Its songs are no longer
puzzles; they're atmospheric, self-contained worlds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
