ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES-STYLE (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore's keen
interest in the signature of his campaign, and George W. Bush's
admitted lack of interest, perfectly captures the stark differences
in how they are running for president. Gore's fingerprints are on
every major move or pronouncement. He prides himself on making
decisions based on his judgment and not on the views of his
advisers. Bush, by contrast, prefers to surround himself with
people he trusts. Once he feels comfortable that they understand
his philosophy, he leaves them to come up with proposals for him to
sign off on.By Richard L. Berke. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``p'' news file.) 3,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INSECTICIDE (Undated) _ One of the most common ingredients
in home, lawn and garden bug killers poses an unacceptable health
risk, particularly to children, and will no longer be manufactured
for that use by the end of the year, environmental officials say.
The insecticide, also called Dursban, has been widely used for more
than 30 years both in agriculture and in products used by
exterminators and homeowners, including more than a dozen kinds of
Raid sprays, Hartz yard and kennel flea spray, and Black Flag
liquid roach and ant killer. By Andrew C. Revkin. (Scheduled to
move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVORS (Undated) _ Establishing its credentials as the
runaway television hit of the summer, the CBS show ``Survivor,''
which chronicles the adventures of 16 real people co-existing on an
island off Borneo, scored extraordinary ratings for the second
straight week, this time even drubbing ABC's ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire.'' By Bill Carter. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``e'' news file.) 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS-BENEFITS (Detroit) _ General Motors, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler division announce that they will begin
offering medical, dental and prescription drug benefits for
same-sex partners of their 466,000 hourly and salaried employees in
the United States, the largest move yet by corporate America to
provide such benefits for gay and lesbian couples. By Keith
Bradsher. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   PROCTER-RESIGN (Undated) _ The chief executive of Procter &AMP;
Gamble resigns as the company announces it will suffer another
disappointing quarter and its stock price fell to less than half of
what it was worth just four months ago. With the move, Procter
acknowledges that it has attempted to remake itself into a more
aggressive company too rapidly. By David Leonhardt. (Scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
