<HEADLINE>
ANGELS CAN'T HIDE FROM RANDY JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- The Angels might have thought there were rid of Randy
Johnson when he left the Mariners, their counterpart in the A.L.
West. But Johnson, who considered signing with the Angels going
into the 1999 season, just won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will come off the disabled list and pitch tonight
against the Angels at Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has enjoyed pitching against the Angels throughout his
career -- he's 14-6 with a 2.70 ERA against them in 25 games. The
14 wins against the Angels are the most by Johnson against any
other team (he also has 14 wins vs. Texas).
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Angels faced Johnson was March 15 in Tucson,
Ariz. in a spring training game. The Angels roughed up Johnson for
11 runs and 12 hits in three-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tim Salmon after the game: ``Any time you evaluate our
performance or his performance, hey, it's spring training. It feels
good, but at the same time you try not to get overly confident.
Because when the gun sounds he's going to have his A-game.''
</P>
<P>
   Good advice. Johnson is 9-1 with a 1.41 ERA and 131 strikeouts
in 95 2/3 innings. Johnson also has hit well, for a pitcher. He's
hitting .222 with five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern that starter Kent Bottenfield might be the next
pitcher to go to the disabled list. Bottenfield has had some
shoulder soreness lately, limiting his ability to pitch deep into
games. In his past four starts, he's pitched at least six innings
only once.
</P>
<P>
   If Bottenfield has to go to the DL, it would save Seth Etherton
from a trip to the minors. Because the Angels don't need a fifth
starter again until June 17, the Angels could call up bullpen help
to replace Bottenfield on the roster and keep Etherton in the
rotation. Lou Pote, who has 10 saves for Triple-A Edmonton, would
likely get called up.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton has made three starts for the Angels, and the last one
was his best -- four runs and six hits in 6 1/3 innings vs. the
Giants. Etherton's biggest problem has been the home run ball. Of
his 17 hits allowed, seven have been home runs (16 1/3 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad was the runner-up for A.L. player of the month for
April after he hit .449 to tie Rod Carew for highest batting
average (minimum 75 at-bats) by an Angels player in any month. But
his name in the record book has already been erased.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Bengie Molina, who has emerged as the leading candidate
for Rookie of the Year, hit .461 in May to set the new record for
highest average in a month.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at BankOne Ballpark
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-9; KMPC-1540, KIK-FM 94.3, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Brian Cooper (2-1, 3.86 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Arizona's Randy Johnson (9-1, 1.41). Tim Salmon has two
career homers off Johnson, but overall is hitting .188 (9 for 48)
against him. Garret Anderson has never gotten a hit off Johnson (0
for 9). Mo Vaughn is hitting .333 (8 for 24) with two homers
against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
