<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR ADVOCATE TALKS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I didn't have a column last week because I had the indescribable
honor of being ``Your Advocate'' at my paper.
</P>
<P>
   The duty of the Advocate, in case you are unclear on the
concept, is to answer any questions and address any problems that
you, the reader, may have.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the official definition of the job here at the
Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the Advocate's job is to handle complaints. The
people who call up the Advocate do not do so to praise the
reporters and editors for their well-researched stories and clever
headlines or congratulate the photographers for their fine pictures
or give thanks to the publisher for confining the lingerie-modeling
ads to the sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   No, they call to complain that the movie-theater phone number we
run is incorrect; the Philadelphia Phillies are missing from the
National League standings; the same story ran twice in the same
section and nobody at the paper understands the difference between
``who'' and ``whom.''
</P>
<P>
   (This seems like a good time to announce that I am personally
organizing a campaign to banish the word ``whom'' from the English
language. The word ``whom'' does nothing that the word ``who''
cannot do equally well and in less space. All ``whom'' is good for
is confusing writers and encouraging former English teachers _
excuse me, teachers of English _ to hunt down obscure grammatical
mistakes in the paper when they should be outdoors getting fresh
air and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   (And regarding the charge that there is no one at the paper who,
or possibly whom, understands the difference between ``who'' and
``whom,'' that is simply not true. We have one old editor whom, or
maybe who, we keep propped up in the corner next to the vending
machine. He understands perfectly the difference between ``who''
and ``whom,'' as well as the difference between ``lay'' and
``lie,'' ``affect'' and ``effect'' and ``Republican'' and
``Democrat.'' The problem is that he is often asleep when these
nettlesome questions of grammar arise, and we, being the polite
sorts that we are, are reluctant to wake him. I am sure that you,
exhausted reader, agree that a few misused pronouns are a small
price to pay for an old man's rest.)
</P>
<P>
   Each Advocate has his or her own way of dealing with these
calls. You can get defensive and point out that a certain number of
mistakes are inevitable given the constraints of deadlines and the
number of words we publish and the fact that we are short-staffed
and overworked and we just got a new computer system that appears
to be possessed by demons and just what the heck do you expect for
a quarter anyhow?
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think this is the wrong attitude, if for no other
reason than because it encourages the caller to stay on the line
and argue. My strategy was to agree with whatever the caller said,
up to and including the assertion that the paper is nothing more
than a propaganda tool for the Bolsheviks in New York. (I did not
point out that all the New York Bolsheviks have moved to Sarasota
because we have better weather.)
</P>
<P>
   Angry callers are thrown off balance if you agree with them.
It's rather cruel, in a way. The caller has gone to all the trouble
of getting geared up for a big fight and instead of fighting back,
you concede.
</P>
<P>
   So, basically, as Advocates go, I was a big, fat coward. I
offered no defense, no excuses. It's like the duck: If it looks
like a screw-up, walks like a screw-up and quacks like a screw-up,
chances are good it's a screw-up.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I have to save my energy for my crusade to rid the
language of the evil word, ``whom.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
