<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EURO-RATES-(TRIMS)-NY     06-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-RATES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING IN EURO IS CHAOTIC AFTER CENTRAL BANK RAISES BASELINE
RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In an unexpectedly aggressive attempt to
help insulate Europe against inflation, the European Central Bank
tightened its grip on monetary policy Thursday by raising its core
interest rate half a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The move, pushing the baseline rate from 3.75 to 4.25 percent,
surprised most economists and sent currency traders into a confused
frenzy over the euro, Europe's common currency.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, which has enjoyed a remarkable turnaround in the last
two weeks, initially climbed against the dollar, going from 96
cents to more than 97 cents. But then it slipped back to 95.7
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates tend to strengthen a currency. The euro's
rise and subsequent fall today, foreign-exchange traders said, may
have been caused by Wim Duisenberg, the central bank's president,
who implied that there would not be any more rate increases soon.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, most currency experts and economists had
predicted that the European Central Bank would increase rates by
only a quarter of a point.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's move came against the backdrop of the euro's travails
in world currency markets. Since its introduction in January 1999,
the euro has steadily plunged in value relative to the U.S. dollar,
from a high of $1.17 to a low of 88.5 cents last month.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the euro suddenly began its first sustained
recovery. Fueled largely by speculation that the central bank would
intervene directly in currency markets _ speculation encouraged by
veiled threats from central bankers _ the euro has climbed 10
percent to about 96 cents.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the bank's decision Thursday, Duisenberg insisted
that the bank was not trying to meddle with exchange rates. Rather,
he based the decision on Europe's accelerating growth and a
heightened threat of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook for growth in the euro area has improved markedly
over the past few months,'' Duisenberg said at a news conference in
Frankfurt on Thursday. But, he said, the risks of inflation had
increased as a result of rising import prices _ for oil in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   But Duisenberg said he remained unsatisfied with what he called
the low value of the euro and acknowledged that this played an
important if indirect role in Thursday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the euro's decline has inevitably led to an
increase in the prices of imports. The euro has slumped against the
yen and the British pound as well as against the dollar, so
Europe's imports from most of the world have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reversal which started about two weeks ago still leaves, I
believe, some potential for further appreciation,'' Duisenberg
said. ``I know that the exchange rate of the euro _ even after the
recent appreciation _ does not yet reflect fundamentals, whatever
they may be.''
</P>
<P>
   But Duisenberg also dampened expectations about additional rate
increases later in the year. ``One of the motives to raise the rate
by a half-point is that such a move will clear the horizon for some
time to come,'' he told reporters. ``We think this move has cleared
the horizon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tony Norfield, global currency analyst at the Dutch bank ABN
Amro, said those remarks might explain why the euro declined after
having initially risen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Norfield predicted that the euro had already ``peaked''
and is likely to slip again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did look fairly aggressive at first,'' Norfield said. ``The
thing that probably took the steam out of the euro was when
Duisenberg suggested that was it and there wouldn't be any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg was deliberately ambiguous and left himself ample
maneuvering room for a shift in emphasis. But his implied message
contrasted sharply with that of Alan Greenspan, chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board, who issued a clear warning about additional
rate increases after the Fed raised rates on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Though surprised by Thursday's move, most economists said it was
justified and came merely faster than they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't do much to damage growth,'' said Holger Fahrinkrug,
an economist at Warburg Dillon Read in Frankfurt. ``I'd say the ECB
was a bit slow before and that this step compensates for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Schneider, head of euro-zone economic research at
Deutsche Bank Research, said that Duisenberg was probably not
reacting to the euro's weakness but that Thursday's action could
nonetheless keep the currency moving upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ECB won't dislike the windfall effect of the euro,''
Schneider said. ``In that respect, the timing is better than as if
the hike had come a few weeks ago. The chances are always better if
you support a market trend that has already crystallized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
