<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SUPER-VISION-BOS &LR;      06-08 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-VISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNNOLOGY MAY GIVE YOU THE EYE OF AN EAGLE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Superman, watch out: A University of Rochester
scientist is developing technology that could someday make ``super
vision'' a reality for almost anyone.
</P>
<P>
   David Williams, professor of medical optics at the New York
state college, says his techniques if used in humans could push far
beyond merely correcting people's vision to the standard 20/20, and
actually produce a kind of enhanced vision that could equal the
legendary sharp eyesight of eagles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the research could lead to improved methods for
diagnosing some eye diseases and monitoring the progress of
treatment, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's techniques come from the same ones astronomers have
used over the last few years to improve the sharpness of telescope
images. Williams is developing the concepts in his newly
established Center for Vision Excellence at the university, and
described his research here Thursday at a meeting of the American
Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Williams ``has been way out in front, exploring how we could
enhance people's vision beyond what is normally thought of as
perfect vision,'' said Scott MacRae, a cornea specialist and
pioneer in refractive surgery who has joined Williams at the new
vision center. ``In the old days, we were just trying to correct
people's vision problems and treat disease. This new research takes
what we consider normal vision and enhances it. This is truly
revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers stress that the work is still in an early
stage and any real applications to human vision are a few years
away, it already attracted the interest of the contact lens company
Bausch &AMP; Lomb, which has licensed the technology and is working
with the university to develop it.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the new method is the use of a device that shines
dozens of narrow light beams into the eye. The beams are reflected
back out and collected by a ``wavefront sensor'' so that computers
can then analyze in detail the tiny imperfections in the eye's
cornea and lens.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional vision correction deals with the overall average
shape of the cornea and lens, but the equipment used is unable to
detect or correct the smaller-scale variations picked up by the
adaptive optics method. The kind of subtle imperfections in the
lens and cornea that are detected by this system are so small that
physicians didn't even know they existed until Williams's lab
developed this technique.
</P>
<P>
   When you look through this laboratory system, Williams said,
``The world looks crisper. In some people, the ability to pick up
contrast, such as minute patterns of stripes, is increased by a
factor of six. It allows for a level of vision correction that's
just not available today. It's like needing glasses and getting
them for the first time. Everything suddenly looks sharper and
clearer, no matter how good your eyes are normally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Williams said, the system should make it possible to
perform a detailed analysis of an individual's eyes and produce
customized glasses or contact lenses _ or perhaps even customized
laser surgery _ designed to correct all of these subtle
imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   He said that experiments show the system could lead to a
doubling, or better, of the amount of detail that humans could see,
thus nearly equaling the visual acuity of eagles and other
predatory birds.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements should be even more dramatic in the case of
night vision, Williams said. While his tests have shown that the
upper limit of human vision as measured by standard vision tests is
about 20/10, or about double the sharpness of ``normal'' vision,
the effects of these corrections are most pronounced in night
vision because the iris is wide open and more of the eye's lens is
used, exposing more of its imperfections. This effect is not
reflected in the usual vision tests.
</P>
<P>
   Tests have shown that the normal maximum detail the human eye
can see is a grid of 60 lines per degree. Cats have much poorer
vision, able to see only about 5 lines per degree, while predatory
birds can see as many as 150 lines per degree.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the sharp-eyed vision of eagles lies in
the superior lenses of their eyes, which can be matched by the new
correction methods. But eagles also have smaller, more closely
spaced light receptors on their retinas, which cannot be
duplicated, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   As a side benefit of his research, Williams has been able for
the first time to take pictures of the retinas of human subjects
that clearly show every individual cone _ the receptors that pick
up light and color. Normally, the distortions of the eye's lens
blur such images, making it impossible to distinguish the
individual cones. The only way such images could be obtained before
was by surgically removing the retina after the patient's death.
</P>
<P>
   The research has also made it possible for the first time to
detect the three different kinds of cones, sensitive to different
colors of light, which make color vision possible, and to see how
these different cones are distributed through the visual field.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement and relative numbers of the cones for different
colors is quite random, and varies greatly among individuals. This
is very different from the eyes of fish, for example, which show an
absolutely regular crystal-like pattern of color cones.
</P>
<P>
   This method of viewing the detailed structure of the retina,
Williams said, could someday be used to monitor the progression of
diseases such as retinitis pigmentosa, which causes a slow
degeneration of the retina, and to observe directly the effects of
experimental treatments for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, this could be a very useful clinical tool,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his experimental results were recently published in the
Journal of the Optical Society of America, and a meeting last month
of the Association for Research in Vision and Ophthalmology devoted
a whole symposium to reports from Williams and other researchers on
the topic of ``enhanced vision.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the pioneers of that telescope technology, Jerry Nelson
of the University of California, who designed the innovative
optical systems for the Keck telescopes in Hawaii _ the world's
largest telescopes _ visited Williams's lab this week. He tried an
experimental version of the new system, and said he was impressed
with the improvement in vision that it produced. ``The potential is
very exciting,'' he said. ``It was amazing to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
