<SLUG> BC-TERRA-LYCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRA HOLDERS VOTE FOR LYCOS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shareholders of Spain's Terra Networks SA have voted to
approve its plan to buy Internet portal Lycos Inc. for about $12.5
billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The step could help Lycos obtain consent from its own
shareholders for the deal, which would form an international
network of Web sites and services to be known as Terra Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Approval from Terra's shareholders was never in doubt, since its
Madrid-based parent Telefonica SA owns about 67 percent and had
arranged the merger, which was announced May 16. Spokesmen for the
companies wouldn't disclose the margin of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But a Lycos executive said shareholders ``overwhelmingly''
approved the deal and that it drew support from more than 90
percent of ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
   That could represent an important vote of confidence for the
proposed merger, because Terra's shares have fallen below the
minimum level of $45.37, in American share equivalents, that would
be used to calculate the final number of Terra shares Lycos
shareholders will receive under the agreement. In Nasdaq trading
Thursday Terra fell $1.625 to $42.375.
</P>
<P>
   Terra's shares traded around $57 each before the deal was
announced, but investors bid down the agreement on concerns the
deal overvalued Lycos. For similar reasons Lycos shares also fell
by as much as 28 percent from their high of $72.625.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos shares have also recovered since, closing at $64 each
Thursday, down $1.875.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Terra chairman Juan Villalonga called the Lycos
deal a ``great leap'' that would help the company internationally.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Lycos chief executive Bob Davis said
he has shareholders' support. ``I've yet to encounter a shareholder
of scale who has been anything but extremely positive on the
deal,'' he said from the company's Waltham headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A Lycos shareholder vote is expected later this summer. Last
year investor opposition scuttled a previous merger agreement Davis
had struck with USA Networks Inc. A key critic was CMGI Inc. chief
executive David Wetherell, whose company then held about a 20
percent stake in Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell has praised the Terra deal's broad outlines but has
yet to say whether he would vote in favor of it. CMGI now holds
around 16 percent of Lycos, down from 22 percent at the start of
1999, according to an executive there.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is completed, the new company would combine Terra
sites popular throughout Latin America with Lycos' mixed bag of
content including search, finance, and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Terra is now based in Madrid; the new company's headquarters
will be moved to Barcelona, Terra said Thursday, but it would
retain a significant Waltham operation. Terra Lycos ``is and always
will be a Spanish company,'' Villalonga said.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the deal would leave Terra Networks with plenty of
cash to compete against Yahoo Inc. and America Online Inc. German
publisher Bertelsmann has also committed to spend $1 billion over
five years on advertising and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
