<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SOUCOM-DC0609-COX     06-08 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUCOM-DC0609-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern buys D.C. area plants
</P>
<P>
   By MATTHEW C. QUINN
</P>
<P>
   c 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Southern Co. will become the primary electricity
provider to Washington, D.C., with a $2.65 billion power plant deal
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's purchase of four power plants from Potomac Electric
Power Co. will be the largest acquisition yet for the Atlanta-based
utility holding company. It's also thought to be the largest asset
purchase by any U.S. utility in a rapidly consolidating industry.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy Inc., Southern's unregulated power subsidiary,
agreed to purchase four plants from the Washington-based utility,
known as Pepco. The plants have combined generating capacity of
5,154 megawatts and are fueled by coal, oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the plants are in Washington's Maryland suburbs. The
fourth is near downtown Alexandria, Va., just across the Potomac
River from the U.S. Capitol and not far from Ronald Reagan National
Airport. Southern also agreed to operate two small Pepco plants in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Southern agreed to sell Pepco all the electricity it needs for
four years at prices below the Washington utility's average cost of
production. Pepco serves 700,000 homes and businesses in Washington
and the Maryland suburbs, including the White House, Congress and
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After that agreement expires, Southern will be free to sell
electricity from the plants at market rates to utilities and other
large users in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Maryland, Delaware,
Virginia and Washington. Southern agree to retain the majority of
the plants' 1,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, subject to regulatory approval, is expected to close
by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Southern paid considerably more than the estimated $1.8 billion
book value for the Pepco plants. But such purchases are not
uncommon in the consolidating $200 billion-a-year electric utility
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Levi, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston, which
advised Southern on the transaction, said the acquisition is a
``piece of the puzzle'' in the company's drive to become a major
U.S. generator with a coast-to-coast network of power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will boost the value of an initial public offering
planned later this year for 20 percent of the shares in Southern
Energy, Levi said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern plans to split off SEI into a separate company that
will manage unregulated utility businesses outside the area served
by the parent company's five regulated Southeastern utilities. SEI
accounted for 26 percent of Southern's profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the Pepco acquisition, SEI will operate 15,000
megawatts of generating capacity, about the same as Georgia Power
Co., Southern's largest subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an aggressive expansion in the last five years, SEI
has made major power plant acquisitions across the United States
and abroad. Until now, the largest price tag was $2.3 billion for a
Hong Kong power company.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of San Francisco, the purchases have until
now not made Southern the primary supplier to a major U.S.
metropolitan area. A Pepco spokesman said Southern will supply
``virtually all'' of the power to the utility's service area.
</P>
<P>
   Pepco put its power plants on the block last year to exit the
power generation business and concentrate on selling electricity
produced by others as well as cable television, Internet access and
other services.
</P>
<P>
   Southern shares closed Thursday at $24.94, down 6 cents on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
