<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUCCESS060     06-08 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUCCESS0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lakers confident, not cocky
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now the really hard part for the Lakers: taking
the Indiana Pacers seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the NBA Finals, Lakers fans and officials had some
concern about that, no matter how much the team denied it. But
after their demolition of the Pacers in Game 1 Wednesday night at
the Staples Center, the task is more daunting.
</P>
<P>
   After the seven-game struggle with the Portland Trail Blazers in
the Western Conference finals, the Lakers seemed to be back on
track in their quest for the championship. They were in total
control of Game 1, even when the Pacers moved to within two points
late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. just got serious again and backhanded Indiana. With
Shaquille O'Neal dominating, the Lakers easily bolted to a 1-0
series lead going into tonight's Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Lakers' posture was the same as it was before Game
1 and even more emphatic: Overconfidence is not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at it,'' guard Kobe Bryant said, ``we're three
games away from accomplishing our goal. By no means are we going to
let down. By no means are we going to let up.''
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics of their 104-87 victory could provide proper
motivation for the Lakers. They figure the Pacers will make
adjustments in how they defend O'Neal, who hit 21 of 31 shots for
43 points and had 19 rebounds. The league's MVP controlled the game
and the Pacers' big men.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the first frontal piece of our offensive machinery and
our primary weapon,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``And teams
are going to have to adjust if they're going to beat us in a
series. We anticipate they'll make adjustments at some level, and
we'll have to counter them.''
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, Indiana will try to be more physical with
O'Neal and double-team him aggressively to force him to pass out to
teammates. The Pacers will try to force other Lakers to beat them
instead of taking another beating from O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be prepared for them being all over Shaq,'' said
forward Rick Fox, who had 11 points off the bench. ``You don't
expect them to leave single coverage on him as much as they did.
When that happened, we all started to feel comfortable. We executed
our offense 10 times better than any game in these playoffs. When
Shaq's playing like that on both sides, patrolling the paint like
that, it's easy to have the games we all had. But now it'll be
about what we do when they double him hard, like I'm sure they
will.''
</P>
<P>
   The other area of concern that should keep the Lakers grounded
is that no one expects guard Reggie Miller to endure another
1-for-16 shooting effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means was that an indicator of what this series is going
to be like,'' Bryant said. ``They're going to be ready to play Game
2. They're going to be more physical. Reggie will take more shots.
We can't take Game 1 and run with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And it could be especially scary that Miller talked of the
Lakers being ``in trouble'' if they play him the same way tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary, man; he was 1-for-16,'' Fox said. ``He may go 16
for 16 the next game. You don't count on him missing those kinds of
shots every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Laker forward Robert Horry said, ``You hate it when a guy of his
nature misses that many shots, because you know he is going to come
back strong the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the consensus and the domination of Game 1, the
Lakers have reasons not to get too confident about their prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand if we'd been in this situation before,''
Horry said. ``But no one has been here. We aren't going to miss the
opportunity. A lot of teams, when they've been there before, get
big heads because they think: `We're good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we're not good,'' Horry said. ``We haven't won anything
yet. And to get what we want, we can't even afford to think the
Pacers are going to let us have it. We have to play hard and the
right way every game. Indiana got here by beating some good teams.
They earned their way. We know that. And still respect them. And
it'll show in our play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
