<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NKOREA-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN TO VISIT NORTH KOREA IN JULY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir Putin plans to visit North Korea
next month, a move that underscores his active foreign policy and
that seems calculated to counter the Clinton administration's plan
for a national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Thursday that it would be the first trip
by a Russian leader to the North Korean capital, Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unprecedented event, a bold step, as no head of
state from our country has ever been in North Korea _ neither in
Soviet nor in Russian times,'' Georgi Toloraya, an official in the
Foreign Ministry, told the newspaper Vremya Novostei.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes on the heels of Putin's meeting with
President Clinton in Moscow, in which the two leaders found
themselves at odds over the administration's plans for a limited
antimissile system.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korea visit will provide Putin with an opportunity to
make his case that diplomacy, not missile defense, is the way to
cope with an emerging missile threat from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Putin can also use the visit to challenge the idea that North
Korea is an irrational ``rogue state,'' a description the United
States has used to justify its antimissile plans.
</P>
<P>
   Those Russian themes are likely to resonate in Western Europe,
where the Western allies remain very anxious that the
administration's plan will start an arms race and leave them
unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Putin took his campaign to Italy, where he urged
Europeans to support a Russian alternative to the administration's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were caught by surprise by the Russian
announcement. They said they welcomed the visit as a way to end
North Korea's isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe that dialogue among all countries in
the region contributes to peace and security on the Korean
peninsula and beyond,'' a State Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Japanese media, Putin's visit is scheduled to
take place in mid-July, just before the summit meeting of the
leading industrial democracies in Okinawa, Japan, from July 21 to
23.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Moscow had become more interested in the
situation on the Korean peninsula as a result of the summit meeting
between North and South Korea scheduled for early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Toloraya, who is deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's Asian
department, said that the Kremlin had proposed the visit and that
the North Korean leader, Kim Jong Il, had issued a formal
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Toloraya said Moscow wanted to assure the North Koreans that
Moscow did not favor a unified Korea dominated by Seoul. Such fears
have grown in Pyongyang, he said, as Russia has developed economic
and political ties with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the case,'' Toloraya said in his newspaper
interview. ``We consider it necessary for the two Korean states to
coexist for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. antiballistic missile plan is very much on the agenda,
according to the Russians. Toloraya said the Russians and North
Koreans would have a general discussion on ``how we can act
together in the world situation, including in connection with U.S.
plans for ABM.''
</P>
<P>
   In an indirect swipe at Washington, he said Russia's new
assertive role on foreign policy had the potential to upset
``somebody else's cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia fears that the limited defense the United States is
planing is just the first phase in a larger system that will
eventually counter Russia's strategic forces. Washington's goal has
been to overcome Russian suspicions and persuade the Kremlin to
amend the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable the United States to develop a limited
defensive system, which could include the deployment of 100
interceptors and the construction of a radar in Alaska.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To make its case, U.S. officials sought to convince Moscow that
North Korea's evolving missile capabilities are a danger to Russia
as well as the West. While the United States has cited a variety of
emerging threats, the missile threats from North Korea have emerged
as the primary argument for moving ahead quickly with a missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   At the summit meeting between Clinton and Putin, Russia
acknowledged that a missile threat was emerging from nations like
North Korea. Still, the Russians insist that the threat is not as
worrisome as the United States says. And while the Americans have
insisted that an antimissile system is needed, the Russians have
urged diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has persuaded North Korea to accept a
moratorium on the test-firing of long-range ballistic missiles.
That has precluded Pyongyang from testing its Taepo Dong-2, a
two-stage missile that Washington fears might eventually be
developed as an intercontinental missile.
</P>
<P>
   The United States fears that North Korea might try to break out
of those constraints. But instead of assuming the worst, the
Russians have been urging more engagement with Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several indications of growing ties between
Russia and North Korea. The Russian foreign minister, Igor S.
Ivanov, paid a recent visit to North Korea. And on Thursday a North
Korean delegation arrived at Sakhalin Island in the Russian Far
East to discuss joint construction projects, the Russian news
agency Itar-Tass reported Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
