<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-GLOBAL-NYT &LR;      06-08 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GLOBAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT BREAKUP ORDER DRAWS MIXED BUT MUTED REACTION ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Windows and Word may be ubiquitous across
Europe and Asia, but news of the court order to break up Microsoft
generated a muted reaction outside of the United States on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of admiration _ mixed with disbelief _ among
many commentators that a government would take such a step. Neither
Europe nor Japan have ever seen a comparable effort to break up a
large company, though European regulators have become much more
aggressive about imposing big fines on companies for
anti-competitive activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breakup of a company is impossible under German law,''
said Stefan Siebert, a spokesman for Germany's cartel office in
Bonn. ``All we can do is prohibit abuses and impose fines.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, La Republica captured the sense that the breakup was
something that could happen only in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Washington judge with the deceptively good-natured image of
a western actor has with almost hate-filled words ordered the
breakup of Microsoft into two separate parts,'' the newspaper said
in an editorial Thursday. ``The century of the New Economy begins
exactly where that of the old economy began: with an America that
breaks up the monopoly of the `new oil.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Monti, head of the European Commission's competition
ministry, said through a spokeswoman Thursday that he
``congratulates'' the U.S. government for its work but said it was
too early to know whether the court order would affect European
investigations into Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Monti has raised questions about the Windows 2000 operating
system, suggesting that it may hinder the abilities of computers
linked over networks and over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His office is also scrutinizing Microsoft's plan to acquire 29.7
percent of Telewest Communications PLC, the British cable
television operator. Microsoft has teamed up with Liberty Media
Group to buy a controlling stake in Telewest from Media One Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that there will be an appeal,'' said Amelia
Torres, a spokeswoman for the competition ministry. ``We will have
to see what the final ruling is.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most European software companies said they would not be
affected by the Microsoft case, several welcomed the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the recognition that monopolies have never been
successful or sensible,'' said Reiner Jung, a spokesman for Brokat
Infosystems A.G. of Stuttgart, a fast-growing developer of
encryption programs and other software used in online banking
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we want a weaker Microsoft,'' Jung added.
``Quite the contrary, we want a strong Microsoft. But what we don't
want is a monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Suse AG, in Nurenberg, which produces software that runs on the
Linux operating system, a competitor to Windows, argued that a
court-orderd breakup of Microsoft might do little to break the
Windows monopoly unless the company makes its code available to
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft will have the ability after the breakup of making
available applications for other platforms,'' said Carsten Fischer,
a spokesman for Suse. ``But Microsoft has to adhere to the rules of
open-source software, which includes opening up its
documentation.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest effect of the Microsoft case in Europe could prove
to be on its many alliances and partnerships. Microsoft has struck
technology deals with scores of European media and
telecommunications companies, and it sought to invest in both cable
television and wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials say their goal has been to gain a foothold
in new media, from interactive digital television to advanced
wireless data communications.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, companies involved with Microsoft are waiting to
see what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have consistently made it clear that we welcome Microsoft
as a potential corporate shareholder, and that remains our
position,'' said Rachel Turner, a spokeswoman for Telewest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
