<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-SENATE-PATIENTS-BOS &LR;      06-08 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-PATIENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP BLOCKS PATIENTS' RIGHTS MANEUVER IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a rancorous prelude to election-year debates
across the country, Senate Republicans Thursday narrowly thwarted a
Democratic effort to bypass stalled negotiations and pass the most
comprehensive overhaul of the managed care industry since the
advent of health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   With medical care for tens of millions of Americans at stake,
the Senate voted, 51-48, to block consideration of a Patients Bill
of Rights that would widely expand federal protections for
consumers in private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who forced the showdown, and Senate
Republican leaders claimed victory after the vote, though afterward
the prospect of Congress passing sweeping new regulations of the
health insurance industry this year appeared more imperiled than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The White House backed Kennedy's move, which the Massachusetts
senator said he made out of frustration over the recalcitrance of
Republican leaders who control a committee of House and Senate
conferees assigned to iron out differences between their competing
plans to regulate HMOS.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly four months, the closed-door talks have produced only
meager progress, and fewer than 40 legislative days remain for the
106th Congress to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few more days like this and the Republicans will stop
stonewalling on the Patients Bill of Rights,'' Kennedy told
reporters, arguing that he effectively came within one vote of a
50-50 tie that would have lead Vice President Al Gore to cast the
deciding vote to pass the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Four Republicans _ Senators Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island, John
McCain of Arizona, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, and Peter
Fitzgerald of Illinois _ joined the unified Democrat minority in
supporting the measure, which was modeled on a landmark plan the
House passed a year ago. Senator Kent Conrad, a North Dakota
Democrat who was absent, would have made the final tally 51-49,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP's chief negotiator, Senator Don Nickles, said
Kennedy's provocative move to bypass the talks had all but doomed
the negotiating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything the White House and the Democrats have done the
last couple of days has been very deterimental to the likelihood of
getting a bill enacted,'' said Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant
Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, flying home from Japan Thursday, sent
senators a letter before the vote urging them to ``put the
interests of patients before those of the special interests'' and
support Kennedy's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles suggested that Senate Republican leaders, in the face of
Democratic opposition, may abandon the negotiating process and work
with their House counterparts to craft a compromise measure that
could pass both chambers with GOP support.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, Senate Republicans accused Kennedy and his
allies of brashly undermining the talks to seize the advantage in
the run-up to the 2000 congressional elections. With polls showing
overwhelming support for tougher federal regulation of HMOS, the
vote was potentially perilous for a number of Republican senators
who face strong challenges in November, particularly Spencer
Abraham of Michigan and Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles argued that the talks have produced substantial
progress, and he expressed disdain that Kennedy and others had
described the conference as ``a charade'' and ``a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy forced the vote by attaching the health-care measure to
a bill authorizing $309.8 billion in defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a lot of people are a lot more interested in
politics and political theater and seeing if they can scare people
and use it to their political advantage,'' said Nickles. ``I very
much resent that.''
</P>
<P>
   The House measure, which the Senate rejected last year and again
Thursday, would guarantee fundamental protections for all 161
million Americans in HMOs and permit patients to sue their health
plans for decisions on medical care that resulted in harm or death.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate alternative, favored by GOP leaders, would cover only
the 48 million Americans who are enrolled in health plans that are
exempt from state regulations and would generally shield insurers
from patient lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   And negotiators have reached full agreement on only two of the
22 major issues in the measures after nearly four months of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the talks have dragged on beyond any reasonable
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an endless road to nowhere,'' he said on the
Senate floor. ``It is long past time for this Congress to stop
protecting HMO profits and start protecting patients' health.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Chafee, the moderate Republicans from New England who
sometimes provide Senate Democrats the margin of victory refused to
break ranks with GOP leaders on the managed-care matter. They were
Senators James M. Jeffords of Vermont, and Olympia J. Snowe and
Susan M. Collins, both of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords and Collins spoke on the Senate floor to defend GOP
leaders for their handling of the conference. ``I find it
incredible that we are not allowing them to complete the process
when they made such progress,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, a Texas Republican, went a step further,
accusing Kennedy of ruining a productive negotiating process solely
for partisan gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Senator Kennedy is proving today is the cynical political
fact that no good deed ever goes unpunished,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats described Gramm's depiction of the talks as fruitful
as ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference between this conference and a glacier is
that a glacier at least moves an inch or two a year,'' said Senator
Byron L. Dorgan, a North Dakota Democrat and assistant minority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defeat, Kennedy and his allies in the House,
including many Republicans, described the vote as a way to refocus
the nation's attention on the issue. They expressed hope that the
renewed attention would increase pressure on Senate majority leader
Trent Lott to speed up the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a certain level and Senator Lott has to look at
losing control of the issue,'' said Representative Greg Ganske, an
Iowa Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-ART     06-08 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD AND DOT-COMS ENTER UNCERTAIN NEW WORLD OF DIGITAL
ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mika Salmi said that he is always a little
cautious when venturing into the wilds of Hollywood from his
Atomfilms home base in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fast in Hollywood,'' said Salmi, whose company
produces short films on the Internet and sells them to outlets like
airlines and shopping malls. ``People are always coming to us,
trying to buy us. We're not anti-Hollywood. The key is just not to
get caught by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year or so, the once separate and distinct worlds
of old-line Hollywood and the Internet dot-com ventures of the new
economy have been intermingling with increasing urgency, taking
their first faltering steps toward the coming age of digital
entertainment, whatever that might turn out to be. While the major
studios, conservative as always, are largely maintaining a discreet
distance from the roiling waters of the Web, many entertainment
executives, filmmakers, celebrities and talent agencies have been
plunging head-first into the digital deep end.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a week passes without the announcement of a new actor or
director signing a deal with a dot-com to create exclusive digital
films, or of a Hollywood insider proclaiming the acquisition or
creation of a new online venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have so many people in Hollywood who know so much about
their business that they convince themselves that they know about
every business,'' said David Wertheimer, chairman of WireBreak.com,
which emphasizes interactive entertainment on its Web site. ``They
look at what's on the Web and they say, `Hey, I can make better
videos. I'll start my own dot-com,''' Wertheimer added. ``They see
so much attention and so much money going to these Internet guys
and they think, `Who's that pimply faced guy on the cover of Time
Magazine? That's supposed to be me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has had to dodge or absorb a steady stream of
challenges over the decades, from sound to color to television to
videocassettes to independent films. Each one was predicted, at the
time, to be the movie establishment's undoing. Yet each time,
Hollywood not only persevered but, eventually, overcame the threat.
Now, while that may well happen again, many are wondering whether
the hidebound studios have finally found an adversary they will be
unable to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   To Joe Roth _ a veteran movie executive who left the top job at
Walt Disney Studios last year to start up the just-unveiled
Revolution Studios, an independent production company, and who is
also involved in two Internet ventures _ the issue is just that
stark: ``When all of this resolves itself,'' he asks, ``who will be
occupying the top tier?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, will the entertainment conglomerates own the
dot-coms or _ as in the case of the America Online acquisition of
Time Warner _ will the dot-coms own the entertainment
conglomerates?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is definitely a time of confusion and
opportunity,'' said Larry Kasanoff, a longtime feature-film
producer whose Threshold Entertainment includes a dot-com operation
aimed at attracting young males with a combination of sophomoric
sitcoms, video-game sagas and models in bikinis. ``Is this period
going to be long enough that a bunch of dot-com start-ups will have
time to get established? I don't know. I think, five years from
now, we'll look back and a lot of these dot-coms will have been
absorbed by the big studios. Others will have been able to use this
confusion time to take their place in the landscape. We intend to
be one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   The new entertainment dot-coms fall into a number of categories.
Some offer so-called streaming video, usually live-action and
animated shorts on the Internet, with a smattering of games and
chat rooms and varying degrees of interactivity. Others are more
business-to-business sites, connecting filmmakers with agents, with
projects or with each other. Some are digital laboratories, aiming
for a niche audience and, through the success or failure of their
programming, providing an incubator for future movie and television
projects. And many are just flat-out marketing tools, dedicated to
the glories of a particular film or image-conscious celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected in a business where celebrity is the
hottest commodity, many of the Hollywood dot-coms have been trying
to outdo one another by signing up major actors and filmmakers.
Shockwave.com, which creates Web-based animation software as well
as maintaining its own destination site, has signed deals with
filmmakers like James Brooks and David Lynch. Z.com, among whose
backers is manager-turned-mogul Brad Grey of Basic Entertainment,
has signed deals with the producer Jerry Bruckheimer and the
director Oliver Stone. And there are dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The invasion of the dot-coms has been, as far as Hollywood is
concerned, a relatively recent phenomenon. ``If you look back to
early 1999, there were maybe six or seven Internet sites offering
streaming video in one form or another,'' said Rick Hess, president
of Propaganda Films, which makes theatrical features as well as
digital entertainment for the Web. ``Today, there are maybe 75, and
that number is going up. But everyone figures that, down the road,
when the dust settles, there will only be maybe a dozen of them
left.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Those in the Hollywood mainstream who have been counseling
caution feel somewhat vindicated by the failure of recent Internet
initial public offerings, and the precipitous drop in high-tech
stock prices. And few can contain their delight at the collapse,
last month, of one of the highest-profile of the entertainment
dot-coms, The Digital Entertainment Network, even though its
financial troubles were largely attributed to its profligate
spending rather than to a flaw in the overall strategy of streaming
video over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one in Hollywood expects that The Den will be the last
entertainment dot-com to fail, and much of the discussion in recent
weeks has been about which will go next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've detected a real change,'' Wertheimer said, as people have
reacted to the one-two punch of the Nasdaq plummet in April and the
collapse of The Den. Many of the players who were poised to jump
into the dot-com waters have decided to pull back, or wait a little
longer, he said, and some of those who are already in up to their
eyeballs are getting a lot more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this may turn out to be Hollywood's Vietnam, with
a lot of people rushing into this without a clear idea of why
they're getting in,'' Wertheimer said. ``We're going to see a lot
of people retreating and declaring victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the field has been particularly difficult, in part
because there is no clear picture of where this is all headed and
because so many of these new entertainment dot-coms have shifted
their strategies in recent months in the face of rapidly changing
technologies, increased competition and growing investor
nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ifilm, initially based in San Francisco and one of the early
leaders, began as a site where filmmakers could post their digital
shorts and try to find an audience. Now, it is based in Los Angeles
and offering not only its own stable of shorts but also serving as
a portal with easy-click access to digital entertainment all over
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Pop.com, an Internet partnership between Steven Spielberg and
Jeffrey Katzenberg of DreamWorks and Ron Howard and Brian Grazer of
Imagine Entertainment, was announced with a lot of fanfare last
October as a site that would be up and running this spring,
offering original short ``pops'' of entertainment featuring some of
Hollywood's top performers and filmmakers. But Pop.com is still not
online and there are reports that its principals are retooling
their Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When this wave of dot-coms took off, much of the initial
momentum was toward building so-called destination sites, aimed at
grabbing and holding an audience, preferably the 12-to-24-year-old
males who drive so much of popular entertainment. Now, however,
with a lot of destinations but with a scarcity of things to watch
there, many of the new start-ups and some of the older ones have
turned their attention elsewhere. Several key companies have
announced, or intend soon to announce, that they will spend more
time and energy on creating content for others' sites than for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   No one has a real clue where all this will end. ``We are in the
middle, right now, of speeding toward some future unknown
environment,'' said Morgan Rector, president of the Imperial Bank
Entertainment Group, one of the financial institutions most active
in underwriting feature films.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood establishment is worried that, with the Internet
offering the promise of new ways to distribute movies while also
competing for eyeballs and entertainment dollars, the new order
might well upset long-standing financial arrangements. And, just as
significantly, there are worries that what has happened to the pop
music business _ with songs being swapped and pirated on the
Internet beyond the reach of record company accountants _ will
happen with movies, too, if firm protections are not put in place
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-coms, meanwhile, worry about being transformed into just
another division of a profit-hungry global media conglomerate that
will prevent them from expanding and exploding outdated
entertainment concepts. ``They always said that Hollywood runs on
fear and greed, and it's definitely true,'' Salmi said. ``The greed
kicks in when they look at all the dot-com millions. The fear is,
oh my gosh, `we'd better act quickly or we'll miss something
big.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To some, there is a bit of a lemming-like quality to the way so
many independent producers and former studio bosses have announced
the formation of their own start-ups, as though having a dot-com in
your roster of in-house activities is now as essential as getting
the best table at Spago or The Grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's like, if you don't have that as part of your
dialogue over lunch at The Grill, then you're not with it,'' Hess
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is meeting the dot-coms in a variety of ways. Each of
the major studios has its own in-house Web operation. Some, like
Warner Brothers Entertaindom.com or Sony's Station.com offer
original entertainment and games. Others, however, are simply
marketing devices for coming releases.
</P>
<P>
   But the heavy action has been in Internet start-up companies.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, for instance, has hired John Hegeman, one of the people
responsible for the successful ``Blair Witch Project'' Internet
marketing campaign, to create Distantcorners.com, a site
specializing in horror and science-fiction. And he bought a
substantial interest in Mediatrip.com, which his Revolution Studios
intends to use as a marketing tool for his feature films and as an
incubator for new characters and offbeat stories.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cooper, former head of production at DreamWorks, recently
announced the creation of a new Internet start-up, which will be
aimed at creating digital content for a variety of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in interviews with more than a dozen top entertainment
executives, every single one either had started his own dot-com,
bought an interest in somebody else's, or claimed he was just
waiting for the perfect moment to announce a new dot-com strategy.
</P>
<P>
   There is more here, they all insisted, than smoke-and-mirrors.
``I believe it,'' Cooper said. ``I'm betting my money on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
