<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Bodies of Evidence 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ Salon.com is running a series of fictional stories, ``31
Ejaculations,'' in which performance artist and writer
 &UR; Eric &LR;  &UR; Bogosian &LR;  purports &UR;  &LR; to describe pre-sex, sex and post-sex.
The pieces were created for a performance in New York four years
ago. ``I believe,'' writes Bogosian in the introduction, ``that God
made sex as a kind of unsolvable Rubik's Cube so that we could have
something to do while we're killing time here on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amtrak is having a sweepstakes to celebrate the renaming of
its San Diego-Los Angeles service, which it is now calling the
Pacific Surfliner. In keeping with the California theme, Amtrak's
Web site invites contestants to ``register here to win $5,000
toward a facelift.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; `THE INSIDER' WARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After speaking last weekend at a national conference of
Investigative Reporters and Editors in New York, &UR; Don Hewitt &LR;  and
 &UR; Mike Wallace  &LR; of ``60 Minutes'' were in the center of a fracas that
erupted over their harsh criticism of  &UR; Lowell Bergman &LR; , who used to
work for them and served as a consultant for the movie ``The
Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who was portrayed in the movie as caving in to CBS fears
about airing a segment about the evils of tobacco companies, said
that Bergman, depicted in the movie as a hero fighting for the
story, was ``a wannabe hotshot reporter.'' Bergman is ``not a
journalist I would allow within 100 miles of a TV news show or
1,000 miles of a journalism school,'' said his former boss.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman is working as a producer for ``Frontline'' and at the UC
Berkeley Graduate School of Journalism. After Hewitt's onstage
remarks, said the Hollywood Reporter, Hewitt and Wallace exchanged
heated remarks with friends and supporters of Bergman, including
``Frontline'' boss  &UR; David Fanning &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by 100 journalists, the three argued, said the
Reporter, ``with Wallace grabbing Fanning's shoulders at least once
to make a point.'' Hewitt charged, ``That son of a bitch turned on
me. He lied. He betrayed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached on Wednesday, June 7, Bergman told Personals that ``a
lot of this is a really old story. We've already hashed this all
out. You can make up your own mind, by the harshness of Hewitt's
remarks and Wallace's behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. New York state officials canceled a talk by  &UR; Jeffrey &LR; 
 &UR; Wigand &LR; , whose whistle-blowing was at the heart of ``The Insider,''
at a state-sponsored conference on young people and smoking last
weekend. Wigand was barred because he planned to criticize New York
Gov.
 &UR; George Pataki  &LR; for vetoing a bill about cigarettes and fire safety
standards. A health department spokesman told the New York Times
that the remarks would have been too political.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; KITCHEN SINK AND ALL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Near Kiev on Thursday, June 8, Bechtel National handed over a
fully equipped kitchen and dining hall used by workers who were
destroying Cold War weapon sites to an orphanage in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Under contract with the U.S. government, Bechtel has been
dismantling missile launch silos and control centers at 10 places
in Ukraine and Russia. When one of the Ukraine projects ended, and
the kitchen, tables and equipment were no longer needed, ownership
was transferred to the Ukrainian army, which, in turn, gave the
equipment to the 67-year-old orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 135 children who live in the facility _ from newborn
to 4 years old, many disabled _ presented flowers to their
benefactors in handover ceremonies yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On the first Sunday night of November sweeps week, reports US
Weekly, CBS will broadcast `` &UR; Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis &LR; :
A Life,'' opposite NBC's broadcast of ``Jackie, Ethel Joan: The
Women of Camelot.''
</P>
