<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HEARTPUMP-HNS &LR;      06-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART </SLUG>
 PUMP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PATIENT `DOING WELL' AFTER 4-OUNCE DeBAKEY HEART PUMP IMPLANTED &HT;     
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Legendary heart surgeon Dr. Michael E. DeBakey
announced the latest in a lifetime of innovations Thursday: the
implantation of a miniature heart pump in a 31-year-old woman with
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The operation, performed by Dr. George P. Noon on Wednesday, was
the first implantation of the device in an American patient.
Developed by DeBakey, Noon and engineers at NASA over 12 years, and
manufactured in Houston, the pump has been implanted in 32 patients
in Europe since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patient is doing well this morning,'' said DeBakey, 91,
chancellor emeritus of Baylor College of Medicine in Houston. ``It
was very gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Noon, a Methodist Heart Center cardiovascular surgeon, said the
woman, who was confined to bed awaiting a transplant prior to the
operation, would be walking by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very pleased, '' Noon said. ``Her main complaint is pain
from the incision.''
</P>
<P>
   The pump, the MicroMed DeBakey VAD, is descended from a category
of pumps called left ventricular assist devices, or LVADs. The
MicroMed pump is one of the tiniest yet, weighing 4 ounces and
completely internal except for a single wire that extends outside
the body and connects to a battery pack.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the Texas Heart Institute implanted another miniature
LVAD, the Jarvik 2000, in December under medical emergency
conditions. They implanted a second in April, the first patient
getting the device as part of a clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   The DeBakey pump and Jarvik 2000 are both approved by the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration for study as a ``bridge to
transplant,'' or a way to buy time until a donor heart becomes
available. FDA rules require the patients to live in the hospital
until they receive heart transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Both pumps are less bulky than earlier generations of LVADs _
the DeBakey pump is one-tenth the size of older pumps. They are
small enough to fit in women and some children. Doctors hope the
smaller pumps will someday serve as a permanent alternative to
heart transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Anderson, president and chief executive officer of
Houston-based MicroMed Technology Inc., said conservative estimates
are that the pump should last ``at least five years and probably
longer.'' The ultimate cost will be ``significantly lower'' than
the current price tag of $60,000 for some LVADs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the pump's performance in Europe compares
``favorably'' to that of other LVADs. He declined to say how many
of the 32 patients have been transplanted with human hearts, or if
some have died, but said six current patients have been on the
pumps ``well over 100 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The MicroMed team hopes to expand to a multicenter trial and
implant a total of 70 patients. Noon is co-principal investigator
of the clinical trial with DeBakey, who is chairman of MicroMed's
medical advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey discovered the potential of LVADs when he implanted the
first one 34 years ago. The pump allowed the patient's heart, which
was in severe failure, to ``rest'' and recover. The patient was
weaned off the device, and resumed a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey calls the new device an ``auxiliary aorta.'' Unlike the
Jarvik 2000, which fits inside the left ventricle, the MicroMed
pump consists of a titanium inflow tube attached outside the left
ventricle.
</P>
<P>
   The tube bends beneath the heart, carrying oxygenated blood from
the left ventricle into the spinning blades of the tiny pump. The
pump pushes the blood through a flexible Dacron graft (invented
decades ago by DeBakey) sewn to the ascending aorta. From there,
the blood is sent into the rest of the body.
</P>
<P>
   The patient must carry two 12-volt batteries in a shoulder bag
that weighs 5 pounds, the size of a medium-sized women's purse.
When one battery reaches one-fourth of its power it beeps, alerting
the patient, and automatically switches over to the second battery.
The batteries can be recharged in 75 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; DeBakey, who has long pursued the creation of an artificial
heart, said he narrowed his focus to the left ventricle device
because it was less complicated, less expensive and had the
potential to help so many patients. He said five million Americans
suffer from some degree of heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   He recognized the pump's potential to restore health by giving
ailing hearts a chance to rest and recover. In addition, DeBakey
said, when a heart transplant is necessary, patients who have been
on the pump are healthier and stronger and more likely to have a
good outcome.
</P>
<P>
   (On the Web: www.methodisthealth.com/vad; www.micromedtech.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
