<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SNAPSHOTS-EXHIBITION-     06-08 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAPSHOTS-EXHIBITION-ART-1,240(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW:  PAST THEIR TARGETS, TO A WRY TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1, 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A woman smiles at the camera, one foot propped on the
running board of a car. A man with an uncanny resemblance to Marcel
Duchamp looks toward the camera, too, his head sticking out the car
window.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about a black-and-white snapshot, circa 1930s,
palm-size. Who are these people? They are nobody and everybody,
like the photographer. One of billions of amateur photographs,
source unknown, the picture is a talisman of evaporated memory that
over the years probably made its way from the corner drugstore to
the family album, where it was briefly cherished. Then, in the
extraordinary way these things happen, it traveled from attic to
Dumpster to flea market into the hands of some scavenging
dealer-collector, whereupon it became an item on the art market
until finally wending its way to its present location: the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't life amazing? You may now come upon the snapshot in a
deceptively modest, highly unusual (for this museum, anyway) and
sublimely endearing exhibition called ``Other Pictures: Vernacular
Photographs From the Thomas Walther Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair guess that the man, the woman and the photographer
(could they still be alive?) would be surprised to find their
memento in a museum. Whenever the picture was snapped, wherever
that was, the man and woman peering into the sun, the photographer
maybe fumbling with the shutter before saying ``Cheese!'' _ none of
them, presumably, had any inkling or even desire that this snapshot
would be art.
</P>
<P>
   But the art is there, plain as day. It is in the reflection of
the woman's body on the car door: by some act of divine comic
grace, the reflection happens to match up precisely with the head
of the man so that he looks like the woman's ghostly, dwarflike
double, a funny-surreal coincidence that, by adding a layer of
unanticipated meaning to the picture, suddenly elevates it from
nothing to something.
</P>
<P>
   Art works this way sometimes. It doesn't arrive through the
front door. It sneaks in the back, the more pleasing for being the
result of dumb luck. This picture would be less likable, I suspect,
if we learned that a professional had planned it. The amateur's
fluke reminds us of a basic good in life, and this is always
heartening; we are reminded that art is out there waiting to be
noticed, the only question being whether our eyes are open wide
enough to see it.
</P>
<P>
   We have had the impassivity of the camera to help us,
fortunately. During the days when box cameras had range-finders,
amateurs went around pointing more or less in the direction of what
they wanted to shoot and hoped for the best, resulting in all those
headless portraits and what Mia Fineman, the curator, in the
accompanying book calls ``successful failures, pictures that sail
past their intended targets and into the foggy ether of a different
kind of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. With luck, the amateur photographers captured what they
wanted, but they often got plenty of other stuff in the pictures,
too, cameras being indiscriminate machines. The amateur who pointed
at the building behind the wrought iron fence in one snapshot in
this exhibition found a giant apple blocking the view. Our
accidental Atget could thank serendipity and the camera's wide lens
for what turned out to be a far more intriguing photograph,
although he (or was it she?) deserves credit simply for preserving
the picture, an act of connoisseurship that has allowed it to come
down to us. It is among several dozen pictures in the exhibition, a
few in albums, all by anonymous amateurs, shot between the 1910s
and 1960s, the heyday of the black-and-white snapshot. They are a
catalog of aspiring masterpieces and glorious errors: blurs, lens
flares, double exposures, overexposures, intruding shadows,
touchingly awkward homespun pornography and amputated compositions.
(Another show to open next week at the excellent Ubu Gallery,
around the corner from the museum, will present several dozen more
gems, equally lovable.)
</P>
<P>
   You will recall that the early part of the century was when
Surrealism thrived, Surrealism having its roots in happenstance and
error. It was also the era of the New Vision photographers, whose
unconventional viewpoints, weird croppings, infatuation with
technology and tendency toward mysterious imagery are qualities
variously echoed in these vernacular pictures: a worm's-eye view of
a man tipping his hat brings to mind the work of Aleksandr
Rodchenko. A view straight down from atop the Eiffel Tower
duplicates almost exactly something Andre Kertesz once did. And a
photo-booth snapshot of a woman with her back turned to the camera
mimics the familiar 19th-century photograph of the woman seen from
the back by Onesipe Aguado, a modernist precursor.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Not really. Walther's taste for modernist
photography accounts partly for the heavy overlap of vernacular and
professional styles here. But there is also the fact that,
consciously or by osmosis, amateur photographers have always
absorbed the language of professionals, as professionals (Walker
Evans, Robert Frank, Harry Callahan, Lee Friedlander; the list goes
on) have tried to emulate the amateur's blithe innocence and
authentic, sometimes comedic charm. This has caused a two-way
traffic in the history of photography, which has only accelerated
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   You are free to ignore this fact at no particular cost to the
pleasure you receive, and also to ignore various links between
these amateur snapshots and current art. For the record, the links
include the rising tide of so-called outsider art, a catchall
phrase for whatever is dubbed art that happens not to be made by
people professionally trained, which includes children, animals,
the insane and by extension, one presumes, hobbyist photographers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the value placed by many young artists on found
objects, a modernist infatuation enjoying fresh respect. Finally,
private snapshots being diaristic, vernacular photographs dovetail
with a diaristic trend illustrated by the works of Nan Goldin,
Elizabeth Peyton and others.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this matters, ultimately. The pictures are actually
more appealing because of their distance from, not connection to,
professional art: blessedly unpretentious, the amateur photographer
expected little or nothing of the public, assuming at most an
audience of family and friends, thus leaving vast room for our
ignorant conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   And this, as the old saying goes, is the beauty part. Strangers
to the images, we are blissfully free to try to fill the space
between what we see and what we know, an anarchic, unbridgeable
gap. What is the meaning of the gesture of a woman in a
tight-fitting dress bent over a panting spaniel? One hand out,
index finger of the other hand pointed up, she is like a crooked
John the Baptist directing us heavenward, a divine puzzle,
decipherable only perhaps by dogs and the woman's descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Or what about the house being dragged on tethers through the
water? It floats as if in the middle of an ocean, an apparition,
inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the man dangling from a zeppelin. The
photograph is not a bad composition, formally speaking, two dark
bands sandwiching one white, with the figure of the man in the
center. He is a sailor; we know that much from the silhouette of
his pants and from the crowd of sailors below him. But is he on the
way up or down? And how did he get there in the first place?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the double exposure of a bedroom and a street,
simply amazing, a dreamlike miscue in which bed lamp becomes
streetlamp and streetlamps become bedposts and a streetcar chugs
past the foot of the bed, where a tiny woman stands alone in the
sunlight. Where did this incredible picture come from?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope we don't find out. Much of the appeal of the best
amateur snapshot is that, alienated from its source, it stays a
riddle, thereby exemplifying the bigger truth that photographs by
their nature never tell us as much as we expect they will.
</P>
<P>
   Private pictures like these disclose especially little except,
maybe, about ourselves: what used to have the narrowest meaning to
the person who snapped it (that's Uncle Bob ironing his pants;
that's Sylvia with the sprinkler on the lawn) becomes a Rorschach
of our imagination. Trying to decipher these tiny mysteries, we
progress from being voyeurs to excavators, combing our memories for
what we may recognize from our own family albums, from our own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   We look for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how artful the photographer,'' the critic Walter
Benjamin once wrote, ``no matter how carefully posed his subject,
the beholder feels an irresistible urge to search such a picture
for the tiny spark of contingency, of the here and now, with which
reality has (so to speak) seared the subject, to find the
inconspicuous spot where in the immediacy of that long-forgotten
moment the future nests so eloquently that we, looking back, may
rediscover it.''
</P>
<P>
   The redolent snapshot is one in a million. Just look at the
albums in the show, which consist of pages and pages of forgettable
photographs. Bear this in mind before devoting the weekend to
fishing through old shoe boxes, in wallets, behind the sun visor of
the car, wherever you keep your keepsakes.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who knows? The world, it turns out, is full of
amazing little surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Pictures: Vernacular Photographs From the Thomas Walther
Collection'' is at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue at
82nd St., (212) 535-7710, through Aug. 27. ``Snapshots: The
Extraordinary Ordinary,'' is at Ubu, 16 East 78th St., (212)
794-4444, from Thursday through July 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PROCTER-RESIGN-ART-10     06-08 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCTER-RESIGN-ART-1075(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
P&AMP;G CHIEF EXECUTIVE RESIGNS, AS COMPANY ANNOUNCES DISAPPOINTING
QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chief executive of Procter &AMP; Gamble, the consumer products
giant, resigned Thursday as the company announced it would suffer
another disappointing quarter and its stock price fell to less than
half of what it was worth just four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the move, P&AMP;G acknowledged that it had tried to remake
itself into a more aggressive company too rapidly and that its core
brands, which include Crest, Pringles and Tide, had suffered as it
focused on developing new products.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G's board immediately named Alan G. Lafley, a 23-year employee
of the company, to succeed Durk I. Jager, the hard-charging
executive who had vowed to shake up the company's staid culture and
force managers to act in a more entrepreneurial style. It also
called John E. Pepper, Jager's predecessor and longtime rival, out
of retirement to serve as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, it's clear we changed too much too fast,'' said
Lafley, 52, who was a president overseeing the company's
beauty-care products and its North American operations. The cost
has been steep: P&AMP;G has lost $75 billion in market value since
January.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many executives are saying they want their
corporations to act like small, entrepreneurial companies, largely
in response to the growth of Internet commerce, P&AMP;G's struggles
indicate just how difficult a successful transformation is.
</P>
<P>
   Under Jager, 57, the company tried to bolster a mediocre growth
rate by developing products more quickly, eschewing the
many-layered approval processes and market tests for which the
conservative company was famous. Jager also moved many managers to
new jobs to shake up a corporate culture in which employees are
called Proctoids because of their efficiency and obedience.
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives have led to some successful new products _ like
Swiffer, a floor-cleaning cloth _ but the price has been too high,
the company said Thursday. Costs have risen almost as fast as
sales, and the money P&AMP;G spent on its new initiatives left less to
spend on the marketing of its largest businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share for the company's fourth quarter, which ends
June 30, will be about the same as they were a year ago, rather
than 15 to 17 percent higher, as the company had estimated. For the
fiscal year, P&AMP;G is now likely to earn $4.23 billion before
one-time charges, up only slightly from its $4.15 billion profit
last year, according to Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of P&AMP;G fell $6.125, to $56.75.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, investors and reporters,
Lafley said he would spend the next six weeks studying P&AMP;G's
spending to decide which efforts should continue to receive their
current levels of investment. ``We will make tougher choices,''
said Lafley, who is known as A.G.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither he nor Pepper criticized Jager by name, they
bluntly repudiated the pace with which he had tried to change the
$38 billion company. The company moved executives between divisions
too rapidly, they said, and it adopted new financial measures that
turned out to be too optimistic. Speed, Lafley said, ``is not a
substitute for good business sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we thought would take about a year to complete is clearly
going to take at least a year longer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of P&AMP;G's most important brands have
underperformed products made by rival manufacturers like
Kimberly-Clark and PepsiCo's Frito-Lay. Crest, for example, has
lost market share to Colgate and Aquafresh as P&AMP;G managers have
been slow to respond to consumers' growing appetite for toothpastes
that promise to do more than simply clean teeth. In the 52 weeks
that ended April 23, Crest's sales grew by 1.3 percent while
overall toothpaste sales increased by more than 3 percent,
according to Information Resources, a Chicago company that tracks
supermarkets, drugstores and larger retailers like Wal-Mart Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Tide is underperforming its rivals in the liquid-detergent
aisle. The growth rate of Charmin toilet paper is trailing those of
Quilted Northern and Kleenex Cottonelle. Zest, Ivory and Oil of
Olay soaps have all lost market share over the last year. And
Pringles has fallen further behind Frito Lay's best-selling potato
chips, according to Information Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus all went to speeding new products to market,'' said
Timothy M. Ghriskey, a senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It was the earnings shortfall _ a result of slower-than-expected
sales _ that led to the resignation of Jager, a native of the
Netherlands who took over the chief executive's post 17 months ago.
Pepper, 61, who is more popular among employees but also considered
less aggressive, originally beat out Jager for the chairman's job
in 1995 only to cede it to him last year after a disappointing and
abbreviated term.
</P>
<P>
   In January, newspapers reported that Jager was considering
buying the drugmakers American Home Products and Warner-Lambert in
an effort to vastly enlarge P&AMP;G's small pharmaceutical division.
Investors thought the idea too ambitious and P&AMP;G stock fell more
than 10 percent, causing Jager to abandon his plan reluctantly.
Jager also made overtures to buy Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   In March, P&AMP;G warned that its third-quarter profits would be
smaller than expected, and shares fell another 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's news brought the shares down to their 1997 level, by
far the largest drop over the last two decades for the widely held
stock. The decline is likely to aggravate morale problems at the
company's Cincinnati headquarters because of the large portion of
employee retirement savings that the company puts into its own
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also offers the latest evidence of the
struggles that consumer-product companies are experiencing despite
the longest economic expansion in U.S. history. Companies like
Coca-Cola and Gillette have been able to push through only moderate
price increases, if any. Consumers have refused to pay more for
staple goods, and retailers, led by Wal-Mart, have gained more
power through their growing size. At the same time, economic
troubles in Asia and Latin America hurt sales in recent years, and
the current weakness of the euro has dampened profits in Europe.
The rise in oil and paper costs have not helped, either.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jager said in a statement that the decision to resign
was his, analysts said it was yet another example of the small
margin of error that chief executives have at a time when the
volatile stock market punishes companies that surprise it with bad
news.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During this year alone, the top executives at Coca-Cola, Mattel
and Xerox have left after presiding over disappointing results.
``The capital market is taking its vengeance on those who do not
get great numbers,'' said Michael Useem, a professor of management
at the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania. ``And
directors are much more inclined just to pull the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafley graduated from Hamilton College in Clinton, N.Y., and
Harvard Business School, and his only full time job outside of P&AMP;G
was in the Navy. He is personable and energetic, said Sally J.
Dessloch, a vice president at J.P. Morgan Securities, and has a
reputation for doing good job of motivating his employees. Other
analysts said his style was closer to Pepper's than Jager's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
