<HEADLINE>
NASA DESIGNS HUMAN-LIKE ROBOT FOR SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The prospect of robots with a distinctly human
appearance working side-by-side with astronauts in space is no
longer a figment of science fiction, experts at NASA's Johnson
Space Center said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of research, a group of space agency engineers
is weaving a collection of small electrical motors, television
cameras, sensors, computer chips, plastic, aluminum and cloth into
the head, right arm and hand of a mechanical man that could one day
lug a wrench on the international space station or examine a rock
on Mars for signs of fossilized life. The left arm and upper torso
should be assembled by mid-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of robotics, this is way ahead of anything that has
been flown in space,'' said Christopher Culbert, chief of the
robotic systems technology branch at JSC.
</P>
<P>
   The most advanced feature of the mechanical creature, which NASA
has christened Robonaut, is a five-fingered hand that can activate
a power drill, scoop sand, hold a kitten or carry a jug of milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the world's best robotic hand,'' beamed
Culbert. ``We are state of the art for this level of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of 10 mechanical, electrical and computer software
engineers embraced the $3 million project to see if it could build
a machine capable of lifting some of the spacewalk burden from the
crew of the international space station. Once the outpost has been
assembled, its seven residents will be responsible for hundreds of
hours of external maintenance annually.
</P>
<P>
   The team, led by NASA's Robert Ambrose, pursued a design that
resembled a large human so the robot could use the same tools and
equipment already developed for astronauts. The result is a machine
that resembles C3PO, the loquacious robot from the popular Star
Wars films, more than it does the chunky industrial robots that
populate terrestrial assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   However, it will take a descendant of Robonaut's to fulfill the
vision of the robot in modern science fiction cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Robonaut is more correctly categorized as a tele-robot, a
machine that moves and performs tasks in response to the commands
of a human operator.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's creation is operated by a human seated only a few feet
away and wearing a special helmet and gloves. The view from two
cameras mounted like eyes in Robonaut's head is transmitted to the
human operator's helmet. Each time the operator moves a finger or
flexes a hand, a command to do the same is sent to Robonaut.
</P>
<P>
   Experts are probably at least a decade away from developing a
robot that could actually turn a human directive like ``retrieve
the folder from the file cabinet'' into action, said NASA's Hal
Aldredge, who spearheaded software development for the robot.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the orbiting space station, Robonaut would be commanded
by an astronaut in the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   In order to lower the risk of a time-consuming spacewalk,
Robonaut would be sent out to remove cover plates and position work
tools before an astronaut dons a space suit and ventures out to
handle the more delicate tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy could cut by as much as 30 percent the length of
time an astronaut is exposed to the deadly vacuum and temperature
extremes of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dangerous environment,'' Aldredge noted. ``We'd
like to keep the astronaut who knows how to do all the high-level
tasks inside in a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, NASA considers the work to develop Robonaut strictly
research.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency would have to find funding to develop a
prototype robust enough for test flights on the space shuttle
before it could assign Robonaut a permanent home on the space
station or a seat on a spacecraft destined for a Mars landing.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, terrestrial interest may grow. Machines based
on NASA's latest in robotics could be used to disarm land mines,
clean up chemical spills or help respond to a crisis at a nuclear
power plant. The design of the hands has also started to pique the
interest of medical experts in prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
