<HEADLINE>
EDDIE IZZARD CIRCLES AND LANDS
</HEADLINE>
  OK, he doesn't really 
circle, but he meant to 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients on or after June 11,
2000) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere in the middle of your conversation with him, Eddie
Izzard interrupts to tell you that there was a direct flight
between Vietnam and Seattle during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's weird,'' the British comedian/actor ponders for a
second before he turns his attention back to you with, ``Sorry,
just a bit of information I thought I'd give you there.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if you don't know what to do with that tidbit, Izzard
just might. There seems to be no limit to what he's willing to put
in his act, and there seems to be no limit to what Izzard can make
funny.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, limits don't seem to exist much for Izzard, a
self-described universal citizen who has done his act in France _
in French; who once performed his act before 11,000 people
(including Prince Charles) _ a Guinness world record for standup
comedians; who has bared it all on the legitimate London stage; and
whoaspires to be a movie star. He starts a five-night, sold-out
stand at the Henry Fonda Theatre on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Izzard, as you may remember, made quite a splash during his
``Dressed to Kill'' tour, which came to America in 1998. It's hard
to imagine riffing on Stonehenge, the American Revolution, Hitler,
European unity, the Anglican Church and Scooby Doo and getting
laughs on all of them, but Izzard did. Not since Robin Williams
burst onto the scene in the late '70s has a comic demonstrated such
an agile mind, which may explain why the American comedian _ who is
a fan _ lent a hand in bringing that tour to the states.
</P>
<P>
   The show then became a cable special. One of the people who
brought that about was Carolyn Strauss, HBO's senior vice president
for original programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, he's really funny,'' she says flatly, describing
why she wanted Izzard's show. ``He has a fantastic sense of
synthesizing the past and the present and his sense of history is
so unusual _ unlike most of today's comedians _ that it becomes an
incredibly fun, fresh point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   But his comic originality was almost overshadowed by his attire,
which consisted of a Chinese jacket, black vinyl pants, frosted
hair and 4-inch heels.
</P>
<P>
   Izzard, as he says, is an ``executive transvestite,'' a bloke
who fancies girls but likes to have the same freedom they have in
dress. Back then he talked about how his role model growing up was
``The Avengers''' Emma Peel (Diana Rigg) in her sexy black outfit
and with her kung fu moves. But he doesn't want to go on about
that, ``otherwise you get the impression that this guy's just a
transvestite and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Izzard has returned to America in a new show called
``Circle.'' Asked what it's about, he offers this rather roundabout
description: ``Circles seem to rule the universe. Planets are
circular. Orbits are circular. Time, space is curved. Buddhist,
Native American religions are about going back to the Earth. The
big bang is exploding and coming back _ almost circular. I thought
I'd knit that into the fabric of the show so that it had circles
coming through as themes. And now I decided not to do that. So I
haven't actually put it in the show.''
</P>
<P>
   So the show's not about circles?
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is called `Circle,' '' he says, ``but it's more long
and stringy than a circle.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you talk about?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some stuff in there that's history but also science,
science fiction,'' he rattles off, ``some things about the monarchy
and the queen mother, Britain being terrible at the Olympics _ we
got no gold medals last time _ and stuff about Flipper.''
</P>
<P>
   The dolphin? ``Yeah, along with whales, seals and swans and ...
Pinochet.'' Aquatic animals and a Chilean dictator _ in Izzard's
world everything ties together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be predictable, although I probably am,''
Izzard almost apologizes. But anyone who's seen Izzard's act knows
that isn't his worry. While most other comedians are navel gazing,
Izzard is exploring a world that's growing more connected every day
and finding the universal joke along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy is human, not national,'' he says, pointing out that
people laugh at the same places in his show whether he's in
Iceland, Sydney or Seattle. ``In Britain, they said that France had
a visual sense of humor. And I thought, `It can't be like that.
They made that up. It can't be that all 80 million people just sit
there going, (in a mock French accent) `Ah, look the birds, they
are funny how they fly,' '' he says, adding, ``Germans got a sense
of humor as well, which is good to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chatting with Izzard, who is on the line from Seattle (now you
get the earlier reference), you can almost feel him working out the
rhythms of his act _ the Ping-Pong verbal volleys connecting him to
his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show's all written in a workshoppy kind of way, depending
on what the audience seems to like,'' says Izzard, who likes to
interact with the crowd. ``If I like it and the audience likes it,
I just keep it in and keep riffing on it.''
</P>
<P>
   And that works, he says, because he assumes the intelligence of
his audience.
</P>
<P>
   So does he pore over history books to get his ideas?
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch telly,'' he says. ``The standup is sort of like
surfing through all the channels at once... it sort of bleeds from
the Discovery Channel to the film channels, to sitcoms and CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took the 38-year-old comedian a while to synthesize his
stream-of-consciousness absurdist humor, he says, citing Monty
Python, the Goon Squad, Steve Martin and Ernie Kovacs as
inspirations. When he started, his material was too strictly
surreal for audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use to say stuff like, `I served in Vietnam. I was a
waiter,' And then I'd go into whole loads of stuff about preparing
foods in war zones. It was quite obviously a lie, but sometimes
audiences wouldn't come with it. They thought, `No you didn't. You
weren't in Vietnam.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Izzard took another tack. ``I found that if you start in real
and then you flip to surreal as you're walking down real you take
everyone with you and they don't even know they've gone there with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, his act just opened up. ``I found that no one was in
the history area,'' he says. ``So I thought, `I'm fascinated by
that,' and then I just thought, `Let's just go anywhere that I'm
fascinated by.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Circle,'' which has been critically acclaimed on its East Cost
stops, will be filmed later this month in New York City. Strauss,
who hasn't seen it yet, says HBO will consider picking it up.
</P>
<P>
   But after this tour standup may take a backseat in Izzard's
career. Last year he performed the title role in a revival of
Julian Barry's ``Lenny'' on the London stage, garnering favorable
reviews like ``deeply convincing,'' ``captivating.'' The Guardian
noted he was ``frequently naked... he performs Bruce's dialogue
with a drum _ in which drum-beats echo the rhythm of a sex chant _
with an inquisitive excitement that suggests his words are being
conjured up on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   If details can be worked out the show may land on Broadway, says
Izzard, who calls playing the irrepressible, foul-mouth American
comedian ``grueling, because you have to burn up at the end of
every performance.''
</P>
<P>
   So far his movie career has been mostly unremarkable, with minor
roles in a few films like ``The Avengers,'' ``Velvet Goldmine'' and
``Mystery Men.'' To change that, Izzard thinks he needs to commit
to movie roles as totally as he's committed to doing standup.
</P>
<P>
   If Izzard does conquer film, it will standup's loss, and then
you wonder: What will he do with that Vietnam-to-Seattle
reference? &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: Eddie Izzard in ``Circle.'' &QL; 
Where: Henry Fonda Theatre, 6126 Hollywood Blvd., Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesday through Saturday. &QL; 
Tickets: Sold out. A few tickets may be made available at the
theater on show day, or try brokers. &QL; 
Information: Henry Fonda Theatre (323-468-1770). Ticketmaster
(213-480-3232). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
