<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-WOMAN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN HELD IN KILLING OF POLICE CHIEF'S RELATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chief Bernard Parks of the Los Angeles police
announced Thursday the arrest of an 18-year-old man in the fatal
shooting of his granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that I would be talking about my granddaughter
in this fashion,' Parks said at a morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged city residents and officials to continue working
with the police to bring an end to the violence plaguing some
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we unite together as a department, city and community, we
can fight this violence,'' he said. ``Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Sharad Shabazz was arrested early Wednesday and charged
with killing Parks' 20-year-old granddaughter, Lori Gonzalez.
Shabazz had been picked up the day before in southwest Los Angeles
for drinking in public. Based on tips, a warrant had already been
issued for his arrest in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe that Gonzalez was the unintended
victim of gang-related violence. A 20-year-old passenger in her
car, identified as Ernest Thomas Gray, is said to have been the
target.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has been described as a gang member with a felony record.
He was apparently wounded about three weeks before the killing,
which took place about 10:15 p.m. on May 28 as he and Gonzalez were
leaving a Popeyes chicken restaurant. He ducked as a gunman
approached the car and shot. Gonzalez was struck several times.
</P>
<P>
   No weapon has been recovered, and police officials said they
were looking for additional suspects. But in announcing the arrest,
Detective Brian Carr said investigators were confident that they
had found the gunman based on evidence and witness identifications.
</P>
<P>
   Shabazz was charged with one count of street-gang murder, which
carries a possible death penalty or life without parole. A law
making gang-related killings a capital offense went into effect
earlier this year. The district attorney's office said it had not
yet decided how to proceed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Shabazz's public defender, arraignment was
pushed back to June 23. Asked in a court appearance whether he
supported the delay, Shabazz vehemently opposed the move.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred in the Jefferson Park neighborhood of
South-Central Los Angeles, where gang-related violence and drug
dealing have been persistent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez lived with her father in Mission Viejo, about 50 miles
south of downtown Los Angeles, and was a student at Saddleback
College there. She was in Los Angeles visiting her mother when she
was shot. She was described as a vibrant young woman who worked two
jobs and volunteered in her church.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-STYLE-ART-3T     06-08 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-STYLE-ART-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH: TELLING SIGNATURES ON DECISIONS AND LOGOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Special Report) 
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT12 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vice president just was not satisfied. A team
of graphic artists had labored to come up with a logo to emblazon
on Al Gore's campaign buttons, bumper stickers and placards, but he
felt they had failed to capture the right spirit. So he sketched an
alternative, a swoosh and a star _ a simple, futuristic look with
the words, ``Gore 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took several of the suggested designs and kind of recombined
them and added a different approach,'' Gore said. ``I sat down and
drew that on the table with the people who had made suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to Gov. George W. Bush to do that. When his
staff presented him with a proposal for a blocky, traditional logo
featuring an American flag and the words, ``George W. Bush For
President,'' his response was quick and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked at it and said, `It looks good,''' Bush
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like a small thing, but Gore's keen interest in the
signature of his campaign, and Bush's admitted lack of interest,
perfectly captures the stark differences in how they are running
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fingerprints are on every major move or pronouncement. He
prides himself on making decisions based on his judgment, built on
nearly 8 years in the White House and 16 years in Congress, and not
on the views of his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president immerses himself intimately in policy, and
often even in logistical matters. Recently, when he was in a rush
to travel from New York to Washington, Gore announced that he was
scuttling Air Force Two because he would make better time on the
U.S. Airways shuttle. His stunned military and Secret Service aides
knew not to try to talk him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, is far more removed from specifics. He
prefers to surround himself with people he trusts. Once he feels
comfortable that they understand his philosophy, he leaves them to
come up with proposals for him to sign off on. Notably, it was
Bush's aides, not the candidate, who plotted a course of action
when the campaign was in crisis after Bush lost the New Hampshire
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The unmistakable contrasts in how Bush and Gore make decisions,
handle pressure and relate to their advisers offer revealing
insights into how they would run their presidencies. In extensive
interviews, officials from both campaigns sought to play up
anecdotes that showed that their candidate would operate most
effectively in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's supporters say his impressive knowledge base allows him
to comfortably make informed decisions. Bush's backers argue that
his lower level of engagement is a virtue because the governor is
not burdened by needless detail.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is possible to move beyond the campaigns' spin to see
striking differences in the candidates' approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Gore bases his decisions on devouring information and reaching a
reasoned conclusion; Bush operates more on gut instinct. Gore often
lectures his advisers; Bush expects his to tell him what he needs
to know.
</P>
<P>
   Gore happily debates policy minutiae; Bush prefers to speed
through meetings to get to the heart of the matter. Gore is not
bashful about sitting at a laptop and rewriting speeches; Bush
prefers using a black Sharpie marker to delete sections or change a
word here or there.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's aides say he sometimes sees himself as the
smartest person in the room, and often he is right. Bush's aides
say he likes to joke to assembled advisers about holes in his
knowledge, which is a healthy sign, they say, of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore scours the newspapers and, often several times a day, will
cut out an obscure detail or paragraph and hand it to an aide with
instructions. He tries to read every word written about him. Bush's
aides said the governor read about himself from time to time, but
preferred to have his wife, Laura, or others sum up what was
written about him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Bush are the stereotypical empty suit
manipulated by handlers. If anything, both candidates tend to be
stubborn, often not yielding to their advisers' suggestions. Not
surprisingly, both are sensitive to caricatures: Gore as a control
freak drowning in specifics who discounts others' opinions or Bush
as a naive puppet.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting in an interview that his artistry on the logo was
``the exception rather than the rule,'' Gore said he tried ``to
avoid getting bogged down in details.'' He made clear that his
style was not like that of President Jimmy Carter, who obsessed
over the schedule at the White House tennis courts, or President
Calvin Coolidge, who endlessly scrutinized guest lists at White
House parties.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Gore asserted that his grasp of policy would be
invaluable in the White House. ``I like the broad brush strokes,''
he said. ``But sometimes a significant detail is actually a broad
brush stroke in disguise. Sometimes, a significant detail can be a
fulcrum around which the test of the issue turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made no excuses for his lapses in knowledge. ``I don't
think anybody knows everything about every subject, and anyone who
pretends they do is someone I don't want to be the president,
because this is a complicated world,'' he said in an interview.
``The key to the presidency is to set divisions, to lay out the
parameters by which decisions will be made and to encourage really
good, competent people to serve the country for the right reasons
and to build a team.''
</P>
<P>
   A Force Behind Decisions
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a figurehead here!'' the vice president snapped, after
a cluster of aides had failed to adequately brief him about an
event in New Hampshire in the primaries. ``I've got to know what's
going on in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, that was an understatement. The reality is that
Gore is the driving force behind virtually every big decision of
his campaign, and many small ones. His propensity to run things
himself has not scared off talented aides. But Gore often turns to
them more as resources to press forward with his own decisions
rather than as principal decision makers.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in late May of his closest advisers at his
residence at the Naval Observatory here, Gore offhandedly told them
he had settled on a new campaign strategy. He would halt the
relentless attacks on Bush that some Democrats feared were doing
Gore more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `That's what I'm going to do,''' recalled Carter
Eskew, one of Gore's top advisers. ``Then he laid out a series of
things, like family issues, that became the basis of the next two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers had felt it was important that Gore stay on the
offensive. But no one dared to challenge him. ``When you work with
somebody, you know when there's an opening _ and when there
isn't,'' Eskew said. ``He was emphatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides also winced when he told them he would propose a
sweeping reform of the campaign finance system. Many thought he
would be ridiculed because of the questions surrounding his own
fund-raising practices in 1996. Others worried that the issue was
not a big vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, they tried to distract Gore by saying other matters
needed attention first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd divert him into some other areas and he'd say, `What
about that speech?''' said Tony Coelho, the Gore campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Such delay tactics, Eskew conceded, were ``a way to try to kill
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore persisted. ``It did not give me pause,'' the vice
president said of the objections.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is similarly never hesitant about upending speeches or
events. Early last month, when he was traveling on Air Force Two
from Washington to Chicago, he abruptly discarded a health care
speech after reading a clipping from a morning newspaper saying
that the National Rifle Association was thrilled at the prospect of
a Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was traveling to a conference of health care
reporters, summoned aides to his cabin and announced that he would
talk about gun violence. The hook: that easy access to handguns is
a health care issue.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said they argued against it, but Gore did not budge.
After Air Force Two landed, Gore kept the motorcade waiting while
he worked the phones. He called one aide in Washington about
statistics he remembered that had been put out by the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her to quickly find out whether or not I was right in
remembering that the AMA had done a big statement or publication on
the handgun and the health care issue,'' Gore said, ``and find
relevant statistics on it. She found the statistics that I said I
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   He then instructed his staff to rewrite the speech.
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly an exception. After Gore's advisers drafted a
statement for him last December that castigated his own
administration's policy on gays in the military, the vice president
thought it was too weak. So he wrote a harder-edged statement
himself, over the objections of several advisers. ``We thought it
would kill him in the South,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Bush announced his plan to cut taxes by $483 billion
over five years, Gore told his aides, ``We need to respond
quickly.'' Riding in a sport utility vehicle headed to Ida, Iowa,
from Sioux City, he began calling experts like Lawrence H. Summers,
the Treasury secretary, and Gene Sperling, President Clinton's
national economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attacked the tax plan at an open meeting and then again at
a news conference, saying it would squander the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Gore plays scheduler. On the morning after the Iowa
caucuses, Gore and his aides were operating on virtually no sleep.
Finally, his entourage made it to a hotel in Nashua, N.H., for a
few hours' nap before the one scheduled event of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But just as two aides, Mike Feldman and Chris Lehane, were
falling asleep in their shared hotel room, Gore came banging on the
door. ``Go away,'' Lehane shouted, not realizing it was the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they opened the door and Gore, clad in a bathrobe with
his schedule in hand, demanded, ``This is all we're doing today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir,'' Feldman reminded him, ``there's six inches of snow on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no use. The aides, reluctantly, added an MTV event to the
schedule and a photo opportunity: they delivered coffee to the
local snow crews.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Because of his deep involvement in decisions, Gore cannot blame
his advisers for ones that go awry, such as how distanced himself
from President Clinton on Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we dragged him kicking and screaming,'' said
one of his top advisers.
</P>
<P>
   A Corporate Executive's Touch
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not inclined to drastically alter a speech or a schedule
on the fly. He behaves more like a corporate executive. His aides
welcome the comparison to President Ronald Reagan, who did not
dither with details and set out broad goals, despite being
ridiculed as out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the most turbulent moment of Bush's campaign, after his
humiliating loss to Sen. John McCain in the New Hampshire primary,
the governor stuck to his policy.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bush made clear to his aides that he was distressed with
the state of the campaign, telling them that it had to be more
aggressive and not watch idly as McCain convinced voters that he
was the only reformer in the race. Then, rather than dictate
remedies, Bush dispatched his aides to come up with suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He laid out the principles of what he thought went right and
wrong in New Hampshire,'' said Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist.
``Then we came up with options that were presented to him formally
and informally over a couple days. He accepted them and rejected a
few.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from what Gore did last September, when former
Sen. Bill Bradley began surging in polls. Without consulting his
aides, Gore uprooted his listless operation in Washington and moved
it to Nashville. ``I announced we were going to do it,'' he
recalled, ``and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides could not cite a time when the governor, responding
to Gore or a news development, ripped up a speech and turned a
day's schedule on its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to control our own agenda,'' said Karen P. Hughes,
Bush's communications director and one of his closest aides. ``That
doesn't mean that he's inflexible. When Cardinal O'Connor passed
away, the governor wanted to attend the funeral. That's an example
of something that changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the decision to attend the funeral of Cardinal John
O'Connor of New York came at the suggestion of an aide, not Bush.
``I don't think it initially came from him,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair, though, to portray Bush as passive. He does
not hesitate to overrule his advisers, and when he does he is often
guided more by instinct than policy.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing a speech he was due to deliver on Social
Security before a group of newspaper publishers in May, Hughes
said, Bush was puzzled by the content because he was scheduled to
deliver a Social Security address the following week. She recalled:
``He turned around and looked at me: `Why are we talking about just
Social Security? Why aren't we talking about the importance of
reforming education and rebuilding the military?''' The speech was
retooled.
</P>
<P>
   Before the South Carolina primary, Bush's advertising team had
produced a 60-second commercial that opened with black-and-white
shots of lobbyists in cigars in a smoke-filled room. The intent was
to portray McCain as in the pocket of lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush rejected the commercial as too harsh. Mark McKinnon,
Bush's media consultant, said: ``He was very affirmative about it:
`This isn't going out under my name.' It was not a debatable
point.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said he argued that because of time pressure it was not
advisable to change the spot. ``Listen, this was in the pressure
cooker of South Carolina and minutes mattered,'' he said. The
governor prevailed and the shots of the lobbyists were pulled.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And the night Bush defeated McCain in the Virginia primary, his
aides had prepared a blistering victory speech. But in his heavy
black marker, Bush deleted several pages of the most negative
sections. For example, he kept the sentence, ``On the next step of
welfare reform, he has no plan.'' But he crossed out the next
sentence: ``His policy agenda is narrow and shallow, and it makes
no place for the poor and the forgotten and the frail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling was we needed to keep the pressure on Senator
McCain,'' Hughes said. ``I told him there was a lot of frustration
at headquarters.'' She said Bush telephoned several aides to
explain that he did not want to undermine them, but felt the speech
was too strident.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Candidates of Divergent Styles
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore fume when staff members arrive late for meetings.
They have little tolerance for aides who are not prepared. Yet
their styles are quite different. Gore is more like a sometimes
overbearing teacher, while Bush often plays the impatient student.
</P>
<P>
   The governor prefers oral presentations to leafing through
briefing books. ``I've seen the governor say, `Why don't you close
the book and tell me what you think is most important?''' Hughes
said. ``He gets to the heart of the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald L. Evans, the campaign chairman and Bush's best friend,
put it this way, ``His classic question is, `Have you told me
everything I need to know?'''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's biggest pet peeve at meetings is when aides leave
their cell phone or pagers on, he is also known for not abiding
long-winded presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't sit there and let a briefing go on that isn't a
good use of his time,'' said Josh Bolten, his domestic policy
adviser. ``You get maybe 60 seconds in. If there's a really good
briefer who's doing a good job, you might get three or four minutes
before he's interrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not bashful about pleading ignorance, and will even joke
about how he failed a reporter's pop quiz on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't know, he'll say, `Hold it,''' Bolten said. ``If
somebody uses an acronym he doesn't know, he'll stop them and say,
`What does that mean?' Sometimes he says, `Use plain English.' He's
not afraid to say when he doesn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining Bush's aversion to too much detail about the
campaign's finances, Evans said: ``We talk about the budget a fair
amount. All he wants to know is, `Are we under or over?'''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has no use for flip charts, aides said, Gore often
draws charts on an easel. ``Some days I think he is a professor,''
said Donna Brazile, the campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore acknowledged that his grasp of issues, and his
certainty about how to proceed, can be intimidating. ``I think
sometimes a young staffer or a new staffer who hasn't gone through
the process before may feel sometimes a little hesitant to speak up
in disagreement,'' he said. ``But it doesn't last long because I
try to encourage it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some who know Gore worry that his vast knowledge can
sometimes lead him to foreclose other points of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore comes off to me as a guy who has absolute confidence in
what should be done and really isn't all that interested in what
you think substantively,'' said Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., a
Delaware Democrat who supported Gore in the primaries. ``Al is
interested in getting briefed, forming an opinion and then it's
settled. That reflects a political certitude: a guy who will make
decisions a la Harry Truman and go home and go to sleep. Except
Truman operated on a gut assessment based on a historical context.
Al operates on an intellectual assessment that doesn't accommodate
much input.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also compared his style to Harry Truman's. But he said that
was a positive attribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Harry Truman's philosophy,'' he said. ``The
essence of it was: `Go ahead and make good decisions and then move
on to the next decision.' Right. You live with the consequences and
you get better as you go along.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The operating approaches of Gore and Bush not only reflect their
experiences but also their personalities and interests. Gore had a
deep interest in his campaign's logo _ as well as in helping dream
up a logo for the Democratic National Convention _ because he has
dabbled himself in painting and thinks political branding is
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that logos and other visual symbols that are
seen over and over and over again actually are pretty important,''
Gore said. ``And if you get one that really hangs together well,
it's much better than having one that's kind of mediocre.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush does not share that passion. In fact, asked about his
logo, he replied, ``You mean what's on the bumper sticker and
stuff?'' Saying that such artistic endeavors would waste his time,
he added, ``There are people smarter than me on designing logos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
