<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      06-08 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE NOW IS A FAST-FORWARD BLUR TO AMERICA'S MOST FREQUENT FLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE _ The door to President Clinton's suite was
closed for much of the trip, meaning, ``Do Not Disturb.'' The
lights were out in the Secret Service cabin. In the back of the
plane, the journalists had their mouths open but only heavy
breathing was coming out.
</P>
<P>
   During occasional moments of consciousness, more than one
passenger aboard the presidential aircraft blamed Vice President Al
Gore for their out-of-whack body clocks.
</P>
<P>
   In other times, it might have been Air Force Two streaking back
and forth across the Pacific like a commuter shuttle for the
funeral of a fallen prime minister. Memorial services have long
been part of the unwritten portfolio of the vice president, and
this one, in the opinion of some White House aides, had Gore's name
written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Jet-Lagged Presidential Mourner
</P>
<P>
   Eleven thousand people crowded into a Tokyo sports arena
Thursday to pay respects to Keizo Obuchi, the prime minister of
Japan who died a month ago. Vietnam sent its deputy prime minister
to the memorial service honoring Obuchi, who had been in the job
two years before being replaced by Yoshiro Mori in April after
suffering a stroke. Macao flew its secretary for social affairs and
culture for the ceremony. Sri Lanka was represented by Dhamasiri
Senanayake, the minister for tourism and civil aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting among them, in a dark suit with a solemn expression on
his face, was a seriously jet-lagged Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides had not been unanimous about making the trip.
There were suggestions to send Secretary of State Madeline
Albright. Gore was out of contention because of his campaign
schedule. But Clinton had overruled the naysayers. He had wanted to
remember Obuchi, who had visited the White House in May 1999, in a
personal way. Samuel Berger, the president's national security
advisor, had backed him.
</P>
<P>
   Berger made the case that the event was important to the
Japanese, and that they would remember a presidential snub long
into the next administration. And other world leaders were
attending: the prime ministers of Australia, Thailand and Malaysia,
for instance, and the presidents of South Korea, the Philippines
and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Clinton is planning a state visit to Japan next
month, and even though he just returned from a trip to Portugal,
Germany, Russia and Ukraine, and even though Japan is 13 hours away
by plane, he sandwiched a trip to Tokyo into his week.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy. He returned from Kiev on Monday night. He met
with King Abdullah of Jordan at the White House Tuesday. President
Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico was arriving for lunch on Friday. Clinton
is off on Saturday for a commencement address in Minnesota. That
left an opening, with just barely enough time to get to Tokyo,
shake some hands, gulp down a spicy tuna roll and climb back aboard
Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton does not have to worry about enough leg room
when he travels. His plane, a modified Boeing 747-200, has the
space of a medium-sized home (about 4,000 square feet), and he has
free run of the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, however, he roamed less than he usually does.
Except for an intense card-playing session with the Air Force
flight attendants in the galley, and another session with aides on
the return trip in the conference room, Clinton spent the bulk of
the trip retired to his room, where aides know not to roust him.
</P>
<P>
   Just a Sentimental Journey?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton broke no records Thursday with his attempt at jet-lag
diplomacy. Back in 1994, he had traveled to Budapest and back in 24
hours, spending just seven hours on the ground. Before him,
President Bush had jetted to and from Cartagena, Columbia, in the
same day. And President Carter had flown to and from Tokyo for a
meeting that was shorter than Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton looked as fresh as can be aside the other dark-suited
leaders at the memorial service, thanks to a steward that keeps his
clothes unwrinkled and an on-board shower. But all the hours in the
air seemed to slow him.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral, a tentative Clinton rose when his name was
called and placed a bouquet of white chrysanthemums at the base of
a large altar that held Obuchi's urn. Clinton bowed twice in the
direction of an large photograph of Obuchi, just as all the other
leaders did. But he and his other sleep-deprived aides awkwardly
traversed the stage, jumping out of each other's way and
momentarily blocking the arriving delegation from the Republic of
Palau.
</P>
<P>
   During his half-day in Japan, Clinton did sit down with Mori for
a short conversation in the morning. President Kim Dae Jung of
South Korea, who is preparing to meet with his North Korean
counterpart for a summit meeting next week, briefed Clinton in the
afternoon. But aides said again and again that this trip was not
about pressing foreign policy interests, and they offered the
brutal schedule as exhibit A of the affection Clinton had for
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole trip, door to door, is about 36 hours,'' said a
senior administration official, overestimating the length of the
trip by a couple of hours. ``That highlights what the president is
willing to do in order to personally be there for this
commemorative event.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
