<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-SURVIVOR-NYT &LR;      06-08 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' TROUNCES `MILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Establishing its credentials as the runaway television hit of
the summer, the CBS show ``Survivor,'' which chronicles the
adventures of 16 real people co-existing on an island off Borneo,
scored extraordinary ratings for the second straight week, this
time even drubbing ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' in
every audience category.
</P>
<P>
   More than 18 million people watched the show Wednesday night,
about 2.5 million more than watched the show's first edition last
week. That time ``Millionaire,'' which ABC had scheduled in an
effort to try to keep ``Survivor'' from taking off, still had more
total viewers. But as ``Survivor'' added viewers this week,
``Millionaire'' lost them. It was down about 1.2 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Survivor'' is almost certain to stoke the
market for similar reality-based programs, most of which were
created by European broadcast companies and which have now been
offered for sale to American networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is set up as a competition in survival skills
between two groups on the island. The emotional core of the show,
and apparently the most important attraction for the audience,
comes in its final moments each week when one group must vote one
of its members either the least helpful or simply the least
well-liked, or least valuable, off the island.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid emergence of ``Survivor'' as a hit raises the
possibility that CBS might be able to duplicate ABC's feat last
summer when one big hit show totally turned around the network.
Before ``Millionaire'' became a weekly series, ABC was languishing
in third place; it ended the season in first place almost solely on
the strength of ``Millionaire.'' As a result, ABC was able to sell
advertising in its upcoming fall shows for more money than any
other network got.
</P>
<P>
   The extra advantage for CBS is the appeal of ``Survivor'' to
young viewers, who are always considered more valuable by
television advertisers. CBS has been handicapped for years by the
fact that its shows are mainly watched by viewers over 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has clearly begun to emerge as part of the wider
culture, with news and discussion about the show widespread on
television and radio talk shows and coverage increasing in
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The show has provided prime comedy material for both David
Letterman and Jay Leno on their late night shows. Letterman did a
top 10 list on ``Top 10 Things That'll Get You Thrown Off the
Survivor Island,'' including ``No. 10 _ Shrieking, `This was a
mistake, we're all gonna die here!' an hour into Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, USA Today carried the results of the second
``Survivor'' episode as though it were a sports event, reporting
which participant was voted off the island by the other cast
members (it was B.B. Andersen, a 60-year-old retired contractor
from Kansas). The newspaper also conducted a poll of readers to
determine whom they would have picked to evict (26 percent chose
Susan Hawk, a truck driver from Wisconsin).
</P>
<P>
   Andersen became an instant interview subject for numerous media
outlets. Besides the CBS ``Early Show,'' which will have each
rejected cast member on the air every Thursday morning, Andersen
appeared Thursday on Fox News Channel, MSNBC, CNN, ``Entertainment
Tonight,'' ``Access Hollywood'' and the E Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising defeat of ``Millionaire,'' the show that
dominated the recently ended television season, may represent a
potential threat for ABC and its corporate owner, the Walt Disney
Co., whose financial picture greatly benefited from the program.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Braun, co-chairman of ABC Entertainment, said Thursday:
``None of us believe that `Millionaire' is at any risk, in the fall
or during the ratings sweep months when we'll have special events
built around `Millionaire.' We've certainly lost no faith at all in
the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun said ABC was simply acknowledging that CBS will probably
be able to achieve this summer what ABC did last summer, a near
monopoly on media attention for their television show. But he said:
``We've had nights before where appointment shows have done well
against `Millionaire.' We certainly don't expect `Millionaire' to
beat everything every night it's on.''
</P>
<P>
   Among viewers between the ages of 18 and 49, ``Survivor'' had a
7.5 rating. ``Millionaire'' had a 4.7. Among the younger group of
adults between the ages of 18 and 34, ``Survivor'' had a 7.6.
``Millionaire'' had a 3.6. (Each rating point represents just over
one million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Mergerson, 24, a music store clerk at a record store
in Emerald City, Wash., said: ``It is certainly not a first of its
kind, but it feels like another, much more realistic twist on the
idea of a reality adventure. It also plays to very basic human
instincts of self preservation, which in itself is alluring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
