</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-DEATHS-ART-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.7 MILLION PEOPLE KILLED BY WAR IN EASTERN CONGO, REFUGEE AGENCY
REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Two years of war have caused the deaths of more
than 1.7 million people in eastern Congo, where people who manage
to flee the fighting often die of hunger and malaria while hiding
in impenetrable forests, a leading refugee agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The figure represents about triple the expected number of deaths
for the area from August 1998 through last month, according to the
study conducted for the International Rescue Committee in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although the normal death toll in the five-province area of 18
million people would be 600,000, the actual number who perished was
2.3 million. Of the 1.7 million additional deaths reported in the
survey, 200,000 were caused by acts of violence, whereas the rest
were attributed to the war-related collapse of health services and
food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men with guns come and wreak havoc on a very regular basis,''
said Les Roberts, an epidemiologist at Johns Hopkins University who
supervised the study. ``Those men cause more death by making people
flee their homes than actually by shooting or slitting throats.
</P>
<P>
   ``People flee into the forest when a village is attacked, often
at night. If they get a little sick and they are not eating, they
often die. One girl told us how she fled her village at night with
her family of eight. Five of the eight died as they hid in the
forest.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in April and May, with random samplings
of houses in and around Moba, in Katanga Province; Kabare, Katana
and Kolonge in South Kivu; and Kisangani in Orientale Province.
Researchers asked residents questions like how many people were in
the family, whether anyone had died since last Christmas _ a major
holiday among the many Roman Catholics in the region _ and how many
died last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta, where Roberts formerly worked, provided baseline
statistics for sub-Sahara Africa. The results from the region, with
a population of 1.2 million, were extrapolated to the interior
regions and neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done what scientists hate to do, extrapolate from 1.2
million people to 18 million people,'' Roberts said. ``But we have
very consistently made conservative assumptions. I think we have
protected ourselves from the criticisms that we are being
extremists or hyperbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finished his survey, Roberts asked the U.N. relief
assistance coordinator for the area and a representative of the U.
S. Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance in the region to look over
his conclusions. They thought he may have been conservative, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he and his team found abandoned health clinics, local
economies in tatters and families struggling without the
subsistence agriculture or barter systems that had sustained them
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Children under five, the survey found, account for more than
one-third of the excess deaths in eastern Congo, an area disrupted
since 1994 by waves of ethnic and civil wars, sometimes
indistinguishable from an armed scramble for gold and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda sent troops into Congo, the former Zaire, in
August 1998 in support of rebels opposed to the government of
President Laurent Kabila. Last summer Rwandan and Ugandan troops
turned on each other, and they have been fighting each other this
week around the diamond center of Kisangani, adding at least 50
more civilian deaths to the toll.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan spoke Thursday with President
Paul Kagame of Rwanda and President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and
was assured that a cease-fire, not the first in recent weeks, went
into effect Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, Ugandan and Rwandan troops were fighting in
Kisangani, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-David Levitte, the French ambassador to the United Nations
and this month's Security Council president, said Thursday that the
council's members ``deplore the loss of life and the damage
inflicted by the forces of Uganda and Rwanda on the Congolese
population.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the International Rescue Committee report, Kisangani had been
found to be one of the brighter spots in a very bleak picture of
life in one of Africa's potentially richest countries. The United
Nations had hoped to make the city a neutral site where a large
contingent of peacekeeping troops could be based and political
negotiations begun to end the Congo war.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that eastern Congo has become ``an unchecked
incubation zone for disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that malaria and diarrheal diseases, including
cholera, appeared to be the leading causes of death, although
meningitis and suspected cases of polio were also found.
</P>
<P>
   Because blood transfusions are often needed for malaria victims,
he said, ``my strong gut feeling is that the prevalence of HIV has
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS and other deadly viruses are known to have flourished in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congo has something like the 14th-highest death rate on the
planet,'' he said. Most of the other 13 countries are in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no blood tested in this region since 1998,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
