s f BC-FIVE-QUESTIONS-BACHEL     06-08 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIVE-QUESTIONS-BACHELDER-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH E. BACHELDER III, AN ENGINEER OF THE EXECUTIVE PAY EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 11)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As shareholders gather for annual meetings, many are finding in
their proxy statements further evidence that executive pay
continues to soar. Even severance packages for top executives can
mount into the millions, or tens of millions. As a leading
executive compensation negotiator, Joseph E. Bachelder III, head of
a Manhattan law firm that bears his name, may deserve a share of
the credit, or the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Bachelder has negotiated employment contracts for Louis V.
Gerstner Jr. at RJR Nabisco and IBM; Lawrence A. Bossidy, the
former chairman at AlliedSignal; and George M.C. Fisher, chairman
of Eastman Kodak. He has also negotiated the severance package for
David Coulter, who left as president of BankAmerica in 1998. For
James Dimon, he negotiated both his severance from Citigroup and
his pay as chief executive of Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   Bachelder agreed recently to discuss whether he was doing too
good a job. Following are excerpts from the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   _STEWART KAMPEL
</P>
<P>
   Q. What justifies these enormous pay packages?
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, they haven't gone up so dramatically. Over the last
50 years, the salary packages of CEO's have grown at a rate of
about 2 percent over the Consumer Price Index, and in the 1950s and
'60s the growth was actually lower than workers' pay rises.
</P>
<P>
   Bonuses, however, are up dramatically. And so are stock options,
as part of pay packages. Over all, major U.S. corporations are
doing very well. Equity has gone up over 10 times since the '80s
and '90s, largely because of the dramatic growth in the markets.
And shareholders have benefited greatly. That's wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy has been growing, and the CEO's are the chief
custodians for extraordinarily growing basic assets. This has been
an extraordinary period, but it was just like at the turn of the
last century. Just look at all those big houses in Newport.
</P>
<P>
   What has also fueled the rise is momentum. There is a very
competitive market for top executives. Executive search firms
hardly existed years ago. Now they're so big that some have even
gone public. That created a dynamic that didn't exist. So the
corporation reflects the general prosperity of many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If the value of a company's stock drops, should executives
with large contracts give something back?
</P>
<P>
   A. What is compensation? It's pay for services over the long
term and the short term. If I worked for 10 years and the company
had 2 bad years, how should we look at it? The CEO was responsible
for the enormous wealth and growth of the company as well as the
opportunity everyone had to ride with its good fortune. Except for
a Michael Jordan, who never had one, CEO's can have a bad year.
They do get fired. Some may ``retire'' at a young age, but a
significant number are really being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many chief executives are getting lavish perquisites like the
personal use of company planes, country club memberships, a car and
driver and services like secretarial help even after they leave or
retire. Are you doing your job too well?
</P>
<P>
   A. I would attribute these unusual perks to unusual
circumstances. First, extraordinary CEO's win special arrangements.
Second, precedent is very important. Then those precedents become
the standard. Say Charlie Snoggs wants the same perks as Jack
Welch. So he becomes a competitor. He's competing for profits. And
he wants a competitive salary, pension and bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your experience is mostly with old-economy companies. What
should an executive of one of these businesses focus on: wages,
perks or stock options? And what should an executive look for in a
new-economy firm?
</P>
<P>
   A. For an old-economy firm, pensions are very important. CEO's
move so frequently today that they don't build up pensions. So it's
important to have the company ensure your pension. And it's vital
to have it funded.
</P>
<P>
   At new-economy companies, one strategy is to purchase stock with
a promissory note, which qualifies for long-term capital gains, and
then have the note forgiven. Stock options will allow you to buy
when the company is private and to cash in when it goes public.
</P>
<P>
   Q. More generally, how can an executive get the best deal?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't exaggerate or misrepresent your salary. You'll be found
out. If you're going to work for a new company, look at their proxy
statements, see what they are paying their top people. Examine the
form and nature of payment. Try to get credit for your service at
your present company.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if there is a change in control of the company? Be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   Check the proxy statement to see the range of bonuses that
senior executives can expect. And don't quit Co. A till you get
what you what you want at Co. B _ in writing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
