<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-LAST-DAY-$ADV11-NYT &LR;      06-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAST-DAY-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY MONEY, MY LIFE COLUMN: THE OTHER RETIREMENT PLANNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 11) 
 By JUDITH L. STEININGER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one warned me about the actual day when I would retire. Sure,
I had read a surfeit of information about retirement, but it
focused only on financial planning and activity planning _ things
like travel, golf, volunteer work, and how not to get into your
spouse's space. None of it talked about how to get through that
final day at a job you had loved for decades.
</P>
<P>
   I had been a college professor for 30 years, the last 23 at an
engineering college. (Before teaching, I worked as a research
chemist and as a Peace Corps volunteer in Kenya.)
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when I decided to retire, I thought I had plenty
of time to prepare. I submitted my resignation letter in the fall
for the following spring. During that time, I continued to teach,
do research and grade papers; in fact, I never discussed my
retirement plans with my students. Of course, I started to feel a
little squeamish when candidates for my position, not to mention my
old office, started to appear. But I even grew accustomed to that.
</P>
<P>
   Then the calendar caught up.
</P>
<P>
   The night before my last day, I slept uneasily. As I drove to
work the next morning, the rest of the world seemed silent. The car
was on auto pilot, having made the trip so many times before. But
my mind started whispering things like ``this is the last time you
will drive into your parking space'' and ``this is the last time
you will walk up these stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived at school, I saw all the usual sights. Some
students were kibitzing in the hall; others were cramming for
quizzes. A kissing couple was scrunched into a corner. Because it
was 10 minutes before the hour, people were pouring into hallways
and onto staircases.
</P>
<P>
   On any other day, I would have enjoyed making my way through
such a crowd. But on this day I felt like a wide receiver in a
slow-motion football play, hunching my shoulders against the rush
of people, caroming off walls and, finally, banging into the frame
of my office door. I lunged through the opening as though it were
the goal post and my book bag the protected football.
</P>
<P>
   I had but one class to teach that day _ contemporary literature.
It was my favorite. I left my office early for the walk to the
classroom building, not wanting to run into another crowd.
Unfortunately, when I got to the room, I found myself among
students who were also early.
</P>
<P>
   On any other day, I would have relished these encounters: the
teasing about homework and papers, the questions you wish they
would ask in class, the hesitant comments about personal lives _
all the seemingly small talk that makes teaching a wonderful
vocation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as I started to teach, I found myself avoiding eye contact
with my students. How unusual that was: for so many years, I always
looked into their eyes, wishing to engage the bored, searching for
the lights I hoped would go on as I made a brilliant point _ or for
the wrinkled brow indicating my point was not so brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted that hour to last forever; it didn't. I could not tell
them that this was my last class. The final minute ticked; I bolted
for the door.
</P>
<P>
   As I left, I felt the travertine floors of the hallway turn into
something akin to sponge. My knees could find no steady place. The
institutional beige paint in the hallways seemed to slide off the
walls. The air was hard to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   One thought assaulted me: This must be what it is like to die;
my life here is ending, and the world is continuing as if nothing
has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there are people for whom the last day at work is one
big Mardi Gras. But I loved teaching, so for me it was the Last
Supper. I suspect that a lot of folks feel as I did.
</P>
<P>
   To the pages being written about retirement, I add this one: To
grieve about leaving something you love is permissible, even good.
And I offer this advice to the colleagues of the soon-to-be
retired: On their last day, thank them for their professional
contributions and tell them they will be missed.
</P>
<P>
   My life, by the way, did not remain in that miasma. I now teach
a couple of seminar courses at the college, and I love it. I also
write for a newspaper and a magazine. The freedom and flexibility
of my new schedule are invigorating. I travel, serve on boards and
play a lot of golf. Life is good, something I would not have
believed possible on that last day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
