<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SEC-KRAMER0609-COX     06-08 1831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-KRAMER0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All the right calls
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Roy Kramer often is described as the most
hands-on commissioner in the history of the Southeastern
Conference. A year ago, the kitchen staff at the Sandestin Hilton
found out why.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC awards dinner, held annually at this beach resort, runs
strictly on Kramer Time. The appetizer is served at 7 p.m. and the
last speech, which is his, is over at 9. Two hours and out the
door. No excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's dinner fell behind schedule because the entrees were
slow getting to the tables. Rather than complain to the head
waiter, Kramer, a 70-year-old grandfather of six, put down his
napkin and marched into the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say he got them fired up,'' said Mark Womack, the
SEC's executive associate commissioner and Kramer's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly motivated, the kitchen staff picked up the pace, and
Kramer Time was restored.
</P>
<P>
   Others also have experienced the joy of Kramer's highly defined
sense of order.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Jo, Kramer's wife of 48 years, remembers a night that was
just supposed to be a quiet dinner for two. Kramer spent a good
part of the evening helping the restaurant manager better organize
his salad bar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the first year the SEC Basketball Tournament was held
in the Georgia Dome, Kramer wondered about the sight lines from the
upper deck. Rather than send one of his younger staff members,
Kramer climbed to the highest point of the Georgia Dome and checked
it out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just never believed that you sit around when something's
wrong and ask somebody else to fix it,'' Kramer said. ``If there's
a problem, you jump in and solve it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it has been since Jan. 10, 1990, when Kramer left his job
as Vanderbilt's athletics director to become the SEC's sixth
commissioner. Kramer has overseen the most dynamic period, both
competitively and financially, since the conference was founded in
1933.
</P>
<P>
   In the 57 years before Kramer's arrival, SEC teams won 47
national championships, including 16 in football or men's
basketball. Since 1990, the SEC has won 73 national titles in 20
sports.
</P>
<P>
   In Kramer's first year as commissioner, the 10 SEC schools
shared $16.3 million in revenue from televised football and
basketball. Last week, when the checks were handed out, the 12
schools shared $73.2 million. In Kramer's 10 years as commissioner,
SEC schools have divvied up more than $470 million.
</P>
<P>
   Financial success _ and the willingness to share revenue _ is
what keeps the SEC so competitively balanced in all sports. Kramer
has been the driving force behind both, conference members say.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a campus in a smaller market like ours, it is essential,''
said Larry Templeton, the athletics director at Mississippi State.
``We don't fund as many sports (11 women's, 9 men's) as other
conferences, but those we do have are funded to be nationally
competitive. For that, you have to give a lot of credit to the
commissioner's leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say that he was the right commissioner at exactly the
right time for the SEC,'' said Vince Dooley, the Georgia athletics
director.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD SENSE OF TIMING
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's sense of timing has served him well throughout his
career. After winning three state championships as a high school
coach in Michigan, he coached 11 at Central Michigan (1967-77),
winning 71.8 percent of his games and the 1974 Division II national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   He still considers himself a football coach, but in 1978, at the
age of 48, Kramer walked away from the profession to become the
athletics director at Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain other than to say that it was just
time,'' Kramer said. ``But my friends will tell you that I still
miss those 2 1/2 hours a day on the practice field.''
</P>
<P>
   The native of Maryville, Tenn., would have been happy at
Vanderbilt for the rest of his career. But late in 1989, when
Harvey Schiller resigned as the SEC Commissioner, Kramer knew it
was time to make another move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him a long time and my sense was this was a job he
really wanted,'' Womack said. ``He knew he could really make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer wasted no time. Less than five months after he took the
job, the SEC's presidents authorized Kramer to explore expansion.
In August 1990, Arkansas agreed to leave the Southwest Conference
and join the SEC. A month later, South Carolina became the 12th
member.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the year, the SEC announced that it would split into
divisions and play the first conference championship game in 1992.
Other conferences scoffed at the idea; then they copied it. Last
year's SEC championship game, the eighth, generated more than $7
million for the conference members.
</P>
<P>
   `PUTS THE CONFERENCE FIRST'
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes him so effective is that with the commissioner,
there is never any doubt that he is putting the good of the
conference first,'' said Jeremy Foley, the Florida athletics
director. ``You may disagree with his decisions, but you can't
disagree with his intent.''
</P>
<P>
   In putting the welfare of the entire SEC first, Kramer has
ruffled some feathers over the years.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1994, the SEC angered the other major conferences
when it left the national College Football Association television
package and struck its own deal with CBS. The other conferences
soon followed suit. Today, the SEC's television deals with CBS,
ESPN, and Jefferson-Pilot are set through the 2008-2009 academic
year and are worth more than $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Just 14 days after that decision, Kramer infuriated the city
fathers of Birmingham, where the SEC headquarters are located. When
Birmingham came up short on its guaranteed payment for hosting the
second SEC championship football game, Kramer moved the game to
Atlanta. Angering the folks in Birmingham was not the politically
smart thing to do, given the fact that the SEC rents its office
space from the city for $1 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Roy took the heat because he knew it was best for the
conference,'' Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   The game has flourished since coming to the Georgia Dome, always
selling out regardless of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after becoming commissioner, Kramer clashed with the
organization that assigned football officials for SEC games.
Officials were assigned based on skill level and the importance of
the game, so the biggest game usually got the six best officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer thought that practice short-changed the other schools and
wanted ta crew system, where the same set of officials would work
together each week. He also wanted the conference office to have
greater control of the officials. Kramer angered the officials, who
said he was heavy-handed in the process, but he won the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the commissioner is convinced he's right on something, he
is going to fight for his position,'' Womack said. ``At the
beginning of the fight, a lot of people may not agree with him. By
the time it's over, he has convinced them.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING CARE OF DETAILS
</P>
<P>
   One reason Kramer is able to persuade friend and foe alike to
follow his lead is that he does his homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Roy brings an idea to the table, you know he has .
. . studied it from every conceivable angle,'' Foley said. ``You
won't come up with a contigency that he hasn't thought of or
doesn't have a plan for.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer does not delegate those details to his staff. When the
Bowl Championship Series (BCS) created a computer formula to pick
its top two teams, Kramer sat up night after night playing with
hundreds of combinations. He would settle on one and then challenge
his staff to find the weaknesses in it.
</P>
<P>
   Once Kramer found the formula he wanted, he sold it to the
conferences, the bowls. a skeptical media and an equally skeptical
public.
</P>
<P>
   His work ethic is legendary. After a full day, either in
Birmingham or on the road, he will break for dinner. From 11 p.m.
to 2 a.m., he reads the early editions of newspapers on-line and
will fire off memos to the staff if something needs to be handled
first thing in the morning. He gets about five hours of sleep and
then starts over at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   During football season, it is not unusual for him to fly to
three games on one day. During the first and second rounds of the
NCAA basketball tournament, he will make four stops in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Womack, Kramer's junior by 25 years, says it is tough to keep
up. ``If I just have half the energy he's got when I'm 70,'' he
said, ``I'll consider myself very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   HE'LL QUIT `WHEN THE TIME COMES'
</P>
<P>
   Kramer turned 70 the day before Halloween, and friends are
starting to ask how much longer he will keep up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say,'' Kramer said. He makes about $300,000 per
year but said that he is working without a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working at the pleasure of our 12 presidents,'' he said.
``When the time comes, they'll know it or I'll know it. Then, one
day I'll just call in and tell them I'm not coming into work. There
won't be any kind of emotional farewell tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Kramer said, he still enjoys being ``the commish.''
Kramer's three children are grown, so Sara Jo can travel with him.
They met in high school and on their first date, Kramer gave her an
18-karat gold locket. She still wears it.
</P>
<P>
   His schedule should be a little slower this year. Kramer
recently turned over his job as chairman of the BCS to the ACC's
John Swofford. Last year, Kramer renegotiated the deal with ABC
television that will keep the series in place through the 2006
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this,'' Kramer said. ``I won't be around to
renegotiate that deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The television deals will keep the conference on sound financial
footing until 2009. Someone else will be responsible after that.
</P>
<P>
   Who will the next commissioner be? The early money is on Womack,
who has been on the SEC staff since graduating from Alabama in
1978. Under three commissioners, Womack worked his way to the No. 2
spot and has been instrumental in negotiating the SEC's television
and bowl deals. Several years ago, he turned down an opportunity to
return to Alabama as athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say,'' said Womack, when asked about his chances
of succeeding Kramer. ``The 12 presidents will make that decision.
But if the opportunity is there, of course I would be honored.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kramer shows no signs of slowing down. In the recent
spring meetings, he announced a new scheduling format for SEC
football that will, in his opinion, provide a better inventory of
games for the fans and for television in any given year. The
coaches weren't crazy about the idea, but Kramer, as usual,
convinced them that it was best for the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you argue with the guy?'' Tennessee coach Phillip
Fulmer asked. ``By now, it's pretty clear he knows what he is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
