<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-INSECTICIDE-760&AMP;A     06-08 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INSECTICIDE-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE OF COMMON INSECTICIDE TO BE CURBED 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most common ingredients in home, lawn and garden bug
killers poses an unacceptable health risk, particularly to
children, and will no longer be manufactured for that use by the
end of the year, environmental officials said Thursday. The
insecticide, chlorpyrifos, has been widely used for more than 30
years in agriculture and in products used by exterminators and
homeowners, including some Raid sprays, Hartz yard and kennel flea
spray and Black Flag liquid roach and ant killer.
</P>
<P>
   Existing stocks of consumer products containing chlorpyrifos
will not be banned from store shelves until the end of 2001, Carol
M. Browner, the administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, said Thursday. But she added that she would encourage
retail stores to voluntarily consider such a move.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA recently reassessed the chemical, also called Dursban,
and found that it can damage the brain in newborn rats and can
cause weakness, vomiting, diarrhea and other symptoms in children.
Children and adults can be exposed when the chemical is applied in
a backyard or building and through residue on fruits or other
foods.
</P>
<P>
   After prolonged negotiations with six pesticide manufacturers _
the largest of which was Dow AgroSciences _ the EPA signed an
agreement with them Wednesday night that will allow continued uses
on many crops but sharply limit the use of chlorpyrifos on apples,
grapes and tomatoes and eliminate it entirely for almost all uses
around homes, schools, day-care centers and other places where
children might be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Dow officials on Thursday said that the chemical was safe when
properly used, but that changes in federal law made continued use
of the ingredient in household products impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules have changed, but the safety of chlorpyrifos
hasn't,'' said Elin Miller, a vice president of Dow's AgroSciences
division.
</P>
<P>
   But Browner said the scientific evidence of unacceptable risk
was clear and justified the agency's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is faster than any other action we have taken against a
pesticide, literally in the history of the EPA,'' Browner said
Thursday at a Washington news conference.
</P>
<P>
   After television reports Thursday about the environmental
agency's decision, some large retail stores received a surge of
customer inquiries on non-chlorpyrifos pesticides. John Simley, a
spokesman for the Home Depot chain, said the company planned to
place signs in its stores identifying alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart will stop selling products with chlorpyrifos at the end
of October, or 14 months ahead of the timetable the EPA is
demanding, a spokesman for Wal-Mart, Rob Phillips, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials said consumers concerned about whether products
now in the home contained the chemical should look at the label,
where, if so, the list of active ingredients will include either
``chlorpyrifos'' or ``Dursban.'' But they stressed that the
agency's decision reflected no need to pull the product from store
shelves or homes immediately, simply to phase it out in an orderly
way.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of products containing chlorpyrifos listed
through the EPA's Web site (www.epa.gov) are Black Flag Liquid
Roach and Ant Killer, Black Flag Roach Control System, Ortho Home
Pest Insect Control, Ortho Lawn Insect Spray, Scotts Proturf Insect
Control Plus Fertilizer, Sergeant's Fast-Acting Flea &AMP; Tick Collar
for Dogs, Sergeant's Flea + Tick Collar, Hartz 330 Day Flea &AMP; Tick
Collar for Dogs, Raid Ant Controller, Raid Home Insect Killer
Formula II, Raid Liquid Roach &AMP; Ant Killer Formula I and Raid Max
Roach Bait III.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Goldberg, a spokesman for Consumer's Union, a private group
that publishes Consumer Reports and tests product safety, said that
the EPA's conclusions should not cause panic, but should prompt
people to consider disposing of products containing the chemical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would encourage consumers to find safer alternatives now,''
he said. He said that homeowners should call their local public
works or health departments to find out how to dispose of
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to avoid an infestation of ants or
cockroaches or other indoor pests, he said, is to clean up.
``Plugging cracks, leaving no standing water, clearing dishes out
of the sink _ if you take care of these other things then you
probably don't have to spray,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The new restrictions on chlorpyrifos (pronounced
klor-PYE-ruh-fahs) grew out of a broad review of organophosphate
pesticides, a group related to nerve gas that includes
chlorpyrifos. The review was required under the 1996 Food Quality
Protection Act and calls for a much stricter appraisal of risks,
focusing on potential harm to children, whose small bodies and
fast-growing brains are particularly vulnerable to toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said that the organophosphates, many of which were
invented decades ago, are antiquated weapons for which safer
alternatives exist. ``Organophosphates are a World War II class of
chemicals,'' she said. ``We can do better today. There are too many
incidents in my experience of children becoming ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the chemical review, restrictions were placed on some
other organophosphate pesticides last summer. The decision on
chlorpyrifos has received intense attention from consumer groups
because it is so widely used.
</P>
<P>
   Simley, the Home Depot spokesman, said that most of the
poisonings and other cases of human exposure identified by the EPA
came through improper use of products with chlorpyrifos. ``Their
main concern is that people rarely read the instructions,'' he
said. ``Given that, we are redoubling our efforts to make sure
people understand how to use the products they buy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision to end residential use of the chemical is not
likely to have a substantial impact on the $5-billion-a-year
exterminating business, industry representatives said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many exterminators have already shifted toward using
custom-tailored chemicals, baits and techniques that kill a
targeted pest without broader effects on wildlife or people.
``We've basically been supportive of the science behind Dursban,
but it's certainly not the only tool out there any more,'' said
Steven Kramer, a spokesman for the National Pest Management
Association, which represents 5,000 pest control businesses.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he said, pest-control businesses would probably
benefit from the EPA's move as consumers find their insecticide
choices at the hardware store shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Legal and environmental experts said it was unclear whether the
move to eliminate household uses of chlorpyrifos would prompt a
flood of lawsuits from people who feel they have been harmed by the
chemical.
</P>
<P>
   Dow and some pest-control companies have been sued sporadically
over the years by people claiming adverse effects from exposure to
the chemical. Several cases ended in settlements in which the
chemical and the company were not found culpable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
