<HEADLINE>
IT'S FUTILE TO PUT A PRICE ON SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, June 9, and thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By PETER SCOBLIC    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its eagerness to persuade Russia to accept deployment of a
U.S. missile defense, the Clinton administration has all but
ignored China, a nuclear power in its own right and an opponent of
these systems.
</P>
<P>
   China currently fields about 20 nuclear-armed missiles capable
of striking the continental United States. For decades, it has
relied on this small force not only to deter a nuclear attack, but
also to guarantee it a place at the table with the other great
powers and to offset their conventional weaponry. In a conflict,
even the limited, 100-interceptor missile defense being pursued by
the Clinton administration would be able to counter China's entire
strategic nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   To many critics of the Communists in Beijing, this sounds like
an excellent idea. But China could not be expected to sit idly by.
Its intentions have never been easy to read, but one point comes
through in its foreign policy statements: China must never again be
subjected to the humiliation that stronger powers inflicted on it
in the past. Nuclear weapons are its protection against such
disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike North Korea and the other rogue states that would be the
primary focus of an American missile defense, China is capable of
compensating by arming its missiles with multiple warheads and
adding sophisticated countermeasures to confuse our defensive
system.
</P>
<P>
   True, China will modernize its nuclear arms to some degree no
matter what we do; the missiles it has now are antiquated and
impossible to launch quickly. But modernization is different from
expansion. An American missile defense would encourage China to
develop a larger, more flexible nuclear force and to put that force
on alert.
</P>
<P>
   China is currently debating what role nuclear weapons should
play in its security policy: the size and structure of its force
and the principles that should govern its use. Neither the
administration nor the Republicans seem concerned about how our
actions on missile defense might influence that debate.
</P>
<P>
   But as the presidential race heats up and the administration
moves toward a deployment decision, missile defense proponents must
explain why obviating a potential threat from a handful of
third-rate states is worth increasing the certain threat from an
established nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   (Peter Scoblic is editor of Arms Control Today.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
