<HEADER>
A8542 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-MICROSOFT-PRIEST     06-08 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-MICROSOFT-PRIEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FUTILE TO PUT A PRICE ON SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, June 9, and thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By GEORGE L. PRIEST    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's decision to
throw the book at Microsoft was not unexpected: his formal
``findings of law'' issued earlier made very clear that he viewed
the company's alleged transgressions in the harshest light.
Nonetheless, it was still a jolt to see the decision _ dividing
Microsoft into an operating systems company and an applications
company _ written in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up an enterprise that was not itself the product of a
merger is unprecedented in antitrust law. And ordering the
dissolution of the flagship firm of the software industry without
hearings on the implications approaches the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written recently about the glorious history of big
antitrust divestitures, with Standard Oil and AT&AMP;T as case studies.
But neither example goes to the point. Standard Oil was a loose
trust of some 30 oil companies, assembled with the goal of reducing
competition. The court simply ordered that the trust be taken apart
the way it had been put together.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, AT&AMP;T was a government-sanctioned monopoly with
semi-autonomous local companies and other divisions, like a
manufacturing arm, for which there was no justification for
government regulation. Dividing the company into regulated local
phone companies and an unregulated company to do everything else is
more like deregulation than the breakup of a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   And for the record, a court did not force the divestiture: it
was the product of a mid-trial settlement in 1982, in which the
Justice Department granted the deregulated AT&AMP;T long-distance
company the right to go into the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson dismissed Microsoft's request for weeks (or even days)
of hearings on the proposed breakup, stating that ``the court has
found testimonial predictions of future events generally less
reliable even than testimony as to historical fact.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know what to make of a judge's rejection of expert
comment. Witnesses from the two sides would no doubt be at odds,
but the judge's unwillingness to assemble a record for both his own
information and that of appellate courts is jaw-dropping.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure, for example, how the copyrights to code
now used by both Windows and other Microsoft software would be
divided between the new operating system company and the
applications company. No one knows how the heavily regulated
Windows company could keep important employees, who would have the
option to jump to the virtually unregulated Microsoft software
applications company.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether (or how much) the independent Windows
company would raise the price of the operating system, once it no
longer had an interest in increasing sales of Office and other
profitable Microsoft applications. Perhaps most troubling, no one
knows how the breakup would affect investment in software. It is
far from clear, for example, that the owners of the regulated
Windows company would be willing to pay the billion-dollar bill for
the next version of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, like everyone else associated with this case, was no
doubt impatient to rid himself of arcane talk of ``middleware'' and
``porting'' and ``elasticities of demand.'' The sad paradox here is
that if he gets his way on the remedy, he will likely be forced to
tie together a million loose ends created by this sweeping, but
casually constructed, divestiture plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the AT&AMP;T case, U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene spent
more than a decade regulating the remnants of the national phone
company. And in that case, you will remember, the division was
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   (George L. Priest, a law professor at Yale, is a consultant to
Microsoft.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
