<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER OF GENERAL AT SITE OF ANTI-GAY KILLING IS PROTESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army's decision to reassign the commander of
Fort Campbell, Ky., where a gay soldier was beaten to death last
year, is provoking criticism from members of Congress and
gay-rights advocates who complain that an investigation of anti-gay
harassment under his command has not yet been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Gen. Robert T. Clark, who steps down on Friday
as commander of Fort Campbell and the 101st Airborne Division, was
appointed early this week to be vice director of operations for the
joint chiefs of staff at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer, which does not include a promotion in rank but
does put Clark in a position of prominence, came before the Army's
inspector general completed an investigation into whether officers
at Fort Campbell tolerated or overlooked anti-gay slurs and
taunting in the months leading up to the killing last July of Pfc.
Barry Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Clark's new assignment was announced, 30 members of
the House wrote to Secretary of Defense William Cohen urging that
he hold the general responsible for what appears to have been a
highly charged environment at Fort Campbell in the months leading
up to Winchell's death.
</P>
<P>
   The members _ most but not all of them Democrats, including the
minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt _ also criticized the decision
to move ahead with Clark's reassignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relocating and promoting Major General Clark prior to the
completion of this investigation would be wrong and undermine the
department's professed commitment to enforce the
gays-in-the-military policy in a fair and legal manner,'' they
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Army announced the investigation in January, saying it was
requested by Clark himself, but the deadline for completing it has
been pushed back to the beginning of July from May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials declined to discuss the reasons behind the delay.
One official said that while the inspector general's investigation
was not complete, nothing had emerged to implicate Clark in
wrongdoing or leadership failings.
</P>
<P>
   Clark did not respond to requests for comment, but a spokeswoman
said he would address the issue at his change-of-command ceremony
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Army's chief of staff, Gen. Eric Shinseki,
said Clark's command at Fort Campbell had been ``distinguished by
great competence and compassionate leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army has placed its trust and confidence in Major General
Clark,'' Shinseki said, ``and I am confident he will continue to
excel in service to our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Winchell's death has become a rallying cry for critics of the
Pentagon's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, which allows gay men
and lesbians to serve in the military so long as they do not
disclose their orientation or engage in homosexual sex.
</P>
<P>
   Another private, Calvin Glover, was convicted and sentenced to
life in prison for killing Winchell with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   In Glover's court-martial, soldiers testified that Winchell had
repeatedly been taunted with anti-gay slurs and that superiors did
nothing to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The killing prompted Cohen to order a survey of attitudes about
gays in the military, which found that disparaging and even hostile
feelings toward gay men and lesbians were commonplace and often
tolerated by superiors.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osborne, co-director of the Servicemembers Legal
Defense Network, an organization in Washington that provides legal
aid to gay men and lesbians in the military, said Clark's
reassignment suggested that the Army did not intend to hold him
accountable for the actions of troops under his command.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that they do a full and fair investigation,''
Osborne said, ``and not try to suggest that anti-gay harassment was
simply isolated to Pfc. Winchell's unit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
