<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA STILL FAILS TO STEM NARCOTICS TRAFFIC, U.S. REPORT ASSERTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Panamanian government has made little progress this
year in its fight against drug trafficking and money laundering,
according to a U.S. Customs intelligence report.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which is expected to be discussed at a congressional
hearing on Friday, said Panama continued to be a major
transshipment point for cocaine and increasingly for heroin, which
are smuggled through weakly patrolled borders and ports. The
reported noted that in 1999 drug seizures declined 80 percent from
1998 and no major drug arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary version of the report, which was provided to a
House subcommittee on criminal justice and drug policy, originally
had harsh words for Panama's law enforcement agencies, saying they
were ``corrupt and ill trained'' and ``overwhelmed'' by drug
traffickers. The final version softened that criticism, saying they
faced ``difficulties dealing with sophisticated trafficking
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said that Panama's sprawling Colon Free Trade Zone
was used by traffickers not only to hide drugs in cargo containers
but also to launder profits. It cited serious security problems at
Tocumen International Airport, where there have been allegations
that cargo and ramp workers are helping to move drug shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials would not comment on the report, which they
said was classified.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the report's observations are sure to be used by
congressional critics and others who have expressed grave concerns
about Panama's inability to secure its border with Colombia less
than six months after the United States withdrew all its troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Panama has taken a dramatic turn for the
worse,'' said Rep. John Mica, R-Fla., who is the subcommittee
chairman. ``The information we have is pretty damaging, especially
since the United States exited six months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   With increased unrest and violence in Colombia, more traffickers
have been seeking a safe haven in Panama. At the same time, the
country's lax banking laws and dollar economy have proved as much
of a lure to them as the high-rise buildings they have settled
into.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about drugs,'' a diplomat said. ``The country is
built on dodging taxes, dodging bizarre exchange rates and evading
court settlements.'' He added, ``The narcos have grafted right
on.'' As a result, the diplomat said, efforts to crack down on
money laundering have been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem has been that the government of President
Mireya Moscoso assumed power only last September and is still
feeling its way. Some critics have faulted her for not having
enough of a vision for the country's future and say that she has
been more preoccupied with petty politics and deciding which
supporters get which government posts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, her government has been ambivalent about what
kind of relationship it wants with the United States after nearly a
century of American influence on Panamanian affairs. It is also
about to sign a long-awaited national security plan that will, for
the first time, outline its strategy for securing its borders and
the canal.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARIS MATCH: PIERCE TO PLAY MARTINEZ IN FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In reality, only a few minutes separated Thursday's
women's semifinals, yet it felt more like decades.
</P>
<P>
   After Conchita Martinez and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario had offered
topspin loops, languid slices and afterthought serves of
yesteryear, Mary Pierce and Martina Hingis hit the fast-forward
button as they bashed the two-handed backhands and bold returns of
today and tomorrow at each other.
</P>
<P>
   But these two matches, so disparate in form and suspense, did
share one significant characteristic: the favorite lost in both.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario lost first, falling prey to her own
inconsistency and to Martinez's hypnotic, anachronistic rhythm
shifts by the score of 6-1, 6-2. Even more surprisingly, the
top-seeded Hingis lost next, saving a match point before winning
the second set but proving unable to match Pierce's big-swinging
baseline tempo, public support or confidence down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, the Canadian-born American resident who represents
France, began to cramp in her left calf midway through the final
set but managed to close out a 6-4, 5-7, 6-2 victory. Both the
sixth-seeded Pierce and the fifth-seeded Martinez had lost seven
times in a row to their semifinal opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after enlisting her brother David as coach, Pierce
succeeded in putting an end to her run of bad form and fortune at
Roland Garros in recent years. Hingis' streak is still very much
alive.
</P>
<P>
   A two-time junior champion here who grew up playing on clay,
Hingis has won all of the Grand Slam singles titles except the
French Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many other players who have never won this
tournament,'' Hingis said. ``I mean, I have a lot of years in front
of me. As you see, Pierce and Martinez never won this tournament.
One of them is going to win. One is 25 and the other 28. I have
nothing to worry about right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, not at her fittest after a riding injury, Hingis was
upset in the final by Iva Majoli, who has beaten few people since.
In last year's final against Steffi Graf, Hingis lost her composure
and the public's sympathy after crossing to Graf's side of the net
to question a line call. After that match, she sobbed on French
player Nathalie Tauziat's shoulder: saying, according to Tauziat,
that she believed she would never win here.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she played well below her best, making 44 unforced
errors against Pierce, who had beaten Hingis in their only previous
clay-court match in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary was just focused,'' Hingis said. ``Definitely that was
the best she played me in a long time. But on a hard court, it's a
different game. She's got more time on clay.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, a French Open finalist in 1994 who has struggled here
since and has been booed regularly for it, happens to be Hingis'
friend and doubles partner, and they reached the semifinals
together on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that Martina thinks very well on the court, and I
think in watching her play singles over the years I think I learned
a lot from her,'' Pierce said. ``I think I've learned a lot from
playing doubles with her, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether she will be able to play doubles on
Friday or have enough time to recover and play her best in
Saturday's singles final. While leading by 4-2 and 15-15 on her
serve in the final set, Pierce leaped and hit a cross-court
backhand winner (her best weapon all day) and started limping after
she landed. Before serving the next point, she stretched her calf
but still managed to chase down a Hingis drop shot in the next
exchange and hold her serve. Still stretching between points, she
then broke Hingis for the ninth time to win the match.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after leaving the court, Pierce said she began cramping
severely in her legs and had to spend more than an hour stretching,
drinking fluids and receiving fluid intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would be able to play on Saturday, Pierce answered:
``I've never had cramps before; I don't know how I'm going to feel
tomorrow. I think I've done everything possible I could this
evening to help myself recover the best possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Martinez will be waiting. Long one of the world's best
clay-court players, she is now in her first French Open final. With
her mind on her father's struggle with cancer and her motivation
waning, she dropped out of the top 20 a year ago. But with the help
of Patricia Tarabini, her Argentine coach and doubles partner, and
a Spanish sports psychologist, Guillermo Perez, Martinez has
rebuilt her fitness and ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been working with Patricia, I've decided to play
tennis with a smile on my face, which was hard the past years,''
said Martinez, never the most diligent in practice or most joyful
on court.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, she beat Hingis on clay en route to the title in
Berlin and by then she was already having a recurring dream about
winning in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of faith in dreams, and I have never dreamed this
until this year, but I have been dreaming it now for the last month
or month and a half,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
