<HEADER>
A8554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-NORRIS-COLUMN-     06-08 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH THE LOOKING GLASS: EUROPE RAISES INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Norris Column) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would the Federal Reserve do if American inflation was
running about 2 percent a year and the unemployment rate was 9.6
percent? Would Alan Greenspan have the nerve to raise rates by half
a percentage point?
</P>
<P>
   If that idea sounds crazy to you, then you are not in touch with
reality, European style. For that is exactly what happened Thursday
to Germans, for whom the above statistics apply. The European
Central Bank, eager to prove its credibility as an
inflation-fighter, decided to confound forecasters and impose a
half-point interest rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, an unemployment rate that high would have long
since become the major national economic issue _ the actual U.S.
rate is now 4.1 percent _ and politicians would be screaming for
easier monetary policy. It would take an inflation rate far higher
than 2 percent to convince anyone that tightening credit was a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But in Europe, things are different. Wim Duisenberg, the central
bank's president, explained that they were worried about inflation
that can be traced in part to high oil prices and a weak euro, and
that the European economy was growing at around 3 percent anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing about Europe now is that it seems to have accepted
high unemployment as a virtually permanent thing. Europe's
unemployment is coming down, but the latest reported rate for the
countries in the euro currency zone is 9.2 percent. The
conventional wisdom is that unemployment is high because of
structural problems such as high wages and laws making it difficult
for employers to hire and fire at will, and that a stimulative
monetary policy would only revive inflation without doing much for
growth. Anyway, the European Central Bank is supposed to keep
inflation from going above 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Solow, the Nobel Prize winning economist, has
suggested that idea is simply wrong. ``European central banks kept
the squeeze on for a long time'' when they fought the inflation of
the 1970s, he wrote a few years ago. ``Suppose,'' he added, ``there
is a tendency for prolonged `cyclical' unemployment to turn into
something that looks like `structural' unemployment. It is not hard
to imagine how that might plausibly happen as the unemployed adapt
to the unavailability of jobs.'' Eventually, he said, central banks
wrongly convinced themselves that high unemployment was there to
stay and the banks could not ``afford to expand aggregate demand''
by loosening monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   It is perfectly true that Europe needs structural reform, but as
Solow noted, ``it would be bad news indeed if this apparently
structural unemployment really would not yield to the revival of
demand for goods and labor.'' He suggested that history indicated
it would. The European Central Bank should find out if he is right.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, there was been good reason to think the
economy was overheating, and the Fed has been right to tighten. But
the Fed's action makes it all the more regrettable that the
Europeans seem scared of growth. ``From the world's perspective, a
surprising strength coming out of Europe gives us the best chance
to survive a necessary sharp slowing in the United States,'' said
Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has been weak because investors have viewed the rapidly
growing United States as a much more attractive place to put money.
The euro is cheap, and will recover eventually. But efforts to slow
European growth are not going to help the beleaguered currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2118EDT &QL; 
