<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GREECE-TERROR-940&AMP;ADD     06-08 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREECE-TERROR-940&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH MILITARY ATTACHE IS ASSASSINATED IN ATHENS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ Britain's senior defense official in Greece was
gunned down here on Thursday, just days after a special report
prepared for Congress recommended sanctions against Greece,
describing it as ``disturbingly passive in response to terrorist
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Greek police officials said that two gunmen they identified as
members of ``November 17,'' a left-wing terrorist group, shot
several times at Brig. Stephen Saunders, 53, the military attache
at the British Embassy in Athens. The police said the gunmen shot
from a motorcycle as he was driving alone through a busy suburban
street at 8 a.m., and they escaped through the traffic. Saunders
died at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first British official assassinated in an attack
blamed on November 17, but the killing was the 23rd attributed to
the guerrilla organization that emerged in 1975 with the slaying of
Richard Welch, the CIA station chief in Athens. Welch was the first
of four American officials killed by the group.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 25 years, no member of November 17 has been
arrested, driving the State Department to identify Greece in a
report issued in April as ``one of the weakest links in Europe's
effort against terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing on Thursday revived one of the most sensitive
disputes between Athens and its allies. Greece is a member of NATO,
and the Socialist government of Prime Minister Costas Simitis won
Western gratitude by not obstructing the alliance's bombing of
Yugoslavia last year, despite overwhelming domestic opposition. But
U.S. officials have long complained that the Greek government,
which has been ruled by the Panhellenic Socialist Movement, known
as Pasok, for nearly 20 years, has shown no signs of seriously
trying to root out November 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``This highlights again that Greece needs to take a tougher
stance against terrorism,'' Kenneth H. Bacon, the Defense
Department spokesman, said on Thursday. The Clinton
administration's views on the terrorist threat in Greece are
repeated ``every time we visit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Richard C. Shelby, the Alabama Republican who is
chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, echoed the
allegation that Greece has been lax about November 17. ``I've long
been distressed by the failure of the Greek government to deal with
this group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Privately, U.S. officials have speculated that the Greek
government has not cracked down on November 17 because it fears
that an investigation could disclose that some Pasok members had
past ties to members of the terrorist group. And in an interview
with a weekly Greek newspaper, Pontiki, published on Thursday, R.
James Woolsey Jr., a former CIA director and a member of a
commission on terrorism that recommended sanctions against Greece
and Pakistan, was quoted as saying: ``I believe there are people
within the Greek government who know some members of November 17.
They are doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that reflected British determination to press the
Greek government, Foreign Minister Robin Cook said, ``I am in touch
with the Greek authorities and am offering them our full
cooperation in making sure that whoever perpetrated this brutal
attack is brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Accusations that Greece has dragged its feet on terrorism are
often dismissed as unfair by Greek officials and much of the Greek
news media, reflecting the country's sensitivity to what it views
as American interference. After the the terrorism commission's
report, which said Greece was ``not cooperating fully'' on
antiterrorism, was released on Monday, Dimitris Reppas, a
government spokesman, said, ``The report's content bears no
relation to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ruled out sanctions, but said it was
pressing Greece for more cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Greek officials expressed outrage and grief over
Saunders' killing, but played down any notion that terrorist
attacks were more prevalent in Greece than elsewhere. Prime
Minister Simitis assured his British counterpart, Tony Blair, ``We
will not spare any effort in apprehending those responsible and
bringing them to justice, and we are determined to actively
continue our difficult struggle against terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement tailored for Greek listeners, he took a
slightly different tone, saying: ``This terrorist act is contrary
to the fundamental law of respect for human life. And it takes
place at a time when Greece is charting a period of success, with
increased international prestige.'' Simitis, who was narrowly
re-elected last April, added, ``The Greek government will do its
duty and will safeguard with all means the country's stable course
and the security of its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has claimed responsibility for the killing, but the
police said shells found at the site came from a .45-caliber
pistol, the type of weapon used by November 17 in other attacks.
The site and the method of the killing were almost identical to two
other slayings attributed to the group.
</P>
<P>
   November 17 took its name from the date on which the United
States-supported military junta sent tanks to crush a student
protest at Athens Polytechnic University in 1973, killing dozens of
demonstrators. The Marxist-leaning group has remained anti-American
and anticapitalist, and has acquired a harsh nationalist tone. It
has has taken responsibility for hundreds of violent acts,
including the slayings of a dozen prominent Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, members fired a rocket-propelled grenade at the
German Embassy last May, narrowly missing the ambassador.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There have never been wide demands from average Greeks for major
antiterrorist sweeps. Most Greeks feel untouched by November 17
violence because it has been largely limited to foreigners and
prominent people. Some of November 17's anti-American ideology is
widely shared in Greece, a country that still resents American
support of the junta from 1967 to 1974, and whose populace bitterly
opposed the British, French and American bombing of Serbia, a
neighbor that shares Greece's Orthodox faith.
</P>
<P>
   Yannis Fokas, 31, a parking attendant, said he was not surprised
to hear of another terrorist attack. But he was baffled by the
gunmen's choice. ``Why a Brit?'' he asked. ``I was expecting them
to attack an American after all this anti-Greek talk and reports
that have been coming out of Washington lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Others seemed perplexed by the international outrage. ``I'm
surprised the British have not become immune to Greek terrorism as
we have,'' said Irene Kafandaraki, 24. ``It's just an other
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Greeks, however, expressed criticism of their own
government. ``After 25 years, the Greek police is powerless to deal
with such a phenomenon,'' said Dora Bakoyannis, a leader of the
center-right New Democracy opposition party, whose husband was shot
dead in 1989 in an attack attributed to November 17. ``If we don't
at some stage realize that terrorism has to be tackled, we will
continue to be the only country which finds itself in this
situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stelios Papathemelis, a senior member of the Pasok party and a
former minister of public order, was critical of his own political
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greece must show stronger political will,'' he said on
Thursday. ``What is needed is a consistent and continuous policy
against terrorism, which Greece lacks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
