u w BC-keyword-HNS &LR;      06-08 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-keyword-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SENATE BACKS McCAIN AMENDMENT FORCING SECRET GROUPS TO NAME DONORS 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Arizona Sen. John McCain, who made campaign finance
reform the No. 1 issue of his failed White House bid, succeeded
Thursday in pushing through the Senate a measure forcing secretive
political groups to identify their contributors and tell how they
spend their money.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first campaign finance reform legislation to pass the
Senate since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've won, it will become law, one way or another,''
McCain said after the vote. ``This is not the end. It is the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Sens. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., and Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., attached their amendment to an unrelated defense spending
bill after senators voted 57-42 to block the Republican
leadership's attempt to thwart the measure on a constitutional
technicality.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen Republicans joined Democrats in supporting the
amendment on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, a much more modest effort than the comprehensive
legislation that McCain and Feingold have proposed for years, was
an attempt to address a tax loophole enjoyed by so-called 527s. The
political groups currently are tax-exempt while collecting
unlimited donations from anonymous contributors. Under current law,
they do not have to disclose the contributors' names or how the
money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would like to close the 527 tax loophole altogether, but
Thursday's amendment would force only disclosure on the groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has not yet voted on the defense bill, but it is
expected to pass. The bill would then move to the House with
McCain's amendment, unless Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott is
able to persuade McCain and his allies to place the amendment on
another bill instead.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 of the tax code was created in 1975 to establish tax
rules for political organizations, such as the national political
parties and political action committees. But unlike these new,
secretive groups, parties and PACs register with the Federal
Election Commission, which requires them to disclose their donors
and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Federal election laws don't cover 527s because the groups do not
specifically endorse candidates, but rather concentrate on issues.
By law, they cannot coordinate their activities, such as running
television ads, with the candidates who benefit from them.
</P>
<P>
   But 527s are playing a prominent role on both sides in this
year's political campaigns. McCain himself was targeted by a Texas
group's ads when he was challenging Gov. George W. Bush for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he sent an e-mail to more than 200,000 supporters,
urging them to call their senators and ask them to vote for his
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that this is last minute,'' he wrote, ``but I need your
help now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats have filed a lawsuit against House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, alleging that the Sugar Land Republican illegally
oversees the operation of several 527s.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has denied that charge. His office did not return calls
from the Houston Chronicle seeking comment on Thursday's action.
</P>
<P>
   During two hours of debate, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., called
the 527 loophole the ``largest, most disturbing, pernicious
loophole in a system rife with backdoor ways to influence
government.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others warned that if the Senate failed to deal with
527s, Americans would have no way of knowing whether and how
foreign governments, organized crime or drug lords are influencing
the outcome of U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to track them down or find it out . . . All
we're saying is disclose,'' Schumer said. ``This is basic
information that the people have a right to know and we have a duty
to see that they get it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier efforts to change the campaign finance system have
stalled as McCain and his allies have been unable to muster the 60
votes needed to overcome a filibuster backed by DeLay and other
Republican leaders. That fact weighed heavily Thursday on some
senators, who feared that if the defense bill were sent to the
House with McCain's amendment it would bounce right back because of
a constitutional provision that requires legislation dealing with
taxes to originate in the House.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that would jeopardize the entire defense bill, which
includes crucial health benefits for military retirees as well as
programs for active-duty soldiers and sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment will torpedo this bill and send it to the
bottom of the sea,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of the
Armed Services Committee and a former secretary of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   McCain had earlier offered to remove the measure from the
defense bill if opponents would agree to attach it to the next
appropriate legislation to come before the Senate. They refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just totally disclosed what this is all about,''
McCain fumed. ``This is not about the defense of the nation. This
is the defense of a corrupt system.''
</P>
<P>
   The 57-42 vote rejecting the constitutional point of order
cleared the way for passage of McCain's amendment. Lott then said
he wanted to discuss putting the amendment on another bill, and
McCain said he would consider it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL ADD END) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the amendment had also argued that if 527s were
targeted, groups like the Sierra Club and the AFL-CIO should also
be included. Those nonprofit organizations also use issue ads and
tend to support Democrats, the senators argued. Under current law,
they are not required to name their contributors, but they do
release their tax returns and their political activities are
limited.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would consider broadening the type of
organizations included in his amendment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
