<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8562 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV1     06-08 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPGRADE MEANS MORE SPACE FOR MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 11) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANTHONY DEPALMA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most exclusive clubs in Latin America is the select
group of nations with the financial stability to earn
investment-grade ratings for their bonds and notes. Just about
every politician in the region dreams of joining.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Alejandro Toledo of Peru. Fighting to unseat President
Alberto Fujimori, Toledo came to New York to denounce electoral
fraud, and ultimately pulled out of a runoff widely thought to be
rigged against him. Even so, he told reporters, he made time to
visit Wall Street and to talk up Peru's prospects for a rating
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, few Latin American nations have ever had the economic
or political credentials to qualify for admission. Chile is a
member, along with Panama, Uruguay and postwar El Salvador. For a
while, Colombia was, too, but shaky finances knocked it out last
August.
</P>
<P>
   The small circle widened earlier this year, when Moody's
Investors Service bumped up Mexico bonds to Baa3, its lowest
investment grade, nearly 20 years after a government default sent
tremors around the world. (Standard &AMP; Poor's still ranks Mexico a
step lower.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Baa3'' sounds discordant, but it is sweet music to
politicians' ears. Mexican officials take it as affirmation of
their harsh policies in the 1994 peso crisis, when the country's
last flirtation with an investment-grade rating fell apart.
Naturally, it has become campaign fodder for the presidential
election in July.
</P>
<P>
   What does it really mean? By all accounts, more than enough to
justify politicians' aspirations. ``Mexico, like the entire region,
has always paid incredibly high prices for capital because of the
volatility of the past,'' said Eduardo Cabrera, senior director of
Latin America strategy at Merrill Lynch. ``Now the cost of capital
will be decreasing, which gives Mexico an incredible competitive
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   With a smaller ``risk premium'' needed to compensate investors
for the risk of default, the government can borrow more cheaply for
new highways and hospitals. But more important, analysts say, the
investment grade opens a much larger pool of potential investors.
Many large pension and money management funds are required to hold
only investment-grade instruments.
</P>
<P>
   And the new status means Mexican bonds are now represented in
benchmarks like the Lehman Brothers Aggregate Bond index. Steven
Berkley, Lehman's global index manager, said that as soon as
Mexico's rating was upgraded, about $16 billion of Mexican paper
was automatically added to the index, joining about $4 billion in
notes from Pemex, the state-owned energy monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The Moody's rating refers specifically to Mexican government
debt payable in foreign currency, but the benefits extend to
corporate borrowers, which are rarely able to win ratings higher
than their home country's, a limit known as the sovereign ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   To Herminio Blanco, Mexico's secretary of commerce and
industrial development, the re-evaluation by Wall Street represents
``thousands more jobs in Mexico in the near future.'' It did not
contribute to the country's blistering 7.9 percent economic growth
rate in the first quarter, he said, but it will help President
Ernesto Zedillo end his administration as he has promised, ``with
no crisis'' _ a far cry from its start in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's based its decision on the perceived success of many
Zedillo initiatives: a more manageable debt load, a flexible
exchange rate policy and a dynamic export sector that is ``well
integrated into the North American economy,'' said Luis Ernesto
Martinez-Alas, a vice president at Moody's.
</P>
<P>
   The agency did see a few areas of Mexico's economy that still
need attention and called for additional spending cuts and a
broadening of the tax base, leaving some economists grumbling that
perhaps Mexico didn't deserve the upgrade just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really should be called a confusion-grade rating,'' said
Roberto Salinas Leon, a Mexican economist. He said too much work
remained to be done in opening competition in the state-run oil and
electricity sectors, updating labor laws and fortifying a rickety
banking system. ``The investment grade was premature,'' he said,
``and the explanations given are exceedingly rosy, unreflective of
a far more problematical situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, investment-grade ratings also bring negatives. The
same decrease in interest rates that helps Mexico's finances will
drive away risk-tolerant investors seeking higher returns. Joyce
Chang, global head of international fixed-income research at Chase
Securities, said some high-stakes players she surveyed were
planning to swap out of Mexico for countries whose bonds yielded
more. Two-thirds of them said Brazil was their top choice. Toledo
would be disappointed to know that Peru, now rated two notches
below Mexico, was on no one's list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
