<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newspaper Chain on Block As Another Sells 38 Papers
</P>
<P>
   Central Newspapers, which owns The Arizona Republic, The
Indianapolis Star and four other newspapers, announced that it was
putting itself up for sale. The move would take another
multigenerational newspaper family, the Pulliams, out of the
business. Shares of Central Newspapers rose $20.50, to $52. A few
hours later, Gannett and Community Newspaper Holdings said they
were acquiring 38 of the 49 newspapers Thomson had put on the
block. Gannett is paying $1.13 billion for 21 newspapers. Community
Newspaper Holdings is buying 17 papers for $455 million. The sale
of the remaining 11 daily newspapers Thomson wants to sell is
expected to be completed within days.
</P>
<P>
   Anatomy of Microsoft Court Defeat
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of state and federal officials who have investigated and
prosecuted Microsoft for the last four years, as well as industry
executives, have seen many moves by Microsoft that they think
backfired and led to a resounding court defeat in the company's
antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor Profit Up
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor reported fourth-quarter earnings that
exceeded Wall Street analysts' estimates as sales increased 22.5
percent. And executives raised their predictions for revenue growth
in the next fiscal year to about 30 percent from 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Fall Ahead of Economic Data
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell as investors pulled back before important economic
data scheduled to be released today. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 144.14 points, or 1.3 percent, to 10,668.72. The
Nasdaq composite index dropped 13.70 points, or 0.4 percent, to
3,825.56, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.69
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,461.67.
</P>
<P>
   Interest Rates Increased in Europe
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank raised its core interest rate half a
percentage point, to 4.25 percent, in an unexpectedly aggressive
attempt to help insulate Europe against inflation. The move
surprised most economists and sent currency traders into a confused
frenzy over the euro, which rose and then slipped back.
</P>
<P>
   `Survivor' Extends Its Hit Status
</P>
<P>
   Establishing its credentials as the runaway television hit of
the summer, the CBS show ``Survivor,'' which chronicles the
adventures of 16 real people coexisting on an island off Borneo,
scored extraordinary ratings for the second consecutive week, this
time even drubbing ABC's ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire,'' in
every audience category. More than 18 million people watched the
show Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Another Soros Executive to Quit
</P>
<P>
   The last of three top money managers announced his departure
from the dwindling empire of George Soros. Scott Bessent, who
oversees European investments for Soros Fund Management, said he
would leave to start a private investment group. The move lowers
the curtain on Soros' run as one of the world's most daring money
managers.
</P>
<P>
   May Prices for Imported Goods Fell
</P>
<P>
   The prices businesses pay for imported goods, excluding
petroleum, fell 0.2 percent in May, the first time in almost a
year, government figures showed, suggesting that inexpensive
imports are helping to contain inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign That Looks Out for No. 1
</P>
<P>
   The recently formed MarchFirst, which offers a variety of
Internet professional services, hopes to stand out among
competitors ranging from management consultants to advertising
agencies to Web site builders through an extensive _ and expensive
_ ad campaign centered on a celebration of being, well, first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
