<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8566 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-MUSIC-CONFLICTS-$     06-08 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MUSIC-CONFLICTS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MUSICIANS ON THE NAPSTER BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 11) 
By ALEC FOEGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   As a rock star and actress,
Courtney Love knows how to grab the spotlight. At a new-media
conference last month in Manhattan's SoHo, she delivered her
keynote address in '70s-style hip huggers and angrily shouted at
paparazzi who were blinding her with their camera flashes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love's message was similarly striking. ``Stealing an artist's
music without paying for it is absolute piracy,'' she said. ``And
I'm talking about major-label recording contracts, not Napster.''
</P>
<P>
   In siding with Napster, the free Internet music-swapping service
that has become the record labels' archenemy, Love demonstrated
that the continuing power struggle between the labels and the
musicians is taking a new turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving the major-label system and there are hundreds of
artists watching my court case and wanting to follow me,'' Love
declared. She and her band, Hole, are in a legal fight to end their
recording deal with Geffen Records, which is owned by the Universal
Music Group, itself part of the Seagram Co.
</P>
<P>
   Love is among the musicians raising the revolutionary notion
that the Internet may offer them a better shake than the labels,
which they accuse of imposing burdensome contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Though some prominent acts like Metallica and Dr. Dre side with
the labels against the free download sites, a loose pro-Napster
coalition is forming that includes rock bands like the Offspring
and Limp Bizkit (which is touring with Napster sponsorship this
summer), as well as rappers like Chuck D and the Beastie Boys.
</P>
<P>
   At a Congressional hearing last month, Sheryl Crow, a singer and
songwriter, criticized the labels' insistence on owning the
copyrights to most songs. Aimee Mann and Jonathan Brooke, two
midcareer artists, have found new careers marketing directly to
fans via the Web, offering free downloads, CD sales and concert
schedules. Some small labels are offering free music downloads as
well as selling discs.
</P>
<P>
   Could free downloads of music, whose rapid growth challenges
existing copyright laws, give musicians the upper hand in dealing
with the record companies? The five major labels, which start
selling digital music downloads this summer, may not like the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Label executives say they offer musicians marketing and
promotion, to radio stations and audiences, that are invaluable in
developing and sustaining their careers. These executives add that
they can perform these services much better than musicians or their
managers can on their own. ``It makes better business sense to pool
together resources, which is what a record label does,'' said Paul
Vidich, an executive vice president at Warner Music, a unit of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Only a musician like Love, with proven marquee value, might be
able to survive without a label deal, executives say _ but probably
not for long. ``They don't have the clout as one artist to get the
kind of broad-reaching breakthrough on the Internet on a worldwide
basis,'' said Kevin Conroy, head of new technology at BMG
Entertainment, which has stars like Whitney Houston and Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Goldberg, a former head of Mercury and Warner Music and
now president of the independent Artemis Records, said the labels
could afford far more marketing than the musicians. ``An artist
without marketing is at a disadvantage in a very cluttered world,''
he said. ``Marketing costs money.''
</P>
<P>
   But some musicians, who complain about being charged high
recording and manufacturing costs before they even see a royalty
check, say they can market themselves with free online music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a gatekeeper is the most profitable place to be,'' Love
said in her address. ``But now we're in a world without gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts even say rapid technological advances could render
copyright laws unenforceable, making battles against free music
futile and forcing a decline of the record business. Musicians
would pursue other income sources, including live performances and
merchandising of T-shirts and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Label executives say free online music will not be a threat.
They point to recent courtroom victories in cases that would
restrict the traffic in free music on Napster and MP3.com, another
digital music site. ``I believe that if we offer consumers an
effective online alternative that is reasonably priced, we have
every opportunity to build a legitimate market,'' Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was even blunter, saying, ``I think it's equally as
likely that land would be free than copyrights would be free.''
</P>
<P>
   But a report in April by Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., a research
firm in New York, predicted that 16 percent, or $985 million, of
the nation's music sales in 2002 would be lost to what it termed as
Web piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to squelch free music have had uncertain results. In
recent weeks, the rock band Metallica and the rapper Dr. Dre
pressured Napster to ban from its site hundreds of thousands of
fans who had downloaded their music free. Many, however, simply
re-registered with different names.
</P>
<P>
   Record labels say they represent their artists' best interests.
But to get recorded, new musicians often sign contracts favorable
to the labels, then hire prominent entertainment lawyers to get
them out of these contracts once they make it big.
</P>
<P>
   Even some stars say their agreements leave most of the profits,
beyond a relatively small advance, to the labels. The contracts
criticized by Love and other musicians can leave them with only
pennies per disk from royalties, after subtracting advances and
production costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling records is not necessarily consistent with the
interest of the artists,'' said Ken Hertz, a partner in the law
firm Hansen, Jacobson, Teller &AMP; Hoberman, which represents big-name
acts like Alanis Morissette and No Doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Since contracts for younger, newer musicians tend to be the
least favorable _ when they can get a contract at all _ those
artists have the greatest incentives to use free music to their
advantage. Hundreds of unsigned acts have uploaded free music files
to Web sites like MP3.com in hopes of getting exposure.
</P>
<P>
   A few smaller recording labels are already using free music as a
promotion tool for young musicians. Scott Ross, director of new
media at Moonshine Records of West Hollywood, Calif., an
independent dance-music label whose most popular artists sell
100,000 albums, said giving away MP3 files over the Web had helped
to double the sales growth rate of his company in the last year and
saved on marketing costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get mainstream radio play; we don't get on MTV,''
Ross said. ``So the Internet is our best source of exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen James Barry, a member of one of Moonshine's best-selling
acts, Cirrus, said that offering free music on the Internet _ where
many of its young fans gather _ had helped to generate bigger
audiences for his group's concerts. Although all its music was
available free on the Internet, Barry said, its CD sales were not
hurt, because Cirrus' true fans wanted to collect everything the
band produced.
</P>
<P>
   He can even see his band deciding to handle its marketing and
sales directly. ``Right now, you don't really need a record
label,'' he said. ``When it becomes cheaper and easier to get your
music and promotion out to the people, then you stop needing the
label.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
