<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-A     06-08 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT QUICKLY SEEKS A STAY OF JUDGE'S ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wasting no time, Microsoft filed a court plea
overnight, asking for an immediate stay of the ruling a federal
judge entered against the company on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The company offered expansive reasoning for the request, saying
the judgment would ``inflict grievous and irreparable harm on
Microsoft, its 35,000 employees, its millions of shareholders, its
thousands of business partners and tens of millions of consumers
around the world who rely on Microsoft's products.''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of legal routine, the appeal went to Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson _ the same judge who ruled against Microsoft. He
can be expected to deny the motion, an action required before
Microsoft can take the case to a Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Joel I. Klein, head of the Justice Department's antitrust
division, said during a news briefing Thursday that Jackson's order
included ``straightforward remedies, things like Microsoft not
being able to intimidate computer manufacturers who choose to
select other people's products, things like not illegally tying two
products together as a way to force them on consumers, things that
are really I think rather basic and fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   William Neukom, Microsoft's chief counsel, offered a different
view. During a news conference on Wednesday night at the software
maker's headquarters in Redmond, Wash., he repeated the company's
complaint that the remedy would require Microsoft to ``disclose our
most valuable intellectual property, even to our competitors'' and
``that we would be required to redesign all of our
operating-systems software products to the government's vague and
ambiguous specifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the continuing harsh language, both Klein and Neukom,
in response to questions, said they would still be willing to
settle the case. A civil case can be settled at any point, even if
it is before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is prepared to engage in meaningful settlement
negotiations,'' Klein said, adding that any settlement must
``meaningfully address the harm that's occurred to this market and
ensure on a going-forward basis that it not be replicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Neukom's theoretical endorsement of settlement discussions was
tepid as well. ``I don't think we ever have or would close the door
to good-faith negotiations to resolve differences,'' he said. ``We
do that every day in the law department here at Microsoft. We've
settled more cases than we've had to try or appeal, and that's good
management, and we'll continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   No movement has been made to start settlement talks, and none is
expected. Jackson, in a recent interview with The New York Times,
said he thought Microsoft had ``probably flexed as far as they were
going to'' during the four-month settlement talks that ended on
April 1. At the end of those talks, the two sides remained far
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Klein announced on Wednesday evening that the Justice Department
would seek to route Microsoft's appeal directly to the Supreme
Court, under a 1974 revision of federal antitrust laws that allows
direct appeals in cases of national significance.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom responded that Microsoft would oppose such an effort to
``try to circumvent an appeal to the Court of Appeals,'' where the
company believes it will receive more favorable treatment. He also
suggested that the Supreme Court might not accept the case because
it had agreed only once before to take an expedited appeal of an
antitrust case, during the suit against AT&AMP;T in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Klein acknowledged that expedited appeals were rare. But he also
said that since 1974, AT&AMP;T's was the only antitrust case of true
national significance that had been in the federal courts. ``So the
paucity of precedent, I think, actually reinforces the government's
view that the act was designed precisely for this kind of case,''
Klein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
