<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8576 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SENATE-ART-735(2TAKES     06-08 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-ART-735(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES STEP TO OVERHAUL CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4 and NYT5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday approved a measure to
require the growing number of tax-exempt groups that now secretly
raise and spend unlimited sums on political activities to disclose
their contributors and spending.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the legislation sponsored by Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., was the first since 1993 in which the Senate approved an
important tightening of campaign finance laws. It and could give
unexpected momentum to a similar measure that the House will vote
on Friday, despite opposition from Republican leaders. It could
also enhance the prospects for McCain's proposed ban on
unrestricted donations called soft money.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday's decisive procedural motion, senators refused by a
57-42 vote to defeat the measure. The margin surprised even McCain
and his chief Democratic allies, Russell Feingold of Wisconsin and
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. In an embarrassing rebuke to
Majority Leader Trent Lott, 14 Republicans voted with 43 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end, this is the beginning,'' said McCain,
beaming and ebullient after his triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote on a second major issue, senators defeated a sweeping
bill to overhaul the nation's managed care system. The vote, 51-48,
was largely along party lines, with most Republicans opposing the
measure and all the Democrats supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters said the vote could doom all hope this year for
Congress to pass bipartisan legislation on managed care. Senate and
House negotiators have been stalled for months on hammering out a
compromise. But Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, vowed that
backers would ``keep trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the managed care and campaign finance measures were
permitted as amendments to a $310 billion Pentagon budget bill. For
the last few weeks, the Senate has been locked in a battle over how
to conduct its business, highlighted by a shouting match on the
floor between Lott and Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate returned this week from a 10-day recess, the two
leaders seemed chastened by the gridlock, and have been working to
patch up their differences. But it is a fragile peace that could
collapse at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both understand that we have got a job to do,'' Daschle
told reporters before the votes Thursday. ``We have to run the
Senate in a way that accommodates not only our caucus interests,
but the interests of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote Thursday marked a new tack by McCain and his allies to
translate his new national prominence from his unsuccessful
presidential race into traction on his signature issue of
overhauling the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   By seizing on a device used by groups large and small, liberal
and conservative, that try to avoid the donor disclosure laws,
McCain picked an issue that could not be challenged on
constitutional grounds, like his proposed ban on unrestricted
donations called soft money.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires a growing number of political organizations
formed under an obscure part of the Internal Revenue Code known as
Section 527 to follow federal campaign law and file tax returns and
disclose a list of their contributors and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 was created in 1975, after the Watergate scandal, to
establish tax rules for political organizations, like the national
political parties and political action committees. But unlike these
new secretive groups, parties and PACs register with the Federal
Election Commission, which requires them to disclose their donors
and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of the groups exist, from those affiliated with the
Sierra Club to organizations with close ties to Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, the majority whip. The groups raise money, buy television
and radio ads, conduct polling, work on issues and conduct other
political activities.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message sent before Thursday's vote to 200,000 of
his supporters nationwide, McCain tried to tap into the same fervor
that propelled his Straight Talk Express candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stood by my side throughout our quest for the White
House,'' McCain said. ``Now today, I am asking for your help to
fight one more battle. As you can imagine, this move is being
vehemently opposed by the big money fat cats who have grown quite
comfortable throwing their millions around in secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said after the vote, ``There's no question that John
McCain's campaign had a lot to do with what happened today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bill mostly sidestepped a fight on the merits of
the measure, retreating behind procedural arguments and warnings of
damage to national security to oppose the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Two Senate Republicans, John Warner of Virginia and James Inhofe
of Oklahoma, praised the substance of McCain's amendment, but said
its passage would doom the entire military bill.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the House Ways and Means Committee warned
Thursday that the amendment amounted to a revenue measure because
it involved possible changes in the tax status of political groups.
Under the Constitution all revenue bills must originate in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have my vote,'' said Warner, chairman of the Armed
Services Committee. ``But this amendment will torpedo this bill and
send it to the bottom of the sea where only Davey Jones could
resurrect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly furious, McCain called the tactic ``a red herring'' that
exposed Republicans' claims to be champions of campaign disclosure
as hypocritical. ``The American people will see through this,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents' arguments backfired badly as supporters clearly were
willing to take the risk that the House would return the bill
unread. Several of the 14 Republicans who defied their leadership,
including Spencer Abraham of Michigan and Conrad Burns of Montana,
have not supported changes in campaign finance law in the past, but
face tough re-election races this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The measure still faces the possible constitutional challenge in
the House. McCain said if the bill was returned, the campaign
finance measure could be stripped off and attached to another bill.
McCain said he was open to a suggestion made by Lott after the vote
to negotiate an even broader disclosure amendment that could
withstand House scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks will take place in the next few days. Until then
Thursday's action stands as senators' most important action on
campaign finance law since 1993, when a Democrat-controlled Senate
in tightened several parts of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats were also instrumental in forcing Thursday's
vote on the managed care legislation. They persuaded four
Republicans to side with them _ two more than last year _ and came
very close to a majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the clearest message that we are going to get a bill
this year,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who shepherded
the bill through the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was identical to the one passed by the House with
bipartisan support last October. It would give patients the right
to sue their health maintenance organizations and would set uniform
national standards for health insurance. The Senate passed its own
Republican-sponsored version last July, offering fewer protections
to fewer people, two important differences that have proved
insurmountable so far to House and Senate negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy called the negotiations a ``charade'' and said the two
sides had made so little progress in reaching a compromise that
Democrats felt compelled to force the House bill on the floor.
President Clinton also weighed in, expressing disappointment with
the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans, infuriated by the Democrats' course of
action, called the move a political ploy and said it all but doomed
bipartisan legislation for the year. Instead, Republicans said they
would draft their own bill and pass it with Republican votes if
they had to, even if that meant Clinton would veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Most Senate Republicans dislike the House bill, which the
insurance industry opposes, saying it would lead to runaway
lawsuits, raise premiums and put employers out of business. They
would like a bill narrower in scope, one that would restrict
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats counter that the ability to sue is critical to making
health maintenance organizations accountable for their decisions.
They say they will continue to negotiate and will try to force the
issue back on the floor, if need be. The American Medical
Association backs the House bill.
</P>
<P>
   Framing Thursday's defeat as a victory, Democrats said they were
now one vote short of success. And by forcing Republicans to vote
on the bill, they hope to be able to portray them on the campaign
trail as beholden to the insurance industry and unwilling to
address consumer concerns about managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we really want a bill, Republicans are going to have to
write this bill and pass it,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, one
of the negotiators. ``The Democrats want a political issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
