<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ROCKER0609-COX     06-08 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker shows in Toledo
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ So much for John Rocker's threat to become a
stockbroker. Atlanta's demoted closer began his minor-league
rehabilitation Thursday, beating the 72-hour deadline with time to
spare.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who had told an Atlanta radio station that he was
considering quitting, reported to the Class AAA Richmond Braves for
the middle game of a three-game International League series against
the Toledo Mud Hens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to never believe anything a player says when he's
first sent down,'' Atlanta assistant general manager Frank Wren
said. ``They are always upset, just like John was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was cheered loudly by most of the crowd of more than
6,000 as he walked across the field to the Richmond dugout before
the game. Then he stopped to sign autographs for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to protect him if he needed it,'' said 80-year-old
Eloise Duncan, a Atlanta Braves fan from Pemberville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker did not pitch in the lopsided Toledo victory or talk to
the media contingent of more than 100. He is likely to pitch
tonight, when the series concludes. Then Richmond goes to Columbus,
Ohio, for two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he pitches once, hopefully all the TV cameras go
away,'' Wren said. ``This has taken a toll on him. You can see
there is stress there. Once he got his uniform on and got out on
the field, his whole demeanor changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker wore No. 43 instead of his usual No. 49 as he threw in
the bullpen for 20 minutes before the game. The Braves hope he can
regain the control that had deserted him recently as the
controversy surrounding him mounted.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was sent to the minors the day after he threatened Jeff
Pearlman, the writer of the infamous Sports Illustrated article
that turned the pitcher's life around. The Braves fined Rocker
$5,000 for his conduct toward the reporter, but said he was being
sent down to the minors because of his pitching problems.
</P>
<P>
   Of the last 18 batters Rocker had faced, 12 reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker allowed 18 hits and 25 walks in 18 2/3 innings. During
his side session before the game with Richmond pitching coach Mike
Alvarez, Rocker still had problems controlling his fastball. After
one bad pitch, he bellowed a loud obscenity that could be heard
throughout parts of the mostly empty stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker arrived at the stadium nearly four hours for the 7 p.m
game and renewed some old acquaintances in the Richmond clubhouse.
Toby Rumfield caught Rocker several times in spring training,
including his first game back after an arbitrator reduced the
original suspension and fine for the Sports Illustrated article.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a bunch of us, he's a friend,'' Rumfield said. ``There
won't be any problems in our clubhouse. We'll welcome him and kid
about all the attention we're getting. As far as I'm concerned,
he's the best lefty in the bullpen there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Said third baseman Wes Helms: ``He needs to feel welcome and
confortable. We want him to do well here and get back to the major
leagues. That's where he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Andy Barkett is new to the Braves organization and
had never met Rocker. ``I introduced myself and welcomed him to the
team. I'll pull for him like any other teammate. We are all here to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said Wednesday he might give up baseball and become a
stockbroker. But he caught a 10:35 a.m. Delta flight Thursday and
arrived in Toledo at 12:20 p.m. More than a half dozen television
camera crews were there to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Titkemeier, 19, of Port Orange, Fla. couldn't believe
Rocker was on his flight. Titkemeier was coming up to visit his
grandmother and was already going to Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slept part of the way and talked on his phone when he
could,'' Titkemeier said. ``Then he signed some autographs after we
landed. I'm a big fan. I told him to go get them.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-car escort from the Lucas County Sherriff's Department
accompanied Rocker, riding in a red Buick Sable, to the Toledo
Holiday Inn West, the team's hotel. He eluded camera crews by going
in a side door.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight at Ned Skeldon Stadium. A half dozen
uniformed police officers were stationed on the field and the
walkway that players take to get to the field was blocked off to
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Booz of Toledo came to the game hopeful of seeing Rocker
pitch. ``I've followed the Braves since they won 13 straight to
start 1982,'' he said. ``I'm afraid that all the pressure and
conflict has got to Rocker's pitching. I hope he can pitch like he
used to. Atlanta needs him.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few fans seemed to be ready to heckle Rocker. One sign in
the bleachers near the Richmond bullpen read, ``Jeff Pearlman Fan
Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
