<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8579 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     06-08 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODEN SPILLS ALL TO WALTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There will never be a time, says Bill Walton, when
he sits down with John Wooden and doesn't learn something new.
</P>
<P>
   But the visit Walton had Monday with the former UCLA basketball
coach at his condo in Encino darn near left him speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Which, as you can guess, is almost impossible these days.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Hoosiers vs. Hollywood'' theme that NBC has given to these
Pacers-Lakers NBA Finals is practically a script of the life of
Wooden, a Hall of Fame player from Purdue who came out to coach
UCLA in the 1940s and created the Bruin mystique.
</P>
<P>
   Off an afternoon-long interview Walton did in the capacity of
NBC reporter, the network will air a comparable sliver before and
at halftime of Sunday's Game 3 coverage from Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Walton says, it's all on tape and will provide an
exceptional piece of archival footage of Wooden's life - as only he
can explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most incredible times I've ever spent with
him,'' said Walton on Thursday from his home in San Diego where he
gets to go between Games 1 and 2 from Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we generally do these kind of features, we spend maybe
20, 30 minutes with the person. He sat there without getting up
from his chair or even asking for a glass of water for 2 hours -
and he was going stronger than ever by the end. He never once
stopped and asked to redo an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always reluctant to talk about himself, but I was asking
one-sentence questions and he'd go on and never stop. It was an
incredible performance for anyone, let alone someone who's 89 years
old. He's a saint.''
</P>
<P>
   In this rare personal insight, Wooden talks about life growing
up on a farm in Indiana without electricity or running water, how
his mother handmade the basketballs he played with, how his love
for poetry came from his father reading to him by the gas lamp, and
the pain he experienced when he couldn't be near his father at the
time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a chance none of that makes the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, maybe more newsworthy, is Wooden's take on the
Bob Knight situation (``I've said that I wouldn't want anyone dear
to me to play for him, but that's because of his language; he's
very profane''), his view on the changes in Reggie Miller from
college to the pros (``A lot of things with Reggie I didn't like
when he was at UCLA'') and why he never cared to coach in the NBA
(``I didn't think you have real control.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saving everything,'' Walton said of the interview,
which unfortunately has to be edited down for broadcast. ``At least
between NBC and CNBC and MSNBC, it'll all get out there. It was an
incredible thing to experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking the line: The Associated Press reported Thursday that
three of Walton's four sons - Nathan, Chris and Luke - were seen
wearing NBC press credentials before Game 1, which gave them access
to areas such as the Pacers' locker room. They greeted Pacers coach
Larry Bird, a former teammate of Walton's with the Boston Celtics,
as he entered the building for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm wrong (for doing that),'' Walton admitted, ``but I
don't get to see my kids too much - I fly 650,000 miles a year -
and they don't get out to too many games. Larry was instrumental in
their lives and to be able to take them to meet up with him to
renew that friendship was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NBC says no, well, then they can't be there, or even ride
to the game in the car with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stoners unite: Bob Costas, in his third and final year as
the NBA Finals play-by-play guy before he gives it back to Marv
Albert, loves to hear theories about how NBC has tried to
orchestrate a particular Finals scenario with the NBA to get better
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Such as those who knew an L.A.-New York final was going to
happen. Then didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NBA had a conspiracy theory,'' Costas said, ``it failed
in the Eastern Conference finals and it was a real case of
brinkmanship in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the plan would have been, let's see if we can have
the team we prefer to have win go down 16 points and have to rely
on a banked-in 3-pointer, have to rely on the other team missing
open shots rather than officials calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the league was interested in cahoots with NBC or
anybody else in engineering an outcome, they wouldn't take it on
the brink that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can see that many perceive the NBA has an ulterior
motive?
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone is inclined to believe that, possibly because
they're rooting for the team that is on the short end or if their
team isn't in it, they resent the New Yorks and the Los Angeleses.
And we understand that syndrome. If they are inclined to believe
that, then any fragment of evidence will be used to support it.
That's just human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the way people filter information and perceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   More myths, half-truths and flat-out lies: The 2-3-2 format for
the NBA Finals as opposed to the 2-2-1-1-1 used in the earlier
rounds isn't anything new - it's been in place since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   And while it was done as a function of helping the media, print
reporters rather than TV networks are the people whose best
interests were being watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at all because of TV,'' said NBA senior VP of
communications Brian McIntyre. ``It started back in the 1980s
because of the constant cross-country trips that had to be made
with the Lakers and Celtics facing each other. It was to cut down
on player travel. The byproduct of it was that newspaper budgets
couldn't always afford to send reporters back and forth, so with
this format, we actually picked up more media.''
</P>
<P>
   How many more? The NBA hasn't counted the number of credentials
issued for the series and wouldn't offer a ballpark figure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -Number crunching for those who care: NBC's ratings for Game 1
was 12.8 with a 21 share, a nine-percent increase over last year's
Game 1 between San Antonio and New York. L.A. registered a 28.7
rating and 44 share - actually, a drop from the 29.4/51 who tuned
in to the Lakers' Game 7 win over Portland. But little-ol'-Indiana
did a 39.6/56 for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   -Did you know: Hannah Storm, NBC's NBA studio maven, has to be
the best network resource on Indiana Pacers history. Her father,
Mike Storen, was the original Pacers GM when they began in the ABA
in 1967-68 and even picked out the team colors and logo. He went on
to become the ABA commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   -Jim Rome's tour stop at Blossom Music Center in Cleveland on
Saturday will be taped to show on Fox Sports Net on July 12 at 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -NBC's celeb cams picked off Gabe Kaplan, Tony Dow (Wally from
``Leave It To Beaver'') and horse trainer Bob Baffert during their
Game 1 let's-go-to-the-fourth-quarter montage. Sure, a welcome
break from Dyan Cannon's stretched-beyond-recognition facial, but
what a way to cheapen a big-time event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
