<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0609-COX     06-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mystery muddled by a man in mink
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The prosecution, after 11 days of testimony, 40
witnesses and a deal that sprung its celebrity defendant, rested
Thursday in the Buckhead stabbings trial.
</P>
<P>
   The two remaining defendants called but one witness between them
and took a little more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony further helped muddle an already confusing case
for the jury, dramatically introducing a mysterious attacker in
mink.
</P>
<P>
   The defense witness testified he threw a man wearing a fur coat
off mortally wounded Jacinth Baker on a Buckhead street and heard
the man mutter, ``I stabbed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Keven Brown, a hulking bodyguard dressed in black, said the man
was holding Baker by the back of the neck and punching him in the
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was stroking him pretty nice,'' testified Brown, giving a
matter-of-fact account of the beating. ``He was wearing a black fur
coat.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither of the remaining defendants in the case _ Reginald
Oakley, 31, of Baltimore, and Joseph Sweeting, 34, of Miami _ wore
a fur coat that night. Oakley called Brown to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard, doing what defense attorneys have
done to him during the first three weeks of the trial, turned the
oppositon's witness into one of his own. Howard's cross-examination
of Brown helped bolster testimony earlier this week by NFL star Ray
Lewis who said he saw Oakley and limo passenger Carlos Stafford
beating Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown did not identify Oakley, Howard is sure to argue
that the second man Brown said he saw beating Baker was Oakley.
Brown testified he was ``90 percent'' sure the man he pushed off
Baker was Stafford, who has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he met Stafford briefly outside the Cobalt nightclub
minutes before the melee. Stafford, a law school student from
Houston, was unable to negiotiate an immunity agreement with
prosecutors in exchange for his testimony. Stafford, through his
attorney, denies attacking anyone during the fight.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown said the attacker wearing the black fur coat had
braided hair. Stafford has been identified in testimony as wearing
a black fur coat that night. His hair was not braided. Sweeting had
braided hair but he and Oakley are being tried for attacking
different men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever it may have been, it was not Reginald Oakley,''
Oakley's lawyer Bruce Harvey said outside the courtroom. ``Reginald
Oakley did not stab anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   To further confuse jurors, Richard Lollar, the other man stabbed
to death that night, had a hair from a mink coat in his hand.
Lollar, 24, and Baker, 21, were killed Jan. 31 during a brawl after
a night of post Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are set to begin this morning and the jury
consisting of 10 women and two men should start deliberating by
early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he left the Cobalt nightclub, having escorted his
client to his car, and was driving home in his gold Honda Civic
down East Paces Ferry Road just minding his own business. But Brown
said he noticed a group of people fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Brown stopped in the street in front of Baker who was ``running
for his life,'' he said. Baker was being beaten to the ground by
the man in the fur coat when another man came up and pulled on
Baker's leg and kicked him, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an all-out brawl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little man was on the ground trying to cover up,'' Brown
said. The 5-foot-3, 146-pound Baker initially fought back but when
he went down on the pavement ``he basically looked like he was
unconscious,'' the bodyguard testified.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he yelled at the men to stop and then pushed the man
in the fur coat off. This man and the other attacker, he testified,
ran away toward Lewis' stretch Lincoln Navigator limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he also looked down the street and saw Lollar under
attack. Moments later, Brown said he saw Lollar walk slowly toward
Baker's body, stand there for a few seconds and then fall over
backward onto the street. The medical examiner earlier testified
that Lollar could have lived for at least 45 seconds after being
stabbed in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Howard tried to persuade Brown into
admitting the ``I stabbed him'' comment might not have come from
the man wearing the black fur coat. But Brown stood firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three people: me, the guy I pushed and the guy
lying on the ground,'' he responded. ``I didn't say it. The guy on
the ground didn't say it. It was the guy I pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's testimony was ironic in that the ``I stabbed him''
admission came from a defense witness. In his opening statement,
Howard promised jurors that limo driver Duane Fassett would testify
he overheard both Oakley and Sweeting say, ``I stabbed mine,'' as
the Lincoln Navigator sped away from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett never delivered that statement in a dramatic meltdown on
the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Like that of many witnesses before him, Brown's testimony, while
confident and direct, was not without contradiction and
inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Brown testified the man in the fur coat, who he believed to be
Stafford, had braided hair.
</P>
<P>
   Howard called a rebuttal witness, Brian Johnson, who testified
he knew Stafford and had seen him Super Bowl night. Stafford did
not have braided hair that evening, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Bonner dismissed some of the charges, granting
partial directed verdicts of acquittal in favor of Oakley and
Sweeting. She dismissed murder, felony murder and aggravated
assault charges against Oakley for Richard Lollar's killing. She
did the same for Sweeting in connection with Baker's killing.
</P>
<P>
   But now the prosecution cannot argue now that Oakley and
Sweeting were part of a joint attack, said Jack Martin, a prominent
defense lawyer not involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means each defendant will be held responsible for what they
personally did,'' Martin said. ``It also means that the
prosecution's original theory never panned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's ruling, in reality, has little impact. If convicted of
murder or felony murder, Oakley and Sweeting will be sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
