<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MAN-WOMEN-SLAY-NYT &LR;      06-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-WOMEN-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET MAN WITH AN UNSAVORY SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JO THOMAS with ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ John Edward Robinson Sr., 56, was a quiet man who
mowed his grass three times a week and grilled the hamburgers at a
neighborhood cookout two weeks ago. But the police say he had a
second life as well, using the Internet to lure women for violent
sex that went bad for the women involved.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after two women complained that Robinson, who the
authorities say called himself ``slavemaster'' on the Internet, had
assaulted and robbed them at local hotels, the police arrested him.
Over the weekend, they began to make a series of grisly
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   A search of a farm Robinson owns in LaCygne, Kan., south of
Kansas City, yielded two barrels, sitting outdoors, swathed in
plastic. Inside were the bodies of two women. A second search, of
three storage units he rented in nearby Raymore, Mo., yielded three
more 55-gallon drums and three more bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the women, Suzette Marie Trouten, 28, of Monroe
County, Mich., has been identified. The authorities say Trouten met
Robinson on the Internet. And as the investigation widens, the
police have linked Robinson to four other women and a baby who have
also disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Morrison, the Johnson County district attorney who filed
the assault charges against Robinson, is now leading a two-state
task force investigating his activities. Morrison said he expects
to file more charges against Robinson, who is being held under a $5
million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's lawyer, Byron Cerrillo, said his client would plead
not guilty to the sexual assault charges and to any murder charges
that might be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent the fact that people are now claiming that Mr.
Robinson, either directly or indirectly, is a serial killer,''
Cerrillo said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Detective David Brown, the Lenexa, Kan., policeman acting as a
spokesman for the task force, said the police had been
investigating Robinson's connection to Trouten when they received
the assault complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon LaPrad, owner of LaPrad Home Care in Monroe, Mich., 35
miles south of Detroit, had employed Trouten for much of the past
decade as a nurse's aide working in the homes of dying and
convalescing patients.
</P>
<P>
   LaPrad said her employee had been contacted last year through an
Internet chat room by a man who offered her a job. Trouten was
lured to her death by promises of a $62,000-a-year job as nurse and
companion for her supposed patron's ``elderly father,'' LaPrad
said.
</P>
<P>
   The job, Trouten was told, would last about a year and offered
world travel, a month off after every two months of traveling, plus
all expenses and extensive health and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Trouten made two trips to Kansas, in October and November, to
look into the job and her prospective employer, and she returned
impressed with what she saw, LaPrad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked her up at the airport in a limousine,'' LaPrad
recalled in a telephone interview. ``She told me he lived in a
mansion. She said she saw the mansion and a guest house. She said
it was something else.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPrad said she personally was skeptical, as were other friends
of Trouten. ``It sounded too good to be true,'' LaPrad said. ``But
she was so confident. `This is on the up and up,' she said.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Trouten, who was single and had no children, left
the Newport, Mich., home she shared with her mother, Carolyn, took
her two Pekinese dogs and drove to Kansas. On Feb. 27, LaPrad said,
she received an e-mail message from Trouten saying she had arrived
with her dogs after a 14-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Trouten's mother received an e-mail message from
her daughter saying she had checked into a motel. A few days later,
Carolyn Trouten received another e-mail message, this one from the
man who had supposedly employed her. It said that Trouten would be
gone for about two months, and it gave an itinerary that did not
provide details.
</P>
<P>
   The mother became suspicious and called the police, LaPrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the other missing women linked to Robinson
include Paula Godfrey, 19, reported missing on Sept. 1, 1984;
Katherine Clampet, 27, reported missing June 5, 1987; Izabela K.
Lewicka, 22, a Polish immigrant who has been missing since last
fall; and Lisa Stasi, 19, who disappeared with her 5-month-old
baby, Tiffany, on Jan. 11, 1985. All of the women were living or
staying in Overland Park, Kan., at the time they vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Citing investigators' reports from 1985, the Kansas City Star
said Stasi was staying in a domestic violence shelter at the time
she met Robinson. The newspaper reported that the police believed
Robinson promised to help her go to Texas to train for work as a
silk-screen printer. He also offered her $800 a month for living
expenses and promised to find her a baby-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Later, according to the newspaper, a lawyer representing
Robinson told the police that Stasi had decided to take care of
herself, and Robinson told the police she had moved to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not disclose any details about the earlier
investigations or provide information about Godfrey, Clampet, or
Lewicka.
</P>
<P>
   At Store-Mor For Less in Raymor, Mo., where the police found
three bodies in Robinson's 10-by-15-foot unit, a manager who asked
that her name not be used said the Robinsons rented three units in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's wife, Nancy, rented the first storage unit in May,
1993, and Robinson rented two more units in November or December,
1993, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me his sister Beverly had gone to work for his
company, Equi II, and he was storing her furniture. She supposedly
had gone to Australia. The last time I saw him, he was saying that
she was in Italy. He said, `She's having a ball. I don't think
she'll ever return.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has a lengthy criminal record of theft and fraud. He
was sent to prison in Kansas in May, 1986. In 1991, he was paroled
and sent to Missouri to serve a sentence for theft. He was paroled
there in March, 1993. He then moved to Olathe. His wife managed the
mobile home park where they lived.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Timmons, 79, the Robinsons' next-door neighbor in a mobile
home park in Olathe, recalled that Robinson ``kept his yard
immaculate. He had elaborate decorations on all the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed he was retired,'' Timmons said. ``He looks older
than he is. They had grown children and at least one grandchild.
There was a sign outside that said `Grandpa's place. We Spoil
Grandchildren.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
