<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FREELOAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STUDY DETAILS POPULARITY OF INTERNET MUSIC  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Demonstrating that Napster-style ``freeloading''
isn't just a college fad, 42 percent of U.S. Internet users who
download free copies of songs are between the ages of 30 and 49,
according to a new study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the independent Pew Research Center found that 13
million people, or 14 percent of American Internet users of all
ages, are projected as ``freeloaders,'' defined as people who
download music they don't already own.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps just as disturbing for the big recording companies, only
2 percent of all Internet users have actually paid for music they
have downloaded, said the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``One conclusion you could draw is that Americans love free
stuff,'' said Amanda Lenhart, the main author of the study
conducted by Pew Internet &AMP; American Life Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``But another thing is that Napster in less than a year has
taken one of the major industries (recording) and got it running
scared,'' Lenhart said. ``It's forcing people to think about new
ways of marketing, new ways of selling music.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies by groups like Webnoize and Greenfield Online
have detailed how sweepingly popular Internet music, especially use
of the Napster sharing program, is among college students.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest study by Pew, a nonprofit public policy research
organization sponsored by the Pew Charitable Trusts, is the first
to detail what music industry observers already knew from anecdotal
evidence _ that the popularity of downloadable and streaming music
is rapidly cutting across a wide swath of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Pew commissioned a monthlong telephone survey of 2,503 people
during April. Of the total, 1,345 were Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found:
</P>
<P>
   -- 38 percent of all Internet users, about 35 million Americans,
have enjoyed online music, either by downloading files or listening
to songs streamed from Internet radio stations or online services.
Still, the other 62 percent of all Net users have never downloaded
or listened to music online.
</P>
<P>
   -- Internet radio and streaming music files draw a larger
audience, about 15 million, than downloading. And this audience,
which the study calls ``samplers,'' is generally older, with 46
percent between the ages of 30 and 49 and 20 percent over 50.
</P>
<P>
   -- Only 2 percent of Internet users paid for downloadable music,
while another 3 percent downloaded free copies of music they
already owned.
</P>
<P>
   -- About 13 million have downloaded free songs using file
sharing programs like Napster or Gnutella. About half were between
the ages of 18 and 29, but 42 percent were aged 30 to 49, while 9
percent were 50 or older.
</P>
<P>
   -- Men (64 percent) were more likely to download songs into
their computers. But more women (52 percent) preferred sampling
songs through Web radio and streaming audio services.
</P>
<P>
   -- Napster users in April offered an average of 100 music files
each. Using the San Mateo company's claim that it has registered 10
million users since August 1999, a number that took America Online
six years to achieve, Pew researchers estimated there were as many
as 1 billion songs available from Napster users.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America, major independent
record label TVT Records Inc., and individual artists Dr. Dre and
Metallica have all sued Napster Inc. claiming songs offered by its
users violate federal copyright protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pew study called them ``freeloaders,'' the term is
a contraction of ``free'' and ``downloaders'' and not meant as a
pejorative term, Lenhart said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in follow up interviews, the Pew researchers found some
freeloaders were still buying CD copies of new songs they
downloaded and enjoyed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to take sides here,'' she said. ``The point
of this report is to get the facts out there to better inform the
debate between the various parties involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard E. King, the Los Angeles attorney who represents both Dr.
Dre and Metallica in their suits against Napster, said the Pew
study showed how daunting a task it is control piracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard not to hear those numbers and realize how
significant the issue is no matter which side of the issue you're
on,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
