r s BC-FBN-KLOSTERMAN-LADN     06-08 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KLOSTERMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DUKE OF DEL REY' DEFINED SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE JARES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The L.A. Rams ran off to St. Louis. The L.A.
Chargers long ago charged to San Diego. The L.A. Express expired.
Loyola University dropped football and renamed itself Loyola
Marymount.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Los Angeles had a dapper, congenial, intelligent
reminder of those days and teams in the person of Don Klosterman.
</P>
<P>
   Until late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man nicknamed ``The Duke of Del Rey'' for his Loyola
quarterbacking exploits died at age 70, a few weeks after
undergoing triple-bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best, the bravest man I know,'' said L.A.
advertising executive Dennis Holt. ``Scores and scores of people
considered him their best friend. I can picture him holding court
at the 'A' table at the Polo Lounge in the Beverly Hills Hotel, but
he was deeper than that. Just a week or so ago he helped me get a
poor kid a two-thirds scholarship to Loyola.''
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman was best known as a pro football general manager. In
that role, he was summed up nicely by writer Dan Jenkins in Sports
Illustrated:
</P>
<P>
   ``... the most visible, capable and popular of general managers,
who seems to have been born to speak fluent Grambling, to date
lovely ladies, to know most of the world's maitre d's and to build
football winners for rich guys....''
</P>
<P>
   He worked for K.S. ``Bud'' Adams (Houston Oilers), Carroll
Rosenbloom and later his widow, Georgia Frontiere (L.A. Rams),
Barron Hilton (L.A. Chargers), Bill Oldenburg (L.A. Express of the
USFL) and Lamar Hunt (Kansas City Chiefs). Everywhere he earned
respect.
</P>
<P>
   In 22 of his 25 years in the pro game, the team for which he
worked made the playoffs. Perhaps the peak was the Baltimore Colts
team that won Super Bowl V.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Rams had an excellent draft,'' Chiefs coach Hank
Stram said in 1981. ``But then any time Don Klosterman has anything
to do with selecting players, it is bound to turn out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Old-time sports fans might prefer to remember Klosterman the
athlete, the relatively small (5-foot-11, 180) quarterback out of
Compton High (one of 15 children) who was turned down by Notre Dame
and ended up at little Loyola, on the cliffs overlooking Marina del
Rey.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great break for Loyola and its coach, Jordan Olivar, in
an era when small colleges in California fielded excellent football
teams, led by such athletes as Ollie Matson and Gino Marchetti at
USF and Eddie LeBaron and Dick Bass at Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions went 8-1 in 1950, the only loss coming to Santa Clara,
which went on to beat Kentucky in the Orange Bowl. That year, the
Duke of Del Rey completed 26 passes for 355 yards against Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Against Florida in his senior year, 1951, he completed 33 passes
for 372 yards. He finished with eight NCAA passing records
(including most passes attempted and completed in a single game,
single season and career), all since broken.
</P>
<P>
   After the 35-33 victory over Pacific in 1951, a local
sportswriter rhapsodized:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Klosterman, the confident and capable field general of
the Lions who scaled the heights of greatness last night, pulling
the team behind him in the rugged uphill struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   His days as a pro quarterback were not so glorious. He was the
first-round pick of the Cleveland Browns but was traded to the
Dallas Texans and then the L.A. Rams, where he was stuck behind two
Hall of Famers, Bob Waterfield and Norm Van Brocklin, in 1952. He
spent two years in the Air Force, then played for the Calgary
Stampeders in the CFL.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Patrick's Day 1957, he suffered a broken back in a ski
accident near Banff and was told by one doctor that he'd never walk
again. But after eight operations, a year in the hospital and 18
months of recuperation, he did. He even danced.
</P>
<P>
   After a short time in insurance (with his old coach, Olivar), he
got into pro football administration with the Chargers. Among his
many feats in his executive years: signing quarterback Steve Young
for the Express.
</P>
<P>
   The USFL was a flop, but Klosterman had other good moments apart
from the Young signing. Handling owner Bill Oldenburg was perhaps
the toughest chore. After a horrible game in Denver, Oldenburg was
ready to fire the coach, John Hadl.
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman, used to the ``rich guys'' referred to by Jenkins,
sat down with his upstart, impatient owner:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Well,' the GM recalled saying, `we have a rookie team, a
rookie coach and a rookie owner. The resolution of the problem is
that you should take a six-week Valium. Come back and your team'll
be in good shape.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and said, 'OK.' He took off and made his
plane, and he didn't come back to see us in a game for six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman almost always could make such a tricky situation turn
out well. His disposition was naturally sunny.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in serious financial trouble, he never gave it
away,'' said his friend, Holt. ``Most of us would show it. With him
there never was a furrowed brow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLE-SFCH     06-08 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 JUSTICE OPENS DOOR TO MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the dust settled on a court order to split
Microsoft, the Justice Department indicated a willingness to
rekindle settlement talks, while the company _ and an outside study
_ affirmed a breakup would cause ``grievous'' harm to millions of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``is prepared to engage in meaningful settlement
negotiations'' to avoid a potentially lengthy appeals process
sparked by Wednesday's ruling, Joel I. Klein, head of the U.S.
Justice Department's antitrust division, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company would have to agree not ``to abuse its monopoly
power,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   But an unbowed Microsoft greeted Klein's comments with more than
a little skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Klein is posturing,'' company spokesman Jim Cullinan said
in an interview. ``We'd always be interested in reaching a fair and
reasonable settlement. But it's become clear from the behavior of
the government that they're bent on breaking this company up
regardless of the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of an accord was touched off by recent comments from U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, the judge overseeing the
case. Last fall the judge prodded the two sides to settle and in
his ruling Wednesday he revisited the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The two-way split ``is perhaps more radical than might have
resulted had mediation been successful and terminated in a consent
decree,'' the judge wrote in an opinion that accompanied the
breakup order. The order, essentially the same plan proposed by the
Justice Department and 17 states suing the company, calls for
dividing Microsoft down the middle. One firm would develop the
various Windows operating systems, and the other would control
everything else including Microsoft Office, Internet Explorer, MSN
and cable network MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which Microsoft immediately vowed to appeal, is
intended as a remedy to the software giant's antitrust violations.
On April 3, Jackson ruled in the government's favor, saying the
company illegally wielded its operating systems monopoly in an
effort to crush competitors. That, in turn, quashed innovation in
the software industry and hurt consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has insisted throughout the two-year antitrust trial
that it does not maintain a monopoly and has done nothing illegal.
Yesterday the company asked Jackson's decree be set aside until its
appeal is heard. The company is confident the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia, which sided with the software giant
in an earlier case, will overturn Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Although the D.C. court is next in line to hear the case, the
Department of Justice is seeking an expedited review by the U.S.
Supreme Court. The justices are not expected to decide whether to
hear the case for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Legal analysts are divided on whether the high court will take
the case. Many believe it will want to read the opinion of the
appellate court first, since that court has experience with
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's final ruling ``will inflict grievous and irreparable
harm on Microsoft, its 35,000 employees, its millions of
shareholders, its thousands of business partners and the tens of
millions of consumers around the world who rely on Microsoft's
products,'' Microsoft wrote in its request to stay the judge's
order.
</P>
<P>
   A report by an independent market research firm in Boston
apparently bolstered that contention _ at least on the financial
side.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Aberdeen Group, a Microsoft breakup would cost
businesses and consumers $43 billion over the 10-year duration of
the order. Businesses would pay an additional $20 billion to
integrate software from other vendors into their organizations. And
consumers would lose two ways: higher software prices or eroded
shareholder value if the two Microsofts experience lower profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no proof that a breakup will benefit consumers or
(technology) buyers or level the competitive playing field,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions fly in the face of the goals of the
government's remedy _ increasing competition which would, in turn,
spark more choices in the software marketplace and lower prices _
and seems to support Microsoft's position that the fallout would be
wide-ranging and detrimental to both businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is much debate over whether innovation will
flourish or whether consumers will pay less for software.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Aberdeen advocated Instead, a court-appointed panel of
business, technology and legal experts to advise the Redmond,
Wash., company on anti-competitive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Cullinan wouldn't comment on Aberdeen's conclusions but said the
company offered as witnesses economists, partners and its own
executives to testify about the impacts of a court-mandated
breakup. Jackson rejected that motion.
</P>
<P>
   But even he has indicated dissatisfaction with a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Washington Post, Jackson encouraged
both sides to ``swallow their own reluctance to compromise and
reach a remedy that both sides, if not elated by, nevertheless are
willing to extend.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had appointed a federal mediator to oversee talks
between the two sides in November. Those talks broke down in early
April, prompting Jackson's scathing ``conclusions of law.''
</P>
<P>
   A settlement would be ``in the interests of the industry (and)
it is in the interests of the company,'' as well as the nation,
Klein said at a Justice Department briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Klein declined to say whether the government would accept a
settlement that did not include a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say there's no procedural reason why the two sides
couldn't sit down together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, they could settle the case at any time _
tomorrow, next week, next month or next year,'' said Rich Gray, a
Silicon Valley anititrust attorney.
</P>
<P>
   However, most say the case will most likely move to another
courtroom rather than the settlement table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always surprises,'' said Richard Gilbert, a
University of California at Berkeley economics professor and former
chief economist for the Justice Department's antitrust division.
``But Microsoft has a lot to gain by going through the appeals
process and not much to lose. Plus, it's unlikely the government
would settle with terms that Microsoft would find acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has signaled willingness to some restrictions on its
behavior _ though not the ones spelled out in the remedy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the structural facet, Jackson's plan includes
strict curbs on the way the company conducts business. As soon as
September, Microsoft would have to release some of the Windows
``source code'' to software developers; in addition the company
would be prohibited from discriminatory pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is seeking to have those measures delayed until the
appeals process runs its course, which could take a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
