r f BC-CHILDCARE-SHORTAGE-SF     06-08 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-SHORTAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHILD CARE PROVIDERS CONSIDER JOINING UNION  &HT;     By JEFF ST. JOHN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's tough to find good, qualified child care
workers. Just ask Rosemary Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, she has run her child care service,
Rosie's Little School, from her home in San Francisco's Stonestown
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A licensed family child care provider, she cares for seven
children - two toddlers and five preschoolers - 12 hours a day,
five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six months, Kennedy has been looking for a
full-time worker to augment her mostly part-time, three-person
staff. Offering $9 an hour, a higher-than-average wage, she has
advertised through the newspapers, San Francisco State University
and City College job hotlines, and by word of mouth _ to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always students available,'' said Kennedy, ``but
it's impossible to find somebody for full-time, consistent, every
day, all-day care because of the low pay.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a persistent problem for child care providers because
many of them are women of color or recent immigrants, who are
struggling to make ends meet and increasingly leaving these jobs
for those offering higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The availability of quality, affordable child care is an
enormous problem in every county of the Bay Area. It's bad enough
statewide, but it is worse in the Bay Area because of the high cost
of living,'' said Patricia Siegel, president of the California
Child Care Resource and Referral Network in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a new element in the equation. Labor unions have
expressed interest in organizing child care workers in an effort to
improve their wages, benefits and training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a national crisis in child care,'' said Margaret
Brodkin, executive director of San Francisco nonprofit Coleman
Advocates for Youth and Children. ``It's reached a point where
child care workers are making less than parking lot attendants and
where one-third of the workers are leaving the field every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, Kennedy has gone to the San Francisco
Child Care Organizing Roundtable, searching for answers. The
Roundtable is a child care union forum hosted by Coleman Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month for the past eight months, the Roundtable has
brought child care providers together with representatives from the
American Federation of Teachers (AFT) and United Educators of San
Francisco (UESF), the Service Employees International Union (SEIU),
the Hotel and Restaurant Employees' Union and others.
</P>
<P>
   They are looking for a common solution to a shared crisis: the
lack of quality, affordable child care in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1999 report by the California Child Care Resource
and Referral Network, a child care worker in San Francisco earns on
the average $16,140 a year. With wages like this, it's not
surprising that about a third of all child care workers leave the
job every year, a turnover rate that takes its toll on the
availability and quality of child care for all families.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a year of infant child care in San Francisco
costs an average of $6,407 a year _ or more than half the annual
income of a minimum-wage earner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is a long list of low-income families seeking
state child care subsidies. On top of that, there aren't enough
licensed child care providers that qualify for the state program.
As a result, an estimated 58,961 children in San Francisco, or 68
percent of those who need it, are not receiving licensed child
care.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kennedy, child care providers are desperate to
resolve the crisis, even if it means taking a step into what is,
for most of them, the unknown world of union organizing.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, unions are interested in establishing
collective bargaining rights for child care workers that will lead
to better pay and benefits. The situation is sensitive, though,
because any improvement in the compensation package will ultimately
result in higher child care rates for working parents. Child care
providers are also worried that the entry of unions could lead to a
loss of control over personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest,'' Kennedy said, ``but everyone
wants to move slowly and carefully, because this is not a
traditional adversarial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Netsy Firestein, director of the University of California at
Berkeley's Labor Project for Working Families, has been working
with groups like the Roundtable from cities across the country. She
pointed out the difficulty of organizing a workforce in a field
where little additional money is available to enhance wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In child care, you can't go to your employer and ask for more
money,` Firestein said, ``because that money comes from paying
parents, who can't afford child care as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sheila Norman, director and owner of the Candlelight Child
Development Center in San Francisco's Outer Mission, this
overriding concern made her leery of union organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wearing two hats,'' Norman said. ``One is as an underpaid
and undercompensated child care provider, and the other is as a
small-business owner with employees who don't make enough either.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Norman said, she was worried that unions'
``outspoken'' way of approaching labor-management issues would
clash with the ``quiet, gentle'' manners of most child care center
directors.
</P>
<P>
   But after attending a few Roundtable meetings, she has come down
on the side of the unions. ``I think the profession would truly
benefit from organizing efforts,'' she said. ``It would help to
professionalize and legitimize the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the Roundtable is to find models for how this
might be accomplished. Last September, Seattle child care center
director Mike Kspirzak came to San Francisco to offer one..
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Kspirzak's Interlake Child Care and Learning
Center became the first in Seattle to recognize SEIU Local 925 as
the bargaining representative for its employees. Since then, Local
925 has signed contracts with 12 Seattle nonprofit child care
centers, representing more than 150 child care teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts resulted in a union pension plan for the teachers,
as well as a marked decrease in teacher turnover. Kspirzak said he
has not lost an employee since he signed the final contract six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that he didn't have initial concerns,
however.``I talked at some length about all the reasons why people
felt nervous about the process,'' Kspirzak said. ``The overriding
concern of the directors, as I saw it, was loss of control over
hiring and firing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, ``For the teachers, the overriding
interest was that they would be listened to and acknowledged as
partners in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Gibson, a key organizer for Local 925 in Seattle, said
her union brought teachers and center directors together to
negotiate a contract that took in the concerns of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't bargain with wages, or anything that has to do
with money,'' Gibson said. ``The standards we created were
lower-end programs. We didn't want to raise the bar too high.''
</P>
<P>
   The process worked, she said, because child care labor and
management had the same interests at heart: the children.
</P>
<P>
   For child care workers who belong to unions in San Francisco,
the benefits are clear.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the 600 or so child care workers employed in the San
Francisco Unified School District's Child Development Centers.
</P>
<P>
   These teachers and aides are members of the UESF, part of the
nationwide AFT. CDC teachers can earn up to $28,000 a year,
significantly higher than the average child care teacher's salary.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Atkinson, the AFT representative at the Roundtable, said
that UESF President Kent Mitchell has expressed interest in
organizing accredited child care teachers working in private
centers.
</P>
<P>
   However, part of the problem with using UESF model of organizing
other child care providers is the fact that UESF was able to win
its benefits through negotiations with a clear bargaining partner:
the school district and the San Francisco Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   For family child care providers, who work out of their homes and
are paid by parents through myriad government subsidy programs, the
issue of whom to bargain with, or against, is less clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, SEIU Local 250 won pay increases for 7,000
home care workers in San Francisco. But that agreement came about
only after the various state and county agencies with a hand in
childcare subsidies and referral services agreed to create an ad
hoc entity to take on the role of employer in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is nothing today in the way of a central bargaining
authority with the clout to represent the interests of the
employers and the various government programs involved in child
care services.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is no stranger to this problem. For the last three years
she has served as president of the San Francisco Family Child Care
Providers' Association, a grassroots organization representing 135
of the estimated 600 family child care providers in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping its members abreast of the ever-changing regulations
and applicable funding opportunities, the association has provided
a network for professionals with few other means of seeking out
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the unions are trying to show child care workers that
working together can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundtable likes to point out the successful cooperative
effort between unions and child care workers in San Francisco
earlier this year. That's when Coleman Advocates brought UESF
members and child care providers together to defeat Proposition 28,
which would have repealed last year's tobacco-tax measure
Proposition 10.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco County has used its Prop 10 funds to implement the
CARES program, which will provide $1.15 million in subsidies for
child care providers this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2213EDT &QL; 
