<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHR     06-08 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: APPRAISERS SCRAMBLE TO KEEP UP WITH FAST-MOVING
HOME  PRICES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you offer $100,000 or more over the asking
price for a home in the Bay Area, your friends, neighbors and
Midwestern relatives might think you've lost your mind, but your
appraiser probably won't.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the real estate market was at its most insane a few
months ago, very few houses failed to appraise for the purchase
price.
</P>
<P>
   Just as home buyers are having to stretch to buy a house,
appraisers are having to stretch to justify the prices buyers are
willing to pay. And although home buyers are happy when their deals
go through, some wonder why they had to pay $300 or more for an
appraisal if it's just a rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Alfonso Acampora put in a winning $660,000 offer
for a house in the Oakland hills that was listed at $499,000. He
had already lost multiple-bidding wars on several other homes, and
was worried about losing this one if the appraisal came in below
the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had not appraised, I would have had to walk way from it
because I put down everything I had to get into it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So he was pleasantly surprised when the appraisal came in at
$669,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before approving a mortgage, lenders require appraisals to
protect their investment and to make the loan eligible for sale to
institutions in the secondary market. Most won't finance more than
a certain amount _ usually 10 or 20 percent _ of the appraised
value.
</P>
<P>
   If the home appraises for less than the purchase price, the
buyer has to increase the down payment and/or persuade the seller
to lower the price. If that doesn't work, the buyer might try for a
loan with a lower down payment and higher monthly payments, for
which he may or may not qualify and that may require private
mortgage insurance. If that fails, the deal may fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Although nobody publishes statistics on this, Bay Area real
estate agents, mortgage brokers and appraisers say they've seen no
increase in the percentage of homes that fail to appraise for the
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not experienced any problems whatsoever with
appraisals,'' says Ric Rocchiccioli, president-elect of the San
Francisco Association of Realtors. ``And I don't think I've heard
horror stories'' from other brokers, even though more than 75
percent of homes sold in San Francisco in the past six months have
gone for more than asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has really not been a problem,'' says Rich Brown, a
spokesman for Bank of America mortgage. He would not say what
percentage of appraisals fall below the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was involved in 13 deals in past year. All except one came
in at the asking price,'' says Christopher Needham, a broker in San
Francisco. In that case, the appraisal was $200,000 short of the
$2.6 million purchase price, but the deal went through because the
buyer was paying cash and only got an appraisal because he might
get a loan in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't more homes fail the appraisal test?
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the purchase price may not be as inflated as it
looks because real estate agents are ``purposely underpricing''
homes to incite a bidding war, says Marcia Larrsonan appraiser in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason is that appraisers are becoming more
creative and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   To come up with a value for a home, appraisers look at a handful
of comparable houses in the neighborhood that have sold recently,
then adjust for differences in square footage, number of rooms, lot
size and squishier features such as character and views.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal market, they look at comparable sales in the last
six months or even a year. But in a rapidly escalating market,
``most of the comps we're using are in the last month,'' says Bob
Singer, owner of Trac, an appraisal firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's hard to find similar homes in the same neighborhood
that have sold in the past month, some appraisers are using homes
that are still in escrow or new on the market. They're also looking
in adjacent neighborhoods or clear across town.
</P>
<P>
   When appraisers still can't get a house to measure up, they
might add a ``time adjustment factor'' of 1 or 2 percent a month.
``If a comparable house sold for $100,000 six months ago, you might
say it would have sold for $106,000 now,'' says Larrson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a lot of stuff that usually we hadn't done in
the past to get to the sales price,'' says an in-house appraiser
for one of the Bay Area's largest thrifts. ``We've had to put out a
lot of phone calls to Realtors for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Realtors are happy to help out the appraiser with comps he
wasn't aware of or a list of the multiple bids on a house.
</P>
<P>
   Rocchiccioli says one appraiser told him he wrote an
``addendum'' to an appraisal saying the $38,500 difference between
his value and the purchase price ``would be made up in the next
three months by appreciation in the market. The lender bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Faudman, a real estate broker in Marin, says appraisals
are really just a ``disaster check'' for the lenders. ``I would not
look at an appraiser's report as a validation of the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The best appraiser, he says, ``is a buyer with a substantial
down payment who has been looking for a long time. The second best
is a real estate agent who has been working with a lot of buyers.
The third best is the appraiser. The worst is the seller. They want
you to look at their closet organizer. They say, `I spent $5,000 on
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many big lenders have in-house appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   Others' appraisers are independent, and usually work closely
with a handful of agents and mortgage brokers who all have a vested
interest in getting deals done. ``They (appraisers) know if they
miss too many appraisals, they just put themselves out of business.
(A real estate agent) can put a certain amount of pressure on the
appraiser.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, in-house appraisers don't seem to be any tougher
than independent ones.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean every house appraises at the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   In fast-moving markets, tract homes and condominiums sometimes
fall short. ``Condos are cookie cutters. It's hard to fiddle with
the appraisal,'' says Evelyn Walker, an East Bay real estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, one of Walker's clients, Peggy McGuire, offered
$295,000 for a three-bedroom condominium in Rockridge. An identical
unit had just sold for the same price, but there was another bidder
so she increased her offer to $310,000.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire says she was disappointed when her unit appraised at
$295,000, but at her agent's urging she had put down 30 percent of
the purchase price, so the deal went through.
</P>
<P>
   Walker says that ``anytime you put down 30 percent or more
you're pretty safe'' because most lenders will finance up to 80
percent of the value.
</P>
<P>
   Appraisal problems also crop up when buyers who are priced out
of one neighborhood suddenly ``discover'' a new neighborhood and
start offering prices that are substantially higher than the going
price in that area. The first few houses that get these abnormally
high offers sometimes won't appraise for the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, this is happening in upper Peninsula. ``All of a
sudden, it is a desirable neighborhood'' for people who can't
afford San Francisco or the Midpeninsula, says Paula Ryan, owner of
Pacific Guarantee Mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   She's had a few houses in Pacifica, Calif., appraise below the
purchase price, mainly because there are relatively few houses in
the coastside city. ``In San Francisco, there are a lot more houses
per square mile to comp out,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's company does about 150 to 200 loans a month, and in the
past three or four months she's had three or four houses that
failed to appraise.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, lenders will send someone to review an appraisal by
driving by the home. If the review appraiser is not familiar with
the area, there might be a problem, Ryan says.
</P>
<P>
   When a lender turns down a loan because of an appraisal, ``we
can do a rebuttal, but it's a big, long process and really messes
up the deal,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Some lenders, particularly those that loan to people with
splotchy credit records, are more stringent that others, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why his institution bothers with appraisals, BofA's Brown
replied, ``It is appropriate due diligence.'' He says BofA also
needs the appraisal in case it decides to sell the loan on the
secondary market.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens if the buyer paid too much and can't make his
payments?
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Chaney, a banking analyst with Sutro &AMP; Co., explains
that banks and insurance companies ``are purchasing millions of
these kinds of loans. If somebody in San Francisco goes into
default because they paid $100,000 too much for a house,'' it might
be devastating for an individual, but it will be a blip for a big
financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
