<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-ALLIANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCHWAB TO SELL BONDS ON INTERNET  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charles Schwab Corp. gave a push to the online
bond-trading market Thursday, announcing that it is joining forces
with an Internet startup to set up an electronic network for
trading fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance between the No. 1 online broker and ValuBond of
Atlanta, which trades bonds through the Web, will permit Schwab
customers to link directly with wholesale dealers to buy muncipal,
corporate and government bonds at posted prices. Officials of the
two companies said they expect to begin the new service in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab said it chose ValuBond as a partner because it operates
an electronic linking system that lets customers see what bonds an
array of wholesale brokers are selling in different categories and
buy directly from them. ValuBond charges brokers a flat fee when a
sale takes place.
</P>
<P>
   The company's technology is similar to the systems that are
shaking up the stock market by giving retail investors peeks at the
prices wholesale brokers are quoting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a neutral hub through which retail investors can see a
broad variety`` of securities, said ValuBond Chief Executive John
Pigott.
</P>
<P>
   Other online bond companies don't connect investors with
wholesale dealers. Instead, they sell securities from their own
inventory at a markup.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's deal with ValuBond is the latest development in the
growing movement of bond sales online.
</P>
<P>
   Many online brokers, including Schwab and second-ranking
E-Trade, already allow customers to buy bonds over the Internet.
But online bond sales has lagged stock trading. That's because only
a few thousand stocks are traded on public markets in the United
States. By contrast, hundreds of thousands of bond issues are
circulating and designing a system to keep track of the market is
tough.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bond-trading process typically isn't automated
once a customer clicks in an order. A human broker often has to
step in to process the trade, sometimes telephoning wholesale
dealers to complete a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Online or offline, customers typically don't know what
commission they are paying their broker to buy bonds. The broker's
profit is embedded in the price it charges the client for the
security.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, a handful of brash Internet startups have
begun to automate the bond-trading process, fueling the growth of
the market. ``In the last six months, about a dozen different
electronic platforms have emerged,'' said Richard Meister, chief
executive of Walnut Creek, Calif.'s eBondTrade.com, one of the new
players in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Inking a deal with Schwab gives ValuBond an enormous boost in
its competition with other Internet rivals. Pigott said the company
expects to announce partnerships with other retail and
institutional brokerages in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
