<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Complex Film in a Plain Wrap
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted this movie to be wrapped in brown paper, like
pornography,'' David Fincher said. This week Fox released his film
``Fight Club'' on DVD in a slipcase illustrated to look like a
wrapper tied with twine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it with the VHS box,'' he said, ``but we gave that up
to get the DVD.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, based on a novel by Chuck Palahniuk, a desensitized
young insomniac (Edward Norton) calls on a primal aspect of
himself, personified by an anarchic '60s-style radical named Tyler
Durden (Brad Pitt), to help reclaim his masculinity by breaking
down and coming back together. Part of the process takes place in a
club, started by the two of them, where depressed, threatened young
men gather to work out their rage and feelings of inferiority by
beating one another bloody.
</P>
<P>
   When the movie was released last fall, preconceived notions of
violence turned off many filmgoers, as did negative reports of
Durden's strutting nihilism. Generally, though, reviews noted the
movie's wit and subtle complexity. ``This film twists and turns in
ways that only add up fully on the way out of the theater and might
just require another viewing,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Her thought makes a blurb on the back of the DVD box, but
Fincher said that while he appreciates viewers taking another look
on video, the film got its due in theaters. ``It's the kind of
movie that's going to divide people,'' he said. ``You don't read
the book and say here's a mainstream fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   DVD, he added, is essentially for preservation. ``I don't know
if the film will have another life on DVD, but it will be the
record that lasts the longest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The film comes on two discs in an elaborately designed package
that opens like a book. The first disc contains the film in the
wide-screen, letter-box format and four separate movie-length
commentaries by Fincher, the stars and various others involved,
including Palahnuik and the screenwriter, Jim Uhls.
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Seven,'' another violent and controversial
film starring Pitt that underwent frequently favorable second
thoughts after its theater run in 1995, Fincher is also known for
lightning-fast visuals and computer-generated manipulations. The
technical aspects work best on disc. ``I'm much happier having a
wide-screen DVD out there than simply a panned-and-scanned DVD,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second disc has extended scenes of the film being made.
``They must have been thinking about DVD or some sort of
after-market,'' said David Pryor, a designer and producer of DVD's
who made these discs.
</P>
<P>
   Fincher said that there were no such thoughts at the time, but
he came to appreciate the wealth of material later.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it was shot from multiple angles. ``I wanted to use as
much of that behind-the-scenes stuff as possible,'' Pryor said.
</P>
<P>
   Is all of this, not to mention the hours of commentary, too
much? ``Nobody is forced to look at it,'' he said. ``It's such a
dense movie, the more perspectives you can get the better.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Green Mile
</P>
<P>
   Paul Edgecomb (Tom Hanks) recalls spiritual revelations when he
was chief guard on death row in a Southern prison during the 1930s.
A fastidious, compassionate man with a painful bladder infection,
Edgecomb runs an orderly operation until the arrival of John Coffey
(Michael Clarke Duncan), an enormous man convicted of rape and
murder. Coffey seems as gentle as his crimes are heinous, and he is
possessed with an inner power to cure maladies. Could he have
committed such crimes? Adapted from Stephen King's novel, Frank
Darabont's film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``boils
down to a well-populated drama with a relatively simple story, one
that could have been told with more economy and fewer talky bits.''
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Warner. $109.99; DVD, 188 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Bicentennial Man
</P>
<P>
   When the owner (Sam Neill) of an industrial robot named Andrew
(Robin Williams) discovers that it has creative powers, he sets the
machine up as a clockmaker. But Andrew longs to be a human and
generations later, when robots possess the emotions to fall in
love, he envisions marriage to his former employer's great
granddaughter (Embeth Davidtz). Free to employ all of Williams'
moist, sad-clown expressions, Chris Columbus' film ``pours on the
sentimentality in lumpy mawkish speeches about freedom, the joys of
sex and the meaning of life'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD, $32.99. 131 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG. Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Third Miracle
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Frank Shore (Ed Harris), a Chicago priest suffering a
crisis of faith, is assigned to look into the mystical phenomena
associated with Helen O'Regan (Barbara Sukowa), an immigrant woman
who is being considered for canonization. Delving into her life,
Father Shore develops a strong attraction for her daughter, Roxanna
(Anne Heche). Strong with this story element and avoiding the
flashy telekinetic mayhem typical of the religious genre, Agnieszka
Holland's film nevertheless ``becomes bogged down in fussy
theological arguments'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $29.95. 119 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Play It to the Bone
</P>
<P>
   Two burned-out middleweights, Vince (Woody Harrelson) and Cesar
(Antonio Banderas), sign to fight a 10-rounder in Las Vegas.
Needing transportation, they are driven across the desert by Grace
(Lolita Davidovich), who was Vince's lover and is about to break up
with Cesar. Both fighters have blown big chances and their case
histories are hashed over perhaps too thoroughly during the trip.
Their fight, a slugfest with flashbacks and hallucinations,
resolves little in a film that ``ends up stranded in serio-comic
limbo'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD, $32.99. 124 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   WITNESS PROTECTION. When the petty mobster Bobby Batton (Tom
Sizemore) gets caught cheating on his bosses and is ordered killed,
he decides to rat on them to the authorities. That lands lands him,
his wife (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio) and children (Shawn Hatosy
and Skye McCole Bartusiak) in a duplex apartment where they are
taught how live in the federal witness-protection program by a U.S.
marshall (Steve Beck). They have a lot to learn, especially the
arrogant Bobby, and, Ron Wertheimer wrote in the New York Times,
the ``process of forced metamorphosis is both fascinating and
frightening.'' 1999. HBO. $79.99; DVD, $19.98. 101 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY IN MOTION and IMAGINE THE SOUND. Two films by Ron Mann
explore Beat writers and '60s avant-garde jazz musicians. Charles
Bukowski, Amiri Baraka William S. Burroughs, John Cage, Allen
Ginsberg and Robert Creely, among others, appear in ``Poetry in
Motion'' (1982, 90 minutes). Cecil Taylor, Archie Shepp, Bill Dixon
and Paul Bley are featured in ``Imagine the Sound'' (1981, 90
minutes). Home Vision. $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   THE MORPH FILES. Peter Lord, a founder of Aardman Animations and
co-director with Nick Park (``Wallace and Gromit'') of the upcoming
film ``Chicken Run,'' helped create the British claymation and
computer animation series about Morph, an ever-changing character
who inhabits a desktop world and lives in a box. 1999. BBC Video.
Three cassettes, $9.98 each. 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
