<HEADLINE>
KLOSTERMAN REMEMBERED FOR COURAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of all the celebrated people I've met in sports
across the seasons, Don ``Duke'' Klosterman ranked among the most
memorable because of the sheer force of his charismatic
personality, his inexhaustible supply of stories and his Who's Who
list of close friends.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it often almost was forgotten that Klosterman was a
shrewd judge of football personnel in his long-time role as an NFL
general manager because of his storied lifestyle that brought him
in close contact with the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman, a one-time Compton High and Loyola quarterback star
who passed away at age 70 on Wednesday, once dated Bobby Kennedy's
widow, Ethel, and became close friends with the entire Kennedy
clan.
</P>
<P>
   A long-time member of the upscale Bel-Air Country Club,
Klosterman resided in Century City and moved in a rarefied social
circle that included people like the billionaire cable TV mogul,
Jerry Perenchio, the Hollywood Park president, R.D. Hubbard, the
actor, Jack Nicholson, the sportscaster, Al Michaels, and numerous
others of a similar vein.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s when I covered the Los Angeles Rams and
Klosterman was their GM---he held similar positions previously for
the Baltimore Colts and Houston Oilers---I nicknamed him the Duke
of Dining Out because of his well-known affinity for frequenting
stylish restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   He even owned one for a time in Beverly Hills with his second
wife, who was from Italy and who he wound up divorcing.
</P>
<P>
   During the time he was single---and he was for most of the years
I knew him---Klosterman was active on the dating scene, and one
evening during the Rams' training camp I had dinner with him and
the actress, Madeline Rhu, at an establishment in Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Don Klosterman was the most admired male I've ever
known because of his having overcome his disability,'' says Beverly
Hills attorney, E. Gregory Hookstratten, the Rams' general counsel
when Klosterman was with the team. Klosterman suffered a terrible
skiing accident near Banff in 1953, and doctors predicted he'd
never walk again.
</P>
<P>
   But Klosterman showed the same toughness and resilience in his
private physical struggle as he once did on the gridiron at Loyola,
where he threw for 19 touchdowns in 1951 and established new
single-game NCAA standards for passing attempts (63), completions
(33) and yardage (373) in a match against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He did manage to walk again, although he would suffer from his
skiing injuries---a broken back, a broken leg and broken ribs---the
remainder of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he was able to endure pain every day of his life was
truly remarkable,'' says Hookstratten. ``He was a very brave man.''
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman, one of 15 children who grew up modestly in Compton,
might have consorted with the handicapped horses on the social
scene but never forgot his roots.
</P>
<P>
   He was affable and charming to everyone he met, and often
ventured out of his Beverly Hills bailiwick to have a meal with his
myriad of friends that I'm sure could be found in every state in
America, as well as various countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He had enormous contacts in the media, and among his closest
were Howard Cosell, Bud Furillo, Melvin Durslag Jim Murray, John
Hall, Bob Oates, etc.
</P>
<P>
   He had many acquaintances and relatives in the Long Beach
area---he even worked here a while back in one of his many business
ventures---and often made appearances at Phil Trani's.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest guys I've ever had the pleasure to know,''
says the Long Beach restaurateur. ``My whole dining room lit up
when Don was in our place. And there was no one he didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Klosterman was an extraordinary raconteur, and he'd keep you
entranced with his tales about some of the people he worked for
like Baron Hilton, Lamar Hunt, Bud Adams and Carroll Rosenbloom and
some of the football players he knew well like Bobby Layne, Gino
Marchetti, John Unitas, Gene ``Big Daddy'' Lipscomb, Bubba Smith,
Otto Graham and countless others.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rosenbloom would get mad at Klosterman once in a while
when Klosterman would exceed his expense account allotment, but the
two men had a deep fondness for each other and were responsible for
building the Rams into a powerful franchise throughout the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   It became an autumn Thursday afternoon ritual during that decade
for Rosenbloom and Klosterman to show up at Blair Field, where the
Rams then trained, and they often would bring along with them
people like Ricardo Montablan and Jonathan Winters.
</P>
<P>
   I always found the repartee with Rosenbloom to be enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   But Duke Klosterman's deft one-liners and mesmerizing yarns were
just as entertaining---and will be missed by those of us fortunate
enough to have been his pal...
</P>
<P>
   -Curiously, if the Lakers are beaten tonight---a distinct
possibility unless they show up at Staples Center with
passion---the Indiana Pacers would suddenly have the advantage in
these NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the next three games will be at the Canseco
Fieldhouse in Indianapolis, where the Pacers were 36-5 during the
regular season and where the Pacers snapped the Lakers' 16-game
winning streak in January...
</P>
<P>
   -I've seen horrid shooting exhibitions before---I've been
watching Glen Rice the entire season---but none matches Reggie
Miller's 1-for-16 abomination Wednesday night...
</P>
<P>
   -Poor Arnold Schwarzenegger. It's bad enough the guy has had so
many bombs lately that he was reduced to having to sit a fifth row
lodge seat at Staples Center near the end of the court, a terrible
social putdown for him. But even worse is that ol' Arnold has had
so many face lifts that I swear he looks exactly now like one of
those aliens he's played in his movies...
</P>
<P>
   -I'm sure Bob Arum was overjoyed that the Lakers survived that
Game 7 against Portland, since it will diminish coverage of his
June 17 welterweight title fight between Oscar De La Hoya and Sugar
Shane Mosley, which is not exactly the talk of L.A. at the
moment...
</P>
<P>
   -Don Fraser reports the recent Golden State Boxers Association
luncheon honoring Bobby Chacon and Danny Lopez had a sellout
turnout of 145 at the Spaghetti Factory in Hollywood. The event
commemorated the two old warriors' classic 1974 showdown at the
Sports Arena in which Chacon emerged with a 9th round knockout
victory over Lopez...
</P>
<P>
   -I just wish all the jocks that cussed me out over the years
were fined $5,000 like John Rocker was for his heated verbal
confrontation with the Sports Illustrated reporter Jeff Pearlman...
</P>
<P>
   -Thank you for all the kind words of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonnell-Douglas Show, featuring Press Telegram columnist
Doug Krikorian and radio personality Joe McDonnell, can be heard
Sunday night on KABC (790 AM) between 9 o'clock and midnight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
