<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NYT &LR;      06-08 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DUTY FOR THE DEMOCRATS' MAIN MONEY MAN: RUNNING THE
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a personal appeal by Vice President Al Gore,
Terry McAuliffe, the Democratic Party's most prodigious
fund-raiser, has agreed to serve as chairman of the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles, which has struggled to overcome
fund-raising difficulties and bickering among its organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic officials said Gore phoned McAuliffe on
Wednesday morning to ask him to succeed Roy Romer, the former
Colorado governor, who was appointed superintendent of the Los
Angeles school system on Tuesday. McAuliffe instantly agreed to the
request, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For months, senior party officials have worried that this
summer's convention could turn out to be a dud, now that Gore has
the nomination wrapped up. Several party activists had quietly
lobbied for McAuliffe's appointment, saying they needed his
enthusiasm to help energize the four-day nominating convention
scheduled to begin Aug. 14 at the Staples Center in downtown Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry's commitment to the Democratic Party is unprecedented,''
Lydia Camarillo, the convention's chief executive, said Thursday.
``Time and again he has demonstrated his deep devotion to our
party's goals and efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe is the most prolific fund-raiser in the history of
American politics. He is also one of President Clinton's closest
friends. Most recently, McAuliffe was chairman of the Democratic
National Committee's gala at the MCI Sports Center here on May 23.
The event, a tribute to Clinton, attracted a sellout crowd of
13,625 people and raised a record $26.5 million for the Democratic
Party. Most of that money will benefit Gore's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, McAuliffe estimated that he had personally raised at
least $300 million for Clinton and Democratic causes, including the
president's 1997 inaugural, the White House millennium celebration,
the president's legal defense fund, Clinton's library in Little
Rock, Ark., and the current campaigns of Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But McAuliffe expects his convention duties, unlike those
earlier assignments, to require spending very little time raising
money. Democratic Party officials hope that McAuliffe can bring to
the Staples Center the pep-rally ambience that existed at last
month's gala here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be joining a terrific convention team,''
McAuliffe said Thursday. ``And I'm looking forward to working with
them to make this the greatest convention in the history of
American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, senior party officials and Gore allies were
concerned that the convention could turn into a disaster. Fund
raising was _ and still is _ behind schedule; $7 million still
needs to be raised by the host committee. The billionaires who had
helped lure the convention to Los Angeles have complained among
themselves. Unions facing contract negotiations had warned of
possible labor unrest.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it off, the city's public officials were reeling
earlier this year from the ugly headlines generated by the worst
police corruption scandal to hit the city in decades. There was
widespread worry that the convention would not be a worthy
successor to the last Democratic convention to be held in Los
Angeles: the 1960 party gathering that nominated John F. Kennedy
for president amid great excitement.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Democratic officials said the convention team had
made great organizational strides in the past two months.
Convention officials said they were looking forward to working with
McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stock is trading at an all-time high,'' said James
Carville, the Democratic consultant. ``He brings some panache and a
lot of enthusiasm to the convention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
