<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REFORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES RESTRUCTURED BUDGET PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Criticizing Washington for what he termed
``too much needless division,'' Gov. George W. Bush Thursday
proposed a wide-ranging overhaul of the federal budget process in
an effort to avoid the bitter annual standoffs between Congress and
the president over taxes and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush put at the center of his plan a call for the president and
Congress to shift from an annual budget cycle to a biennial process
like the one in Texas, his home state. ``If the discord in
Washington never seems to end this is partly because the budget
process never seems to end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan, however, was narrowly defeated in the
Republican-dominated House just last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, also
called for a new effort to pass legislation giving the president
line-item veto power. And he asked for a change in budget
procedures to require the president to sign the annual spring
budget resolution, which now is the work of Congress alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not dismiss the serious disagreements that are part of
the political process,'' Bush said, ``but the reality is that
Americans look upon this spectacle in Washington and they don't
like what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal for structural changes came against the backdrop
of 5{ tumultuous years of partisan bickering between President
Clinton and the Republican Congress that was elected in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there was ``enough blame to go around.'' But appearing
in the home state of Vice President Al Gore, his Democratic
opponent, he went on to level most of his criticism at the Clinton
administration, particularly at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized Gore for the tone of his responses to Bush's
policy proposals, particularly one to divert some Social Security
payroll taxes into individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideas he doesn't share are never just the other side of the
issue,'' Bush said. ``They're called reckless or radical. Proposals
he disapproves of are never just arguable, they are always `risky
schemes.' This unnecessary rhetoric is characteristic of the tone
in Washington, D.C. It's the war room mentality: the hostile
stance, the harsh charges, the lashing out at enemies. We have had
eight years of this, and eight years is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, which in recent days has toned down much of
its criticism of Bush, said the governor was trying to duck serious
policy debate. ``This rhetoric is Gov. Bush's way of avoiding real
debate on issues such as his plan to privatize Social Security,''
said Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   With his appearance Thursday, Bush continued the reliance on
policy speeches that have marked his campaign this spring and that
he and his advisers believe help him draw a contrast with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech allowed him to compete with Gore on one of the
vice president's trademark issues _ ``reinventing government'' _
and it also borrowed from Bush's Republican primary opponent, Sen.
John McCain, who crusaded against pork barrel spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed the creation of a bipartisan legislative
commission that would comb spending bills for pork barrel projects,
combine them into one list and then require Congress to take an up
or down vote on whether to approve the entire package.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the governor's ideas were not new. President Clinton
also sought line-item veto powers, and Congress passed such a law
in 1996. But two years later the Supreme Court held that it had
unconstitutionally granted the president unilateral power to change
statutes, and it struck down the law.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Goldsmith, Bush's chief domestic policy adviser, said
the campaign had consulted with constitutional experts and believed
line-item veto legislation could be rewritten to meet
Constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Clinton administration and the Republican Congressional
leadership also support biennial budgeting. Although Republicans
like Rep. Bill Archer, who heads the Ways and Means Committee, and
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert support the idea, such a plan was
defeated 217-201 in the House last month. The opponents, mostly
Democrats, said it would reduce Congress to fiscal lame ducks,
unable to exercise authority over federal agencies. A proposal like
Bush's to have the president sign the congressional budget
resolution was also defeated in the House 250-166.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also outlined several other steps to end gridlock. To head
off the threat of a government shutdown he proposed that if
spending bills were not passed by the start of the new fiscal year,
spending would continue at whatever was lowest: the previous year's
levels or levels proposed by the president in his own budget.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged the Senate to take no more than 60 days to act on
presidential nominees. The delays have become so severe that during
the Clinton administration 44 percent of nominations took more than
six months to come before the Senate, and some have been stalled
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Senate confirmation hearings had become too partisan.
``Often,'' he said, ``they are occasions for pushing a larger
agenda having nothing to do with the merits of the nominee. At some
memorable low points, hearings have become a gantlet of accusation,
interest group warfare and public humiliation. And this has done
too much harm to the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
