<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NEPHEW-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG BUSH IS THE STAR IN ADS SET FOR NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Calif.)   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Bush will be featured in a new commercial that
is to run here on Sunday. No, not that George Bush, and not the
other one, either. This is George P. Bush, the 23-year-old nephew
of the presumptive Republican nominee and a budding star of the
Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The new spot, produced in Spanish and in English _ George P. is
fluent in both, campaign advisers say _ is being released to
coincide with the staging on Sunday of the Puerto Rican Day Parade
in Manhattan, in which the younger Bush is also scheduled to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial, the young man, the son of the candidate's
brother Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida and his Mexican-born wife,
Columba, talks about how his uncle is reaching out to voters of
diverse backgrounds, Bush strategists say. But they add that his
good looks could also help draw in younger voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's able to deliver a message in a very natural way, and is,
in fact, not only a handsome young man, but also totally
Latino-looking and as proficient in Spanish as he is in English,''
said Lionel Sosa, a San Antonio advertising man and an architect of
Gov. George W. Bush's marketing campaign directed at Hispanic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are making an aggressive pitch this year for the
Hispanic vote, long seen as reliably Democratic, in part because
Bush has been successful in winning Spanish-speaking voters in
Texas. In Fresno, Calif., several weeks ago, the Republican
National Committee spent about $150,000 on a test run of a
commercial intended to attract voters of Latin American descent.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising time in New York for the English-language spot was
bought during WNBC's coverage of the parade, and the
Spanish-language version will be broadcast on the Telemundo
network, Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he recognized the telegenic potential of George
P., who is to begin law school in the fall, when he saw him work
the crowd at a meeting with farm workers in San Bernardino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   People there were so taken with him, Sosa said, ``they forgot he
was a Republican.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-MEDICARE-NYT &LR;      06-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PLANS TOUR ON PROSPERITY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore plans to kick off a new
stage of his campaign next week, making a ``progress and
prosperity'' tour devoted to the relatively new questions of how
best to guide the nation in an era of budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would open the discussion on Tuesday in New York
City with a speech about protecting Medicare from what he called
``political poaching'' and reserving it for the use of the 40
million Americans for whom it was collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a turning point in our country's history,'' Gore, the
putative Democratic presidential nominee, said in an interview here
Thursday. ``We've never had a debate about how to make decisions
concerning a large, continuing surplus, and there are a number of
big choices that we have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The decisions related to the surplus are no less
difficult or important than the decisions we have made concerning
the deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Medicare, he said he would delve into other questions,
including: ``How to use entitlements correctly; how to pay off the
debt more quickly in order to reduce interest rates and promote
more economic growth; and how to make the investments that are
needed in top priorities like education, to get people access to
the skills they need.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's new focus is less about Medicare than about
the ongoing debate over how best to take advantage of the nation's
newly found fiscal health. It is part of Gore's effort to sell
voters on debt reduction as a smarter alternative to the big tax
cuts advocated by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his expected
Republican rival this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It is also part of the Gore campaign's effort to put a positive
sheen on Gore's candidacy and to make explicit use of what his
advisers say is perhaps his best argument for being elected: the
unprecedented prosperity of the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not received much direct credit for that prosperity,
but the tour, to highlight the economic progress in states like
Pennsylvania and Ohio that will be major electoral battlegrounds,
should increase his association with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve the credit for the strength of the
economy,'' Gore said. ``I think the policies of this
administration, which I've helped shape, have indeed unlocked some
of that potential and made it much more likely to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president frequently points to his association with
Robert E. Rubin, the former Treasury secretary and one of the
nation's most respected financial analysts, as testimony to his
fiscal discipline, but he said that he came up with the idea of
putting Medicare into a ``lock box'' on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consult with Bob Rubin all the time,'' Gore said Thursday.
``But this particular proposal on the Medicare lock box I put
forward, and I hoped that he would react positively to it, and he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare surplus this year is projected by its trustees at
$22.3 billion, and to total $250 billion over 10 years. The surplus
comes from payroll taxes levied on employees and employers to pay
for hospitalization, nursing home care and other health benefits
under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Under the government's accounting rules, the Medicare surplus
has been considered part of the general government surplus, unlike
the surplus generated by Social Security, which both legally and
politically has been segregated from excess general government
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Democratic and the Republican parties have agreed to
use the Social Security surplus, which amounts to more than $2
trillion over the next decade, only to reduce the national debt
held by the public. The public debt stands at $3.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the non-Social Security surplus over the next
decade range from $800 billion to nearly $2 trillion, depending on
what assumptions are made about how fast government spending will
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is relying on the non-Social Security surplus to pay for
his tax cut plan, which is valued at $1.3 trillion over the rest of
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Medicare ``lock box'' proposal would reduce the amount of
money available for tax cuts by $250 billion, making it easier for
him to portray Bush's tax plan as fiscally irresponsible,
especially when added to Republican proposals for additional
spending on programs like national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has been determined to avoid negative
references to Bush over the last few weeks. He said Thursday that
the intention of his Medicare proposal was not to make Bush's plan
seem riskier, but he would not be unhappy if a voter drew that
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that makes it harder for someone to use the Medicare trust
fund for purposes other than Medicare, then that should be one of
the effects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would also restrict Democrats from using all of the
non-Social Security surplus for additional spending.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Horney, an analyst at the Center for Budget and Policy
Priorities, a liberal-leaning research group, said of the Gore
plan: ``This is obviously an attempt to reduce the likelihood of
there being big tax increases or spending that would eat up the
surplus. If it helps to avoid big tax cuts or spending increases
before dealing with the long-term issues of Medicare and Social
Security, that would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Medicare surplus, Horney said, ``It's not
nearly as much as the Social Security surplus, but it's still a
significant amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's lock box plan would not do anything to shore up Medicare,
which, without any changes, is expected to become insolvent around
2025. By earmarking the Medicare surplus for debt reduction, the
main economic effect of Gore's plan would be to underscore his
commitment to paying off the national debt by 2013 or sooner, a
path that he says would help keep interest rates down and stimulate
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But by setting up even an indirect tradeoff between Medicare and
tax cuts, Gore is returning to a political strategy that Democrats
have used successfully against Republicans for years: implying that
Republican tax cuts for the rich would endanger health insurance
for some of the nation's most vulnerable citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
