<SLUG> BC-LORAL-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT MEMO SAYS DONOR WAS CLEARED 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a House committee released thousands of pages
of Justice Department documents on Tuesday about Democrats'
fund-raising activities, the papers included some that cast a new
and more forgiving light on the activities of Bernard Schwartz, a
top Democratic Party contributor and the chairman and chief
executive officer of Loral Space and Communications, a satellite
company.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Schwartz, who contributed about $1.5 million in 1996,
has lingered under a shadow of a Justice Department investigation.
That was because Schwartz's donations to the Democratic Party came
as Loral was seeking White House support for a waiver that would
allow the company to export satellite technology to China. The
inquiry into Schwartz was not closed until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., suggested at a hearing
that the former head of the Justice Department's campaign finance
unit, Charles G. La Bella, had, in a 1998 memorandum to Attorney
General Janet Reno, urged the appointment of an independent counsel
to investigate Schwartz's dealings with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But La Bella's memorandum of July 16, 1998, and an addendum on
Aug. 12, 1998, cast a fuller light on the matter. The documents,
which were made public by the House Government Reform and Oversight
Committee, show that La Bella never believed there was any evidence
against Schwartz and concluded that Schwartz had not broken the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a matter which likely did not merit any
investigation,'' La Bella wrote in his addendum. Portions of La
Bella's memorandums about Schwartz were first reported by The Los
Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a Loral spokesman expressed satisfaction that the
documents had finally come to light. ``We are pleased that the
facts in this case have now been made public and that Schwartz and
Loral are shown to be innocent of any wrongdoing,'' said Thomas B.
Ross, a company vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said in an interview that he did not realize at the
hearing that Schwartz had been exonerated by the Justice Department
because he had not seen La Bella's addendum. ``When I was
questioning him it was from his initial report,'' Specter said. ``I
did not know at that time there was a supplemental report.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first report La Bella suggested that the justification
for the inquiry into Schwartz was based not on evidence but on the
concerns of Justice Department officials that they could be
criticized if they did not investigate.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella wrote, ``Although no one could articulate a solid basis
upon which to predicate a criminal investigation, given the
political climate, it was generally felt that the department had to
commence an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   La Bella said in an interview that he never believed that there
was concrete evidence against Schwartz. He said he cited the matter
in his memorandum because of what he had concluded was a double
standard in which the Justice Department began an inquiry into
Schwartz over the contributions but refused to open an
investigation of Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
