A8642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS0609-COX     06-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect comeback of hack-a-Shaq
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So, what do you do with a man who rips you open
for 43 points and 19 rebounds, who makes two-thirds of his shots
and does it with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   When the question was put to Shaquille O'Neal after Game 1 of
the NBA Finals, he said, ``I'd just go home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers won't do that, so the question remains. They
still have to try to stop the Lakers' 7-foot-1, 320-pound center.
</P>
<P>
   When your own team is soft in the middle and slow to react on
the wings, how do you prevent the most dangerous man in the NBA
from beating you into submission?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the hack-a-Shaq,'' analyst and former NBA coach Kevin
Loughery said Thursday. ``I mean, the guy took 31 shots (and made
21) and only took six free throws, four of which came on
three-point plays. So, they didn't make him do it from the line. I
don't understand that. You've got to foul him, and you do it with
everyone except (power forward) Dale Davis because that's the guy
you can't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers lack the depth and quickness to challenge O'Neal as
Portland did in a seven-game Western final. But Loughery says they
can stymie him by using a cadre of players to prevent the league
MVP from catching the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand in front of Shaq,'' Loughery said. ``Put guys in front
of him on the strong side of the floor. That's what Portland did.
You can ignore (Ron) Harper and Kobe (Bryant), as long as he's on
the perimeter. Now you have numbers, and they can't find Shaq to
get it to him. The other guys have to make outside shots. If they
can't, L.A.'s in a lot of trouble. That's why I still think Indiana
has a chance in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird said his Pacers must make dramatic changes today.
``After the way Shaquille laid us up last night, obviously we're
going to try to be more aggressive. We got there last night on the
double teams, but it wasn't aggressive. If you come down there soft
on him, he'll make you pay every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird agreed that O'Neal must be forced to the line in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's going to take 30 shots, he should go to the line
12, 14 times. There will be situations we might have to foul him,
if he gets the ball too close to the basket. Last night it looked
like Rik (Smits) had his hands on the ball several times, and Shaq
went and powered through.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird sees no easy fix. ``It's going to be tough. No question.
It's not an easy series for us. The matchups aren't good. They're a
quick team. They're big with Shaq and strong. They're able to score
points in bunches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' defensive strategist, Dick Harter, says the Pacers
must be more attentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna have to give more fouls. Portland had (Arvydas)
Sabonis, who is stronger (than Smits) with a wider base, and Brian
Grant. Beside that, they've got Scottie Pippen and Rasheed Wallace
back there one step off, and they can be effective. If we're one
step off, we might as well be out back posing for holy pictures.
We've got to get nose to nose and get tough on them. If we don't
come out of this with bloody noses and skinned-up knees, we won't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Harter wants to see if the Pacers can come back from a soaking,
as they did in previous rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got backed up into Lake Michigan by Milwaukee one night,
came back and won the series. We got shoved into the Hudson River
and embarrassed by New York and came back and dominated. This time
we put our toes in the Pacific, and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
