<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS EXPECT MILLER TO FIRE RATHER THAN RETREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last summer during a chance meeting at an area
gymnasium, Los Angeles Lakers guard Kobe Bryant and Indiana Pacers
guard Reggie Miller decided to share some secret information about
their basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Bryant didn't teach Miller everything he knows.
After going 1-of-16 from the field and scoring just seven points in
the Pacers' 104-87 loss to the Lakers in Game 1 of the NBA Finals
on Wednesday, Miller might be tempted to seek more advice from
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who joined Ron Harper in defending Miller, said their
chance meeting last summer was interesting, with Miller showing him
how to come off screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just taught him some basic skills, the crossover dribble
between the legs, and kind of being creative with the basketball,''
Bryant said. ``He did a good job getting to the basket \Rin Game
1\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't have the hops to put his elbow on the rim.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller might not have had any hops, but the Lakers expect him to
bounce back in Game 2 at 8 tonight at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the first five times he has a chance, the ball will be
flying up,'' Harper said. ``I expect every time he touches the ball
he'll fire it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's performance Wednesday was the worst of his postseason
career, and the third-worst in NBA Finals history. Seattle's Dennis
Johnson (1978) and Baltimore's Chick Reiser (1948) each were
0-for-14 from the floor in their respective championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Miller refused to credit the Lakers for his dismal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of my 16 shots, 11 of them were wide open,'' he said.
``And as a shooter, you know you encourage that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep shooting. It can't get any worse; it can
only get better. So I'm going to shoot my way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said he was going to defend Miller the same way he did in
Game 1. When asked how he defended Miller, Harper was quick to say:
``I didn't do anything. He missed shots. He missed wide-open
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers know Miller can get hot like he did when he closed
out the Eastern Conference Finals by scoring 17 points in the
fourth quarter against the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits any shot right now, for him it could start him off
on a pace where there's a fire that would be hard to put out,''
Lakers forward Rick Fox said. ``One-for-16 is not characteristic of
shooting for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you don't want to get him started. You don't want to give
him any kind of light, or give him the same kind of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's shooting woes in Game 1 probably would have been easier
for him to accept if this wasn't the NBA Finals. Add that to the
fact that Miller _ he grew up here, his parents still live here,
and he played at UCLA _ had friends and family members at the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Miller was even talking about trying to concoct some
hatred for the Lakers, much like he despises the Knicks. He figures
that mindset could jump-start his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any bad feelings about LA, but you know you need
that extra motivation,'' Miller said. ``You need to create that own
little something to get you ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've created that myself by going 1-for-16 in Game 1
of my first- ever NBA Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird remains confident in Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one that's taken us through the playoffs, and he's
played extremely well this year in the playoffs,'' Bird said.
``That's why we're here now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie worked hard for me the last three years, not only in
the games but in practice. He gave me an honest effort at least
95-96 percent of the time. Obviously he's not happy with his \RGame
1\S performance, but I'll never give up on the guy.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
