<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT HARD TO FIGURE DESPITE HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports sometimes gives us things that are difficult to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Look to Paris. No American-resident singles player made it past
the quarterfinals of the French Open this week, marking the first
time since tennis' ``open'' era began in 1968 that Americans have
performed so poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Look to New Jersey. Didn't you hear more than once that the team
that advanced past the Stars-Colorado Avalanche series could go
ahead and hoist the Stanley Cup? So who are these Devils guys?
</P>
<P>
   Look at New York. For the first time since 1970, the winners of
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes both will miss the Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   When the rest of the sports world reads about these items,
people lose interest. There must be a lake to swim in on Saturday,
a flea market to browse through.
</P>
<P>
   But junkies don't ditch their sport. Tennis fans will tune in to
the French Open and watch unknowns Franco Squillari and Magnus
Norman play in the semifinals, even though the rest of us have no
idea who those guys are. And horse racing fans will go out to the
track to bet on Aptitude and Appearing Now, even if those horses
were also-rans in previous races.
</P>
<P>
   What the average sports fan thinks is a dud, a horse racing fan
thinks is a good betting race. And if this Belmont turns out like
the 1970 Belmont, this will be a good betting race.
</P>
<P>
   When Derby winner Dust Commander skipped the '70 Belmont and
Preakness winner Personality was scratched out of the race, High
Echelon won the Belmont at odds of 9 to 2. Needles N Pens finished
second and paid $11.80 to place. Third-place Naskra was 9 to 1. My
Dad George, second in the Derby and Preakness, was a 6 to 5
favorite but finished off the board.
</P>
<P>
   If they had offered an exacta or trifecta in those days, the
exacta would have paid an easy three-digit price and the trifecta
would have threatened or surpassed $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone trying to find a historical trend from 1970 to help them
in betting the race this year likely will be frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   High Echelon won the Belmont after running third in the Derby
and fourth in the Preakness. That sounds kind of like Impeachment
this year, third in the Derby and third in the Preakness. But High
Echelon also raced at Garden State Park in between the Preakness
and Belmont and finished fourth in that race.
</P>
<P>
   Needles N Pens and Naskra both raced competitively (first and
third respectively) in the '70 Peter Pan before the Belmont. So
this year's Peter Pan winner Postponed, second-place finisher
Unshaded and third-place finisher Globalize could run well in the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   My Dad George ran second in the '70 Derby and lost the Preakness
by a neck before throwing the dud in the Belmont, so does that mean
Impeachment (the only horse this year to finish on the board in the
Derby and Preakness) is due to go backward?
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded is a supplemental nomination, a horse whose owner had
to pay an expensive late entry fee. There was one of those in 1970,
too. Delaware Chief won a race at Belmont, which encouraged his
owners to pay the late entry fee. He was 5 to 1 (Unshaded's
morning-line odds are 5 to 1), but Delaware Chief finished ninth in
the field of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Trends or trash? The only thing history dictates is that this
year's Belmont _ without Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus or Preakness
winner Red Bullet _ is still a race worth a look, and a bet.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
