r s BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     06-08 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEED TO GIVE YOUNG PITCHERS A LOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Clark's time has come and gone. The time has come instead
for the Rangers to take a hard look at their starting rotation and
see if some of their young pitchers can actually do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Start with Matt Perisho, then Ryan Glynn and finally Doug Davis.
Keeping them stuck in the bullpen or Triple A isn't doing them or
the Rangers any good. They've been developed. Now it's time for
trial by fire.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if the Rangers are in a pennant race. At least
one of the three should be able to improve on Clark's 8.15
earned-run average and be able to give the Rangers six decent
innings on a regular basis. Clark was once able to do that, but
continuing to hope he can recapture that form is only wasting
valuable time that could be used looking at some of the young
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Because, come August, the Rangers must decide on a fifth
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho should get first crack because he's sitting there taking
up a roster space based on potential alone. The Rangers are afraid
to expose him to outright waivers because they might lose him to
another team, but they'll never know how good he can be if they
never pitch him.
</P>
<P>
   So let him pitch against the Tampa Bay Devils Rays on June 17
and put Clark in the bullpen. Give Perisho] two or three starts and
see what he has. If Perisho does the job, he stays, Glynn and Davis
keep pitching in Triple A and Clark works in middle relief. It
might be 10 cents on the dollar in return for Clark's $5 million
salary this season, but at least it's something.
</P>
<P>
   If Perisho can't do the job, then bring Glynn back after the
All-Star break and give him a month to do the job. His 2-0 victory
against the Los Angeles Dodgers on Monday suggests he would be
fine. But if he should falter, then it would be time for Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, one of the three ought to be able to serve as a fifth
starter. If not, the Rangers are doing a lousy job developing
pitching in their farm system.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers need to start finding out now, and not just
because Clark is struggling. Both Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver
have missed time because of shoulder trouble and that might be a
recurring problem all season. Oliver especially should be a concern
considering his arm history and that he has complained about his
shoulder after each of his past two starts.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some long-term considerations, starting with
Esteban Loaiza, who is 3-3 with a 4.99 ERA. Loaiza is raking in
$2.65 million and is eligible for arbitration next year. The
Rangers still harbor hope he'll be a big winner, but if he's not,
he's going to get too expensive. If the Rangers have to make a
decision about him it would be made much easier if they had a
better idea about some of their young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since the Rangers had a young pitcher
come up from the farm system, break into their rotation and stay
there for an extended period. Oliver did so, but only after a year
in the bullpen (1994) and a year of arm trouble (1995). Roger
Pavlik came close but could never stay healthy. After that you have
to go back to Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rangers have either bought their pitching through
free agency or traded for it at the expense of good young talent
like Ryan Dempster, who was sent to Florida in the 1996 John
Burkett trade and is now the best pitcher on the Marlins' staff.
But some of that money is going to be needed elsewhere this winter
to give Rusty Greer a three-year, $21 million contract extension,
to re-sign John Wetteland or to extend Tim Crabtree's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said one of his goals all
along was to start developing young pitching in the farm system.
The time has come to give it a chance.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
