(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Former Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin has turned
out to be a great free-agent signing for the Colorado Rockies. He
is hitting .330 with a .420 on-base percentage as the Rockies'
leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He also has become a dangerous base stealer. Goodwin has 26
stolen bases in 30 attempts, which has helped the Rockies' overall
running game. They are second in the majors behind the Florida
Marlins with 58 steals in 78 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just puts so much pressure on the defense and makes
pitchers speed up their deliveries,'' Colorado manager Buddy Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies will put their running game to the test this weekend
against Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who has led the major
leagues in throwing out base stealers for five consecutive years.
The Rangers open a three-game series tonight at Coors Field in
Denver.  &QL; 
Rangers sign four
</P>
<P>
   Rice outfielder Jason Gray, drafted in the 26th round of the
First-Year Player Draft this week, has signed with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also signed20th-round pick Tyler Martin, a second
baseman from Mississippi State, 21st-round pick Marion Gleason, a
right-handed pitcher from Bountiful (Utah) High and 23rd-round pick
Robert Evans, an outfielder from Pepperdine University.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also signed three undrafted free agents:
right-handed pitcher Thomas Graham from Fresno State, right-handed
pitcher Reggie Rivard from Washington State and shortstop Leland
Swenson from College of St. Scholastica in Duluth, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers assigned Martin and Evans to Pulaski (Va.) of the
Appalachian League and sent the other five to the Gulf Coast
Rangers of the Gulf Coast League.
