<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-TRUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTY TRUCK TEAM MAKING STRIDES TOWARD RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A little less than a month ago, the
foundation of Petty Enterprises was rocked by the death of
19-year-old Adam Petty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petty, the first fourth-generation driver in NASCAR who made his
only Winston Cup start at Texas Motor Speedway in April, died May
12 after he crashed during practice for a Busch Grand National
event at New Hampshire International Speedway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His death was felt throughout racing, but yesterday at TMS,
Richard Petty, Adam's grandfather and NASCAR's king, was in the
garage making sure the entry he owns, Steve Grissom's No. 43 Dodge
Motorsports truck, was running well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racing is the Petty family business, and life has continued at
the racetrack and at the shops in tiny Level Cross, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really hard to put into words what you felt or what you
feel now,'' said Grissom, who is in his first year in the Truck
Series. `` It has been a tough situation and is a tough situation.
But it really shows the character and the strength of the Petty
family and Petty Enterprises. Everybody is doing everything they
can to get through and move on.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petty Enterprises is moving on after the devastating events in
May and the loss of family patriarch Lee Petty in April. Kyle
Petty, Adam's father, returned to racing last week at Dover, Del.,
and Richard met the media for the first time since Adam's death
before the Coca-Cola 600 last month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard was here this weekend overseeing his Truck Series
operation and will be in the pits for tonight's race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shop ``is getting back to normal, and it is a whole lot
better this week than it was last week and each week it just keeps
getting better,'' said Travis Owens, the interim crew chief on
Grissom's truck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grissom enters tonight's Pronto Auto Parts 400k at the 1.5-mile
quadoval seventh in points, but that comes after a frustrating
couple of races. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On May 23, crew chief Fred Wanke left to ``pursue other
opportunities,'' and the team is using a two-crew-chief system in
which Owens, the team's jackman, makes calls at the racetrack and
Dale Smith, the shop foreman, oversees the operations during the
week at the race shop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Wanke left, Grissom finished 21st in Fountain,
Colo., which broke a streak of eight consecutive finishes of 11th
or better. Two weeks later, he finished a disappointing 26th at
Evergreen Speedway in Monroe, Wash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The team seems to be rallying around Travis,'' Richard Petty
said. ``Really, the team hasn't run that bad; it's just that luck
hasn't been on our side lately. Luck is a strange thing. When it's
going your way it's your best friend; when it's not it's your worst
enemy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those two finishes dropped Grissom from third in the standings
to seventh, and Owens also talked about luck leaving the team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The first of the year we had all the luck we needed,'' said
Owens, who has been with the team since it was formed in 1996.
``The last couple of weeks we have run better than what we showed;
it's just luck has got to go in our way. When we get the luck back
on our side we will be all right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Texas could be the place where Grissom's luck returns.
Grissom qualified 20th for tonight's race, but he has had success
at the track in a Winston Cup car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 and 1998 Cup races, Grissom, who was driving for
Larry Hedrick, finished 10th after starting 42nd and 35th,
respectively. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Petty Enterprises has been around for 50 years and is still
going strong,'' Grissom said. They've been through all kinds, types
and sorts of situations. All the equipment is there for what we
need to win and basically it is just up to us.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
