<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-MUSIC-TEX     06-08 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Lone Ranger had the ``William Tell
Overture.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Favor, Rowdy Yates and the boys had that great ``Rawhide''
ditty _ ``Move 'em on, head 'em up, head 'em up, move 'em on; Move
'em on, head 'em up, Rawhide! Count 'em out, ride 'em in, ride 'em
in, count 'em out; Count 'em out, ride 'em in, Rawhide!''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rockford didn't start solving cases, and the cops on ``Hill
Street Blues'' didn't leave the squad room to be careful out there
until the Mike Post music was cued. The gang at Cheers didn't begin
trading witticisms in earnest until we heard that they hung out at
the place ``Where Everybody Knows Your Name.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every hero _ and anti-hero _ has a theme song, it
seems. So why should baseball players be any different?
</P>
<P>
   While baseball players have requested music be played for them
for many years, the current practice of a song for almost every
player is a recent development.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers leadoff batter Luis Alicea walks to the plate as Salsa
music plays. Public address announcer Chuck Morgan turns down the
music, introduces Alicea, then turns it up again. The music stops
as the pitcher looks in for the sign.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Ivan Rodriguez steps in to a Ricky Martin
song. Rafael Palmeiro has ``Changes'' by 2pac, David Segui ``All
Along the Watchtower'' by Jimi Hendrix, Chad Curtis ``One of These
Days'' by FFH, and on it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it goes back to when the organ first came into play,''
Morgan said. ``The organist would come up with a little ditty that
would have something to do with the player's name or where he was
from. Then I think it's evolved into what we have now.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers have now is a song for almost every batter in
the lineup. The only exceptions are rookie Mike Lamb, who said he's
got other things to worry about, and veteran Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him not to play anything,'' Greer said. ``It doesn't
interest me, I don't guess.''
</P>
<P>
   That's OK. It interests just about everyone else on the team to
one degree or another. There are almost as many musical styles and
reasons for choosing songs as there are players.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, one of the most active players in choosing his own
music, has five songs play in rotation, all from the contemporary
Christian field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is what I do, but Christian is what I am,'' he said.
``I think it's good music, and it's also proclaiming what I'm
about. Actually, I listen to a lot of slower, worshipful-type
songs, but you're not going to play that in the stadium on your way
up to bat. The idea is kind of energy. For the setting, it works
good to have these songs. I really enjoy the lyrics. Those are
powerful songs that have great messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro also chose his song, ``Changes,'' because of the
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listen to the whole song, it talks about change, how
things need to change for the better, making a difference in
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The player whose song perhaps best fits his role is closer John
Wetteland, who enters to ``Don't Fear the Reaper'' by Blue Oyster
Cult. But Wetteland said he didn't choose it off the title or the
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said what's your favorite, and it was the first thing off
the top of my head,'' he said. ``I just liked the song. It has
nothing to do with lyrics or anything like that. I like the guitar
work in it, I like the feel of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Wetteland, most of the players picked their songs because
of the sound, not the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton usually asks that an old ``classic'' by
Funkadelic called ``Knee Deep'' be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my favorite songs of all time,'' he said. ``The
guitar solo at the end is off the hook. The beginning part of it is
good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler also goes by the music, but his is the pulsating
rhythms of rap, the ``stuff I listened to growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beat more than the lyrics,'' he said. ``Most guys
play something that gets them going, makes them feel good. But you
have to be real careful with the lyrics when you go with rap music.
It's a family ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The family ballpark not only is subjected to Kapler's rap, it
also rocks to Segui's Hendrix and Frank Catalanotto's Pearl Jam and
Creed, and dances to the Latino rhythms of Alicea's Salsa music and
the Martin song Rodriguez uses.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan has been playing music for Rangers players since the
mid-to-late '80s. Former reliever Jeff Russell wanted to hear the
theme from ``Top Gun'' when he entered the game. Nolan Ryan, for
reasons no one is certain about, liked ``Don't Go Breaking My
Heart'' by Elton John and Kiki Dee.
</P>
<P>
   While only selected players used to request music, now almost
all of them want a special song to mark their appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ring-leader in '96 was Bobby Witt,'' Morgan said. ``He got
a list together and kept me updated on what guys wanted to hear.
Then it went over to Mark McLemore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now clubhouse attendant Kelly Terrell is responsible for
rounding up the players' choices. Morgan doesn't care what style of
music they pick, but he does screen the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way a lot of today's music is, you've got to be real
careful on what you play,'' he said. ``I make sure we listen to it
and make sure it's OK to play. The last thing we want to do is
offend somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it is a family ballpark.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
