<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-GEAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING WAYS HAVE FANS WANTING TO BE SHAQ OFF THE RACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Laker mania sweeps L.A., fans are flocking to
sports merchandise stores to load up on anything purple and gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest sales push I've had in the NBA
(merchandise) in 10 years,'' said Scott Damschroder, owner of the
Scorecard sports store in the Studio City neighborood. ``It's just
like Super Bowl week.''
</P>
<P>
   Damschroder said store sales of Shaquille O'Neal jerseys and
other Lakers gear shot up nearly threefold Wednesday, the day the
Lakers won Game One of the NBA Finals against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, fans stopped by the store to buy dozens of
T-shirts to celebrate L.A.'s dramatic come-from-behind victory over
the Portland Trail Blazers to win the Western Conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Scorecard is not the only company that is seeing brisk sales.
Stores throughout the area have been cashing in on the Lakers all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It continues to be strong, but it has been strong the entire
year,'' said Craig Levra, president and chief executive officer of
Sport Chalet. ``There was an excitement in town the day Phil
Jackson got here, and all the Lakers fans' expectations are being
fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   National Basketball Association officials estimate that
postseason sales represent anywhere from 15 percent to 25 percent
of total merchandise sales, depending on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoffs and the finals are like our holiday season,''
said Chris Heyn, senior vice president of the NBA's global
merchandising group.
</P>
<P>
   Individual retailers also have a lot at stake in the closing
weeks of the NBA season. After the Lakers won the Western
Conference on Sunday, retailers such as Scorecard began stocking up
on Western Conference Champions gear that will be obsolete in a
matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a countdown,'' Damschroder said. ``You get this stuff,
and you only have 10 days to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Levra said Sport Chalet does not usually stock up on Western
Conference gear, waiting instead to see if the local team goes all
the way to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a somewhat fickle town,'' he said. ``You have to win a
lot to get people excited. You have to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Lakers do beat Indiana, retailers say they will be
ready with T-shirts and caps the next day. And other popular items
_ including shot glasses, beer steins, mugs, pins and wastebaskets
_ will not be far behind
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8651 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKW-MULKEY-ROBERTSON-     06-08 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MULKEY-ROBERTSON-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Kim Mulkey-Robertson admits to having been the
inquisitive type as a little girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nosy, I guess,'' the new women's basketball coach at Baylor
confessed.
</P>
<P>
   So, on that day more than 30 years ago when she saw a man drop
off a package on the Tickfaw, La., elementary school playground for
the physical education coach, she couldn't resist learning the
contents. She slapped her jeans, freeing small clouds of dust
accumulated from that spring day's recess football game as she
ambled over to the package. What she found was a stack of
application forms for summer Little League baseball that the PE
coach later passed out to the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking that here he is giving out these forms to boys
that I play with on teams every day, and I'm better than any of
them are,'' Mulkey-Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   She stuffed an application into a back pocket. The form sat on
the desk in her room at home for the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a deep thinker,'' Mulkey-Robertson said. ``I put a lot of
thought into it for a couple of days. There were no organized
summer activities for girls to compete in then. I just wanted to
play, and I knew all the guys I would be playing with and against,
because I played with them every day at school.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one night at supper, she handed the form to her father
and told him what she planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if that's what I wanted to do, to go for it,'' Kim
said.
</P>
<P>
   She showed up for tryouts dressed in her trademark jeans and
T-shirt, pounded the pocket of her red-white-and-blue glove and
walked straight to the pitching mound, where she proceeded to
handcuff most of the boys who tried to hit against her.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first player chosen in the draft. Later in the
summer, she made the all-star team as a pitcher, shortstop and
catcher _ five years before legal challenges forced Little League
Baseball in 1974 to change the rules to allow girls to play the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some people mouthed about it,'' Mulkey-Robertson
reflected. ``But really, in my hometown it wasn't a big deal.
People knew who I was because of my family. I had grown up in the
area. And they knew I could play. But it did kind of shock some
people that I made the all-star team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot of lessons because of that ... that some
people don't learn until later in life. Although things were out of
my control sometimes, I didn't let it defeat me.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials kept her out of the all-star playoffs that year
on a thinly-veiled technicality, but Mulkey-Robertson persevered.
She moved up to Pony League the next season and made the all-star
team at that level, too. It was the start of one of the most
memorable athletic careers in Louisiana sports history, one that
will be capped tomorrow with her induction into the second Women's
Basketball Hall of Fame class in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the last time she shocked her peers.
\Nsubheds:Success came early From the moment she began playing
basketball, Mulkey-Robertson knew nothing but winning.
</P>
<P>
   She played on an undefeated basketball team in the eighth grade.
She led her Hammond (La.) High School basketball team to four
consecutive state championships in Louisiana's highest
classification. In July 1980, she was honored with her own day in
Hammond and commissioned an honorary state representative before
her adoring fans sent her off to Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Her life was only slightly less eventful playing for the Lady
Techsters, who won 130 games in her four years, including two
national championships. She played on the 1984 U.S. Olympic team
that won a gold medal, after which she returned to yet another day
in her honor in the township of Tickfaw, where much of her family
had its roots and where she lived before moving to Hammond. The
street that runs in front of the Tickfaw elementary school was
renamed Kim Mulkey Drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics were the greatest experience of my life,'' said
Mulkey-Robertson, who married former Louisiana Tech quarterback
Randy Robertson in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter she settled in as an assistant coach for Leon
Barmore, where the winning continued, right up to this spring, when
the Lady Techsters made it to the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   It was always assumed Mulkey-Robertson would succeed Barmore
when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Mulkey-Robertson, however, shocked a university and legions of
longtime Lady Techster fans in April when she turned down a
four-year offer to succeed Barmore and accepted Baylor's five-year,
$1 million offer. After 20 years as a player and assistant coach,
the past four as Barmore's associate head coach, she was suddenly
gone. Barmore soon afterward came out of retirement to take his old
job back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a stage in your life when you make decisions that
are challenging,'' Mulkey-Robertson said. ``And this is a challenge
ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who questioned how she could leave a college she spent
nearly 20 years at as a player and coach, Mulkey-Robertson said,
``I will always have a special place in my heart for Louisiana
Tech. How could I not? But I don't think there was a right or wrong
and there shouldn't have been a division.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people would step back, they should be happy for both.
Happy they could get Leon out of retirement because he's so loved
in the community. And happy for me because I had a belief, and I
gave 19 years of my life to that university.''
</P>
<P>
   At Louisiana Tech, the best she could have done was continue a
tradition. At her first news conference at Baylor, she said she
felt she had to escape from Barmore's shadow to make her own mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was very important to go where I felt my career
could develop,'' she said. ``At Louisiana Tech, we'd been to 13
Final Fours; it's hard to keep that going.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulkey-Robertson's mother says the storm has passed over in
Louisiana, though she admits shock at her daughter's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got over it yet,'' Dru Mulkey said. ``But when I
asked her why, she said, `Momma, I've got a gut feeling that I'd
better do this.' And when she has a gut feeling, you'd better back
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulkey-Robertson's husband, Randy, fully supports his wife's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the choice she made was the best for her career,''
Robertson said. ``I have encouraged her to look for offers to
become a head coach for a lot of reasons. She passed on some
wonderful opportunities, but I'm 100 percent behind the choice she
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people haven't gotten over her decision, which she
grudgingly has conceded turned in part on Louisiana Tech's refusal
to give her a five-year contract. Barmore apparently remains so
sensitive about the turn of events and the feelings they stirred
that he declined to be interviewed. \Nsubheds:Ready to take off For
most, Mulkey-Robertson's memories and accomplishments as a young
woman would be enough for a lifetime. Now, however, she approaches
a new job in a place she never thought she would be.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year old first-year head coach looks to her future at
Baylor with the expected optimism of a rookie, calling the program
``a rocket ready to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   She has hired a staff and signed three players off a Grayson
County College team that won 36 of 37 games and finished third in
the NJCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But her heart will always be back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the country with aunts, uncles and grandparents
down the road,'' she said. ``My grandparents had a dairy and
strawberry fields, where they later built a ball field when they
became too old to tend the strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was old before my time. I never got into riding
around the drive-in. My idea of fun was sitting on the porch
drinking a Barq's root beer and talking to my grandmother, then
going to a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dru still has one problem. Standing in her yard is a large
birdhouse that Kim received as a gift last year from inmates she
visited at a Louisiana prison, where an original 20-minute talk
turned into a three-hour discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That birdhouse is one of her most prized possessions,'' Dru
said. ``But it's painted red, white and Columbia blue, which are
Louisiana Tech's colors. I've got it up, but now I need a Baylor
flag to put on the top.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
