<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-BIKECOPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE GET A BOOST WITH ELECTRIC BIKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Police officers who patrol the streets of Chicago
on bikes are about to receive some motorized help in an effort to
reduce fatigue and lengthen the amount of time they're on patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's ComEd, an electric energy company serving Northern
Illinois, has placed an order with Currie Technologies for 130 of
their electric bicycles, a Currie official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bikes will be donated to 100 police departments in Chicago
and Northwestern Illinois, said Ken Justice, executive vice
president of Currie Technologies, based in the Los Angeles suburb
of Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the largest single order for police bikes in
the history of the industry were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Justice said the ``Law Enforcement Special,'' which can be
pedaled normally until officers activate the battery propulsion
system, is a modified 27-speed Fuji mountain bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the system is that it's on demand,'' said
Justice. ``It gives bike police officers a greater range, and the
power allows them to respond quicker to an emergency call.''
</P>
<P>
   The bikes are also designed to reduce officer fatigue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech bicycles are powered by the company's patented
direct drive propulsion system, which utilizes a 24-Volt brushless
DC motor, for instant acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of bikes will be delivered next week, with the
balance of the order delivered over the next couple of months, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fuji Police Special bicycles are modified at the company's
Van Nuys plant, he said. Each bicycle is equipped with pursuit
lights, sirens and a storage bag for police equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech bikes also feature an oversized lightweight
aluminum alloy frame and is rugged enough to work in all weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with Fuji and then adapt the bike to fit our power
systems that drives the motor,'' Justice said. ``The engine can
provide enough torque for speeds up to 18 miles per hour to help
climb any hill encountered.'
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
