<HEADER>
A8655 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBC-GARRIDO-TEX     06-08 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-GARRIDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CWS ENDS TEXAS FANS' DOUBTS ABOUT COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Two years ago, as the Texas baseball team
struggled through the program's first losing season since 1956,
second-year coach Augie Garrido stopped construction on a house he
was building in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Garrido _ who had lifted Cal State Fullerton from
supreme obscurity to glittering prominence with three national
titles _ said simply, ``Thank God I didn't get this job when I was
young.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 61, Garrido is young again and the Longhorns (46-19) are
here to face LSU at 6 p.m. tomorrow in their first College World
Series engagement in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 28th trip overall for Texas and the eighth for Garrido
_ who won a national championship on his last visit with Fullerton
in 1995. Although he is third on the all-time career list with
1,284 victories, he had begun to wonder if he and the Longhorns
would ever do this together.
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to put Texas back where it belongs, where it
has been so many times in the past,'' Garrido said. ``The longer
the drought went on, the more impatient the fans became.''
</P>
<P>
   Hired as Cliff Gustafson's replacement, Garrido arrived in the
fall of 1996 with a respect for Texas traditions that bordered on
reverence. There were other aspects of the situation, however, that
offered a rude awakening.
</P>
<P>
   One was the state of the program, which had begun to slip
talentwise and was no longer the dominant force in a region of
programs that made annual postseason appearances. Another was the
cherished dream of those programs to rub Bevo's nose in the dirt at
every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   A mediocre year was followed by the unthinkable _ a losing
season _ before the 'Horns finally made it back to postseason play
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an adjustment, really, a matter of adjusting to a
totally different environment,'' Garrido said. ``I had to make some
changes, and there has been pressure and a lot of passionate
feelings involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebuilding it has taken time ... in some people's minds, too
much time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Harmon, a former UT player who has been an assistant coach
there for 12 years, said, ``Augie had won three national
championships coming in here, but this place is an adjustment for
anybody. I doubt if there is a program in the country where you
have the pressure you have here. It's been a tremendous load on him
and he's handled it well.''
</P>
<P>
   One particular oddity manifested itself immediately: in
Garrido's first three years, the Longhorns went 15-11-1 against
national powers Southern Cal, Stanford, LSU and Miami, Fla., but
were cuffed around so much by the locals that Garrido said, ``This
year, we wanted to beat Baylor so badly that we rendered ourselves
incapable of playing effectively against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have things here _ such as the Texas-Texas A&AMP;M rivalry _
that almost exceed anything you find elsewhere. I learned quickly
that the `X' in `Texas' is where you shoot the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``And obviously, there are people who don't think I should be
the coach. But we have finally built the kind of team we wanted.
This is the first group that has totally bought into what we were
teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   In the time-tested Garrido style, it is a team long on pitching
and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs? The Longhorns have hit 31 of them _ putting them one
ahead of LSU's Brad Cresse, the national leader. They have also set
an NCAA record with 126 sacrifice hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I wouldn't mind it if we had more power,'' Garrido
said. ``I honestly prefer the home run _ it requires less teaching.
But it will probably be our style, most of the time, to manufacture
runs as a team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense is rarely a problem, with even the outfielders turning
double plays, and the second base//shortstop tandem of Tommy
Nicholson and Todd West is officially the best in the nation with a
.974 percentage that does not take into account the runners they
have thrown out while down on their knees or flying through the
air. They also rank fourth among keystone combos in hitting, with a
combined .338 average.
</P>
<P>
   As for pitching, Beau Hale (12-5) is a first-round draft choice
(Baltimore), with a fastball that has hit 99 mph, the most recent
outing being a three-hit, 12-strikeout shutout of Penn State in the
final of the Super Regional. Starter D.J. Jones (12-5) is battling
a sore arm, which could turn the spotlight on Phil Seibel (5-1),
who missed 10 weeks with arm problems but beat Arizona State in the
regionals. Closer Charlie Thames is third in the nation with 19
saves.
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the iceberg. More to come in future reels. And the house?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not built yet,'' Garrido said. ``But I'm working on it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
