<DOCNO> NYT20000608.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-IRL-TEX     06-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All-oval all the time, the Indy Racing
League is providing a clearly defined paved path to the
Indianapolis 500 for aspiring all-American drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ray, Scott Sharp, Mark Dismore, Robbie Buhl, Davey
Hamilton, Jeff Ward and Sarah Fisher all fit the born-in-the-USA
model envisioned by IRL founder Tony George when he launched the
open-wheel series in January 1996. But the league never has
operated as a closed shop, offering equal amounts of opportunity
and frustration to a steady lineup of foreign-born drivers. Five of
the 27 drivers entered for the Casino Magic 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway tomorrow night are foreigners, ranging in experience and
from two-time Indy 500 runner-up Scott Goodyear of Canada to series
rookie Shigeaki Hattori of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into its 39th race, the IRL acronym easily might stand
for International Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll ever have just an all-American series,
and I don't think that was Tony's intention by any means,'' said
team owner Dick Simon, who fields the car driven by series regular
Stephan Gregoire of France. ``Tony wasn't saying we don't want any
foreign drivers. He never said that. Tony was trying to make it an
all-American series that anyone could come to.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the most needed series in automobile racing
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost containment and the opportunity for all comers to compete
with equal equipment remain key ingredients of George's formula for
the renamed Indy Racing Northern Light Series. While Ray, the
reigning series champion from Plano, has been among the format's
biggest benefactors, the league also helped accelerate the
open-wheel career of Sweden's Kenny Brack. The 1998 IRL champion
and winner of the 1999 Indy 500, Brack parlayed his success in this
series into a ride with Team Rahal in the rival Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series.
</P>
<P>
   Brack, whose background is in European road racing, joined the
IRL with Galles Racing in 1997 after a Formula One test program
with the lackluster Arrows team. With no oval-track experience and
without benefit of financial backing from a major corporate
sponsor, Brack rolled the dice with the IRL _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an attraction for foreign drivers to come and race in
the States, to begin with, because of the Indianapolis 500,'' said
Eddie Cheever Jr., an IRL owner/driver whose background includes
stints in Formula One and CART. ``A lot of foreigners have won the
Indianapolis 500. You can't begrudge somebody for wanting to run in
the States, anymore than you could begrudge Kenny Brack for wanting
to come and race in the IRL.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, a native of Toronto and defending champion of the TMS
spring event, said the IRL offers several incentives to aspiring
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the draw of gaining experience in high-horsepowered,
open-wheel cars,'' said Goodyear, driver for Pennzoil Panther
Racing. ``And it's having an opportunity to race at a lot of
diversified tracks _ one-mile, mile-and-a-half, high-banked tracks
and flat tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And times have changed in the last decade. As a North
American, when I first went to Europe in the 1980s and tried to get
into Formula Three, they wanted nothing to do with me. Teams now
are going to take drivers and crew members who are the best people
for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL rookie Airton Dare of Brazil, homeland to F1 heroes Ayrton
Senna, Emerson Fittipaldi and Nelson Piquet, said Brack's positive
experience definitely influenced his decision to run this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indianapolis is the biggest deal,'' said Dare, who joined
Rockwall-based TeamExtreme in December 1999 and raced as high as
third during the 84th Indy 500 last month. ``And the second thing,
I used to race in Indy Lights, a series that's a `school' for CART.
I was talking to both IRL and CART at the end of last year, and I
figured out the teams I was talking to in CART were going to be
teams that if you really do well, you finish top 10. Since I
started my career in Jet-Ski, I like to win races and be fighting
for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series, you are motivated every race. You can win every
race, if you do everything right. You can show what you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lopes, team manager for TeamExtreme, said Dare's
nationality did not factor into the hiring process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an evaluation of talent,'' said Lopes, who has paired
Dare with IRL veteran and grassroots racer Davey Hamilton. ``We
looked at Airton's oval record, and if his car was running at the
end of the race, he was always in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we would love to have all-American drivers in the cars.
Davey Hamilton, he fits the bill of what the IRL has been all
about. And I think Airton does as well. He just happens to be
Brazilian.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, whose primary sponsorship is provided by aircraft
insulation manufacturer Mexmil, has brought a distinguished list of
drivers to open-wheel racing in the States. Simon and his wife,
Dianne, have fielded cars for Dutchman Arie Luyendyk, before he won
two Indy 500s; IRL regular Eliseo Salazar of Chile; Raul Boesel of
Brazil; and Americans Jimmy Vasser, Scott Brayton, Scott Pruett and
Lyn St. James.
</P>
<P>
   But one driver Simon could not work out a CART deal for was a
young Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where Jeff Gordon decided to go to NASCAR,'' Simon
said. ``He came and talked to me way back, me and many of the
owners. All he got was turned down, because he didn't have enough
money to get a ride in CART, or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 28, has won 50 Winston Cup races and three championships
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Only two Americans, Michael Andretti and Vasser, currently have
permanent rides in CART. While that has made the series an easy
target for critics who contend foreign drivers are buying up those
rides, Cheever said it is easy to understand an owner's thought
process when trying to secure a $12 million to $15 million CART
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``On equal footing, with the same amount of backing for one
driver and another, I would go obviously for talent,'' Cheever
said. ``I wouldn't even care about gender. The IRL allows you to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've _ Tony George _ made Indy very accessible and
competitive. And the tires do not know if you are from Mars, from
Venus, if you are male or female, black or yellow, old or young.
The tires have a certain amount of grip, and every driver has to
decide how hard they're going to push 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you have the ability and the will, you will make it.
And you will enter a car in the Indy 500.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-00 2310EDT &QL; 
