A8759 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-TMS-TRUCKS-TEX     06-08 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-TRUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Greg Biffle's eyes widened when he started
talking about whether there was any speed left in his Ford F-150
race truck after winning the pole for tonight's NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series event.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle, driving the No. 50 Grainger.com Ford Truck owned by Jack
Roush, will start inside the front row for tonight's Pronto Auto
Parts 400k at Texas Motor Speedway after a hot lap yesterday of
178.130 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It might not have been a record lap, such as has been common
when the Truck Series comes to TMS, but Biffle said with NASCAR's
aerodynamic package for this weekend, his truck performed nearly
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys may have wiggled and had a little bit of speed left
to give,'' said Biffle, who is second in Truck Series standings.
``But that was as fast as the thing would go.''
</P>
<P>
   Biffle heads an all-Ford front row, with Rob Morgan starting
second after posting a speed of 177.760 mph. It's the best start of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's champion, Dennis Setzer, will start third after a
lap of 177.334 mph in his No. 1 Mopar Performance Dodge. Marty
Houston had the fastest Chevrolet at 176.257 mph and will start
fourth. Rookie Kurt Busch, Biffle's teammate, will start fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost had a race setup when we qualified, and that is
good,'' Setzer said. ``With the new package that NASCAR has, the
good trucks are going to be able to run wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying speeds were slower this year because of a new
aerodynamic package NASCAR implemented for the boxy trucks at the
1.5-mile quadoval.
</P>
<P>
   The rear spoiler was raised from seven to eight inches, and the
angle on it was increased from 55 degrees to 65 degrees. Also,
NASCAR made modifications to the front end to create more drag,
which results in slower speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The package is similar to what the series used at Daytona
International Speedway and will use at two-mile racetracks in
California and Michigan. After the Winston Cup-Busch weekend at
Texas, where speeds increased dramatically because of a new
Goodyear tire, NASCAR officials wanted to slow the trucks..
</P>
<P>
   Biffle said the new rules actually helped his Ford, which he
says has consistently been behind the Chevrolets and Dodges on the
superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cab, or greenhouse area, the Dodges are almost two
inches narrower than we are, and the Chevrolets are 11/2 inches
narrower,'' said Biffle, who gave Ford its first truck pole on a
track 11/2 miles and longer since1997. The Dodges and Chevrolets
``were probably a little bit tight, but the package has made the
trucks more stable and makes it easier to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   And making the trucks easier to drive could help create some
interesting racing tonight. Setzer said the draft, which has always
been a factor on the high banks at TMS, could be an even bigger
player in tonight's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR and Dodge have given us a safe package for a track like
this and still kept the aerodynamics competitive,'' Setzer said.
``If you can get it tightened up enough to run flat out, it could
be who can stay on the floor the longest.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was not talking about aerodynamics after he qualified
second, but how his team has continued to improve this season. For
the third time in four races, Morgan will start in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired \Rformer Winston Cup crew chief\S Bill Ingle, and
under his direction, the team has come a long way,'' Morgan said.
``We also changed our motor program. So, it's just a lot of little
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Reffner, driving for Indy Racing Northern Light Series car
owner John Menard, will start sixth, Jamie McMurray seventh and
rookie Scott Riggs eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Houston, who is third in points, will start ninth alongside
series points leader and defending champion Jack Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what I ran, but it was wide open and pretty
uneventful,'' Sprague said. ``It was all she'd go.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
