<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-08 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     06-08 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUNNINGHAM SIGNS THREE-YEAR CONTRACT WITH COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Quarterback Randall Cunningham became a Cowboy
yesterday when he signed a three-year deal that will pay him $1
million this season ($500,000 signing bonus, $500,000 base salary)
to be Troy Aikman's backup.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, will count $667,000 against the salary cap. His
contract essentially is a one-year deal because of what is believed
to be a sharp increase in base salary for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Cowboys offensive coordinator Jack Reilly tried to
entice Cunningham into joining him in St. Louis. Reilly was the
Rams' offensive coordinator and Cunningham was an out-of-work
quarterback after 11 seasons in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked him out. I took him to dinner. I really got to like
him,'' said Reilly, who ended up not signing Cunningham, who sat
out the '96 season before signing the following year with
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham referred yesterday to Aikman as ``a gentleman who has
won three Super Bowls,'' then added, ``I think Troy and I are two
quarterbacks who can get along. I know my role _ and he's the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and Aikman have radically different playing styles.
Together, they give the Cowboys a quarterback tandem that will
force opposing teams into extra preparation in case Aikman has to
come out of a game or is unable to start.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, without a playoff victory since 1996, are returning
to the same basic philosophy of offense that helped win three Super
Bowls in the 1990s, an offense best suited to Aikman's accuracy on
timing routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be adjustments that we're going to have to
see from Randall ... \Rbut\S he's going to fit in just fine here,''
said Reilly, who is eager to see Cunningham in action during the
Cowboys' upcoming mandatory minicamp, Monday through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who missed two starts and parts of two other games
because of back-to-back concussions last season, now has a
change-of-pace backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to do all the timing stuff when \RCunningham\S
is in there,'' Reilly said. ``There's enough variety in this
offense that we can pick and choose what he's most comfortable in
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly was just as positive that there is no problem with Paul
Justin, who was signed three months ago to a $500,000 contract to
be Aikman's backup. The 31-year-old free agent has had 10 NFL
starts in five seasons with Indianapolis, Cincinnati and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't, in any way, want to minimize how much we care about
him,'' Reilly said of Justin, who will battle Cunningham for the
No. 2 job, or could possibly make the team if the Cowboys can find
a way to fit a $500,000 third-string quarterback's contract under
the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Patterson, Cowboys defensive tackles coach, spent the past
two seasons with Cunningham at Minnesota, and marveled at the 1998
NFL Player of the Year's ability to be a loyal backup to Jeff
George, who became the Vikings' starter seven games into the '99
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall was still a leader in the locker room,'' Patterson
said. ``He was tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Cunningham, the Cowboys waived rookie
quarterback Charles Puleri of New Mexico State.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
