<SLUG> BC-IRAN-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S NEWEST NEWS SOURCE BROADCAST FROM AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   California's San Fernando Valley may be thousands of miles from
Iran, but a new satellite television station there is hoping to
provide the news and entertainment Iranians lack from sources
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting from a modest North Hollywood studio _ which was
shown off during its official launch Thursday _ National Iranian
Television produces news and talk shows focusing on Iranian culture
in America. The Farsi-language station also creates original pop
music videos and broadcasts classic Iranian movies.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasts are sent by satellite to Iranian communities
throughout the world _ including to Iran itself, where the station
claims to provide the only native-language news not regulated by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   NITV, as it is known, has been broadcasting since March. Station
executives don't have exact audience figures, but said it is
possible for 74 million people around the globe to receive its
signal.
</P>
<P>
   NITV's founder and chief executive officer is Zia Atabay, a
popular singer in Iran before the 1979 revolution. He came to the
United States in 1980 for a concert, met his wife here and soon
settled in Los Angeles. Since then, he has remained involved in the
business side of the entertainment industry, including producing
Persian television shows.
</P>
<P>
   Atabay said the station is his way of linking Iranian people now
scattered across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to America following the revolution, it was my
dream to one day reunite my countrymen around the world, to combine
and share my cultural experiences as an American Iranian,'' Atabay
said.
</P>
<P>
   Atabay said the station does not have a political stance, and
simply seeks to report news as well as entertain Iranians
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   The station's news department has reporters in Paris, London,
Washington and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters in Iran, however, operate clandestinely, phoning
or faxing their reports without official government sanction.
</P>
<P>
   NITV News Director N. Sabetlmani said many people in Iran are
skeptical of the government-approved newscasts, and look to
independent voices like NITV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell the truth,'' Sabetlmani said.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, satellite dishes are technically illegal, but the
government does not actively prosecute dish owners, Atabay said. He
does not know how many people there watch his programming, but said
the station's talk shows get numerous calls from Iran, as well as
Europe, Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
