<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAN-WOMEN-SLAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S FARM REVEALS UNSAVORY SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout; subs headline)   By JO THOMAS with ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ John Edward Robinson Sr., 56, was a quiet man who
mowed his grass three times a week and grilled the hamburgers at a
neighborhood cookout two weeks ago. But the police say he had a
second life as well, using the Internet, where he called himself
``Slavemaster,'' to lure women into violence.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the police arrested Robinson after two women, who say
they met him in local hotels for sadomaschostic sex, complained
that he assaulted and robbed them. The arrest took place Friday,
and then over the weekend, the police began to make a series of
grisly discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   A search of a farm Robinson owns in La Cygne, Kan., 57 miles
south of Kansas City, yielded two barrels sitting outdoors, swathed
in plastic. Inside were the bodies of two women. A second search,
of three storage units Robinson rented in nearby Raymore, Mo., 54
miles northeast, yielded three more 55-gallon drums and three more
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the women, Suzette Marie Trouten, 28, of Monroe
County, Mich., has been identified. The authorities say Trouten met
Robinson on the Internet, although they declined to discuss the
nature of the site. And as the investigation widens, the police
have linked Robinson to four other women and a baby who have also
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Morrison, the Johnson County district attorney who filed
the assault charges against Robinson on Friday, is now leading a
two-state task force investigating the suspect. Morrison said he
expected to file more charges against Robinson, who was being held
on a $5 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's lawyer, Byron Cerrillo, said his client would plead
not guilty to the sexual assault charges and to any murder charges
that might be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent the fact that people are now claiming that Mr.
Robinson, either directly or indirectly, is a serial killer,''
Cerrillo said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Detective David Brown, the Lenexa, Kan., police officer acting
as a spokesman for the task force, said the police had been
investigating Robinson's connection to Trouten when they received
the assault complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has been investigating computer crimes for several
years, said the case underscored the importance of caution when
meeting people through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon LaPrad, owner of LaPrad Home Care in Monroe, Mich., 35
miles south of Detroit, had employed Trouten for much of the past
decade as a nurse's aide working in the homes of dying and
convalescing patients.
</P>
<P>
   LaPrad said her employee had been contacted last year through an
Internet chat room by a man who offered her a job. Trouten was
lured to her death by promises of a $62,000-a-year job as nurse and
companion for her supposed patron's ``elderly father,'' LaPrad
said.
</P>
<P>
   The job, Trouten was told, would last about a year and offered
world travel, a month off after every two months of traveling, plus
all expenses and extensive health and other benefits. The money,
she thought, would pay for her dream _ to train to become a
licensed practical nurse and eventually a registered nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Trouten made two trips to Kansas, in October and November, to
look into the job and her prospective employer, and she returned
impressed with what she saw, LaPrad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked her up at the airport in a limousine,'' LaPrad
recalled in a telephone interview. ``She told me he lived in a
mansion. She said she saw the mansion and a guest house. She said
it was something else. The man had a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   They were going to travel for a couple of months, she told her
friends, and then she would have a month off.
</P>
<P>
   LaPrad said she was skeptical, as were other friends of
Trouten's. ``It sounded too good to be true,'' LaPrad said. ``But
she was so confident. `This is on the up and up,' she said.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouten related that she had received and signed a contract for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   When Trouten quit her job at LaPrad Home Care at the end of
January, no one advised her not to go to Kansas. ``All we said was,
`Suzette, please be careful,''' LaPrad said. ``We hope you are
positive and know who this man is.' Oh, she said, he lives in a
mansion. He's got a lot of money. We're going to travel. It's
$62,000 and everything paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouten told LaPrad that it was not a permanent arrangement.
``Her last words to me summed it up,'' LaPrad said. ``She put her
arm around me and I wished her luck and she said, `This is only
going to be for a year. It's not forever. I'll be back and forth.
I'll see you in a couple of months.'''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Trouten, who was single and had no children, left
the Newport, Mich., home she shared with her mother, Carolyn, took
her two Pekingese dogs and drove to Kansas. On Feb. 27, LaPrad
said, she received an e-mail message from Trouten saying she had
arrived after a 14-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Trouten's mother received an e-mail message from
her daughter saying she had checked into a motel. A few days later,
Carolyn Trouten received another e-mail message, this one from the
man who had supposedly employed her. It said that Trouten would be
gone for about two months, and it gave an itinerary that did not
provide details.
</P>
<P>
   The mother became suspicious and called the police, LaPrad said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the authorities released the names and, in some
cases, photos of four missing women and one missing baby whose
disappearances, they said, might be linked to Robinson. They were:
Paula Godfrey, 19, reported missing on Sept. 1, 1984; Katherine
Clampet, 27, reported missing June 5, 1987; Izabela K. Lewicka, 22,
a Polish immigrant who has been missing since last fall; and Lisa
Stasi, 19, who disappeared with her 5-month-old baby, Tiffany, on
Jan. 11, 1985. All of the women were living or staying in Overland
Park, Kan., at the time they vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Citing investigators' reports from 1985, The Kansas City Star
said Stasi was staying in a domestic violence shelter at the time
she met Robinson. The newspaper reported that the police believed
Robinson promised to help her go to Texas to train for work as a
silk-screen printer. He also offered her $800 a month for living
expenses and promised to find her a baby-sitter and a place to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Later, according to the newspaper, a lawyer representing
Robinson told the police that Stasi had decided to take care of
herself, and Robinson told the police she had moved to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not disclose details of the earlier
investigations or provide information about Godfrey, Clampet, or
Lewicka.
</P>
<P>
   At Store-Mor For Less in Raymore, Mo., where the police found
three bodies in Robinson's 10-by-15-foot unit, a manager who asked
that her name not be used said the Robinsons rented three units in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's wife, Nancy, rented the first storage unit in May,
1993, and Robinson rented two more units in November or December,
1993, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me his sister Beverly had gone to work for his
company, Equi II, and he was storing her furniture. She supposedly
had gone to Australia. The last time I saw him, he was saying that
she was in Italy. He said, `She's having a ball. I don't think
she'll ever return.'''
</P>
<P>
   The manager said Robinson had paid his rent on time, often in
person. ``He would run through here _ I guess to check on his
bones,'' she said. ``Lately he's been sending his check in.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has a lengthy criminal record of theft and fraud. He
was sent to prison in Kansas in May, 1986. In 1991, he was paroled
and sent to Missouri to serve a sentence for theft. He was paroled
there in March, 1993. He then moved to Olathe. His wife managed the
mobile home park where they lived.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Timmons, 79, the Robinsons' next-door neighbor, recalled
that Robinson ``kept his yard immaculate. He had elaborate
decorations on all the holidays _ Christmas, Halloween, Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed he was retired,'' Timmons said. ``He looks older
than he is. They had grown children and at least one grandchild.
There was a sign outside that said `Grandpa's place. We Spoil
Grandchildren.' They were cordial, but they were always in a
hurry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
