<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A CAMPAIGN CENTERED AROUND `FIRSTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a riddle that used to appear in magazines
like Highlights for Children and Boys' Life, asking readers to name
the only day of the year that can also be a sentence. The answer:
March Fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Back up the calendar three days and you have the name of a
recently formed company, offering a variety of Internet
professional services, that seeks to solve another riddle: how to
stand out amid competitors ranging from management consultants to
advertising agencies to Web site builders. The company, called
MarchFirst Inc., is hoping the right answer will be an extensive _
and expensive _ offline and online media campaign centered on a
celebration of being, well, first.
</P>
<P>
   MarchFirst began operations on, yes, March 1, with the
completion of the merger of the USWeb/CKS Group, a Web services
company, and Whittman-Hart, an Internet consulting firm. A brief
``teaser'' campaign ran in newspapers to introduce the name, which
was created by staff members at McKinney &AMP; Silver, the ad agency
unit of USWeb/CKS perhaps best known for its work for the Audi
automobiles sold by Volkswagen of America.
</P>
<P>
   The second, much larger, phase of the MarchFirst campaign, also
produced by McKinney &AMP; Silver, is to begin on Monday with ads in
daily and weekly newspapers. Ads in business, trade and lifestyle
magazines will follow later in the month along with TV commercials
on sports and other programming. The online portion includes a Web
site to go up on Monday (www.marchfirst.com).
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the entire campaign, carrying the theme ``A new
company for the new economy,'' is $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to cut through all the clutter,'' said Robert
Bernard, chairman and chief executive at MarchFirst in Chicago,
particularly, he said, when dozens of dot-coms are striving to
establish themselves in the business-to-business and
business-to-consumer realms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for us to get the name out there, to
create a strong brand awareness,'' Bernard said, adding that basing
the campaign on ``the human desire to be first'' would accomplish
that ``because people will be attracted to the emotion, the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about crossing a finish line first,'' he added,
``but also about tackling problems, taking risks, taking on
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The device the campaign uses to gain attention is to demonstrate
the effects of famous firsts rather than portray the causes. For
instance, a print ad captioned ``The first rock star'' shows not
Chuck Berry or Elvis Presley or Bill Haley but screaming, sobbing
fans pressed against a chain-link fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to being first,'' the text reads. ``Here's to
leading.''
</P>
<P>
   A second print ad, captioned ``The first cubist exhibition,''
displays not ``Nude Descending a Staircase'' but a gallery of men
and women staring, glaring and even tilting their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be first,'' the text reads, promoting MarchFirst
as providing businesses with ``a new way of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV commercials are to present the effects of events like the
wearing of the first miniskirt, as passers-by are seen registering
shock and surprise; the first man on the moon, as a family watching
television is glimpsed crying and cheering; and the first
expedition to the South Pole, as penguins are shown turning their
heads in unison from left to right as if they were humans at a
tennis match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power is in the effects these firsts had in moving
society,'' said David Baldwin, senior vice president and executive
creative director at McKinney &AMP; Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have said: `MarchFirst. Integrated solutions for your
many needs,''' he added, laughing. ``But it's better to say we're
making sure MarchFirst is always trying to win for clients and
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Sara Cavin, executive vice president for marketing,
the campaign is aimed at MarchFirst's employees _ current and
prospective _ as much as existing and potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly `re-recruiting' our employees to make sure
they've an understanding of what we do,'' Cavin said. That is
crucial because MarchFirst, with 9,000 employees at 70 offices in
14 countries, does so much: creating traditional advertising;
building and putting up Web sites; offering brand and corporate
identity consulting and strategic positioning; and installing
so-called front-end and back-end technology services.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not you like the company's unusual name, it offers
one major advantage, according to Bernard: ``Every year, we can
celebrate our anniversary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
