<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-OIL-270&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING ENERGY SELF-RELIANCE, BRAZIL AUCTIONS 21 OIL LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ With the sale of 21 potential oil-producing
areas on and offshore, Brazil has taken a major step toward
reducing its dependence on energy imports _ even as the country
gives foreign petroleum companies a greater role.
</P>
<P>
   It is still too soon to tell how much Brazil's oil production
will increase because of the concessions that were auctioned by the
government on Wednesday in Rio de Janeiro, attracting bidders from
all over the world. But as a result, the domestic petroleum
industry is expected to receive as much as $1 billion in technology
and infrastructure investment over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can think about growth without energy,'' said the vice
president of Brazil, Marco Maciel, whose presence at the auction
underlined the government's commitment to modernize the oil
industry in Brazil, Latin America's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   The nation imported an average of 339,000 barrels of oil a day
last year _ about a third of its oil needs _ spending $2 billion.
This year, with the surge in oil prices, Brazil's spending on
imported petroleum will be far more. And with a growing population
and an expanding industrial base, Brazil has been struggling to
meet new demand for oil.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleum industry experts said the auction, where international
oil companies spent $262 million to buy 9 onshore and 12 offshore
concessions, was a forward step for Brazil's ambition of energy
autonomy and an important vote of confidence in the opening of
Brazil's petroleum industry, which until two years ago was
dominated by state-owned oil company, Petroleo Brasileiro, or
Petrobras.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To attract foreign investment and help expand exploration and
drilling, the Brazilian Congress voted to open the oil industry in
1997, after a protracted battle with nationalists, who feared
excessive foreign influence over a strategic resource.
</P>
<P>
   A new regulatory body, the National Petroleum Agency, forced
Petrobras to give up the rights to potential oil finds that it
lacked the resources to develop. The company kept 397 areas, and
has since signed a number of joint venture agreements with
multinational oil companies to develop the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the government auctioned the first set of concession
areas that were relinquished by Petrobras, earning $178 million.
Although the government considered the effort a success, only 12 of
the 27 blocks on offer were sold, partly because of economic
uncertainty caused by the devaluation of Brazil's currency, the
real, early in 1999. The sales were also hampered by some concern
about the government's commitment to free competition in a country
where, until a few years ago, many major industries had been
state-run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of the first round didn't give time for a lot of
people to assimilate what the changes in the Brazilian market
meant,'' said Martin Jones, general manager in Brazil for Amerada
Hess. ``We are now moving from the theory of investing in Brazil to
the practice of investing in Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   While partly relying on high oil prices to invigorate interest
in the auction, the government this time around also relaxed some
bidding restrictions to attract smaller domestic and foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was a larger pool of bidders in this round,
Petrobras still emerged as the big winner, buying seven of the
concessions and participation in an eighth. The company surprised
auction participants by offering winning bids of $56 million and
$89 million on two offshore blocks in the Santos basin, where it
already has operating wells.
</P>
<P>
   There was some grumbling about the strong Petrobras showing in
the auction. Critics said the company benefited from an insider's
knowledge of the local oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave a very competitive bid, but it wasn't good enough,''
said Victor Dauzacker, the representative in Brazil for Fay
Richwhite Holding Ltd., which was outbid for an onshore concession
by Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to bring more companies into Brazil's oil industry,
Petrobras plans to auction 73 mature fields _ those with declining
production in the northeast of the country _ on a date to be
announced in July. The National Petroleum Agency also plans to
auction a third round of concession areas in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
