<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT A SHAQ BRICK, JUST A FREUDIAN SLIP!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sometimes a cigar is just a cigar, as Sigmund
Freud is said to have said. And, may I add, sometimes a
buzzer-beater is just two points, an alley-oop pass is just an
assist and an airball is just a misfire.
</P>
<P>
   But you wouldn't know it by listening to the analysis - verging
on psychoanalysis - that follows any big NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   There it was again Thursday, when as the NBA finalists convened
at Staples Center to figure out what happened in Game 1 and
practice for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   You thought the Lakers trounced the Indiana Pacers because
Shaquille O'Neal is bigger, stronger and faster than everybody
else, and Reggie Miller had a really bad shooting night. Oh, no,
it's never that simple.
</P>
<P>
   In the language of pro basketball, the Lakers are on their way
to the NBA championship because O'Neal is on a mission, Kobe Bryant
has come of age, the two of them have bonded and the squad as a
whole has accepted Phil Jackson's leadership and the concepts of
``sustaining energy'' and living ``in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the language of pro basketball, the Pacers lost in their
first-ever NBA Finals game not because they're smaller, weaker and
slower but because - well, let their boss handle the pop
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I was sitting, we looked a little shell-shocked,''
Pacers president Donnie Walsh said after watching his team fall
behind the Lakers 33-16 in the series' opening minutes. ``Maybe
they (the Indiana players) were overwhelmed by the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelmed by the occasion'' being the opposite of ``stepping
up in pressure situations,'' which is what the Lakers are credited
with doing lately.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, had the Lakers' Game 7 rally against the Portland
Trail Blazers fallen short, it might be have been attributed to the
Lakers' being ``overwhelmed by the occasion'' - or lacking ``guts''
or failing to ``learn how to win'' while winning 67 regular-season
and 10 previous playoff games.)
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that all this talk about players' mental and
emotional states, and their intricate professional relationships
with each other, seems a bit high-flown. You'd think they're being
asked to walk a tight rope across the Grand Canyon or form a new
civilization on a desert island, not throw a ball in a hoop.
</P>
<P>
   It just seems to me that the athletes and teams in basketball
are subjected to more probings of their moods and proclivities than
those in any other sport.
</P>
<P>
   A pitcher throws a home run pitch and it's because his release
point is off. A quarterback throws an interception and it's because
somebody failed to execute the X's and O's from the playbook. But a
basketball player bricks a free throw and it's because he's afraid
of failure. Or success. One of the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is amusing to hear some of the things that are
said sometimes,'' Lakers guard Derek Fisher said. ``(The game)
(begin ital)is(end ital) psychological, but to be able to put a
specific definition on things, I think it's hard, because each
player has his own things going on.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal makes all nine free-throw attempts in Game 4 against
Portland, and explains that his 3-year-old daughter told him to
``bend your knees.'' It's all in the head, see?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal goes right back to his usual 50-percent foul shooting in
the ensuing games, and - what, he already forgot his daughter's
sage advice?
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scores 25 points on 11-for-18 shooting, and passes to Ron
Harper for the game-winning basket in Game 3 against Portland and
his performance is hailed by teammates John Salley as
``Jordanesque.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant goes 9 for 28 in the next two games and we're told to
remember he's just a kid.
</P>
<P>
   If you believed this stuff, you'd have to conclude that NBA
players are the most unstable creatures this side of rats in a
psych student's lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a game that requires split-second timing, so
there is a focus on whether guys are at the point in their careers
where they can read defenses, react the right way,'' Walsh said.
``(But) I laugh when some of the analysis goes so deep. You think
you're talking to Freud himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we overanalyze, to be honest with you. We're
overanalyzing why we lost (Game 1). It could be as simple as we
weren't good enough, we didn't shoot well enough, we didn't defend
well enough. But we always feel like we've got to go deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys do it at the end of the game, we think he's got
this, that or the other (quality), when it's just (that) he's good.
Michael Jordan was really good. Shaq is really good. And bigger and
stronger....''
</P>
<P>
   There might not be a psychologist's couch sturdy enough to hold
Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Some sportswriters wish they'd studied labor relations (to make
it easier to cover baseball) or criminal law (the NFL). I wish I'd
paid better attention in psychology class so I could understand an
NBA press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this emphasis on head games began with Pat Riley and the
old Lakers coach's talk of ``message games,'' the ``comfort zone''
and something he called ``toxic envy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, like most phenomenons we think are recent
developments, it actually has been going on forever. Maybe, while
Dr. Naismith was hanging the first peach baskets, he was muttering
about the players' lack of ``intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody suggested I ask a doctor about this.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Ramsey happened to be in. And he thinks he understands
why everybody turns into Frasier Crane when we get around
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``In basketball, you've got fewer players, they're very visible
and you see the emotion,'' said Ramsey, who coached Portland to the
1977 NBA title. ``While it's a team game, there's a lot of
individualism and you (begin ital)see(end ital) demonstrations of
leadership. Guys do it in all different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   This is probably the simplest explanation. We think we can see
into the minds and hearts of basketball players because - unlike
the helmeted and scripted athletes in football, hockey and baseball
- they appear almost literally naked to us on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   So Walsh's perception from the stands was correct? The Pacers
were ``overwhelmed by the occasion''? ``Shell-shocked''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not any more than we were,'' said Fisher, who had a closer
view.
</P>
<P>
   I still want to know what Red Auerbach likes about those cigars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
