<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAKES WILL STILL BE HIGH AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ There may not be a Triple Crown at stake at
Belmont Park this weekend. But three days of major racing with $2.5
million in purses will be staged, starting Friday with the Acorn
Stakes, the first event in the Triple Tiara series for fillies, and
closing on Sunday with the 112th running of the Brooklyn Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the 132nd Belmont Stakes, the main event of the year
in New York racing, will be run. True, it will be run without the
two top 3-year-old colts in the country, the injured Fusaichi
Pegasus and the resting Red Bullet. But it will feature 11 other
horses searching for the 3-year-old championship the two absent
colts are still expected to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend will be anchored by four Grade I stakes, beginning
with the Acorn and its undefeated star, Roxelana, who has won all
four of her starts by a combined total of 29 lengths. A month ago,
she scored big time in the La Troienne Stakes at Churchill Downs by
nearly 12 lengths. ``She amazes me each time she runs,'' said her
trainer, William Huffman. ``The Acorn is never an easy race. It's a
Grade I in New York. So, we're going to run her and see if she fits
in with that group. She's passed every test so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Roxelana will be surrounded by nine other fillies in the
one-mile run, including Darling My Darling, Finder's Fee, Circle of
Life and Tugger. The second race in the Triple Tiara series, the
Mother Goose, at a mile and an eighth, will be run at Belmont on
July 1, and the third, the Coaching Club American Oaks, at a mile
and a half, on July 22. Only eight fillies have swept all three,
most recently Sky Beauty in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Racing reaches a peak Saturday when four other stakes support
the Belmont on a day festooned by parachute jumping, world-class
buglers and marching bands. The cast for the $1 million Belmont
includes several candidates for the 3-year-old championship,
including the favored Aptitude, who ran second to Fusaichi Pegasus
in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Belmont is a great race for the pedigree,'' said Bobby
Frankel, who trains Aptitude, ``and the money isn't bad, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the mile-and-a-half Belmont will be the $400,000
Manhattan Handicap at a mile and a quarter on the inner turf
course; the $150,000 Riva Ridge at seven furlongs; the $150,000
True North at seven furlongs; and the $150,000 Just a Game
Breeders' Cup at one mile on the turf. The Manhattan will be
contested by five Grade I winners, notably Yagli, who won the race
last year, but has struggled since then.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's run of races will close with flourishes on Sunday
with the Brooklyn Handicap at a mile and an eighth, a race that has
been won by such stars as Exterminator, Whirlaway, Assault and
three straight times by Discovery in the 1930s and by Forego in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The horse with a cause this year is Running Stag, who won the
race last year and who campaigns as relentlessly as a political
candidate. He is an international traveler who has raced in
England, America, Dubai and Hong Kong in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   For Running Stag, who is 6 years old, this will be his 38th
start and his third in three weeks. He won an allowance at Belmont
on May 24, won the Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs last
Saturday and will be back in action Sunday at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that a lot? Roger Teal, the assistant trainer, said the
horse got back to Belmont last Sunday and took life rather easy
this week. ``We can't see any problems in running back on Sunday,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
