r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-08 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERKINS HAS UPHILL BATTLE WITH MT. SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sam Perkins patrols the post for Indiana. His
wife, Dionne, patrols the streets of Seattle. Normally we wouldn't
deign to question which partner in this power couple has the more
treacherous job. Usually we'd agree that being a police officer
makes being a power forward seem like, well, child's play.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, this isn't any ordinary assignment that Perkins
has drawn in the ongoing NBA Finals. He is being asked to move a
mountain so majestic many people worship at its foot. Perkins has
never scaled Mount Whitney or Mount Rainier, but he does feel a
little like Sir Edmund Hillary now that he's face-to-face with
Mount Shaq, a.k.a. ``The Big Himalaya.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is a conquest, almost, in a sense,'' said Perkins of
the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal, who is four inches taller, 70 pounds
heavier and nearly 11 years his junior.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 of the best-of-seven championship series, Perkins
couldn't have felt more powerless if he had been trying to stop an
avalanche. He leaned on O'Neal, he jostled him and, still, the
7-foot-1 center converted nine field goals to Perkins' one in the
21 minutes they stalked each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just so strong,'' Perkins said of O'Neal. When he has the
ball, ``he leans in on you and you flop, but it's not really a
flop. It's the real thing. A couple of times (Wednesday) I was
leaning in on him and the refs were telling me, `Hey, that's
enough.' What they don't realize is that was just a tap compared to
what I really wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to inequity, O'Neal blocked one of Perkins' shots
in the second quarter, after which the former Laker put up just two
more shots the remainder of the Pacers' long, long night.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked Perkins after the Pacers' practice Thursday if
there was anybody else he could think of who is O'Neal's equal
physically. Perkins smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butterbean,'' he said, referring to the pro boxer. ``But
that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think the coming of age of the 28-year-old O'Neal is
reason enough for veterans such as Perkins to be going, you'd be
wrong. He could have retired after last year. He's glad he returned
to take O'Neal's physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go out against the best to say, `Cool, I did
it,''' said Perkins, who is leaning toward calling it a career
after this series. ``It's not disheartening. You just take it as a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   People say Perkins personifies the old, slow Pacers. Perhaps,
but he also is capable of keying their perimeter game. He has the
outside shot to pull O'Neal out of his comfort zone on defense,
into his no-man's land, the high post. Perkins, who turns 39 next
week, once made eight 3-pointers without a miss in a game against
Toronto three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles basketball historians might also remember Perkins
made the winning jumper in the Lakers' lone NBA Finals victory of
the 1990s, against Phil Jackson's Chicago team in the 1991 series
that the Bulls took in five. Jackson, in his first season with the
Lakers, waxed eloquent as he is want to do on Perkins' star turn
before Wednesday's Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good that he brought it up,'' Perkins said. ``But that
ain't going to do any good for me in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is no good to the Pacers so long as he lets O'Neal
freeze him. That's especially true if Reggie Miller, Indiana's
designated gunner, comes out again in tonight's Game 2 shooting so
cold he'd be hard-pressed to hit the Pacific Ocean with a beach
ball.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask Lakers backup center John Salley, the Pacers were too
passive in the way they played O'Neal. Salley's opinion carries a
lot of weight insofar as he battles O'Neal every day in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The bad boys he played with in Detroit in the 1980s OK, mainly
bad boy Bill Laimbeer wouldn't have been so tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Shaq to death,'' Salley said, ``but he would have
thrown a punch at Bill, and that's exactly what we would have
wanted to happen. These guys come down and go, `Oh, my god, I've
got to play against Shaquille. Bill would have thought of a way to
get Shaquille (in foul trouble).''
</P>
<P>
   To play like that, Perkins first would require a personality
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Salley understands. He really does. He won't give Perkins
advice, but he'd be happy to slip him the name and phone number of
his chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got him on call,'' Salley said. ``Every day, I gotta go
to him, and he re-adjusts my back and neck. I get dumped on by
Shaquille in the tailbone and the ribs and the shoulders on a
regular basis. I have scoliosis because of him. If he can hit me
and I'm his boy, I feel sorry for anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins played for Dean Smith at North Carolina. Surely the Dean
of college coaches had some sage advice for handling O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't called me yet,'' Perkins said. Smiling, he added,
``I guess he hasn't figured out what to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
